<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 00:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2643 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-1STLD     06-04 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GOOD NEWS, BAD NEWS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 3rd graf to make it read: `battle casualty'; subs last graf
to make it `stumbled' stead of `blundered')  By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What should we think of Thursday's news of a potential deal in
Kosovo? We should think there is potential good news here and
potential bad news.
</P>
<P>
   What the Serbs acknowledged Thursday is that the air war has
really hurt them, that they are ready to sit down and negotiate,
and they are ready to do it according to the principles set out by
NATO and Russia. In other words, what happened Thursday is not the
end of negotiations, it is the beginning of them. NATO wanted to
avoid a ground war in Yugoslavia and it may have done that with the
air war. But the purpose of the air war was to determine who would
go where, with what arms and with what mandate on the ground, and
all that will now have to be negotiated by military men on both
sides _ and the air war can't stop until it is.
</P>
<P>
   If the details can be negotiated, and they really do allow a
strong NATO presence in Kosovo, the first piece of good news would
be that NATO's basic objective _ getting the refugees back home
under some form of credible international protection _ will be
possible, without splitting the alliance, without NATO having
suffered a single battle casualty and without a ground war. That
ain't beanbag.
</P>
<P>
   The thing to worry about is what NATO has won: the right to
manage relations between Kosovo Albanians and Serbs indefinitely,
just as NATO is now doing between Serbs, Croats and Muslims in
Bosnia. Why should one worry about that? Because Kosovo is not
Bosnia. The Bosnia peace accords began with a political agreement
between the leaders of each faction for a de facto partition of
Bosnia. The military arrangements were then built around that core
understanding. That is why it has been so stable.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is just the opposite. We are going to have a military
arrangement on the ground, with no political understanding between
Serbs and Kosovo Albanians on what the political future of Kosovo
should be. The Kosovo Albanians still want full independence; the
Serbs still want NATO out and permanent sovereignty over Kosovo.
This means that NATO and Russia will not be sitting on basically
contented parties, but on still-aggrieved parties that could draw
the U.S. and Russia into their ongoing feud.
</P>
<P>
   If this deal is real, the second bit of good news is that
Milosevic will have been seen to lose in some very important ways.
He personally has been indicted as a war criminal; he would be
accepting foreign troops on his soil, something he had rejected;
and his army and his economy have both been mauled as punishment
for his actions. No one can say he is walking away a winner. He
will, though, be walking away a survivor, because NATO is not going
to go after him, so as not to upset any deal. As in Bosnia, there
will be a trade-off in Kosovo between justice and stability.
</P>
<P>
   If this deal is real, the third bit of good news is that the
Russians will have tacitly signed on to NATO's basic agenda in
Yugoslavia, and that's important. It could turn out to be a bridge
for re-establishing broader NATO-Russian cooperation. The thing to
worry about is that if Russian troops are to be in one zone in
Kosovo and NATO troops in another, friction and misunderstanding
will always be possible _ particularly if the Kosovo Liberation
Army seeks revenge on the Serbs in the Russian zone.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, from the start the Kosovo problem has been about how we
should react when bad things happen in unimportant places. Some
argued that Kosovo was so unimportant that you just had to ignore
the bad things happening there. Some argued that what was happening
in Kosovo was so bad you had to overlook its strategic
insignificance for America and mount an all-out ground war.
</P>
<P>
   Some, including myself, argued that once the refugee evictions
began, ignoring Kosovo would be wrong, mounting a ground invasion
would deepen the disaster, and therefore using a huge air war for a
limited objective was the only thing that made sense. If this deal
proves real, it will establish that an air war for limited
humanitarian goals can be effective, albeit costly.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, though, the Clintonites stumbled into this
strategy, after completely underestimating Milosevic's intentions
and capabilities. The Kosovars have paid heavily for these
blunders. We will be lucky if the majority of them can now return
home. Which is why whatever this war proves about what air power
can do to achieve limited humanitarian goals, it is not something
anyone is going to want to try again real soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
