u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALMON-TREATY-SPI &LR;      06-04 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-TREATY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND CANADIAN SALMON TREATY HAILED AS MAJOR STEP FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Endangered chinook salmon runs of Puget Sound and the
Columbia River system emerged as apparent big winners Thursday as
U.S. and Canadian officials offered details of the 10-year Pacific
Salmon agreement reached by the two countries' negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Washington and Oregon achieved a key conservation goal as Canada
agreed to sharply cut back fishing for U.S.-bound chinook in waters
off Vancouver Island and the Strait of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will make it much easier to promote restoration of salmon
habitat. Before, it was difficult to make the case for habitat when
not many fish were coming back to spawn,'' Oregon Gov. John
Kitzhaber said.
</P>
<P>
   But fishermen in Alaska waters will continue to catch hundreds
of thousands of chinook, sockeye and coho salmon bound for rivers
in British Columbia and the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will still be a major kill,'' Canada's fisheries
minister David Anderson acknowledged after a Seattle news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said, however, that the agreement is ``a step
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaska has agreed to take fewer fish in years when runs are
weak. The two countries will replace fixed quotas with an
``abundance-based'' system that adjusts the catch to relative
abundance of runs.
</P>
<P>
   During 1996, when Canada closed its fisheries due to low runs,
Alaska took 170,000 chinook. The average Alaska chinook catch has
been about 250,000 fish a year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if chinook salmon populations remain similar to those
observed in the past few years, Alaska-based fishermen under the
agreement can catch between 150,000 and 207,000 chinook a year.
They also will be able to catch sockeye and coho salmon bound for
Northwest rivers.
</P>
<P>
   British Columbia Premier Glen Clark wasn't pleased by the
agreement, saying it entrenches ``the right of Alaskans to catch
more B.C. salmon than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement _ which ends a five-year conflict between the
United States and Canada _ appears likely to produce certainty and
allow long-term planning for salmon conservation.
</P>
<P>
   The ending of the impasse at sea produced relief by most
officials of both countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't easy, but after five frustrating years of
negotiating breakdowns, we finally ended the stalemate,'' said
Washington Gov. Gary Locke, whose ad hoc fish conservation
agreements with Anderson last year helped open the way for a
long-term settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Both government officials and fisheries groups said they can
concentrate on preserving and restoring salmon habitat now that
peace is in place in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's agreement is absolutely integral to our long-term
strategy to bring the salmon back,'' Vice President Al Gore said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Locke and Kitzhaber had particular reason to smile. Canada's
concessions are likely to mean more _ many more _ salmon returning
to Northwest streams, according to figures released Thursday by the
National Marine Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   If the agreement had been in effect the past few years, between
25 percent and 30 percent more salmon would have returned to Puget
Sound rivers. The return of chinook salmon to the Columbia River
would have been 40 percent higher. Imperiled Snake River salmon
runs would have seen double the number of spawners.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement won't come cheap, however.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, as the price of preserving chinook and coho
salmon, the United States agreed to limit its catch of Fraser River
salmon to 16.5 percent, down from a historical average of 20
percent. Last year, U.S. fishermen took 25 percent of the catch.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government and Washington state are expected to
appropriate another $30 million to $35 million to buy out the
licenses of U.S. fishermen, including some Indians, who will lose a
big chunk of their customary Fraser River catch.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement sets up two funds, under joint U.S. and Canadian
management, for fisheries science, restoration and enhancement. A
$75 million Northern Fund would cover Alaska as well as northern
and central British Columbia, including B.C.'s troubled Skeena
River fishery. A $65 million Southern Fund would cover southern
British Columbia _ including the Fraser River _ as well as
Washington, Oregon and Idaho's Snake River basin.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has committed to seek money to pay the $140
million for both funds _ in addition to the $100 million salmon
enhancement program already proposed by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll get it,'' said Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash.,
pointing to the number of Northwest lawmakers on the appropriations
committees that control Congress' pursestrings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, deeply felt differences were apparent Thursday,
particularly between Alaska and British Columbia fisheries
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska fishermen ``should not be made to make more
concessions,'' said Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, chairman of the House
Resources Committee. However, Young praised negotiators and said he
was ``glad we have a long-term agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Clark argued that last year, British Columbia
fishermen caught no B.C.-bound coho salmon in order to assure
survival. ``At the same time, Alaskans caught 800,000 B.C. coho,''
Clark said. ``This year B.C. will not catch any endangered coho.
The Alaskans will. In fact, Alaskans will catch endangered B.C.
coho next year, the year after that and every year for the next 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The premier's concerns were reflected even among British
Columbians who generally support the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any deal was better than no deal, and the real danger is that
our salmon runs will disappear,'' said Ric Careless, director of
B.C. Spaces for Nature, a conservation group. ``The real question
is what will happen up the coast with Alaska's continued
interception of chinook and coho.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fulton, who represented Prince Rupert in Canada's parliament
for 14 years, added: ``I wish this were a better agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Curtis, western conservation director for Trout Unlimited
in Portland, raised a different concern. ``The agreement is
incredibly technical,'' Curtis said. ``Can they pull it off? Manage
the details? And will Congress put up the enormous amount of money?
Those are the questions remaining before us.''
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the agreement acknowledged as much. ``This is a
beginning,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Strong, a longtime leader of the Columbia River Intertribal
Fisheries Commission, compared challenges facing U.S. and Canadian
negotiators to salmon trying to find their way home from the
Pacific Ocean to the river of their upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   Resolving the dispute has ``spawned new perspectives'' about
conserving a resource shared by different countries and cultures,
Strong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
