<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME MOVEMENT TOWARD AGREEMENT ON NEW YORK STATE BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Prospects for approving a state budget moved
Thursday from abject stalemate to the realm of serious negotiation
as Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver agreed to cut his house's
spending proposals by $1 billion or more, the first significant
movement by any side in three months.
</P>
<P>
   The shift means that the overall budget figure proposed by the
Democratic-controlled Assembly is near that of the
Republican-majority Senate, though both still want to spend
significantly more than Gov. George Pataki, a Republican. The two
houses are close enough that they could soon convene a conference
committee to decide how the available money should be spent.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki welcomed the Assembly's movement, but he said Thursday
that the state remained far from settling a budget.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have felt under siege over this budget, now 64 days
overdue. For months, Pataki has loudly assailed their proposal as
unrealistic and irresponsible, while refusing to get involved in
budget negotiations, an unusual stance that was intended to
distance him from the looming fiasco of another very late budget.
</P>
<P>
   He made it clear that he felt no pressure to jump-start
negotiations and did not mind keeping the government running with a
string of emergency spending bills, a stopgap that Democrats
disliked because it limits spending to last year's levels.
</P>
<P>
   A new law that requires withholding legislators' paychecks when
a state budget is not completed by the deadline of March 31 has
begun to exert great personal pressure on some lawmakers. And
social service agencies, school districts and hospitals that rely
on state money have begun to clamor for some degree of certainty
about what they will receive as they prepare their own budgets.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Assembly adopted a plan that was, by the
Democrats' estimates, $2 billion higher than the governor's.
Republicans insisted it was actually $4 billion more. The Senate
adopted a plan $1.1 billion higher than the governor's.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Silver said he had agreed to cut his overall
spending plan to $1.1 billion to $1.5 billion over the governor's
plan, suddenly putting the Assembly on the same general terrain as
the Senate and nearly eliminating the main obstacle to a conference
committee. By the Democrats' estimate, they had reduced their
demands by about $1 billion; the Republicans said Silver had come
down by $2 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Silver, clearly angry at the governor and
the Senate majority leader, Joseph L. Bruno, blamed them for
reducing allocations for programs he said were needed, and delaying
the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Silver, normally a reticent, colorless public speaker, gave an
agitated account of the year's budget process, at one point giving
a four-minute response to a simple question.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining how the Democrats' retrenchment began with a
conversation he had with the governor late Wednesday, the speaker
charged that Pataki's exploration of a possible presidential run,
an idea that he abandoned last week, had consumed the governor's
time and attention, leaving no time for state issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that his presidential campaign has come to a halt,''
Silver said, ``and he's been here, I chose to speak to him and
explain to him his characterization of the Assembly budget has
always been wrong, but that I was prepared to meet him more than
halfway.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver and Bruno agreed that once the conference committee
convenes, a detailed budget can be hashed out in 10 to 14 days,
raising the prospect _ all but unimaginable at the start of the
week _ that a budget could be passed by the scheduled end of this
year's legislative session, on June 16.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki tried to douse any high expectations that might be
raised by the Democrats' new stance, saying, ``We are still very,
very far apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
