<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2649 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-CRASH-TEX_1s     06-04 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-CRASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL OFFICIALS SAY PILOTS TRIED `EVERYTHING IN THEIR BAG OF
TRICKS'
</HEADLINE>
 _ 1st Lede Writethru (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Flight data recorder information shows that
the pilots of American Airlines Flight 1420 tried ``everything in
their bag of tricks'' to keep the plane under control as it
careened uncontrollably down the runway before crashing, a federal
source said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also said that wing spoilers that would have
helped slow down the plane after it landed did not deploy, and that
the pilots apparently tried twice to use the engines' thrust
reversers to control the aircraft's speed on the runway.
</P>
<P>
   The plane's flight data recorder showed that only one of the two
thrust reversers activated about eight seconds before the plane
crashed, said George W. Black Jr., the National Transportation
Safety Board member in charge of the crash investigation.
</P>
<P>
   That data, Black said, could indicate that the thrust reversers
malfunctioned or the pilot was attempting to use them to steer the
plane as it careened down the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the source, who asked not to be named, said the
evidence so far points to pilots who were trying desperately to
control an aircraft that was being pushed sideways off the runway
by high winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indications are that pilots were trying to use everything in
there bag of tricks to bring the aircraft under control and get it
stopped,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft's tires left sideways scuff marks on the pavement,
the source said. That evidence, the source said, is consistent with
strong cross winds blowing the aircraft sideways.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Black said the pilots of doomed aircraft had
been alerted to wind shears but had no way of knowing the severity
of the thunderstorm pounding Little Rock National Airport with high
winds, blinding rain and hail.
</P>
<P>
   Without the Terminal Doppler Weather Radar that is installed at
major airports, not even the air traffic controllers guiding the
pilots knew that the thunderstorm packed the severe rating of Level
6, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crew could not have known it was a Level 6 storm,'' Black
said. ``We only know that from our analysis of the Doppler weather
radar data after the accident.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather is suspected as a primary factor in Tuesday night's
fiery crash, which killed the captain and eight passengers on the
McDonnell Douglas Super 80 jetliner. At least 82 others were
injured, some critically, but 136 people survived.
</P>
<P>
   The plane _ whose pilot had aborted one landing to make the
ill-fated approach from the opposite direction _ slid off the
runway, hit a large steel stanchion supporting runway lights, broke
apart and burst into flames.
</P>
<P>
   Black said the pilots had been given regular updates on the
deteriorating weather conditions, consisting primarily of wind
speed and direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather was changing rapidly,'' Black said. ``There's even
indications the tower controller was providing sort of a
play-by-play wind direction and velocity sequence of radio
transmissions during the approach.''
</P>
<P>
   NTSB chief investigator Greg Feith described the stormy
conditions as ``a very dynamic situation, with wind conditions
changing every 20 to 30 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Feith and Black both emphasized, however, that it was up to the
plane's captain, not the controllers, to decide whether to land or
divert to another airport.
</P>
<P>
   The controllers initially cleared the aircraft to land from the
north on Runway 22-Left. Informed of the shifting wind, the pilots
then requested permission to land on the same runway, but from the
south.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft touched down about 2,000 feet down the 7,200-foot
runway but then veered off the concrete, went over an embankment at
the end of the runway, hit a steel support for runway lights and
broke in two, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they have not determined the plane's speed
when it touched down, whether it was blown off the runway by a
strong wind gust or whether the aircraft's tires hydroplaned on the
wet pavement, causing the plane to go out of control, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane crashed at 11:51 p.m., when airport winds were clocked
as high as 35 mph. Within five minutes, the safety board said, a
gust of more than 80 mph was recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Burnett, a former safety board chairman, said the pilots had
enough information about the tumultuous storm that they never
should have tried to land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to race a thunderstorm to the airport is like trying to
race a locomotive to the railroad crossing,'' said Burnett, who
served as safety board chairman from 1982 to 1988 and is now a
Clinton, Ark., lawyer and transportation safety consultant. ``Even
if you tie, you're in bad shape. And this airplane tied.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Baker, American's executive vice president of operations,
cautioned against speculation blaming the pilot for the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, he said, must learn ``exactly what the facts are
regarding the wind velocity and direction ... exactly when that
airplane was making the approach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to want to try to figure out exactly what the
\Rcockpit\S crew knew. What did the tower tell them? What did the
en route \Rair traffic control\S center tell them? Did the crew
have the information to make an intelligent decision? And then what
were the actual wind conditions?''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett also said pilot fatigue could have played a role in the
decision to land rather than divert to another airport.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Richard Buschmann, 48, the pilot who was killed, and
Michael Origel,the co-pilot who survived with a broken leg, had
been on duty 13 hours, 20 minutes at the time of the crash. The
limit for American pilots is 14 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked longer than 14 hours yesterday, but nothing I did
affected the lives and safety of anyone,'' Burnett said. ``With
pilots, the last thing they do at the end of a 14-hour shift is
land an airplane, which is the most difficult part of any flight.
They were called upon to make value judgments as well as to use
their flying skills to bring that airplane down safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 14 hours is just too long for pilots to work.
Eventually something will go wrong, like it did here.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett also said the accident might have been averted if the
airport had the Federal Aviation Administration's state-of-the-art
Terminal Doppler Weather Radar, which could have given controllers
better information about the position and intensity of the
thunderstorm approaching the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The sophisticated radar system has been installed at such major
U.S. airports as Dallas/Fort Worth Airport, Dallas' Love Field and
Houston's George Bush Intercontinental, but smaller airports such
as Little Rock's were not budgeted to get the multimillion-dollar
system.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett, who left the safety board in 1991 while the Terminal
Doppler Weather Radar program was being developed, said he was
pressured by the federal Office of Management and Budget ``not to
advocate a lot of these radar systems'' because of their expense.
</P>
<P>
   The Doppler radar was developed in direct response to the deadly
1985 crash of Delta Air Lines Flight 191 at D/FW Airport, which was
attributed to a microburst of wind from a thunderstorm over the
airport as the pilot of the Lockheed L-1011 tried to land.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., chairman of the House Committee on
Transportation and Infrastructure, questioned why the Little Rock
airport did not have the Terminal Doppler Weather Radar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike the system at Little Rock now, this radar could warn
the pilot in advance that dangerous winds were developing,'' he
said. ``There is no reason that airports like Little Rock should be
lacking the latest in weather prediction technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Rock has a regional Doppler weather radar facility about
seven miles northeast of the airport, but it does not provide the
detailed information about wind shear and microbursts _ highly
localized, high-speed downward blasts of wind _ that an airport
Doppler system is designed to detect, safety board officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The airport does have a less-sophisticated, low-level wind-shear
alert system with sensors that measure wind speed and direction. A
computer links the sensors and compares their information to give
controllers information about wind shear _ rapid changes in wind
speed and direction that can be deadly to a low-flying aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   That system alerted controllers to wind shear as Flight 1420
approached the airport, and that information was relayed to the
pilots, Black said. (Staff writer Maria Recio contributed to this
report, which contains material from The Associated Press.)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
