<HEADER>
A2651 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HN     06-04 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MILWAUKEE _ Wednesday's guarded optimism turned into Thursday's
false hope, and today the Astros find themselves in the same rut
that has plagued them throughout their lengthy stretch of mediocre
play.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Too little offense, too many lapses in the field and just enough
mistakes on the mound add up to defeat. That was the
all-too-familiar story line in Thursday's 4-1 loss to the Milwaukee
Brewers at County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros managed just seven hits Thursday and only 21 in the
three-game series. They are hitting .195 in their last 15 games,
going 7-8 during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's would-be breakout (nine hits, nine runs) seemed like
ancient history Thursday when the Astros were shut down by Steve
Woodard, Eric Plunk and Bob Wickman.
</P>
<P>
   ``After (Wednesday's) game, I said I wasn't sure if that meant
we were ready to break out,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
``It sure didn't look that way today.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewers manager Phil Garner said of Woodward, ``Even though I
didn't think he was as sharp as I've seen him in the past, he did
manage to hold them down. He used more off-speed pitches today, and
even though he wasn't as sharp with them as I've seen him in the
past, he stayed out of trouble by going to his off-speed (stuff).''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' run came on Bill Spiers' home run in the second
inning. They advanced only two runners into scoring position after
that.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Shane Reynolds gave up four runs on nine hits,
including a pair of solo homers by Brewers catcher Dave Nilsson,
who was 3-for-3 and scored three runs. Reynolds lasted 5 innings,
his shortest outing since the Expos knocked him out after three
innings May 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane was below normal in terms of his velocity,'' Dierker
said. ``He obviously didn't pitch one of his better games. But the
bottom line is that you have to score more than one run if you're
going to win most games.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds was 4-1 with a 2.65 ERA in April but dropped off to 3-3
with a 4.69 ERA in May. He is 2-4 with a 5.45 ERA in his last six
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been having trouble getting into a groove, and I never
could get into one today as far as getting the ball down.''
Reynolds said. ``It was just a situation of them capitalizing on my
bad pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson made sure the Astros' one-run lead didn't last long when
he launched a hanging splitter into the right-field bleachers in
the bottom of the second. The lefthanded slugger hit three home
runs and a double in his final six at-bats of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one was just a bad pitch,'' Reynolds said. ``Everyone
knows my out pitch is the splitter, and he was sitting on it. When
they're waiting on the split and it's not a good one, they're going
to hit it. They have a good-hitting lineup, and you have to give
those guys credit. They did their job, and I didn't do mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson struck again in the fourth, and Mark Loretta singled
home Geoff Jenkins to give the Brewers a 3-1 lead in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never hit Shane Reynolds at all,'' said Nilsson. ``I
think if you'd speak to him, he'd say they were mistakes. When
you're going well, that's what you hit is a lot of mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds was knocked out of the game in the sixth, but he might
have been able to hang around a little longer with some help from
center fielder Carl Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson led off the sixth with a deep fly to center field.
Everett drifted to the warning track and seemed in position to make
the catch but mistimed his leap and came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ball should have been caught,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds quickly retired the next two batters, which meant he
would have been out of the inning had Everett prevented Nilsson's
double.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just missed it,'' Everett said. ``I should have caught it;
that's all there is to it. I drifted and didn't come up with it. I
don't know what kind of leap that was. The ball landed in my
footprint. I may miss another one, but I won't miss another one
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins made the Astros pay for their fielding snafu, stroking a
two-out, two-strike RBI double to left field. Second-guessers might
question why Reynolds pitched to Jenkins with the pitcher's spot
next in the order.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker visited the mound to discuss the situation with his
righthander, and they agreed to take their chances with Jenkins. It
turned out to be a moot point because Brewers manager Phil Garner
sent Rich Becker out to hit for Woodard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew the pitcher wasn't going to bat,'' Reynolds
said. ``I thought I made good pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   But on a day when the offense returned to its struggling ways,
it wasn't enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
