<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HEALTH-APPOINT-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-SURGEON GENERAL CHOSEN FOR HEALTH CHIEF BY PATAKI
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ After a protracted search, Gov. George Pataki
nominated Dr. Antonia C. Novello, the former U.S. surgeon general,
as New York's health commissioner on Thursday, drawing cries of
betrayal from the abortion rights movement because Dr. Novello,
unlike the governor, opposes abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing her at a news conference, Pataki praised Dr.
Novello for her extensive experience in public health. He said she
had been a trailblazer in addressing children's health issues and
would help lead the state's effort to save money by moving
recipients of Medicaid, the health care program for the poor, into
managed care.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has devoted her life to public health issues,'' Pataki
said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor generally supports abortion rights but adopted that
position later in his career, and some abortion rights groups
remain wary about his dedication to their cause. Questioned on
Thursday about abortion, Pataki declared that Dr. Novello would
carry out his policies rather than impose her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The policies of this state with respect to a woman's right to
choose are not going to change,'' he said. ``They are not set by
the health commissioner. They are set by the executive and the
Legislature. I am pro-choice. We will continue to protect a woman's
right to choose, and continue to protect a low-income person's
access to Medicaid funding, if that is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Novello, 54, a pediatrician by training, said her beliefs _
she opposes abortion except in the case of rape, incest or a threat
to the health of the mother _ would not influence her work. ``My
personal and private opinion has nothing to do, now or ever, with
the performance of my duties,'' she said. She declined to discuss
the issue further.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has been seeking to add luster to his standing in
the national Republican party, which is dominated by politicians
opposed to abortion. With Dr. Novello, he is turning to a figure
who was popular with some conservatives for her abortion stance.
</P>
<P>
   It was not lost in the State Capitol on Thursday that Dr.
Novello served as surgeon general under President George Bush,
whose son, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, is considered the
front-runner in the race for the Republican presidental nomination.
Pataki endorsed Governor Bush last week, and Pataki aides said
Pataki would like to be considered for the Republican
vice-presidential choice.
</P>
<P>
   As a state legislator in the late 1980s, Pataki opposed abortion
but he later switched. While he does now favor abortion rights, he
has supported some restrictions, including a ban on the procedure
that opponents call partial-birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination for health commissioner requires approval by the
State Senate, which is controlled by Pataki's Republican allies,
and Dr. Novello is expected to win backing there easily. She would
be paid $197,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The job has been open since late last year, when Dr. Barbara A.
DeBuono, who was supported by lawmakers of both major parties,
resigned to become a hospital executive. Dr. DeBuono favored
abortion rights, as did her predecessors dating back to the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   As surgeon general from 1990 to 1993, Dr. Novello, the first
Hispanic person and woman to hold the job, repeatedly chastised
tobacco companies for what she said were marketing campaigns aimed
at children and sought to broaden public health efforts for people
in minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   Since stepping down as surgeon general, she has worked at the
United Nations Children's Fund and Johns Hopkins University.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the aspect of her career that came under the most scrutiny
here on Thursday was her position on abortion and her support for a
rule adopted by President Bush that prohibited workers at family
planning programs receiving federal financing from discussing
abortion with their patients. President Clinton revoked the rule in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference on Thursday, Dr. Novello declined to
disavow that rule, but she pointed out that it was enforced by
other officials in the Bush administration, not the surgeon
general. She sought to focus her comments on her pleasure at
winning the appointment. ``I want to pledge to the governor, and I
want to pledge to the people of New York, that I will represent
them strongly and compassionately,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some abortion rights groups reacted angrily to the nomination,
as did several Democratic lawmakers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
