<HEADER>
A2654 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-CHARISMATIC-HNS &LR;      06-04 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-CHARISMATIC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Twenty-six years ago, Secretariat provided a
thrill unequaled in horse racing's voluminous history when he won
the Belmont Stakes by 31 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Chenery, owner of that massive burnished chestnut colt,
recalls: ``He was in another gear. When you watch the tapes, his
stride never changes. He doesn't accelerate. He looks as if he
could do that forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Chenery is rooting for a descendant of Secretariat, a
similarly colored and well-sized colt. She says ``it would be
wonderful'' if Charismatic on Saturday joins Secretariat and only
10 other equine gods in becoming a Triple Crown winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, he's the same color and he has four white feet
instead of three,'' she says, comparing Charismatic and his
maternal great-grandfather. But she adds, ``He doesn't quite look
like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't strike me that he runs with the same force.
Secretariat dived with his head to get his hindquarters off the
ground. A.P. Indy had a running style like that, but I don't know
that Charismatic does.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Lukas, trainer of Charismatic, agrees: ``We're not talking
Secretariat here. I'm going to be optimistically guarded about our
chances in the Belmont.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chenery feels Charismatic is unfairly downgraded for
being put up for sale in a couple of $62,500 claiming races.
</P>
<P>
   She argues: ``If Wayne had realized earlier _ and this is a
criticism he himself made _ that Charismatic was like Secretariat,
a horse that needs a lot of hard work, he would not have been a
claimer. That will forever tarnish his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had he been recognized as having the Secretariat training
needs, he might be looking at a career with only a couple of
defeats _ and in greater races.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lewis, owner of Charismatic, raised no objection when Lukas
recommended entering the colt for a tag. ``I felt we needed to stop
the bleeding,'' Lewis says.
</P>
<P>
   The two horsemen can be excused for discounting Charismatic's
breeding. Few of Secretariat's offspring distinguished themselves
on the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Chenery remembers how Secretariat in the 1980s was ``a dud in
the stud _ I heard that all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But subsequent generations have vindicated the bloodline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a classic pattern,'' she says, ``where a champion
stallion passes his genes through his daughters.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Charismatic a great-grandson of Secretariat, the
colt is inbred to both the sire (Bold Ruler) and dam (Something
Royal) of Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Roach, who along with former Houstonian Will Farish was a
co-breeder of Charismatic, says, ``He's probably got more
Secretariat in his bloodlines than any horse in America, without it
being dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Roach saw a trace of the equine immortal when Charismatic
charged through an outside lane on the far turn of Pimlico. He says
it was ``the best move I've ever seen in the Preakness other than
Secretariat's on the first turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Charismatic's Secretariat-loaded genes and
strong-closing style, Lukas is confident the Belmont's 1{ miles
will be no strain.
</P>
<P>
   Chenery remembers, however, the doubts surrounding her horse
even as he separated from the Belmont field. His sire, Bold Ruler,
had turned out tremendous speed in his children but limited
stamina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know he would win it when he opened up in the far
turn,'' Chenery says. ``We were still thinking, `Bold Rulers can't
go a mile and a half.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her only regret is that she and trainer Lucien Laurin sometimes
failed to recognize Secretariat's peculiar needs: ``I feel his few
defeats were ours and not his. We didn't manage him consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Chenery now is reliving the Secretariat moment _
actually two minutes and 24 seconds, beating the Belmont track
record by two seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Secretariat should have been called Charismatic,'' she
says, ``because he had such an attraction for people. After he went
to stud, he became even more popular. Claiborne Farms booked tours
so people could see him, even in the breeding season.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she believes there ever will be another horse as great
as her ``Big Red,'' Chenery says, ``I'll be disappointed when he's
supplanted, but I'm sure there will be another horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody suggests Charismatic is the one. But maybe he's close
enough to do what no horse has done since Affirmed in 1978: sweep
the Triple Crown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
