<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2655 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-FRENCH-HNS &LR;      06-04 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PARIS _ Steffi Graf has changed her mind. Only recently, like just
a couple of weeks ago, Graf was of the opinion Wimbledon offered
the best opportunity for her to resume pursuing Margaret Court's
record for Grand Slam championships.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I think it's Paris,'' Graf said Thursday, relishing a
profoundly satisfying three-set victory over Monica Seles in a
wind-whipped, rain-delayed, nostalgia-laden French Open semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Graf thinks this because, after defeating her one-time nemesis
Seles 6-7 (7-2), 6-3, 6-4, she is one match away from a sixth
Roland Garros title and her 22nd in the Slams, which would leave
her two behind Court. A frustrating year that had her contemplating
retirement suddenly has turned promising. Nobody, Graf included,
could have predicted the remarkable French fortnight she has
enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to play it down,'' she said of her lack of
self-confidence, brought on by a scarred, 29-year-old body that
keeps wanting to betray her. ``But deep down I didn't believe I
would be (in the final). There have been a lot of moments where I
haven't really been very happy about the way I was playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I came here to get a few matches before Wimbledon,
not really thinking I'd be doing that well.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the most severe test looms. Next up Saturday is Martina
Hingis, who has surpassed Graf as the top woman player in the
world. Hingis routed Graf's contemporary and last year's winner,
Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, 6-3, 6-2 to serve notice she's ready to
complete a career Slam before the age of 19, a Steffi-sized feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope she will be a little nervous,'' Hingis said of Graf,
who is competing in her first Slam final since reconstructive knee
surgery forced her into a yearlong sabbatical. Wrist surgery
followed last fall after a third-round Wimbledon flameout and a
fourth-round U.S. Open loss. She also recently has undergone a
minor foot operation.
</P>
<P>
   Graf's last triumph in a major came at Flushing Meadow in 1996.
But as for a nerves attack she suggests Hingis had best not hold
her breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obviously feel I don't have to prove anything,'' Graf said.
``For sure, I think that's going to work for me.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1987 through last year, Graf or Seles won at Roland Garros
on all but four occasions, with three championships going to
Sanchez Vicario. In a battle befitting their stature as the two
most accomplished players of the decade, Graf and Seles made their
15th meeting one of the most memorable in the series (led by Graf
10-5) despite the nasty conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Graf chipped away at Seles with a mixed bag of old-fashioned
howitzer forehands, delicately sliced backhands and the occasional
drop shot. Seles answered with her usual barrage of grunt-driven
two-fisted blasts from the baseline, putting Graf in a 3-0 bind at
the outset and then holding on to take the tiebreaker convincingly.
</P>
<P>
   But Seles' game is more sensitive to blustery conditions, and
she began to lose her edge as the wind gained strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just never felt comfortable,'' she said. ``It was difficult.
I couldn't get my racket through quick enough, and I made way too
many errors because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf's crucial break at 4-all in the third came with her
returning into the face of the gale. Undaunted, she hammered back a
series of forehands with everything she had, and Seles, back on her
heels, blinked. Graf served out the match at love.
</P>
<P>
   ``After match point,'' she said, ``it was extreme joy for me.
It's a great, great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Which lasted only until the questions about the challenge Hingis
presents began. Graf admitted Hingis would be a load even if her
tired legs didn't feel so heavy.
</P>
<P>
   Of the final she said: ``I think that's looking too far ahead.
It's a great showing to just be able to play on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis is a huge hurdle, no question. Rarely has a defending
champion been given less of a shot going in than Sanchez Vicario
received against her. The cocky, clever Swiss miss had beaten the
27-year-old Spaniard nine times in 10 meetings, suggesting a
competitive imbalance that wouldn't be easily overcome no matter
how many French titles the latter had collected.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanchez Vicario never had been forced to go through Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sanchez Vicario's dogged retrieving still serves her
well against lesser players, Hingis' shot-making skills put more of
an onus on an opponent to play proactively, and such is not Sanchez
Vicario's counterpunching style. Ultimately, one must force
openings to thwart Hingis, and again she couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica played better today,'' Sanchez Vicario said. ``I had
chances, but I couldn't take advantage of enough of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The top seed and No. 1-ranked player prevailed in a perfunctory
first set, building a 5-0 lead after a drenching thunderstorm
pushed back the start of play. Then, breaking twice, Hingis blew
out to a 3-0 second-set bulge in just 10 minutes before suffering
another lapse in concentration, fooling Sanchez Vicario into
believing she might have a decent chance to regroup.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Losing her serve in the fourth game brought back Hingis' focus,
and she promptly closed out the match in short order. A punishing
inside-out forehand provided the felling blow, propelling her into
a second Roland Garros final in three years. Iva Majoli had
thwarted Hingis' bid for a Grand Slam here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Again Saturday, she faces a woman with vastly more experience on
Court Central and a far more impressive rsum. But the consequences
of same seem fairly inconsequential considering how Hingis is
playing after her lost year in '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's either Steffi or Monica,'' she had said merrily,
``it doesn't matter. They both have won many times. I'd be happy to
win once. They can leave one for me, no?''
</P>
<P>
   Probably yes. But against Graf, she will have to earn it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
