<SLUG> BC-CALIFORNIA-SNOW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL NINO HANGOVER BRINGS JUNE SNOW TO SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Record rainfall fell in Chatsworth. Santa Clarita
had hail. A funnel cloud hovered over San Pedro -- and snow fell on
mountain passes.
</P>
<P>
   Strange days indeed for the first week of June in Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures are expected to warm up Saturday, with partly
cloudy skies and highs near 70, but not before another round of
drizzle Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have thunderstorms around _ there's no doubt
about it,'' said Gary Ryan, meteorologist with the National Weather
Service office in Oxnard, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   And commuters this morning could awaken to a closed Grapevine
through the Tehachapi Mountains, as temperatures dip to freezing.
Snow fell in Frazier Park on Thursday and could reach as low as
5,000 feet overnight, with accumulations of 3 to 6 inches possible
above 6,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very low for this time of the year,'' Ryan said. ``The
whole system is unusual and they never come this far south.''
</P>
<P>
   While Southern California shivered, on the other coast, Boston
was baking with a high of 84 degrees, compared with 66 in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Common, Public Garden and Swan Boats were packed with
people soaking in weather more typical of late summer than late
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``One person described it to me. They said, `How do you like
this August weather in June?','' said Bea Flammia, special events
director at Boston's historic Ritz-Carlton hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little warm and muggy, but we love it,'' she said. ``It
is a beautiful day to be out in the garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Rain in June is odd enough, but measurable amounts are even more
rare. Rainfall was expected to range from a half-inch in the
foothills to a quarter-inch downtown late Thursday and into today.
</P>
<P>
   The 0.05 of an inch recorded in Chatsworth, at the city of Los
Angeles' northern reach, for the 24 hours ending at 5 p.m. Thursday
topped the record for a June 3, which was a trace in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Record rainfall for the date also was reported at:
</P>
<P>
   --Los Angeles International Airport, with 0.05 of an inch
compared with 0.02 in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   --Pasadena, with 0.23 of an inch compared with 0.08 in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   --Mount Wilson, with 0.38 of an inch compared with 0.04 in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   --Long Beach, with 0.02 compared with a trace in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   --UCLA, with 0.08 compared with 0.02 in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   The wet roads made for dangerous driving. The Los Angeles Police
Department reported a fatal, single-car crash related to the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Climatologists attribute the unseasonable weather to the El Nino
hangover. The El Nino weather pattern that brought record rain in
1997-98 was followed by the cold and dry La Nina pattern over the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You expect to go back to normal, but we're not back to
normal,'' said Bill Patzert, a satellite oceanographer at the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena. ``The climate system is really
still out of balance and so we're getting a lot of unexpected
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get this much rain in June is really unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather system moving across the basin Thursday and into
today is a low pressure area dropping from the Gulf of Alaska that
contains unseasonably cold air.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said overnight lows were expected to drop near 50, which
compares with lows typically near 60 degrees. Today's highs should
reach into the upper 60s, which compares with highs typically in
the high 70s to lower 80s.
</P>
<P>
   The mountain lows and forecast for snow left motel managers
wondering whether Caltrans might close the Golden State Freeway,
sending motorists in search of lodging. That's what happened in
April when the last unseasonably cold weather hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past time that it snowed, we had people sleeping in the
hallways and the lobby. We had people that didn't even know each
other sharing rooms,'' said Laura Mendiola, who helps run the
54-room Caravan Motor Inn in Gorman, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans officials said there were no planned closures, but snow
and ice can change the driving climate quickly on the Grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't usually see this kind of stuff to start June off
with,'' said Sgt. Tim Kappen, night shift supervisor for the
California Highway Patrol's truck stop at Castaic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
