<HEADER>
A2660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANES-WEATHER-1STLD-     06-04 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANES-WEATHER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRREGULAR SETTINGS FOUND IN PLANE THAT CRASHED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating new top of story) (sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Devices to slow a plane's landing appear to have
been deployed irregularly as an American Airlines jet touched down
in Little Rock, Ark., on Tuesday before crashing, killing 9 people
on board, an air safety official said.
</P>
<P>
   But the official, George W. Black, the member of the National
Transportation Safety Board who is in charge at the scene, drew no
conclusions about what role the irregularities played in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Information from the flight data recorder show that thrust
reversers, which make the engines brake the plane, were set up in
an unusual way in the last seconds of the jet's skid down the
runway, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Eight seconds before the end of the data, he said, the recorder
showed that the left thrust reverser was deployed but the right one
was not. Thrust reversers are usually used in tandem, to prevent
uneven forces that could make the plane turn.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said, the reversers had been opened and closed twice
moments before the crash. That would be unusual in a normal
landing.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, when one thrust reverser was deployed and the
other was not, the engines were near idle. Usually if the plane is
still moving fast, the engines are at higher power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that the only person who knows the answer to that
question is no longer with us,'' Black said of the captain, who was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts said it was possible that one of the reversers was
damaged in the landing, but that asymmetric deployment of thrust
reversers can cause an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Black also said that the spoilers, devices that pop up on the
tops of the wings to spoil lift and make sure the plane stays on
the ground, did not deploy on landing.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Thursday, Black said that air traffic controllers had
given detailed weather information to the pilot of the jet before
and even while it crash-landed in high winds and rain at Little
Rock National Airport on Tuesday. But he did not say whether that
information should have led the pilot to abort the landing.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty were also injured in the fiery crash of the MD-80.
</P>
<P>
   Two wind-shear alerts had been issued before the crash, but
officials have yet to determine how major a factor the weather was
in the crash, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   The flight touched down with plenty of room for a controlled
landing under normal conditions but slid right and then left before
plowing off the end of the runway at high speed, investigators
said.
</P>
<P>
   Black praised the flow of information from the control tower to
the pilot about the wind conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe they provided even more than they'd get at a busier
airport, because it appears they were getting periodic wind
vectors,'' he said of the descriptions of wind direction and speed.
``Actually, they continued to give wind vectors after the aircraft
had already crashed. They didn't know it had crashed.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service tracked a powerful thunderstorm
approaching the runway from the northwest as the plane, Flight
1420, came in from the southwest. But thunderstorms are localized
phenomena, and Black took pains to note that the storm had not
reached the airport at the time of the crash. Safety board
investigators are trying to reconstruct weather conditions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As investigators here and in Arkansas examined evidence from the
plane, including the flight data recorder and cockpit voice
recorder, the Federal Aviation Administration began looking into
the characteristics of the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Spitaliere, a spokeswoman, said that since the late 1980s
the agency had required 1,000-foot overrun areas at the ends of new
runways. The runway involved in the crash does not have one, and
the airport had evidently been given a waiver, but officials were
not immediately sure why.
</P>
<P>
   The airport authority, Ms. Spitaliere said, has been planning to
install an ``arrestor bed,'' a long pad of crushable concrete
designed to stop runaway planes, next year.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 1420, with 145 people on board, was landing on Runway 4
Right, which at 7,200 feet is typical for a runway for big jets,
but is 1,073 feet shorter than Runway 4 Left.
</P>
<P>
   The two runways have the same equipment for handling instrument
landings, but only the right one has big steel light standards at
the end of the runway, which the American Airlines jet struck after
landing and losing control. The jet split open and burst into
flames after that impact.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were not certain which of the two men in the
cockpit was flying the plane, although they said they believe it
was the captain, Richard Buschmann, who was killed in the crash,
with communications being handled by the first officer, Michael
Origel. Origel was hospitalized and investigators hoped to talk to
him on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how the plane executed its approach is not yet known.
</P>
<P>
   In general, pilots approaching runways in bad weather increase
speed, to counter the danger of shifting winds. A headwind that
suddenly reduces in speed, or turns into a tailwind, can cut a
plane's speed through the air to the point where the craft becomes
uncontrollable.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the air speed to compensate for the wind conditions
would also make the plane somewhat harder to stop on a slick
runway. Black said that investigators would measure the traction of
the runway where Flight 1420 landed, which is grooved for better
water drainage.
</P>
<P>
   When flying in a crosswind, as the airplane was doing, normal
procedure is to approach in a ``crab'' position, with the nose
pointed into the wind, which in this case would have been somewhat
to the left of the plane's course over the ground. If the plane
were pointed straight ahead, the wind would blow it to the right.
</P>
<P>
   But to avoid landing sideways, according to pilots, just before
touchdown the crew would align the plane with the runway, dip the
left wing into a slight bank, and move the rudder slightly to the
right, to keep the plane moving straight over the ground. That
would make the left landing gear touch down first.
</P>
<P>
   A swept-wing jet like the one that crashed acts like a weather
vane, its nose seeking to point straight into the wind. The MD-80
is slightly longer than many other planes and shows that tendency
more strongly.
</P>
<P>
   A gust just before landing, or just after, could twist the
plane, experts said, although it is too soon to say that happened
in this case. If the plane were not pointed straight down the
runway when the crew engaged the thrust reversers, that, too, would
tend to twist its course.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's crash was the airport's second weather-related crash
in recent years. A 21-seat Gulfstream II jet crashed there in
January 1990, killing all seven people aboard. The safety board
attributed the crash to pilot errors and a faulty weather
instrument on the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
