</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WHITSITT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITSITT HAS TRAIL BLAZERS ON TITLE TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Paul Allen, billionaire owner of the Portland
Trail Blazers, usually sits courtside for home games at the Rose
Garden, near his team's bench and with a guest to his left.
</P>
<P>
   Often on his right is one of his best investments in the past
five years _ Bob Whitsitt, the team president and general manager
he got from the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers are playing in the NBA Western Conference finals
Friday night in Portland largely because of Whitsitt. From the
coach to each name on the roster, he added every facet of this
team.
</P>
<P>
   And all it cost Allen to get him, besides Whitsitt's salary, was
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   According to the mutual release agreement between Whitsitt and
the Sonics, any NBA team that signed him within 12 months of his
release owed the Sonics that sum.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. Whitsitt joined Portland three weeks after leaving
Seattle, where he had been team president for eight years, and the
Blazers fullfilled the June 20, 1994 agreement by writing a total
of four $125,000 checks over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   The Post-Intelligencer obtained a copy of the previously
confidential agreement from a source close to the league.
</P>
<P>
   What seemed like a small sum at the time is paying big dividends
for the Blazers. They are playing for a trip to the NBA Finals for
the first time since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances surrounding Whitsitt's departure from the
Sonics remain unclear. He says he was fired, although he did sign
the agreement and sent a memo to owner Barry Ackerley on May 25,
1994, asking for his release. The Sonics refuse to comment
officially but believe Whitsitt wanted to go to Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt, 42, had offers from about six teams at the time he was
available. Vancouver and Portland made the strongest pitches.
Whitsitt said he chose the Blazers because of their tradition and
owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mature operation with a great track record,'' Whitsitt
said. ``Plus, Paul genuinely wants to win a championship. And I'm
not just saying that.''
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving in Portland, he has transformed the oldest team
in the NBA to the fourth-youngest, the deepest and most versatile
team in the league. The player who has been with the Blazers the
longest is center Arvydas Sabonis, who is in only his fourth
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't argue with success,'' backup point guard Greg
Anthony said. ``Bob knows what he is doing. He's aggressive and
that's how you have to be in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   A Blazer game is one of those rare occasions you will find
Whitsitt idle.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, he spins the wheels on his car and in his head about
the same: Hard and fast.
</P>
<P>
   If Whitsitt is not physically transporting himself from Portland
to Seattle _ where he moonlights as president of the NFL's Seahawks
_ his mind is in motion on eyebrow-raising deals.
</P>
<P>
   What Whitsitt did was make 12 lively trades that eventually
yielded 11 players picked in the lottery without actually making
those draft choices himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes to be a little more aggressive and more of a
risk-taker can cost you your job. You may not go very far, but you
may keep your job,'' Whitsitt said. ``We've always taken the
position that we owe it to the fans to do everything we can
possibly do to make our team a good as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   An easy workday is 12 hours. A tough day could be 16 to 18. He
seems to work seven days a week doing homework and legwork, acting
on his vision.
</P>
<P>
   A source of pride for Whitsitt is the Blazers are an
inexperienced group that seldom plays like one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these players on (contending) teams are 33, 34, 35
years old when they get to this level,'' Whitsitt said, ``So it
gets pretty exciting to know that we're a good basketball team now
and we should could continue to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt had to grow on the Blazer faithful. After all, he came
from the hated Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have given them free money and they wouldn't like
me,'' Whitsitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt also was the one who had to break up the veteran team
that made the 1992 Finals. That included trading All-Star Clyde
Drexler to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked to be traded,'' Whitsitt recalled. ``But even if a
guy asks to be traded, if he's popular fans aren't going to like it
... It seems like I'm always the guy who has to climb and build.''
</P>
<P>
   In case you did not know, scaling obstacles is Whitsitt's forte.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were a 31-win team when he arrived in Seattle.
Ackerley hired the then-30-year-old Whitsitt in 1986, making him
the youngest team president in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Under Whitsitt's watch with George Karl as his coach, they won
the franchise's second Pacific Division championship, played in the
Western Conference finals, posted astonishing regular-season
records and developed Shawn Kemp and Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   However, Whitsitt's Sonics missed the playoffs in 1990. His
63-win team lost to Denver in the first round in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The first-round debacle led to a strange series of events.
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt, who was named Executive of the Year, was locked out of
his office less than a week after he requested his release in the
memo to Ackerley.
</P>
<P>
   The tumultuous and baffling period ended with Whitsitt's
departure before the NBA draft. That would have been the last time
Whitsitt legitmately drafted a lottery player.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd had been there it would have turned into Eddie Jones
(10th overall pick), or worst case Jalen Rose (13th pick),'' said
Whitsitt, who watched the Sonics take Carlos Rogers with the 11th
pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind that if I had stayed in Seattle we
would have won a championship. We were pretty close to the top of
the mountain. ... Having said that, I'm very happy where I am and
our future looks pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   And Whitsitt has found his way near the top again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three of the four teams standing do it the way we do it,''
Whitsitt said. ``Look at the depth of New York, the depth of
Indiana and the depth of Portland. The people that tell you what
you can't do are the people who aren't playing. If we're still
playing we must be doing something right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
