<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR MARKS IN CITIZENSHIP FOR UW, WSU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Now that there is hope for peace in Yugoslavia, it's
time to bring troops home where they're needed _ protecting the
communities surrounding our state's citadels of big-time college
football.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you have read that some football players from the
University of Washington and Washington State are in danger of
scoring poorly on the citizenship part of their report cards. This
is considered serious, because the category makes up one-third of
the overall score, along with penmanship and lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Poor report cards mean big trouble for football players. They
have to work harder to stay eligible, which can mean doubling the
number of girlfriends willing to write papers under the fellas'
names.
</P>
<P>
   Such a hassle.
</P>
<P>
   When you're a football player at Humungous State U., there's so
much to remember. There's the playbook, the weight-room records,
the booster handhake$, the andro supplements, the football-loving
faculty members.
</P>
<P>
   On top of it, there is an expectation to remember right from
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Jeez, how much can be demanded of unpaid entertainers who
represent the last vestige of indentured servitude in America?
</P>
<P>
   What unfair burdens.
</P>
<P>
   So as these miscreant Huskies and Cougars think about putting on
the well-worn robes of victimhood, here's a helpful guide (clip and
save) to stick in the wallet next to the coach's phone credit card.
</P>
<P>
   1. Don't slug women. (Or men, unless it's Don King).
</P>
<P>
   2. Don't steal stuff.
</P>
<P>
   3. Don't throw furniture through frat-house windows and clobber
persons within.
</P>
<P>
   The rules are a little complicated, for sure. And since nobody
other than their mothers, fathers, grandmothers, grandfathers,
aunts and uncles had mentioned these things to them in the last
week or so, the list is easy to forget.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if just a handful of Cougars and Huskies had just known
these things, we could have kept our troops working over Belgrade
embassies and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Pending a summer-quarter class that will help the players
memorize these theorems, there is another option that can be
employed by coaches Rick Neuheisel and Mike Price to aid in
retention:
</P>
<P>
   Football suspension and denial of all athletic privileges.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to take credit for this novel suggestion, but Price
beat me to it. The Cougar coach Wednesday suspended wide receiver
and co-captain Nian Taylor, who allegedly blasted down an apartment
door in order to punch a woman in the chest. No word yet on whether
she refused to write a paper, but he was arrested and charged with
assault and malicious mischief.
</P>
<P>
   He also acted in a similar fashion with running back Kevin
Brown, wide receiver Jason White and defensive back Ramin White
after they were charged, in an unrelated episode, for stealing
$1,900 worth of electronic equipment from a Pullman apartment.
</P>
<P>
   If the players are found guilty, Price has promised to boot them
from the team, presumably including loss of scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel, however, is waiting. The Husky coach had several
players involved in a two-night fracas that resulted in $5,000
damage to a frat house near campus. Since none of the players have
been identified publicly and the issue is still under
investigation, no charges have been filed.
</P>
<P>
   But my guess is Neuheisel knows exactly what happened and who
was involved. His predecessors, Jim Lambright and Don James, knew
just about everything that went on. Some football players have a
way of making almost as many enemies as friends, and many of those
enemies are delighted to share their observations. Whether the
coaches cover up or deal honestly is a subject for another day.
</P>
<P>
   As a fan of due process, I'm a believer that the perpetrators
have a right to be heard. I also believe high school and college
athletic participation is a privilege, and it can be denied for
well-articulated team rules that are shy of legal standards.
</P>
<P>
   Scholarship revocation is a more serious matter, which requires
more due process than most athletic departments generally indulge.
Players are often so scared they don't challenge a revocation
despite what may be unfair claims.
</P>
<P>
   But most coaches are efficient in dragging the truth out of
their wayward charges. Besides, in these episodes, there were
multiple witnesses. Coaches rarely need more than a day to
determine whether a player is responsible for misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   A suspension based on a preponderance of evidence, particularly
if it cuts out meal, workout and tutorial privileges, makes a far
more persuasive statement than muddling around waiting for a court
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Word that the Huskies as individuals will pay back the frat for
damages is hardly a resolution. That's what they're supposed to do.
It's like wanting applause for driving down the right side of the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Too many players, drunk at minimum with a sense of entitlement,
need a fuller grasp of consequences than is provided in an order to
run extra sets of stairs.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, they owe it to the large number of their
teammates who are solid citizens and students to avoid creating a
rich target for wise-guy columnists.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
