<HEADLINE>
SISTER RECOUNTS VIOLENT ENCOUNTER DURING SLEEPWALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sister of accused killer Scott Falater testified Thursday
that he threw her across the room while sleepwalking more than 20
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He turned around and lifted me up and just tossed me through
the air,'' said Laura Healy, who said the incident began when she
brushed against her brother in an effort to stop him from leaving
the home.
</P>
<P>
   Healy added that her brother later had no memory of the event at
their Illinois home.
</P>
<P>
   Healy, a freelance medical editor, also testified that her
Internet research was the genesis of the legal defense that claims
Falater was sleepwalking in early 1997 when he killed his wife.
</P>
<P>
   She said her brother initially rejected her suggestion that he
was sleepwalking when he stabbed his wife 44 times in the back yard
of their Phoenix home, then hid the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Well, if you don't believe me, and you're not willing
to look at these articles, then what happened, Scott?' '' Healy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Falater's parents also testified Thursday about several
instances when he had walked in his sleep as a youth.
</P>
<P>
   The parents, who divorced when Falater was in high school,
described him as an introspective, mild-mannered boy who sometimes
wet the bed. They said he had once intervened to stop his alcoholic
father from choking his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Healy's testimony also countered Wednesday's startling
revelation by the prosecution of a potential witness who overheard
Falater, three weeks before his wife's death, discuss a Canadian
case in which a sleepwalking defense led to acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Juan Martinez hopes that that witness, likely to be
called to testify later in the trial, will help prove that Falater
committed premeditated murder of his wife of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Healy fondly recalled her brother as brainy and low-key, the one
most likely to break up fights among his four younger siblings. She
drew smiles from the jury when she described him as ``a nerd (who)
wore that plastic pocket protector'' in his shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Healy's testimony also countered Martinez's theory that her
brother's marriage had turned sour by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   She described a Dec. 27 trip to Sedona for a Jeep tour with
Scott and Yarmila Falater and their two children, Megan and
Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Healy read to the jury an e-mail she received from Falater after
the trip. In it, he expressed affection for his wife, whom he would
kill about three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Megan is always ragging on Yarm and me because she claims
we're always making out in front of her. . . . We have more fun
kissing in front of her just to tease her,'' Falater wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor is seeking to undermine the credibility of more
than a dozen defense witnesses who have described Falater as a
loving husband, dedicated father, faithful Mormon and respected
engineer at Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's session in Maricopa County Superior Court is scheduled
to begin with testimony from a witness who originally testified for
the defense but later contacted the prosecution with potentially
damaging information about Falater.
</P>
<P>
   With the jury out of the courtroom, Motorola colleague Randy
Keadle is expected to tell Judge Ronald Reinstein about information
he received that Falater may have once dragged his daughter up some
steps by her hair.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has indicated in court that Keadle also may talk about
another Motorola worker, who allegedly overheard Falater talk about
the Canada sleepwalking case.
</P>
<P>
   That third Motorola worker is secretary Debbie James, already a
witness for the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Reinstein said he will announce Friday whether he will permit
testimony from Ann Walker, a former neighbor of the Falaters and a
nurse practitioner who allegedly provided Yarmila Falater with
information about a venereal disease. Martinez said Walker will
testify that she told Yarmila that Scott had been ``mess ing
around.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
