<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOLEST-PASTOR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TACOMA YOUTH PASTOR CHARGED IN MOLESTATION OF BOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACK HOPKINS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TACOMA, Wash. _ The youth pastor at one of Tacoma's largest
churches was charged with eight counts of rape and child
molestation Thursday for what police say was part of a
four-year-long series of sexual assaults on at least 17 children _
most of them members of his congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Herman Glenn of Bethel Christian Assembly Church
pressured the 13- to 15-year-old boys into having sex with him by
convincing them he had an evil alter ego he couldn't get rid of
without their sexual favors, prosecutors said in papers filed in
Pierce County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, 34 and youth pastor at the 2,000-member church since
1991, made up an elaborate video-style game with codes and
passwords to ensnare the youths in the sexual activity, police and
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   He led them to believe the sexual activity occurred while he was
sleepwalking, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of mind control was involved in it,'' said Pierce County
Sheriff's Department spokesman Ed Troyer.
</P>
<P>
   Bethel Christian Assembly Executive Pastor Julie Jenkins said
Thursday the church had no warning there was any problem with
Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   But court and police documents indicate that in 1993, two years
after Glenn's arrival in Tacoma, the church received a telephone
call from a Chicago-area church where Glenn had previously worked
warning that allegations of inappropriate touching had been made
against Glenn by two young boys.
</P>
<P>
   The Tacoma church sent Glenn to a counselor, who dismissed the
incident as ``experimenting'' by a young person, court documents
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins would not reveal the name of the Chicago-area church.
</P>
<P>
   None of the alleged sexual assaults took place in the church,
Troyer said. They occurred at Glenn's apartment in University Place
and at other locations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bethel Christian Assembly learned of the activity Tuesday
afternoon after a church elder became suspicious and confronted
Glenn at a revival service. The youth pastor confessed to raping or
molesting 17 children and resigned his church post, according to
court records.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn then wrote letters of apology to church officials and his
victims, telling the teenagers they weren't responsible for the
sexual activity and he hoped they could forgive him, prosecutors
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My prayer is that the Christ of heaven will bring complete
healing to your heart and life and that you will not allow my sin
to be a lasting destruction to your walk with Jesus Christ,'' he
said in his letter to the
</P>
<P>
   youths.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials immediately notified the sheriff's department,
touching off a round-the-clock investigation that led to filing of
the eight charges Thursday after-
</P>
<P>
   noon. Glenn was charged with six counts of third-degree rape,
one count of second-degree rape and one count of child molestation
resulting from alleged sex acts.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, who is being held in the Pierce County Jail in lieu of
$75,000 bail, pleaded not guilty at his arraignment on the criminal
charges that carry a potential penalty of life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors told Pierce County Superior Court Judge Sergio
Armijo that the eight charges involved only two of the victims and
more charges are likely to be filed.
</P>
<P>
   Police and church officials said none of the children _ some of
whom are now adults _ ever accused Glenn of sexually assaulting
them.
</P>
<P>
   Police praised church officials for contacting them about the
matter immediately after learning of the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church has been fully cooperative and very timely in
this,'' said Troyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were shocked and devastated by this, and all of our energy
is focused on assisting those who have suffered,'' Jenkins said,
adding that the church is offering counseling to the victims of the
alleged assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the report of the local counselor to which Glenn was
sent and the lack of criminal charges filed against him in
Illinois, Bethel Christian Assembly kept Glenn on as its youth
pastor, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Like all church personnel, he was supposed to follow a church
policy that requires two adults be present any time young people
visit the homes of church staffers. Police and prosecutors say
Glenn ignored that policy.
</P>
<P>
   Bethel Christian Assembly, which is slated to move into a new
$10 million building in Parkland this fall, is the second Puget
Sound-area church to be rocked by a sex scandal during the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, elders of Overlake Christian Church in Redmond,
Wash., said they have testimony that supports allegations of sexual
misconduct against the Rev. Bob Moorehead, who resigned last year
from Washington's largest congregation amid a cloud of suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, the elders dismissed allegations of sexual misconduct
against Moorehead by 17 men. They said the incidents weren't
substantiated by eyewitnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But now elders say they have received supportive testimony since
Moorehead stepped down last June and they have concluded Moorehead
violated the scriptural standards of trust, self-control, purity
and Godly character required for the office of elder and pastor at
Overlake.
</P>
<P>
   No criminal charges were filed against Moorehead for the alleged
violations in King County.
</P>
<P>
   Moorehead came under scrutiny starting in late 1997 when it was
learned he had been charged with masturbating in a public restroom
in Daytona Beach, Fla., in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were dropped under controversial circumstances, but
disclosure of his arrest prompted several men to allege that
Moorehead sexually molested them during adult baptism and wedding
ceremonies in the 1970s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
