<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAINBIO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN CAMPAIGN VIDEO HAS SOME FOOTAGE THAT ISN'T REAL THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Viewers of John McCain's presidential campaign
video, which shows spectacular Vietnam War footage of the former
POW, may be surprised to learn that some of the most dramatic
scenes aren't the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   When the video was released this week, it appeared the producers
had uncovered amazing archival film of McCain, now an Arizona
senator, parachuting to Earth after his plane was shot down on a
bombing run over Hanoi during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out the parachuting man depicted in grainy
black-and-white is not McCain at all, but stock Defense Department
footage of someone else.
</P>
<P>
   And a clip of an ``angry mob'' seen ready to grab the
unconscious McCain is actually a generic group shot of some
Vietnamese people, not really the hostile bunch that confronted the
fallen Navy pilot after he landed in a lake, a McCain aide said.
</P>
<P>
   There are other liberties taken in the nine-minute video
biography, titled ``The Character to Do What's Right. The Courage
to Fight for It.''
</P>
<P>
   Since they are not told, viewers will have little way of knowing
that some scenes are genuinely part of McCain's story _ a part of
American history, really _ while others are representations.
</P>
<P>
   McCain aides said that they never intended to deceive anyone and
that it is common to use representations in such videos if the
story itself is true.
</P>
<P>
   The look-alike scenes, some of them quite heroic, are
interspersed with the others and often appear in the same jerky,
black-and-white footage as the real McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   The tape dramatically tells the story of how McCain, on a
bombing mission, ejected from his plane and was captured, beaten
and imprisoned from October 1967 until March 1973. McCain sent
50,000 copies of the video biography this week to likely voters in
New Hampshire's Republican presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   The actual McCain clips in the video are dazzling. Some were
obtained from the Vietnamese government and helped to fill in gaps
in the history of the war and to illustrate the experience of
McCain, regarded by many as a U.S. hero.
</P>
<P>
   Some scenes seem very real, but are not.
</P>
<P>
   During the parachute sequence, for example, the voice-over
declares, ``McCain ejected as his plane spiraled violently to
earth. The force of the ejection knocked him unconscious. Both of
his arms and one leg were broken.''
</P>
<P>
   The video seems to perfectly match the narrative by showing a
grainy, unrecognizable figure who appears to be unconscious falling
through the air.
</P>
<P>
   There's no indication that it's not a shot of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The voice-over then declares that an ``angry mob'' formed on the
ground that was ``seeking retribution for the rain of bombs.
Dragging (McCain) from the lake, they broke his shoulder with a
rifle butt and bayoneted him repeatedly.''
</P>
<P>
   A mob is seen forming, but, ``I don't think that's the mob that
approached McCain,'' said Mark Salter, McCain's chief of staff. ``I
think that's just a Vietnamese mob.''
</P>
<P>
   In another scene, the narrator refers to the ``infamous Hanoi
Hilton'' where McCain spent most of his captivity. In fact, the
video shows a clip of another prison where McCain was first held
that Americans had nicknamed ``The Plantation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually know what prison that is (in the video) because
I've been there,'' Salter said. ``It's the first prison John was
held in. It's not the Hanoi Hilton.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no attempt to mislead anyone, said Greg Stevens, whose
Virginia-based media firm produced the video.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a representation of what happened,'' he said. ``I
don't know any footage that exists showing John McCain parachuting
from the plane. We have to put something up there that represents
what's going on. I've probably done 30 or 40 of these (videos) and
it's very common.''
</P>
<P>
   While most newspapers will inform readers if representations are
used to depict people or events, the standard is different for
videos and often for television, Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the words reflect the truth and do the pictures illustrate
the words? We're absolutely on target,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The video producers said they enjoyed making the video because
they consider McCain a hero.
</P>
<P>
   More than other presidential candidates, McCain is relying on
his personal story, particularly the war years, to support his
campaign theme that he has the courage to be a leader.
</P>
<P>
   The video also features a clip of a dazed McCain lying on his
back and being interviewed by a French film crew after he was
captured.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a shot of the Hanoi sky and landscape as McCain
and the other Americans were over a power plant on his ill-fated
bombing run.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at that very closely, you'll see a little fireball
up in the top right hand corner, and that is his (McCain's) plane.
All the smoke and stuff is the power plant they were bombing,''
Salter said. The photo was taken by another pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at anything on TV, for example, and even in news
reports there are demonstrations and depictions,'' said Howard
Opinsky, McCain's campaign spokesman. ``When you're telling the
whole story, you don't want to be limited to just what you have
footage of.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
