<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2671 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WENATCHEE-SPI &LR;      06-04 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WENATCHEE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULINGS, NEW HEARINGS ARE FAVORING WENATCHEE DEFENDANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As Washinton state's high courts continue to untangle
questions of injustice surrounding the Wenatchee child
sex-investigations, Doris Green, a 36-year-old mother of four
imprisoned since 1994, has won the right to a new hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The state Court of Appeals in Spokane has ordered a rare
investigative hearing to look into and gather evidence in Green's
case, echoing its calls for similar hearings in other cases.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling follows last month's rejection by the state Supreme
Court of prosecutors' arguments against holding the same kind of
hearing for Manuel Hidalgo-Rodriguez, who won the right to the
evidence-gathering procedure in December.
</P>
<P>
   Chelan County prosecutors, meanwhile, have told Henry
Cunningham, 50, whose 47-year conviction was overturned by the
appeals court in February, they will not try to send him back to
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Green, Hidalgo and Cunningham were Wenatchee residents accused
of child sex-abuse during a sweeping _ and since discredited _
series of investigations in the Wenatchee area in the mid-1990s. A
total of 43 people were arrested, accused of nearly 30,000
instances of sexual abuse involving 60 children.
</P>
<P>
   A Seattle Post-Intelligencer investigation of questionable
actions by local police, prosecutors, state social workers and
others in Wenatchee was published in early 1998, when 17 defendants
remained in prison. Since then, six defendants have been freed by
higher courts.
</P>
<P>
   Green, a 37-year-old mother of four, is serving a 23-year prison
term imposed in 1994 on child rape and molestation charges
involving children of a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The court, responding to her appeal, ordered the yet-to-be
scheduled fact-finding session known as a reference hearing.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Whitman County Superior Court Judge Wallis Friel
will examine several issues raised by Green's lawyer, Suzanne Lee
Elliott. These include whether former Wenatchee Police Detective
Bob Perez used improper and coercive techniques to prompt Green's
confession. Perez and state Child Protective Services investigators
have been criticized for failing to keep records of their
interviews with accusers and the accused.
</P>
<P>
   The high court wants Friel to determine if Perez used
inappropriate techniques to obtain accusations of abuse from two
children in Green's case.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott also documented a variety of other apparent
improprieties, including conflicts of interest involving Perez and
judges and lawyers connected with the case.
</P>
<P>
   Chelan County Prosecutor Gary Riesen said he is ``perplexed''
about the legal basis for Green's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to hang on the belief that Detective Perez coerced
the confession from her, but that's not what was proven in her
trial. Nor have the children who testified against her recanted
their accusations,'' he said. ``But we'll hold the hearing and see
what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott disagreed. She said the question is not whether children
recanted, but whether statements they made were planted or
suggested by Perez, who worked closely with CPS investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant decision that goes right to the heart of
the case. The actions of Detective Perez and his coercive
techniques in getting accusations and confessions,'' Elliott said.
``This has the potential be a house of cards for the rest of the
Wenatchee group in prison ... what will it take to get the state to
accept that something was very wrong with all the cases?''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Cunningham was freed from prison in February after Riesen
asked the state Court of Appeals to free Cunningham pending a
decision on whether he would be tried again. In 1994 Cunningham was
sentenced to 47 years on 23 counts of raping and molesting three of
his four daughters. In a scathing review of the case, an appellate
court said his court-appointed lawyer was so bad that he did not
receive a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham's appeal, written by a team of lawyers that has taken
on the Wenatchee cases as the Innocence Project Northwest, said
Cunningham's lawyer urged him to plead guilty while failing to seek
witnesses to corroborate his client's alibi. Riesen said he won't
challenge the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much time has gone by since the incident. The children, the
victims, are now grown and have their own lives and their own
families,'' Riesen said. ``I don't know if it's in anyone's best
interest, including the community, to go through another trial.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 12, Friel will begin taking testimony and evaluating
evidence in the case against Hidalgo, a 36-year-old fruit picker
who was charged in 1995 with two counts of first-degree child rape
and two counts of child molestation. He was convicted of one count
of sexually touching a child and was sentenced to 5{ years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Post-Intelligencer earlier this year reported that one of
the girls has admitted she and her sister lied when they accused
Hidalgo, and that medical evidence used to convict Hidalgo was
doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle lawyer Robert Van Siclen, who with New York appeals
specialist Robert Rosenthal last year took on Hidalgo's appeal,
said the upcoming hearing will highlight errors common in all of
the Wenatche cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these cases are tied together, all are cross
contaminated.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Siclen and Elliott are among the 60 lawyers, law professors
and students volunteering their time and services to the Innocence
Project Northwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
