A2673 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-AVERTED-SPI &LR;      06-04 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-AVERTED-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIP FROM SCHOOL GUARD MAY HAVE PREVENTED ANOTHER SCHOOL TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KIMBERLY A.C. WILSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A school guard's tip about a series of drive-by
shootings led police to the home of an Auburn, Wash., teen
Wednesday night. What they found inside his bedroom was more
chilling than the crimes that brought them there.
</P>
<P>
   Pasted on the wall above the 18-year-old suspect's bed were a
handful of newspaper headlines about the teen killers and death
toll from the Littleton, Colo., school massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we averted another school shooting,'' Black Diamond
police Detective Chris Hurst said. ``If this person wasn't
predisposed in that direction, I don't know who is.''
</P>
<P>
   The teenager, who is expected to be charged Monday, has a
juvenile criminal record for fourth-degree assault in 1997. He was
booked into the Kent Regional Justice Center early Thursday morning
on suspicion of felony second-degree assault for allegedly firing a
.17-caliber pellet rifle at pedestrians and bicyclists from a
moving car.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency doctors told police one of the victims might have died
had the pellet struck a major artery just centimeters from his
wound.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary court appearance is scheduled for Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The tip that led authorities to the suspect came Wednesday from
a security officer at a Kent high school. Students there told the
guard the suspect, who attends an alternative high school in
Auburn, was behaving strangely. When they suggested the teen was
involved in the drive-by shootings, the guard called police.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the youth's home last night went unanswered, but Hurst
said the suspect's parents ``were pretty shocked'' when they
learned that police were investigating his role in a pair of
drive-by shootings on March 31 and April 1.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the shootings occurred just before 6 p.m. when an
off-duty firefighter was struck while bicycling near the Lake
Sawyer area of Black Diamond. Witnesses said the shots were fired
by a passenger in a pickup truck and struck the man once in the
hip.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, a real estate agent was strolling with his wife and
young daughter just after 5 p.m. when he was shot in the groin by a
passenger in a station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, police learned of a third shooting in unincorporated
King County that occurred on the same road about an hour after the
real estate agent was shot. That victim was struck in the hand
while standing outside a grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were picked at random, just for the purpose of seeing
what it would be like to shoot someone,'' Hurst said.
</P>
<P>
   Although different vehicles were used in the assaults, police
suspected early on that the drive-by shootings were related because
slugs recovered from two of the victims were of the same small
caliber and displayed similar markings.
</P>
<P>
   They appear to match the 17-caliber pellet rifle found in the
suspect's bedroom along with a sniper's scope, a few violent
videotapes and the disturbing newspaper clippings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
