<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2675 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN--FRENCH-HNS &LR;      06-04 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN--FRENCH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ The natives, of course, do not refer to their Grand Slam
tennis tournament as the French Open. Non, mon dieu! It is Roland
Garros, s'il vous plat.
</P>
<P>
   In case you might have forgotten _ not that Bud Collins would
ever let you _ M. Garros was an ordinary, undecorated, barely known
aviator who perished just days before World War I ended. But the
members of his sporting club, unaffected by the fact he apparently
didn't even play tennis, chose to honor his memory by naming their
grounds after him.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, they also decided to turn the facility over to
France's tennis association to use as the site of its annual
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Which might explain everything. It pays to be obscure, the more
obscure the better, around here. La diffrence est normal. Among the
men pros, if not necessarily the women, nothing levels the deck
quite like the lovely red clay.
</P>
<P>
   Libert, galit, fraternit indeed. By any name, the French Open
has become exactly that in the closing decade of the 20th century.
Wider than wide-open. Gaping-chasm open. A tournament for the
huddled masses, yearning to be free.
</P>
<P>
   Oops, wrong country metaphor there. Excusez-moi.
</P>
<P>
   As a 66th-ranked nobody, Brazil's Gustavo Kuerten blasted
through the field unscathed two years ago. As the favorite, if not
the top seed, following victories on clay in Rome and Monte Carlo
this spring, Kuerten got samba-ed out on his ear in the quarters,
beaten soundly in straight sets by the previously slumping
Ukrainian, Andrei Medvedev.
</P>
<P>
   Before Roland Garros, Medvedev hadn't won two matches in a row
since October.
</P>
<P>
   Need a new no-name Brazilian to cheer? Say hello to 54th-ranked
Fernando Meligeni, a flaky free spirit whose abject anonymity might
be his greatest asset as he closes in on the Slam that least lends
itself to handicapping.
</P>
<P>
   Of the final four hommes, only Andre Agassi is famous, and only
Agassi was seeded coming in _ a so-what 13th, which has been a
lucky number for him. He has been a finalist twice, but it was a
long time ago, back when he had hair.
</P>
<P>
   Should Agassi prevail, he would join countryman Jim Courier and
Russia's Yevgeny Kafelnikov as just the third champion of Roland
Garros over a bizarre 10-year span who has won as many as one of
the other four majors. The terre battue has turned into a cimetire
for the most famous and celebrated players of the day, Pete Sampras
toweringly conspicuous among them.
</P>
<P>
   Figures. You have to be starving to win on this dirt. You can't
rest on your big-serve assets. You must bow your back, suck in your
gut, set your jaw and harden your resolve, then be willing to
expend hour after grimy, thankless hour hacking your way through a
thicket of gritty Spaniards and robotic Eastern Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   It's grubby, nasty work, tennis for the proletariat, not the
haute bourgeoisie who occupy most of the seats in the stands. The
Metro strike paralyzing Paris has had a minuscule impact on
attendance at Roland Garros. This crowd, believe me, does not deign
to travel by public conveyance.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the players do, though. If Meligeni, 28, who hadn't
survived a fourth round in any of his previous Slam appearances,
has been in a limo, it's because the nouveau-riche Kuerten gave him
a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando is the modern French Open, right down to his clay-caked
socks, stringy hair and cap, which he wears backward.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Chang, only 17 and hence too naive to know any better,
launched the procession of upstart winners in 1989. Champions since
have included Courier, the prototypical lunch-pail-lugging type;
Spain's one-trick pony, Sergi Bruguera; and Kafelnikov, who as the
world's No. 1 player didn't make it through the second round last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity doesn't pay in Paris, unless you are trying to shop
on the Rue Fauborg-St. Honore.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Agassi takes on the vowel-challenged Slovak, Dominik
Hrbaty; Medvedev and Meligeni scuffle in the ``who's-he?'' semi.
Should Hrbaty and Meligeni _ or, for that matter, Medvedev _
advance, NBC might fall on its sword and pull the plug on the
weekend telecast. You could count the U.S. television audience on
one hand and not need your thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Pacers-Spurs would look like Celtics-Lakers to the network
suits.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Agassi can save the show by his lonesome as he pursues the
completion of a career Grand Slam, something no man has
accomplished in 30 years. Andre's resurrection as a contender is a
lifesaver for the ATP Tour, such a dreary place these days that
Kafelnikov clings to his top ranking despite having won two matches
in eight tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a Y2K bug. That computer needs chucking, not a
tweaking.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, nothing can be done to it to create a reliable form
chart for the annual French crapshoot. They should pick the seeds
here out of a chapeau. The result couldn't be less reliable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
