<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2676 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-HNS     06-04 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ So much for the grieving.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few things in New York evaporate faster than yesterday's
tragedies, so the fact Patrick Ewing will miss the rest of the 1999
NBA playoffs was suitably chewed over and subsequently swallowed.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's practice for the Knicks meant it was time to move on,
especially because the Eastern Conference finals continue Saturday
at Madison Square Garden, leaving precious little time for
hand-wringing.
</P>
<P>
   Especially because the Knicks are trying to earn a trip to the
NBA Finals. With that in mind, Ewing addressed his teammates before
Thursday's practice at Purchase College, hoping to get them focused
on the quest for an NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel that we have an opportunity to win it,'' Ewing
said. ``I'd love to be a part of it. I mean, I'd love to be healthy
and be a part of it. I want to be on the floor to help the team
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still going to be on the sidelines cheering them on _
patting them on the back, cursing 'em out _ doing whatever I have
to do to help them win. I'm human, I want to be out there
performing. But I'm not going to be able to. I just have to do the
next best thing. I feel very confident in my teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that before practice started that I believe in
them, for them to go out and get me my ring.''
</P>
<P>
   As in NBA championship ring, something for which Ewing has been
striving throughout his 14-year NBA career. Ewing led the Knicks to
the 1994 NBA Finals, but they lost to Hakeem Olajuwon and the
Rockets in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to try to get a ring anyway,'' said Allan
Houston of the team's reaction to Ewing's talk. ``It's not like now
we're really going to try. We're here for a reason, we've done some
things to get to this point. If we do get that ring, it will be
that much more special because of this injury, this adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk fired up Ewing's teammates, who appear to have a new
sense of purpose about their best-of-seven series with the Pacers,
which is tied 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to play, I'm juiced up,'' said backup power forward
Marcus Camby, who figures to get a lot more playing time. ``I wish
we were playing today. The mood was great, really.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew about (Ewing's) situation yesterday, so we knew
coming in we had to work harder today. It won't be easy losing our
captain, our go-to guy. But somehow we have to find a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy must instead wring a few
victories out of his suddenly depleted talent pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find some answers,'' Van Gundy said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for those answers began Thursday, when the Knicks went
through their first practice minus Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good atmosphere,'' Houston of Thursday's practice.
``Everyone when they first found out was a little overwhelmed _ it
takes you aback. We feel terrible for Patrick, but we don't have a
lot of time right now to let our emotions carry over to the court.
We have to get ready for Indiana right now. Practice was great. One
of the best we've had.''
</P>
<P>
   The mission won't be as difficult as it seems because the Knicks
had begun to retool the offense that had been de-emphasizing Ewing
anwyay. With Houston, Camby Latrell Sprewell and Chris Childs more
comfortable in the running game, the Knicks have put pressure on
the Pacers in Games 1 and 2 by fast-breaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll run more if we get the (defensive) stops,''
Sprewell said. ``We didn't do a good job of getting stops and
rebounding last time. We have to do a better job of getting stops.
Can't run without the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone knows I like to run. That's the way I play.
It's ingrained in my brain. So any time I have an opportunity to
go, I do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers seem to have done better with Ewing on the floor,
outscoring the Knicks by six points in Game 1 (86-80) and by 19 in
Game 2 (57-38) while Ewing hobbled about the court.
</P>
<P>
   In Chris Dudley, the Knicks have a defense-minded center who can
at least put a body on Indiana's 7-4 Rik Smits and force him out of
the post. But Dudley doesn't want to be called Ewing's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'm supposed to be the man, but I'll cover
Smits, and do whatever,'' Dudley said. ``I'm going to do the same
things I do when I come off the bench. The shots will just go
different places. But we've been playing kind of that way anyway,
so it's more of the same, as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   More of the same, as in things are never easy in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been like that around here,'' Houston said. ``This
is just an exclamation point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
