<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2679 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-HOUSING-SPI &LR;      06-04 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-HOUSING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF PEACE DEAL COMPOUNDS THE UNCERTAINTY FOR REFUGEE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GORDY HOLT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After escaping from the terror in their Yugoslavian
homeland for placid Mercer Island, a refugee family from Pristina,
Kosovo, viewed Thursday's news of a proposed peace accord and
wondered what next?
</P>
<P>
   So what if the war ends back home, Shkelzen Syla was asked?
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old looked to his father for an answer, but one did
not come quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is peace, we go back,'' the father said, his son
translating. ``But only if NATO is there. We are still afraid of
the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sylas _ Shkelzen and his sister, Mirjeta, 14; their father,
Shaquir, 57, a firefighter; and Habibe, 51, their mother _ arrived
in Seattle Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying them were Shaquir's brother, Hasan, his wife,
Hasime, and their only child, 12-year-old Remzie.
</P>
<P>
   They are ethnic Albanians, the targets of ethnic cleansing in
Kosovo by Serb forces, led by Yugoslavian President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard for either family to ignore the news of Belgrade's
capitulation to NATO's demands even as they moved into apartments
and began to sort out a new life in a strange land.
</P>
<P>
   How long might they stay was anyone's guess, they said. But
again, there was a long pause before the answer came from the
father through his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am old. She is old,'' Shaquir Syla said, pointing to his
wife. ``We don't matter. But if they want to stay,'' he said,
gesturing toward his children, ``it will be all right with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Shkelzen wore a wide grin, enough to communicate the relief he
and his family feel now that they have a place to live in Mercer
Island's Shorewood apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   As Shkelzen told of the families' flight to America, he spoke in
English he learned at school and by watching American action
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the Sylas _ mother, father, son _ sat in straight-back
chairs around a table in the apartment's dining area while Mirjeta
lounged on the couch. A small color TV rumbled in a corner.
</P>
<P>
   The memories of their last few hours in Pristina won't soon
fade, especially the sight of a burned man lying dead in the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will they forget their neighbors, Serbs, who marched them at
gun point to the train station, on their way to a camp in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   What other possible horrors awaited them had they lingered have
been documented since Milosevic launched his ``ethnic cleansing''
policies.
</P>
<P>
   As the International Rescue Committee's Seattle office helped
the two Syla families settle on Mercer Island, other Seattle-area
refugee agencies were girding for the arrival of as many as 300 to
500 more Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Most will arrive as the Sylas did, from a processing camp at
Fort Dix, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   But there appears to be no rhyme or reason as to their
placements with various relief agencies, said Bob Johnson, the
International Rescue Committee's director in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The humanitarian effort is unfolding on the fly, he said,
holding up a cryptic fax he received, which noted , ``26 and 27 . .
. deletion.''
</P>
<P>
   The message, Johnson said, means that two people listed on an
airline manifest list would not be arriving as expected. Johnson
helped secure the Syla families at Shorewood, where they will be
allowed to stay for 90 days, rent-free.
</P>
<P>
   Shorewood spokeswoman Debbie Hanan said her experience helping
house Bosnian, Somali and Iragi refugees helped paved the way for
the latest relief effort.
</P>
<P>
   Not as lucky so far is Cincy Koser, refugee resettlement
director of Catholic Emergency Services in Seattle. Koser said
Thursday her agency has been dealt two families of eight people
each, and doesn't yet know where to put them.
</P>
<P>
   `We've been told to stand by and to expect just 48-hours
notice,'' Koser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid to walk by the fax machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Koser said she has had offers to house one or two people, ``but
not a family of eight. Since we'd like to keep them together, we're
in a bit of a panic right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rising real estate prices have driven up rents. A home big
enough for a large family would cost about $1,500 a month range.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we desperately need is something for $500 to $600,'' she
said. ``And a van. We need a van for that many people. We don't
have one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
