<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2701 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     06-04 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOURCES: RAMBIS WILL RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Nothing is signed yet, but the Lakers are prepared
to hand Kurt Rambis the reins of the team for at least one more
season _ this time a real, 82-game season, not a lockout-marred,
soap-opera whirlwind.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources close to the team, Lakers management wants
to retain Rambis and will offer him either a two-year deal or one
year with a team option for a second.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis' reappointment is awaiting only final approval from team
owner Jerry Buss, who is known for taking his time on major
decisions. And with Rambis and his staff under contract through the
end of the month, the Lakers feel no urgency to make the deal
official.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement is not expected until at least June 14, after
the annual pre-draft camp in Chicago next week. Rambis will be
attending the camp with executive vice president Jerry West and
general manager Mitch Kupchak. The draft is June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have declined comment on other reports regarding
Rambis, and West reiterated that the team continues to mull
coaching options.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still discussing it. Obviously we'd like to get it done
as soon as possible,'' he said, dismissing reports that Rambis will
be retained as ``more speculation than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis' agent, Lon Rosen, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Some team observers said Buss is delaying a decision in case a
more intriguing candidate emerges. But the obvious candidates are
unlikely to get much consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have long shied away from high-profile coaches with
large salary demands, which would rule out former Bulls coach Phil
Jackson and retired Magic coach Chuck Daly, who both command in
excess of $5 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Del Harris, who coached the team for four-plus seasons before he
was fired in February, earned less than $1.5 million in his final
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers also have a long tradition of promoting from within,
and the 41-year-old Rambis has been with the team as a player and
coach for a combined 13 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Rambis removed himself from consideration for head
coaching jobs with the Clippers and Sacramento Kings, preferring to
remain an assistant under Harris for a fifth season. He was
rewarded for his loyalty when Harris was dismissed after a 6-6
start.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis was named interim coach Feb. 26 and guided the Lakers to
a 24-13 record in the regular season and a 3-1 first-round playoff
series win over the Houston Rockets. But the Lakers' season ended
with a disappointing sweep at the hands of the San Antonio Spurs, a
series in which Rambis' coaching was criticized.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in light of all the Lakers had to endure this season _ the
firing of Harris, the trade of Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell for
Glen Rice, the Dennis Rodman experiment _ management felt it would
be hasty to give up on the promising Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really can't evaluate him fairly,'' West acknowledged
after the Spurs series. ``He was put in a most awkward position.
The on-the-job training is difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis has called the past season a learning experience and
admitted to making some mistakes but said he hoped to prove himself
in a full season, starting with a complete roster and a training
camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 0221EDT &QL; 
