<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 03:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2715 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ICE-AGE-SFCHRON &LR;      06-04 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICE-AGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARTH MAY BE IN NEW ICE AGE, STUDY FINDS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  If you think this spring is colder and wetter than any you've
ever endured, just imagine what it's been like around the world for
the past half-million years or so.
<P>
   Drilling a hole straight down through more than two miles of ice
in Antarctica, scientists from Russia, America and France have
found evidence from their drill cores that four long and bitter ice
ages must have frozen vast portions of planet Earth and lasted as
long as 100,000 years at a time.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the global warming trend of recent years, a new ice
age may have begun only 18,000 years ago, the scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   But during the intervals between all those ice ages, the Earth
was much warmer. Even in the big deep freezes of long ago, the same
``greenhouse gases'' produced by modern industry probably polluted
the ancient atmosphere naturally and helped speed the warming
process, the scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty researchers have been involved in the drilling project at
Russia's Vostok Station in East Antarctica for nearly 20 years. In
a report published Thursday, they described what the ice cores have
revealed about Earth's climate over the past 420,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Antarctica, of course, is always cold, and the Vostok research
facility stands at the coldest part of the continent, where the
average year-round temperature is 67 degrees below zero.
</P>
<P>
   Over hundreds of thousands of years, however, the atmosphere has
carried trace amounts of gases that settle to the ground year after
year. In Antarctica, every snowfall traps those gases in tiny
bubbles of ice to form a continuous, permanent record of the
climate, the local temperature, the rate of snowfall and even the
strength of the winds.
</P>
<P>
   The gases include carbon dioxide and methane, which are major
components of today's rising levels of industrial pollutants that
scientists blame for the increasing rate of global warming during
the past century. One of the rarer isotopes of oxygen in the ice
bubbles provides clues to changes in the world's ice volume and
precipitation.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting in the journal Nature, the Vostok team said the past
420,000 years have been marked by ice ages that began about 335,000
years ago, 245,000 years ago, 135,000 years ago and 18,000 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   By that calculation _ and if the 100,000-year intervals between
ice ages are continuing _ then despite the past 100 years of
continued warming, the Earth is heading into another ice age even
now.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Still Just a Theory
</P>
<P>
   According to J.R. Petit, the French lead author of the Vostok
team's report, several factors have played a role in the world's
climate changes from icy cold to relative warmth. These include
subtle shifts in the Earth's orbit that bring it alternately closer
and farther from the sun; changes in the sun's own heat output; and
periodic changes in the levels of ``greenhouse gases'' that can be
emitted by decaying plankton in the oceans and other plants on
land.
</P>
<P>
   But the exact causes of the regular cycles of cold and warmth
over the millennia are in dispute, according to Bernhard Stauffer,
a climate physicist at the University of Bern in Switzerland who
commented on the Vostok team's report in a separate Nature article.
</P>
<P>
   To Stauffer, the most likely explanation for the end of each ice
age would begin with a subtle change in the Earth's orbit, then an
increase in greenhouse gases that decaying plants produce as a
result of the warming, and finally even more warming as the
continent-sized huge ice sheets shrink and the bare earth is
exposed to absorb the sun's heat.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is still theory, however, noted Frank Carsey of
NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, who leads an
international team planning to look for signs of life in the lake
that lies beneath the bottom of the Vostok drill hole.
</P>
<P>
   The argument that greenhouse gases are a major influence in the
cycles of past ice ages is ``surprisingly strong,'' and it's quite
likely that changes in the Earth's orbit can ``kick-start the
process,'' he said in an interview. But building an entire theory
that explains just how ice ages start and end ``still takes a
certain amount of cheerful belief,'' Carsey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
