<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-SFCHRON(ANALYSIS) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: CHINA'S TRADE STATUS SAFE DESPITE OUTCRY
OVER  RIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is no small irony that President Clinton called
for an extension of China's favorable trading status Thursday on
the 10th anniversary of the Tiananmen Square massacre.
</P>
<P>
   It was blood on the streets of Beijing that gave birth to the
annual congressional fight over trade. Led in part by San
Francisco's Rep. Nancy Pelosi, the fight over the terms of China's
trade status became a vehicle to pressure leaders in Beijing into
taking human rights more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   But each year it becomes increasingly clear that China's human
rights policy has been largely unaffected by the threats of a trade
war. And under enormous pressure from the business community, which
has billions of dollars at stake, the United States has shown less
and less of an appetite to use trade as a bargaining tool.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even during this low moment in U.S.-China diplomacy, the
debate in Washington is not whether to suspend trade relations but
whether to extend them permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a real threat to cutting off the annual renewal,''
said Rep. Bob Matsui, D-Sacramento. ``We've had so much trade with
China in the last decade that it is very difficult to now cut it
off.''
</P>
<P>
   The House, which received formal notification of Clinton's
decision Thursday morning, will now go through its yearly China
trade dance, a complicated series of steps choreographed by a
25-year-old law governing commerce with communist countries.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on Clinton's certification of China's ``normal trade
relations'' _ formerly known as ``most favored nation'' status _ is
expected in July. Although congressional approval of China's trade
status is a foregone conclusion, relations between the two
countries have soured less than two months after Chinese Premier
Zhu Rongji visited the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade _ as well as
the anti-American rage on display in Beijing afterward _ and recent
allegations that China has stolen many of the United States' top
nuclear secrets as part of a vast espionage program have embittered
many on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a business decision,'' said California Rep. David
Dreier of San Dimas in Los Angeles County, who, like many other
Republicans, has been harshly critical of Clinton's overall China
policy but supportive of continued trade. ``It is very important
for our economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The more suspenseful debate is likely to take place later this
summer, when Congress is expected to consider a deal to back
China's attempts to join the World Trade Organization. China's
entry into the WTO would eliminate the need for annual action on
trade policy with China.
</P>
<P>
   To some, like Pelosi, that would be a loss. Pelosi, a Democrat,
believes that the annual exercise is a useful tool for pressuring
the Chinese in the areas of human rights, trade and weapons
proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in prisons told us their conditions improved every time
that (China trade) was up for a vote,'' Pelosi said.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Clinton's renewal, Pelosi said: ``Just as the
president's timing is sad, so too is his policy. This
administration's China policy, like that of the administration
before it, has not succeeded in making trade fairer, people freer,
or the world safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton advanced several reasons Thursday for extending trade
relations.
</P>
<P>
   First, he said that trade with China ``is good for Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since the Tiananmen Square massacre, Clinton said,
exports to China have quadrupled, and he said 400,000 American jobs
are dependent on such trade.
</P>
<P>
   The president said a deal to get China into the WTO would be
even better, and he warned that revoking trade relations ``would
derail ongoing negotiations to increase our access to China's
market and to promote economic reforms there.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, whose decision was praised by Republican presidential
candidates George W. Bush and Elizabeth Dole, also said economic
engagement remains the best way to persuade to China to make
reforms sought by the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade also remains a force for social change in China,
spreading the tools, contacts and ideas that promote freedom,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A continued policy of principled, purposeful engagement
reinforces these efforts to move China toward greater openness and
broader freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Some see another motive _ money. American businesses earn
hundreds of billions of dollars from trade with China, and they
have spent tens of millions on a lobbying effort to enhance their
access to the lucrative Chinese market. Pelosi and others have
accused Clinton, and President George Bush before him, of being
bought off by the ``exporting elite.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi's involvement with the annual trade debate sprung from
the violence in Tiananmen Square. Shortly after the June 4, 1989,
massacre, which left probably hundreds dead and thousands injured,
she introduced legislation to stop Chinese students studying in the
United States from being forced to return home. Congress passed the
bill, which was vetoed by Bush. But Bush later relented and signed
an executive order that spared the students from having to return
to China.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, some members of Congress used Tiananmen
Square as an argument for revoking China's trading privileges.
Pelosi seized the issue as a valuable way to ``leverage'' China
into making concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, the debate ... is a referendum on the
administration's policy,'' Pelosi said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has been shaped to a great extent by the brutality
met the 1989 protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiananmen Square has affected U.S. policy because it serves as
a reminder to the American people of the repressive nature of the
(Chinese) regime,'' Pelosi said. ``It speaks more eloquently than
anything we can say about the oppression in China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
