<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDESTRIAN MAN KNOWS WHERE TO DRAW THE LINE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ On my way to a meeting with Pedestrian Man, I
stepped into a crosswalk on Stockton and got my shoes run over by
the car of a very important person probably late for his job of
finding a cure for cancer.
<P>
   On closer inspection, the guy missed my feet. You know the old
saying about how there are two types of pedestrians: The quick and
the dead. I train by jumping over candlesticks.
</P>
<P>
   But quick and nimble as I be, I almost became a white chalk
outline on the pavement, which would have been a hilarious
coincidence, since dead-pedestrian outlining is what Pedestrian Man
does.
</P>
<P>
   Under cover of darkness, he spray-paints a generic outline of a
body on San Francisco streets. Each outline notes the time, age and
gender of a person killed by a car at or near that spot. (He omits
the name for several reasons, including respect for privacy.)
</P>
<P>
   PEDESTRIAN MAN doesn't call himself that. He calls himself Ken
Kelton. He's surprisingly normal for a guy who commits illegal
vandalism all over the city in his one-man crusade to raise
awareness of pedestrian wipeouts, to help stop 'em, and to
memorialize the fallen.
</P>
<P>
   I was hoping for the sake of this column that Ped Man would look
like Rasputin and have a bit of fire-and-brimstone action. Alas,
Kelton has neat gray hair and a neat beard; he dresses like the
respectable contractor he is. He looks like a CPA lumberjack.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks quietly and carries a spray gun.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes it is a weapon of mass destruction of the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Kelton compiled a list of recent pedestrian
deaths in the city. The list now spans 21 months and has 50 names,
plus info on each tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   He creeps into the streets at 4 a.m., sets up construction
barriers with blinking lights at a corner where a walker was
killed, and spray-paints the stencil.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Ken's 23-year-old son Jesse comes along to help out.
So far, Kelton has painted 50 of the outlines.
</P>
<P>
   HERE ARE the answers to two of the more obvious questions:
</P>
<P>
   -- Yes, his wife thinks he's crazy.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Basic citizenship,'' he explains. He saw a problem and
opted to become part of a solution. Nothing more dramatic than
that.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that struck Kelton when researching the human road
kills was how minor and fleeting was the notice. A small story in
the paper or no story at all, some police markings at the scene, a
brief report, then POOF.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fatalities are all terribly isolated,'' he says. ``I just
want to connect the dots. I'm raising the questions; I don't have
any answers. I'm just a construction guy. But I know this (what's
being done now) isn't good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   KELTON FIGURED if he collected some data, some trends might be
spotted, then brought to the attention of people who might be able
to make corrections.
</P>
<P>
   He nailed a map of the city to his office wall. He stuck red
pins for fatalities, yellow pins for serious injuries. Fifty reds,
137 yellows.
</P>
<P>
   He started to see things. Surprise: The biggest clump or red
pins was right in his own neighborhood, eight deaths within a few
blocks of Mission and Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Kelton's wall became a graphic representation of the carnage.
But on the streets, the dead people were quickly gone and
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   What to do? Ken is bike rider (mountain bikes; he says city
biking is too dangerous) and through the S.F. Bicycle Coalition, he
heard of a New York man who paints dead-ped street outlines. Kelton
talked to the man, decided to try it here.
</P>
<P>
   It appealed to the neo-anarchist (his description) in his soul.
Kelton volunteered for Vietnam, did his time in the combat zone
with the Seabees (Construction Battalion), became disillusioned and
radicalized. He went back to college and became an anti-war
protester, then grew up and got a job.
</P>
<P>
   Now his kids are both college age, business is good, he's got a
little spare time and he decided to start flexing his social
conscience again.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began his 4 a.m. painting parties.
</P>
<P>
   (He's got a web site, www.pedsafe.org.)
</P>
<P>
   What Kelton hopes will happen:
</P>
<P>
   -- City officials becoming more outraged. ``This level of
carnage is unacceptable,'' he says, ``but the city government is
accepting it.''
</P>
<P>
   -- A more detailed analysis of data by the Department of Parking
and Traffic.
</P>
<P>
   -- More ped-safety education for drivers. Kelton feels many
drivers just don't know the rules and laws.
</P>
<P>
   On this point, I think he is being either generous or wrong.
Drivers who endanger pedestrians know what they're doing, but don't
give a flying fig, since car-pedestrian collisions rarely kill
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Kelton would also like to get the city's official OK for the
street-outline memorials, and he'd like to re-do them with better
paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``They fade quickly; they get worn off,'' he says. ``But they're
still lasting longer than the memory of the people who died.''
</P>
</TEXT>
