<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2852 &Cx1f; taf-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIMETIME-CHIC-NYTSF &LR;      06-04 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMETIME-CHIC-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMETIME CHIC  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature from W magazine _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales
Executive DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES are available ELECTRONICALLY by E-MAIL. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 By MOLLY KNIGHT and ELENA ROMERO 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   There's no question that teens are watching youth-friendly shows
such as WB's ``Dawson's Creek'' on primetime and TNBC's (Teen NBC)
Saturday-morning shows like ``City Guys,'' but are they taking
their fashion cues from them?
</P>
<P>
   ``Teen television shows have a huge impact on fashion,'' said
Hayley Hill, fashion director at Teen People. ``For the first time,
shows like `Dawson's Creek' and `Felicity' have real people on them
that teens can relate to. The creators have done a lot of research
to make the characters a reality and the teens relate to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Relating to the actors might be accomplished through story
lines, character portrayal or their actual wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids want to dress trendy but comfortable, and television
shows depict this,'' Hill said. ``If you go to college campuses,
the students are wearing jeans and T-shirts like they do on
Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the brands worn by stars on the show, Hill said, are
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, Tommy, Polo Jeans, DKNY, Mudd Jeans, LEI and
Lucky Brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that our consumers are watching these teen shows,''
said Jamie Lockard, director of advertising for Lee. ``Through our
research, they've indicated the shows are very important to them.
These kids are so savvy _ they're pulling their fashion clues from
a wealth of places, and the shows they watch have a huge impact.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent profile of the WB Network in US magazine,
Nielson ratings for the WB Network are up 6 percent for this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Some of its popular shows include ``Dawson's Creek,'' ``Buffy
the Vampire Slayer,'' ``Seventh Heaven,'' ``Smart Guy,'' ``Sister
Sister'' and ``The Jamie Foxx Show.''
</P>
<P>
   WB has 4.6 million viewers in the 12- to 34-year-old bracket.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's teen line up includes ``Boy Meets World''; ``Sabrina the
Teenage Witch''; ``Brother's Keeper'' as well as ``Two Guys, a Girl
and a Pizza Place.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC has launched a number of shows for its successful
Saturday-morning TNBC block of educational and informational
programming targeting teens. Its three-hour block of teen
programming includes shows like ``Saved by the Bell: The New
Class,'' ``One World,'' ``Hang Time,'' ``City Guys'' and ``NBA
Inside Stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Bass is the costume designer for ``Hang Time,'' a show
based on an Indiana high school basketball team. She wardrobes
about 10 characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting show, especially when building its
wardrobe,'' she said. ``Because the guys are part of a basketball
team, they tend to look similar. It's important for me to find
their individuality. I try not to exchange the wardrobes because
each of the actors have to be unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass shops a variety of stores for the casts' wardrobe _ from
sporting and surf stores to the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very eclectic look,'' she said. ``We do a lot of
layering with vests in nylon or neoprene, fleece with a lot of
pockets and snowboard pants. There's also lot of shorts, or even
board shorts, worn with sneakers or boots.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bass, creating the look takes priority over brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't look at the labels,'' she said. ``We work with
tight budgets and want the looks that can be found in more boutique
stores. It's not as easy as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bass has a number of methods that she goes by when creating the
show's looks. She scours magazines, shops showrooms and purchases
outfits from boutique and upscale retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Hang Time,'' Adam Forst plays Michael Manning, the captain
for the Deering High School basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the all-American look,'' Bass said. He wears brands
such as the Gap, Ralph Lauren, Tommy Hilfiger in a classic look
that consists of plaid shirts, T-shirts and chinos.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, actor Danso Gordon who plays Kenny ``Silk''
Hayes dresses in bright, saturated colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dress him in athletic looks,'' Bass said. ``Breakaway
pants, layered tank tops with T-shirt underneath. He's got a little
of a hip-hop look.''
</P>
<P>
   To Bass, the characters' looks are understandable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really important to have looks that are somewhat
accessible,'' she said. ``Our shows are a lot about the look and
kids who watch it want to relate to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bentley Kyle Evans, creator/executive producer of the WB's ``The
Jamie Foxx Show,'' said fashion has a major influence because
viewers mimic characters they relate to.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they see the lead character wearing Fubu or Enyce, they
automatically realize it's a cool thing to wear,'' Evans said.
``I've had people call the show and send me fan mail, saying they
liked what the actors wear.''
</P>
<P>
   On NBC's ``City Guys,'' on the average, there are about 35 to 40
outfits per show for the principal cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashion is increasingly critical,'' said Charles Winston,
costume designer for ``City Guys,'' who is a 20-year veteran in his
craft. ``The target audience continues to be younger. They tune in
with fashion being the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston has experienced first-hand ``City Guys''' fashion
influence on teen looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids from all over write to our chat room,'' he said. ``They
don't know where to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston answers their fashion questions and provides them with
tips on where to purchase the looks seen on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``City Guys'' uses a variety of brands, including Varcity, BC
Ethic, Fresh Jive, Donna Karan, J. Crew, Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, Enyce
and Karl Kani.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our purchases reflect the styles upcoming or already
established without exposing the market to logos,'' he said. ``In
most cases, we have no logos at all. I don't want any one
particular brand to overshadow the show's concept.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Molly Knight and Elena Romero are reporters for Fairchild
Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To purchase this special one-shot feature _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
