<HEADER>
A2875 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN05-COX     06-04 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holocaust exhibit finds fitting home at Air Force Museum
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``What does a Holocaust exhibit have to do with
the history of aviation?''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the Air Force Museum fields that question about
``Prejudice and Memory: A Holocaust Exhibit,'' its new permanent
installation. ``I fail to see any connection between (the museum's)
objectives and the Holocaust,'' stated a recent letter to the
editor.
</P>
<P>
   Does a Holocaust exhibit belong at the Air Force Museum? Visit
``Prejudice and Memory'' with a group of schoolchildren, as I did
recently, and you'll have the answer. Dozens of children stood
intent, solemn-eyed, before a concentration camp uniform, or
listened to one of a half-dozen volunteer docents.
</P>
<P>
   For teacher Susan Lightcap, the connection is clear. ``All you
have to do is go around the corner and look at the World War II
exhibit,'' said Lightcap, among eight teachers squiring a group of
85 fifth-graders from Harold Schnell Elementary School in West
Carrollton. ``It all ties together very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum, after all, is about a lot more than airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Retired Maj. Gen. Charles Metcalf, the museum's
director. More and more, Metcalf said, the museum is telling
people's stories _ the human element in combat and the development
of technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airplane is the biggest artifact in a museum, but in many
cases it's not the most important,'' Metcalf said. ``The airplane
is a big unfeeling thing, with no sense of loyalty or devotion to
duty, of service to one's nation, of sacrifice. All of those are
very human emotions and traits.''
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf deserves credit for having the vision to make the
exhibit a permanent installation. A four-year labor of love for
project director and curator Renate Frydman, the exhibit had
traveled to 10 locations in 18 months. Initially, it was to be a
temporary exhibit at the Air Force Museum as well, until the day
Metcalf came to Frydman and said, ``What if we told you we like it
so much we want to keep it?''
</P>
<P>
   Frydman, who worried about security for the exhibit, was
overjoyed that it now had a home where 1.25 million people a year
could view it.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit is one of only a handful nationwide that focus on
local Holocaust survivors. For the Air Force Museum, it hits close
to home in other ways as well. Airmen not only helped to liberate
the concentration camps, Metcalf said, but some were imprisoned
there: ``It's a little-known fact, but every one of the internment
and extermination camps held American POWs ... held as long-term
prisoners. At the Berga concentration camp in 1944, they celebrated
Christmas by decorating 14 U.S. airmen as Christmas trees and
hanging them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes the case all the more that we need to tell this
story,'' said Metcalf, who plans to expand the exhibit to include
more Air Force history.
</P>
<P>
   You don't get far into the exhibit before you see the connection
with Air Force history. A wall panel titled ``The Liberators''
features local airmen and soldiers who served among the troops
liberating concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Unger of Dayton was one of them. Serving under Gen.
George Patton, he was among the troops from the 90th Infantry
Division who liberated the Flossenburg concentration camp in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the American soldiers were coming in, the survivors were
being shot as fast as they could be shot,'' Unger said.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit deserves a home at the Air Force Museum, he said;
the Holocaust is the supreme example of what the Allies were
fighting. ``This shows the Air Force Museum is sensitive to the
fact that the Holocaust is an intrinsic part of World War II, and,
as such, deserves a place in this museum,'' Unger said.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Weil agreed. The Harrison Twp. man came to tell the
students his remarkable story of survival and loss. By a fluke of
fate, he made it out of Frankfurt on one of the last children's
trains out of Germany. His parents and sister died at Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. prides itself on justice and freedom _ the kinds of
things taken away from people in the Holocaust,'' he said. ``The
U.S. Air Force is a branch of the government that defends those
freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubters have been few, Metcalf said; the response has been
overwhelmingly supportive. Each week the exhibit draws almost 2,000
students, who go on to explore the rest of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Proof positive, he said, that this exhibit fulfills the museum's
primary mission: Education.
</P>
<P>
   Frydman, he said, carefully constructed an exhibit that would
touch children. She avoided graphic photos, telling the story
instead through powerful artifacts and family photos.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, the students were quiet, attentive, engaged.
Megan Lee and Nicole Valencia, both 11, said the Air Force Museum
was the right place for the exhibit. ``People could come to learn
about planes, and wander back here and learn about the Holocaust,''
Megan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could teach people not to make the same mistakes,''
Nicole added. ``It could teach people that, even though someone
looks different or does different things, he is still a person.''
</P>
<P>
   The children's interest, Metcalf said, is exceeded only by the
veterans'. ``They are very, very intent on this. This is the reason
they were fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Veterans understand better than any of us, after all: Airplanes
alone can't tell the story of war.
</P>
<P>
   To tell the story, you need the concentration camp uniform, the
violin miraculously saved from the Nazis, the snapshot of the
smiling child with the caption in ink: ``Killed by the Nazi
extermination.''
</P>
<P>
   To tell the story, you need more than military hardware. You
need humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
