<HEADER>
A2876 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN05-COX     06-04 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawless lyrics and disorder
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Newspaper headline: ``150 Rally in Griffin
to protest RockFest '99 scheduled for June 7 at Atlanta Motor
Speedway.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time renting out the superspeedway for a
music festival has caused controversy. We had some tense moments
back in 1969 when promoters leased what was then Atlanta
International Raceway to put on a Southern version of Woodstock,
the signature event of the '60s youth rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Alf Knight, one of the early promoters of grass-roots stock car
racing _ every driver for himself, no corporate sponsors _ was
track superintendent. He and his wife, Madaline, had a home on the
premises, just off the first turn. Their friends included a young
couple from Plains. They listened to country music together and
sometimes visited dirt tracks on Friday and Saturday nights.
</P>
<P>
   When Jimmy Carter ran for governor, the Knights were among his
earliest supporters. Alf would introduce him to guests in the press
box while Madaline helped out with mailings and things like that.
After the Carters moved into the Governor's Mansion, they hosted an
annual barbecue for the Knights and their automobile racing
friends.
</P>
<P>
   When the Carters moved to Washington, they did the same at the
White House. Madaline made out the guest list, which ranged from
Lewis Grizzard to Willie Nelson to Richard Petty and Bobby Allison
spinning their cars around the South Lawn driveway while everybody
sipped cold longnecks iced down in Sears, Roebuck rowboats. The
'70s were hard years for Atlanta International Raceway, often
referred to as Atlanta International Rainway because of a pattern
of costly rainouts. AIR seemed forever on the verge of bankruptcy,
and suspicions were that Alf and Madaline sometimes subsidized
operations from their personal funds. Although he was technically
only an employee, Alf definitely felt an ownership stake in the
troubled track.
</P>
<P>
   When the owners rented it to promoters who were putting on a
weekend rock festival, he continued to do business as usual. He and
his work crew were making an asphalt patch in the third turn when
one of the promoters came up and ordered them to clear out. Alf
didn't cotton to being ordered off his own track. After a short
conversation, the promoter was observed in a prone position in the
middle of third turn, victim of a right-hand punch that made Alf
rather famous in racing circles.
</P>
<P>
   AIR's owners, anxious to avoid more trouble, offered Alf and
Madaline an all-expenses vacation for the duration of the rental
agreement. Naturally, they chose Daytona Beach. They had been there
only a few hours when Alf's foreman called from Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mister Alf,'' he said. ``You better get yourself home. Them
hippies done broke your plate glass window, and they're in your den
drinking beer and smoking marijuana.'' Alf's return trip from
Daytona set a highway speed record that likely still stands.
</P>
<P>
   As the festival wound down and finally ended on a Sunday
afternoon, local police had trouble getting the crowd to leave. The
infield was still filled with guests in various stages of
intoxication Monday morning when management of the track reverted
to Alf. With a trusted aide at his side, he picked up a length of
2-by-4 and began clearing the premises. By 10 a.m., everyone was
gone except for a young woman sleeping stark naked in the pit area
and a loaded Volkswagen about to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Alf shouldered the young lady, walked over to the Volkswagen
packed with six young men, poked his head into the window, and
inquired: ``Where are you fellows going?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To Miami,'' they replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good,'' Alf said, opening the door and poking the young lady
inside. ``So is she.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Alf won't be around to supervise the events of June 7 at
Atlanta Motor Speedway, I wish the media _ newspapers and
television _ would give extensive coverage to RockFest '99.
</P>
<P>
   The Griffin protesters, indulging clergy and Spalding County
Sheriff Richard Cantrell, are disturbed over violent lyrics that
apparently are stock in trade for some of the bands.
</P>
<P>
   In light of Littleton, Colo., and Conyers, they have reason to
be disturbed. I don't know what the lyrics say. I hear only
smatterings. Despite the reasons we hate to hear such things on
television and read them in newspapers, it's time to let the world
know exactly what our kids are listening to.
</P>
<P>
   If what we suspect is true, we need to do a bit of adjusting on
the First Amendment while we're tinkering with the Second. Keeping
military weapons away from civilians and keeping guns away from
criminals and children has nothing to do with the right of a
militia to bear arms. Marketing violence to kids has even less to
do with freedom of speech and press.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Consitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
