<HEADER>
A2880 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD05-COX     06-04 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jointing shouldn't table a project
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A question has arisen about how best to prepare and
edge-glue boards to make something like a table top. Actually it is
one of the easier tasks in woodworking, given a well-tuned jointer
plane and the proper clamps.
</P>
<P>
   To begin, select the boards for the project and cut them to
length and square them up. Although I use a jointer and planer to
square the boards, I always prepare the edges by hand. Why? Well,
for whatever reason, I always seem to get a better joint that way.
At least I think I do.
</P>
<P>
   Determine the face side of each board and the sequence. This is
very important to the final appearance of the top. Move the boards
around to get the most harmonious appearance, blending the figures
as best you can. The idea is to wind up with a top that looks as if
it was one incredibly broad plank. While this is seldom possible,
judicious arrangement will usually obscure to some degree the
disparity between the boards' color and figure.
</P>
<P>
   Some woodworking texts tell you to alternate the faces of the
boards to minimize any tendency toward cupping of the entire top. I
disagree; I've never seen this phenomenon, and I won't let the
possibility of it dictate the appearance of the completed top.
</P>
<P>
   Once the sequence is satisfactory, mark the boards' face side
with their place in the sequence and their face side.
</P>
<P>
   Now take boards 1 and 2 and place them back to back on the
workbench, with the edges to be joined uppermost. Clamp them _
remembering to use scrap wood pads under the clamp jaws _ with the
ends even.
</P>
<P>
   If the boards are fairly long, it's usually best to secure them
in the bench vise, still with the joining sides up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, take the jointer plane and square this two-board edge. The
plane should be set to take the thinnest shaving, and you must take
care, of course, to keep from rounding off the ends.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of doing both edges at once is that inadvertently
canting the plane will do no harm. If the combined edge is, for
instance, off of 90 degrees by 10 degrees or so, the edges will
still match perfectly when the boards are laid flat and brought
together.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as you are taking a full ribbonlike shaving off both of
the boards, you can stop.
</P>
<P>
   Continue this routine through the sequence of boards. Next will
come the other edge of No. 2 and the matching edge of No. 3, and so
forth.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're ready for glue up, a task that should not be rushed.
Some shops, I know, have a standing rule that there will be no
glueup at the end of the day, when everyone is tired and ready to
hang it up.
</P>
<P>
   If the top is fairly large, an extra pair of hands is extremely
useful, if not a downright necessity.
</P>
<P>
   If a lot of boards are required, consider glueing them in
segments. For instance, if you've got a six-board top, glue up two
sets of three boards, let them set up, and then glue the two
segments together.
</P>
<P>
   Some folks glue up on a special table, some on a sawhorse setup
and others on the bench. Whatever the case, cover the work surface
with wax paper to protect it and minimize the mess.
</P>
<P>
   Get your clamps ready, set to the proper length, with plastic
pads on the jaws or wood scraps ready to serve the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
   If the top is long enough to need more than two clamps, it's a
good idea to alternate them top to bottom. If you're going to do
that, put the bottom clamps in place and cover them with wax paper,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Beginners always have trouble determining the right amount of
glue. You want a happy medium. If there's no squeeze-out when you
apply clamp pressure, you probably didn't use enough glue. But you
want just a little squeeze-out; you don't want to be up to your
elbows in glue.
</P>
<P>
   Run a bead of glue down the edge of the first board and use a
thin piece of scrap or cardboard to spread it evenly across the
edge.
</P>
<P>
   The glue bottle will tell you to put glue on both edges. Not
many woodworkers do that.
</P>
<P>
   From here, things must proceed at a quick, but not panicky,
pace, since the glue begins to set in a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Continue this sequence until there's glue on every joint.
</P>
<P>
   Now bring the clamp jaws up and begin applying pressure, a
little bit at a time, with each clamp, working from the ends
inward. Don't bear down with one clamp a great deal more than with
the clamp next to it.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to bring enough pressure to bear on the boards to
get an even line of glue squeezeout across each joint. You don't
want to squeeze all the glue out, and you don't want to apply so
much pressure that the top begins to bow.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the boards want to slide around on the glue and get
out of alignment. If you can't control that by hand, you'll have to
prepare some scrap boards with at least one flat edge, cover them
with wax paper and clamp them top and bottom across the workpiece
to keep the alignment. Usually two sets, one near each end, will do
the job.
</P>
<P>
   Once everything is secure, clean up as much of the squeezeout as
you can with a damp cloth. Leave the workpiece in clamps for 24
hours, and remember that all the dried glue that didn't get wiped
off will now have to be scraped off, because it won't take a
finish.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
