<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DIABETES-BORDER (San Antonio) _ Plans are under way for an
ambitious, binational project to try to tackle the diabetes problem
along the U.S.-Mexico border. The undertaking, which will entail
door-to-door contacts with nearly 3,000 border residents, involves
the six Mexican states and four U.S. states along the border. By
NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-PROFILING (San Francisco) _ The American Civil
Liberties Union has filed a federal lawsuit charging that the
California Highway Patrol violated a lawyer's civil rights when
officers stopped him and other Latinos allegedly because of their
race. By VENISE WAGNER.
</P>
<P>
   YUPPIE-ERADICATION (San Francisco) _ As police continue to
investigate Kevin Keating, the man they believe is behind the
so-called Mission Yuppie Eradication Project, property owners vowed
to rally Sunday against hate crimes targeted at their cars, homes
and restaurants. ``We're the only people left that it's OK to hate,
politically _ successful Caucasians who drive nice cars,'' said
Samantha Spivack, a three-year resident of the Mission
neighborhood. By EMILY GURNON.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (San Francisco) _ As the director of the U.S.
State Department's Refugee Admissions Office, Theresa Rusch is
impresario for a vast and far-flung operation that each year
resettles tens of thousands of people fleeing war and civil strife
the world over. By ANNIE NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-BATHOUSES (San Francisco) _ The return of San Francisco's
gay bathhouses moved one step closer when a key advisory panel
voted in favor of reopening them. By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Few PC companies have been pushing
home networking as aggressively as Compaq Computer Corp. Rather
than waiting for home networks to become the next big thing, Compaq
is trying to make it happen faster.By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ Assorted computer-related
questions from readers. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ United Parcel Service sends its
managers to soup kitchens and homeless shelters for a month to
learn about what life is like outside the comfort zone, so they can
better understand their customers and employees. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD-GUYS (San Francisco) _ The original Good Guy is back.
Ronald A. Unkeferwill again take the helm of the consumer
electronics retailer he founded 26 years ago. But this time around,
he'll be in charge of saving the chain, which has been losing money
since 1996. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PLASTIC-RADIOS (Houston) _ Art dealer Thom Andriola knows his
plastic radios. The Texas man and his wife, Annette Wilzig, have
more than 250 models from the 1930s to the 1970s that line a wall
in the couple's home. ``They're just beautiful to look at,'' says
Andriola. By CATHY GORDON (Photo available on NYT database)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-INSTINCT (Undated) _ In ``Instinct,'' Anthony
Hopkins plays a growly scientist jailed for killing Rwandan park
rangers. Hopkins is watchable, which he always is, and believable,
which he usually is, and ogrish, which he sometimes is. He's also
one of a few remotely interesting elements in a movie so fat with
cliches it needs liposuction to squeeze through the door. By AMY
BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-REAL (Undated) _ ``Get Real'' is a coming-of-age
film, a coming-out film, a falling-to-pieces film and a film about
coming together. It is small and smart, painful and funny. The film
rests on a simple plot: Boy meets boy. Boy loves boy. Boy and boy
cope variously, and furtively, with the pressures of being gay
adolescents in a straight world. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   SANTANA-ALBUM (Undated) _ Veteran guitar hero Carlos Santana, a
pioneer of the Latin-rock sound, one of the sparkplugs of the 1969
Woodstock festival and a member of the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame,
is about to release a new album that will almost surely guarantee
his return to the top of the charts. By GREG HAYMES.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-POISONING (Undated) _ Food safety quiz: What does a
hamburger teeming with sickening amounts of bacteria taste like?
Answer: A hamburger. That's the problem with most food poisoning _
the bacteria that cause the misery of stomach cramps, diarrhea,
nausea, and vomiting cannot be tasted, seen, or smelled, according
to an article in the July issue of Redbook magazine. And what may
cause you a few days of feeling yucky can be a serious, even
life-threatening, illness for your child. By STEPHANIE YOUNG. (For
release Wednesday, June 9.)
</P>
<P>
   With BC-SWIMMING POOLS and BC-IF-GET.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The Protestant ethic is long
gone. No more asceticism, except for that black Prada look. Nobody
works to get into heaven and few work to better the community. The
idea is to get into the best restaurant, pull out the newest laptop
and talk business on the smallest cell phone. The work ethic of
slaving hard at a job you hate to better your kids is out. Except
among the poor people, of course. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   WW2-ANNIVERSARY (Danville, Calif.) _ Four years before D-Day _
in June 1940 _ France fell to the Nazis. Her swift and complete
surrender, after only six weeks of combat, shocked the world. But
the Fall of France was _ and still is _ more than the story of an
amazing military upset. By CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday, June 6:
</P>
<P>
   FILM-POWERS-PROFILE (Los Angeles) _ Shhh, baby. Snuggle up
close, and I'll whisper a secret. No way this Mike Myers chap is
the same fabulously groovy fellow playing that cool Austin Powers
or that deliciously evil domehead Dr. Evil. How could this shy and
rather, er, unimposing guy be the irreverent, hiply stupid swinger
of the summer's second-most-talked about sequel? ``Austin Powers:
The Spy Who Shagged Me'' opens Friday, June 11. By LOUIS B. PARKS
(For release Sunday, June 6.)
</P>
