<HEADLINE>
NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE ADVISORY
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following is a menu for this week's New America News
Service:
</P>
<P>
   LATINAS ARE CLIMBING THE CORPORATE LADDER. ``Hispanics are going
to be the largest minority group in the country. There will be
opportunity for those who can understand the culture and the
language,'' says Amanda P. Contreras, a member of the steering
committee of HACEMOS, an organization that promotes the advancement
of Hispanics. While at first glance, the prospects of a Latina
finding success in the upper echelons of corporate America may seem
dismal, Contreras and other Latinas have broken through the glass
ceiling. By Kimberly Garcia. Excerpted from Hispanic magazine.
(slugged: BC-CORPORATE-LATINAS-NU-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   HARDWORKING MEN AND WOMEN DEFEAT THE UNION. Just days ago,
Mexican-born strawberry pickers in California once again tossed the
``suit-sponsored United Farm Workers Union out on its ear _ like
free men can and should,'' writes Raoul Lowery Contreras. In this
commentary, Contreras offers a brief history of the UFW and details
its recent attempt to organize the pickers. Contreras praises the
workers for voting for the Coastal Berry Farmworkers Committee, a
local organizing committee that, to Contreras, has the pickers'
best interests at heart. Contreras is an editorial board member of
La Prensa San Diego. (slugged: BC-HIGH-TECH-HISPANICS-NU-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   HISPANICS IN TECHNOLOGY. Though they currently don't participate
in technology to the extent of other ethnic groups, Hispanics are
gaining in number in high-tech careers. ``The Internet is the
language of the future,'' says Jorge Toro, CEO of Toro Technologies
Inc., in Clayton, Mo. ``Being bilingual, Hispanics are especially
fitted for that future. We bring a more international perspective
that prepares the country for the global market.'' By the editors
of Hispanic Business magazine. (slugged:
BC-HIGH-TECH-HISPANICS-NU-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   THE LEADERS IN HIGHER EDUCATION FOR NATIVE-AMERICANS. What's one
of America's best-kept secrets? According to Tim Giago, CEO of book
publishers Lakota Times Publishing Inc., its the 32 tribal colleges
scattered across our nation. These institutions have enjoyed near
unprecedented success despite congressional criticism, opposition
and meager appropriations. They would have certainly failed, Giago
writes, were it not for the determination of certain Indian
educators and leaders _ including Dr. Leroy Clifford and Dr. Lionel
Bordeaux _ who understood the importance of higher education among
Native-Americans and took action. (slugged:
BC-TRIBAL-COLLEGES:GIAGO-NU-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   A WHIRLWIND TOUR OF GAZA, INCLUDING THE INSIDE OF A JAIL. ``On
May 22, I spent almost three hours in the custody of the
Palestinian police in Gaza City,'' writes Bill Maxwell, New
America's African-American columnist currently on assignment in
Israel. ``After recovering from fear of being tortured and locked
away for years, I acknowledged to myself and to my captors that,
because of my ignorance, I belonged in Yasser Arafat's jail.''
Maxwell's offense: taking pictures of the Palestinian Authority's
new headquarters, which he mistakenly thought was a new school.
Maxwell's detailed descriptions of his adventures in Gaza rival any
Hollywood script. (slugged: BC-TOURING-GAZA:MAXWELL-NU-NYTSF)
</P>
