<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-UPS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRS DEMANDS FOR BACK TAXES A 'P.R. GAME,' UPS SAYS
 &HT;    By JERRY MOSKAL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ United Parcel Service says the Internal Revenue
Service is playing a public relations ``game'' by continuing to
file tax cases while both sides await a U.S. Tax Court decision on
the 1983 spinoff of Overseas Partners Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   UPS filed a petition May 24 asking the tax court to overturn an
IRS order seeking $495.19 million in back federal taxes, penalties
and interest for the 1988-90 tax years. In April, UPS filed a
petition appealing an IRS demand for $333.3 million for 1985-87.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the IRS continues to play this P.R. game, it appears we
will be seeing more of these filings,'' said Norman Black, the
company's chief spokesman. ``We're not exactly sure why they feel a
need to file this stuff. It just seems to be a waste.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another chapter in a very old book, and it's getting
very old,'' Black said in a telephone interview Thursday. ``What
the IRS is doing for each three-year block is saying that, 'If we
win this, this is how much UPS will owe us.' They have no more
grounds to assume they're going to win that case than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   An IRS spokesman said the agency does not comment on pending tax
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Black said the issues for the 1988-90 tax years are a replay of
those in the 1985-87 tax case, and involve investment tax credits
and depreciation schedules and deductions.
</P>
<P>
   All these are peripheral matters, he said, which could be
resolved in negotiations with the IRS once a decision is reached by
Tax Court Judge Robert Rowe in the 1995 trial.
</P>
<P>
   That case is over possible tax consequences to UPS from the
firm's decision on Dec. 31, 1983, to give its shareholders a
dividend in the form of Overseas Partners Ltd. (OPL) stock that
made the Bermuda-based reinsurance company independent. UPS claims
the OPL stock
</P>
<P>
   dividends are taxable to the shareholders who received them. The
company claims it has no ties to OPL.
</P>
<P>
   OPL offers reinsurance to companies on policies that UPS
customers buy from independent insurance companies such as National
Union Fire Insurance Co. of Pittsburgh to insure packages that are
worth more than $100.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very comfortable and confident about our position on
that particular issue of OPL,'' Black said. ``We're confident about
our case and we look forward to receiving the judge's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS, which was founded in Seattle in 1907 and has 330,000
employees worldwide, argued in its latest petition that the IRS
erred when it ruled that the construction of 15 package delivery
centers were depreciable property, but that land improvements
</P>
<P>
   couldn't be depreciated.
</P>
<P>
   The company also challenged the IRS ruling that it had to
depreciate rather than deduct inspection and maintenance costs of
its fleet of jet cargo aircraft, and the amount and timing of
investment tax credits for the purchase of aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS notice of tax deficiency was filed Feb. 23, and the
agency has 60 days to respond to the company's May 24 petition. If
the case is not resolved in negotiations, it could go to trial
before a tax court judge.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
