<P>
   &UR; STEM CELLS COULD SCREEN OUT TOXIC NEW DRUGS &LR;  _ A biotechnology
company in California believes that embryonic stem (ES) cells could
provide a quick, accurate way of identifying dangerous experimental
drugs that might damage the liver. The team believe that cultures
of ES cells could screen out excessively toxic pharmaceuticals
before they are tested on animals or people. By Philip Cohen. 350
Words.(slugged: BC-TOXIC-DRUGS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRAINY MICROWAVE OVEN COULD WARN OF DANGER &LR;  _ A new intelligent
microwave oven, developed in New Jersey, that knows how to cook
convenience foods, could also warn people with allergies that their
dinner may contain potentially dangerous ingredients such as
peanuts. You simply swipe the packaging from your ready meal over a
bar-code scanner on the oven's front panel. By Duncan
Graham-Rowe.400 words. (slugged:
BC-BRAINY-MICROWAVE-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MELTING GLACIERS THREATEN SOUTH ASIAN FLOODS &LR;  _ Melting
Himalayan glaciers are threatening to unleash a torrent of floods
into mountain valleys, and ultimately dry up rivers in South Asia.
A new study from the University of Delhi predicts that most of the
glaciers in the region will vanish within 40 years as a result of
global warming. By Fred Pearce. 550 words. (slugged:
BC-MELTING-GLACIERS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RADIO TRANSMITTERS KEEP TABS ON PLAYERS &LR;  _ Sports people who
push themselves too hard can now be spotted before it's too late
thanks to a system developed by a software company in Melbourne.
During training, players wear a device sewn into their sportswear
which can relay physiological information, such as heart rate, to
medical staff. By Ian Anderson. 300 words. (slugged:
BC-RADIO-TRASMITTERS-NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
