<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2980 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-INSTINCT-     06-04 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-INSTINCT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTHONY HOPKINS' BAD HAIR DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not to disparage the thatch on one of the planet's great actors
(oh, why not?), but have you ever noticed that the length of
Anthony Hopkins' hair is directly proportional to the silliness of
the movie in which he appears?
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Mask of Zorro,'' a good silly movie, he suffers in
prison and grows his hair after witnessing the murder of his wife.
(Twenty years later, it's only down to his shoulders.) In ``Legends
of the Fall,'' a bad silly movie, Hopkins suffers a stroke and
grows his hair after witnessing the complete narrative collapse of
the plot.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Silence of the Lambs,'' on the other hand, his hair is
short, neat, brutally slicked back _ as befits a blade-sharp serial
killer. In ``Howards End,'' it's clipped and Edwardian. ``Remains
of the Day'': short. ``Amistad'': bald on top, longish in back,
reflecting the uneven merits of the film. ``Shadowlands'': short.
``Bram Stoker's Dracula'': over the ears.
</P>
<P>
   Given this trend, it's obvious what to expect from ``Instinct,''
a film in which the Hopkins hairdo hits Monica length, minus the
flip. Playing a growly scientist jailed for killing Rwandan park
rangers, Hopkins is watchable, which he always is, and believable,
which he usually is, and ogrish, which he sometimes is. He's also
one of a few remotely interesting elements in a movie so fat with
cliches it needs liposuction to squeeze through the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instinct'' was directed by Jon Turteltaub (who gave us the
more felicitously cliched ``Phenomenon'') and ``suggested'' by
Daniel Quinn's eco-novel ``Ishmael,'' implying that not much other
than environmentalism and large primates were borrowed from it.
Hopkins is Ethan Powell, a career-obsessed anthropologist who
spends two years living in the African jungle with a family of
gorillas.
</P>
<P>
   When Powell whacks a pair of rangers with a wooden club, he gets
arrested, turns mute and is quickly extradited to the psychotics'
ward in a foul Florida prison. There he encounters Theo Caulder
(Cuba Gooding Jr.), a young, ladder-climbing shrink with an
unctuous mentor (Donald Sutherland, no slouch in the hair
department) and the naive belief that he can get the prisoner to
answer a list of dry psychiatric questions.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, he hasn't seen enough movies. If Theo had only bothered
to rent ``Silence of the Lambs,'' he would have realized that
jailed killers always seize control of every interview with all
young saplings. ``These sessions can be your opportunity,'' he
says, delivering the sort of psycho-squishy aphorism that litters
Gerald DiPego's screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   Listen, Cuba Gooding is a fine actor. He exudes smarts, handles
dialogue with trim economy and holds his own with the big bear
Hopkins, who has a way of eating lesser co-stars. Their wrangling
(some of it literal) is entertaining in a skanky, visceral way,
like watching a bull trying to gore a matador or a woman pulling
her boyfriend's hair on ``Jerry Springer.'' You know Powell is
going to have the upper hand, but still, it's sick fun when he
slaps duct tape on Theo's mouth and forces him to confess his
inadequacies in thick red crayon.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what happens: Theo learns The Truth of what happened on
that fated day in the forest. Guess what else happens: He begins to
regard Powell as a friend, a teacher, a guru who awakens him to the
brutish arrogance of human beings. He also spends a major subplot
trying to reform the psych ward (peopled with offensive stock
wackos) and a minor subplot trying to patch up Powell's
dysfunctional relationship with his daughter (Maura Tierney,
underused).
</P>
<P>
   All of this is done to the tune of Danny Elfman's noisy,
sniffling score, which launches into a celestial chorus whenever
Hopkins happens to glance at the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse us, but isn't it time to call a moratorium on heavenly
choirs? No more of those _ ever, on any movie soundtrack, under any
circumstances. No more people standing in the rain, arms
outstretched, faces broad and placid, as the healing powers of
water baptize them anew. And no more variations on ``I Am
Spartacus!'' There's got to be some other way to convey the
brotherhood of the oppressed.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and one more thing: the Hopkins hair. Snip it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
