<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2984 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-REAL-HNS &LR;      06-04 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-REAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GET REAL' CARRIES UNIVERSAL APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Get Real'' is a coming-of-age film, a coming-out film, a
falling-to-pieces film and a film about coming together. It is
small and smart, painful and funny.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Simon Shore (``The English Wife,'' for British
television) from Patrick Wilde's adaptation of his own stage play
(``What's Wrong With Angry?''), ``Get Real'' rests on a simple
plot: Boy meets boy. Boy loves boy. Boy and boy cope variously, and
furtively, with the pressures of being gay adolescents in a
straight world.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tale of forbidden love, told with a trickle of references
to ``Romeo and Juliet.'' It is not, therefore, either original or
surprising; anyone who's seen a few high-school movies knows
exactly which characters are going to turn out to be homophobic
louts. But Wilde's script maneuvers around stereotypes so deftly
that even the screenplay's most obvious moralizing _ about
acceptance, and love, and damaging assumptions _ never gets
saccharine or preachy. And Shore directs with a generous heart but
scant sentimentality, drawing fresh performances from a young,
mostly unknown cast.
</P>
<P>
   The standout is Ben Silverstone, whose biggest role thus far was
the young Humbert Humbert in Adrian Lyne's ``Lolita.'' As Steven, a
closeted British teen-ager with a yen for the Big Man On Campus,
Silverstone has a man-boy weariness that's half ironic
self-possession, half vulnerable schoolkid. He may brag about the
hunk he snared in the public toilets, but he's still just a child
yearning for acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   The object of Steven's affections is John (Brad Gorton), a
popular, wavy-maned track star who seems to incite the lust of
every girl in school. By all indications he's straight as a pencil;
he even dates a model, surely the gold standard of male
heterosexuality. But out of nowhere, John hits on Steve in a
bathroom _ rattling Steve, terrifying himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what came over me,'' he says, and quickly
disavows the urge that led him there. From the beginning, one thing
is clear: This ain't gonna be easy for him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet John can't keep away from Steven. Despite his misgivings,
the two become lovers _ stealth lovers, sworn to secrecy and
determined to keep up facades. Both are closeted, but John is
petrified; he can't admit he's gay to himself, much less the track
team. And as they embark on their affair, the agony of being true
to each other and false to everyone else begins to chip away at
their romance, their friendship and their self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   The moral is clear: Society should accept kids as they are, love
as it is and Get Real. But Shore and Wilde have crafted such a
big-hearted, character-driven story that even its most brazen
speechifying doesn't feel awkward; it's dramatically apt.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton brings transparent suffering to the riven John, turning
what might have been a boiler-plate dim jock into a complex,
sympathetic character. The rest of the cast _ including David
Lumsden as Steven's blindered dad and Charlotte Brittain as Linda,
his staunch best pal _ add humor and light to an already affable
film.
</P>
<P>
   Like most movies about randy teens (gay or straight), ``Get
Real'' takes a relaxed attitude toward sex. There's much discussion
of the act, little discussion of the consequences. Then again,
adolescents are always confusing sex for love. They're always
experimenting. And they're always looking for ways to escape _
themselves, their fears, their sense that the world at large is
always watching.
</P>
<P>
   It's a universal tale, and anyone who survived puberty will
relate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
