<SLUG> BC-WW2-ANNIVERSARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FALL OF FRANCE 59 YEARS AGO WAS A SHOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA BASS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Calif. _ Sunday is the 55th anniversary of D-Day,
which in this country is probably the best-known battle of World
War II. Less well known than how D-Day happened is why it happened.
</P>
<P>
   What, on June 6, 1944, was France doing in Nazi hands in the
first place? The answer is both depressing and highly instructive.
</P>
<P>
   Four years before D-Day _ in June 1940 _ France fell to the
Nazis. Her swift and complete surrender, after only six weeks of
combat, shocked the world.
</P>
<P>
   But the fall of France was _ and still is _ more than the story
of an amazing military upset. It is also the story of how
attitudes, both public and private, undermined an entire nation
long before Germany fired a single shot.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, France fell so fast even Hitler was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the war in September 1939, France seemed well
equipped to defend herself. Possessing a great military tradition,
an excellent army _ the finest in Europe, according to Stalin _ and
the pride of having already beaten the Germans once this century,
she appeared, without question, ready to beat them again.
</P>
<P>
   However, as soon became clear, there were flaws in French
military preparations. Because the thick forests of the Ardennes
looked like tough going, even for tanks, they were left virtually
undefended.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Maginot Line was reinforced, while the remaining
troops joined the British on the Belgian border. But it was
precisely through the Ardennes that Germany's panzers pounced,
straight into the heart of France.
</P>
<P>
   The second flaw was even more serious. France was well-supplied
with planes, artillery, tanks and infantry, but _ unlike in Germany
_ they did not operate in tandem, but rather as competing services.
</P>
<P>
   This competition crippled communications and the coordination of
action; one order took over 48 hours to travel from headquarters to
the front. By then, the front had become the rear, and the order
was meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   The third _ and most vital _ flaw was strategic. France won
World War I by mounting a ferocious defense against a slow-moving
enemy, and was ready to do so again. But the Nazi war machine was
fast-moving: This was its very essence.
</P>
<P>
   Although the French knew that, having seen Germany in action in
Poland, they persisted in stubbornly planning for a gradual
conflict and a long defensive struggle. Then they were stupefied
when the Nazis didn't play along.
</P>
<P>
   All three of these flaws contributed to France's fall. But they
don't explain why she fell so fast. That failure of will lies deep
within the culture and society of pre-war France.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Bloch, arguably this century's greatest historian _ and a
veteran of both world wars _ explained it best. France collapsed in
the face of the Nazis, Bloch said, because before the war even
began, she had already collapsed internally.
</P>
<P>
   Her leaders had long disdained those who voted them into office;
her electorate had long believed all politicians were corrupt. The
result was a democracy which distrusted democracy, and a nation
which, when the Nazis invaded, was already at war _ with itself.
</P>
<P>
   What Bloch called ``the timidity of the nation'' manifested
itself in numerous ways: a second-rate press which lied to the
people _ and which people knew lied _ but which nobody bothered to
challenge; an educational system out of touch with the needs of the
nation; a leftist tradition too doctrinaire to distinguish between
capitalism and fascism, and a right wing so in love with the past
it could find nothing of merit in the present.
</P>
<P>
   None of these woes was, by itself, enough to destroy a great
nation; together, however, they made France so morally weak that _
when combined with her military weaknesses _ they produced a
surrender breathtaking both in speed and totality.
</P>
<P>
   This same moral weakness prevailed for the next four years, as
the toadies of Vichy France collaborated with the Nazis, right till
the end.
</P>
<P>
   Great nations are made up of great people; when a great nation
falters, its people die. The death of France led to the death of
her greatest scholar; Marc Bloch became a resistance fighter, was
captured by the Nazis, tortured and _ 10 days after D-Day _
executed. Witnesses report his last words were ``Vvive la France.''
</P>
<P>
   Since we appear, at century's end, to be suffering similar
symptoms to those of mid-century France, we should ask ourselves
what we can do to cure ourselves, and how soon we can do it, before
another great nation aids its enemies by defeating itself.
</P>
<P>
   For how much wiser _ and easier _ and less heartbreaking _ it is
to combat cynicism, distrust and moral weakness now, than to read
about our martyred heroes at some bleak future date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
