<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3060 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANTANA-ALBUM-HNS &LR;      06-04 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTANA-ALBUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERO OF LATIN SOUND PREPARES TO RELEASE NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREG HAYMES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Veteran guitar hero Carlos Santana _ a pioneer of the Latin-rock
sound, one of the sparkplugs of the 1969 Woodstock festival and a
member of the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame _ is about to release a
new album that will almost surely guarantee his return to the top
of the charts.
</P>
<P>
   Slated for release June 15, the album titled ``Supernatural'' is
Santana's first for Arista Records and reunites him with Arista
executive Clive Davis, who signed Santana to his first record deal
with Columbia Records more than 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supernatural'' also finds the guitar great collaborating with
a top-notch collection of special guests _ longtime friends and
compatriots as well as newcomers _ who have been influenced by
Santana's music over the years including Eric Clapton, Dave
Matthews, Lauryn Hill, Wyclef Jean, Everlast, Rob Thomas (of
Matchbox 20), Eagle Eye Cherry and more.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the parade of multiplatinum musicians who grace the
album, Santana didn't have his eyes on chart-success when he was in
the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``This album was conceived directly to touch our children in
junior high schools, high schools and universities. With everything
that's happening in our schools, all of these shootings, it's
important to create something that can bring us all together and
not divide us,'' he said during a recent telephone interview from
his New York City hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   ``This music is not entertainment. This is healing music.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look in the dictionary under `healing,' it says `To
be whole and sound.' That's how I wanted the music to sound, with
that kind of balance.''
</P>
<P>
   There has always been a deeply spiritual side to Santana's
instantly recognizable, supremely soulful guitar playing. For all
of the ferocious fire and intensity that he pours into his playing,
there's an undeniably spiritual center to his music, a kind of calm
at the eye of the raging, swirling sound.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Supernatural'' is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   The ball started rolling back in February, when Santana
performed with golden girl Lauryn Hill at the Grammy Awards show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric Clapton was sitting in the front row that night, and he
wanted to know if he could participate in my album,'' Santana
recalls. ``He said, `If you can hear me on your album, I'd like to
be on it, if there's any room for me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Santana laughs. ```Oh, my God,' I said. `Sure.' From there, it
was like a chain reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before that, the album was really just a concept, but kind of
like the Bible says, `This begat that, and that begat this,'''
Santana explains. ``It wasn't intended to be an all-star-studded
album, but the songs really dictated different singers and
different musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really grateful because everyone who participated really
brought the best of their hearts. There was no ego-tripping. Nobody
had a cow.''
</P>
<P>
   Most musicians would be touring straight through to the end of
the year to support such an impressive new album. Santana takes a
more civilized approach to his roadwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since my wife and I had our first child, we decided that it
was important to find a balance,'' Santana says. ``So I go out on
the road for three weeks, and then I'm home for three weeks. I'll
go out for four weeks and stay home for four weeks. Five weeks is
the most time that I'm willing to spend out on tour at one time. I
don't care how much money they dangle in my face, after five weeks
I go home and just be a father, take out the garbage and stuff like
that. Being a person is more important to me than being a
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing more important than my family my wife, my
children, my mom. I'm a person first, middle and last. It's just
that I happen to play the guitar, and people like it, and that's
wonderful. It beats washing dishes for a living. So that's what I
do, but that's not who I am completely.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Santana lineup of musicians has constantly evolved over the
years, and includes such distinguished alumni as keyboardist Gregg
Rollie, drummer Michael Shrieve, vocalist Buddy Miles, bassist
Alphonso Johnson and guitarist Neal Schon (who will be playing at
the Saratoga Performing Arts Center in Saratoga Springs, N.Y.,
later this month as a member of Journey).
</P>
<P>
   The current band features former Tower of Power keyboardist
Chester D. Thompson, former Miles Davis bassist Benny Rietveld,
percussion master Karl Perazzo, conga player Raul Rekow, drummer
Rodney Holmes and vocalist Tony Lindsay.
</P>
<P>
   Santana is often credited with inventing the fusion of Latin and
rock with his early albums ``Caravanserai,'' ``Santana III,''
``Abraxas'' and his self-titled '69 debut. He doesn't see it that
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, one of the first people who cracked that door open was
Ritchie Valens with `Donna' and `La Bamba,''' Santana says.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent upsurge in popularity of Ricky Martin and the
whole rock en espanol movement, Santana isn't comfortable with the
term ``Latin music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This music from `La Bamba' on down is really African music,''
he declares. ``So this whole wave of Ricky Martin, Jennifer Lopez
and Gloria Estefan is really popularizing African music. It's not
Spanish or Latin. It's really African music, whether it's a bolero,
cha-cha, rhumba or samba. Whatever you call it, it's still African
music, and I always like to clear that thing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I play, and that's what I've played from the
beginning _ African music. I combined it with blues, and that's
what made it different, but it's always been African music.''
</P>
<P>
   The blues have remained one of the foundations of Santana's
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can play the blues completely nakedly and truthfully,
then you can play just about any kind of music,'' Santana explains.
``You can't lie when you're playing the blues. You're either
telling the truth or you're trying to fake it. You can't hide.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when the young guitarist formed his band back in 1966,
it was originally called the Santana Blues Band. Three years later,
the band, with the name then shortened simply to Santana, burst
onto the national rock scene with a historic performance at the
Woodstock festival, even before the band had released its first
album.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his most vivid memory of that legendary
Woodstock performance, Santana doesn't hesitate. ``When I close my
eyes, I can still hear the sound,'' he says. ``I remember that I
could hear the sound before I played it. I heard it inside my head,
and then it came out through my fingers. Then through the monitor
speakers. Then the PA. Then from the PA, the sound went out all the
way across this ocean of bodies. Then it came back to me again. So
I was hearing a kind of six or seven dimensional sound coming in
rounds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
