<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans four pages of stories on Kosovo for
Saturday, June 5.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX (Washington) _ Lede-all: Developments,
political reaction, assessment. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ Gen. Michael Jackson, the
British officer who will command peacekeeping force, is going to
Belgrade on Saturday to meet Yugoslav Army brass; bombing may end
Sunday. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-RECOVERY (Washington) _ On how Yugoslavia's recovery might
be constrained by fact that its president has been indicted on
war-crimes charges. By R.W. Apple. (Eds: May become an analysis, in
which case -ASSESS will be added to slug.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Why Milosevic said
yes. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ How/why the military campaign is
coming to its end. By Eric Schmitt and Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ China's reaction to peace deal. It
insists bombing must end before Security Council adopts resolution.
By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Washington) _ Military and intelligence planning
for the Kosovo Liberation Army; the KLA also calls news conference
in Tirana, Albania, to talk about the deal (may become separate
story). By Steven Lee Myers and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
