<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-BORDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY TO FOCUS ON RISE IN DIABETES IN BORDER STATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE FOY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Health officials plan an ambitious, binational
project to try to tackle the rising incidence of diabetes along the
U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   The undertaking, which will entail door-to-door contacts with
nearly 3,000 border residents, involves the six Mexican border
states as well as Arizona, California, New Mexico and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials from each country will attempt to monitor the
increasing prevalence of diabetes among people who live along the
border. They also plan a comprehensive diabetes prevention
education campaign that would be tailored to the specific health
needs of the region.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Espey, an epidemiologist with the New Mexico
Department of Health, told members of the U.S.-Mexico Border Health
Association on Thursday that the existing statistics on border
diabetes and related risk factors are not extensive enough to
adequately measure the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it really looks like there is a much higher
diabetes burden on the border,'' he said. ``But we need a more
complete picture about conditions on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, Espey said, is the lack of a uniform
sampling method. The aim of the new initiative, called the
Collaborative U.S.-Mexican Diabetes Prevention and Control Project,
is to gather comparative data from both sides of the border, Espey
said. Existing statistics indicate Mexican border states have
experienced a dramatic rise in recent years in the mortality rates
associated with diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Those increases have ranged from 5 percent to 13 percent. The
U.S. side of the border also is struggling with the scope of the
problem. For instance, the prevalence of diabetes in the lower Rio
Grande Valley is about three times the national average,
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   The onset of diabetes in adults is most often associated with
poor diet, obesity and other health factors. The disease attacks
the eyes, kidneys and heart, although proper medical treatment can
reduce the effects.
</P>
<P>
   Although the border project remains in the development stages,
public health officials plan to begin a door-to-door survey of
residents at risk for diabetes. Health officials plan to interview
350 residents in each of the four U.S. states and 250 residents in
each of the six Mexican states.
</P>
<P>
   Information collected will include a person's height, weight,
blood pressure and access to health care. Participants then will be
given a financial incentive to follow up at a local laboratory for
diabetes glucose testing.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with information on the scope of the problem, health
officials hope to more effectively construct diabetes prevention
programs, Espey said. The survey is scheduled to begin in about six
months.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Health has committed $60,000 to fund the
initial stages of the project. Several other funding sources from
both sides of the border are ``coming together,'' Espey said.
</P>
<P>
   Also during the U.S.-Mexico Border Health Association's annual
meeting, held in San Antonio, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas,
stressed that more needs to be done to support public health in the
border region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to redouble my efforts in Congress to make sure that
this area of the country is getting its fair share of the
attention,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison commended the Texas Legislature for recently
earmarking $50 million for a new Border Health Institute, to be
located in El Paso. She also stressed that the North American
Development Bank needs to make more headway on certifying water,
sewer and other environmental projects along the border.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison also said she supported collaborative efforts by the
United States and Mexico to try to eradicate tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is stunning to me that in the United States of America, we
have had a resurgence of tuberculosis,'' she said. ``This was a
disease that we thought was a disease of the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
