<SLUG> BC-GOOD-GUYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDER TO RETURN TO STRUGGLING ELECTRONICS RETAILER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The original Good Guy is back.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald A. Unkefer will again take the helm of the consumer
electronics retailer he founded 26 years ago. But this time around,
he'll be in charge of saving the chain, which has been losing money
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Good Guys, which has 79 stores in California, Nevada, Oregon
and Washington state, posted a 1998 loss of $8.9 million on sales
of $929 million. The Brisbane, Calif.-based company's stock also
has been in the doldrums in trading on the Nasdaq exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer, who will begin his post as the company's chairman and
chief executive on July 1 and is taking a 10 percent stake in The
Good Guys, said his first priority would be to beef up profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to restore it to its glory days,'' Unkefer said
Thursday in a telephone interview from Dallas, where he's been
chairman of a venture capital company, First Ventures, for 2 1/2
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is still positioned well,'' he added. ``Sales have
not gone down. The customer base is still here.''
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer said he did not yet have a specific plan for restoring
the company to profitability, but he's considering a reorganization
of the company, a strategy that would stock the stores with new,
higher-end electronics, or a combination of both approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``By July, when I show up, I'll have a clearer plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer said he would definitely strengthen The Good Guys'
marketing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Good Guys has enjoyed the upper-end niche of the market,''
he said. ``We have to make that point clearer.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the company becomes profitable, Unkefer said The Good Guys
would launch a ``monster Internet site'' where customers can buy
products.
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer replaces Robert A. Gunst, who resigned in April after
serving as the company's chief executive since 1993. Gunst, who had
been with The Good Guys a total of 13 years, was previously the
chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer left The Good Guys in 1996. To date, he has invested in
eight high-tech start-ups, including Redwood City, Calif.-based
InfoGear Technology Corp., a small company that makes phones with
mini-computer screens for Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer wouldn't comment on the financial problems at The Good
Guys, but analysts said the company has suffered from a dearth of
new product offerings and growing competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Good Guys has ``a lack of new product introductions, and
they've shifted toward more commodity products,'' said Annie Erner,
an analyst at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. in New York. ``So you can buy them
at Wal-Mart as easily as a consumer electronics retailer.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Alton, managing partner of the San Francisco investment
bank L.H. Alton &AMP; Co., said other retailers, particularly Circuit
City and Best Buy, have chipped away at The Good Guys market, which
was once the dominant retailer in the San Francisco area.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the challenges, Alton was optimistic about Unkefer's
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron has charisma,'' Alton said. ``Of all the people I've known
in this business, Ron would have a chance. Gunst is really a CFO
and should never have had the helm. The difference between being a
CFO and a good marketing guy is figuring out what customers need
and how to get it to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
