<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-REFUGEE-BOS-ART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEE HAS TALE TO TELL HARVARD PEERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Before he falls asleep, Harvard senior
Selamawi ``Mawi'' Asgedom pulls a sheet across his face, a
protective ritual he has repeated every night since he was a young
boy fleeing strife in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother told me to always sleep with a sheet over my head to
keep away the snakes,'' says Asgedom, a half-Ethiopian,
half-Eritrean refugee. ``In the refugee camps there were cases of
people who were killed after snakes slipped into their open
mouths.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long journey from the snake-infested refugee camps
in the Sudan to Harvard's Tercentenary Theatre, where Asgedom will
stand next week before thousands and give the senior English
oration on Commencement Day.
</P>
<P>
   But America has not been the safe haven Asgedom's family thought
it would be. Having escaped civil war in the Horn of Africa,
Asgedom's father and brother were killed in separate accidents by
drunk drivers in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Asgedom has never shown any outward sign of anger, said
Richard Marius, a retired senior lecturer of English at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a gentleness that has come from the horror,'' said
Marius, who was among the judges who picked Asgedom as speaker.
``You and I might become very bitter . . . But Mawi has become very
gentle as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   Asgedom was born in 1976 on the Ethiopian-Eritrean border. Since
the early 1960s, Eritrea had been locked in a brutal civil war for
independence from Ethiopia, a conflict that left many thousands
homeless, wounded, or dead.
</P>
<P>
   Asgedom's father, Haileab, was a rural doctor and an ardent
Eritrean nationalist allied with a rebel group, the Eritrean
Liberation Front. When another rebel group took control of the
area, Haileab, afraid for his life, fled to neighboring Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Seven or eight months later, fearful that they would be
murdered, the rest of the Asgedom family began the long, perilous
trek to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling by donkey and camel but mostly by foot, the family
made their way to dusty, semi-desert grasslands on the border with
Sudan. Asgedom's mother, Tsege, carried the 3-year-old Selamawi and
his 2-year-old sister, Mehret, for hundreds of miles while their
7-year-old brother, Tewolde, walked.
</P>
<P>
   When they reached a refugee camp in Kassala, Sudan, they were
reunited with Asgedom's father. The camp was a desperate,
fly-infested place, and many of the refugees arrived more dead than
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``One woman,'' recalled Asgedom, ``walked the soles off her
feet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Asgedoms spent three years in a UN camp. With assistance
from the Wheaton, Ill.-based refugee assistance group, World
Relief, his family was able to move to the United States. A church
in Wheaton provided the family with clothing, food and housing.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a painful transition. ``I got Cs and Ds in first
grade,'' Asgedom said. ``It was hard being poor and black and not
speaking English in an all-white community. Kids would call us
names, things like `Black Donkey.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The change was particularly hard on Asgedom's father. Unable to
qualify as a doctor in Illinois, he took a job as a janitor. But
after a few years he had to stop work because of failing eyesight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has always been one of the saddest things for me,''
Asgedom said. ``I only knew him as a handicapped individual. He'd
gone from being one of the most esteemed and respected and useful
people to someone who didn't feel useful and appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   By third grade, Asgedom was speaking fluent English. By the
junior year of high school, he had done so well that he was told he
could attend any college he wanted. He was accepted at both Yale
and Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a bittersweet triumph for Asgedom, who had lost his
brother in 1992, when a drunk driver crashed into Tewolde's car as
he drove to visit a friend in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember coming home to see my mother screaming and my
father screaming,'' said Asgedom, whose dorm-room wall is decorated
with a photograph of his brother flanked by flags of Ethiopia and
Eritrea. ``We were really close.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, last year, tragedy struck the Asgedom family a second
time. A woman struck Asgedom's father as he rode his bicycle just a
few yards from their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems impossible that the same thing could happen to the
same family twice,'' said Asgedom. ``The fact that my father and
brother both survived war, famine, and disease things, but came to
America and couldn't survive drunk driving seemed amazingly tragic
in a twisted, Shakespearean sort of way.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite it all, Asgedom still considers himself fortunate. At
Harvard, which paid for much of his tuition, he concentrated in
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there have been some nasty blows along the way _ two
really nasty ones. But I can't forget the things I've been given
that a lot of my countrymen will never have. There are still a lot
of reasons to keep smiling in this world.''
</P>
<P>
   When he graduates, Asgedom wants to set up an Africa-based Web
site and teach. In his spare time, he said he wants to speak to
schools about his life experiences and about the dangers of drunken
driving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1426EDT &QL; 
