<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3123 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICH-SCHOOL-VIOLENCE-     06-04 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-SCHOOL-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEGED PLOT BY MICHIGAN TEENS FUELS CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JON HALL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT HURON, Mich. _ It started with several students in the back
of a classroom discussing Time and Newsweek articles about the
shootings at Columbine High School in Colorado, then continued on a
dock near the shoreline of Lake Huron.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the students were upset about family problems, not
getting along with parents and a couple of fellow students. Soon
the talk turned to re-creating the violence at their own middle
school. They kept talking about it for several days. Others
overheard, and three weeks ago, four of the youths were charged
with plotting a mass murder.
</P>
<P>
   One of the defense lawyers says the plot might be better named
after the movie ``Dumb and Dumber.'' ``If this was adults, we'd be
laughing,'' said Kenneth Lord.
</P>
<P>
   But no one in the town of 34,000 is laughing, as police and
prosecutors try to build a case against the youths, based on the
overheard comments and the words of one of the 14-year-olds, Justin
Schnepp.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Schnepp's statements that he and others intended to
``shoot up'' the school are a confession. Defenders of the youths
say the comments are just teenage bravado blown out of proportion
by authorities overly skittish in the aftermath of Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Fick and Jonathan McDonald, both 13, have been bound over
for trial in Circuit Court, while a decision is pending on whether
there is probable cause to try Schnepp and another 14-year-old,
Jedaiah ``David'' Zinzo. A decision on the latter two is due after
legal arguments are submitted June 11. A trial date will be set for
the younger two on June 14.
</P>
<P>
   A tough stance against students making threats is not unique to
Port Huron. Nationwide, police and school officials are cracking
down on any behavior that appears threatening. Civil rights lawyers
say they have heard a string of complaints from parents whose
children have been arrested or disciplined for everything from
vaguely threatening speech to unconventional dress or disturbing
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   In a case similar to the one in Port Huron, four boys in
Jacksonville, Ark., were detained by police after they allegedly
discussed bringing guns to school, and one had reportedly said he
could get a gun from an uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Sklar, executive director of the Arkansas American Civil
Liberties Union, was quoted by the Washington Post as saying the
boys' gun talk was ``schoolyard chatter,'' and criticized the
Arkansas law for not distinguishing ``what's a threat from what's a
fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, defense lawyers say the law forces the use of a
harsh statute on conspiracy to commit murder. Even that, they say,
requires definite acts, deeds, and agreements that have not been
shown in this case.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the government's case is this: Several students
say they were present when the suspects said they planned to steal
guns, go to school, attack the principal, then call an assembly, at
which they would murder as many students as possible. Also, one of
the suspects reportedly asked another student to help work up a
map, but the student refused and told school officials the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no physical evidence of the alleged scheme _ none
of the hit lists, maps, or annotated plans that police had said
existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked ... for the hit list, any maps, etc.,'' said
another defense lawyer, Frank Mitchell. ``The prosecutor's office
doesn't have anything.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the suspects had guns, and testimony in court hearings
during the last week indicated little agreement on how they might
rob a local gun shop, attack the school, or kill students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no consistent version,'' said Fred Lepley, another
member of the defense team. ``You get different stories from
everybody, and there's a simple reason for that because there
simply was never any agreement in this matter. There's no
conspiracy here to commit murder.''
</P>
<P>
   The testimony indicated that the Port Huron plot was only idle,
angry chatter, much of it in classes or hallways of the school.
``If you're going to do this,'' said Mitchell, ``you certainly
don't tell half the school.''
</P>
<P>
   One key witness, student Dana Thomas, testified that she did not
think the four youths were serious. ``I figured that they were just
blowing off some steam because they were all pretty angry with
their parents that day.'' She and others also testified that some
of the four were angry at being teased by other youths.
</P>
<P>
   School Superintendent William Kimball refused to discuss the
facts or evidence, but said he does not think authorities
overreacted.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Prosecutor Michael Wendling, one who is handling the
case, agreed that at another time, the situation would have been
handled differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``As prosecuting attorney, I look at the facts that are brought
to me,'' Wendling said. ``I would agree that maybe 10 to 15 years
ago, things, threats of this nature wouldn't have been taken so
seriously in this society.''
</P>
<P>
   But he says that in light of the school shootings, he has to
take the threats seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any parent that would want us to throw
the dice,'' Wendling said, ``or take a chance on this just being an
childish prank.''
</P>
<P>
   And with some reason. The day after initial phone threats to the
592-student Holland Woods Middle School and the arrests of the four
youths, a pipe bomb was found near an outside wall. The origin of
the bomb remains under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, police arrested more students in connection with
making bomb threats, both to Holland Woods, and for threatening a
``blood bath'' at the city's high schools. Police said there is no
connection between the latest arrests and the murder-conspiracy
case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
