<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO WINS THE WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the right war for the right reasons in the place it had
to be fought if the West were to stand for anything. The NATO
bombing was necessary to curb a far greater evil. The West won; the
West was always going to win; the West had to win.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was late. Sure, there were lots of things we should
have done, or tried to do, before the first Cruise missiles flew.
Maybe late, maybe disorganized, maybe not as skillfully or as
resolutely as, in hindsight, we might have wished, but the right
thing was done to rectify a dreadful situation not of the West's
making.
</P>
<P>
   NATO redeemed its promises, its budget commitments, and its
intricate command-and-control structure, a miracle of high-tech
string-and-chewing-gum that held together a fragile coalition. But
an even greater miracle was the delivery of a fierce onslaught from
the air without a single NATO combat casualty.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, Tony Blair, and the political chieftains of
NATO prevailed. Slobodan Milosevic capitulated. Driven farther back
into his cave by a barrage of air attacks, the rogue Serb is
finally contained.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off his self-imposed impeachment ordeal, Clinton was
physically and psychologically exhausted, personally embarrassed,
financially imperiled, and substantially diminished. Politically,
he was near-impotent. Even the newspapers that had editorialized
against impeachment routinely treated him with contempt.
</P>
<P>
   No moral authority, thundered his critics. He can't lead. He's
too weak, too indecisive, too accommodating. His Republican enemies
_ and a lot of them are true enemies, not just political opponents,
after Clinton's year of living dangerously _ savaged him over the
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not worth the life of one American Marine,'' blustered Pat
Buchanan, the Vietnam-era speechwriter whose bad knee kept him out
of Nixon's war. The Republican majority in the House even denied
Clinton formal authorization of the US-led NATO bombing campaign, a
gratuitous gesture spawned in the post-impeachment swamp that
swallowed the GOP leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Alone among the 11 Republicans running for president, Senator
John McCain of Arizona called for a win-at-any-cost strategy,
including the commitment of ground troops, a commitment Clinton
refused to make. ``Although I agree that American interests and
values are at such risk in the Balkans that we must fight to
protect them,'' McCain said, ``what has concerned me most has been
the president's willingness to sacrifice American stature and honor
abroad, his willingness even to lose a war, rather than risk his
own political capital.''
</P>
<P>
   The nub of McCain's argument is that Clinton should have been
willing to accept American casualties to press the war. This is the
Ulysses S. Grant approach, admirable in a warrior, but not always
dominant in the mind of a politician who has more to think about
than just the military man's preoccupation with victory on the
battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Fears that the Russians, the Chinese, or European public opinion
would rebel against the United States are now fading. NATO leaders
gambled that air power alone would defeat Milosevic, and won their
bet. Milosevic started the whole thing, driving one million ethnic
Albanians from their homeland at bayonet-point _ their homes
destroyed, their men shot, their women raped, their papers
destroyed, their cash and valuables looted.
</P>
<P>
   The UN says that 983,451 individuals have fled since Milosevic's
dogs of war were let loose 15 months ago, an exodus of biblical
proportions. Not since Hitler raged across the European land mass
in the 1940s has so much bloodshed been triggered by one evildoer.
Those who argue that the bombs aggravated the refugee situation
have to account for two uncomfortable facts: 100,000 refugees
sought asylum or were driven out before the first bomb fell, and
the overwhelming majority of them approved of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In the 72 days since March 24, NATO warplanes flew 31,529 combat
sorties over some of the roughest terrain, in some of the lousiest
weather, and brought every man in every air crew back alive. That
is a phenomenal record. The professionalism, training, and
equipping of the NATO airmen forced the Serb dictator to back down.
</P>
<P>
   By NATO's count, the Serb forces that had ravaged Bosnia,
Croatia, and Slovenia before Kosovo lost over 100 aircraft, 314
artillery pieces, 471 military vehicles, 120 tanks, 14 command
posts, 45 rail and highway bridges, 57 percent of fuel stockpiles
and 29 percent of ammunition stores.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic capitulated because he had no other choice. The Serb
forces must retreat, and then come back to clear their land mines.
Now, there's a job for Slobodan. With any luck, he'd be Slobo-gone
in short order after a stint of mine-clearing.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's ranking war criminal has wrecked the country he has led
for 12 years. ``No one will dare to beat you,'' he roared to Serb
partisans in Kosovo 12 years ago. He never figured NATO would step
up as it did.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
