<HEADER>
A3134 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HORSE-LISTENER-BOS &LR; - &UR;      06-04 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSE-LISTENER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAN WITH HORSE SENSE AND SENSIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
 - ART  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass _ ``I'm on a mission,'' Monty Roberts sats,
before a small group gathered recently at the Harvard University
Coop to listen to the man who listens to horses. ``I'm on a mission
of nonviolence. Nonviolence toward animals and nonviolence toward
people. That's what I've learned from the horses. That violence
never works.''
</P>
<P>
   Like an old-time revivalist, Roberts, who earlier in the day had
spoken at Angell Memorial Hospital, travels from town to town
spreading the latest gospel on nonviolent horsemanship and, through
metaphor and parable, the message of gentler human relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Later Monday night, he preached to the viewers of Channel 11,
the New Hampshire public television station, during their auction
period. Later, before an overflow crowd at the Topsfield
Fairgrounds, he illustrated his ``Join-Up'' method for training
horses through cooperation rather than domination.
</P>
<P>
   While Roberts, 64, made his reputation as a horseman, it wasn't
until his first book, ``The Man Who Listens to Horses,'' hit The
New York Times bestseller list and stayed there for two years that
Roberts's reputation transcended the horsy set.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done to the horse is criminal,'' he says. ``We must
make it up to a species that has been wonderful to us while we've
abused and mistreated them. For no reason except ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   He hits the last word hard.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts learned a bit about performing while working on movie
sets. In 1940, at the age of 5, already an accomplished horseman,
Warner Bros. signed him to do stunts and bit parts. His movie
career included doubling for Roddy McDowall in ``My Friend Flicka''
(1943) and riding for Elizabeth Taylor in the long shots in
``National Velvet'' (1944).
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, the studio asked him to become a technical adviser on
Elia Kazan's ``East of Eden,'' starring James Dean. Roberts and
Dean became friendly, and the young actor asked Roberts to look for
a horse farm he might buy. On Sept. 30, 1955, Dean was on his way
to a California auto rally and to look at a farm with Monty when he
was killed in a traffic accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked him very much,'' says Roberts. ``He was a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   (Roberts's most recent experience with the movie business was
different. Although Nicholas Evans interviewed Roberts for his
novel, ``The Horse Whisperer,'' and Robert Redford inquired about
his availability to be a technical adviser on Redford's film
version, the trainer was disillusioned by both experiences.)
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who raises racehorses, realizes that the time around
Triple Crown events elevates public awareness of matters equine.
His New England visit is sandwiched between last Saturday's
Massachusetts Handicap, where Real Quiet, last year's Kentucky
Derby winner, finished third, and Saturday's Belmont Stakes, where
Charismatic is a threat to become the first colt since Seattle Slew
in 1977 to win the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   While Roberts doesn't object to horse racing, he's trying to
persuade jockeys to drop their whips.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the advantage if none of the horses are hit?'' he asks.
``(Track announcer) Trevor Denman, who's seen thousands and
thousands of races, says that 95 percent of the accidents are
caused by whipping. The horses drift into each other because
jockeys whip tiring horses. Scandinavia is out of the whipping
business. Germany is beginning to take steps. As is England. The US
is foot-dragging.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Roberts, there are now dozens of books on nonviolent
training methods. Most training used to be based on forcing horses
to submit, primarily through fear, to man's will. Trainers broke
horses with all the force and violence that the verb implies.
</P>
<P>
   It's a reality that hits close to home. Roberts's father, Marvin
Earl Roberts, was a traditional trainer who, by tying ropes around
a horse's fetlocks and running them up to the halter, could force a
horse to submit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father abused horses and he abused me,'' Roberts says. ``I
had a brutal father.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts pauses. ``Brutal. But he taught me one important lesson
_ violence is never the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A humane touch
</P>
<P>
   Roberts came up with his ideas about training horses from
observing mustangs in California's high desert country. Like Jane
Goodall, who studied apes in the wild, Roberts saw the manner in
which wild horses were treated in the herd. Those who didn't
cooperate were ostracized. Over years and years of being around
horses, Roberts developed his equine sign language.
</P>
<P>
   For decades no one really listened. That's where Queen Elizabeth
II comes in.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1988, Roberts received word that Her Majesty would like
to see, first hand, his training methods. The following January,
several members of the Royal Staff visited the Flag Is Up Farms to
observe Roberts's ``Join-Up'' techniques. He passed the test. In
April 1989, he demonstrated the technique for the royal family and
gave 14 lectures/demonstrations at various English cities. Then he
was offered the job of training horses for the queen. The results
were so astonishing, she encouraged him to write the book that
became ``The Man Who Listens to Horses.''
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``Shy Boy,'' with photographs by Christopher
Dydyk, Roberts details how the mustang featured in his PBS special,
``Monty Roberts: The Real Horse Whisperer,'' deals with the tough
decision of whether to return to the wild or stay with Roberts at
his farm.
</P>
<P>
   The mustang's plight mirrors the decision many a troubled
adolescent has confronted.
</P>
<P>
   During the past 40-plus years, Roberts and his wife, Pat _ who
have three biological children _ have touched the lives of 47
foster children who came under their care. Like the horses, most of
the children benefited from a system of hard work, dedication,
truth telling, and respect for self and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty of them are real success stories,'' says Roberts. But
it's the ones that got away that eat away at Roberts at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one young girl in particular,'' he tells a woman who
was getting her copy of ``Shy Boy'' signed after Roberts's
discussion at Harvard. ``Her parents were both cocaine-dependent
and alcoholic. They were the abused who became the abusers.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts pauses. His blue eyes cloud up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We signed a deal that said we'd send her home after a year for
a visit,'' he recalls. ``A week or two before she was to return she
started showing signs of aggravation. I could tell she didn't want
to go, but a deal was a deal. In retrospect, it was a terrible
mistake _ after she'd been home for just two days she stuck a knife
in her mother's stomach and killed her. Now she's in prison. That
remains a heavy burden for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   A little later, Roberts says that his next book, due next year,
will be about ``human-to-human communication.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence never solved anything and it only teaches us to be
more violent,'' he says. ``The other day, after that terrible
tragedy in Littleton, Colorado, where the schoolchildren ended up
dead, the president came on a press conference and asked how such a
thing could happen. Where did the children learn about such
violence? Later that same day he went on the television to talk
about bombing Kosovo. Where does he think they learned it?''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts allows the question to linger in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we start looking for alternatives to violence,'' he
says, while signing another copy of his book, ``we're doomed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1432EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
