<HEADER>
A3136 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-INSTINCT-BOS &LR;      06-04 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-INSTINCT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANNIBAL LECTER , WITH A TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INSTINCT &QL; 
Directed by: Jon Turteltaub &QL; 
Screenplay by: Gerald DiPego, based on Daniel Quinn's novel,
``Ishmael'' &QL; 
Starring: Anthony Hopkins, Cuba Gooding, Jr., Donald Sutherland,
Maura Tierney, George Dzundza, John Ashton, John Aylward, Thomas Q.
Morris, Doug Spinuza, Paul Bates &QL; 
Rated: R (some intense violent behavior) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Hopkins is at that point of his career where he's never
boring. He always gives you something. No matter how limited the
material, he'll give you reason to go on watching. Signing him was
the best thing the producers of ``Instinct'' could have done
because it's a pretty predictable outing, to the point of being
cliched.
</P>
<P>
   It trades shamelessly in Hopkins's Hannibal Lecter vibe, as he
plays Ethan Powell, a primatologist imprisoned in Florida for a
grisly murder in a Rwandan jungle, where his immersion in the study
of gorillas was bloodily interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   He won't talk about the crime _ or anything else. He just sits
in prison, looking murderous, although heavily medicated. Enter
Cuba Gooding Jr. as Theo Caulder, a young shrink on the career fast
track, figuring that getting the accused to open up will move him a
few rungs up the ladder and land him a hefty book deal besides.
It's mostly a nice piece of work from Gooding, who may be following
Robin Williams in trying to veer away from motormouth comedy by
playing a sensitive healer. Yes, Gooding's psychiatrist does find
his sensitivities getting the better of his ambition.
</P>
<P>
   He also finds Hopkins's primatologist getting the better of him.
Powell displays withering contempt for the mind games he wards off
with insolent ease, and even more contempt for the shrink's values.
Although Caulder does get him talking rather easily, Powell hasn't
much use for so-called civilization. He'd rather be back with the
gorillas. Apart from sentimentalizing nature, the film is rather
too simplistic and schematic, as Powell elevates the sights of the
shrink just as the gorillas have made Powell a better human being.
</P>
<P>
   If Hopkins's Powell recalls Hannibal Lecter as he glowers
murderously at bad-news guards and fellow inmates, he's at least a
high-minded Hannibal Lecter, erupting for the best of reasons. And
the truth is that it's fun to watch Hopkins override the cliches in
the script and compel our attention. The others turn in good work,
too, but face a more uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   Gooding proves that he can be just as convincing in a
show-me-the-values role as a show-me-the-money role. John Ashton's
thuggish guard, George Dzundza's malleable prison doc, and Paul
Bates's hulking bully tamed by Powell have their moments, too.
</P>
<P>
   So, amazingly, does Maura Tierney as Powell's daughter,
shortchanged emotionally by her father's lifelong careerism. But
her role is scanted most in a film that backs away from the
interpersonal complexity that could have generated more of the
dramatic conflict it needs. Instead, we're left with a simplistic
ennobling process passed from primate to prof to callow young
shrink. Hopkins even makes disgust and menace fun to watch but,
while good, he isn't superhuman. Thus, he can't disguise the
thinness of this film, which never seems to take on a life of its
own because it's too busy reminding us of other, better originals _
``Gorillas in the Mist,'' ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest,'' or
maybe an environmentalist ``Shawshank Redemption.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1433EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
