<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3137 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SEXCITY-BOS &LR;      06-04 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEXCITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOCKING THE MATING GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEX AND THE CITY &QL; 
Starring: Sarah Jessica Parker, Kim Cattrall, Kristin Davis,
Cynthia Nixon, Christopher Noth &QL; 
On: HBO &QL; 
Time: Sunday at 9 p.m. &QL; 
Rated: TVMA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most viewers never watched it, but HBO's ``Sex and the City''
was one of last summer's small delights. A very cynical comedy
series, it openly mocked the mating games of successful single
women and slippery bachelors in New York City. It laid bare the
pretensions of the chic nightclub scene, turning a neon-lit
flirtation into a grueling chess game in which the women usually
end up as pawns. And it managed to reach through its own layers of
irony to touch on the despair, frustration, and self-sabotage that
lie behind all the ogling and angling.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night at 9, ``Sex and the City'' returns for its second
season with as much savvy and withering wit as ever. It's a
pint-size show, really, one whose half-hour seems to pass in a New
York minute. But it's worth a gander if you enjoy hip urban
reference, shrewd satire about relationships, and the kind of frank
genital humor that fueled so many famous gags on ``Seinfeld''
(remember ``shrinkage''?). Sarah Jessica Parker plays Carrie
Bradshaw, a journalist and self-labeled ``sexual anthropologist''
who uses her adventures, and those of her three best friends, to
write a column about Manhattan's night life. The comic action turns
on the stories the women trade at their gab sessions, as they
dabble in girlfriend truisms (you always see an ex when you look
most awful) and explicit sexual matters (lovers who talk dirty
during lovemaking).
</P>
<P>
   The ``Sex and the City'' scripts are always drum tight, partly
because, as with most HBO series, only a few new episodes air each
season. (The writers delivered 12 half-hours last year, and promise
18 this year.) Also, the writing benefits by avoiding the standard
sitcom setup-punch line rhythm, as it glides meditation-like
through the observations Carrie makes in her newspaper column. Each
episode establishes a loose theme _ Sunday's premiere is about
breakups _ and then portrays each of the women dealing with that
theme. The season premiere, which relies on a tacky ball-and-bat
metaphor, has Carrie rebounding from a love affair by pursuing
``The New Yankee,'' while the hopeful Charlotte is dating a man
compelled to adjust his crotch in public. At the same time,
predatory Samantha is distraught about her boyfriend's
measurements. ``Me, James, and his tiny penis are one big happy
family,'' she groans. (Next week, he drags her to couples therapy,
and she suddenly longs ``for the simple days of emotional
unavailability and hot one-night stands.'')
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Seinfeld,'' the show never pretends to have any serious
moral value. It fairly revels in the superficiality of its
characters, and the ways that New York can serve as a massive
distraction from honest self-scrutiny and spirituality. Elaine
Benes would fit in perfectly with the ``Sex and the City'' crowd.
This is bound to turn off some viewers, as is the show's somewhat
retro view of women. Like Ally McBeal, who has undergone her share
of public criticism, Carrie and her friends are professionally
empowered, but obsessed with finding the right man to make them
happy. Next week, sensible Miranda stalks out of a typical
breakfast conversation about men: ``It's like seventh grade with
bank accounts,'' she yells. ``Does it always have to be about
them?'' But later, devastated after seeing her ex-boyfriend with
another woman, she reverses her opinion and affirms the show's
guy-talk premise. David E. Kelley could have written it.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Sex and the City'' is based on Candace Bushnell's
columns in the weekly New York Observer, it is brought to cable by
Darren Star, the creator of ``Melrose Place.'' But don't expect cat
fights and back stabbing among these attractive women. One of the
few sincere undercurrents of the show is the power and solace the
four find in one other's friendship. The actors form a comfortable
ensemble, with Kim Cattrall stealing scenes as man-eating Samantha
and Kristin Davis offering nice moments as her Charlotte clings to
innocence. And Cynthia Nixon is effective at showing Miranda's
struggle between intellect and emotions. As Carrie, Parker
successfully holds the show together with the right mix of fashion
sense, romantic longing, and wry self-consciousness. It's sweet to
watch her, distraught about her breakup, pulling a piece of gum out
of her mouth to submit to the consolations of Miranda's wee-hour
diner fries. Someday, she still hopes, it will be breakfast at
Tiffany's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1434EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
