<HEADER>
A3139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-LIMBO-BOS &LR;      06-04 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LIMBO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENSE OF CONNECTION FORTIFIES NEW SAYLES OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMBO &QL; 
Written and directed by: John Sayles &QL; 
Starring: Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio, David Straithairn, Vanessa
Martinez, Kris Kristofferson, Casey Siemaszko, Kathryn Grody, Rita
Taggart, Leo Burmester, Michael Laskin &QL; 
Rated: R (language) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Sayles's ``Limbo'' is two films.
</P>
<P>
   The first is beautifully textured, giving its actors material of
a richness and originality that are as rare as they are humane.
It's set in contemporary Alaska and focuses on a couple _ or at
least we hope they'll become a couple _ that have been around the
block a few times.
</P>
<P>
   David Strathairn's Joe has handled with grace a couple of
misfortunes _ injured knee that finished a basketball career, fatal
accident that ended his fisherman's career (just as well because
fishing is being downsized). Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio's Donna is
keeping her singing career alive, although just barely, and worries
about her relationship with her teenage daughter, Vanessa
Martinez's Noelle, who completes the satisfyingly realized trio.
</P>
<P>
   America's last frontier, in other words, is a place of narrowing
options, where the self-reinvention had better happen fast if the
inhabitants are going to survive. Joe is pushed back into risk
taking, first by a couple of local women who are trying to restart
a small fishing business, then by his rolling-stone brother, who
shows up after having been away for years and talks Joe into taking
a trip he doesn't realize will be fraught with danger. But the most
interesting throw of the dice is the one involving Donna and Joe.
</P>
<P>
   As they edge together, you find yourself caring what will happen
to them _ so much so that you don't mind Sayles switching his
attention from the economically squeezed Juneau community to the
couple.
</P>
<P>
   Watching and listening to Mastrantonio make you realize how good
she is and make you wonder why she isn't seen more. Your heart
gravitates with ease and speed to her nervous but emotionally
courageous woman. Donna is something of a rolling stone herself,
working cruise ships, clubs, wherever the work is. You believe not
only in her connection to singing (as a bonus, Mastrantonio turns
out to be a very good singer), but in her prickly connection to her
daughter. You don't want anything bad to happen to Donna when she
rebuffs the advances of Kris Kristofferson's bush pilot, who has a
tangled history with Joe.
</P>
<P>
   But then, one adventure later, Joe, Donna, and Noelle find
themselves on a wilderness island, and the film goes aground.
Suddenly, this rich, affecting trio finds itself marking time,
turning away from pursuits we feel are living, breathing
interactions and veering into something airless and abstract, right
up to an ending that may be justified, but is exasperatingly
unsatisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Until it goes off course, ``Limbo'' not only is up to Sayles's
high standard, but extends it. Its first part is so filled with
several kinds of rightness, including the believable tentativeness
that necessarily must be a part of any impending relationship
between people who bear emotional scars, that I wish it were
possible for Sayles to go back and rework the second part.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
