A3140 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARTH-MARKETING-TEX     06-04 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARTH-MARKETING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTRY SUPERSTAR TAKES OFF HIS COWBOY HAT FOR YET ANOTHER
MARKETING MAKEOVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM and DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when it looked as if Garth Brooks would lay down his bat
for the San Diego Padres and pick up his Stetson again, he has
another new gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the superstar credited with bringing ``event
marketing'' to country music is trying ``a concept album.''
</P>
<P>
   And if history is any indication, he'll score big again.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign of what's to come is the mysterious album cover
making its way around the Internet. It's Garth all right, but he's
hidden behind the makeup, hairpieces, bangs, lighting and touch-up
wizardry of Hollywood stylists.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as an actor getting into character, says Scott Stem
at Capital Records in Nashville. Then think of Garth ``acting'' on
a CD. That's what a concept album is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Garth, the singer, has been talking about Garth, the actor,
since 1997 at least. He has said he wants to do a movie. This album
is the soundtrack to a upcoming movie called ``The Lamb.'' It's
about a rock star named Chris Gaines, and although the script isn't
finished and producers haven't decided whether Garth will play
Gaines, Garth will at least ``sing'' for Gaines.
</P>
<P>
   Garth? Singing rock?
</P>
<P>
   That's part of the new gig, too.
</P>
<P>
   His love of rock 'n' roll has been well-documented. He speaks
often of his love of Kiss and Styx, among others, and how the
former's massive stage productions inspired his own stage shows.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Brooks recorded his own version of Kiss' ``Hard Luck
Woman'' on a Kiss tribute CD several years ago. A major fan of
Billy Joel, he also recorded the piano man's ``Shameless.''
</P>
<P>
   But the upcoming album, ``In the Life of Chris Gaines,'' is a
complete departure for Brooks. The concept here is that the 14
songs are Gaines' ``greatest hits,'' and are drawn from Gaines'
catalog of CDs, none of which actually exists, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The CD comes out in September. The first single, ``Lost in
You,'' will be sent to radio stations in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to make you a fan of Chris Gaines before you go
see the movie,'' says David Waldman, an assistant to Brooks'
publicist.
</P>
<P>
   Waldman says some of the songs have ``an '80s John
Mellencamp/Bruce Springsteen'' feel. At least one is reminiscent of
Eric Clapton's smash hit ``If I Could Change the World.'' Brooks
will not be touring to support the ``Gaines'' CD, Waldman says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting as a way not to alienate his country fans and
make a pop album,'' says Jamie Mattison, the country editor of
``Gavin.'' ``This is arguably the biggest pop entertainer of our
generation, and now he wants to do a pop album. But he's doing it
so that it's not ``Garth Brooks'' doing a pop album. It's really
strange, but if it works it'll be amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   But will it work?
</P>
<P>
   History says yes.
</P>
<P>
   Garth ranked 15th in last year's Forbes list of the 100 richest
people, and part of his $54 million comes from an uncanny ability
to market himself and his music.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the free concert in Central Park? The live HBO special?
There was a record-breaking ``Double Live CD,'' the CD taped in a
Los Angeles studio and broadcast live to every electronics
department in more than 2,000 Wal-Marts. There was the NBC special,
the Rockefeller Center gig, and yes, the spring spent playing as
No. 77 for the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   The big question, of course, is whether Brooks' enormous country
audience, which bought more than 1 million copies of his ``Double
Live'' CD in its first week of release, will want to hear Garth
play pop-rock. And will mainstream pop-rock fans accept the songs
on the Gaines CD?
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris Gaines'' is being marketed directly to Top 40 and adult
contemporary radio, not country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a calculated risk,'' says Kevin Carter, the Top 40 editor
of ``Gavin.'' ``He's going after a whole new audience. It's a way
to stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter heard Brooks perform a number of the ``Chris Gaines''
songs recently at a Paramount sound stage, and walked away
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of it had a familiar sound. You think you've heard it
before,'' he says. ``There was pop-rock stuff and some R&AMP;B-tinged
numbers. He prefaced the music by saying, `You have to imagine me
as the character. Go along for the ride with me on this.' He looked
like Garth, but he didn't have a cowboy hat on. I think he can
cross over. The songs are strong and fun, and if people are willing
to go along for the ride, this could be very successful.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
