<HEADER>
A3141 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SIXWAYS-BOS &LR;      06-04 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SIXWAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOING JUSTICE TO A ROLLICKING STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIX WAYS TO SUNDAY &QL; 
Directed by: Adam Bernstein &QL; 
Screenplay by: Bernstein, Marc Gerald (novel: Charles Perry) &QC; 
Starring: Norman Reedus, Deborah Harry, Adrien Brody, Elina
Lowensohn, Jerry Adler, Isaac Hayes &QL; 
Rated: R (graphic bloody violence, strong language, sexuality and
brief drug use) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charles Perry's novel, ``Six Ways to Sunday,'' makes him seem a
soul brother to Jim Thompson, the godfather of pulp noir. In his
film of ``Six Ways to Sunday,'' Adam Bernstein drolly preserves
Perry's rollickingly outrageous sense of mischief, reveling in its
perversity as opposed to judging it.
</P>
<P>
   The film is centered _ if that's the word _ on the off-kilter
mother-son tandem of Deborah Harry and Norman Reedus, and loses no
time zeroing in on its mix of grotesque comedy and twisted eclat.
When it errs, it errs on the side of the lurid as it traces the
odyssey of a young hamburger flipper turned mob enforcer for the
Jewish mafia of Youngstown, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   If Reedus's Harry Odum had a mother who owned a motel, he'd be
the next Norman Bates. As it happens, they live a low-rent life,
but Odum has a pal who asks him along on a collection errand to a
deadbeat strip-joint proprietor. It brings out the tough guy in the
hitherto mild-mannered Odum. He finds himself with an instant mob
job after having successfully terrorized the callous owner. It soon
becomes obvious that there was an Oedipal component in his violent
behavior. And as soon as we've seen a little of his stiflingly
possessive mother, Kate, played with droll, blowzy obliviousness by
Deborah Harry, it removes any mystery about why her grown but
retrograde son should experience the difficulty with women that he
does.
</P>
<P>
   Then Odum falls for Elina Lowensohn's maid in the mansion of
Jerry Adler's mob boss, and she reciprocates his feelings. The
scene when he takes her home to his anything but welcoming mom is
one of the film's peaks, especially as he tries not to notice how
chilly and poisonous the atmosphere gets. The gorier but no more
vicious mob stuff is OK, too, especially when the lethal
instability of its personnel, including Odum's underboss mentor,
becomes ever more inescapably clear in its bullet-riddled way. And,
just to round out the feast, there's a vaguely creepy atmosphere
pervading the overlord's overdecorated lair.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the world of the film seem akin to Thompson's is its
tongue-in-cheek acceptance of everyone's warped behavior and
refusal to be shocked by any of it. The film does hit a few
glitches, the most serious being Odum's violent alter ego, which
never is smoothly or persuasively incorporated into the film's
clever tabloid attitude. The Youngstown setting (moved from
Brooklyn in the '30s) is a help. Postindustrial Youngstown suggests
a huge piece of gritty found art and bolsters the film's pervasive
feeling of dislocation. Isaac Hayes is another plus, as a tough,
corrupt cop. So is the period jazz scoring. ``Six Ways to Sunday''
is a juicy updating of yet another festering piece of the American
dream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1437EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3142 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIRECTOR-SAYLES-BOS-A     06-04 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRECTOR-SAYLES-BOS-ART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISK IS STARTING POINT   FOR SAYLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETSY SHERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Sayles was able to duck out of his downtown Boston hotel
for a stroll around the neighborhood. ``There are a lot of
Vietnamese restaurants; there used to be only Chinese'' is one
quick impression of Boston, 20-plus years after he used to live
here.
</P>
<P>
   Sayles and his producer and longtime companion Maggie Renzi
lived in East Boston in the mid-1970s, before they embarked on a
movie career with ``The Return of the Secaucus Seven.''
</P>
<P>
   Sayles, 48 _ in town to promote his new movie, ``Limbo'' _
invokes defunct Boston institutions such as The Real Paper and the
Orson Welles Cinema (where ``Secaucus Seven'' had a long run) as he
speaks of his days working at an East Cambridge sausage factory. It
was after he'd been laid off and was collecting $48 a week on
unemployment that the Schenectady, N.Y., native and Williams
College graduate wrote his first novel, ``Pride of the Bimbos.''
</P>
<P>
   Sayles shot ``Secaucus Seven'' in 1978 in New Hampshire, with a
cast of actor friends. He launched the project with the $40,000 he
had earned as a Hollywood scriptwriter for hire, notably for Roger
Corman's New World Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The paycheck wasn't the only pleasure, says Sayles. ``The best
thing was that you actually got to make the movies. Big studios
make one out of 20 screenplays that they develop. But if Roger
developed a screenplay, it was going to be a movie very quickly. I
got to work with the directors, and see what my stuff looked like
up on a screen.''
</P>
<P>
   The self-taught filmmaker soon won a devoted following for his
independent films, which combine character studies with an edge of
social commentary. These range from the satiric ``Brother From
Another Planet'' to the miners'-union story ``Matewan,'' from the
Irish fantasy ``The Secret of Roan Inish'' to the baseball-scandal
picture ``Eight Men Out.'' In true maverick style, Sayles followed
his attention-getting 1996 ``Lone Star'' with the Spanish-language
drama ``Men With Guns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo'' began with the marrying of a place and a group of
characters. Sayles and Renzi accepted an invitation 11 years ago to
hold film seminars in Alaska. The territory and the people stuck in
Sayles's mind. Two things in particular struck him, that one could
walk 15 minutes outside of the capital city, Juneau, and be in the
wilderness, and the way ``a lot of people had gone there to
reinvent themselves. You meet college professors who became bush
pilots. You didn't need a pedigree to get ahead there. There was a
frontier quality to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another jumping-off point was a true story about some fishermen
who had caught so many fish that, while they were sleeping, their
boat sank and some of them drowned. ``I started to think about who
that survivor would be. That got me thinking about risk, and how
people react differently to having risked something and failed.''
The male protagonist of ``Limbo,'' Alaska native Joe Gastineau,
``basically hasn't taken another risk for 25 years. He hasn't gone
back to sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe, played by David Strathairn, begins a relationship with
itinerant singer Donna, played by Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio.
Unlike Joe, Donna has risked her emotions repeatedly, in spite of
frequent heartbreak. Sayles added a third protagonist, Donna's
lonely teenage daughter Noelle. ``There are kids I know or have
read about who have, not really diseases, but symptoms. Anorexia,
bulimia, cutting themselves. They've seen what the world has to
offer, and they don't want to get into it.''
</P>
<P>
   The first movement of ``Limbo'' paints a vivid picture of a town
in transition from an economy based on fish factories and the
timber trade to one dependent on the tourist industry. The shpiel
of the tour guides becomes a sort of Muzak, counterpointed by the
true-to-experience stories told by the natives in the local bar.
</P>
<P>
   Joe, Donna, and Noelle ``can exist in this society,'' says
Sayles, ``but they're really isolated within it.'' Then, because of
a con perpetrated by Joe's half brother, Joe and the women end up
stranded on an uninhabited island, with the threat that a group of
drug dealers may come back to kill them.
</P>
<P>
   In the harrowing second half of the film, Sayles wanted to
explore the concept that ``people are romantic about nature, but
nature is not romantic about people. Only if you find yourself in
nature by accident, unprepared, do you realize just how hard it is
to survive. Most people don't want to rough it that much. They
might want to go down the river, but they want the river guides
there when it's time to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo'' was an opportunity for Sayles to craft a lead role for
Strathairn, who has been in six of his films. The mysterious Joe
``doesn't have much dialogue. Getting information out of him,
especially about himself, is a lot of work. So we hear stories
about him from other people.'' Strathairn, who attended Ringling
Brothers Clown College after going to Williams, ``is a very good
physical actor. He's also a competent person _ he can do carpentry,
he can run a boat, he can throw a curveball.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Sayles, the film's title provides a key to
understanding its stylized ending. ``I was raised Catholic. When I
thought about risk, I thought about the concept of limbo. It's
supposed to be the place where unbaptized souls go. It's not
heaven, and it's not hell, and it's not purgatory. Purgatory is
temporary, but limbo is forever and ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about how many people exist in that
neither-here-nor-there state, because they have to stay in a
certain job they hate, or a relationship, or a political situation.
The way out of limbo is basically a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   (Note: If you prefer no clue to the film's ending, read no
further.) As a final image, Sayles employs a fade to white, which
has a different visceral effect than the more familiar fade to
black. ``For me, a fade to white is like going to the infinite. It
says, nothing ends or begins here, we are bringing you to a certain
moment and you don't know what happens next. We do this with the
sound as well, where we raise it and raise it until it's almost
unbearable, and then cut it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do with this ending is send you back into the
movie. `If it wasn't about them living or dying, what did I get
from this? What did happen on that island? Well, the last thing I
saw was these three people together, after all those shots of them
alone, disconnected.' This isn't an action-adventure movie that's
all about plot. There is an emotional resolution, which is that the
three are touching each other for the first time. They're going to
be a family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3144 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      06-04 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAPIN-CARPENTER ENLIVENS GREATEST HITS PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time, a greatest-hits collection meant just that _ a
collection of hits that had originally been done in the studio.
Today, many artists expand the concept to include hits and a
coupleof new songs to entice collectors and fans.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mary Chapin Carpenter has taken the concept even further.
She not only adds two new songs to the just-released ``Party Doll
and Other Favorites'' but attaches some live versions of hits and
some oddities pulled from her appearances on TV specials and film
soundtracks. The result is an enchanting potpourri.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want this to be interpreted as a definitive
collection, but as more of an informal one,'' says Carpenter, who
comes to Boston July 23. ``When I see a lot of greatest-hits
records today, it seems they come from artists who have maybe two
hits. But I wanted this collection to be different.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, a crafty singer-songwriter who straddles the world of
country, folk, and rock, has recorded for 10 years and enjoyed a
slew of hits. But the fun part of the new disc is how some of these
were done: the spicy ``Down at the Twist &AMP; Shout,'' for instance,
was taken from a live performance with Beausoleil at the Super Bowl
in New Orleans two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The original studio takes of ``Shut Up and Kiss Me,''
``Passionate Kisses'' (written by Lucinda Williams), and ``He
Thinks He'll Keep Her'' were included. But other additions are a
cover of Mick Jagger's ``Party Doll'' (from his solo album,
``Primitive Cool''), a cover of John Lennon's ``Grow Old With Me''
(from the tribute album to Lennon, ``Working Class Hero''), and
``Can't Take Love for Granted,'' from an appearance on ``Late Show
With David Letterman'' in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The album is fleshed out with live tracks from theaters in
England, Wisconsin, and the Ryman Auditorium in Nashville; and two
new tunes in ``Almost Home'' (co-written with Beth Nielsen Chapman)
and ``Where You Are,'' with some of Carpenter's most tender lyrics:
``I'm looking for a strong and steady heart / I'm looking for some
eyes that have shed some tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter not only shook up the notion of a greatest-hits CD,
but has shaken up her band. Instead of using dual guitarists Jon
Jennings and Duke Levine (a Bostonian) as she's done in the past,
she has installed Levine at lead guitar and moved Jennings over to
bass. ``There are times when I miss the stereo guitars, but it's
important to change things around sometimes. It shakes up the
repertoire, too.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Carpenter is still at heart a wordsmith with a guitar.
``Every time I wake up and can still call myself a songwriter, I'm
ahead of the game,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Axl Rose surfaces: Guns N' Roses singer/fusebox Axl Rose is on
the cover of the Spin magazine that comes out Tuesday. He confirms
that guitarist Slash is no longer in the group and that the new
lineup contains guitarists Paul Huge (a childhood friend of Rose's)
and Robin Finck (who played with Cirque du Soleil). Other members
are keyboardist Dizzy Reed, bassist Tommy Stinson (formerly of the
Replacements), and punk drummer Josh Freese (formerly with Suicidal
Tendencies and the Vandals). A new, supposedly more
industrial-sounding album is being produced with Sean Beaven, who
has worked with Nine Inch Nails and Pantera. Here's a peculiar
note, though: hoop star/rapper Shaquille (I Got Swept Again) O'Neal
is on a track, following a chance meeting with the band in a
recording studio. ``I saw Guns N' Roses listed on the bulletin
board in the lobby of the studio, so I stuck my head in to check it
out,'' says O'Neal. ``They asked me to join them, so I started
freestylin' over their track. It was the first time I ever performd
with a rock group, and it felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Millennium madness strikes again: Celebration 2000's ``Party of
the Century'' is at New York's Jacob Javits Convention Center Dec.
31 with Aretha Franklin, Andrea Bocelli, Sting, Enrique Iglesias,
Chuck Berry, and Joan Rivers. Can you believe tickets are $1,000
and $1,500? More info: 1-877-556-2000 .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
