<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3155 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-RENT-BOS &LR;      06-04 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-RENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW LEASE FOR `RENT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that ``Rent'' is a certified theatrical institution, what's
new to say about it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still news, only now it's just theater news, back on the
theater pages,'' says Jeffrey Seller, who produced it on Broadway
in 1996. ``For a while, it went off the theater pages and became
news.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many things have surprised me about this show,'' he adds,
``that I find myself now regularly surprised.'' He was speaking on
the phone from Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The show is returning June 15 to Boston's Shubert Theatre for a
newly extended engagement through July 11. It played a
record-breaking 29 weeks here in 1996, the first city it toured
after its Broadway success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rent,'' of course, is the massively hyped hit Pulitzer Prize-
and Tony Award-winning rock musical, the fifth musical to win both
a Pulitzer and Tony, the most honored musical since 1976's ``A
Chorus Line.'' Billed as ``the rock opera of the '90s'' and an
``East Village `La Boheme,' '' it chronicles the struggles of urban
artists of all persuasions. It was written by Jonathan Larson.
</P>
<P>
   Seller says the show's selling points still are pertinent.
``There's been no show like this in my adult life,'' he says. ``It
speaks to young people and how they look at the world. And how they
look at themselves, their hopes, their dreams, their aspirations.
How to hook up with each other. Sex. And then the collection of
songs we have in the show seals the deal. And then there was the
death of the author.''
</P>
<P>
   Larson died unexpectedly of an aortic aneurysm hours after the
production's final dress rehearsal off-Broadway, 10 days before his
36th birthday. He was hoping to see ``Rent'' confirm his belief in
it as a ``Hair'' of the '90s. Living in a grungy East Village
apartment, Larson was hanging on during the musical's seven-year
odyssey from its conception. Seller says that the show has
successfully toured, both nationally and abroad, playing 40 cities
in the United States in its second national tour.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he says, it can be said the Boston audience foretold
success in such venues as Des Moines and Kalamazoo Mich.: ``Des
Moines sold every single seat. Kalamazoo, $740,000 worth of tickets
in one week.''
</P>
<P>
   The producer recounts the tales of the original plans to present
``Rent'' off-Broadway and of its eventual Broadway appearance
``with people telling us it doesn't want to go uptown and it'll
fail with the downtown audience. Twenty-four hours later, we sold
out in 16 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it won't sell on tour. We're up to $15 million.
Boston did $29 million the last time. When was the last time a show
toured starting in Boston on the East Coast and then sold out in
Dallas and Tempe, Ariz.? It does well in conservative areas. And in
(liberal) St. Paul; it sold out for 10 weeks. Now I'm not surprised
by anything. I expect to do well in Gainesville, Fla., next year.
And I'm looking to do well in Charlotte, N.C. We sold out Raleigh.
That's Jesse Helms country. Another thing about this show is that
it's a reaction against the politics of exclusion of the right,
against meanness. It's about inclusion, acceptance, and loving your
friends and neighbors, not hating them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
