<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3161 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-04 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S CUP HAS LOST STEAM DURING LAYOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Peter Blake and the invincible Kiwis announced their plans
for the next America's Cup back in 1995 at the San Diego docks,
there were groans all around.
</P>
<P>
   The next Cup would be held in 2000, Blake said, five long years
after the Kiwi victory over the United States. So now, some 170
days until the first gun starts round one of the challengers'
series, the event picks up a thread after the longest haitus since
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   When the last America's Cup was raced, there was at least some
choppy continuity with the history of the event. But now, it seems,
for viewers and readers who came to expect to hear about the Cup
every three years or so, it becomes a bit more difficult to pick up
the story after such a layoff.
</P>
<P>
   Not so the sailing teams and fund-raisers who have been working
since May 1995, to win a best-of-five race series that begins Feb.
19, and whose winner will hold the oldest trophy in sports.
</P>
<P>
   For most East Coasters, that thread is easy to follow from the
time the Cup left Newport in 1983 and went to Fremantle, Australia,
where Dennis Conner won it back in 1987. It went to San Diego and
from that point, for the next decade-plus with legal battles, the
catamaran fiasco, a new Cup class boat sailing in a light air
venue, and finally the victory by New Zealand who then took the Cup
back down under _ the America's Cup has not been easy to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Whether a coherent storyline will take shape to reawaken
interest in the Cup, whether Americans will be staying up to watch
the races on ESPN _ as they did in 1986-87 _ is a question mark.
</P>
<P>
   In that Australian season of 86-87 the storyline rang as clear
as a John Wayne movie, with Conner in the saddle: the Aussies had
taken away our Cup after 20 years of trying, they won using a
sneaky weapon at best, and by God, we were going down there and
show those upstarts a thing or two about American pride. For
emphasis, Conner flew a football field-size American flag from the
masthead of Stars &AMP; Stripes after every victory.
</P>
<P>
   And of course the conditions _ those boisterous Australian winds
and big lumpy seas that blew out sails and dismasted many a
12-meter _ all put on a compelling show to the TV viewers in those
post-midnight rituals that so many stayed up for or taped.
</P>
<P>
   Sailboat racing as dull as paint drying? Tell that to the suits
at ESPN, for whom that '87 Cup was a watershed event. Unfortunately
for ESPN, the magic never quite struck again when the Cup went to
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   What will spark some excitement around the old America's Cup
home grounds is of course if Young America, carrying colors of the
New York Yacht Club, can show some real strength in the early
going. If they look believable in the three fall round robins, with
a bit of hype going into the millennium hoopla down under (where
New Year's rings in first), the guess here is that Cup fans will be
back.
</P>
<P>
   Once the dream becomes palpable (and rational) that the
America's Cup would be coming ``home'' to Newport, that droopy-eyed
legion of midnight race followers will be back.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a few other challening syndicates _ four from the US
_ are trying hard to ensure this scenario remains a fantasy. One,
America True from the San Francisco Yacht Club, has wrapped up four
months of sailing in New Zealand along with Young America and
America One, Paul Cayard's campaign also based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are full on for New Zealand with a new boat,'' says Dawn
Riley, captain and CEO of America True, which is sailing in the
former Tag Heuer, Chris Dickson's boat in the last Cup. ``We are
really ahead, and on track. We have NASA and STRC software, and
also all of Bill Koch's '95 data.''
</P>
<P>
   America True, says Riley, has one boat under construction by Jim
Betts in Truckee, Calif., while Young America and America One claim
to have two-boat programs.
</P>
<P>
   But in some early pre-Cup intelligence gathering, Riley says she
has reason to believe none of the other American challengers will
be able to pull off two-boat programs.
</P>
<P>
   The difference could be night and day. Many Cup observers
believe it is virtually impossible for a one-boat program to beat
two boats. The reason: a one-boat team simply can't develop the
design data quickly enough to move forward at the speed of a
two-boat campaign, which can leapfrog its boats' performance
development.
</P>
<P>
   But Riley isn't so sure. ``The two-boat approach is minimized
these days by the strength of our computer programs,'' she says,
adding her serious doubts about the other US campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   To date, only three International America's Cup Class numbers
have been assigned to US syndicates, one each to America One (USA
49), Aloha Racing (USA 50), and America True (USA 51). Under Cup
rules, sail numbers are not allocated until boat building has
commenced, though two other US boats are under construction.
</P>
<P>
   Much speculation swirls around the question of how badly Young
America was set back in its fund-raising when it had to break a
sponsorship deal with Fox Sports Net because of a conflict with
ESPN, the Cup's official broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox deal included logos on sails and boats, and ESPN
objected to televising its rival's logos, so Young America was
released from that part of the deal, said to have been worth $2.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Jane Eagleson said in a phone interview from the
Portland, Maine, offices of Young America that the broken deal with
FOX would not slow the syndicate's two-boat program. Its boats are
being built at Goetz Custom Yachts in Bristol, R.I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
