</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNREPENTANT FAGAN THUMBS HIS NOSE AT US ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts let a liar, charlatan, and cheat get away
_ again.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Stephen Fagan, the daddy dearest who kidnapped
his two daughters 20 years ago, could have sent a powerful message
to parents who take the law into their own hands. Instead, the case
for morality, decency, and compassion disintegrated into a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Have you heard the one about the Palm Beach con man? He fooled
the women he married, the two girls he fathered _ and the
prosecutor who pursued him.
</P>
<P>
   That is a harsh, even cruel, assessment of the Commonwealth
versus Stephen Fagan. But a week after Fagan's PR circus blitzed
Boston and then blew out of town, this much seems very clear:
</P>
<P>
   Middlesex District Attorney Martha Coakley got a guilty plea
from Fagan. But Fagan got more. He has his freedom; he will spend
not a second in jail. And he won another opportunity to viciously
denounce Barbara Kurth, his ex-wife and mother of the girls he
stole from her so long ago.
</P>
<P>
   The defense was poised to trash Kurth during a trial. They
trashed her without one. As Fagan's lawyer, Richard Egbert, bragged
after his client's guilty plea: ``I would have shown in open court
that she was an alcoholic, neglecting the children to the point
that they were in jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one could have predicted this assault coming Kurth's
way after Fagan's guilty plea, not even an experienced prosecutor
like Coakley. But the reality is, if Coakley wanted to protect
Kurth by avoiding a trial _ she failed.
</P>
<P>
   Coakley was part of the team that skillfully navigated the
twists in the case against British nanny Louise Woodward for the
death of 8-month-old Matthew Eappen. Media spin control was very
much part of the Woodward case. Yet, with Fagan, Coakley admits:
``We were surprised there was a personal, vitriolic attack on
Barbara Kurth. We thought, maybe somewhat naively, that Mr. Egbert
would want his client to go quietly back to his private life. We
were wrong about that.''
</P>
<P>
   It leads to several questions:
</P>
<P>
   How could prosecutors so misjudge a man who has a long history
of doing and saying anything, no matter how despicable, to get what
he wants? Did the Woodward case affect Coakley's judgment here?
After all, she watched the defense and the press vilify Matthew
Eappen's mother. She watched a judge turn a second-degree murder
charge into a manslaughter verdict. And then she watched Woodward
return to England, a folk heroine.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, in trying to protect Kurth from similar harm, did
prosecutors wrongly avoid a trial?
</P>
<P>
   Coakley makes a strong case for her decision to accept Fagan's
guilty plea. A trial, she says, would have exposed Kurth to more
trashing. A jury could have decided Fagan did what was necessary,
given the circumstances. Or, a judge could have altered a guilty
verdict, as in the Woodward case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trial would have been war, and there would have been
casualties of war,'' says Coakley. After prosecutors laid out a
probable trial scenario, Kurth did sign on to the plea agreement,
according to a Jan. 6 letter from her lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's argument is convincing _ in the prosecutor's
office. Back in the journalist's office, it is less so. The eyes
wander from the computer screen to the sort of family photos that
decorate desks everywhere. It is summer, and sunbrushed kids grin
happily, their toes in the sand and their arms around mom. Imagine
if someone suddenly snatched them away. Imagine if the someone was
a man you once loved. Imagine if he told them you were dead. Then,
when they learned you were alive, he told them you were too weak,
flawed, evil to be their mother. And believing him, the children
shoved you aside with contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Could anything that happened during a trial be worse than that?
As Kurth put it last week after her ex-husband's court appearance:
``Some days I believe Stephen Fagan would have been kinder to
really have murdered me, rather than having done so only in the
minds of my children. At least there would have been no question as
to his punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fagan case is about emotion and law. As Coakley rightly
points out, ``We can't regulate the emotional destruction of one
person by another.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true it would take much more than a criminal justice
system to turn Fagan into a decent, honorable human being. But the
law is another matter. He should be punished, and he was not. He
leaves us unscathed, unrepentant, and thumbing his nose at the
mother of his children and the Commonwealth of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   (Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1448EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
