<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3169 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-04 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIEST GETS NO RESPECT FROM POLICE OFFICER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The most insidious aspect of what happened to the Rev.
Filipe Teixeira was not the most obvious, not his bizarre arrest in
handcuffs by Boston police, not even the inexplicable night he
spent in jail after he said he identified himself as a priest. It
was what he claims officer Paul Painten said through the driver's
side window upon hearing Teixeira's Angolan-Cape Verdean
accent.``You speak English?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Speak English?'' he seethed. ``I went to St. John's
University, majored in philosophy and theology. I speak Portuguese,
Cape Verdean Creole, Italian, Spanish . . . So when he asked me if
I spoke English, I knew it was trouble. He was saying, `You are
nothing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the next moments, Teixeira would be treated like nothing. On
the evening of May 25, Teixeira pulled up to a street fight in
Boston's Dorchester neighborhood. The 33-year-old ecumenical priest
began the day meeting with police over its relations with people of
Cape Verdean descent. That afternoon, he worked out at a gym and
talked with a detective. Police commander Al Goslin said Teixeira
``has been proactive in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Teixeira has been proactive with the police, even though he has
reason to be a cynic. He said he has been stopped over 10 times for
no cause by Boston and state police in cases of DWB, Driving While
Black; WWB, Walking While Black; and JBB, Just Being Black. Each
time, he was not wearing his clerical collar.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has been stopped and asked why he was driving into
South Boston. He has been accused of running a stop sign when it
was a white woman ahead of him who had zoomed through the sign. He
has been stopped by officers who seemed friendly but then asked for
an ID. Teixeira even suffered the indignity of being pulled over on
I-93 by a young white man impersonating a cop. The man fled when
Teixiera asked to see a badge. He chased the man to a restaurant
and called the police. After talking to the man, the police told
Teixeira nothing would be done. ``It turned out the guy was the son
of a former MBTA officer. So I guess that's why nothing could be
done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be done for a man who picks up 50 youths for five
hours of activities and Mass on Saturdays at St. Martin the Porres.
Nothing for the man who has helped abused women graduate from
college and gotten jobs for youths with criminal records. Teixeira
said, ``I've always prayed, `Lord if this is what I'm called to do,
I want to see the results.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The results, unfortunately, come with a healthy dose of HWB,
Helping While Black. He has been berated by cops when trying to
assist in a domestic crisis and when asking why police have put
black and Latino youth face down on the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like, we're all dogs,'' Teixeira said.
</P>
<P>
   May 25 was Teixeira's turn to be thrown into the pound. He was
trying to see if there was anyone he knew in the fight. Then
Painten bellowed the ominous, ``You speak English?'' Teixeira said
he held tightly to his rosary beads, praying, ``My Lord, I need you
right now. Tell me what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   This was of too short notice even for God. Teixeira asked for
Painten's badge number. Teixeira was hauled out of his car by the
neck and jailed for blocking traffic and for not showing his
license and registration. Teixeira said he was never asked to
identify himself or move his car. He said, ``When the officer put
the handcuffs on me, I begged, `Please don't do this. I'm a priest.
Please call your captain. He knows me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Painten made no call. He declared Teixeira guilty of PWB,
Parking While Black. The final insult was not so much spending the
night with swearing drug dealers bragging about their sexual
exploits. It was not so much even that his car was towed, costing
him $115. It was when he heard the penalty for PWB was $100 or 20
hours of community service. He assumed this had less to do with
saving souls than to spear roadside trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me says this is nothing,'' said Teixeira, who survived
civil war in Angola. ``I've crossed rivers with crocodiles, jumped
over dead bodies and fired machine guns. I don't think I killed
anyone, but to this day I have nightmares.'' The other part says
this American nightmare is too searing to the psyche to remain
silent. If the police don't drop the charges, Teixeria, without his
collar, is just another dog without tags, another creature to be
impounded by the Inhumane Society. ``My altar boy came to me and
said, `Father, how can they do this to you?' '' Teixeira said.
``What do I say to him?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
