<HEADER>
A3176 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-KING-BOS &LR;      06-04 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-KING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE STORYTELLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE KING OF MASKS &QL; 
Directed by: Wu Tianming &QL; 
Screenplay by: Wei Minglung &QL; 
Starring: Zhu Xu, Zhou Ren-Ying, Zhang Riuyang, Zhao Zhigang &QL; 
Unrated &QC;
</P>
<P>
   One of the most remarkable stories in cinema is that of Wu
Tianming. He came to prominence as head of the Xian Film Studio and
launched China's famous ``Fifth Generation'' of filmmakers, which
included Chen Kaige, Zhang Yimou, Huang Jianxin, and Tian
Zhaungzhaung. In 1986, he took his place alongside them with his
own film, ``The Old Well.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, when Tiananmen Square erupted and changed everything,
Wu was in the United States as a visiting scholar. He wound up
staying five years, during which he brought his family here and
supported them by running a video rental store in Los Angeles. In
1994, he returned to China and film directing. His 1996 film, ``The
King of Masks,'' makes it seem as if he scarcely had skipped a
beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The King of Masks'' is a small gem, set in 1930, about the
bond that develops between an aging street performer and the child
he buys so he can pass along his skills. When he discovers the
``boy'' is a girl, he's bitterly disappointed. Her nickname, in
ironic keeping with her status in traditional China, is Doggie.
But, as played by Zhou Ren-Ying, she's a resilient little thing who
hangs in there. Apart from the fact that the film is set 70 years
ago, it seems of a piece with 19th-century novels in its
matter-of-fact acceptance of a self-sufficient street kid learning
to survive poverty, starvation, and danger. ``Dickensian'' is a
word that springs to mind, and that goes for the old man of the
title role, too.
</P>
<P>
   Although he's poor, Zhu Xu's performer is a man proud of having
mastered a demanding craft. His nickname refers to his skill at the
ancient art of face changing, using speed and a conjuror's moves as
he slips a succession of silk masks over his face. Professional and
personal pride makes him want to pass along his skill to an adopted
son. Although he's disappointed in her gender, the old man is kind
and even affectionate to the young girl. To repay him and solidify
what she hopes will become a more stable emotional bond, she hits
the streets, rescues a kidnapped boy even younger than she, and
brings him back to what's left of the old man's barge after she
accidentally had set it afire. Needless to say, there are grave
consequences she cannot foresee.
</P>
<P>
   Quite apart from its cliffhanger plot, the film works because of
its warm bond between outsiders. Zhu Xu and Zhou Ren-Ying, a young
real-life acrobat, convince us they care for each other in this
film, which more than slightly recalls Charlie Chaplin's ``The
Kid'' and a dozen more like it. There's a third outsider, a man who
has grown rich and famous as a performer of female roles and as the
young Buddha in the Sichuan Opera, and who exchanges a mutual
respect with the old man, whom he asks to join his troupe and whose
polite turndown he accepts with grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The King of Masks'' isn't afraid to embrace old-fashioned
ethical values, as well as old-fashioned filmmaking virtues, and
charmingly succeeds by finding the common ground inhabited by its
old and young survivors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1450EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3180 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-INNOCENCE-BOS &LR;      06-04 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-INNOCENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGGIS TAKES CHANCES WITH `SEXUAL INNOCENCE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE LOSS OF SEXUAL INNOCENCE 
Written and directed by: Mike Figgis 
Starring: Julian Sands, Saffron Burrows, Stefano Dionisi, Kelly
Macdonald, Gina McKee, Jonathan Rhys-Meyers, Bernard Hill, Rossy De
Palma 
Rated: R (strong sexual images, pervasive nudity, violence and
language) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At its best, Mike Figgis's new feature, ``The Loss of Sexual
Innocence,'' has an exciting sense of reach and striving and chance
taking. But there's no getting around the fact that it's an uneven
exercise that shows signs of having gestated too long. It's finally
sunk by a too-explicit Adam and Eve story line involving a black
man and a white woman gamboling idyllically in an Eden; it turns
out to be an estate from which they eventually are brutally hunted
down and banished by uniformed guards leading vicious dogs.
</P>
<P>
   One can't help wishing Figgis had more faith in his main (and
what should have been only) narrative, involving the world
constantly throwing difficulties in the path of a boy we see grow
through adolescence into a troubled filmmaker, played by Julian
Sands. The film begins with the boy growing up in Kenya,
voyeuristically sneaking glimpses of forbidden sexuality. There's
more than a hint of the hermetic mystery of early Jane Campion
vignettes as the boy grows and proceeds through a frightening but
fascinating immersion in various rites en route to adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   With young Nic, and the older version played by Sands, it's not
a matter of being expelled from Eden, but of never being admitted.
As a fat, awkward boy, he's humiliated. Later, as an adolescent, he
finds the road to sex torturous and booby-trapped with
embarrassments, even when the girl is willing.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when he's married, his wife isn't terribly willing,
although she dreams a dream that's sexually charged while he dreams
one that's threatening. The film's strength is its flow of
narratively discontinuous images that add up to an unfulfilled
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Loss of Sexual Innocence'' peaks when Nic journeys from
England to Italy to Tunisia to work on his latest film, and urgent
blasts from the past are replaced by urgent intrusions from the
present. Things climax joltingly in the desert when Nic finds
himself in a sexual crossfire between an Italian photographer
(Stefano Dionisi) and an assistant producer (Saffron Burrows), who
earlier had just missed an encounter with a doppelganger in Rome's
airport. A flareup of violence in a market square sparked by a
terrified blind woman separated from her dog, and later, a desert
tribe they accidentally wrong, remind them of the difference
between their respective cultures. And the power and stark
immediacy of these two scenes underscore the shortfall of these
qualities elsehwere.
</P>
<P>
   There is in ``A Loss of Sexual Innocence'' a genuine
experimental impulse, plus a personal dimension that makes it both
brave and rare, worthy of comparison to the likes of ``The Singing
Detective'' and early Antonioni. But except for the uneasy pilgrim,
Nic, the characters remain too sketchy and opaque to satisfy,
packing less expressive punch than the Chopin on the soundtrack.
And the naive and questionable idea of innocence being corrupted,
or blocked by self-styled civilization, falls apart, or rather
never takes convincing shape beneath the flow of sometimes
powerful, sometimes brilliant, but more often undersupplied images.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1452EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3182 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-HALLIWELL-BOS &LR;      06-04 1741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HALLIWELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LONGER JUST ONE OF THE GIRLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ginger Spice is dead. She was 25. She rests in peace.
</P>
<P>
   Geri Halliwell lives on. She is 26, and the world may still be
her oyster.
</P>
<P>
   Halliwell _ once called Ginger Spice and before that Sexy Spice
_ is set to reemerge this month with a solo album,
``Schizophonic.'' Critics may snicker and say her 15 minutes have
been used up _ and just wonder how much more the world wants of
this buxom and brassy lass who shouted ``Girl Power!'' at us every
10 seconds _ but she's on the cover of UK editions of Allure, Marie
Claire, and Mademoiselle, and she's reinvented herself. She's still
a teeny thing, but she is looking rather . . . ladylike. Her
streaked copper hair is now strawberry blond; her freckles shimmer;
her makeup is minimal. There's less decolletage. Once, in her
pre-Spice Girl life, she modeled nude. With the Spice Girls, her
bust was pushed up. Now, she's the girl next door, not exactly
demure, but, well, much less of a pop tart. Adorable.
</P>
<P>
   Halliwell's record label, Capitol, is mounting a big push on her
album. ``She is a major, major priority in this company,'' says a
spokeswoman. ``Look at Me,'' the sassy first single, is No. 8 on
MTV and has just been released to radio. In England, the single is
near the top of the charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Me'' suggests the giddy pop sensibility of the Spice
Girls is intact _ with just a bit more bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``My album is Johnny Rotten meets Julie Andrews,'' says
Halliwell, from New York. ``There's an anarchist in me.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Look at Me,'' the first single, she sings these couplets,
``Bigmakeup/little breakup. . . . Old feel-ing/new beginning. . . .
Cold blooded/hot gossip. . . . Fake honey/real plastic. . . . Fast
lovin'/Slow movin'/No rhythm/But I'm groovin'.'' She sings about
spinning ``little white lies.'' In the video, an old-fashioned
hearse passes by with GINGER written on the side. Shortly,
Ginger/Geri is in the casket, wickedly waking up from being dead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Her life in the Spice Girls, and departure from it, is ``one
level'' of the song, says Halliwell, ``but on a bigger level it's
about not taking each other at face value. I think we all put
labels on each other _ you're black, you're gay, you're fat, you're
thin _ and I just think that is a load of (expletive). . . . We all
hide behind images. The point is, whether I've got on a bustier and
some hot pants or dressed all in black, your heart and mind is the
same, you have the same hopes and fears. That's what I believe.
Call me an old hippie.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip back in time, to about a year ago. May 29, actually. The
Spice Girls, having conquered Britain, were gearing up for their
first American tour, which would sell out almost instantaneously.
They were set to beat the bushes and discuss Spice world with the
American press. Halliwell _ de facto leader of the Girls _ was to
ring me up. At the last minute, a publicist called and said Emma
Bunton (Baby Spice) would be chatting. Halliwell was ill. Later,
that day the bombshell exploded: Halliwell would be leaving the
Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ill?'' Halliwell is asked, finally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was a porky pie they told you!'' says Halliwell,
ever chipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``A what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A porky pie. That's an expression for a lie.'' (Specifically,
it's cockney rhyming slang.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to clear that matter, deal with the past, go on to the
future so you know where I'm at,'' says Halliwell. ``I actually was
going to leave the Spice Girls at the end of the American tour; I
hadn't planned to go before that. But it was kind of like when
you're in a relationship and you're not in love anymore and you
think it's time to move on _ I don't love you like I did four years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in a band is like a marriage. When you first break up
and dissolve the partnership, it's a little tricky. You are
detaching yourself and it is hard. I had to create a new space for
myself. I felt I needed to rebuild. I wasn't just saying goodbye to
them, I was saying goodbye to the family and friends, the
establishment, everything. But I think that like all ex-husbands
you still love them and care for them even if you're not in love
with them. I just think I have grown out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who was Ginger Spice, then?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when you go on a first date,'' says Halliwell, ``and
on that date you put your best clothes on, you give your funniest
lines, and there is probably one dimension of you. That was the one
side I have, and Ginger was a part of me when I was 17 years old. I
wore platform shoes. Nothing was contrived about Ginger, but I just
moved on. I was changing internally. When I left Spice Girls I
didn't know I was going to go solo. I was very afraid to admit
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Halliwell says she was entering a more serious phase of her
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never about the money,'' Halliwell says of the Girls.
``I was on a mission. So I just thought I would like some integrity
with what I do, and leave after the tour. But then in May, the
night before (the interview) there was this breast cancer interview
I was meant to do and it got canceled, and it made me question who
I was.'' (She'd had a benign lump in her breast when she was 18;
she had just finished reading a heart-wrenching book about breast
cancer, ``Before I Say Goodbye.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why, but sometimes in life something happens and
it just makes you think, `Who am I? What am I doing? Where is my
soul? Has my ego eaten that up?' It is such a self-obsessed
industry. I thought I was meant to be the advocate of girl power.
And I think it had grown for me into something else, with more
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   She works for the United Nations as a good-will ambassador.
``When you are famous,'' says Halliwell, ``people obviously pay
more attention to certain issues, and all I can do is lend my fame.
I'm not claiming to be a pool of knowledge. It is a lifelong
project. I am not sort of jumping in and rushing around. I think we
all have multiple careers and this is one part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Halliwell also became a champion of breast cancer research,
selling all her Ginger Spice clothes to benefit the cause.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I think is important in life is to keep
perspective on what life is all about,'' says Halliwell. Yes, she
recently bought a huge house in the country, and she can live well
forever. ``I would rather have the money than no money, but I have
to say if anyone is chasing that dream of money, well, you know the
cliche: Money will not bring you happiness. It will distract you
from unhappiness and buy you a little bit of freedom. We can all
get caught up in self-importance and materialism. When you realize
there are people starving to death in Africa and wars going on and
people dying from ignorance . . . it keeps your feet on the
ground.'' Of her charitable work: ``I get as much out of it as I
give.''
</P>
<P>
   One of her best friends is George Michael. He is her ``only
celebrity friend, but we haven't got a celebrity relationship,''
she says. ``He comes from the same area as me. We were both kind of
ugly kids at school; we both had a Mediterranean parent; we have an
empathy, and it's so nice we're in the same business.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, both have reaped stardom's benefits as well as
suffering the slings and arrows.
</P>
<P>
   Her music is ``very eclectic,'' says Halliwell. ``Like a
painting, you stare at it, and one person might get good colors and
think of it as entertaining and light, and another person might
look at it and see darkness, and meaning and depth. That's what I
try to do with my music. I think women will identify with it; it's
like a PMS mood swing. I think creatively, I write better when I'm
down. And I have no sex when I'm writing as well. It steals my
creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   Halliwell is no diva. She's a pop gal. ``I know I'm not Celine
Dion,'' she says, ``but I have heart and passion and the running
theme, I think, is honesty. I'm trying to talk to you as a friend
when you put my CD on. I want to keep you company. You should be
able to respond to it whether you are 16, 6, or 60. I kind of make
love to my music. . . . I always make songs that the average person
in the street can sing along to. I'm never patronizing. I hate it
when you can't join in. I think each song should touch you
differently _ some for your heart, some for your mind, some for
your feet, and some for your groin.''
</P>
<P>
   Halliwell does not want to take issue with her ex-mates in the
Spice Girls, nor criticize the music. ``I'm very proud of where I
come from and I never want to diss it,'' she says. ``I hope Spice
Girls fans have liked what I've done, but everybody needs to grow.
It's like nature, we are growing and changing. I had a big input
with the imagination, the imagery, the direction _ so I can't knock
it _ but obviously being in a band you've got to swallow your ego
and make room. It's a team effort to a certain degree. But whatever
I gave to the Spice Girls I took with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Halliwell would like to tour, but says, ``That's up to the great
American public.'' That is, if they buy ``Schizophonic'' in
sufficient numbers to justify a tour. She says she doesn't have
sales goals; she's not aching for a Grammy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't just bosh around with the guitar,'' she says. ``I'm
going to give you something, good old-fashioned entertainment. If
you like me or not, I'm going to make you smile. Music is very
powerful. We need joy in our lives. There is a fundamental serious
message in some of the things I sing about. It's not brain surgery,
it's escapism.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Halliwell passes the 15 minutes of fame mark and marches
boldly into the future. ``At the end of the day,'' she says, ``I
like being famous, but there's ups and downs. I've grown used to
it, so fame doesn't really exist anyway, nor does the 15 minutes.
It's more like a 30-second feeling, and you don't think about it
all the time. It's more about being given the opportunity. I feel
lucky to be given a second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Halliwell, who is now partially self-managed, says she
frequently stresses out and has to keep reminding herself to chill.
The best advice she can offer anybody similarly stressed is this:
``For God's sake, laugh at yourself. Think `Is this going to matter
when I'm 80?' No, it's not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1453EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3185 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-WIND-BOS &LR;      06-04 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WIND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARADISE LOST  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
DARK WIND 
A Survivor's Tale of Love and Loss 
By Gordon Chaplin 
Atlantic Monthly Press, 225 pp., $23 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just before sunset on Nov. 9, 1992, the Lord Jim dropped anchor
at Wotho atoll in the Marshall Islands, a cluster of dots in the
Pacific Ocean. For captain Gordon Chaplin and his partner, Susan
Atkinson, the day was full of the pleasures of arrival. They
stripped and dived into the balmy water, reveling in the interplay
of light and color as the sun slipped lower. Susan whispered,
``This is paradise. And you made it possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a soft, effortless procession the days slipped by like
tradewind clouds. We were sustained by what I could catch in the
sea and what the villagers gave Susan: crab, clams, . . . conch,
snapper and more fruit. We never argued anymore; there was nothing
to argue about. The issues between us resolved themselves or faded
into insignificance. Time was different here. We had a feeling it
could go on forever.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``Dark Wind'' were a novel, and a typhoon roared in and
splintered all this perfection, the cliche would be too much to
bear. But Chaplin's book is nonfiction. The storm packing 105-knot
winds is real, and the destruction and loss it leaves in its wake
are irrevocable. Chaplin and Atkinson, who had ridden out storms
before, made a fateful decision to stay with the boat. When the
Lord Jim was ripped from its anchor and dashed against a reef, they
plunged overboard with half-inflated life vests. Atkinson slipped
out of her vest, floated just out of reach, and drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Doubt, recrimination, and searing questions weigh Chaplin down
like so much ballast. Like other writers who catalog extremes,
Chaplin is the haggard survivor left to obsess over what went
wrong, and when. And why.
</P>
<P>
   ``This book began as pure therapy,'' he writes in an afterword.
It is a story cobbled together ``from highly personal
woolgatherings, love-ramblings, euphoria, hallucinations,
should-have-dones, excuses, and mea culpas.'' In the hands of a
less gifted storyteller, ``Dark Wind'' would flirt with the
lachrymose. But Chaplin's style is stripped down and unsparing, and
he sets limits on his own self-pity. He uses his journalistic
skills (he has written for The Washington Post and Newsweek) to
analyze his own role in the disaster. The result is an absorbing
and unsettling tale of hubris, hindsight, fate, and random rotten
luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did the pattern of our lives lead inexorably to disaster? And,
if so, why have I been left to stand alone on the top of a hill in
upstate New York while the sun goes down another time, and another,
and I watch summer give way to fall, fall to winter, and the
twentieth century give way to the twenty-first? I am beginning to
realize that I have to write our story. By the time I finish, maybe
I'll understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin and Atkinson had put themselves at the center of storms
before. They met in the mid-'60s, when each was married to someone
else. Their first cruise, with their spouses, was on a weeklong
vacation in Maine. Looking back, Chaplin finds plenty of shadowy
portent. On the last day, in Penobscot Bay, a squall bore down on
them. Chaplin and Atkinson voted to stay with the boat, not wanting
to run from a little bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   They met again 12 years later, in the late '70s, and romance
swept in ``like an unavoidable force of nature.'' Within six
months, Chaplin had left his wife and two daughters. Sailing became
the center of Chaplin and Atkinson's lives, the place where they
felt most in synch as a couple. Chaplin wrote about their cruise
along the eastern shores of Central America in ``Fever Coast Log.''
They moved their blended family to Baja California for six months,
and Atkinson duly recorded the disasters that ensued in a
young-adult novel called ``Taking Off.''
</P>
<P>
   Both seemed courageous, adventuresome, willing to put themselves
in the hands of chance. But frailty hid behind the bravado. Chaplin
had a knack for escapism. Atkinson kept her real fears to herself.
After her death, Chaplin found a letter in a drawer at their farm
in New York. ``The thing that scares me the most,'' she wrote, ``is
that you will continue to choose not to listen to me when I voice
my fears. You don't care if I am scared. You don't stop teasing
when I beg you to stop. You ridicule and denigrate my concerns and
act as if they are not real. They are very very real.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a mark of Chaplin's basic honesty that he includes the
letter. In the end, he realizes, some actions (and inactions) leave
an indelible mark in the world. If Atkinson never made it back from
the Marshall Islands, neither did Chaplin, in some sense. ``Someone
who looks like me and has my name came back. Like Pip, in
`Moby-Dick,' I'm not really here anymore. I'm at Wotho atoll with
her, planning our next leg.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1455EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
