<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3189 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-KINKADE-2TAKES-SF     06-04 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-KINKADE-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET THERE BE LIGHT: PAINTER THOMAS KINKADE WRITES BOOK ON
JOYFUL  LIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM WHITING  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Thomas Kinkade's new book is called ``Lightposts
for Living: The Art of Choosing a Joyful Life,'' and it's not too
tough to figure out. Just open the door to one of the cotton-candy
houses in his paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The artist's cutesy cottages invariably show light glowing
through the windows as approached from a cobblestone walkway lined
with red and gold flowers in the summer, fallen leaves in the damp
autumn. Smoke puffs from a stone chimney, and light beams down from
heaven. The message seems to be that a wholesome family is inside
reading Scripture, just like the Kinkades.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no people in his paintings of lighthouses, homes
or flower-laced gazebos. They're all on the outside looking in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a part of their home that is so compelling to them that
they step into that world continuously and it gives them comfort.
It gives them relief,'' says the ``Painter of Light,'' a trademark.
``People become so attached to it that they will write me letters
and say, `If there's ever a fire in my home, I'm going to grab my
old puppy dog first and my Thomas Kinkade second.'''
</P>
<P>
   Art critics and curators might like to watch a Kinkade burn, but
that doesn't bother him. He is a Christian evangelist, and God is
the only critic he hears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paint sentiment because I'm not afraid of it,'' says
Kinkade, who lives in Los Gatos, Calif. ``I have in my heart a
great romance for living, and I put that in my paintings
unashamedly.''
</P>
<P>
   He's unashamed of commerce, too. Last year his Media Arts Group
showed a $55 million profit on sales of $83 million, according to
the company's Web site. Lithographs are cranked out of a San Jose
plant with a capacity of 1,000 prints a day and sold for $225 to
$35,000 at 200 Kinkade galleries across middle America. His left
hand has created the most profitable brand name in art, with
licensees including Hallmark, Avon and La-Z-Boy.
</P>
<P>
   Kinkade claims to be the most-collected living artist in America
_ according to his estimates, a Kinkade print hangs in one out of
every 20 American homes.
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible to lounge on a Kinkade recliner while
gathering warmth from a Kinkade blanket and coffee mug, and that's
not counting the warm fuzziness in his pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Next it will be Kinkade homes filled with Kinkade furnishings.
According to his company Web site, he has entered into an agreement
with a Texas company to build Thomas Kinkade Villages inspired by
his work.
</P>
<P>
   As a business arm of the gospel, Kinkade may have commercial
reach second only to that of the Mormon Church. He's the only
artist with both a listing on the New York Stock Exchange (Media
Arts Group) and a show on the QVC home shopping network.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with ``Lightposts for Living'' (Warner Books; $20), he has
entered the self-help market.
</P>
<P>
   The book offers bits of advice, which he calls ``lightposts.''
There are 12 principles, just like a step program, including
``Living in the Light of Abiding Happiness'' and ``Living in the
Light of the Lovely.'' These are combined with inspirational
quotes, anecdotes and images of his paintings. Every home has a
television, and every home should have a Kinkade for balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are bombarded with moving images, but we have no still
imagery,'' he says. ``In the shouting of all that culture, the soft
whisper in the distance catches your attention. My paintings are
that soft whisper in the midst of the shouts of our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   A Kinkade monologue can last an hour without interruption, even
though he is booked at half-hour intervals and his next appointment
is waiting. It takes half an hour just to describe the miracles in
his life.
</P>
<P>
   The first came when he was 4 and his big sister was drawing a
driveway. It didn't look real, so Kinkade took her pencil and
corrected the driveway to recede in depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden something clicked in my brain, which was an
epiphany that shaped my whole life,'' recalls Kinkade, 41. ``I saw
that you could take lines on paper and create a third dimension,
little worlds that you can step into.''
</P>
<P>
   The second miracle came 10 years later. A poor boy growing up in
a broken home in Placerville, Calif., he needed an artist mentor,
and one moved in right next door: Bay Area figurative artist Glenn
Wessels, who had been a professor of fine arts at the University of
California at Berkeley. ``Right in those years where a father
figure is so critical, God miraculously had his hand in my life,''
Kinkade says. ``Out of nowhere, a hundred feet from our house, one
of the greatest minds in art instruction moved.''
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for cleaning his studio, Wessels agreed to teach the
boy.
</P>
<P>
   The next miracle came after Kinkade had washed out of the art
schools at both UC Berkeley and the Art Center College of Design in
Pasadena. ``I had a conversion to the Christian faith which was
deep and it was profound,'' he says. ``When I got saved, my art got
saved. It was as though the light came on.''
</P>
<P>
   He became the Painter of Light, a missionary. That's when the
miracle of lithography touched him. He couldn't see putting his
vision into one painting for one buyer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``It dawned on me if I could find a way for more people to see
it, then I might be able to get this message out more broadly.'' In
1984, Kinkade and his wife, Nanette, pooled their life savings to
make 1,000 prints of his favorite painting, which he sold for $35
each.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I did that my artist friends said, `You've sold out,' and
it struck me as absurd,'' he says. ``That would be like a writer
not publishing a manuscript. Or a musician saying `I won't ever do
CDs.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kinkade likes comparing painters to authors and recording
artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average person can name the five top musicians they just
love. Literature has done the same thing. The masses have access to
literature,'' he says. ``But there has been no populist expression
of the arts. The artists have alienated themselves from the
culture, and the average person has no interest in their work.
That's the plane at which I began to think in the late '70s and
early '80s.''
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1990s his way of thinking has resulted in a
workforce of 600 people. ``God's been good to our company,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor has it that it's a paint-by-numbers operation, and Kinkade
just adds the light in the windows. Not true, he says. ``There's
never been a brush stroke on my paintings other than mine. I do all
my own work, all my own research. I'm just old-fashioned, I
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Nanette have four daughters, and no television. His
family lives simply and frugally, he says, even though the Wall
Street Journal recently calculated his worth at $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kinkade has committed to painting 150 pictures over the next 15
years. He no longer sells the originals, which have gone for as
much as $500,000. He's now marketing a ``San Francisco
Collection,'' the tourist views in very soft focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never base my paintings on a place, and when I do I change
it so much that it's almost unrecognizable,'' he says. ``I always
tell people, `It's my world, welcome to it.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
