<HEADER>
A3195 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-ADV06     06-04 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD PHENOMENON IN A BRAND NEW FORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 6, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have a sort of weird situation on my dining room ceiling.
It's a darkish stain the exact same size and shape as the water bed
frame on the floor of the bedroom above. I don't think its a leak;
if it was it would be a lot worse. What is it, how can I get rid of
it, and how can I keep it from coming back?
</P>
<P>
   A.N., Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It's an old phenomenon, but in a uniquely new form: the water
bed. What has happened: the frame of the bed sitting on the floor
has made that part of the floor, and the ceiling below, cooler than
the rest of the ceiling. Water vapor condenses on that cool area,
making it damp. You may not notice it is damp, but it is, enough
for dirt to cling to it, or mildew to grow on it. To get rid of it,
test an area first with household bleach; if that area turns white
within 10 seconds, it is mildew, and can be killed and cleaned off
by wiping with a solution of one part household bleach and three
parts water. If the area does not lghten up with the bleach test,
it is dirt, and can be removed by washing the entire ceiling with
detergent and water. This must be said: Wear skin and eye
protection when working with bleach.
</P>
<P>
   To keep it from coming back, set the bed frame on short wood
blocks; 2 x 4s or 1 x 4s will do; all you need to do is lift the
frame so air will circulate under it.
</P>
<P>
   I referred to the stain as an old phenomenon; such stains
usually show up on the joists behind a ceiling or the studs behind
a wall, which are cooler than the rest of the ceiling or wall. The
water bed outline is a new variation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am concerned about gaps developing between hardwood floor
boards. Is there a way to prevent that? I want to put a hardwood
floor in a three-season porch that is still to be built.
</P>
<P>
   JIM SEE, Wakefield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Those opening seams seem to be a plague, caused my moisture.
What happens is that the boards take up moisture and expand. So far
so good; the seams are tight. But when the boards dry out and
contract, they may contract enough to make gaps. This may take
several cycles of expansion and contraction to happen.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cure except relaying the boards. One technique to
prevent their occurrence is to store the boards in the room for two
weeks before laying. This will make their moisture content the same
as the materials in the room, minimizing expansion and contraction.
</P>
<P>
   Also, and I think it is a better idea, install the boards in
winter, when the heat is on, and storing the boards for two weeks
will dry them out even more, making them as small as possible when
installed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am ready to repaint a door, but I noticed that the plastic
film was never removed from the brass kickplate that was installed
some time ago. Now I can't get it off, or it comes off in tiny
shreds. Any easy ways to remove it?
</P>
<P>
   ELIZABETH RANIERE, Woburn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Try heat from a hair dryer; place the heat along an edge, to
try to get the film started in one piece; then as you pull the
film, keep the heat under the film.
</P>
<P>
   Or, try vinegar or oil; WD-40 is a good oil to use, easily
dispensed from a spray can. As with the heat, try to pull off some
of the film so you can spray the oil or apply the vinegar under the
film, pulling it off as you spray.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am installing a new deck outdoors. It will be free standing
(not attached to the house), 16 by 20 feet, four to six inches
above the ground. I have had several suggestions as how to anchor
it, all different. One adviser said to set it on Sonotubes
(concrete columns) set four feet into the ground. Another said to
put 8-inch by 16-inch concrete blocks on the ground, and set posts
on that. A third suggested smoothing out the ground, apply plastic
and crushed stone, and put the deck on that. What is best?
</P>
<P>
   LOUIS D'AMBRORSIO, Hampton, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The best way is to set the Sonotubes 4 feet into the ground.
In New Hampshire, this will put the bottom of the tubes below the
frost line, so there will be no heaving or moving of the deck. (In
Massachusetts the rule is generally three feet.)
</P>
<P>
   The second best, not even mentioned, is to sink 4 x 4
pressure-treated posts into the ground, three or four feet.
</P>
<P>
   The worst are setting blocks or crushed stone on the ground and
putting the deck down. This would make it float on or near the
ground, and heave up and down in winter.
</P>
<P>
   And, being so large, it is more likely to heave in different
sections, resulting in a deck that is out of skew and off level.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A handyman caulked my storm windows and did other jobs around
the house, but he also caulked over the weep holes in the storms'
bottom frame (an alumnum sill that sits on the wood). Should I
drill new holes?
</P>
<P>
   STEPHANIE ROGERS, Newton
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. No need, although there is a need for weep holes. You can
probe the aluminum frame at the sill to locate the holes, which
should be as close as possible to the wood sill. Then ream out the
hole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1459EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
