<HEADER>
A3198 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV06     06-04 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVERTING SOME MONEY WOULD EASE HEAVY DOSE OF LARGE-CAPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 6, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a 36-year-old woman with an annual income of $40,000.
I'm concerned my investments aren't diverse enough because they are
mostly large-cap blend funds. They include $26,152 in Fidelity Blue
Chip Growth, $25,311 in Fidelity Dividend Growth, $25,399 in
Fidelity Spartan U.S. Equity Index, $17,851 in Vanguard Index 500,
$2,075 in Vanguard Windsor II, $6,209 in T. Rowe Price Dividend
Growth, and $6,001 in T. Rowe Price Value funds. I also have
$61,863 in the ESOP plan of a former employer. Should I move some
of my money to other funds? I would like to invest in a health care
sector fund.
</P>
<P>
   P.H., Boston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There's no argument that the large-cap blend funds are out of
whack _ I tally 92.5 percent of the fund portfolio invested there.
You don't mention whether these holdings are in tax-deferred
account such as IRAs or are taxable. If they are taxable accounts,
you want to think about how much you'll give up to the taxman by
making changes; since it's clear that you're a good saver, if these
are all taxable accounts you might decide to work toward a better
portfolio balance by directing new investments to different market
sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is that you might be able to roll over the
assets in that ESOP account into an IRA, thus giving you a vehicle
which might help get a better-diversified portfolio without making
any major changes.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not possible, here's what I suggest: First divert
$20,000 from the three Fidelity funds to Fidelity Health Care, even
though it wouldn't really reduce reliance on the large caps; while
Health Care is a sector fund, its portfolio is dominated by
large-cap growth stocks.
</P>
<P>
   If these are tax-deferred accounts, I'd also divert about the
same amount of money from the three dominant Fidelity funds to
Fidelity Overseas. I'd also suggest moving about $6,000 to a
small-cap fund, perhaps T. Rowe Price Small-Cap Stock or Vanguard
Small-Cap Index.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to make these moves, you would reduce the
concentration in the large-cap blend sector from that 92.5 percent
to 50.3 percent. Still, when you add in the Windsor II and Health
Care positions, you would have 70.6 percent in domestic large-cap
stocks, and I suggest you seek to reduce that to about 60 percent
by concentrating future investments in the mid- and small-cap funds
until you've achieved the desired balance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My granddaughter is 3 and has approximately $3,000 in the
bank. I told her father that he should put it into a mutual fund
and add to it as the years go by, for her education. I mentioned
Northeast Investors Growth fund. What do you think of that?
</P>
<P>
   R.B., Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Northeast Investors Growth has a lot of the things investors
should look for, in my opinion. It has a long and strong record,
all of it under the same portfolio managers. It has no load or
12b-1 fees, low turnover, and a fairly consistent investment style.
In the last ten years, it has evolved from the large-cap growth
sector to a large-cap blend portfolio. During the last decade, it
has averaged 19.27 percent annual returns; over three years,
average annual returns have been 30 percent, and its 6 percent
year-to-date gain for 1999 has been a bit above the average for its
peer funds. All of this adds up to a top five-star rating from
Morningstar Mutual Funds.
</P>
<P>
   There are, though, two things you might think about. One is its
propensity to use leverage from time to time _ that's to say, to
borrow money against its portfolio to give more oomph to its market
plays. This can be a great thing in strong markets and with the
right market plays, but it can cause trouble when the markets are
weak and/or the manager's stock selection is off.
</P>
<P>
   The second factor which might give you pause is the fund's
tendency to concentrate the portfolio in certain market sectors
from time to time. Currently the favorite is financial stocks,
where its position represents 30.9 percent of the portfolio and is
nearly twice the concentration of financial stocks in the Standard
and Poor's 500 index.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the coin, the fund entirely spurns the
utility sector, and holds only modest positions in energy and
durable goods stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, I think the plusses pretty much outweigh the reasons
an investor might pause before investing here, and I find this an
excellent choice for an investment of 15 years or so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I will be retiring next month. He is 59 and I
am 58. He will have a pension of $26,200 per year and I will
collect about $600 per month from Social Security at age 62. We
have an income need of about $46,000 a year. Our savings is in two
portfolios. First is a taxable portfolio of $205,000 with 28
percent in Fidelity Equity-Income II and 24 percent each in T. Rowe
Price Tax-Efficient Balanced, T. Rowe Price Spectrum Income, and
Vanguard Prime Money Market funds. A tax-deferred portfolio of
$250,000 is 28 percent invested in Fidelity Fund, 30 percent in
Fidelity Puritan, 10 percent in Fidelity Diversified International,
9 percent in Fidelity Utilities, 15 percent in Fidelity Investment
Grade Bond, 5 percent in Fidelity High Income, and 3 percent in T.
Rowe Price Science and Technology. Our approach is this: We plan to
draw down the taxable account at a rate of $2,000 a month until it
runs out, hopefully not before ten years. This will allow the
tax-deferred portfolio to grow for another ten years. Is this plan
realistic? More important, is the deferred portfolio properly
allocated for something that will sit for another ten years?
</P>
<P>
   C.M., Medway
</P>
<P>
   A. I think you've really got a handle on this. If you achieve
average 7 percent returns from the taxable portfolio, it should do
even better than you suggest _ supporting a sequence of $2,000
monthly withdrawals for a little more than 153 months. During that
period, projecting 9 percent portfolio growth within the deferred
account, that would grow to $750,630 _ a figure which should be
sufficient to support a sequence of $3,000 monthly withdrawals with
no diminution of principal, and in fact with moderate additional
principal growth. Why $3,000? Don't forget about inflation.
</P>
<P>
   I think you have balanced the tax-deferred portfolio nicely, and
I see no reason for changes now. But I do suggest you plan to make
some modifications beginning about five years before the date at
which you anticipate drawing upon it. At that point I would begin a
slow process of moving investments toward the fixed-income side.
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
