<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD WORK ISN'T ALL THAT GREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Work is cool. That seems to be the new work
ethic being promoted in America.
</P>
<P>
   The Protestant ethic is long gone. No more asceticism, except
for that black Prada look. Nobody works to get into heaven and few
work to better the community. The idea is to get into the best
restaurant, pull out the newest laptop and talk business on the
smallest cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   The work ethic of slaving hard at a job you hate to better your
kids is out. Except among the poor people, of course. For the
masses, including the new ditch diggers of data entry, it's still
``Work sucks.''
</P>
<P>
   The work-is-cool ethic is for those with portfolios and projects
_ and I don't mean housing projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``All work of economic value is project work,'' writes Tom
Peters, author of ``In Search of Excellence,'' in the magazine Fast
Company.
</P>
<P>
   You are your projects. For columnists, that means ``You are whom
you have for lunch.'' It's not an appetizing thought.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fast Company is the handbook of the new work-is-cool ethic. The
magazine is quite a piece of work, and it's cool-looking, as if
Wired met Forbes for a team-building exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Each issue is filled with articles by career coaches,
consultants and others who have cool jobs telling readers how to
build teams, hold meetings, set agendas and have cool jobs (I mean
projects) on the fast track.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine even has a feature called ``Job Titles of the
Future,'' featuring trendy-looking people with titles like
``Minister of Enlightenment.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy with that cool job is a Ph.D. who says he enlightens
employees by using Kant to teach them to think independently.
</P>
<P>
   The company he works for, tellingly enough, is MacTemps, a $100
million business that he calls ``a talent agency.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd call it a temp agency, where the unenlightened are forced to
take their projects _ namely, their unemployed selves.
</P>
<P>
   How can a magazine become extremely successful promoting the
work-is-cool ethic?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are meant to feel they spend so much time at
work that it's this avenue for great spiritual awakening,'' said
Daniel S. Levine, author of ``Disgruntled, the Darker Side of the
World of Work.'' ``But it's hard if you don't have time and sit all
day at computers.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What about the less successful temps, the outsourced and the
downsized?
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how many new job titles there are for the jobless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disgruntled'' quotes a corporation's vice president for human
resources who said, ``Jobs are being replaced by `projects' and our
`fields of work,' giving rise to a society that is increasingly
`jobless but not workless.'''
</P>
<P>
   The amount of work being piled on people keeps increasing,
whatever you call it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the Council of Economic Advisors shows
families today are spending an average of 22 fewer hours together a
week than families did 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, all the figures on (work) hours appear to be
rising,'' said economist Juliet Schor of Harvard University.
``There are more and more people trying to get up and out of it,
but it's not helping.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost a decade ago, Schor wrote ``The Overworked American: The
Unexpected Decline of Leisure,'' which detailed the pressures that
caused American work hours to increase over the previous 20 years.
When I phoned her, she was harried and didn't have much time to
talk.
</P>
<P>
   The final chapter of her book, called ``Exiting the Squirrel
Cage,'' had a few small suggestions for countering the irrational
pressure for ever-longer workweeks. The last section of that
chapter was called ``Reclaiming Leisure.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't happened. The squirrel cage is now filled with
obsessional objects like Palm Pilots, pagers, cell phones and
laptops, and we're running perpetually.
</P>
<P>
   An ad in Fast Company by Microsoft for hand-held PCs refers to
them as ``your significant other PC.'' Yikes, now Bill says we're
married to them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was disturbed to read about the ``10-minute, mind-cleansing
virtual vacation,'' as a couple of ``futurists'' called it. The
idea is that digital slaves can take safaris or visit museums
without getting away from the screen.
</P>
<P>
   As Schor noted in her 1991 book, ``One of the most notable
developments of the 1980s is that paid time-off is actually
shrinking.''
</P>
<P>
   I hate to think that in the next millennium it'll shrink to a
10- minute ``virtual vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Cotton Mather, the New England Puritan moralist, said,
``Laudable recreations may be used now and then, but I beseech you,
let those recreations be used for sauce and not for meat.''
</P>
<P>
   Recreation and work have been turned into hash. But it's modern
fusion hash, and how do you get people to swallow something
distasteful?
</P>
<P>
   Tell them it's cool.
</P>
<P>
   Me, I take the Ronald Reagan point of view. ``Disgruntled''
quotes our former president as saying,``''They say hard work never
hurt anybody, but I figure why take the chance?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
