<SLUG> BC-HORMEL-APPOINTMENT-4THLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON USES RECESS APPOINTMENT TO NAME HORMEL TO LUXEMBOURG POST 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: ADDS Hormel's age in 2d graf.) 
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton used a recess appointment Friday
to install San Francisco philanthropist and gay rights advocate
James C. Hormel as ambassador to Luxembourg, bypassing opposition
from the Republican Senate leadership that sidetracked the
nomination for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, 66, thus becomes the first openly gay American
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's press secretary, Joe Lockhart, issued a statement
saying: ``The president today announced the recess appointment of
James C. Hormel to serve as United States ambassador to
Luxembourg.''
</P>
<P>
   By naming him to the diplomatic post during a congressional
recess, Clinton overcame a stubborn political stalemate with
conservative Republican senators who have blocked action on the
nomination since the Senate Foreign Relations Committee approved it
in a 16-2 vote in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. _ who
likened homosexuality to alcoholism, sex addiction and kleptomania
and urged Americans to help gays change their sexual orientation _
declined to lift the so-called ``holds'' that the four
conservatives had imposed, thus refusing to bring the nomination to
the Senate floor for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Congress returns from its 10-day Memorial Day recess on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Constitution empowers a president to make recess
appointments and says that they ``shall expire at the end of
(Congress') next session,'' meaning that Hormel can serve until
January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Traditional Values Coalition, a conservative group claiming
to represent 40,000 churches, charged Friday that Clinton's action
was ``a cowardly tactic of sneaking in an undesirable appointment
while avoiding public scrutiny.'' It called Hormel ``a purveyor of
smut'' and said that a San Francisco center he financed ``is one of
the biggest collections of pornography and pro-pedophilia
literature ever assembled.''
</P>
<P>
   But David M. Smith, communications director at the Human Rights
Campaign, the nation's largest gay rights organization, said
Clinton's appointment was ``a bold move that is a testament to his
commitment to treating all people fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith added: ``This fight was never about trying to get the
first openly gay ambassador. This has always been about making sure
that anti-gay bias was not a barrier to good people doing public
service for their country.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes Clinton's action will not invite retaliation
from Capitol Hill. ``The usual suspects are going to be jacked up
about this, just as they are about all gay issues,'' he said.
``They will continue to try to enact policies that discriminate
against gay people.''
</P>
<P>
   John Czwartacki, a Lott spokesman, called the recess appointment
``a slap in the face to Catholics everywhere.'' He said Lott was
concerned about what he called Hormel's support for groups critical
of the Catholic church. Czwartacki was referring to the fact that
Hormel, witnessing a parade of San Francisco drag queens dressed as
nuns several years ago, laughed at their antics targeting the
church's hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican critics and conservative activists have
expressed concern that Hormel, a former dean of the University of
Chicago Law School, might use the Luxembourg post to proselytize
others to embrace homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, a founder of the Human Rights Campaign, sought to allay
the concerns of critics last year with a letter to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not use, nor do I think it appropriate to use, the
office of the ambassador to advocate any personal views that I may
hold on any issue,'' Hormel wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The critics have focused on Hormel's $500,000 donation to the
San Francisco Main Public Library, which then named a collection of
gay and lesbian material after the contributor. Researchers at the
library have access not only to the papers of San Francisco gay
activists such as the late Harvey Milk and Randy Shilts, but also
to materials provided by controversial groups such as the North
American Man Boy Love Association, an organization that critics
accuse of advocating pedophilia.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said Hormel also has contributed to a program that sends
speakers to discuss homosexuality with elementary school children.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that Clinton's recess appointment of Hormel will
enable the ambassador to serve in Luxembourg for the remaining 18
months of Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's maneuver gives the appointee all the legal authority
of a presidential appointee confirmed by the Senate but not the
political clout that a Senate confirmation conveys.
</P>
<P>
   The senators who announced their ``holds'' on Hormel's
nomination are Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark.; James Inhofe, R-Okla., and
Bob Smith, R-N.H. The fourth remains anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they had won commitments
from at least 60 senators to support confirmation of Hormel, 66,
the heir to the Hormel Meat Co. fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has used recess appointments in the past to install
nominees for whom he could not win Senate confirmation. For
instance, he defied Senate opponents in December 1997 to give a
recess appointment to California civil rights lawyer Bill Lann Lee
to serve as acting assistant attorney general in charge of the
Justice Department's civil rights division.
</P>
<P>
   The president acted after his nomination of Lee, a prominent
Asian American civil rights lawyer, had languished before the
Senate Judiciary Committee for six months.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton renominated Lee to the post on March 5, setting the
stage for Lee to continue in the post as an acting assistant
attorney general for the remainder of Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
