<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CHAMPION-BOS &LR;      06-04 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CHAMPION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVYWEIGHT CAST CREATES A WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THAT CHAMPIONSHIP SEASON 
Starring: Paul Sorvino, Vincent D'Onofrio, Terry Kinney, Tony
Shalhoub, Gary Sinise 
Directed by: Sorvino 
On: Showtime 
Time: Sunday at 8 p.m. 
Rated: TV14 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The boys in the band have got nothing on the self-loathing,
secret-bearing, monologue-delivering men of ``That Championship
Season.'' These five fellows aren't gay, or at least they don't get
around to that particular revelation in the course of Showtime's
adaptation of the Pulitzer Prize-winning 1972 play. But they sure
are tortured, and they sure do know how to turn a little party into
a big old drunken drag, complete with plenty of blood, sweat, and
tears, not to mention vomit, which conveniently finds its way into
the basketball trophy at the symbolic center of the drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Championship Season,'' which airs Sunday night at 8, is
heavy going, to put it mildly. It might be compared to having a
tooth pulled with a Robert Bly audiotape blaring over the dentist's
speaker system. As it jumps from macho confrontation to dazed
soul-baring and back again, Jason Miller's script is a bucket of
Big Statements about masculinity, America, capitalism, and
fraudulence, and self-important metaphors like ``You quit on the
field, you'll quit in life. It's on the playing field that wars are
won.'' And the storyline, about the 20th reunion of four high
school basketball stars at the home of their coach, is unnervingly
static, as far too many of its critical events happened at another
time, offstage. It's two hours of verbal aftermath. Maybe the
testosterone hysterics of ``That Championship Season'' were
fascinating and fresh in 1972, but these days they're pretty
bombastic.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, and yet. It takes some savvy acting to turn all this
wordy angst into something more than poetic poop, and acting is
what the Showtime version has going for it. Indeed, the cast of
heavyweights actually manages to make it worthwhile, particularly
Paul Sorvino, who also directed. Sorvino played one of the
basketball players (the amoral businessman) on the stage and in the
1982 movie adaptation, but this time out he takes the juicy role of
Coach, the demented father figure who tells the four men, ``You
boys are my real trophies.'' Sorvino puts a monomaniacal glaze
behind Coach's eyes as he tells them how to lead their lives,
delivering racist and anti-Semitic lines without a moment's pause.
But Sorvino also manages to milk a sense of tragedy out of his
pathetic character, who treats life like a competitive game,
desperately afraid to lose again after a childhood loss. He's
really in top form here.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent D'Onofrio also keeps the production alive, as the
wealthy strip miner who had an affair with a wife of the one of the
other men. D'Onofrio is one of our most underrecognized actors,
with a string of great performances that include ``Full Metal
Jacket,'' ``The Whole Wide World,'' and the classic subway episode
of TV's ``Homicide.'' His Phil Romano is a viper who needs to be
needed financially, a man whose loyalties shift with the political
wind. He's a big baby, which D'Onofrio makes abundantly clear in a
momentary facial expression after a rifle has been aimed at him. As
the cuckholded mayor, who needs Phil's money for his reelection
campaign, Tony Shalhoub is effective as a Mr. Nice Guy who's filled
with rage beneath his friendly veneer. And Terry Kinney from ``Oz''
is perfectly cowardly as James, the nervous man who wants to run
the mayor's campaign. Unfortunately, Gary Sinise is mostly wasted
in the role of Tom, the cynical alcoholic who can only speak the
truth among this group of liars. It's not a very original role.
</P>
<P>
   These are all electric stage performances, and they nearly jump
off the TV screen. When each character has his predictable
``moment,'' the actors give you something to chew on beside the
dramatic cliches. Unfortunately, Sorvino's directing instincts
didn't lead him to open up the story visually, to make it more
cinematic and less of a filmed play. The camerawork is fine, but
the claustrophic house set becomes a tedious Nowheresville early
into the second hour. By then, we already know all too well that,
20 years after their shining moment, these guys are doomed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
