<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3218 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-BATHHOUSES-HNS &LR;      06-04 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-BATHHOUSES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVISORY PANEL RECOMMENDS REOPENING GAY BATHHOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE CONSTANTINOU  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A health advisory panel recommended late
Thursday that the San Francisco Health Commission allow bathhouses
and private rooms in gay sex clubs to reopen, 15 years after they
were banned at the height of the AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   The 9 to 1 vote by the HIV Prevention Planning Council hardly
expressed deep support within the council, which makes policy
recommendations to the Health Commission. Seven panel members
abstained because they wanted to postpone the vote until the
council's next meeting. And nearly half of the council's 32 members
were absent.
</P>
<P>
   The council's recommendation went against the views of Dr. Mitch
Katz, director of the city's Department of Public Health. He urged
that bathhouses and private rooms in sex clubs continue to be
banned.
</P>
<P>
   Current policy permits gay sex clubs but requires that they
provide condoms and monitor sexual activity to prevent the spread
of the acquired immune deficiency syndrome. At the sex clubs, men
typically gather in large common rooms and have no privacy.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS is an affliction in which the human immunodeficiency virus
weakens the immune system, subjecting the body to serious
infection. The disease is most often spread through sexual contact,
sharing contaminated needles and infected blood products.
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of AIDS deaths and new HIV patients in San
Francisco has declined since 1984, Katz said the virus is still
spread by unsafe sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key question is which is safer: A bathhouse or sex club in
which there is constant monitoring, or no monitoring?''' Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   Two dozen speakers who appeared before the advisory council
voiced support for reopening the bathhouses and of allowing sex
clubs to provide private rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denying privacy does not prevent new infections,'' said David
Attyah, of Health Watch, a group of AIDS health advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monitoring merely relocates sex to other venues, precisely
because it drives away men who want anonymity, intimacy, or control
over a sexual encounter. These people end up in places that lack
the key ingredients to safer behavior: information, support and
condoms.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were deep divisions on the council, with some members
saying they needed time to digest the testimony of Katz and the
others.
</P>
<P>
   A. Toni Young was the most vehement proponent of waiting to
vote, and was cast the sole negative vote on the recommendation to
the Health Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But Maria Rinaldi, who made the motion for the council
recommendation, said that the meeting had been well-publicized, and
that ignoring the mandate of those who cared enough to show up was
insulting to the audience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1521EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3238 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PRIMAKOV-INTRI     06-04 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PRIMAKOV-INTRIGUE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 IN RUSSIA, ENDLESS INTRIGUES and CLUELESS LEADERS, BUT LIMITED &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Mikhail Gorbachev's
monthly column on world affairs. To publish as a ``separate buy''
article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from
one of these New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 c.1999 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Politics and power are inseparable; there is nothing new about
that. But it is policies that, in the final analysis, define the
nature of a government, the goals that it pursues and the interest
that it serves.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, the trend in many countries has been
to allow the prevalence of tactical, self-serving and even cynical
politics at the expense of responsible policy-making. This is
happening at a time when the world is changing rapidly and
fundamentally, when today's decisions could affect the future in
dramatic and defining ways. Hasty, thoughtless decisions have
already cost us dearly in a number of regions and even on a global
scale. The diagnosis of world politics today is very clear: The
patient is seriously ill.
</P>
<P>
   This disease has taken a particularly severe and acute form in
Russia. The political crisis here has become virtually permanent,
with reform its main victim. The attempt to solve overnight the
problems involved in the difficult transition from one system to
another has affected all aspects of Russia's life in the most
destructive ways.
</P>
<P>
   Politically bankrupt and clueless, Russia's rulers are flailing
about, rushing to extremes and changing ministers like gloves.
Endless intrigues serve to conceal continuous failure of policy.
Yevgeni Primakov and his cabinet are the latest victims of those
intrigues.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite clear from the start that President Yeltsin's
decision to dismiss the cabinet had nothing to do with his declared
intention of kick-starting the Russian economy. That was just a
pretext _ so much so that even Primakov's designated successor,
Sergei Stepashin, at first stated that he would continue the
economic policies of the previous cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   What, then, was the real reason behind the decision taken by the
small coterie of Yeltsin's close associates, whom many Russians
call the family politburo? One reason, which is clear at a glance,
was the Russian president's jealousy of Primakov's popularity and
well-deserved public support.
</P>
<P>
   Having taken over when Russia's economy was in ruins, Primakov
was able to keep the country from falling into the abyss and to
create an atmosphere of stability. And, although the life of the
average Russian has not yet improved, people were beginning to see
a ray of light, of hope that an end to chaos and some improvement
was in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, of course, resented the fact that while his own
approval ratings had plummeted to 2 percent or 3 percent, Primakov
had the support of about two-thirds of the populace, according to
opinion polls. Still, that reason, while obvious, was not the main
one.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov stood in the way of those in Russia who had illegally
accumulated tremendous wealth, who had grabbed vast amounts of
property through corruption and outright theft. It is those people,
fearful of losing what they had plundered, who orchestrated an
anti-Primakov campaign, declaring war on him in the media and in
the corridors of presidential power.
</P>
<P>
   By firing Primakov, Yeltsin forfeited Russia's real interests
and acted in the interests of himself and of a group concerned only
with its own future _ and with finding a successor who could make
that future secure and comfortable. A self-proclaimed ``guardian of
the constitution,'' Yeltsin is acting more like the guardian of the
property and safety of a corrupt group.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the president's actions have destabilized the
situation in the country. The fact that the State Duma, Russia's
parliament, approved the choice of new premier does not at all mean
that the government crisis is over.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is continuing, now in the form of a fierce struggle
for seats in the cabinet, levers of influence and control over
major financial flows. Stepashin, who did not want to appear as a
puppet in the hands of the president's entourage and the group of
crony capitalists, is being cut off from decision-making on these
matters.
</P>
<P>
   We see emerging from the shadows and put in key positions people
who don't care one bit about economic reform and even less about
democracy. The anti-corruption drive begun under Primakov has for
all intents and purposes been stopped, and indicted officials and
businessmen are being allowed to get away from justice.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Russia's final stretch to parliamentary elections later
this year and then the presidential election in 2000 will be even
tougher than it had to be. The Duma's approval of the new prime
minister's appointment was primarily meant to deprive Yeltsin of
any pretext for dissolving Parliament and perpetuating the regime
of one-man rule. I think that in doing so, the Duma acted properly.
The important thing now is where the leading Russian politicians
will go from here. They, and the political groups now being formed
around them, must act with a sense of utmost responsibility and
balance.
</P>
<P>
   Of great importance will be what Primakov decides to do. It
would be unfortunate if his dismissal and the insulting way he was
treated caused him to leave the Russian political arena. My advice
to him would be to give the entire situation serious thought. He
could retain his broad-based support. Significantly, he continues
to lead all opinion polls. If the elections were held today, he
would most probably be elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's Mayor Yuri Luzhkov has already offered Primakov a
partnership within the political group he is now creating.
</P>
<P>
   It is my considered opinion that the ``optimal way'' scenario
for Russia would involve amending the present constitution. We must
get rid of its authoritarian straightjacket. Prudent changes in the
constitution would strike a proper balance between the presidency,
a more authoritative and responsible cabinet of ministers and a
reasonably strong parliament. I continue to believe that within
such a structure of government, Primakov would be the best choice
for president and Luzhkov for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is capable of leaving behind the overly long and painful
stage of its ``start-up development.'' Responsible policies and
policy makers must replace its current strain of politics. And,
though conditions differ, many Western countries too could set for
themselves a similar goal.
</P>
<P>
   Once it is achieved, we could begin to address together the
challenges of the coming century.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __ Translated from the Russian by Pavel Palazchenko. &LR; __
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and a Nobel Peace Prize winner, heads the
Gorbachev Foundation for International Peace and lectures
frequently around the world on subjects related to post-Cold War
trends and politics.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3239 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PRIMAKOV-INTRI     06-04 1264
