<SLUG> BC-PREACHING-ALTERNATIVETEENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNICATING WITH `ALTERNATIVE'' TEENS IS ALL IN A SUNDAY'S WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAIME JORDAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Terry and Julie Ann Stephens weren't always
the Bible-toting do-gooders who teach youth Bible class at First
Baptist Church of Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, Terry Stephens was a drug pusher and Julie Ann
Stephens was an exotic dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Now they use their not-so-wholesome backgrounds to help youths
who are off the beaten path, not only spirituality, but also in the
way they are viewed by their peers.
</P>
<P>
   The Stephenses describe the youths who attend their class as
``alternative.'' Many fit the ``Goth'' image, with black clothes
and black hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like our class because it's not cliquey; everyone accepts
everyone the way they are,'' Julie Ann said. ``Obviously, for Terry
and I, no wonder we don't judge. We have no place to judge.''
</P>
<P>
   In light of the Columbine High School shootings, in which peer
acceptance may have been a factor, more church groups should adopt
an open-door policy, the Stephenses say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've turned kids who might not have come to a regular
church,'' Julie Ann said. ``Our kids, nobody expects them to be
perfect, and because nobody expects anything, they'll be open and
let it all out. Our kids are all dealing with drugs, sex and
prejudice. Other kids are worrying about, `I don't know if I'll
have a date for prom.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Terry Stephens, 35, has been open about his past
drug use makes his message a more credible testimonial for
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, felt like an outsider in the church, and his alienation
led him to find new friends, who led him to a seven-year affair
with drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he almost died, it wasn't until Terry prayed for
change that he stopped shooting up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would have thought I would have gotten off it when a guy
held a pistol to my head. You would have thought I would have
gotten off it when I laid in the hospital for four days with
hepatitis and 106.1-degree temperature and they thought it was
AIDS,'' he said. ``But that didn't do it. It was God, plain and
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Terry shares his testimony with the teens in his class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I surrendered my life to Christ to serve God years ago,'' he
said. ``I've staggered at times ... but God is using me now in a
tremendous way.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Terry's past is out in the open, very few church
members and only a handful of the youth know about Julie Ann's
background.
</P>
<P>
   But at 30, she still carries the emotional scars that came with
baring her body to strangers for money.
</P>
<P>
   And though she is reluctant to share her story as openly as her
husband does, she said her testimony does make her more credible,
especially with the girls in the class.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the cases where girls are kind of going on the wild side,
that's when it comes up,'' she said. ``I say, `Hey, I've been
there, done that, it's not worth it. You just don't do something
like that and it's all over. You do something like that, and the
memories last forever.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Stephenses use their life experiences to relate to the
youths in ways that more traditional Bible classes could not. And
out of that bonding have come several success stories, such as the
change that has taken place in David Howard, 20, who three years
ago was a skinhead who wore Nazi patches and terrified people.
</P>
<P>
   The first day the Stephenses met Howard, he had gone to the
church to fight with another teen. Terry Stephens stepped in the
middle and began praying for Howard. A year later, Howard was
saved.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is a leader in the church and recently married the
mother of his child. And though premarital sex is considered taboo
in Christian teachings, the Stephenses have focused on how far the
boy has come.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those who have changed their lives, the class is not
without its share of failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of our kids have been to prison,'' Julie Ann said.
``Obviously, we're not proud of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with me, the change was like night and day,'' she said.
``Nothing happened before I got saved. I used to say `I'm not going
to get saved because I like what I do.' I was not going to stop
dancing (because of) God. I liked the money, and I wasn't going to
stop. I see a lot of teen-agers who are like I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Curt Grice, a youth pastor at the church, said the couple has
had a positive effect on many youths.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've become a part of a lot of their lives, and they can
share the victory and the pain because they're not all happy
endings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
