<HEADLINE>
U.S. TRIES TO SMOOTH WAY FOR REFUGEES FROM KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANNIE NAKAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As the director of the State Department's
Refugee Admissions Office, Theresa Rusch is impresario for a vast
and far-flung operation that each year resettles tens of thousands
of people fleeing war and civil strife the world over.
</P>
<P>
   She was in San Francisco Thursday to publicize the department's
campaign to aid 20,000 ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, refugees
America has agreed to shelter until they can be safely returned to
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   For the 6,000 refugees from Kosovo already in the United States,
the international peace plan that was approved this week by
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and his government is only
the latest uncertainty in the chaotic lives of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next few days will be telling,'' Rusch said. ``Milosevic
agreed to many things in the past that have not come about.''
</P>
<P>
   Once processed at Fort Dix, N.J., the refugees are being flown
to their receiving cities at the rate of 100 per day. It might be
some time before any refugees can return, Rusch said, even with the
peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to do with how fast things move and how much
destruction has to be reversed,'' Rusch said. ``That's the big
question mark right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Army and police units have destroyed homes and villages
abandoned by the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, a province of Serbia,
which is the dominant state in Yugoslavia. In addition, the
refugees say soldiers and border guards confiscated their driving
licenses, passports and other identity papers as they fled the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Since World War II, more refugees have been relocated to America
than anywhere else in the world. Since 1980, more than 1.7 million
have been admitted to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   More than 800,000 people in Kosovo fled during the height of
reprisals by the Yugoslav military and police, and the bombing by
North Atlantic Treaty Organization nations that begin in March.
Some 28 nations have agreed to temporarily resettle some of the
refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the new refugees are going to New York,
New Jersey, Connecticut, Michigan, Wisconsin and Illinois, areas
with existing Albanian populations.
</P>
<P>
   Their reception is being handled by 10 agencies that are well
versed in helping refugees resettle.
</P>
<P>
   One, the International Rescue Committee, has resettled 45,000
refugees in the San Francisco Bay area since the IRC's first office
opened in here in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Like refugees the world over, these newcomers need housing, food
and medical attention. But people from Kosovo are different.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's new about them is that they really haven't had any time
to internalize what's happened to them,'' said Don Climent,
regional director of IRC in San Francisco. ``Everything's happened
to them in a very extreme and fast way. There's no time for
decompression.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees escaping war also bring up other issues, Climent said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people are resettled in a situation where war or civil
strife is unresolved, it carries with it some other dimensions _
people can feel guilty for having been saved,'' he said. ``Or they
are very concerned about the safety and whereabouts of their
relatives. So it brings on a sort of heightened anxiety for
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamie McLeod, regional director of IRC's San Jose office, said
she saw that in the recent arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a feeling of hopelessness in the situation
over there,'' McLeod said. ``These families are families we've all
heard about _ they had two minutes to leave, were put on trains,
they went through that whole experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
