<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$adv06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-STEMMED COSMOS FOR AN ARMFUL OF BEAUTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 6) 
(jt) 
 By GEORGEANNE BRENNAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cosmos, a reliable summer bloomer, is usually available in
garden centers. The plants are often part of the dwarf Sonata
series in shades of pink, lilac, rose, white or mixed.
</P>
<P>
   This is unfortunate, because one of the splendid characteristics
of cosmos is the extraordinary height and mass of bright green,
lacy foliage; waxy buds, and broad blooms that a single tiny seed
can produce. (There are 8,000 to an ounce.) The dwarf varieties
grow only 20 to 30 inches tall, but the standard varieties reach
four feet and more.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmos (Cosmos bipinnatus) was popular 30 years ago, when people
grew flowers from seed, rather than buying transplants for flower
beds. Today, however, the bedding plant business is booming, which
creates a problem for flowers like cosmos.
</P>
<P>
   Bedding plants, flower transplants that give quick color, sell
better if they are blooming, but standard cosmos grows too large to
be contained in a six-pack of plants until it blooms. In those
conditions, if it grows long enough to bloom, chances are it will
be too root-bound to be of much use once transplanted into the
garden.
</P>
<P>
   Pan American Seeds in Lompoc, Calif., found a remedy, breeding
Sonata, a dwarf cosmos that blooms in a six-pack and still performs
transplanted in the garden. In 1996, Sonata, in red, carmine and
pink, won the flower industry's respected Fleuroselect Quality
Award for its novelty, and it remains a strong seller.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, Sakata Seed, a large Japanese company
known for breeding specialty strains for commercial cut flowers,
introduced its Versailles series of tall cosmos in two colors,
carmine and pink eye, followed by blush pink and pink in 1993 and
white and mixed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   These are full-size plants, which grow to four feet tall,
starting to bloom at two feet. They are popular in the cut-flower
trade because of large clusters of flowers carried near the top of
the plant on long, strong stems rising above the foliage, but they
are rarely found in six-packs at garden centers.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmos, along with the more glamorous zinnias and dahlias, is a
member of the sunflower tribe, a subgroup in the Compositae or
Asteraceae family distinguished by their flowers. Each flower is a
group of small flowers arranged to give the appearance of a single
flower. The florets in the center are disk flowers, and the florets
around the outside, which carry showy, colorful petals, are ray
flowers. The ray flowers, which are usually sterile, bloom first,
and then the disk flowers bloom in a circular pattern from the
outside in.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmos, which are annuals, are closely related to the dahlia
and, like the dahlia, are native to Mexico. C. bipinnatus occurs in
shades from white to dark purple, but C. sulfureus, a plant one and
a half to two feet tall, with thicker foliage than C. bipinnatus,
produces red or bright yellow flowers. A number of novelty cosmos
are available through seed catalogs, including some with tubular
petals, picotee edges and a new soft yellow dwarf, billed as a
Sonata descendent.
</P>
<P>
   The hardy cosmos can be grown almost anywhere and needs little
care. It is important, however, to keep the flowers cut and to
remove dead blooms, not only to insure the continuing production of
new flowers, but also because a ragtag plant covered with spent
blooms makes it difficult to find lengths of fresh flowers to cut.
Cosmos is an excellent cutting flower and is valuable in
arrangements for its flowers, as well as for its lacy leaves and
tight buds, which act as fillers in bouquets and add texture.
</P>
<P>
   To grow cosmos from seed, scatter the seeds over a prepared bed
and cover them only a scant quarter of an inch. (Do not work
fertilizer into the soil at planting, nor add it later, because
cosmos grown in rich soil become very vegetative, leggy and
scraggly, producing little or no bloom.) Keep the ground moist
until germination occurs, in about seven days, then keep the top
foot of soil moist, but do not overwater. Overwatering is an enemy
of cosmos, particularly in warm humid areas, and can contribute to
root and stem rot.
</P>
<P>
   When the plants begin to fill and bloom, they will provide
armloads of cut flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Seed Sources  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cook's Garden (P.O. Box 535, Londonderry, Vt. 05148;
800-457-9703; free catalog) offers seven varieties, including
Versailles Mix and Sea Shells, which has fluted, tubular petals.
</P>
<P>
   Seymour's Selected Seeds (P.O. Box 1346, Sussex, Va. 23884;
803-663-3084; free catalog) has six varieties, including Yellow
Garden and Sweet Dreams, which is white with a deep pink face.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
