</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AIRPOWER (Washington) _ With a peace dear near in Kosovo,
military airpower advocates are claiming that sustained allied
bombing over two and a half months was the key factor in forcing
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to agree to halt the killing
and uprooting of ethnic Albanians in the province. We look at
lessons learned from the air campaign. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GO-HOME (Washington) _ Will the estimated 1.6 million
displaced residents of Kosovo go home once it is safe to do so? The
Clinton administration says the refugees are eager to. But more
than three years after implementation of the peace agreement in
neighboring Bosnia, only 32 percent of the 1.8 million Bosnians
uprooted by that conflict have returned to their homes. The key,
says the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, will be whether the
Kosovars feel secure. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ The Senate will soon take up
controversial Social Security ``lock box'' legislation already
passed by the House. It would put budget surpluses derived from
Social Security tax payments off limits to lawmakers. Clinton
administration officials and other critics call it a political
gimmick with many loopholes. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HURRICANES (Port Lavaca, Texas) _ The last hurricane to
strike the Texas Gulf Coast was in 1989, when Jerry, a Category 1
storm, hit Galveston Island. Since the early 1800s, there had never
been a 10-year period when the Texas coast has gone without a
hurricane hitting land, until now. And after a decade of coastal
boom, officials fear that many residents have never experienced a
storm and need to be prepared for the next one _ when it comes. By
RALPH WININGHAM.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-ISRAEL (Jezzine, Lebanon) _ We look at the unraveling of
the Israeli-backed militia in southern Lebanon _ the protectors of
Israel's border settlements _ and what it means for the people in
the area and the Israelis. By DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
