<HEADER>
A3310 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIBURN-AMATEURS-960(     06-04 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-AMATEURS-960(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIANIST OVERCOMES DRUG ADDICTION AND PRISON TERM TO COMPETE IN
CLIBURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMOND, Okla. _ The Steinway grand piano was the last thing to
go.
</P>
<P>
   He placed an ad in the Sunday edition of the Daily Oklahoman,
and four days later the piano sold for $14,500. It was worth about
$27,000.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Fisher didn't care at that point. He needed the money. And
when the final $9,000 check came from the buyer, Fisher and his
girlfriend took a taxi to the bank, then to their drug dealer and
then to the Marriott Hotel in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they checked out three days later, they had smoked
$1,300 worth of crack cocaine. Within a month, the entire 14 grand
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   That was June 1995. In October, Fisher was in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Orange jumpsuit, shorn hair, monthly visits from his mother:
This was Greg Fisher nine years after he left the University of
Missouri-Kansas City Conservatory, one recital shy of his master's
degree in piano performance.
</P>
<P>
   He had his excuses for leaving school: a bad breakup with a girl
he planned to marry, a struggling family business back home in
Edmond that needed a hand, the feeling that his blue-collar parents
and siblings considered his pursuit frivolous.
</P>
<P>
   So he packed his music books in cardboard boxes and went home to
help boost sales at AAA Edmond Glass &AMP; Mirror.
</P>
<P>
   He succeeded _ when hadn't he? _ and was looking for ways to
spend his windfall when a new girlfriend introduced him to cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   But that part of Fisher's life, the part without music, is over.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the 38-year-old Fisher will perform in the first
round of the Van Cliburn International Piano Competition for
Outstanding Amateurs. Just over 140 people applied, and of the 92
accepted, most make their livings as highly accomplished
professionals: the consul general of Brazil in Miami, the
philosophy lecturer at Cambridge, the ophthalmologist with perfect
pitch, the chief art critic from The New York Times, the public
policy professor and former staff member of the National Security
Council during the Kennedy administration. And on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Fisher installs window glass. He still sees a probation
officer once a month, and most of his relatives prefer
country-western to classical.
</P>
<P>
   But his musical resume and the list of pieces he has learned and
performed were enough to convince the Cliburn Foundation that he's
worthy of a shot _ though victory is less important to Fisher than
simply having made it this far.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, considering where I've come from, where I've been,'' he
says, ``I've already won.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Fisher lives in a small white house that he leases from his
parents in a middle-class section of Edmond. It's a five-minute
drive to the glass shop, where he works, and a three-minute drive
to the campus of the University of Central Oklahoma, where he is
studying, again, for his master's degree in piano.
</P>
<P>
   In November, he bought a 6-foot-1-inch Baldwin grand piano that
takes up most of his living room. He should have bought a car, he
says, but he bought the piano instead for $12,000, which he is
paying off in $300 monthly installments. These days, he gets around
in a white Dodge Ram van with ``AAA Edmond Glass &AMP; Mirror'' painted
on its sides.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher works mornings at the shop, alongside his mom, dad,
brother, sister and sister-in-law. He used to manage the front
office, but that was before the drugs and the jail time and before
Fisher had sacrificed the trust of his family. When his parents
took him back into the business, they told him he'd have to work
his way up from the bottom. So now Fisher installs auto glass. He's
gotten good at it, but the experience has been humbling.
</P>
<P>
   On a rainy Monday morning, Fisher replaces the driver's side
window of a Buick LeSabre. He sits on a red dolly wearing a blue
work shirt with ``Greg'' stitched onto a rectangular patch. He's
been here since 7 a.m., and his thick, square hands are grimy. Bud
Fisher watches over his son's shoulder, wearing a gimme cap on his
head and a tape measure on his belt. Greg's mother, Marlene, a
petite woman with a Sicilian temperament, nurses a plastic-foam cup
of coffee from the nearby Conoco station.
</P>
<P>
   The Fishers remain guarded, if hopeful, about their son's
recovery and his rededication to piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' Bud says later while prying a window out
of a school bus. ``Seems a shame to waste the talent.''
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoons, Greg Fisher attends class and then returns
home to practice. He sits at the Baldwin for six hours a day,
refining his competition repertoire. The pieces he's chosen
resonate with his personal experiences: Debussy's ``Ondine,'' named
for the mythological water nymph who lured men to their deaths
(Fisher says he's always been attracted to the wrong kind of
woman), and Liszt's ``Sposalizio,'' inspired by the composer's
viewing of Raphael's painting ``Betrothal of the Virgin'' (Fisher
says he owes a lot to his religious faith).
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
