<HEADER>
A3313 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIBURN-AMATEURS-2ndT     06-04 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-AMATEURS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
EDMOND, Okla.: religious faith). 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Piano is Fisher's therapy. He weeps and rages and loves through
the music he plays. He says he needs his audience to hear that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of me,'' he insists. ``It will always be part of me.
And it took me a long time to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Fisher hadn't taken a music lesson in 13 years when Jan Steele
called him last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Steele had been his first piano teacher in Oklahoma and taught
him from ages 14 to 19. She had followed the promising trajectory
of his academic career after he left the University of Central
Oklahoma (UCO) for Kansas City. Later, she had heard about his drug
addiction. She knew he had quit piano and was now urging him to
come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's what's missing in your life,'' Steele told
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   In September, he signed up for applied piano at UCO _ $300 for
two credit hours.
</P>
<P>
   The first months were frustrating. Fisher's fingers refused to
obey. His mind functioned sluggishly. ``I felt like a third-year
piano student,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   At Steele's instruction, Fisher relearned all the Chopin etudes
_ complex technique studies _ and the inspiration gradually
returned. In January, he committed to a full load of classes and to
completing his master's degree. And in May, 300 people, including
family members, watched Fisher perform with the UCO Orchestra, an
honor bestowed upon the music school's top students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like classical music,'' admits Fisher's sister, Linda
Leonard. ``The only time I like it is when I hear him play. Then it
takes on a whole different meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Music was Greg Fisher's first addiction. He was 8 when he
decided he wanted to pursue piano, though no one in the family
could figure out why. None of the relatives played an instrument.
No one listened to classical music except Fisher's maternal
grandmother, Catherine Monfre, a Van Cliburn fan. But Fisher
begged, and his mother relented. After all, Marlene had yearned for
music lessons as a child and had never had them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I originally wanted them to play country-western,'' Marlene
says of her children. ``It never entered my mind, classical.''
</P>
<P>
   The family lived in Milwaukee at the time: Marlene and Bud; Greg
and older sister Linda; Pat and Pam, the twins, younger by only 11
months. Bud delivered oil for Pennzoil before managing a glass
store and moving the family to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   By age 10, Fisher had won a partial scholarship to the Wisconsin
College Conservatory. But the lessons, instruments and travel
expenses still cost more than the family could afford at the time.
Marlene took a second job, waiting tables in addition to working at
a service station.
</P>
<P>
   Monfre thought her daughter was crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would get my mom aside and say, `Just have him drop it,'''
Fisher recalls. ```It's not going to serve us any benefit, and we
can't afford it. What do you think he's going to do, go to college
for piano or something?'''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Fisher broke out in hives for two months after his family moved
to Oklahoma. He was 14 at the time, and his piano teacher in
Milwaukee had wanted Fisher to continue studying under her; she
even offered to house the teen-ager. The stress overwhelmed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg was very quiet, he was introverted,'' Marlene says. ``The
other kids did fine, but Greg kept everything inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher landed with Steele and eventually won a full scholarship
to UCO. He was the first person in his family to attend college.
Two years later, he transferred to the University of
Missouri-Kansas City Conservatory, a much more competitive venue.
</P>
<P>
   His self-confidence plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the worst,'' Fisher confesses. ``I mean, I used to call
home and cry to my mom, `I want to come home. I'm the worst pianist
here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher nearly packed it in, but his professor, Richard Cass,
convinced him he was capable of catching up. Within two years,
Fisher had won the school's top award _ first place in the
concerto-aria competition _ and a first place in the Missouri Music
Teachers Association Graduate Honors Auditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people who come at piano from an intellectual
point of view, and they master it one way or another,'' Cass says.
``But Greg had a flair for it from the beginning. That's something
that can't be taught.''
</P>
<P>
   The breakup with his girlfriend came just before Fisher would
have started buckling down for his final master's degree recital.
Her parents didn't approve of the relationship and had refused to
pay for her education if she continued seeing him. So she broke it
off. Fisher was devastated and took it as a sign.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he wasn't meant to be here. Maybe the glass shop was a
better option.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1986, he left Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed,'' says Marlene, sitting in a back
room of the shop. ``I still am. I try not to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fisher excelled as a businessman. He worked 12- to 14-hour
days and all but forgot about piano. Sales at the shop rose, and
AAA Edmond Glass &AMP; Mirror moved to bigger quarters on the city's
main retail strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got busy, made lots of money, and everybody was happy,
happy, happy,'' Fisher says. Everyone but him.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher had been out of school for three years when he started
doing cocaine on the weekends. He liked the intensity of the high,
liked being able to forget the empty feeling that followed him
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Money was no problem. Fisher had enough to buy a Jaguar and a
ski boat and finally the Steinway. He rarely played at that point,
except when his girlfriend, an exotic dancer, encouraged him to
dabble. She would tape-record Fisher's occasional Henry
Mancini-like improvs and called his melodies ``angel music.'' She
also urged him to try crack. He was hooked after the first time.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
