<HEADER>
A3315 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLASTIC-RADIOS-ART-HN     06-04 1758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLASTIC-RADIOS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSICS IN PLASTIC: ANTIQUE RADIO COLLECTION PLEASES THE EYES, NOT
THE EARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By CATHY GORDON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Art dealer Thom Andriola is radical about radios.
</P>
<P>
   Not just any kind of radios.
</P>
<P>
   Classics in plastic.
</P>
<P>
   His collection of 250 plastic radios, from table-top models to
transistors, lines an entire wall of his Houston home in colorful,
flamboyant detail.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate-brown models made of the first synthetic plastic,
Bakelite, which was patented about 1910. Rare Catalin radios from
the late 1930s and mid 1940s in rich green, caramel and
butterscotch colors. Funky finds from the midcentury in tropical
Life Savers shades.
</P>
<P>
   Eye candy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just beautiful to look at,'' says Andriola, himself a
colorful statement in his royal blue shirt and matching shoes. His
Great Wall of Radios provides a visual history of the plastic radio
from the 1930s to the early 1970s. But don't stare at the
candy-colored Catalins too long. Their mouth-watering colors
confuse the senses.
</P>
<P>
   These are radios, after all. Boxes with components. Made to emit
sound.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, however, they sit here in warm chunks of color,
arousing the taste buds as if they were giant, delectable treats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catalin radios, especially, have such a richness to them.
They almost look like candy,'' says Andriola, owner of Houston's
New Gallery, which displays contemporary paintings and sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   While he cherishes the radios for their unique blend of
technology, art and style, you won't find them on display at his
gallery. This is a floor-to-ceiling private collection, started 14
years ago when his wife, Annette Wilzig, happened upon a little
brown Bakelite radio with a crack in its side.
</P>
<P>
   Wilzig, an assemblage artist, often peruses junk and antiques
shops for objects to use in her sculptures. She spotted the radio
among a sea of books at an antiques mall. Its side was stapled to
keep it from additional cracking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took pity on it. I had to have it. It needed me,'' says
Wilzig, who quickly snapped up the 1946 Farnsworth model, intending
to use it in one of her sculptures. But she adored its streamlined
art deco style and loved it unconditionally for what it was: ``a
permanently punctured little Bakelite radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Today that hapless little radio with staples in its side is
still her favorite, despite a collection of rare, pristine-looking
models that share shelf space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call me sentimental,'' Wilzig says. ``It was our first. And
besides, I love imperfect things.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Bakelite radios are represented in the couple's
collection, as are 20 rare Catalin radios. It did not escape
Andriola's attention when Time magazine recently named Belgian
chemist Leo Baekeland, the inventor of Bakelite, as one of this
century's greatest minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody did their homework,'' says Andriola. ``Bakelite is
the first pure man-made plastic. It's probably the most important
invention for almost everything that's happened in this century as
far as economics goes, as far as industrialization goes. The entire
concept of transistorizing and computerizing _ it was really
plastic that made these things possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, the radio was as important to most households as
television is today. Up to this time, wooden radios were most
common. But a society strapped by the Great Depression looked to
Bakelite as an excellent, cost-effective way to simulate the look
of wood. Along with Catalin, these plastics revolutionized the way
radios and other objects could be made.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MANY COLOR POSSIBILITIES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bakelite and Catalin are of nearly identical chemical
composition, both being made of varying amounts of phenol and
formaldehyde mixed with a catalyst. Bakelite is a molding powder,
and Catalin is a casting resin. Catalin, clear or tinted to almost
any color or mixture of colors, was responsible for the marbleized
plastic effect that became so popular in radio cabinets in the '30s
and '40s.
</P>
<P>
   These brightly colored Catalin radios with modern styling were
considered ahead of their time. Some Catalin radios oxidized into
completely different colors over the years. For instance, an ivory
Catalin radio becomes a butterscotch color with age, while blue
melds into a green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, this Fada Bullet radio is blue,'' says
Andriola, holding up a green-looking radio that shows hints of its
true colors under light.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CATALIN FADA BULLET RADIOS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among Andriola's favorites are four Catalin Fada Bullet radios,
named for their distinctive shapes. The Fada Bullet's overall
styling was a radical departure from its boxy predecessors, and it
came in a variety of color combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Andriola can recite model numbers, production dates and
historical facts about the radios with ease, but don't ask him
about a radio's guts. He couldn't care less if a radio works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even tried listening to them. I'm just interested in
their beauty and great design,'' Andriola says. ``It's the idea
that these radios represent the last kind of eccentric design you
see that was mass-produced in America. That's what's really great
about them. A lot of them probably work, but I wouldn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Andriola and his wife are not follow-the-pack collectors.
</P>
<P>
   They started collecting radios long before it was in vogue, long
before books were written on the subject and long before prices
went up and up and up, although Andriola prefers not to reveal the
collection's worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the collection is worth way more today than we would ever
even think of paying for it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   While a rare Catalin radio costs more than $2,000 today,
Andriola says he paid from $150 to $900 for his Catalin radios.
</P>
<P>
   Radios were competing for shelf space in the couple's home a
decade before auctions on the Internet made such collecting
possible with the click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When others get on the train, we get off,'' says Andriola, who
admits their zest has been somewhat zapped ``by everyone coming on
board.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple preferred collecting when radios were cheaper and
finding them was a challenge. ``It's all about the thrill of the
hunt,'' Andriola says.
</P>
<P>
   And hunt they did.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Texas antiques or junk shops were of much help _ at
least not at first.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TEXANS NOT BIG ON PLASTIC &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of collecting has really been a challenge because we
discovered that plastic radios apparently were not that popular in
Texas back when they were new,'' Andriola says. ``We'd go into
antique places and say, `Do you have any radios?' They'd show us
wooden radios. We'd say, `No, no, no. Plastic radios.' They looked
at us like we were insane. `Plastic radios from the '30s or '40s.
Who'd even want one?'''
</P>
<P>
   The couple's fascination with plastic radios from the '50s and
'60s is evident, too. These radios make a splash with loud colors
and emblematic dials.
</P>
<P>
   A 1959 turquoise-and-ivory radio by Trav-ler with its
cartoonlike biomorphic shape and Mercedes Benz-like dial, is one of
Andriola's favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Midcentury Crosley radios, made to match the refrigerators in
colors such as avocado green, look ready to roll with their blaring
automobile motifs.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the James Bond radio. Not the proper name for this
late 1950s RCA Victor model, but it seems to fit with its sleek
look and hip dial on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my nickname for it. You can just picture it next to his
bed. It's a gentlemen's radio,'' says Wilzig.
</P>
<P>
   The display of ceiling-to-floor radios impresses visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the UPS guy comes or somebody who's not expecting it,
they say, `Whoa!' Then they start pointing all over the place, and
it's deja vu. Like, `Oh, my grandmother had that one,''' says
Wilzig. ``Also, the transistors. It's like, `Hey, I had that
transistor in high school.'''
</P>
<P>
   Who can resist a transistor? Andriola can't.
</P>
<P>
   Transistors make up a large part of the collection these days.
The story of this miniaturized sound box, perfected by Japanese
technology, is represented in a bevy of brands in varying colors,
grilles and futuristic motifs that epitomized American culture.
</P>
<P>
   Andriola's latest find? An early Toshiba pocket-size transistor
called the Bathroom Scale because it resembles, well, a bathroom
scale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TRANSISTORS APPROPRIATE HERE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's fitting that Andriola should include transistors in his
collection. After all, Houston is the transistor's birthplace. In
July 1954, engineers from Houston-based Texas Instruments met with
counterparts from an Indianapolis electronics firm to brainstorm
about this top-secret project, hoping to have the first small
all-transistor radio in stores by Christmas. The radio was dubbed
the Regency TR-1. While it didn't set the American mass market on
fire, Japan's efforts with the miniaturized radios soon did.
</P>
<P>
   One of Andriola's favorite transistors is Sony's first
commercially exported pocket-transistor, the TR-63, circa 1957, in
red with a silver grille and gold dial.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Sony transistor sold for $1,000 on the Net,'' he says.
``Just a few years ago, you could find that particular one for,
like, $25.''
</P>
<P>
   Andriola is also nostalgic about a 1957 black Arvin transistor
with a gold-and-black abstract applique on its grille, the first he
collected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my segue to pull transistors into the collection. It
seemed to fit with its look of abstract expressionism that was so
popular back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Andriola and his wife say they aren't actively looking to expand
their collection. But they still keep a discriminating eye peeled
for that rare radio at the right price (preferably pocket-size
because space is lacking) that might fit the mix.
</P>
<P>
   After all, they know their plastics. Wilzig keeps a large,
leather-bound album of vintage advertisements for all kinds of
plastics, Catalin and Bakelite included.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can almost sniff it out. I've been known to track down a
woman a block away because I can hear her Bakelite bangle bracelets
clanking,'' says Wilzig, who also has a collection of rare Bakelite
jewelry. She reaches behind some radios to retrieve a 2-inch round
rod of bright red Catalin. A rod of Catalin like this was used to
make things like backgammon game pieces, she explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like with the radios. So delicious-looking. It's
like a big cherry Life Savers stick. Hard to believe a material can
look this yummy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
