<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3317 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIBURN-AMATEURS-3rdT     06-04 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-AMATEURS-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
EDMOND, Okla.: first time. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marlene knew something was wrong. Her son, the former
workaholic, would leave work for a lunch break and never come back.
He had run through $50,000 in savings in six months and once begged
his brother for an emergency $400 loan, swearing that his dealer
would shoot him if he didn't pay on time.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1995, Fisher held a garage sale, selling furniture and
dishes to support the couple's $400-a-day habit. In May, the
Steinway went.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a no-brainer at that point,'' he says. ``I was in a
self-destructive mode.''
</P>
<P>
   That fall, Fisher hit bottom, emotionally and financially. When
he broke into a house and was arrested on a felony burglary charge,
he was almost relieved. The judge sentenced him to five years' jail
time and five years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Prison was humiliating and cathartic. Fisher says he experienced
a spiritual awakening six weeks after being jailed. When he would
awake drenched in sweat from withdrawal-induced nightmares, he
would turn to the Bible for solace. After four months, his mother
started visiting and could not believe the change in him. Other
family members started coming, too.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months into his sentence, the state transferred Fisher to a
work camp in Walters, Okla. He made $7 a month helping to build a
nearby church. In his spare time, he led Bible studies and played
the piano during Sunday services.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven months later, in June 1997, Bud Fisher drove to Walters
to bring his son home.
</P>
<P>
   The first month back at the shop, Fisher worked alone painting
the outside of the building. Interacting with his family,
especially his siblings, was painful. But the tension has eased
since he recommitted to piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has helped focus him,'' says Fisher's sister Linda. ``It's
boosted his self-esteem and hopefully given him some sense of
accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher believes he owes his recovery to faith; he doesn't take
his talent for granted anymore. It's God-given and God can take it
away, he says.
</P>
<P>
   When Steele presented him with the announcement of the amateurs
competition, that, too, seemed like a divine gift. ``He'll tell
you, it's like God opened up this contest just for him,'' Marlene
says.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other 142 people who applied, Fisher sent the Cliburn
Foundation $50, a black-and-white photograph of himself and his
music resume, brief compared with many of the others. Like 91 of
them, he fit the requirements of being a serious pianist, over 30,
who did not play professionally.
</P>
<P>
   He was on his way to Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The Cliburn event has focused Fisher more than anything since he
left graduate school. He even returned to Kansas City for some
refresher sessions with former professor Cass, whom he hadn't seen
in 13 years. They are polishing his Chopin ``Ballade in g minor,
Opus 23,'' and tinkering with Debussy's ``Feux d'Artifice,'' or
``Fireworks.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning the amateurs competition would mean $2,000 and perhaps
the chance to perform with some orchestras around the country. It
would probably assure Fisher admission to the doctoral program of
his choice and perhaps secure him a future teaching position at the
university level.
</P>
<P>
   Winning would be nice, but it's beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   When Marlene Fisher saw her son perform with the UCO Orchestra
in May, she cried. She videotaped the concert and took it with her
to Milwaukee for his grandmother to see.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mother's Day weekend, and as the two women watched the
tape together, they beamed with pride.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Fisher needs no other reason than that to keep playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes everything worthwhile,'' he says. ``It makes
everything OK.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
