<HEADER>
A3330 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     06-04 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUMBEL GRUMBLE, MAD ABOUT HAIR, AND OTHER READER THOUGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next up: Frank Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime reader, first-time complainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am unfortunate enough to be one of those evil white males
that seem to concern you so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh. Frank is responding to an 825-word analysis of Bryant
Gumbel's return to morning television, 22 words of which asked
whether Gumbel's less-than-reputable reputation had anything to do
with what I see as a societal perception of self-assured black men
being seen as ``cocky'' and ``pompous.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank's issue: We should see folks on an individual basis. Not
by race, not by attire, not by beliefs. ``I don't like pompous
people whether they are black or white, and that's why I don't like
Bryant Gumbel or Peter Jennings,'' said Clarke, an Arlington,
Texas, resident, who added, ``Come to think of it, I probably
wouldn't like YOU if we ever had the misfortune to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Clarke, who sees us all on an individual basis. Not by
race, not by attire, and certainly not based on beliefs that aren't
on par with his own.
</P>
<P>
   Other readers also had something to say about Gumbel, the former
``Today'' co-host who will take over a retooled morning
infotainment show at CBS on Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot went like this: ``Who cares,'' said caller Susanne
Lenny. ``I watch CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   Many responded to Sunday's ``Best of ...'' package to wrap up
the season. E-mails ranged from ``You're brilliant'' for picking
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' as top series to ``You're joking,
right?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Joust: It's a bunch of whiny kids pontificating on sex.
Why they want it, why they don't want it. It's sophomoric. It's
wasteful. It's nauseating.''
</P>
<P>
   It's ``Dawson's Creek''?
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Elston: ``The so-called evil menaces, the ghouls and
other out-of-this-world creatures ... they're fake and unrealistic.
And the girls can't act.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that ``Charmed''?
</P>
<P>
   Most began like this: ``I would like to compliment you on your
excellent taste.''
</P>
<P>
   (Best to mention here that I picked ``Two of a Kind,'' the
sitcom with the Olsen twins, as a can't-miss hit, thought
``Brimstone'' had possibilities and ``The Hughleys'' didn't.
``Two'' and ``Brimstone'' are gone; ``The Hughleys'' returns. Oh
well.)
</P>
<P>
   Cathy R. Atkinson was speaking of ``La Femme Nikita,'' the dark,
moody drama about a ruthless, underground outfit of assassins that
I ranked No. 4 for the season. ``I consider the show to be one of
the best-kept secrets on television,'' Cathy e-mailed. ``And I'm
thrilled when somebody points that out, and gives new viewers the
idea that maybe `LFN' isn't the typical fare for the USA network.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe? Airing right before ``LFN'': ``Silk Stalkings'' soft-porn
masquerading as a police drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' is appointment TV for Clyde L. and
Stephanie K. Harris. ``Bet we are the only couple in their 50s who
watch and enjoy the show, in Whitney, Texas. Any takers?'' the
e-mailers wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   Also on their menu: ``7th Heaven,'' ``The X Files,''
``Pretender'' and ``Profiler.'' But in ``Buffy,'' ``The characters
are realistic. We know. We were among the nameless faces in the
school halls. A cousin of my wife who was popular at school denied
that he was related to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Charity, a k a ``Taygeta,'' thinks there's a certain appeal to
Buffy being on a smaller, underdog network, particularly in the age
of the Internet. ``As you mentioned, `Buffy' is a reflection of the
high school outcast, and in the sense of Internet users, therein
lies the `Buffy' fan base,'' she e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Forrest Puckett responded to the analysis of ``Home
Improvement'' and ``Mad About You,'' sitcoms ending their long
runs.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Mad's'' Helen Hunt: ``She drove me up the wall with the
continual flipping of her hair. So I got so I counted the seconds
to the next flip instead of watching the plot.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Home's'' Tim Allen: ``His grunting, barking, simulated body
functions, etc., to me was a huge turnoff ... Was he auditioning
for the part of cheetah on the next Tarzan episode?''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't stop there. On ``Walker, Texas Ranger's'' Chuck
Norris: ``Two or three days' growth of whiskers ... This guy's like
the clone of the dad on `The Simpsons.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Forrest, reminding us all that the quality of one's acting
doesn't mean much, also gripes about a ``really good actor'' who
has ``protruding teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Seems Forrest finds that distracting as well.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't say which actor. I didn't ask.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
