<HEADER>
A3332 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-PROFILING-HN     06-04 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-PROFILING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC LAWYER FILES SUIT OVER RACIAL PROFILING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VENISE WAGNER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The American Civil Liberties Union has filed a
federal lawsuit on behalf of a San Jose lawyer who says the
California Highway Patrol violated his civil rights when officers
stopped him and other Hispanics allegedly because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, the CHP pulled over Rodriguez and at
least five other Hispanic drivers on the Pacheco Pass portion of
Highway 152 while carrying out its federally funded
drug-interdiction program, ``Operation Pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed Thursday, charges that this stop was standard
CHP practice in which ``suspicious'' minority drivers are stopped
for minor traffic violations as a pretext for searching their cars
for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was business as usual for the California Highway Patrol,''
said Michelle Alexander, director of the ACLU's Racial Justice
Project and one of the lawyers representing Rodriguez. ``They
cruise the freeways looking for excuses in the form of minor
traffic violations. Victims are searched and treated as criminals,
even when there is no probable cause. (Rodriguez's) sole misfortune
was being Latino on a California highway.''
</P>
<P>
   The CHP released a statement in response to the suit saying it
has policies prohibiting racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the ACLU has announced the filing of a lawsuit
alleging this violation of civil rights based on racial profiling
should not infer that this has actually occurred in the CHP,'' said
CHP Commissioner Dwight (Spike) Helmick. ``The CHP, as alleged by
the ACLU, does not engage in race-based stops ...''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is one of the first major legal challenges to
alleged race-based law enforcement operations in California. To
determine how pervasive race-based profiling is in law enforcement,
the ACLU led a campaign pushing the state Legislature to adopt laws
that require officers to document the race of drivers they stop.
The state Senate passed the ``driving while black or brown''
measure this week.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, Maryland, Massachusetts, New Jersey, Rhode Island, and
Virginia adopted similar legislation earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., recently reintroduced
legislation that would require the U.S. attorney general to study
police stops nationwide to determine if the police are using racial
profiling in making traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Pipeline is a national program administered by state
patrol agencies designed to yield drug arrests through a high
volume of searches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's law enforcement by hunch,'' Alexander said. ``These
tactics of engaging in pretext stops are totally ineffectual and
have a discriminatory impact on people of color.''
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU and Rodriguez are asking the courts to prohibit racial
profiling in all CHP operations. They also want law enforcement
agencies to begin collecting data on those stopped.
</P>
<P>
   On June 6, 1998, Rodriguez said he was driving with an associate
on Pacheco Pass, a roughly 15-mile stretch of Highway 152 south of
San Jose, when he noticed CHP officers pulling over dark-skinned
Hispanic men, one after another.
</P>
<P>
   They photographed the stops and were eventually pulled over
themselves, purportedly for driving with headlights on and for
touching the yellow dividing line, the lawsuit states. Headlights
are required on that stretch of Highway 152.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said his car was searched and that an officer
eventually apologized for the delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous,'' Rodriguez said. ``I thought that the way he
was conducting himself was illegal. I felt helpless. Essentially,
on the highway they're the law and if they are abusing or
mistreating you, you don't have any recourse. At least not on the
highway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
