<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3339 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-KLA-0605-COX     06-04 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-KLA-0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KLA AGREES NOT TO SHOOT WITHDRAWING SERBS, BUT STILL REFUSING TO
DISARM
 &HT;    650&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-CLINTON-0605.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Representatives of the rebel army fighting to
liberate Kosovo from Serb control said Friday they will continue
their campaign until they see Serb forces pulling out.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Liberation Army, however, said it will not impede the
Serbs once they begin to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never attack anybody who's running away,'' said Jakup
Krasniqi(CQ), the KLA's chief spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But he was not clear about what immediate role the KLA intends
to play in Kosovo, the southern province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's
dominant republic. The rebel army has agreed to demilitarize once a
peace plan is implemented but not disarm, indicating that its
members intend to hang on to their weapons even after a peace deal
is signed. The KLA sees itself as the potential core of an ethnic
Albanian security force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Albanian population, they want their own army that will
give them security in the future,'' Krasniqi said.
</P>
<P>
   This could become a major sticking point because the Serbs
consider the KLA a band of terrorists that must surrender its arms
once a peace plan is implemented.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Krasniqi expressed skepticism of the new
peace plan and a deep distrust of Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, the leader of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic has agreed many times to many things and we still
are waiting for him to keep his word,'' Krasniqi said. ``Maybe it
is another maneuver to play for time.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic last year agreed to a plan to withdraw his troops from
Kosovo and then later ignored it, prompting NATO to begin bombing
of Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Also, KLA political leader Hashim Thaci(CQ) accused Serb troops
of attacking civilian and military targets early Friday with
grenades and other weapons in at least three regions in Kosovo
province. Thaci describes himself as the president of the
provisional government of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic on the one hand is declaring he is in favor of peace
and he is accepting the accord,'' Thaci told reporters at the
European Union summit in Cologne, Germany. ``But on the other hand
he is doing the opposite on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serb-dominated Yugoslav government on Thursday accepted a
plan envisaging a withdrawal of its forces from war-ravaged Kosovo
and deployment of an international peacekeeping force to ensure the
return of hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA says the peace plan approved Thursday by the Yugoslav
Parliament means little until the international community irons out
the details, however.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the KLA, which has been fighting Serb soldiers,
police and paramilitary gangs for more than a year, objects to
allowing even a small force of Serb policemen to remain in Kosovo,
Krasniqi said. The current plan calls for a small force remaining
to police border checkpoints and such.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops are expected to form the core of the international
peacekeeping force, but Russia's special envoy to the Balkans,
Viktor Chernomyrdin, has said Russian forces will be under separate
command from Moscow and will not take orders from NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to include a significant force of Russian troops
also is a problem for the rebel army, Krasniqi said. ``They have to
move under NATO control, because at the moment the Russians are
under Serb control.''
</P>
<P>
   Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli Majko, who is closely allied
with the KLA, also opposes the Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any foreign military presence in Kosovo outside the control
and management of NATO would establish a premise for permanent
conflicts in the region and for the division of Kosovo,'' Majko
said. ``The government of Albania considers that the peacekeeping
force in Kosovo should be under the unique command of NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees reacted with reservation. Sabra Jmahone, who lives with
his family at the U.S.-built Camp Hope, listened to the news Friday
morning on a transistor radio outside his tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must see,'' he said. ``But we have heard these words
before. We must see it, see the NATO troops in Kosovo, see the
Serbian troops and police go. Then, God willing on that day, I will
go home.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The KLA, which wants Kosovo to become a separate country, has
indicated it will accept an arrangement that removes Kosovo from
Serb control and places it within the Yugoslav federation. This
would provide an opportunity for the province to seek independence
more easily.
</P>
<P>
   KLA officials in recent days have said they were making great
strides in their fight against Serb forces near the Yugoslav border
with Albania. Some have suggested privately that they believed they
were getting close to capturing a Kosovar town of Prizren. Western
military observers have been skeptical of the KLA's claims of
success. There is no independent confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the KLA has been flooded with volunteers,
including Americans who have been given basic training and handed
guns before being deployed at the front.
</P>
<P>
   Krasniqi also took a swipe at Thaci's rival, Ibrahim Rugova, who
has held the title president of the Republic of Kosovo for seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova is seen by many Albanians as too moderate in his push for
an independent Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have not been fighting the real enemy, the Serbs,
but instead have been building their careers,'' Krasniqi said in a
clear reference to Rugova.
</P>
<P>
   The deepening rift between the men is seen by Western officials
as a potentially damaging problem for Kosovo that must be resolved
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
