<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3340 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRINIDAD-HANGINGS-060     06-04 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRINIDAD-HANGINGS-0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRINIDAD HANGS THREE CONVICTS; FIRST EXECUTIONS IN NEARLY FIVE
YEARS
 &HT;    400&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Trinidad and Tobago led three convicts bound by
straight-jackets to the gallows Friday, where they were hanged
shortly after dawn, the first in a string of nine executions to be
carried out by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The executions were the first by the twin-island Caribbean
nation in nearly five years.
</P>
<P>
   The hangings are being staggered because each convict must hang
from the gallows for at least an hour to make certain they are
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Death penalty opponents feared the move would open the
floodgates to dozens of other hangings throughout the Caribbean,
where former British colonies have vowed to go forward with such
executions despite mounting opposition from Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we feel this is going to become a trend in the
Caribbean,'' said Sarah DeCosse, an expert on the Caribbean for
Human Rights Watch in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly oppose the death penalty,'' she added. ``Hangings
are a cruel and unusual punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that Cuba _ a communist island that carries out
executions with a firing squad _ is the only other country in the
Caribbean to carry out an execution so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Trinidad has pledged to press forward with as many as 85
hangings over the next several months. Other nations, too, plan to
resume hangings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People deserve a severe punishment when they commit a severe
crime,'' said Barbados Attorney General David Simmons, a proponent
of hangings.
</P>
<P>
   Violent crime in the Caribbean, much of it drug-related, has
left most residents in favor of capital punishment, emphasizing
that the relatively small size of the region means everyone shares
the impact of even the slightest rise in crime.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad and Tobago hanged reputed drug lord Dole Chadee and two
henchman Friday for the 1994 murders of a family of four in a drug
dispute. Three other members of Chadee's gang were to be executed
on Saturday; three others on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   According to Amnesty International, which petitioned Trinidad to
halt the hangings, there are about 250 convicts on death row in
English-speaking Caribbean nations, with a population of 5 million
_ one of the highest rates in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Britain banned hangings in 1991 in its five Caribbean
territories, but they remain on the books in all 12 former British
colonies in the Caribbean. Those former colonies maintain loose
ties with Britain as members of the commonwealth, and recognize the
British monarch as head of state.
</P>
<P>
   Hangings were discontinued throughout much of the Caribbean,
though, in the 1980s in response to protests from human-rights
groups.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, nations have taken steps to change their
justice systems and constitutions, as well as break long-standing
ties with international appeals bodies, so that the death penalty
can be carried out more easily.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, justice ministers from more than a dozen
countries meeting in Grenada are completing a plan for a Caribbean
court to replace London's Privy Council.
</P>
<P>
   That council, which has final say on legal appeals in the
region, drew outrage from Caribbean leaders in 1993 when it ruled
that it was inhumane to execute people who had waited on death row
more than five years.
</P>
<P>
   That ruling virtually eliminated hangings since appeals often
drag on for anywhere from five to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The council had strongly criticized Trinidad for its last
hanging _ of murderer Glen Ashby in 1994 _ because authorities
performed the execution only hours after lawyers revealed plans to
appeal to London.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
