<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KUKES-$ADV05 _ KUKES, Albania _ In the cool springtime
mornings, acrid smoke from the garbage dump hangs close to the
ground. The water supply, now rationed, is low and only the lucky
few who rose before the sun will have showers. Nearly everywhere is
the rank odor of open sewage. So begins the day for more than
100,000 refugees and 25,000 locals in Kukes, a ramshackle town
famous as the home to Kosovo's dispossed. A profile of a poor town
hosting destitute refugees. (Holmes, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   With information for a locator map. EDs: MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JACKSON _ ATLANTA _ Jesse Jackson calls for release of
Australian CARE workers, convicted on espionage charges in
Yugoslavia, at a press conference in Atlanta. Malcolm Fraser, vice
president of CARE International and former Prime Minister of
Australia, and Peter Bell, president of CARE USA, also take part.
(Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON _WASHINGTON _ His foreign policy under increasing
fire just days ago for ``mishandling'' the Kosovo crisis, experts
say the Serb acquienscence to the peace plan is a much-needed
feather in Clinton's cap. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA _ TIRANA, Albania _ A primay x factor in the
international peace plan to halt the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia is
the disarming of the Kosovo Liberation Army. Will the KLA rebels
who have been fighting the Serb military forces all along adhere to
the Rambouillet proposal? And what are the latest reactions from
the Kosovar refugees here as the absorb the news first-hand from
radio broadcasts? Developing. (Roughton, Cox News Service) WITH
PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO _ CNN allowed to enter Kosovo. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TRINIDAD-HANGINGS _MIAMI _ Trinidad and Tobago carried out two
hangings on Friday, the first of a string of nine executions to be
completed by Monday. These are the first executions in the former
British colony in five years. Experts say the hangings could lead
to the execution of dozens of other convicts throughout the
Caribbean. Britain, meanwhile, has been putting heavy pressure on
the Caribbean to end the death penalty. Developing. (Emling, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DRUGS _ MEXICO CITY _ A fresh round of scandalous
allegations about Mexican politicians _ including President
Zedillo's secretary _ are intruding on the annual U.S-Mexico
Binational Commission meeting in Mexico City Friday. U.S. anti-drug
czar Gen. Barry McCaffrey virtually dismissed press reports of
confidential investigations into possible drug trafficking by
President Zedillo's secretary and Carlos Hank Gonzalez, one of
Mexico's wealthiest men and a two-time cabinet member. McCaffrey
said if the United States had very strong evidence of guilt, it
would have taken it to Mexican authorities. The commission is
expected to discuss how anti-drug efforts are going, as well as
immigration and pollution problems. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 6:30 p.m. EDT
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GORE-RELIGION _ WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore is usually
thought of as a politician who understands science he began talking
of plans to ``publicly emphasize his faith in God'' and getting
government to work with ``faith-based organizations'' on policy
goals. But Gore, a former divinity student, said at a luncheon last
week that his religious ideals and government service have never
been separate in his mind. (Shepard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Moving Thursday in (w) Washington, (p) politics and (l)
lifestyle categories for release Saturday, June 5.
</P>
