<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: It's manners that matters
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There's nothing so proper as a fancy restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want to impress the head waiter, forget about
greasing his palm. Better you use a slick tongue.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean you have to lick his hand, like a dog. Just the
opposite. He'll be eating out of yours, with the right words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get to'' are the right words. Leastwise, they were for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pardon me for asking,'' the head waiter said, after seating me
at a table that had been reserved by a friend, who hadn't yet
arrived. ``But what part of the country are you from?''
</P>
<P>
   ``East Texas,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell from the way you talk,'' he said, smiling. ``I'm
from Georgia myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I get to Atlanta from time to time,'' I said, ``and always
enjoy visiting there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure like the way you say 'get to,''' he said, all the more
friendly.
</P>
<P>
   A little bit of down home goes a long ways for a Southerner a
long way from home.
</P>
<P>
   But I couldn't help asking.
</P>
<P>
   ``How'd you wind up so far North?'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for the opportunity,'' he said, shrugging as if to excuse
himself. ``A bunch of Yankees open up a fine restaurant, but they
have to pay good money for a genteel fellow from the South who
knows how to treat customers with hospitality.''
</P>
<P>
   We both got a good laugh out of that. But it's true. Good
manners are inbred in the South, despite the inbreeding.
</P>
<P>
   And I told him this story that had been passed along to me by an
old friend from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   I forget the exact names and places, but in this particular
county _ way north of the gnat line, to be sure _ a ne'er-do-well
had managed to marry into a prominent family a couple of
generations back.
</P>
<P>
   The youngsters who had grown up since then on either side of the
family _ call them the Gotrocks and the Hadnots _ never thought
twice about it. The old folks of the prominent family had never
gotten over it.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that a couple of cousins, a young man and woman, were
visiting in the home of the aged matriarch of the Gotrocks lineage,
and she was regaling them with one story and then another about old
times not forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   But her memory wasn't what it once was, and she faltered
occasionally in trying to recall exact details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see, now,'' she said, breaking off in the middle of a
story. ``For the life of me, I can't remember what year that was.''
</P>
<P>
   She pondered a moment and then added:
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm pretty sure it was the same year that the Hadnots
burned their house.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man couldn't help himself. Turning to his cousin, he
asked, as if in passing, ``Wasn't your grandmother a Hadnot?''
</P>
<P>
   The woman, trying to keep a straight face, nodded. ``Yes, as a
matter of fact, she was.''
</P>
<P>
   The matriarch never missed a beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, back then,'' she said, dismissing the subject with
a dainty wave of a withered hand, ``everybody was burning their
house.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing so fancy as proper manners.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.; web page, http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
