<HEADER>
A3347 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUPPIE-ERADICATION-HN     06-04 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUPPIE-ERADICATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURAL FRICTION ARISES IN SAN FRANCISCO NEIGHBORHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EMILY GURNON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The real turf war in San Francisco's Mission
District has nothing to do with young gangs staking out their
particular corners. This is a conflict between the rich and the
poor, between those who can afford to own property and those who
can't.
</P>
<P>
   Property owners vowed to rally Sunday against what they called
``hate crimes'' targeted at their cars, homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only people left that it's OK to hate, politically _
successful Caucasians who drive nice cars,'' said Samantha Spivack,
a three-year resident of the area. She was referring to the series
of flyers posted in the Mission District over the last several
months advocating vandalism to cars and property owned by
``yuppie'' newcomers to the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to read these posters and not feel a little
threatened,'' Spivack said.
</P>
<P>
   And police were investigating the so-called Mission Yuppie
Eradication Project, which produced the flyers.
</P>
<P>
   One flyer read: ``This yuppie takeover can be stopped and turned
back. We can drive those cigar-bar clowns back to Orinda and Walnut
Creek where they belong,'' referring to two affluent Bay Area
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``How: vandalize yuppie cars: Lexus- Porsches-Jaguars, sport
utility vehicles. Break the glass. Scratch the paint. Slash their
tires and upholstery. Trash them all.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not an isolated sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some very real resentment and real fear developing,''
said Christian Parenti, 30, a writer and teacher who has lived in
the Mission off and on for the past 10 years. Parenti is not a
member of the Yuppie Eradication Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neighborhood is increasingly the playground of really
wealthy young and middle-aged folks who live in Silicon Valley;
they come here because it's authentic and hip, and, not
intentionally, end up destroying those qualities and displacing
people in the process. People just cannot afford to live here
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent anti-yuppie poster, seen in both English and
Spanish around the Mission, calls for the destruction of four
specific bars and restaurants. It also names one new resident of
the neighborhood, a realtor, as ``a leading force behind Mission
gentrification.''
</P>
<P>
   Police are continuing their investigation of Kevin Keating, who
was arrested May 14 on suspicion of making terrorist threats and
malicious mischief in connection with the flyers.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were subsequently dropped pending further
investigation, but police Capt. Kevin Dillon said investigators are
going through evidence seized at the Mission District apartment
Keating shares with his girlfriend, who is also under suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Keating, 38, said this week that police have targeted him for
political reasons. They took some 70 books from his apartment _
anything related to anarchism, communism or revolution, Keating
said.
</P>
<P>
   The search warrant lists among the items confiscated an acid
bomb recipe, books by Karl Marx, volumes on the Spanish and French
revolutions, copies of Keating's own fiction writing, boxes of
paste and a framed picture of Malcolm X. Keating's computer and
computer disks were also seized.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon denied any political motivation. ``We don't target
individuals because of their political beliefs,'' he said. ``People
in this community feel threatened by what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating said he has never advocated violence against individuals
and would never make a bomb. But the aspiring writer and filmmaker
believes that strong language is needed to make a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The posters have a provocative language, and if the message
weren't provocative, the underlying and more important issues would
never be acknowledged or addressed,'' Keating said. The main issue:
that real estate speculators ``are out to drive the working class
and poor people out of their homes because there's lots of money to
be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Buhrz, owner of the Beauty Bar, one of the establishments
targeted in the latest Yuppie Eradication flyer, was critical of
Keating.
</P>
<P>
   Keating is inciting other people to vandalize and damage
property, Buhrz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people in this town who are listening to him
and going nuts over it,'' Buhrz said. But he added that he has not
been the victim of any anti-yuppie vandalism because of the flyer.
</P>
<P>
   A backlash against the flyers _ and the sentiment behind them _
appears to be growing.
</P>
<P>
   A group calling itself the Mission New Property Owners Action
Pact, among others, is sponsoring a ``Stop the Hate'' rally Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're tired of being insulted and terrorized just because
you own property and drive a nice car, then show your support for
building a stronger Mission by coming to our rally on Sunday . . .
'' was the message on an organizer's telephone answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   One local business owner wrote to her neighborhood newsletter
that she was able to ignore the anti-yuppie campaign at the outset
but not any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The latest posters targeting specific businesses really
frightened me,'' she said. ``I am absolutely against people being
evicted from their homes . . . but do not feel that anyone who
somehow managed to start an independent business should be targeted
in such a violent manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Spivack says ``Everybody here is just trying to live their life.
Sorry that we came and bought a house here because it's the last
affordable place in the city. Sorry if that offends you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a newspaper ad promoting Sunday's rally, organizers urged
residents to ``Stop the Hate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate crimes against new residents of the Mission have
terrorized many of those of us who, having moved to this community
to empower ourselves as property owners, find that instead we are
treated with contempt and targeted by vandals,'' the notice reads.
</P>
<P>
   The reference to hate crimes is ``just asinine,'' said Heather
Rogers, a Mission District artist and member of MAGIC, the Mission
Artists Gentrification Insurrection Coalition. Her group opposes
gentrification and works to support low-income residents of the
Mission _ those who are the real victims of hate crimes, Rogers
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
