<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Saturday, June 5, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Henry Warnlen; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX (Washington) _ President Clinton declared
Friday that he was ``anxious to end the bombing'' in Yugoslavia,
and the Pentagon said that the 10 week air war could end as early
as Sunday if Serb military authorities begin their troop withdrawal
from Kosovo. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-RECOVERY-ASSESS (Washington) _ The war in Kosovo appears to
be ending with many major issues unresolved, not least the future
of President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia and what the United
States and its allies ought to do about him. By R.W. Apple.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ As soon as Russia came
to agreement with NATO on the principles for a peace settlement for
Kosovo, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic understood that he
had no choice but to accept the terms put in front of him, senior
Yugoslav officials said Friday. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ How/why the military campaign is
coming to its end. By Eric Schmitt and Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Washington) _ Through the war, NATO has only
warily dealt with the Kosovo Liberation Army, the only fighters on
the ground in Yugoslavia. Now with a settlement at hand, NATO is
even more wary of the emboldened rebels, who see themselves as the
emerging political and military power in a liberated Kosovo. By
Steven Lee Myers and Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-POLICE-SHOOTING (Los Angeles) _ A homeless woman, who was a
former banker with schizophenia, was killed by police after waving
a screwdriver. The death prompted protests over police brutality.
But without activists like the Rev. Al Sharpton to fan the flames
of outrage, the incident has not become a national issue. By Todd
S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y.-BUDGET (New York) _ After two weeks of relatively painless
negotiations, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and City Council leaders
agreed Friday on a $35.3 billion budget that takes advantage of
record tax revenues and contains only a smattering of cuts. By
Abigail Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y.-ALLERGY (New York) _ On top of a building in downtown
Brooklyn _ with nice views of the harbor on one side and Manhattan
on the other _ sits a little monitor of human misery called a
Rotorod Sampler, Model 140. It doesn't measure bad vibes, but it
might as well. It counts grass pollen, which along with tree
pollens waged its nastiest assault in years last spring and summer
on the city's allergy sufferers. This year, according to the
detector, it is much worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
