<SLUG> BC-CAR-EARNHARDT-JR.-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALE JR. PASSES WINSTON TEST WITH FLYING COLORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   c.1999 N.Y. Times
News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You would have thought this decision would have been made long
ago, because there has never been any indication that Dale
Earnhardt Jr. ever wanted to do anything but drive a race car.
</P>
<P>
   But after finishing 16th in his first Winston Cup race Sunday,
the Coca-Cola 600 at Lowe's Motor Speedway outside Charlotte, N.C.,
Earnhardt admitted he went in with some trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought for years and years that this was what I wanted to
do,'' said the 24-year-old son of Dale Earnhardt Sr. ``And
suddenly, I was getting ready to find out whether I was right or
not, whether this is really what I want to do or whether this ain't
what I expected it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr., who is known to fans as ``Little E.,'' plans to
move full time to the Winston Cup next year, but he is back on the
Busch circuit this week where he will run in Saturday's MBNA
Platinum 200 at Dover Downs International Speedway in Delaware. He
set a race record average speed of 130.512 mph last year at Dover.
</P>
<P>
   If there were any doubts about his Winston ambitions, they were
apparently resolved with his performance Sunday. Never in NASCAR
history has so much attention been riveted on a newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   In that atmosphere, it would have been easy for a young driver
to try and charge to the front, to try and live up to the hype.
</P>
<P>
   Showing great maturity and common sense, Earnhardt resisted that
temptation. He quickly found out his car wasn't capable of staying
with the leaders, so he fell back to where he could run safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope all those drivers out there are a little more
comfortable with me and that's one thing I was trying to accomplish
_ not to tear up a race car and try and gain some respect from
these guys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to learn as much as I could following them and
seeing how they were driving and seeing what happened to their cars
on long runs later in the race,'' Earnhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I was very tentative in making passes and stuff,
especially being underneath guys going into three or going down
into one,'' he said. ``I didn't want to get loose in the center of
the corner and get up into them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys have got the experience to drive through there.
That's something we've got to learn over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised with some of the things they can do
with the cars and how they drive them,'' he said. ``You'll see some
drivers put their cars in positions you just don't see how they got
through there.''
</P>
<P>
   He said such maneuvers are rare in the Busch Series, but he has
seen them from Matt Kenseth.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth, 27, leads the Busch Series points standings and, as a
young driver, is as highly regarded as Earnhardt Jr. by some. Like
the younger Earnhardt, Kenseth will move full time to Winston Cup
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest worry was my endurance and my ability as a driver
to drive the car competitively for that length of time,'' Earnhardt
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to pace myself as much as I could, and I'm real
happy with what happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as this being what I want to do all my life?'' he said.
``I'm now satisfied it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Was there ever any doubt, really?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
