<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEYWORLD-COOL-NYTR-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW DISNEYLAND KEEPS CUSTOMERS COOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By BILL DEAN   The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   c.1999 N.Y. Times News
Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The giant bottle of Coca-Cola looks like just
another prop at Disney-MGM Studios.
</P>
<P>
   But as guests walk by, the unmistakable sound of a pop bottle
being opened grabs their attention _ before the bottle releases a
cooling spray of watery mist.
</P>
<P>
   Pop, pop, fizz, fizz, oh what a relief it is.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to all four of Disney World's theme parks expect great
attractions, grandiose shows and characters in costume. But they
may not realize that Orlando's largest collection of parks also
takes great pains to keep them cool during Florida's sizzling
summers.
</P>
<P>
   At various and surprising locations in its parks, Disney has
installed misting stations and interactive fountains to ensure
guests sizzle more from Space Mountain than they do from Florida's
oppressive heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like it,'' says Disney spokesman Craig Dezern about the
misters. ``It's summer in Florida _ hot _ and people are ready to
cool off and get wet.
</P>
<P>
   ``So our imagineers have taken water and turned it into a
plaything.''
</P>
<P>
   Some recently opened attractions, including Animal Kingdom's new
Kali River Rapids, virtually drench visitors in water to cool them
off.
</P>
<P>
   But the parks also use hidden misters or themed sprays to
surprise guests with kinder, gentler means of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Easiest to spot are the Coke Cool Zones. The 20-foot-tall bottle
that sprays automatically as guests walk by is in Disney-MGM
Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Near Epcot's new Test Track attraction is a Coke Cool Zone that
looks like a car wash _ except it's guests who walk through and
receive a cooling ``wash'' or mist.
</P>
<P>
   In the World Showcase, there is what looks like a collection of
vending machines. ``There's no signage to tell you to do this, but
if you go over to them and open them up, all of a sudden it sprays
you with water,'' Dezern says.
</P>
<P>
   Other misting stations are set up at such locations as Animal
Kingdom's Tamu Tamu ice cream shop _ where a giant fan has a hose
behind it to blow a cooling mist at guests walking by.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's first experiments in cooling visitors started about
five years ago with interactive fountains installed for kids. The
first fountains proved so popular that Disney decided to do
something for adults as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the fountains, we discovered the interactivity that
people enjoy,'' Dezern says. ``Then we took it the next step and
came up with the misting stations for everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of discover them as you walk by. And you don't even
feel like you're wet. You just feel cooled off.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of The New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
