u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GUNS05-COX     06-04 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AN ANGRY CLINTON DEFENDS PACE OF GUN CONTROL EFFORT
 &HT;    370&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's famous temper flared on
national television Friday as he responded to a suggestion that his
gun control proposals ``are not going to make a damn bit of
difference'' in keeping guns out of the hands of children.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton acknowledged that enacting significantly stronger
measures could ``take years,'' because he was forced to ``take what
I can get'' from a reluctant Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton became testy as ABC's Charles Gibson quoted an
unidentified friend of the president's who had suggested that after
the fatal school shootings in Colorado this April, Clinton ``had a
chance to roar on gun control and he meowed'' instead by proposing
modest measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, let's join the real world here,'' Clinton said, his eyes
narrowing and his finger wagging at Gibson during an interview on
``Good Morning America'' broadcast live from the White House. ``You
want to have an honest conversation? Let's have an honest
conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For you to say that I shouldn't take what I can get,'' he
said, ``and instead I should ask for things that I am absolutely
positive will be defeated in the Congress is quite wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview preceded a portion of the program in which the
president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton brainstormed with
40 teenagers on what should be done to curb violence in their
lives. Some of the teens came from schools in Littleton, Colo.;
Springfield, Ore.; West Paducah, Ky., and Conyers, Ga., that had
been the sites of shootings by students.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who participated was Trey Carver, 15, who attends
Heritage High School in Conyers, Ga., where six students were
wounded by a classmate last month.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady sought to recruit the students into the
administration's anti-violence campaign, urging them to speak out
for tougher gun controls. ``There's no reason why a lot of you who
are about to be or are already 18 can't let your voices be heard,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But even one of the students, Albert Smith, whose sister was
wounded in gunfire in Evanston, Ill., raised questions about the
president's handgun proposals. ``How spectacular is this
legislation and what makes it different?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In his interview with Clinton, Gibson said the pending gun
control measures would allow Democrats and Republicans to score
``political points,'' but that ``it's not going to make a damn bit
of difference _ only on the margins _ in the way kids get guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted, however, that the measures ``can save
children's lives,'' and explained in detail why he is pursuing gun
control legislation at a deliberate pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the first president who ever took on the (National Rifle
Association),'' Clinton said in recounting the seven-year
congressional battle that led to the 1993 enactment of the Brady
Bill, which requires background checks on handgun purchasers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To ignore the fact that my administration and my party took on
this issue when no one else would and paid a huge price for it _
and lost control of the House of Representatives in all probability
because of it _ and to pretend that this is an easy thing now
because Littleton happened is wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president said Gibson was ``absolutely right'' in suggesting
that stronger measures could be taken, including registration of
handguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do my best to advocate more, but ... I want to do this
in sequence,'' he said, beginning this month with an expected House
vote on Senate-approved legislation to require background checks on
gun show sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I want to us to come back with a second set of
recommendations,'' he added. ``I intend to keep working on this. I
think this is going to take years. We have _ the Congress is out of
touch with the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted, for example, that the Senate measures passed by only
one vote. Furthermore, he contended, Republican leaders delayed a
House vote on the Senate measures until after the holiday recess in
order to give the gun lobby more time to persuade members to water
down the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
