u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WASH-COLUMN-NYTR-NYTR     06-04 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASH-COLUMN-NYTR-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL VOUCHERS LIKELY TO BE SUBJECT OF TEST FOR HIGH COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Maine, Ala., Mass., Wis., Fla., S.C., Tenn., N.C., Alaska)   (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers.) 
(dw) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   NYT Regional Newspapers   c.1999
N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As conflicting court decisions on public vouchers
for private school tuition mount and more states explore the
controversial idea, the issue appears headed to the U.S. Supreme
Court for resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Judges in the Midwest have upheld using taxpayer funds to
subsidize private and religious schools. But a federal appeals
court in Boston ruled unequivocally a few days ago that a Maine
voucher program violated the nation's historic separation of church
and state. That ruling _ by the highest court to review the issue
thus far _ came as a legal fight brewed over Florida's new voucher
plan and Louisiana legislators debated a voucher system there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pot is boiling to say the least,'' remarked Joseph Conn, a
spokesman for Americans United for Separation of Church and State,
a group opposed to vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   He said it will be months before a voucher case reaches the high
court, where his group anticipates a ruling in its favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like a huge step for the Supreme Court to allow
public money to be used to advance religious instruction,'' said
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   But voucher advocates are putting their faith in the wisdom of
the Wisconsin Supreme Court, which found no Constitutional
objection to public subsidies of private schools and portrayed the
matter more as one of school choice.
</P>
<P>
   Florida will be the next battleground as opponents promise to
sue as soon as Gov. Jeb Bush signs his voucher plan into law. His
allies believe they will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, the statute here in Florida has been crafted more
carefully than those elsewhere,'' said Patrick Heffernan, head of
Floridians for School Choice.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Several federal programs with deep roots in the South are under
attack by a government watchdog group as either wasteful, outdated
or ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers for Common Sense is taking aim at a boll weevil
eradication program, a loan program for providing electricity in
rural areas and the federal peanut program.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Ashdown, a spokesman for the group, questioned the need
for the latter two efforts, noting that nearly 100 percent of the
United States has electricity compared to 11 percent when the
agency was created in 1935. And the peanut program, he said, means
that consumers pay more for peanut butter at the supermarket due to
production quotas and import restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   As for boll weevils, Ashdown acknowledged that the insect is
still a problem in the South, but he questioned the effectiveness
of the current program. President Clinton requested $3.3 million to
battle weevils next year, but House members want to increase that
amount to $16.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   All three programs are included in the agricultural spending
bill, which has already run into criticism from GOP conservatives
for its spending level.
</P>
<P>
   SUCCESS STORY?
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on Capitol Hill are crowing about a new report that
suggests welfare reform works and fewer families now depend on
government aid for help.
</P>
<P>
   The report from the General Accounting Office found that
employment rates ranged from 61 to 87 percent for adults in
families who left welfare.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina and Tennessee were two of seven states nationwide
that had compiled significant data on such families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lives indeed are changed for the better,'' said House Speaker
Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-six percent of former welfare recipients surveyed in
South Carolina disagreed with the statement that ``life was better
when you were getting welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, congressional Republicans pushed through a welfare
reform package that placed restrictions on social service programs,
including a limit on the length of time a family could receive
government benefits. Many states had enacted their own reforms
before Congress acted.
</P>
<P>
   HARD LESSON
</P>
<P>
   After six months in office, Sen. John Edwards, a freshman
Democrat from North Carolina, is getting an education in how
lawmakers spend taxpayers' money. He's not impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards bemoaned the recent $15 billion ``emergency'' spending
bill that paid for the military operation and humanitarian aid in
Kosovo. It was also crammed with other pet projects, including $2
million to study a proposed wood veneer plant in Alaska and an
extra $500,000 for GOP leaders to run their offices in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was my first real taste of Washington spending and I
didn't like it,'' said Edwards, who voted against the measure. ``In
fact, it was shameful.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin work in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
