<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, June 6, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-LESSONS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Was the NATO bombing campaign
in Yugoslavia a success? Technically, it apparently achieved its
goal. But the allied obsession to avoid casualties and maintain
consensus contributed to drawing out the bombing far longer than
anyone anticipated, and thereby to massive damage and significant
casualties in Yugoslavia and to strained relations with Russia and
Chinese. By Serge Schmemann. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   DAMAGE-SUITS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Across the country, accounts of
bizarre jury verdicts and huge damage awards (like the McDonald's
customer who spilled coffee on herself and collected $2.9 million)
have been used to prove that the courts are wacky or worse. But
increasingly, some political scientists, legal scholars and
consumer advocates are suggesting that accounts of outlandish
cases. By William Glaberson. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL-HEALTHCARE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Shouldn't people with
mental illnesses, which can destroy lives and families, be entitled
to the same amount of insurance coverage as those with physical
illnesses? It sounds like a fairly simple question. But as in all
things having to do with health care, and especially the often
vaguely defined area of mental illness, the issue can be
maddeningly complicated. By Joe Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-COACHES-CLOTHES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The 29 head coaches in
the NBA are considered the best-dressed coaches in the world, as
these things go. While their counterparts in the NFL and Major
League Baseball wear warm-up jackets, baseball caps and, in the
case of baseball managers, team uniforms, the coaches in the
media-savvy NBA wear suits by some of the most stylish designers on
the market. By Chris Broussard.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM-BLOCKBUSTERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Summer is blockbuster
season, from the multiplex to the august halls of culture. Museums
may shun comparisons with Hollywood but they, too, strive for that
explosion of interest that by any name spells blockbuster, filling
the coffers, swelling the membership rolls and exciting admiration
and envy at fellow institutions. By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSE-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at the dramatic _ and
conflicting _ announcements on the age and nature of the universe
that have been made in the past couple of weeks. The area of
disagreement between cosmologists seems to be always increasing or
shrinking. By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   TRIVIA-QUIZ-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ On the last night of classes
at Williams College in Williamstown, Mass., the student radio
station WCFM conducts a marathon trivia contest. Some questions and
answers.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-SAFRICA-REVIEW (Abuja, Nigeria) _ The different paths
taken by Nigeria and South Africa to democracy. Nigeria was once
the uncontested leader in Africa, the staunchest backer of
liberation movements in South Africa and other white-ruled
countries. Yet South Africa preceded Nigeria into democratic
government, holding its first all-race elections in 1994 even as
Nigeria slipped into a ruthless military dictatorship. By Norimitsu
Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-REVIEW (Jakarta) _ Since President Suharto was forced
to resign in May 1998, Indonesia has been learning fast, moving
from street demonstrations to party organizing, from utopian
philosophizing to the beginnings of coalition building. Still,
nobody knows what patterns voting will take, how the elections will
play out or how this nation of more than 200 million jostling and
often feuding people will manage the outcome. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-U.S.-REVIEW (Cairo) _ Teheran is abuzz again, divided now
over whether America really is still the Great Satan. And as usual,
the ferocity of Iran's internal power struggles make it hard to
know just what is going on. So here's a quick primer on the latest
in U.S.-Iranian relations _ a succession of winks, nods and
backhanded slaps that might amount to a lot or to absolutely
nothing at all. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-TERMS-REVIEW (Istanbul) _ Turkey's treatment of its more
than 10 million Kurds has been widely criticized abroad. The
Interior Ministry has declared that the government needs to adopt a
``unity of terminology'' in presenting its case to the world. A
look at the the unacceptable terms and what what the government
says are correct ones that should be used in their place. By Steven
Kinzer.
</P>
