</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA SEEN LIKELY TO BACK KOSOVO SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A day after Yugoslavia accepted an international peace
plan for Kosovo, China on Friday restated its demand that NATO halt
its bombing before discussions begin in the United Nations about a
peacekeeping force. But Chinese support for the peace plan seems
likely.
</P>
<P>
   In brief statements issued Friday, Prime Minister Zhu Rongji and
the Foreign Ministry spokesman held back from openly endorsing the
peace plan, stressing the need for a bombing halt ``to create
necessary conditions for a peaceful settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the plan goes forward, the NATO attacks are likely to be
suspended in coming days in any case, to permit withdrawal of
Serbian troops from Kosovo. After a telephone conversation with Zhu
on Friday, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said he was
confident that China as well as Russia would go along with a U.N.
Security Council resolution to carry out the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the main features of the settlement _ a U.N. mandate for
a peacekeeping force and formal preservation of the territorial
integrity of Yugoslavia _ address major concerns that China has
angrily expressed since the start of the bombing campaign more than
two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   China was outraged by NATO's decision to act without
authorization from the United Nations, where China could exercise a
veto. With a history of foreign invasions and fears about ethnic
unrest at home, China also felt deeply threatened by the principle
that Western powers could intervene in a sovereign country because
of ethnic disputes. Chinese leaders have railed against what they
call an act of illegal aggression by ``United States-led NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese television and the official New China News Agency both
reported Friday night on the telephone call Zhu received from
Schroeder, who appeared to be trying to assuage China's hurt pride
and insure its cooperation in the United Nations. In the call,
Schroeder described the peace plan and promised to send an emissary
to China to give a more detailed briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond reiterating that the bombing should stop, Zhu also said
that the Kosovo conflict should be solved ``on the principle of
respecting the sovereignty and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia
and protecting the rights and interests of the various
nationalities in the Kosovo region,'' according to the press
account. These conditions would be met under the proposed
settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3422 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX     06-04 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGNS IT'S TIME TO DITCH YOUR PC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: My problem began when we lost the icon for File
Manager. I was told the only way to get it back was to restore my
system. I tried with both a recovery CD and a recovery diskette. I
kept getting a message ``a valid hard drive format number was not
found.'' The message goes on to say, ``If you push Enter, you will
exit the program.'' I have the feeling that I received the wrong
recovery disc, but when I try to ask the manufacturer, they won't
even talk to me unless I pay them $35. I feel this is unfair. Every
time I have had a problem with this unit, it has taken me weeks _
with their help _ to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Had It up to Here
</P>
<P>
   DEAR HAD IT: So, I guess you won't be a repeat customer. Your
experience with these clowns should have told you something. I
purposely omitted the manufacturer's name, as many of our fine
advertisers offer outstanding bargains on these inexpensive PCs.
They will be just as happy, though, to sell you much better-quality
merchandise at a slightly higher price.
</P>
<P>
   There is a reason some brands are the lowest-priced on the
market. They stink. The component quality is marginal, the
workmanship is shoddy and the support is nonexistent, as you found
out. I'm as cheap as the next guy, but I'd rather pay a few extra
bucks upfront than spend it on migraine cures down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, let's try and make some lemonade. I'm guessing you had
Windows 3.x, since you said ``File Manager'' instead of ``Windows
Explorer.'' If the icon simply disappeared, that was no reason to
restore the system, no matter what anybody said. In Windows, just
go to the Program Manager's File menu and pick New. Fill in a
couple of blanks, and you get a new icon. In Win95/98, just
right-click on the desktop and pick New, then Shortcut from the
menu that pops up. Same general procedure.
</P>
<P>
   But it sounds like your problem was worse than that. Assuming
that trying to run a restore process didn't hammer things, it's
more likely your hard drive has started to flake out, which is
pretty common in low-end PCs. There. Give me 35 bucks.
</P>
<P>
   I would probably just wipe the drive and start over if there's
no serious physical damage to the disk or no moving parts worn out.
Make yourself a boot floppy (the DOS command is FORMAT A: /s) with
Fdisk.exe and Format.com on it, then restart your system with it in
the drive. Fdisk will completely zap any data on your hard drive,
so go read the DOS manual first. Once you've used it to make a
nice, clean disk, do a format (FORMAT C: /s/v) and you'll be ready
to install Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Oh. Did I forget to mention you'll need to reinstall Windows? If
you don't have a fresh copy, you can still get Win95, generally for
about 70 bucks. You might even find a copy of Windows 3.1 in an
antique shop somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But, look, if you owned a toaster that burned everything you put
in it or a car that died every five blocks, I bet you wouldn't put
up with that. Maybe it's time to bite the bullet and invest in a
new PC instead of keeping your pile of junk on life support. Even
the best brands have models starting around a grand. And, no, I
don't get a kickback from the advertisers. At least, not a very big
one.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay will endorse any
product for a nominal fee. Cash only. He can be reached at
drbombay(at)Nstar-telegram.com, via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101, or fax: (817) 390-7257.
In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial systems
manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
