<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TONYAWARDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE TONY TONYS GIVE UP THE HOST OF PAST AWARDS SHOWS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by TONY AWARDS-PICKS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Tonys might be onto something _ this year, there's no host.
For this, we could thank Rosie O'Donnell, who has hosted the past
few years and declined this year. Was she so good that no one could
follow her?
</P>
<P>
   Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of a host, the 1999 Antoinette Perry ``Tony'' Awards,
airing Sunday night, will use a ``paired host'' concept, in which
two actors will present an award and moderate a portion of the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   The pairings range from cool (Kevin Spacey and Jason Robards) to
interesting (Stockard Channing and Laurence Fishburne) to downright
scary (Julie Andrews and Carol Burnett). And we can't wait to see
who will outdiva the other in the Christine Baranski/David Hyde
Pierce duo.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, we'd love the Oscars, Emmys, Grammys, Billboards, etc.
to latch onto this concept. Billy Crystal seems to be the only
awards-show host who hasn't been critically lambasted during the
'90s, and even he's getting tired.
</P>
<P>
   But the Tonys are different. This awards show is definitely more
esoteric, and considering that its honorees are readily accessible
only to folks in the Northeast _ and even then, scoring a Broadway
ticket isn't as easy as buying a CD or turning on the tube _ it's
no wonder that folks in the heartland often couldn't care less.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe because the Tony Awards isn't watched by all of America,
it's a higher-quality awards show: It doesn't have to cater to the
masses. There are no inane tributes to people who have nothing to
do with the art form being honored; there's no overlong Debbie
Allen-choreographed interpretation of the nominated scores, no
Michael Flatley, no Stomp. Or at least not this time. Instead,
there will be numbers from the best play, musical and musical
revival nominees, including Bernadette Peters and Tom Wopat from
``Annie Get Your Gun.'' Yee-haw.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a theme on Broadway this year, it was the return of
great American playwrights. Eugene O'Neill's ``The Iceman Cometh''
and Arthur Miller's ``Death of a Salesman'' _ both among the top
American plays of the century _ are nominated for best revival, and
the leading man in each is nominated for best actor.
</P>
<P>
   And Tennessee Williams' 1938 play ``Not About Nightingales'' is
nominated for best play, having been discovered only recently and
brought to the Great White Way this year.
</P>
<P>
   The most noticeable omission is British playwright David Hare,
who had three plays on Broadway _ ``Amy's View,'' ``The Blue Room''
and ``Via Dolorosa'' _ none of which was nominated for best play.
Dame Judi Dench was nominated (and will likely win) for ``Amy's
View,'' but it's no surprise that Nicole Kidman was looked over for
``The Blue Room.'' Maybe she would have been nominated if there had
there been a category for Most Hyped Five-Second Nude Scene.
</P>
<P>
   The show's highlight might be the Lifetime Achievement awards.
OK, so no big Elia Kazan-type controversy, but check these honorees
out. Actress Uta Hagen _ who has written books about acting and
this year starred opposite Fort Worth's Lorca Simons in ``Collected
Stories;'' Arthur Miller, whose works have become textbooks for
college theater classes (and some high schools that can tolerate
his crude language); and Isabelle Stevenson, chairman of the board
of the American Theatre Wing, the group behind the Tony Awards.
Hmmm.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it doesn't look like a bad evening. But did you
expect anything less from the kings and queens of drama?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
