<HEADLINE>
HANDICAPPING THE TONYS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies TV-TONY AWARDS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the major nominees and those our survey (read:
conventional wisdom) says will win:
</P>
<P>
   Best New Play:
</P>
<P>
   ``Closer'' by Patrick Marber
</P>
<P>
   ``Lonesome West'' by Martin McDonagh
</P>
<P>
   ``Not About Nightingales'' by Tennessee Williams
</P>
<P>
   ``Side Man'' by Warren Leight
</P>
<P>
   Survey says: McDonagh's got buzz, and it was an upset when he
didn't win last year for ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane,'' but no
one _ not the Emmys, Oscars or the Tonys _ can resist awarding
posthumously. Williams is the hot cat here.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Best New Musical:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fosse''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't Nothing but the Blues''
</P>
<P>
   ``Parade''
</P>
<P>
   Survey says: ``Parade'' is a strong contender, but it didn't
last on Broadway very long. Besides, what did we just say about
posthumous recognition? Look for the musical tribute to legendary
choreographer Bob Fosse to dance its way to the Tony.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Best Revival of a Play:
</P>
<P>
   ``Death of a Salesman'' by Arthur Miller
</P>
<P>
   ``Electra'' by Euripides
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iceman Cometh'' by Eugene O'Neill
</P>
<P>
   ``Twelfth Night'' by William Shakespeare
</P>
<P>
   Survey says: This is a tough one. Two playwrights who have had
serious staying power for centuries and two of the most important
plays in the annals of American theater. It'll be close between
``Iceman'' and ``Death,'' but look for the latter to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Best Revival of a Musical:
</P>
<P>
   ``Annie Get Your Gun''
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Me''
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Pan''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown''
</P>
<P>
   Survey says: Bull's-eye for ``Annie,'' which has had a huge
success at the ticket booth.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Best Performance by a Leading Actor in a Play:
</P>
<P>
   Brian Dennehy, ``Death of a Salesman''
</P>
<P>
   Brian O'Byrne, ``The Lonesome West''
</P>
<P>
   Corin Redgrave, ``Not About Nightingales''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Spacey, ``The Iceman Cometh''
</P>
<P>
   Survey says: Dennehy sold it, but Spacey cometh forth for the
Tony.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Play:
</P>
<P>
   Stockard Channing, ``The Lion in Winter''
</P>
<P>
   Judi Dench, ``Amy's View''
</P>
<P>
   Marian Seldes, ``Ring Round the Moon''
</P>
<P>
   Zoe Wanamaker, ``Electra''
</P>
<P>
   Survey says: Judi, Judi, Judi. And this time, she actually
appeared for more than eight minutes in one role.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Best Performance by a Leading Actor in a Musical:
</P>
<P>
   Brent Carver, ``Parade''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Cooper, ``Swan Lake''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Short, ``Little Me''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wopat, ``Annie Get Your Gun''
</P>
<P>
   Survey says: Carver had the year's freshest and brightest face.
He deserves his own parade, and he's likely to get it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Musical:
</P>
<P>
   Carolee Carmello, ``Parade''
</P>
<P>
   Dee Hoty, ``Footloose''
</P>
<P>
   Bernadette Peters, ``Annie Get Your Gun''
</P>
<P>
   Sian Phillips, ``Marlene''
</P>
<P>
   Survey says: Broadway can't resist Bernie, but Phillips could
pull an upset with her acclaimed portrayal of Dietrich.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Best Original Score:
</P>
<P>
   ``Footloose,'' Tom Snow, Eric Carmen, Dean Pitchford, Sammy
Hagar, Kenny Loggins and Jim Steinman
</P>
<P>
   ``Parade,'' Jason Robert Brown
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War,'' Frank Wildhorn and Jack Murphy
</P>
<P>
   ``Twelfth Night,'' Jeanine Tesori
</P>
<P>
   Survey says: Brown's score was beautifully dark, but red-hot
Wildhorn is said to be the next Webber, and you know how Broadway
loves a musical that sells tickets. Anything to keep Carmen, Hagar,
Loggins et al. away from the podium. Are they serious?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Best Choreography:
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Birch, ``Parade''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Bourne, ``Swan Lake''
</P>
<P>
   A.C. Ciulla, ``Footloose''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Marshall, ``Little Me''
</P>
<P>
   Survey says: Hands _ or, um, feet _ down, Bourne's work on the
all-male ``Swan Lake'' has got this one wrapped up.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Best Direction of a Play:
</P>
<P>
   Howard Davies, ``The Iceman Cometh''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Falls, ``Death of a Salesman''
</P>
<P>
   Garry Hynes, ``The Lonesome West''
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Nunn, ``Not About Nightingales''
</P>
<P>
   Survey says: Another toughie. But Davies deserves this, if only
for having to stage O'Neill's trying four-hour-plus drama.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Best Direction of a Musical:
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Bourne, ``Swan Lake''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Maltby Jr. and Ann Reinking, ``Fosse''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mayer, ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Prince, ``Parade''
</P>
<P>
   Survey says: Mayer made ``Charlie Brown'' fun again, but who
could resist that incredible courtroom scene in ``Parade?'' Our
money's on Prince.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
