<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3430 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV06-COX     06-04 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANTITRUST TRIAL TO FOCUS ON MICROSOFT-IBM RIFT
 &HT;    540 and insert. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, June 6.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The often troubled dealings between Microsoft and
IBM, two giant firms that together have done much to shape today's
computer world, will take center stage Monday at the Microsoft
antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   Government prosecutors will seek to show that Microsoft chairman
Bill Gates orchestrated a vendetta against International Business
Machines Corp. when it refused to dump its rival operating system
in favor of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations of specific illegal conduct on Microsoft's part
will be in counterpoint to the broader issues of purported monopoly
power that were raised by Franklin Fisher, the government's chief
economic witness, who ended four days on the witness stand Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's place will be taken by Garry Norris, the IBM executive
in charge of the firm's relationship with Microsoft from 1995 to
1997, a time when IBM sought in vain to achieve a marketing
breakthrough with its OS/2 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Norris's testimony, based on a handwritten diary, could ruffle
the current relationship between the two firms, which has warmed
since IBM stopped marketing OS/2 as a ``desktop solution'' and
decided to mount Windows silks as a Microsoft ``business partner.''
</P>
<P>
   But Norris's allegations could also strengthen the case in a
critical sector. Even with his appearance, the government has
proved unable to convince any large computer manufacturer to
testify against Microsoft because, the prosecutors maintain, all
these companies fear Microsoft's wrath.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, Microsoft lawyer Richard Pepperman will
elicit from Norris that he did not enter the federal courthouse as
a corporate representative of IBM, but rather as a private
individual whose testimony had been sought by the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   At his May 28 deposition, Norris recalled that Gates had at one
point offered IBM major financial incentives if it would dump its
OS/2 software. The Microsoft co-founder, Norris said, raised the
prospect of close business ties, including deep pricing discounts,
preferential marketing programs and advanced technical support for
IBM.
</P>
<P>
   When IBM spurned the deal, Norris said, Microsoft retaliated by
raising prices, refusing to share advanced Windows code,
blacklisting IBM officials from attending Microsoft-sponsored
events, and failing to return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   It was IBM's own prolonged antitrust woes in an earlier era that
prompted the company to look for an outside source when it needed
an operating system for its path-breaking personal computers in
1981.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, IBM gave the contract to Gates, at a time when
Microsoft was a 14-employee shop in Seattle. Gates bought the basic
code from another company, tweaked it a bit, and licensed it to IBM
as DOS 1.0.
</P>
<P>
   It soon became clear, however, that DOS would not be powerful
enough to run the next generation of Intel-based computers.
Microsoft and IBM thereupon entered into a new joint venture, which
produced OS/2.
</P>
<P>
   In time, the partners quarreled. IBM then took over OS/2
development, including full rights to Windows 3.1 code, while
Microsoft concentrated on what in time emerged as Windows 95 and
Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In his court appearance, Fisher, an economics professor at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, held that Microsoft
``probably had attained monopoly power'' when it was selling
Windows 3.1, but that it did not fully consolidate its commanding
position in the marketplace until the release of Windows 95 in the
fall of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In its defense, Microsoft made heavy use of newly disclosed
documents this week to argue that America Online Inc.'s recent
purchase of Netscape Communications Corp. illustrated how
competition in the high-tech industry is robust and further federal
intervention is not needed.
</P>
<P>
   But Fisher said his own analysis showed that the merger would
have no bearing at all on Microsoft's monopoly stance _ a view also
held by executives of both AOL and Netscape, which survives as a
brand name but not as a company.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3431 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPETITION-VS-INNOVA     06-04 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPETITION-VS-INNOVATION-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: to waste.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But market prices do not produce wondrous results in the
presence of imperfections like monopolies. One imperfection, called
an externality, is crucial to understanding the important message
of the Baumol manuscript. Markets go haywire when the impact of a
trade between buyer and seller extends beyond the two parties
directly involved.
</P>
<P>
   Take innovation. The profit from innovation routinely leaks to
third parties. A firm spends a lot of money bringing to market a
clever new electronic organizer or tennis racket. Ten nanoseconds
later, another firm tears the product apart and reverse engineers a
variation that gets around the patent. So the first firm winds up
making relatively little money, a heavy disincentive for would-be
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Edward Wolff, a colleague of Baumol at New York
University, estimates that innovators can expect to earn about 10
cents a year from each dollar they invest. But because the
innovation leaks to other companies and other sectors, the economy
as a whole reaps a benefit of about 50 cents. The implication,
according to the textbooks, is that capitalism provides
entrepreneurs too little of the profit that investments create for
the economy. So they invest too little in the development of
products. Consumers suffer from high prices, restricted choice and
delayed innovation.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional analysis, then, says that capitalism blunders at
generating innovation over the long run. Baumol's manuscript
reverses this presumption. Competition forces firms to innovate,
engaging in what Baumol says ``is tantamount to a technological
arms race.'' The technology-sharing compacts, by generating a
steady flow of licensing fees for IBM, Perkin-Elmer and other
innovators, turn innovation into a routine profit-making activity.
The competitive system, he says, goes ``a long way, perhaps all the
way, toward generating the right amount of innovation.'' The
compacts overcome leakage by pouring more of the economy's gains
from innovation into the bank account of the innovator.
</P>
<P>
   By reducing the risk of innovation (a company that goes down the
wrong technological road can lease the innovations it did not come
up with) and increasing revenues, technology-sharing compacts make
innovation profitable, routine and plentiful. As proof, he points
to nonmarket societies that generated plenty of inventions but few
applications. Medieval China, for example, invented gunpowder,
paper, the printing press and probably the compass and the water
wheel. But these inventions failed to raise living standards until
adapted into consumer products by societies that were less hostile
to commerce. The genius of Western capitalism was to translate
invention into the goods and services that enrich everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Baumol tells a tale rich in details about the market's use of
collaboration to overcome problems of innovation. Along the way he
turns standard analysis upside down. Textbooks congratulate markets
for their short-run efficiency, even though the short run is
nothing spectacular. Entrenched monopolies, labor-market
rigidities, perverse management incentives and many other problems
are pervasive. The standard analysis goes on to criticize the
market for shortchanging innovation and growth, when in fact
``spectacular growth is the market's outstanding accomplishment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
