<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANTITRUST TRIAL TO FOCUS ON MICROSOFT-IBM RIFT
 &HT;    540 and insert. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, June 6.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The often troubled dealings between Microsoft and
IBM, two giant firms that together have done much to shape today's
computer world, will take center stage Monday at the Microsoft
antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   Government prosecutors will seek to show that Microsoft chairman
Bill Gates orchestrated a vendetta against International Business
Machines Corp. when it refused to dump its rival operating system
in favor of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations of specific illegal conduct on Microsoft's part
will be in counterpoint to the broader issues of purported monopoly
power that were raised by Franklin Fisher, the government's chief
economic witness, who ended four days on the witness stand Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's place will be taken by Garry Norris, the IBM executive
in charge of the firm's relationship with Microsoft from 1995 to
1997, a time when IBM sought in vain to achieve a marketing
breakthrough with its OS/2 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Norris's testimony, based on a handwritten diary, could ruffle
the current relationship between the two firms, which has warmed
since IBM stopped marketing OS/2 as a ``desktop solution'' and
decided to mount Windows silks as a Microsoft ``business partner.''
</P>
<P>
   But Norris's allegations could also strengthen the case in a
critical sector. Even with his appearance, the government has
proved unable to convince any large computer manufacturer to
testify against Microsoft because, the prosecutors maintain, all
these companies fear Microsoft's wrath.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, Microsoft lawyer Richard Pepperman will
elicit from Norris that he did not enter the federal courthouse as
a corporate representative of IBM, but rather as a private
individual whose testimony had been sought by the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   At his May 28 deposition, Norris recalled that Gates had at one
point offered IBM major financial incentives if it would dump its
OS/2 software. The Microsoft co-founder, Norris said, raised the
prospect of close business ties, including deep pricing discounts,
preferential marketing programs and advanced technical support for
IBM.
</P>
<P>
   When IBM spurned the deal, Norris said, Microsoft retaliated by
raising prices, refusing to share advanced Windows code,
blacklisting IBM officials from attending Microsoft-sponsored
events, and failing to return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   It was IBM's own prolonged antitrust woes in an earlier era that
prompted the company to look for an outside source when it needed
an operating system for its path-breaking personal computers in
1981.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, IBM gave the contract to Gates, at a time when
Microsoft was a 14-employee shop in Seattle. Gates bought the basic
code from another company, tweaked it a bit, and licensed it to IBM
as DOS 1.0.
</P>
<P>
   It soon became clear, however, that DOS would not be powerful
enough to run the next generation of Intel-based computers.
Microsoft and IBM thereupon entered into a new joint venture, which
produced OS/2.
</P>
<P>
   In time, the partners quarreled. IBM then took over OS/2
development, including full rights to Windows 3.1 code, while
Microsoft concentrated on what in time emerged as Windows 95 and
Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In his court appearance, Fisher, an economics professor at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, held that Microsoft
``probably had attained monopoly power'' when it was selling
Windows 3.1, but that it did not fully consolidate its commanding
position in the marketplace until the release of Windows 95 in the
fall of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In its defense, Microsoft made heavy use of newly disclosed
documents this week to argue that America Online Inc.'s recent
purchase of Netscape Communications Corp. illustrated how
competition in the high-tech industry is robust and further federal
intervention is not needed.
</P>
<P>
   But Fisher said his own analysis showed that the merger would
have no bearing at all on Microsoft's monopoly stance _ a view also
held by executives of both AOL and Netscape, which survives as a
brand name but not as a company.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
