<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ CREATES NETWORKING NEWS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few PC companies have been pushing home networking as
aggressively as Compaq Computer Corp. Rather than waiting for home
networks to become the next big thing, Compaq is trying to make it
happen faster.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, Compaq has been selling Presario home PCs that
let you use your existing home phone wiring to create a network.
Just plug a pair of computers with the feature into your home's
phone jacks, and presto! _ instant network.
</P>
<P>
   This removes one of the big obstacles to setting up a network in
a house _ wiring. In most homes with more than one computer, the
machines are not in the same room. Those who want to have a
traditional, Ethernet network similar to those used in offices must
run cables through the walls, a daunting task even for the most
dexterous handyman.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq also has simplified what may be an even more intimidating
task _ configuring the software part of the network.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PITTING CHIP AGAINST CHIP &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In order to test this feature, I tried out two high-end Presario
models in the 5600 line. These machines are available via Compaq's
online store, as well as through kiosks set up in stores such as
Best Buy and CompUSA.
</P>
<P>
   This also gave me a chance to check something else. One of the
systems, a 5600i, had a 450-megahertz Pentium III chip from Intel
Corp. The other, a 5600S, had a 450-megahertz Advanced Micro
Devices K6III processor. This let me pit chip against chip, since
the basic configuration of both machines was similar.
</P>
<P>
   Both had 128 megabytes of memory, Diamond Multimedia Viper V550
video cards with 16 megabytes of video memory, DVD-ROM drives and
56K modems. Both also came with Compaq's new 15-inch, digital
flat-panel monitor, the FP700.
</P>
<P>
   The 5600i had a bigger hard drive at 22 gigabytes, compared to
the 5600S, with its 13.5-gigabyte drive. The 5600S used a Sonic
Impact audio card with Aureal 3D 2.0 chips; the 5600i had a Diamond
Monster Sound MX300 card, which also uses the Aureal chipset.
</P>
<P>
   And the 5600i came with a secondary network card, so you could
use it on a traditional network, or with a cable modem that
requires a network card.
</P>
<P>
   The 5600i costs about $1,845, as configured on Compaq's Web
site. The 5600S was about $1,575. You can add the flat-panel
monitor to either one for $645.
</P>
<P>
   Both computers were typical Compaq machines _ loaded down with
bells and whistles. Both were very fast in everyday tasks _ opening
applications, saving files, running entertainment and game
software. Compaq continues to improve the software used to run its
Internet Keyboard. It's now much easier to customize than it was in
previous incarnations.
</P>
<P>
   They also had excellent sound. The 5600i's Monster sound card
can be configured to run up to four speakers, for dramatic and
realistic surround-sound effects.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOT EVERYTHING WENT SMOOTHLY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both machines also had serious problems with the video card. The
Viper V550, which uses nVidia's Riva TNT chipset, is notorious for
its buggy drivers. On the 5600i and occasionally on the 5600S, the
system would lock up midway through the boot-up process and the
video would die. Compaq even supplied me with a second 5600i, and
it had the same behavior.
</P>
<P>
   I also was unable to run a very popular children's drawing
program, Broderbund's KidPix Studio Deluxe, on either machine. The
program generated the dreaded Blue Screen of Death, forcing a
system reboot.
</P>
<P>
   The boot-up problem was fixed in both machines by getting the
latest drivers from Diamond's Web site _ if you buy a 5600 series
machine with the Viper V550, that Web site should be your first
stop on the Net! _ but it did not cure the KidPix problem. My two
daughters were bummed.
</P>
<P>
   The home networking component worked as advertised. A setup
wizard instantly configured the machines for a network, rebooted
once, and the machines were immediately talking to each other. It
was similar to the setup process included in the upcoming Windows
98 Second Edition (see last week's review at
www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/99/05/28/compute.html).
Advanced users can use the Network module in the Windows Control
Panel to add other features and protocols.
</P>
<P>
   I was able to talk on the phone, with no noticeable loss of
volume or voice quality, while the two machines were using the
network.
</P>
<P>
   The connection, which operates at 1 megabit a second, is
considerably slower than Ethernet speeds of 10 or 100 megabits, but
still was fast enough for most uses. Games, printing and
modem-sharing were just fine. The only use that bogged the system
down was the copying of large files from one computer to the other.
That, which is almost instantaneous with 10- and 100-megabit
networks, seems interminable with a 1-megabit connection.
</P>
<P>
   In testing the K6III versus the Pentium III chips, I found that
the two were quite competitive so long as the applications involved
used AMD's 3D Now extensions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there is a 3D Now version of id Software's Quake
II. I ran it on the 5600S, and the game was just as fast as it was
on the Pentium III machine. But if I ran the regular version of
Quake II on the 5600S, it was noticeably slower than the Pentium
III-based 5600i.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I can heartily recommend the Compaq FP700 digital
flat-panel monitor. Its display is very bright and crisp, so long
as you use it in 1,024-by-768-pixel resolution. As is the case with
most flat-panel monitors, the image degrades when you switch to
what's called ``non-native'' resolutions, but the FP700 is better
than most. You'll need a graphics card that can accept the special
digital connection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
