<HEADLINE>
WHEN PORTAL DOWNLOAD LED TO PROBLEMS, READER WORKED OUT WAYS TO
RESOLVE THEM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Two or three weeks ago, I downloaded a version of Internet
Explorer 5.0 from ZDNet. It was a fairly simple matter to delete
the bookmarks that were included in the ZDNet package and change
the ZDNet homepage to my preferred homepage, but I was left with
two other annoying remnants of the portal download: a hyperkinetic
ZDNet logo where the Microsoft spinning globe usually resides in
the upper right-hand corner of the browser, and a ``brought to you
by ZD University'' notation in the title bar.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, according to a CNet Web article, is to uninstall
the portal version and reinstall a clean version from Microsoft.
Fine, except that requires another long, quirky download from
Microsoft, which was the reason for downloading from ZDNet in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Through trial and error and reading the newsgroups, I worked out
some alternative solutions.
</P>
<P>
   First, the animated logo is a .bmp graphic stack. I did a ZD
file search and found it in the Signup folder inside the Microsoft
Internet folder. I modified the name of the file and opened the
browser to see if that worked. The ZDNet logo was gone and the MS
globe was back.
</P>
<P>
   Now I can safely delete the ZDNet .bmp stack. The title bar
notation problem involved an unguided excursion into the registry.
After opening the registry with regedit, I used the Find command on
the Edit menu and located the file with the offending phrase under
HKEYLOCALMACHINESOFTWAREMicrosoftInternet ExplorerMain. I
right-clicked on the ``Window Title'' file icon, selected Modify,
and deleted the advertising notation.
</P>
<P>
   If I work up enough courage to go back, I may try adding a
phrase to personalize the title bar. I don't know if this will work
for anyone else, but I'm happy to be able to open Internet Explorer
without all the advertising.
</P>
<P>
   A: That's an excellent tip. Many people got IE5 from these
portal sites because the Microsoft download area was so sluggish
from overcrowding. But they were stuck with so-called ``branded''
versions of the browser. I suspect your note will draw a lot of
interest!
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I've heard from quite a few readers who have had
problems with the klunky IE5 setup process, in which users must
download a program that, in turn, downloads the rest of the
browser. The best solution is to order the CD from the Web site at
cdorder.one.microsoft.com/ie5/default.asp.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am interested in copying the setup components of the
Windows 98 installation CD to my hard drive to make it simpler when
I install software that calls for the CD. However, there's a lot of
stuff on there, most of which I suspect I don't need. What folders
should I copy over?
</P>
<P>
   A: The primary folder for the Windows 98 setup is the Win98
folder. This includes the setup routine and all the .CAB files,
which contain the ``ingredients'' for building Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   You may also want to copy over the Drivers folder, though this
is seldom used except for a full install of the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you might browse through the ToolsReskit folder _ there
are some interesting Help files that might be worth having on your
hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am thinking about building my next computer. I've bought a
recent book, and nothing looks too complicated. However, a friend
of mine mentioned that the different components that I'm
considering have not been tested for compatibility with each other,
and may cause frequent crashes. What's your take on this?
</P>
<P>
   A: You should be fairly safe if you choose name-brand
components, particularly for the video card, modem and motherboard.
Off-brands may not have been tested with each other, but the name
brands are your best bet for compatibility.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
