<HEADLINE>
NO, IT'S NOT MTV. ANDREW COPELAND REALLY DID WIN ON THE `THE PRICE
IS RIGHT' 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By BILL DeYOUNG   The Gainesville Sun   c.1999 N.Y. Times News
Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ If you don't think the world turns in
mysterious ways, consider the case of Andrew Copeland, singer and
songwriter for Sister Hazel, the million-selling rock 'n' roll band
from Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland and the rest of the group are in Los Angeles recording
their second album for Universal Records. On Monday, Copeland took
the afternoon off and while visiting Mann's Chinese Theatre, he and
girlfriend, Cari Cascio, were given free passes to a nearby taping
of ``The Price is Right.'' With nothing else to do, they went to
the CBS-TV studio.
</P>
<P>
   Before you could say ``it's all for you,'' the announcer was
calling out ``Drew Copeland! Come on down!'' and the 31-year-old
pop star was a contestant on America's longest-running game show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole time I'm thinking, `This isn't really happening,' ''
said Copeland, who _ as is his custom _ took his shoes off before
walking onto the stage. ``It looks like you need to win some
shoes,'' Bob Barker joked, and then announced that Copeland would
be a contestant in a game for ``A Brand New Car!''
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is, you pick these numbers and they flip them
over, and if you spell C-A-R, or if one card has a picture of a car
on it, you win the car,'' Copeland explained. He had to bid on
three items _ a pot-and-pan set, a water purifier and a pottery
wheel. To everyone's surprise, especially his, he got them all
correct and was handed the keys to a 2000 Ford Escort.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell I wasn't even planning on being there,''
Copeland said. ``Bob asked me what I did for a living, and I said I
was in a band ...'' He never mentioned Sister Hazel, or the fact
that his group has a platinum album. ``I'm thinking, I'm here
cheesing out on `The Price is Right,' I don't need to be dragging
the band into it.' '' He did, however, admit to Barker that he
didn't know how to play the game. ``Bob whispered `Just pretend
that you do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Copeland made it to the Showcase Showdown, but he doesn't
remember much about it (``I'm still trippin' because I just won a
car''). He didn't win the Fiji vacation or the year's supply of
Rice-a-Roni. He pledged to Barker that the Escort was to be a gift
for his father, Jack Copeland, back in Gainesville. Bob liked that.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, it was back to the studio, where Sister Hazel's
album is being produced by Mike Clink, who handled ``Appetite For
Destruction'' for Guns 'N Roses, way back when.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in the group, Copeland says, believed that he was
actually a contestant on ``The Price is Right,'' much less that he
won A Brand New Car.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be singing a different song when the show airs on CBS at
11 a.m. Friday, June 11.
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville Sun is part of The New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
