<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3444 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AIRPOWER-$ADV0     06-04 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AIRPOWER-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS LEARNED: ADVOCATES OF AIR POWER SAY KOSOVO WAS A SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a peace agreement near in Kosovo, advocates of
military air power are triumphantly claiming that sustained allied
bombing for 10 weeks was the key factor in forcing Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to accept peace terms.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful air armada of 720 American aircraft and 348 allied
aircraft made more than 33,000 flights or sorties since the bombing
campaign began March 24; some 14,000 bombs and precision guided
weapons were dropped on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But the most notable statistic in the campaign was a zero: Not a
single NATO pilot was lost to enemy fire.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, NATO officials estimate that the air attacks
inflicted more than 10,000 Yugoslav casualties and destroyed
hundreds of artillery pieces, armored personnel carriers and tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The air campaign had to overcome bad weather, a cumbersome
political process to select targets and high-profile blunders such
as the accidental bombings of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade by a
B-2 stealth bomber and of Kosovo Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But for boosters of air power, the bottom line added up to a
huge success.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Merrill McPeak, a former Air Force chief of staff,
boasted that ``a lot of the so-called expert projections didn't
turn out to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People said the B-2 would never be used in combat; it was used
over downtown Belgrade. Then there were people predicting
Yugoslavia had a very rugged air defense network and that we would
lose pilots; none of that happened,'' McPeak said.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``absolutely amazing'' that NATO suffered no casualties
to enemy fire, McPeak said. ``If any wild-eyed air power advocate
had made that prediction before the conflict, they would have been
laughed out of town,'' McPeak said.
</P>
<P>
   Two U.S. planes were shot down, including a U.S. F-117A stealth
jet, but their pilots were rescued. Two Apache helicopter crewmen
died in a training accident.
</P>
<P>
   In six weeks of bombing during the Persian Gulf War, 19 U.S.
airmen were killed in action.
</P>
<P>
   McPeak said that the Kosovo operation validated the Air Force's
post-Gulf War emphasis on developing better precision-guided
weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Air Force Lt. Gen. Buster Glosson, the architect of air
operations during the Persian Gulf War, said the Kosovo conflict
proved that air power could hasten victory on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict underscores that ``anytime air power can be
decisive and reach a political end, it should be the force of
choice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major lesson is that you should have the patience to let
air power take the maximum toll it can before putting one Marine or
soldier on the ground,'' Glosson added.
</P>
<P>
   A big congressional booster of air power, Rep. Norm Dicks,
D-Wash., a senior member of the House defense appropriations
subcommittee, said Kosovo ``will vindicate'' air power advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of people who didn't buy the idea that we
could prevail in a conflict without putting ground forces in, and I
shared some of that skepticism,'' said Dicks, whose district
includes the Boeing Co., manufacturer of the B-2 bomber.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have air power and you don't lose any human lives but
you achieve your political objective _ it doesn't get much better
than that,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness of air power has been studied at the nation's
military academies for 50 years, and the conflict in Kosovo no
doubt will add more chapters to the textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Some military experts contend that air attacks on Yugoslavia
weren't the only reason Milosevic backed down.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Lt. Col. Ralph Peters, a former Army intelligence
officer who has written widely on military matters, said that a
convergence of events forced Milosevic to accept peace terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question air power did the heavy lifting,'' Peters
said. But he argued that air power was helped by a little noticed
force of ground troops _ the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA, consisting mainly of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo,
forced units of the Yugoslav army to come out of the hiding places
they had built to conceal themselves from the air attacks.
</P>
<P>
   That in turn made the Yugoslav units vulnerable to NATO strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't hitting them hard, but suddenly, when they had to
emerge from hiding, air power could do its job,'' Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said the KLA has become a viable fighting force
of nearly 15,000 troops that has made successful hit-and-run
attacks against Yugoslav forces operating in Kosovo over the last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Peters also contended that the recent war crimes indictment of
Milosevic by a U.N. tribunal in The Netherlands was ``a lynch pin
move'' that added to Milosevic's change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The indictment personalized the conflict and probably really
spooked Milosevic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Steinbruner, a military expert with the Brookings
Institution, a non-partisan think tank, argued that strong hints
from NATO of a possible ground attack played a central role in
forcing Milosevic to back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has produced the agreement was the unmistakable sign in
the last couple of weeks that NATO was moving towards a ground
operation. That was the threat that mattered,'' Steinbruner said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the success of air power, the conflict in Kosovo
provided other valuable ``lessons learned,'' military experts said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, McPeak said President Clinton's announced position
at the outset of the air war that the United States wasn't planning
for a ground invasion gave Milosevic reason to dig in his troops
for the long haul and wait out the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should never, ever give up options at the beginning of a
contest. All that did was raise the bar for air power and make a
self-inflicted strategic setback,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Glosson said that the campaign was unnecessarily long because
military planners delayed bombing many key targets such as the
electrical grid and other infrastructure until the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had paralyzed them in the first two weeks, this would
have been over in about five or six weeks,'' Glosson said.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid allied casualties, most NATO pilots were ordered to
stay above 15,000 feet to avoid surface-to-air missiles. This made
accurate bombing more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The altitude limitations _ combined with Clinton's resistance to
plan for a ground war _ was a case study in how not to wage war,
said Maj. Gen. Lewis MacKenzie, a retired Canadian army officer who
has conducted peace keeping operations in Bosnia on behalf of the
United Nations in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had come up with a solution like that at the U.S. Army
War college, I wouldn't have been failed, I would have been sent
home for incompetence,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
