<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3463 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GO-HOME-$ADV06     06-04 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GO-HOME-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSNIAN CONFLICT SUGGESTS REFUGEES MAY NOT RETURN TO KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that the allied onslaught against Yugoslavia
has cleared the way for an estimated 1.6 million displaced
residents of Kosovo to eventually return home, will they?
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton remains convinced that almost all displaced
ethnic Albanians will return to their agrarian, mountainous
homeland, White House aides say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You listen to the people, the refugees who the president spoke
to, and I think you get the very real sense that these people very
much want to go home,'' White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart
said Friday. ``And they want to go home as soon as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a radio message to the people of Kosovo last week,
emphasized steps being taken by the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization and the United States to provide security and
humanitarian assistance once the Kosovars return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will return,'' Clinton vowed. ``Remember that no matter
what has happened to you, you are not alone. The United States and
NATO are with you, and we will stay with you long after you return
home.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials underscore that the NATO alliance waged the first
war in its 50-year history to enable uprooted Kosovars to return
home.
</P>
<P>
   But if history is any guide, the U.S.-led effort may face an
uphill struggle persuading refugees to return to Kosovo, a province
of Serbia, which is the dominant republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   More than three years after a U.S.-brokered peace agreement
ended a four-year conflict in neighboring Bosnia that claimed
200,000 lives, barely 574,000 of the 1.8 million uprooted Bosnians
have returned to their homes, according to U.N. refugee officials.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining Bosnian refugees have elected not to return to
their homes because ``their home villages are now controlled by an
ethnic group other than their own,'' according to refugee officials
at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 700,000 Bosnian refugees who fled to Europe, for example,
nearly 400,000 are still living in their adoptive countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of the return program hinges primarily upon the
removal of local obstructionism blocking the returns of
minorities,'' the U.N. says. Other impediments include destroyed
homes, devastated sewer, power and water facilities and the
residual threat of unexploded land mines.
</P>
<P>
   Recovery efforts are lagging as well in Bosnia, where
international donations to a $5.1 billion recovery fund are falling
behind.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials say they remain confident that the
experience in Bosnia will not afflict refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bosnia conflict stretched out over a much longer period
and people were out (of their homes) for a much longer time,''
Lockhart said. ``The vast majority of refugees from Kosovo remain
in the region nearby.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees says almost 850,000
predominantly Muslim Kosovars were driven out of the province by
the Yugoslav army and police forces, mostly after the NATO bombing
campaign began in March.
</P>
<P>
   Another 76,475 have found temporary refuge in 28 nations,
including the United States. An estimated 700,000 Kosovars remain
uprooted inside Kosovo, driven from their homes and too frightened
to return.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the way is cleared for repatriation, major obstacles
remain. Yugoslav forces have destroyed homes and villages abandoned
by the ethnic Albanians. In addition, the refugees say soldiers and
border guards confiscated their passports and other identity papers
in an effort to impede their return.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.N. refugee specialists say they are gearing up to assist
refugees interested in leaving tent cities in Albania, Macedonia
and elsewhere and return home. But, adds the U.N. agency in a
statement: ``The return of refugees and the displaced will depend
on the security situation in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to making preparations to help Kosovo refugees to
home, U.N. officials say they also are laying the groundwork for
Kosovo refugees who elect not to return.
</P>
<P>
   Uprooted Kosovars must have ``a free, voluntary and
well-informed decision regarding repatriation or return,'' with
assurances that Kosovars ``who are not willing or able to return to
Kosovo can continue to receive protection and necessary
assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. agency vows that it will ``begin to facilitate
repatriation and return movements only after being satisfied that
all necessary preconditions have been met and that return can take
place in conditions of safety and dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
e-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0605-C     06-04 1540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH KOSOVO PEACE PLAN, CLINTON APPEARS TO PULL VICTORY FROM
JAWS OF DEFEAT-- BUT WITH A PRICE
 &HT;    1000&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-KLA-0605.
 &HT;    EDs: An analysis sig may be used with this story.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last February, as Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic pressed forward with his bloody assault on Kosovo,
President Clinton huddled with his national security team to review
the grim slate of options before him.
</P>
<P>
   It was, Clinton's deputy national security adviser James
Steinberg later recalled, a sober session with no good alternatives
and NATO air strikes appeared increasingly likely.
</P>
<P>
   On the central point, though, Clinton seemed resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president himself said 'I don't think we should assume
that Milosevic is going to give in to the first wave of strikes,'''
Steinberg recalled. Said Clinton, ``We have to be prepared to
follow through on this.''
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, having led an international coalition through 2 1/2
months of high-stakes bombing, Clinton appeared headed for a
landmark victory in the Balkans, with Milosevic capitulating to a
set of demands Clinton has articulated without waiver through week
after week of an often difficult campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It is a triumph tempered by tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the world's mightiest alliance, it turned out, could
halt the bloodshed and terror that put more than one million ethnic
Albanians to flight.
</P>
<P>
   Most will have the chance to return to their land, however, just
as Clinton repeatedly promised they would. If their suffering
couldn't be prevented, he has said, at least there's the chance it
might be reversed.
</P>
<P>
   For an impeached and acquitted president who has struggled to
find the proper role for the last remaining superpower in the post
Cold War world, taking risks and standing firm to strike a blow
against ethnic repression in Europe seemed a fitting close to the
bloodiest century on record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in Kosovo because we want to replace ethnic cleansing
with tolerance and decency,'' Clinton said in April, in a speech
here to open the 50th anniversary of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are fundamentally there because the alliance will not
have meaning in the 21st Century if it permits the slaughter of
innocents on its doorstep,'' Clinton said. ``This is not a question
of territorial conquest or political domination, but standing for
the values that made NATO possible in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Just six months after being impeached by the House for charges
stemming from his relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky, Clinton's leadership stands to be vindicated by
victory in a stark and brutal land that was once as remote to U.S.
interests as it is forboding.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Americans, Clinton knew or cared little about the
Balkans six years ago: he's since learned more than he ever wanted
to know.
</P>
<P>
   He began his education by reading Robert Kaplan's book ``Balkan
Ghosts,'' a tableau of centuries of ethnic violence in the tortured
region. For three years, Clinton assuaged his guilt over inaction
in Bosnia by telling himself there was little to be done to stop
the cycle of murder and revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I regret it now more than I can say, for I have spent a
great deal of time in these last six years reading the real history
of the Balkans,'' Clinton confessed last month during a speech at
the National Defense University here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that a lot of what passes for common wisdom in
this area is a gross over-simplification and misreading of
history,'' Clinton said. ``The truth is that for centuries these
people have lived together in the Balkans in Southeastern Europe,
with greater or lesser degree of tensions, but often without
anything approaching the intolerable conditions and conflicts that
exist today.''
</P>
<P>
   After Serbs unleashed 3 1/2 years of atrocities on Bosnia,
leaving a quarter of a million people dead and some 3 million
homeless, Clinton led NATO to air strikes and peace talks that
ended that conflict in November, 1995. He was determined, aides
said, not to stand by and watch a similar tragedy unfold in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``His experience in Bosnia and seeing the ethnic cleansing there
has stiffened his resolve to stand against it here (in Kosovo),''
said Clinton's long-time political adviser, Paul Begala, who left
the White House earlier this year to teach government at Georgetown
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is like the welfare bill,'' said Begala,
referring to the split-the-difference instincts that have guided
much of Clinton's political career. ``I think he approaches this
with an extraordinary sense of resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   Having looked on in frustration and even anger as Serbs violated
48 separate cease-fires in Bosnia before finally agreeing to the
Dayton peace accords, Clinton developed a deep and almost visceral
distrust of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   When the Serb leader agreed last October, under the threat of
NATO air strikes, to end his campaign of repression against ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, Clinton was disappointed, but not surprised,
to see him renege on those commitments -- citing terrorist
activities by Kosovar rebels -- as he continued to do from December
until air strikes were launched March 24.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks that followed, Clinton stood fast by his core
position: the air strikes would continue until Milosevic pulled his
troops out of Kosovo and agreed to turn over control of the
province to a NATO-led peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   There were intense pressures on Clinton to ease up, particularly
after the first three weeks of the campaign, during which Serb
troops, police and paramilitary gangs went on a rampage of murder,
destruction, rape and pillage that ran an estimated 1.5 million
ethnic Albanians from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights activist Jesse Jackson, whose influence over black
voters has bought him remarkable cache with Clinton, urged him to
halt the bombing a month ago and try to negotiate a settlement with
Milosevic. While that surely lent succor to Milosevic, Clinton
didn't nibble.
</P>
<P>
   He stood his ground, also, against criticism from other
quarters, voices urging him to escalate the fighting by sending in
ground forces or Apache helicopters, either of which would have
guaranteed American casualties. Clinton stuck instead to his
conviction that Americans had a low threshold of pain for Kosovo,
and he refused to place the mission at risk by asking his country
to pay a cost few were willing to bear.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pressed on through other trials as well, including a
Congress deeply divided over the air strikes and an excruciating
series of NATO errors that killed hundreds of civilians, many of
them the very ethnic Albanian refugees the alliance was trying to
protect.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton even rode out the mistaken bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade, a grotesque blunder by the U.S. intelligence
community that set relations between the United States and the
world's most populous nation careening down a dangerous path at a
critical moment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warded off inner anxieties as well, and made no attempt
to conceal them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not relish every night sending young Americans and our
NATO allies up in planes, flying very fast under very hazardous
circumstances in which their safety is at risk,'' Clinton said
during a May 3 press conference. ``I do not relish the thought
that, inevitably, some of those bombs will go astray and some
Serbian civilians or some Kosovar civilians could be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   He even felt compelled to explain himself to a group of
Democratic supporters in Austin, Texas, last month, saying the use
of military force runs counter to his nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not that sort of person,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But let me tell you,'' he continued. ``Ethnic cleansing, and
killing people wholesale because of their race or religion, is
wrong. And the United States is in a position to stand against it,
and we ought to.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the air war staggered through week after inconclusive
week, Clinton's will to persist appeared to be strengthened by the
actions of Serb forces inside Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   On May 6, Clinton spent several hours visiting in Ingelheim,
Germany with ethnic Albanians who had fled Kosovo. As he listened
to them, some sobbing as they recounted the horrors they had
witnessed _ a woman who had seen her brother shot to death; a
teacher forced to watch as Serbs beat his students; a mother who
had no idea what had become of her children _Clinton seemed to take
strength from their suffering, even as he sought to lend them
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let yourself be broken by this,'' Clinton implored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll look for your students and we'll look for your family
members,'' he pledged. ``But remember, you cannot give a victory to
the kind of oppression you have been subject to. We cannot see
these children robbed of their childhood. And the adults, the older
among you, you must not let the younger people lose heart. And we
will stay at it until you can go home again.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
