</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-AWARDS-$ADV06-ART-940&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWARDS GALA EXCEEDS EXPECTATIONS FOR TEDIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Italy)   (For release Sunday, June 6)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first and by no means only foul-up at the Council
of Fashion Designers of America's annual awards gala last Wednesday
was that hardly any of the guests at the Lexington Avenue armory
could see one another. This was crushing: 1,200 of New York's most
glamorous people poured into a kind of holding room for cocktails
and _ sink! _ it looked like a cave. Somebody had draped the room
in black and dimmed the lights. You had to be practically on top of
a person to see who it was.
</P>
<P>
   And pretty soon it could have been Calvin Klein or Donna Karan,
Michael Kors or Hugh Grant and his girlfriend, Liz Hurley _ all in
this madhouse, in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   The awards evening has a reputation for being longer, duller and
ultimately less fun than almost any such event, and it surpassed
expectations this year as technical delays _ presumably caused by
the ceremony's being televised for the first time _ turned it into
a six-and-a-half-hour ordeal of dinner, speeches and wilting
hairdos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand any of this,'' said a nonplused John
Fairchild, the former publisher of Women's Wear Daily, whose snowy
cap of hair made him more visible than others. He had flown in from
London, where he lives these days, to present a lifetime
achievement award to Yves Saint Laurent. ``I'm just here for Saint
Laurent,'' Fairchild said, shouting above a cocktail-lounge band
that was flailing away in the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Nan Kempner, a Saint Laurent stalwart, said, ``I was going to
wear long, but Yves told me to wear short, and I'm glad I did.''
She had given a lunch that day for the designer; about 20 people,
including Bill Blass, Pat Buckley and members of Saint Laurent's
entourage, had spinach souffle in her Park Avenue apartment.
</P>
<P>
   It was 12:30 a.m. when the show at the armory finally ended,
though by then nearly half of the tables were empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excruciating,'' Mrs. Kempner said the next day. ``I thought if
I sat there any longer I could claim squatter's rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Leeds, a former Seventh Avenue executive who now runs
his own capital management firm, bailed out around 11. ``The
evening just took too long,'' he said, ``considerably too long. You
can't expect people who work the next day to sit there.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-and-a-half-hour show, to be broadcast on June 13 on the
E! cable channel, certainly had some captivating moments: the
tributes to Saint Laurent; the elation of young design winners like
Josh Patner and Bryan Bradley of Tuleh, who captured a Perry Ellis
award for new talent in women's wear, and the emotions expressed by
Andrew Tilberis, who accepted a humanitarian award for his wife,
Elizabeth Tilberis, the Harper's Bazaar editor in chief who died in
April. He made their life together vivid when he said: ``There was
a private Liz. Not your Liz. My Liz.''
</P>
<P>
   As Anna Wintour, the editor in chief of Vogue, said later, ``All
the good will just ran out because it was simply too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Length wasn't the only problem. From the outset, the show lacked
a sophistication worthy of the industry. Around 9:30, as guests
were still picking through their dinner and fanning themselves with
the menu cards, a voice announced in the soap-bubble tone of a
game-show host that the ``festivities'' were about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Festivities? It sounded as though the audience was expected to
rise up in couture silks and start bashing a pinata.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it was hard to deny that some of this nuttiness was
mesmerizing. It was like being in a giant massage parlor for the
demand-feeding ego, with design winners thanking fashion editors
and editors thanking designers, and celebrities doing their best to
make the event seem more important than it was. When the actress
Julianne Moore, the ceremony's hostess, got up to announce that
Sophia Loren wasn't there to accept her style award, she looked
ready to crumble with mortification. ``I'm so sorry,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As the show got under way, the first honoree, Yohji Yamamoto,
presented a synopsis of his spring collection. As the models came
out on a runway in the middle of the room and artfully began to
shed a layer of their outfits, young women dressed in black darted
onto the platform, like ball girls at Wimbledon, and retrieved
them.
</P>
<P>
   Then Andre Leon Talley, Vogue's contributing editor at large,
strode out to present Yamamoto's award. He was dressed regally even
for Talley, who is known for his flamboyance: He wore a long black
coat, lace shirt, cummerbund and glimmering stole _ a potentate as
imagined by Shakespeare. He said a few words and Yamamoto clambered
onto the stage.
</P>
<P>
   A modest man, Yamamoto said that Talley had advised him that
saying only ``thank you'' might seem rude. So Yamamoto said,
``Thank you very much.'' This drew laughs. He added that he was
humbled to be in the presence of Laurent, whom he called a god, and
said, ``My feet are shaking, my heart is pumping and my brain is
screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   One would have thought the show's producers would have moved
Saint Laurent's acceptance speech, the evening's main draw, up in
the program _ what with all the gathering sentiment. The Tuleh
designers acknowledged Saint Laurent. So did Bette Midler, who, as
she gave an award to Simon Doonan, the Barneys New York window
dresser, joked that she was ``in front of God _ that's apparently
Yves Saint Laurent.'' And when Marc Jacobs' turn came to accept a
statuette for accessories, he was apparently so overawed that he
said of the award Saint Laurent was still waiting to get, ``It's
not a lifetime achievement, it's an achievement for a life.''
</P>
<P>
   Saint Laurent still had to wait until the bitter end, about
12:10 a.m.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the evening wore on, the gaps between segments seemed to
lengthen, with nothing to stop the audience from sinking into a
trough of boredom after the occasional big laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The comedian Chris Rock came out to give a menswear award to
Calvin Klein. Rock has been known to tomahawk many a person with
his wit, and he let Klein have it with a couple of jokes about
their imagined childhood together. But after Klein had graciously
accepted his award, the audience plunged back into boredom.
</P>
<P>
   On it went. One can only guess how people passed the lulls. At
Giorgio Armani's table, where the actress Claire Forlani sat with
members of the designer's publicity staff (he was in Italy), Robert
Triefus gamely held Ms. Forlani's cigarette while she powdered her
nose and recounted her exploits in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Up on the stage, Matt Nye, wearing a tight French nautical
sweater that verged on an off-the-shoulder top, accepted the Perry
Ellis young designer's award for menswear. There was light
applause. It was nearly midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Then Saint Laurent stepped on stage and the audience rose. He
spoke in broken English, saying that fashion was ``a source of
immense joy and immense anguish.''
</P>
<P>
   But can anyone really understand what such passion means in a
soap-bubble era? Before Saint Laurent spoke, a video was shown of
last year's World Cup in France, when Saint Laurent models, maybe
500 in all, marched somberly around the stadium. How many other
designers can claim an allegiance on a par with that of a national
sport?
</P>
<P>
   It was the most powerful image of a thoroughly lopsided evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
