<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-INDULGENCE-ART-$ADV06-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 PRICE IS NO OBJECT.com  
 (For release Sun., June 6)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)(jt) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What's the modern way to buy a corporate jet?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just click,'' said James Finkelstein, sitting at a mahogany
conference table in his midtown office, and casting the occasional
adoring look at his wife of 16 months, Pamela Gross. She returned
the affection, playing with his ear lobe.
</P>
<P>
   And what's the modern way to buy caviar from Le Cirque 2000? Or
diamond earrings in Asprey &AMP; Garrard's signature daisy shape?
</P>
<P>
   Click. Click.
</P>
<P>
   If everything goes as planned, the above items and more will be
available on the Internet in August, as part of a plan by
Finkelstein and Ms. Gross to wire the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, as faithful readers of the party pages may recall,
were married in a 1998 ceremony at Le Cirque attended by a who's
who of the social Upper East Side, including Nina Griscom and Dan
Baker, Blaine and Robert Trump, Judy and Alfred Taubman, Vera Wang
and Arthur Becker, Leonard and Allison Stern, Allan and Deborah
Grubman, and Pauline and Dixon Boardman.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gross was one of the founding editors of Manhattan File, the
trendy, young magazine distributed only to oh-so-social buildings
on Fifth Avenue and environs. Finkelstein, 50, is a son of
Manhattan File's original owner, Jerry Finkelstein, who made his
fortune investing in securities, real estate and publishing,
including owning The New York Law Journal and a string of weekly
papers. The younger Finkelstein, took over The New York Law
Journal, founded The National Law Journal and put them both on the
Internet. He eventually sold the company to the Wasserstein Perella
Group for $203 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a new project, the couple hit upon what came natural
_ amassing the accoutrements of a well-cushioned life in Park
Avenue duplexes, and intermingling business with social ties.
</P>
<P>
   They founded LuxuryFinder.com, an E-commerce site that will sell
high-end merchandise like Ghurka luggage, Brioni men's accessories
and hair-care products from John Barrett of Bergdorf Goodman. It
will offer online services like an ``electronic secretary'' to
alert subscribers when the latest handbag has arrived at Fendi, and
online chats with Ms. Wang, the designer, or Sirio Maccioni, owner
of Le Cirque, who will also sell his caviar and petit-fours.
</P>
<P>
   To finance the venture _ put at $15 to $20 million by one person
familiar with the deal _ Finkelstein tapped a network of ultra-rich
New Yorkers, many of whom were eager to participate in the Internet
gold rush they'd been reading about in the financial pages, and
knew the founders of LuxuryFinder.com socially (most of them were
at the wedding).
</P>
<P>
   The investors _ whose stakes amount to six-figure pocket change
for many _ include Leonard Stern, the chairman of the Hartz
Mountain pet food and real estate empire; Allen Grubman, the
entertainment lawyer whose clients include Madonna and Michael
Jackson; Leon Black, who heads Apollo Management, one of the
country's largest private investment companies; Dixon Boardman, the
managing director of the Optima Fund, and Terry Allen Kramer, a
Broadway producer whose father was a founder of the investment firm
Allen &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happened to bump into him, probably at a dinner party in
Southampton,'' Stern said, recalling how he and Finkelstein first
got together on the Web deal. The exact date is hard to pinpoint,
he said, because ``we populate the same world.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said he broke his own rule of never investing in a
friend's business. ``I asked Jimmy what he was doing,'' he said.
``It sounded good and I said, `Come down to my office and we'll
talk.'''
</P>
<P>
   Another investor, Fred Seegal _ he's the man who recently sold
his East Hampton beach house to Helmut Lang for $15 million _
remembered, ``Jimmy called up and said, `Here's what I'm doing,'
and I said, `Great.''' Seegal, who is the president of Wasserstein
Perella, the boutique investment bank, added, ``Jimmy is a winner.
All he had to do was call.''
</P>
<P>
   For his first venture into E-commerce, Finkelstein looked to a
Lord _ Lord Charles Spencer-Churchill, a grandson of Winston
Churchill _ to conduct chat sessions on life at Blenheim Palace. An
online concierge will make those hard-to-get reservations at the
Ritz in Paris. A calendar will show all the right events _ Ascot,
the Hamptons Classic, Wimbledon, the Deauville season.
</P>
<P>
   And a taste council, including a former buyer from Bergdorf's
and two magazine editors, will provide online editorial features
and the answers to questions to help educate the newly wealthy on
what the moneyed class buys. ``There are all these people out there
who have made all this money and don't know what the best sheet is
or what the best cufflinks are,'' said Ms. Gross, who intends to
help them learn.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gross, who is in her late 30s, is sometimes known to friends
as Glamala for her high-maintenance blonde hair, eye-popping
Verdura engagement ring and love of the latest designer must-haves.
</P>
<P>
   She and her taste council will decide which retailers have the
cachet to make it onto the Web site. ``Coach is too low-end,'' she
said, naming one example. ``We're more about Fendi.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Dannenberg, who worked with Ms. Gross at Manhattan File,
is running around with her to old retail contacts and designers to
get them to buy advertising or offer goods online.
</P>
<P>
   They've lined up Prince Dimitri of Yugoslavia and Angela
Cummings, whose cufflinks and jewelry, respectively, are sold at
Bergdorf's. The Gym Source will sell home-exercise equipment
starting at $10,000, and the Web site has a warehouse of antique
furniture, valued from $5,000 to $100,000, that will be sold
online.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done business with Julie wherever she's been,'' said
Philip Warner, president of Asprey &AMP; Garrard of New York, the
American arm of the jewelers to the British royal family. The
company has agreed to sell its popular silver-topped vases ($150
and up) and daisy earrings ($3,000 to $4,900). Beyond that, it is
taking a wait-and-see attitude _ typical of how luxury retailers
have approached the gold-rush-fever of E-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have purchased up to $100,000 sight unseen from our
catalog,'' said Warner, who is optimistic about selling on the
Internet. ``What concerns us is how our product appears and who it
sits next to. We need to be assured ourselves that it is presented
in the right way.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gross and her team have met resistance from some they've
approached, and they hired Peggy Siegal, the publicist known for
corralling a society crowd for movie premieres, to help with
introductions. ``I was brought in as a consultant to get Donna
Karan and Barry Kieselstein-Cord,'' Ms. Siegal said. ``They've got
Barry and they have a meeting with Donna.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growth of online commerce _ a market projected to
grow to $41 billion in 2003 from $3 billion last year by Jupiter
Communications, an Internet researcher _ high-end retailers have
been slow to take the plunge. What is selling best on the Internet
are books, toys, airplane tickets and the bric-a-brac of E-bay.
Blue-chip brands have worried about cheapening their images and
undercutting their traditional retail outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, competition to bring luxury goods to the Web seems
to be brewing. LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton has made recent
investments in Boo.com, a sneaker and active wear source, and
Icollector, an online auctioneer, raising speculation that LVMH may
one day sell its own brands _ including Vuitton, Christian Dior and
Givenchy _ on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The genie is out of the bottle, the Internet is here and there
is a huge opportunity for those who can figure out selling
high-margin products,'' said Joshua Schroeter, director of
strategic planning and founder of the Center of New Media at
Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jupiter figures, 65 percent of online households
earn more than $100,000 a year. ``Hence, that's why there's a
clamor to get into the luxury market,'' said Ford Cavallari, an
E-commerce specialist at Renaissance Worldwide, a Boston-based
management consulting firm. ``It's a wide-open field.''
</P>
<P>
   Next question: do people who buy private jets, like the new
10-seater that LuxuryFinder.com intends to sell for 14.5 million,
surf the Net?
</P>
<P>
   Stern, of Hartz Mountain, admitted, ``Men my age who run
businesses are in the Dark Ages, and they're proud of it. They say,
`I have my secretary print out my e-mail.' They are so rich they
can insulate themselves in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the middle of a revolution,'' he added. Still, he
said, ``No one has been able to explain to my satisfaction where
the profit plan is.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Finkelstein and Ms. Gross' staff numbers 17,
projected to grow to 45 by they time they are up and running. In a
month, they will move into 16,000 square feet of office divided
between two sites, one on East 59th Street and the other on East
49th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have plenty of money invested and a call for more, as much
as I need,'' Finkelstein said, spreading his arms wide. ``I did
turn away a lot of people. I needed serious investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Grubman, the entertainment lawyer, said Finkelstein made his
pitch to him over dinner. ``I thought it was a fabulous idea and I
think he is very, very smart,'' Grubman said, admitting that he is
only just beginning to learn to use a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the promotional parties will begin. They are being planned
for Los Angeles, Manhattan and Southampton, N.Y., where Finkelstein
and Ms. Gross have a new home that was just photographed for Elle
Decor.
</P>
<P>
   While Finkelstein tends to the business plan, Ms. Gross is busy
weighing the thread counts of Pratesi versus Ralph Lauren The
Estate Collection, to determine which should be approached to offer
its products on her site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for the first time there is an upside to my
shopping,'' she said. ``I can say, `I'm researching.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
