<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPS IS DELIVERING FOR LESS FORTUNATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's become popular for companies to put together teams of
employees to pick up trash along highways after work or build
houses for the poor over a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But not many send their managers hundreds of miles away to spend
a month at a soup kitchen or homeless shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The United Parcel Service has a community internship program
that sends about 50 managers each year to four cities so they can
get a first-hand view of the problems some of their customers and
employees face.
</P>
<P>
   They go to such places as New York, Chicago, Chattanooga, Tenn.,
and McAllen, Texas, and spend their days tutoring low-income
children, touring prisons and, in McAllen, riding with the border
patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drive through every neighborhood in America,'' said Don
Wofford, community relations coordinator for UPS in Atlanta. ``We
often don't know what goes on behind the four walls.''
</P>
<P>
   The program, which started in 1968, the year the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr. was assassinated, began as the company's
contribution to the civil rights movement. Since then, 1,100
managers have gone through what for many has become a life-changing
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Tamara Barker, the district plant engineering manager for UPS in
Houston, recently returned from a month at St. Margaret of
Scotland, a shelter and school for low-income children on the South
Side of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Living in the church rectory with six other interns, Barker
cooked and served food for the poor, helped paint a homeless men's
shelter, tutored 9-year-old twins in reading and math, toured a
house for people with AIDS, and toured a drug and alcohol abuse
treatment center.
</P>
<P>
   She also observed a juvenile court case, counseled inmates at
the Cook County Jail on basic skills they will need to get jobs and
took ``her twins'' to a White Sox baseball game, buying every kind
of junk food available.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SOME STAFF COMMITTED FOREVER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was an eye-opening experience, she said, recalling how she
watched from an upstairs window at the rectory as gang members
bought and sold weapons and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we're losing a whole generation of children to drugs
and violence,'' she said. There seems to be a tremendous need to
mentor these kids, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Barker said she is planning to become a volunteer at a school
close to the UPS facility in a low-income neighborhood in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Wofford said UPS hopes managers get more involved with their own
communities after finishing their internships. He said one manager
who returned took a walk around his UPS neighborhood for the first
time and, from that, organized a big food drive during the
Christmas holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Barker also said that she became more sensitive to the problems
of employees living on the edge.
</P>
<P>
   If someone calls in because a car has broken down, they may be
unable to get a ride from a spouse or take a cab, she said. ``You
take a cab and that could be meals for a week.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TOUR OF AREA IN NEED LED TO IDEA &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Daniel Mallette, pastor of St. Margaret of Scotland,
said the UPS interns ``just shoot so much life into this parish.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallette said the latest group installed a water heater for a
family whose six children had just buried their mother.
</P>
<P>
   The work the UPS managers do influences the lives of many people
in the community, he said, recalling Barker's work with a teen-age
boy who was shot while sitting on a porch in his neighborhood. She
really connected with the 14-year-old, who spends 18 hours a day on
intravenous feeding.
</P>
<P>
   Several PS volunteers return on their own to help out, he said,
and one invites a child he met during his internship to his ranch
in South Dakota each summer.
</P>
<P>
   Mallette first encountered the UPS program in 1968. He was
working in New York for Fordham University trying to recruit and
raise money for black, Puerto Rican and poor white children to
attend college.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting with Walter Hooke, then a vice president of UPS, led
to the company making a grant of stock that generated about $70,000
a year _ enough to send 70 students to college.
</P>
<P>
   Hooke was interested in civil rights so Mallette took him around
the community. From that, the internship program was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless UPS,'' Mallette said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
