<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAPEZE-THERAPY-2TAKE     06-04 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAPEZE-THERAPY-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREATEST OF UNEASE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCLEAN, Va. _ I'm not sure what I was thinking when I decided to
fly the trapeze. In retrospect, it seems, I wasn't thinking at all.
</P>
<P>
   I arrived at Circus Arts Workshop, an outdoor trapeze rig here,
to meet Sam Keen, the author of ``Learning to Fly: Trapeze _
Reflections on Fear, Trust and the Joy of Letting Go,'' (Broadway
Books, 1999; $23).
</P>
<P>
   Keen is based in Sonoma, Calif., where he runs a program called
Upward Bound, teaching people to use the trapeze experience as a
mechanism to examine their own fears about life. It has been
particularly successful with abused women and recovering drug
addicts, but garden variety neurotics like me have also been able
to benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The act of climbing a 35-foot ladder, grabbing the trapeze,
swinging out and, ideally, being caught by someone swinging toward
you, seems to make sense as an exercise in fear and trust. And
unlike Outward Bound, it takes only a few hours and I could plug in
my hair dryer when it was over.
</P>
<P>
   Keen is 67 _ another incentive, I felt, figuring that if he can
do it, I certainly could. He first discovered the joy of letting go
at 62. He discovered more joy when Broadway Books gave him a
$500,000 advance to write ``Learning to Fly,'' envisioning it as
the next ``Zen and the Art of Motorcycle Maintenance,'' the Robert
Pirsig classic.
</P>
<P>
   Circus Arts is owned by Michel Bigotti and Laurent Givry, former
instructors for Club Med, and offers classes ($30 for one, less for
a series), birthday parties and corporate events. Though Bigotti
and Givry wore shorts and jeans, Keen arrived clad in tights and
slippers.
</P>
<P>
   He looked like a bony old bird, his frame lean and spare from
years of flying. He has bright, hard blue eyes and talks about the
trapeze with the passion of a preacher, which he is, having
graduated from the Harvard Divinity School and Princeton University
with a PhD in philosophy of religion.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years he was an editor at Psychology Today, and
``Learning to Fly'' is his 14th book. His previous one, ``Fire in
the Belly'' (1991), about male identity, was on the New York Times
best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   As we talked, I looked dispassionately at the trapeze rig. I do
not fear heights or flying and had no butterflies at the prospect
of the first step, simply swinging out, letting go and falling into
the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trapeze is a natural for dealing with fear, self-image and
trust,'' Keen said. He told the story of a woman who took four days
just to climb the ladder, who kept saying she was afraid of being
dropped. Ultimately, he maintained, she recovered memories of her
father's sexual abuse. ``One experience is a template to begin to
learn, not an instant cure for everyone's problems,'' Keen said.
``It's a choice to look at fear, panic and trust _ what to do with
it and how it relates to the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Keen admits to being afraid himself when he flies. ``The first
level is physical, the second is performance,'' he said. ``I'll
look stupid, you'll laugh at me. But trapeze will cure you of
perfectionism. We can't hide our mistakes because they happen in
midair. Trapeze is a brief but regularly scheduled vacation from
your ego.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounded good to me. A few minutes later, though, I was
convinced that Keen takes regularly scheduled vacations from
reality. He had me swing on a practice trapeze first, which hurt my
hands terribly. He and the other two men had thickly calloused
palms from years of grabbing the thickly taped rung.
</P>
<P>
   They gave me hand guards, which helped somewhat. Once I was
hanging, Keen instructed me to draw my knees to my chest, hook them
over the trapeze and hang upside down. If his face had been
anywhere near mine, I would have laughed in it.
</P>
<P>
   I told him I couldn't do that because I had no upper body
strength. He told me I didn't need any, that it was all in the
swing. Finally, he and Givry helped me do it. Back on the ground, I
was thoroughly nauseated. This time when I looked up at the rig not
a phrase of Keen's prattle about trust was left in my head. I felt
pain in my hands and fear in my heart. And everywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The more hesitant I became, the brisker Keen was. Time to climb
the ladder. He seemed convinced that the moment I was airborne all
would be well. Givry secured a safety harness around my waist (I
wore a T-shirt, leggings and a pair of socks) and it was so tight I
could barely breathe, but loosening it did not seem an option.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I was 35 feet up, I was markedly queasy. Keen did
not seem interested. He had me curl my toes around the edge of the
platform and pulled the trapeze toward us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thrust your hips out,'' he said, and when I did the sky
started to spin. I was about to slip right off the platform. I
gripped the rigging desperately with my left hand. ``I'm having an
anxiety attack,'' I proclaimed, finally getting Keen's attention.
But not for long. He gave me a moment to breathe, then got behind
me and pressed his knees into mine.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll just step off now,'' he said and I was awash in that
sickening inevitability you get as your car is about to crash and
there is nothing you can do to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The platform dropped away. I swung out and yelled louder than
Tarzan. All around me was open air, space, rushing wind, empty,
wide, vast areas where nothing could protect me. Everyone on the
ground, including Givry, who was controlling my safety harness,
laughed. Screaming is commonplace for first-timers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lay back,'' Givry called, when he wanted me to fall. I tried,
but the brain knows better than to lay back flat in midair. My head
jerked forward. As I fell, whiplashing onto the net, everyone
applauded.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more,'' I declared, rolling off. If that's what the most
basic step felt like, then the next one _ flying through the air by
my knees and grabbing someone else's wrists _ was entirely out of
the question. I fell onto the grass, practically hugging it. Keen
settled his long, knobby frame beside me. ``The first time is for
fear,'' he preached. ``The second time is for fun.''
</P>
<P>
   I shook my head. I didn't want to hear it. He persisted. ``What
if you stopped sex after the first time?'' he asked. I stared. What
kind of sex was he having?
</P>
<P>
   As he talked, Keen fixed his ball-bearing eyes on me and I knew
I had to try it one more time. Back on the platform, I started to
negotiate. ``I'll do this now if you promise you won't make me do
it again,'' I said, sounding like a 6-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   He was noncommittal. The hell with him, I thought. Once more and
that's it. I had sweat through my clothes and still felt as if I
couldn't breathe. I felt his knees behind mine again _ a gesture
far too intimate for a stranger, I decided _ and felt the hopeless
lurching in my stomach as I lost the ground beneath me. This time I
didn't scream. But when Givry called for me to lay back, I froze. I
didn't let go.
</P>
<P>
   It took three more calls before I released, bouncing awkwardly
onto the net. This time I lay there, spent. Givry walked over,
underneath me, and talked soothingly in my ear. I tried explaining
that my hands hurt, that the strain of supporting my body weight
with them seemed impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that,'' he said. ``You're tense, you're afraid.''
Suddenly his voice seemed the most lulling thing in the world. As I
lay there, a splayed lump, I had a revelation. He was the Horse
Whisperer. And I was the horse.
</P>
<P>
   This time, when Keen approached, I gave him a ball-bearing stare
of my own. He backed off, and used his time to play peacock,
luxuriating in his flying, basking in the compliments these
professionals threw his way. So much for abandoning ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're into perfectionism,'' he told me later. ``You have to
work on your tendency to say, `I failed.' You were a lot more
scared than you thought you could be, yet you went back up a second
time in the face of your fears. That's a success.'' He made a stab
at warmth, Father Hen style. ``You were spunky,'' he said. ``You
done good.''
</P>
<P>
   All I could think of was Lou Grant telling Mary Richards:
``You've got spunk. I hate spunk.''
</P>
<P>
   I went back to my hotel and curled up in a ball on the bed.
Twenty-four hours later, after Advil, bourbon, hot showers and
massage therapy, I felt better. And I got a chance to read the
previous day's papers. This was my horoscope: ``The only thing to
fear is fear itself. How many times have you heard that? And how
many times have you put your fears behind you and plunged headlong
into the unknown? Not nearly often enough if you are a typical
Virgo. Worry less and explore more today.''
</P>
<P>
   I put it in the trash. As far as I'm concerned, worry is a
completely underrated commodity. It's free and readily available.
And you don't need hand guards. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
