<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-SOLANA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO CHIEF IS NAMED EUROPEAN UNION'S FOREIGN-POLICY AND SECURITY
CZAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Javier Solana, who as secretary-general of
NATO pressed strongly for the Yugoslavia bombing campaign, was
named Friday by European Union leaders as the first foreign policy
and security czar of the union.
</P>
<P>
   Solana, 56, a former foreign minister of Spain who is also a
trained theoretical physicist, later told allied ambassadors here
that he would stay in his NATO job until the Kosovo crisis was
under control.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, at a meeting in Cologne, Germany, the leaders of
the 15 European Union countries decided to create a military force
for the union. In the new position, Solana is generally expected to
create a framework that will give European leaders the same ability
that they now have only within the U.S.-dominated NATO to carry out
peacekeeping and other military operations like the one in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat said that in a brief meeting in Brussels on
Thursday night with Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott,
Solana was in tears at the prospect that the NATO operation in
Kosovo might finally be on the verge of success.
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters Friday that the most important thing to him
personally about the operation was the refugees' safe return.
</P>
<P>
   As a student in the repressed Spain of Generalissimo Francisco
Franco in the 1950s and '60s, Solana, an underground member of the
illegal Socialist Party, opposed the dictator. Later, as a member
of the opposition in the nascent post-Franco democracy in Spain, he
was against Spain's joining NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own generation was often torn between the values we were
taught and the harsh reality _ a reality that did not always
correspond to those ideals,'' he said recently. ``Today, I am
heading this alliance, and many of our generation are in positions
of responsibility. Today, we all realize how difficult it is to
translate values into policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
