<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3506 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY05-COX     06-04 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HILLARY CLINTON TAKES MAJOR STEP TOWARD SENATE CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    560&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton took one of the
final steps Friday toward becoming a candidate for the U.S. Senate
in New York, announcing that she would form an exploratory
committee to begin raising campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to open an exploratory committee in July. And then
I'll spend some time _ a lot of time _ in New York listening to
people, and I'm looking forward to that,'' she said, inching closer
to becoming the first first lady to seek public office for herself.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its historical significance, a Clinton campaign would
shake up national politics in 2000. Her candidacy would prolong the
polarizing influence of the Clinton presidency, energizing both
voters and campaign donors across the country.
</P>
<P>
   A debate is already under way as to whether her candidacy would
help or hurt Vice President Al Gore's presidential hopes and those
of House Democrats to regain a majority.
</P>
<P>
   An exploratory committee, which can raise money for staff,
polling and travel, will help Clinton avoid a brewing controversy
about her frequent trips to New York at taxpayer expense. She has
made 10 trips to New York this year, purportedly on official White
House business.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that no determination had been made on whether or when to
formally announce her candidacy, Clinton's press secretary, Marsha
Berry, said, ``This is part of what she needs to do to make a final
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's chief political operative is former White House aide
Harold Ickes, who told the Associated Press the exploratory panel
was needed because ``You can't be sort of a wandering minstrel. She
herself likes structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is also receiving informal advice from James Carville,
the political mastermind of her husband's 1992 presidential victory
and the president's staunchest defender during his impeachment and
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Her announcement Friday, which appeared to be an afterthought at
the conclusion of an ABC-TV ``Good Morning America'' broadcast on
youth violence, immediately triggered a response from political
conservatives that recalled the vehement opposition her husband has
encountered throughout his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, a group called Conservatives for Effective
Leadership announced the formation of a new political action
committee that would conduct direct mail and advertisement
campaigns to oppose Clinton's Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has she ever introduced a piece of legislation, run a business
or even served on her local school board? The answer is no,'' said
Gary Nolan, a radio talk show host who is president of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a Yale-trained lawyer, worked for one of the
congressional committees involved in the Watergate investigation of
Richard Nixon in the 1970s. Prior to her husband's election as
president, she served as president of the Children's Defense Fund.
And during the Clinton presidency, she spearheaded the
administration's ill-fated health care reform measures.
</P>
<P>
   But she has never lived in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the National Republican Senatorial Campaign
Committee sent the first lady a map of New York and a letter
suggesting that she take time to ``learn about'' the state. The
letter also suggested that Florida may be a more appropriate home
for the first couple, given the president's fondness for golf.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Such responses did not surprise political experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question on the minds of a lot of New Yorkers is what does
she need this aggravation for?'' said Lee Miringoff, director of
the Marist Institute for Public Opinion, whose latest polling shows
the first lady in a neck-and-neck race with her most likely
opponent, Mayor Rudy Giuliani of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   As a candidate for the U.S. Senate, ``she will become the new
devil figure for Republican fund-raisers nationally,' said Larry
Sabato, a University of Virginia professor and author of ``Dirty
Little Secrets,'' a 1996 book about political corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the first lady manages to win the New York seat, she
may help the GOP pile up enough cash to secure a couple of dozen
other Senate and House seats in anti-Clinton territory in the South
and the West,'' Sabato added.
</P>
<P>
   But no one will need the money more than Clinton herself. Some
Democratic political advisers have estimated it may take as much as
$25 million to finance a Senate race in New York. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, whose retirement has created the open seat Clinton is
pursuing, spent nearly $7 million in 1994 against token opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
