<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: UPDATES and ADDS KOSOVO-CASUALTIES.) 
 (nk) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans four pages of stories on Kosovo for
Saturday, June 5.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX (Washington) _ President Clinton declared
Friday that he was ``anxious to end the bombing'' in Yugoslavia,
and the Pentagon said that the 10 week air war could end as early
as Sunday if Serb military authorities begin their troop withdrawal
from Kosovo. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ After a faxed request from the
chief of Yugoslavia's armed forces for a meeting to discuss
arrangements for a pullout of all Serb forces from Kosovo, NATO on
Friday told the designated commander of its 45,000 peacekeepers to
find a place near the Serbian border for a field conference
Saturday morning on withdrawal terms. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-RECOVERY-ASSESS (Washington) _ The war in Kosovo appears to
be ending with many major issues unresolved, not least the future
of President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia and what the United
States and its allies ought to do about him. By R.W. Apple.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ As soon as Russia came
to agreement with NATO on the principles for a peace settlement for
Kosovo, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic understood that he
had no choice but to accept the terms put in front of him, senior
Yugoslav officials said Friday. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CASUALTIES (Washington) _ By one set of casualty figures,
the NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia has been a extraordinary
victory for the Western alliance: No pilots were killed in combat
during more than 31,000 sorties over the past 10 weeks. But another
set of casualty figures - for Yugoslav civilians - is a reminder
that the type of high-altitude air war that the United States
prefers to fight has deadly consequences for those on the ground.
By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ How/why the military campaign is
coming to its end. By Eric Schmitt and Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ A day after Yugoslavia accepted an
international peace plan for Kosovo, China on Friday restated its
demand that NATO halt its bombing before discussions begin in the
United Nations about a peacekeeping force. But Chinese support for
the peace plan seems likely. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Washington) _ Through the war, NATO has only
warily dealt with the Kosovo Liberation Army, the only fighters on
the ground in Yugoslavia. Now with a settlement at hand, NATO is
even more wary of the emboldened rebels, who see themselves as the
emerging political and military power in a liberated Kosovo. By
Steven Lee Myers and Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ Refugees try to make up their minds on what to
do. Dateline and byline to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   There are also several graphics in the works, including one map
looking at the overnight bombing after the deal was accepted.
</P>
