<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3514 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PASSPORT-ART-$ADV     06-04 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PASSPORT-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEEDING UP A PASSPORT (BEFORE PANIC SETS IN) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of passport expediters is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6)  
 (af)  
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andrew Schwarz, a New York real estate executive, was at a
meeting in Atlantic City last month when he got the call. His
office wanted him in Tokyo that weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But Schwarz had a problem. On his last trip to Japan,
immigration officials there had told him that his passport, with
his picture about to fall off, was too badly damaged for them to
honor again. Now he needed a replacement. Fast.
</P>
<P>
   For help, he did what many others in similar circumstances do _
he turned to an expediter, one of a handful of companies in New
York and other big cities that make a business of quickly getting
passports and visas for their clients. With global business
booming, many corporations rely on these firms, but so do a good
many people traveling on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're paying for somebody to walk your documents through the
system,'' said John M. Pile, an executive for a private
international health organization in New York who lost his passport
just before a trip to Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department says its passport offices in New York and a
dozen other cities can often deliver a new passport or a renewal
within a day, given proof of urgency like an airline ticket or
printed itinerary showing an immediate departure.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of work load,'' said Maria Rudensky, a
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, people who need passports in a day or so are often
more willing to spend extra money than to wait long hours at the
passport office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It chews up your day,'' said George Brokaw, a New York
investment banker. ``If six hours of your time is worth more than
$150, you're going to be prepared to use one of these services.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, facing the order to get to Japan, decided to take no
chances. He went directly to one of the expediters. They usually
charge about $150 for guaranteed same-day delivery of a new
passport or renewal. That's on top of the passport agency's $35 for
rush service, along with $60 for a new passport or $40 for a
renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are at the passport offices every day, the
professional bureaucracy-busters know the procedures cold. And they
become friendly faces to agency clerks, who usually deal with
harried, sometimes demanding, strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people walk in with an attitude that they're entitled
to a passport,'' said Mark Schimel of It's Easy, an expediting
service in Manhattan with 20 years' experience in speeding along
passports. ``But if they can't prove their citizenship and identity
to the agent's satisfaction, they just don't get the passport. It
happens every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The expediters rely on attention to detail and, often, on the
ability to jump to the head of the line. At many passport offices
around the country, local directors give the expediters regular
daily appointments at which the agency can process 15 percent or 20
passports at a crack. The applications are usually flawless. ``They
help us to be more efficient,'' Ms. Rudensky said.
</P>
<P>
   At the passport office in lower Manhattan, Schwarz, with Schimel
at his side, stepped up to a bulletproof window and handed over his
papers.
</P>
<P>
   The clerk took one look at Schwarz's passport and asked to see
his birth certificate, which, as usual, he was not carrying. For a
moment, the Japan trip hung in suspension. Then Schimel said, ``We
want to do a PFM.''
</P>
<P>
   The clerk smiled. She slid a form toward Schwarz, asked to see
his driver's license and disappeared into another room, where she
punched his name into the Passport Files Miniaturization system.
</P>
<P>
   The system confirmed that Schwarz held a valid passport. He paid
$15 more for the extra steps, and that afternoon a messenger sent
by It's Easy delivered the passport to his office.
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw travels so much that he carries his passport every day.
Yet he failed to notice until the day before he was scheduled to
fly to London this spring that it had expired. He had two new
photographs taken that afternoon and went the next morning to the
passport agency with Schimel to sign his application. He picked up
his new passport at It's Easy on the way to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Christman, 17, a model, was recently offered his first
overseas photo shoot, from Elle magazine, on the Spanish island of
Ibiza. But he had never been out of the country. His agency, Next
Models, called It's Easy on a Thursday, and his passport arrived
the next day at his home in Pelham, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Some travelers say bureaucratic confusion and rudeness drive
them to the expediters. A New Jersey writer, headed for Brazil,
said someone in the New York passport office hung up on her when
she called for an appointment. The writer, who spoke on condition
of anonymity, then called an automated number and found the tape
inaudible. The expediters got the job done in a day.
</P>
<P>
   A Manhattan leather distributor discovered when he tried to
board a flight to Italy that his passport had expired. When he went
to the passport agency, he said, there was no record of the
appointment he had made and the clerks were ``very unfriendly and
very rude.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rudensky acknowledged that service is sometimes less than
perfect, but, she said, ``That's certainly not our aim, and we
would expect that those incidents are very few.''
</P>
<P>
   Many expediters also deal with driver's licenses or other
documents. But their passport clients are among the most grateful.
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw, the investment banker, put the expediting business into
Wall Street terms. ``What you're paying for,'' he said, ``is the
elimination of uncertainty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
