<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE WEALTH, MORE STATELY MANSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn., Calif., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of percentage of homes over $1 million is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6)  
 (af)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The beige, three-story mansion fills a one-acre lot on Clover
Street in Memphis. Roof turrets, tall windows, columns that frame
the front door at the head of a majestic, sloping driveway all
heighten the impression of a palace incongruously placed in an
ordinary suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch house next door seems, by comparison, like a shack. It
is empty, however, soon to be torn down so that another mansion can
rise. And a neighborhood of small homes on large leafy lots
gradually becomes a neighborhood of million-dollar mansions cheek
by jowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such houses are conspicuous proof that a family has achieved a
level of wealth way beyond its physical needs,'' says Kenneth
Rosen, chairman of the Fischer Center for Real Estate at the
University of California at Berkeley. ``A mansion, more than luxury
cars or anything else, shows everyone in the community that you are
rich.''
</P>
<P>
   A wealthy doctor and his family recently moved into this
particular six-bedroom brick mansion, with its cathedral ceilings,
balconies, stately fireplaces and elegant rooms. But there are many
Clover Streets springing up in the United States today, in new
suburbs as well as in older ones where the demand for trophy
mansions not too far from downtown has made the land more valuable
without a home than with one.
</P>
<P>
   So the homes are bought for the land by America's growing
population of multimillionaires, who replace the existing houses
with mansions. ``In-fill,'' it is called in Memphis, and
``teardown'' in the Northeast. In the San Francisco area, it is
known as the ``scraper'' phenomenon _ you buy a house, scrape it
off the lot and build a bigger one.
</P>
<P>
   The million-dollar mansion _ or multimillion-dollar mansion, in
some cities _is emerging as a high-profile badge of the gilded late
1990s, not just in the traditional pockets of wealth, but also in
Middle American cities like Memphis where such homes had been rare.
</P>
<P>
   They are emblematic of an economic divide: The wealth generated
in the boom that began in late 1995, while touching many people,
has gone disproportionately and in huge quantities to the richest 5
percent of the nation's households. They have pocketed most of the
gain from the stock market run-up, wich has created thousands of
multimillionaires overnight. And they have conspicuously channeled
a big chunk of their gains into mansions.
</P>
<P>
   There have been stock market run-ups in the past, of course, and
mansions to show for it. But not since the 1920s, Rosen said, has
mansion-building been as widespread as it is today. So much so that
in some suburbs _ Scarsdale, N.Y., and Westport, Conn., for example
_ restrictions have been placed on the teardown phenomenon, or are
being considered.
</P>
<P>
   One survey of large metropolitan areas turned up 9,257 new and
existing homes that were sold for $1 million or more last year, up
from 3,427 in 1996. And that did not count all the mansions
custom-built by the families that occupy them.
</P>
<P>
   Just how skewed is wealth creation in the late 1990s? And how
many rich people have emerged to create such a historic surge in
mansions?
</P>
<P>
   A new study by Edward N. Wolff, a New York University economist
who tracks the distribution of wealth in the United States, found
that 4.1 million of the nation's 102 million households had a net
worth of $1 million or more last year. That compares with 3 million
such households out of 99 million in 1995, when the stock market
really began to gain steam.
</P>
<P>
   (Net worth is calculated by first totaling a household's cash
savings, the market value of its stocks and bonds and the value of
a house and other holdings _ then subtracting all the debt,
including mortgage debt.)
</P>
<P>
   Rarely in history has there been such a rapid minting of rich
people, Wolff said. While the number of American households rose by
3 percent over the three-year period, the number of million-dollar
households jumped 36.6 percent. Make the wealth cutoff $10 million
or more, and 275,000 households qualified in 1998, up from 190,000
in 1995, a 44.7 percent increase. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From his analysis of Federal Reserve data, Wolff gleans another
insight: While net worth grew rapidly for the richest 10 percent of
the nation's households in recent years, the remaining 90 percent
lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is debt,'' he explained, referring to the source of
so much consumer spending and home buying in recent years. ``The
middle class in particular has mortgaged itself to death,
basically.''
</P>
<P>
   What if wealth had somehow been distributed more evenly _ and
income, too, for that matter? Would there have been so many
mansions? Probably not. A mansion that simulates a palace, in which
a few family members rattle around in too many rooms, makes an
unequivocal statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone,'' said Richard Sennett, a New York University
sociologist, ``understands this prize that only a few can afford.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
