<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3516 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUD-HONEY-SALON-ART-$     06-04 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUD-HONEY-SALON-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALON WITH A SNARL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6)  
 (af)  
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The other day at Mud Honey, a hair salon on Sullivan
Street that caters to a rock 'n' roll clientele, the five members
of the Toilet Boys, whom their manager likes to call ``gorgeous
East Village gutter trash,'' were getting their hair trimmed and
touched up.
</P>
<P>
   After touring in Canada to promote an upcoming CD, ``Sinners and
Saints'' (Cold Front), the long nights in smoky clubs had taken
their toll on Miss Guy, the cross-dressing lead singer. His hair
was an insipid shade of tobacco yellow instead of his signature
platinum blond.
</P>
<P>
   As Michael Matula, Mud Honey's owner and chief stylist, applied
a toner to Miss Guy's hair, the band's 6-foot-6 guitarist, Sean _
who recently stripped naked on the Howard Stern show and whose
stage act includes fire breathing _ explained why the Toilet Boys,
a glam-rock outfit, are regulars at the salon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate people that cut hair uptight, and here they don't give
uptight hair,'' Sean (please, no last name) said, patting the
matted orange-y tufts sprouting from the top of his head and
stroking the stringy, brunette wisps framing his face, a hairdo
that looked more animal than human.
</P>
<P>
   Matula, 37, who favors an Elvis-style pompadour himself, agreed:
``We're not from the Vidal Sassoon school of styling,'' he said,
adding that at a certain kind of uptown salon, ``you get attitude
from the receptionists.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Mud Honey is full of attitude, too. But instead of
snootiness and pampering _ there are no glasses of chilled
sparkling water with lemon wedges _ the salon proudly offers
service with a snarl.
</P>
<P>
   ```You get what you get and you get out'' is our motto,'' Matula
said with a grin. ``If you're needy and demanding, it's not about a
haircut, it's about a psychiatrist. If you don't shut your trap,
we'll throw you out onto the sidewalk with wet hair and half a
haircut, and your bags will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   At $50 to $60 a haircut, and $60 to $120 for hair color, Mud
Honey doesn't charge uptown prices. The decor, which is enlivened
by black rubber flooring, S &AMP; M devices dangling from the ceiling
and hair dryers meant to resemble electric chairs, has more in
common with a dominatrix's chamber than a flower-filled beauty
parlor.
</P>
<P>
   Matula and the other staff members are indistinguishable from
their clientele, favoring tattoos, piercings and cigarettes. ``I
wanted the image of the salon to be Frankenstein meets the Barber
of Seville,'' Matula said, pointing out a tray of surgical
instruments lying side by side with hair scissors.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike publicity-minded hairdressers who name-drop at every
opportunity, Matula is tight-lipped about his clientele. ``I don't
ever try to profit off their names,'' he said. ``I think it's tacky
that salons do that to further their business.''
</P>
<P>
   Which might mean that Mud Honey has no celebrity clients to
speak of. It does, however, have a following among downtown
musicians and artists, developed over 11 years. This month, Matula
plans to open another branch on Bond Street, which, at 1,200 square
feet, is double the size. The new space will have a Fu Manchu vibe,
inspired by 1970s Bruce Lee films, he promised.
</P>
<P>
   As Matula was adding some last-minute bleach to Miss Guy's dark
roots, I impulsively asked for a haircut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you look too newscaster-y,'' he replied, frowning at my
chin-length bob. ``You need some edge.''
</P>
<P>
   As he sliced jagged chunks out of my wet hair and fringed the
ends with his scissors, Mr. Matula kept up a steady patter of
hairdresser chitchat.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what are you into?'' he asked, and without waiting for an
answer added: ``My hobby is serial killers. I have John Wayne
Gacy's painting of Elvis and the receipt from the freezer Jeffrey
Dahmer bought at Sears. I have every book ever written about serial
killers. Do you want to borrow any?''
</P>
<P>
   I politely declined. He moved on to another favorite topic,
Jocelyne Wildenstein, whom he admired despite her multiple plastic
surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't she a plastic-surgery candidate's nightmare? I asked,
growing alarmed at my reflection. I was calculating the weeks it
would take for my hacked-up coiffure to grow out.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Jocelyne Wildenstein is eccentric,'' Matula said. ``That's
what's cool about her. She's rock 'n' roll without even knowing
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
