<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE TO TACKLE SOCIAL SECURITY LOCK BOX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As they return this week from a 10-day recess,
Senate Republican leaders are preparing to take up a bill creating
a Social Security ``lockbox'' _ a procedure to make it difficult
for lawmakers to spend the Social Security surplus funded by
payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the House passed lockbox legislation by an
overwhelming bipartisan vote of 416-12. The House version would
block any bill that draws money from the surplus unless at least
218 House members or 60 senators vote for a waiver.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to protect the surplus, projected at $1.8 trillion over
the next decade, is proving to be the Republicans' main calling
card in their battle with Democrats to seize the high ground on
preserving Social Security for future generations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials have charged that the lockbox
is a gimmick with too many loopholes to be effective. Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin has vowed to recommend a presidential veto,
saying the lockbox could leave policymakers unable to combat a
recession by refinancing debt.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security surplus represents the accumulated excess
amount of payroll-tax revenue funneled into the U.S. treasury and
not paid out in benefits. It represents a big chunk of the current
total budget surplus. This year's payroll-tax surplus, including
interest, is pegged at $886.8 billion, according to Social Security
Administration figures.
</P>
<P>
   As the Social Security tax money accumulates, the government
issues U.S. treasury bonds and uses the cash to pay its bills.
Thus, the Social Security surplus is an integral part of the
congressional budgeting process.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate lockbox proposal _ written by GOP Sens. Spencer
Abraham, of Michigan, John Ashcroft of Missouri and Pete Domenici
of New Mexico _ parallels the House version passed last month.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and other Republican
leaders consider the lockbox a priority as the Memorial Day recess
ends, an aide to Lott said Friday. Other top issues include the Y2K
computer problem and a measure authorizing funds for the Defense
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham, who is seeking reelection in 2000 and faces a challenge
for Rep. Debbie Stabenow, D-Mich., said Michigan voters ``have made
it very clear to me that they expect us to take those Social
Security dollars and use them exclusively to fix the broken Social
Security system.''
</P>
<P>
   The politics of the lockbox may far outweigh any practical
effect it would have on Social Security. Dire predictions of
bankruptcy and prescriptions for fixing the 64-year-old federal
old-age pension benefit have been a fixture on the campaign circuit
in the late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   With the 77-million-member baby boom generation born between
1946 and 1964 set to begin retiring in 2011, the Social Security
trust fund will not be able to pay full benefits starting in 2034,
according to current estimates.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has proposed spending 62 percent of the total
surplus to bolster Social Security and having the government invest
15 percent of the surplus in the stock market. Congressional
Republicans agree in principle on the 62-percent plan but, for the
remainder of the surplus, prefer to rely heavily on private
investment accounts, giving beneficiaries maximum control over
them.
</P>
<P>
   With both sides so far apart, substantial Social Security reform
appears dead at least for this year. But the lockbox plan has
surfaced as an alternative stop-gap measure enabling Republicans to
tell voters that saving Social Security is not just a Democratic
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Republicans hope the lockbox inoculates them against
Democratic charges that the GOP favors tax cuts for the wealthy at
the expense of Social Security's future soundness.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the lockbox proposal in the House drew 198 Democratic votes
out of a possible 211 _ a measure of Democratic wariness over the
prospect of appearing opposed to any Social Security measure in GOP
campaign commercials.
</P>
<P>
   One of those who voted for the lockbox was Abraham's challenger,
Stabenow. But she voiced strong reservations about the measure.
``It's not a box and it's not locked,'' Stabenow said after the
House vote.
</P>
<P>
   She echoed Clinton and other Democrats in calling for a
moratorium on spending any of the entire surplus _ estimated at
$4.4 trillion over the next 15 years _ until lawmakers agree to a
permanent fix for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democratic critics of the lockbox point to such loopholes
as one that allows an exemption for any legislation that deals with
``Social Security reform'' or ``Medicare reform.'' That, the
critics say, would allow creative legislation writers to claim
their funding proposals come under those headings.
</P>
<P>
   Also, they say, Senate rules already on the books set up many of
the same procedural hurdles against domestic ``emergency'' spending
that would dip into the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   And, they say, the House Rules Committee routinely ignores
objections from lawmakers that the House has not obeyed its own
rules. It could do the same when confronted with an objection that
a spending bill would eat up part of the surplus, they add.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., the ranking Democrat on the House
Appropriations Committee, called the lockbox ``the No. 1
legislative fraud of the year.'' Yet Obey voted for the measure in
the House last month.
</P>
<P>
   One critic quipped that instead of ``putting the Social Security
surplus into a lockbox, we should remove politicians' political
courage from it.'' The critic, Richard Thau, executive director of
Third Millennium, said, ``This way we can get started with real
Social Security reform.'' Third Millennium is a group lobbying on
behalf of ``Generation X,'' those born between 1964 and 1980 who
will be in their prime working years as the baby boom generation
retires.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
