<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3519 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT     06-04 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMANDER OF PEACEKEEPERS TO MEET WITH LEADER OF YUGOSLAVIA'S
FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ After a faxed request from the chief of
Yugoslavia's armed forces to discuss arrangements for a pullout of
all Serbian forces from Kosovo, NATO said Friday that the
designated commander of its 45,000 peacekeepers would meet the
Yugoslavs Saturday morning on the border of Kosovo and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   At that meeting, officials said, the allied officer, Lt. Gen.
Michael Jackson of Britain, who commands 16,000 British, French and
German troops already in Macedonia, planned to work out
arrangements with Gen. Dragoljub Ojdanic, the Yugoslav chief of
staff, which would permit the 40,000 Serbian army, police and
paramilitary troops in Kosovo to start leaving by designated routes
on the weekend, allied officials said.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson and Ojdanic agree on a schedule and ways to verify
the pullout, allied diplomats said, NATO ambassadors in Brussels
could order a temporary halt in the bombing as early as Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are not there yet,'' warned NATO's spokesman, Jamie P.
Shea. ``Until such time as we see concrete implementation, facts on
the ground, the air operations will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for the allied military command, Maj. Gen. Walter Jertz
said allied planes had flown 610 missions overnight and were
continuing to bomb targets Friday all over Yugoslavia, but
noticeably not in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no signs of preparation for withdrawal up to now,''
Jertz said, citing Serbian operations against ethnic Albanian
rebels near Mount Pastrik, on the Albanian border. ``However
movement of Serb forces has generally diminished.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Yugoslav forces also launched three surface-to-air
missiles at allied planes Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Though the alliance was at pains to give the impression that the
bombing would continue with undiminished intensity until the Serbs
began pulling out, some diplomats said Gen. Wesley Clark, the
American supreme allied commander, was now under instructions to
avoid targets with a high risk of causing civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Restraint of this sort would deprive President Slobodan
Milosevic of a pretext to renege on commitments he gave European
and Russian mediators in Belgrade on Thursday. Milosevic promised
to stop his attacks in Kosovo, pull out, let nearly a 1.5 million
refugees return to their shattered homes and allow an international
force, made up substantially of NATO troops, into the province.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and the foreign ministers
of Russia, Germany, France, Britain, Italy, Canada and Japan are to
meet in Germany on Sunday and could approve wording of a U.N.
Security Council resolution authorizing the allied force and a
temporary international civil administration for Kosovo, Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to ministers of the European members of the group worked
on the wording overnight at a European Union summit meeting in
Cologne, and German officials said Gunter Pleuger of the Foreign
Ministry took the draft to Moscow Friday and would take it to China
on Sunday. China, like Russia, Britain, the United States and
France, is a permanent member of the Security Council and has veto
power over its resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials hope that Beijing is no longer so rankled over
the mistaken bombing of its embassy in Belgrade that it would block
such a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said the allied force would be expected to disarm the rebel
Kosovo Liberation Army, which agreed to demobilize if there was an
internationally supervised peace agreement. The rebels signed one
such agreement in Paris on March 14, but that agreement, negotiated
last winter at Rambouillet castle outside Paris, collapsed when
Milosevic refused to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav leader bowed to NATO's demands on Thursday after
the Russian mediator, former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin,
and the European Union's negotiator, President Martti Ahtisaari of
Finland, made clear that the allies would keep bombing until he
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said Jackson's headquarters in Skopje, the Macedonian
capital, was now on 24 hours' alert to be ready to move its 50
officers and supporting staff members into Kosovo if the Serbs
started to withdraw. NATO troops could start moving in within 72
hours of the beginning of the withdrawal, other officials said, and
so could any refugees who wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has received pledges from more than 30 countries for a
total of 47,868 troops for the Kosovo force, but that number does
not include any Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said the allies hoped to begin discussions with Russian
officials soon on arrangements that would let Russian troops join
the mission, perhaps under command arrangements like the ones they
have with the NATO-led force in Bosnia, where their commander works
under an American officer and has direct links with Clark's staff
in Belgium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
