<HEADER>
A3526 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     06-04 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CITY' RETURNS WITH ITS SMART, SEXY ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there were ever a series I expected to be about as
emotionally deep as something plucked from an adult video-store
shelf, it's ``Sex and the City.'' Airing on HBO, rated for ``mature
audiences'' and offering the premise that good men and good sex
aren't hard to find but a combination of the two is darn near
impossible, this overheated little series is hilarious AND
sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is surprising, because when ``Sex and the City''
quietly debuted last June, the most interesting thing to flow out
of pre-series interviews with marquee star Sarah Jessica Parker and
producer/writer Darren Star was Parker's refusal to bare her
breasts and utter certain four-letter obscenities.
</P>
<P>
   No-nudity and -profanity clauses aside, Star managed to heat up
this talky series over its run of a dozen episodes; he was rewarded
with a second season of 18 more episodes that gets under way at 8
p.m. CDT Sunday. And he did it without ``Sex and the City'' turning
into soft porn.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: Star has already shown an uncanny ability to
create television that makes you reach for a smoke afterward. The
key to his successes with ``Melrose Place'' and ``Beverly Hills,
90210'' was their increasing procession of back-stabbing acts
generated by sex and greed _ shrewdly combined with the gorgeous
landscape offered by perfectly chiseled stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City'' offers its share of pretty faces (and as a
bonus, bare breasts and male biceps from time to time), but by
focusing tightly on four thirtysomething women performing the
dating ritual in Manhattan, the series has become adventurous,
vulnerable, smart, and, due to its spicy, frank talk, disarmingly
honest.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the series' most noteworthy accomplishment is its
ability to remain a social satire while offering a perversely
poignant world inhabited by professional but cynical women who've
reached the conclusion that if you can't get married, at least have
fun. (Read: Have sex and don't care whether he calls later.)
</P>
<P>
   The women chatter constantly and candidly about sex,
relationships (''Relationships are built on the foundation of lies
and mutually acceptable illusions'') and more sex (''Talking dirty?
Sex is not the time to chat!'') while prowling the modish clubs,
party circuit and weekend getaways of the rich and pampered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City'' should be praised for its idiosyncratic yet
canny casting. Parker, 33, is splendid as Carrie Bradshaw, a
columnist who chronicles the mating habits of single New Yorkers,
sharing her column prose via voice-over narration. She portrays
Bradshaw with, alternately, warmth and iciness _ like a real person
who has good days and bad-hair days. (Bradshaw's adventures are
based on New York columnist Candace Bushnell's cynical tales of
lust and dating games.)
</P>
<P>
   The others, also in their 30s, are just as fitting. Cynthia
Nixon, the terrific Broadway actress, is Miranda, a corporate
lawyer who is no-nonsense, sexually astute and perhaps the group's
biggest cynic. Kim Cattrall is public relations executive Samantha,
a lusty socialite wannabe unable to commit. Kristin Davis, lifted
from ``Melrose Place'' just in time, is art dealer Charlotte, the
virginal optimist who replaces her latest with a dog.
</P>
<P>
   When I talk to female friends who consider ``Sex and the City''
water-cooler TV, what they most appreciate is how the gender roles
have been transformed. The women are in control, and every scene is
about what they want and need. Men are objectified, their
significance downplayed. The guys don't even have names _ only
clues for quick and easy reference. ``Mr. Marvelous,'' ``Groovy
Guy,'' ``Artist Guy,'' ``New Yankee'' and ``Spring Roll Guy,'' whom
Miranda so names because she meets him at a Vietnamese food stand
in front of her apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   The most defined male character goes by simply ``Mr. Big,'' a
rich power broker played by Chris Noth. The sexual relationship
between the too-smooth Mr. Big and Bradshaw has had a grounding
effect on the series, and it manifests nicely in the first two
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's installment explores break-up rules, which to
Charlotte are quite simple: ``It takes half the total time you went
out with someone to get over them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but I side with the lovesick Bradshaw, who has severed
ties with Mr. Big and feels miserable. Emotions don't come with
timers. Episode writer Michael Patrick King, who is also one of the
executive producers, agrees; Bradshaw has a tough time even when
dating the latest addition to the New York Yankees. (Thus, ``The
New Yankee.'')
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has experienced lost love will connect with
Bradshaw's narration that the place where the two of you spent time
becomes ``a deserted battlefield loaded with emotional land
mines.''
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants, streets, your own bedroom. ``Be careful where you
step,'' Bradshaw warns, ``you can be blown to pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   You could say that ``Sex and the City'' is vindication for Star,
whose prime-time soap ``Central Park West'' died a painful death on
CBS after the network brought him in to attract a younger
demographic. He says CBS changed its mind (CBS simply says the
viewers never showed) and asked him to retool the series, adding
older characters and shifting dialogue to sound more like
``Dynasty.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers of Bushnell's book will notice that Star doesn't stray
much from it, lifting specific character names and lines of
dialogue. Still, it's ironic that Star is being credited for a
series that captures the inner emotions and girlspeak of women,
independent and otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   To ``Sex and the City,'' two things are clear:
</P>
<P>
   One should never compromise one's heart.
</P>
<P>
   And men come and go, but you always have your girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
