<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAZDA PICKUP IS REALLY A FORD UNDERNEATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of Mazda's strengths in the U.S. market has long been its
well-built, long-lasting, B-series pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   But because of its alliance with Ford Motor Co., which owns
controlling interest in the Japanese automaker, Mazda no longer
builds pickups.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, today's line of Mazda B-series pickups are Ford Rangers
underneath. Mazda gets to put its signature on the vehicles by
making cosmetic changes in the exterior and interior designs, and
offer special option packages not available in the Ranger lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda truck fans _ which include me _ bemoan the fact that these
new B-series pickups aren't Mazdas, and we miss the quality and
durability that were hallmarks of the true Mazda products.
</P>
<P>
   Ford makes a good compact truck, too. So it's not necessarily a
bad thing that Mazda chose to exit the truck manufacturing
business.
</P>
<P>
   And this week's test drive _ the Mazda B-4000 Troy Lee Designs
four-door, extended-cab, four-wheel-drive pickup (base price
$23,485 plus $510 transportation) _ is different enough from a
Ranger that many people might not
</P>
<P>
   realize that it is a Ford underneath.
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit that until Mazda brought me this truck to drive,
I had never heard of Troy Lee or his designs. I thought perhaps he
was that kung fu guy, but then I realized that was Bruce Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Lee, according to the Mazda press information, designs
custom-painted helmets for motocross racers, and someone at Mazda
decided that it might be a good idea to allow him to jazz up a
pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda put the original Troy Lee design on a Ranger-clone pickup
for the 1997-98 auto show circuit, then decided to produce three
production models with his signature for the 1999 model year.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the B-4000 model, the Troy Lee design also is used for a
B-3000 two-wheel-drive four-door model, and a B-2500
two-wheel-drive with a regular-size cab.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers in the model designations differentiate the vehicles
by engine size. The B-4000 comes with a 4.0-liter V-6 rated at 158
horsepower; the B-3000 has a 3.0-liter V-6 with 145 horsepower; and
the B-2500 is equipped with a 2.5-liter four-cylinder that cranks
out 117 horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   All three get the Troy Lee special package, which includes a
two-tone gray and beige upholstery with the Troy Lee Designs
monogram in the door panels. Only the B-4000 comes with leather
interior. The rest get cloth seats and door panels.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the Troy Lee touch includes flame-colored trim tape
down both sides. It has the boy-racer look of some of those
aftermarket striping kits that Kmart used to sell in its automotive
department back in the '70s. I'm sure some people might like it.
The first thing I would do is peel it off if one of these trucks
were mine.
</P>
<P>
   Except for that and the abysmal fuel-economy, I enjoyed driving
the Troy Lee B-4000. The EPA ratings _ 16 miles per gallon in the
city and 20 mpg on the highway _ are considerably lower than the
30-plus mpg that earlier Mazda trucks provided. Midway through my
weeklong test drive, I had to refill the 15.9-gallon fuel tank.
There is plenty of power. That's what you get in trade for poor gas
mileage.
</P>
<P>
   This is a truck that can go just about anywhere. It comes with a
raised suspension for serious off-roading, and has front and rear
skid plates to protect the underside of the vehicle on rough
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Other B-4000 features include custom 16-inch wheels (the others
have 15-inch wheels), fog lights, an optional five-speed automatic
transmission (packaged with air-conditioning on our vehicle for
$1,130), and a trailer hitch with towing capacity of up to 5,600
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The four-wheel-drive system is the same used on the Ford
Explorer, which is essentially a version of the Ranger pickup. This
system has true shift-on-the-fly capability, with automatic locking
front hubs. You can shift into four-wheel drive at any legal speed,
and you don't have to stop and get out of the vehicle to lock the
hubs. You don't even have to back up the vehicle to unlock the hubs
as you do with some shift-on-the-fly four-wheel-drives.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first import-branded pickup with four doors _ a
nice feature for loading and unloading kids, groceries or other
stuff in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   The B-4000 uses unleaded regular gas, but the B-3000 comes with
a so-called flexible-fuel engine. It will run on gasoline or
clean-burning E85, a mixture of 85 percent ethanol (a type of
alcohol) and 15 percent gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   These vehicles are produced in limited numbers. Just 4,000 of
all three models will be available for the 1999 model year, Mazda
says.
</P>
<P>
   Total price on our test model was $25,125, including
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE:
</P>
<P>
   1999 Mazda Troy Lee Designs B-4000 pickup
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Compact, four-door, five-passenger, V-6 powered,
four-wheel-drive pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: This special-edition truck comes with leather
interior and the design signature of Troy Lee, who makes fancy
helmets for motorcross racers. It's the first of the import brand
compact pickups with four doors. It's essentially a Ford Ranger.
There is lots of power, and off-road capabilities are awesome.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: Silly boy-racer flame graphics on the sides. Poor
fuel economy for a compact pickup.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Nissan Frontier crew cab, Toyota Tacoma
Xtracab Limited, Dodge Dakota Club Cab 4WD.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 16 miles per gallon city, 20 highway.
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE: $23,485 plus $510 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE AS TESTED: $25,125, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is the Star-Telegram's transportation
writer and automotive columnist. Contact him at 3201 Airport
Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford, TX 76022; telephone (817) 685-3810;
e-mail chambers(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
