<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL-OFF CHILDREN MAY BE JUST AS PRONE TO VIOLENCE, EXPERT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANASTASIA CISNEROS-LUNSFORD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Children who are handed everything without having
to earn it often feel as deprived as those who have nothing, and
those feelings can sometimes erupt in violence, a leading
psychologist said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Upper-middle-class teens who get everything they want, from
designer clothes to cars, have no experience with ``pulling the
lever of life to produce results,'' Dennis Embry, a child
psychologist from Tucson, Ariz., told a Koch Crime Institute
seminar here.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officers, judicial representatives and school
administrators attended the one-day session on youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists like Embry and Dave Grossman, a retired Army
psychologist and former West Point professor, discussed the mass
killings at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., a
comfortable suburb of Denver; the schoolyard bloodshed in
Jonesboro, Ark.; and the effects of negative reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Children need to feel rewarded but only when they have
accomplished something, said Embry, the founder of PeaceBuilders, a
nationally recognized violence-prevention program.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have the BMW and everything they've ever wanted, but
they will act like deprived children,'' he said. ``(Children) are
just given stuff, but they don't feel fed because (they) didn't
make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The hunger for social acceptance, Embry said, creates a bath of
negative brain chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A balanced brain is filled with action. There is a belief that
good things happen. It enjoys novelty but has a tolerance for
order. It doesn't overreact (to commands) and is not constantly mad
at the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a skit, Embry compared two extreme environments at the
fictional Terminator High and Positive High.
</P>
<P>
   At the first campus, a tardy student was punished in a hostile
environment. At Positive High, the student was treated nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Majni, a counselor at El Dorado Elementary School in San
Antonio's North East School District, said consequences and zero
tolerance of bad behavior must be balanced within a positive
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Often, Embry said, law enforcement officers and educators are
too busy trying to predict which child will be violent, instead of
improving the environment in which they learn.
</P>
<P>
   He likened it to seeing a peaceful pond filled with frogs
perched on lilypads and worrying about which one would jump first
into the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is how quiet is the pond. We're looking, however,
for which frog is going to jump first,'' Embry said. ``That will
drive you crazy. Instead, we're creating an agitated pond of
turmoil.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas-based Koch Crime Institute, founded by philanthropist
Bill Koch, is a crime and justice research center that studies
juvenile crime prevention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
