<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN SUPPORT FOR NATO PLAN DOOMED FURTHER RESISTANCE FROM
MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ As soon as Russia agreed with NATO on the
principles for a peace settlement for Kosovo, President Slobodan
Milosevic understood that he had no choice but to accept the terms
put in front of him, senior Yugoslav officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But they expressed deep concern that the international force
being assembled by NATO would not move into Kosovo quickly enough
to protect the Serbs there from separatist Albanian guerrillas. And
they worry about Belgrade's enormous task of reconstruction, for
which it expects little Western help.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these problems, the officials added, Milosevic will
retain his grip on power, and the ultranationalist leader of the
Radical Party, Vojislav Seselj, has agreed not to vote against the
government even if he quits as deputy prime minister of Serbia to
protest the Kosovo deal. Seselj has also promised not to lead
demonstrations against the pact.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians won some important concessions for Milosevic, the
officials said, which made the final offer better for Belgrade than
the earlier Western plan presented to the Serbs and the Albanians
at Rambouillet, France. The Albanians accepted that plan; Milosevic
rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we knew that when the Russians came in with this plan,
that was it,'' said one official close to Milosevic and his
influential wife, Mirjana Markovic. ``We knew it from the
beginning. We knew that the carpet bombing of Belgrade would start
the next day after we refused, so what was the choice?''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO alliance had threatened to take out the rest of
Serbia's bridges, electricity supply and telephones, and the
Yugoslav officials said there was no longer any reason to wait for
such destruction. Continuing the unequal war was pointless, the
official said, and it obviously posed greater risks to Milosevic's
own hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alternative to acceptance was not a humane one,'' the
official said. ``We couldn't be reckless and risk elimination of
the state, the army and the people for the sake of rhetoric, and
without any substantial support in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The key part of the proposal that made it acceptable for
Belgrade, the officials said, was the limitation on the movement of
the international forces, mostly NATO and Russian troops under a
United Nations flag, to Kosovo itself.
</P>
<P>
   Under an annex of the Rambouillet accords, a purely NATO force
was to be given full permission to go anywhere in Yugoslavia, and
be immune from any legal process. ``NATO personnel shall enjoy,
together with their vehicles, vessels, aircraft and equipment, free
and unrestricted passage and unimpeded access throughout the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia including associated airspace and
territorial waters,'' the annex read.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also noted that the new proposals did not
recommend a re-examination of Kosovo's sovereignty after three
years, or any referendum on that topic, as the Rambouillet
agreement did.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials also said their resistance had forced NATO to
find a solution within the United Nations and with the
participation of the Russians. And they emphasized the
international guarantees of Serbia's sovereignty over Kosovo,
unlike the temporary sovereignty proposed at Rambouillet.
</P>
<P>
   On a more personal level, the officials expressed deep concern
that up to 200,000 Serbs and Gypsies now living in Kosovo would
flee the province rather than ``wait for the KLA,'' as one official
put it, referring to the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear that Serbs won't be in Kosovo anymore,'' the official
said. ``How many international troops are ready and how quickly can
they deploy over this burned land? We pretend that NATO controls
the terrorists of the KLA, but truthfully no one really controls
them.''
</P>
<P>
   And he predicted that the large numbers of poor ethnic Albanians
from Albania and Macedonia who had never lived in Kosovo would try
to move into the province as refugees, attracted by the large
Western presence and promises of aid.
</P>
<P>
   The mood of the officials was resigned and at moments even
bleak. They understood that the West was unlikely to provide
reconstruction aid so long as Milosevic remained in power, but they
expressed few doubts that he would remain firmly entrenched as head
of state.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   They offered few clear ideas for coping with Yugoslavia's dire
economic problems, other than motivating Serbian self-reliance and
ingenuity. Already weakened by eight years of international
sanctions, Yugoslavia's economy has been blasted by NATO's war
against bridges, highways, factories and refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Russian help would be required, they said, to get enough natural
gas for the winter and the gasoline and fuel needed to complete
this year's harvest. And they said they expected Yugoslavia to
continue to have to pay well over market price for the goods it was
able to import or smuggle past the sanction monitors.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``People are now happy with the simple fact that the bombing
will stop,'' said another senior official. ``And the day after that
no one knows. People have responded to the war in a remarkable
fashion, and now we must organize people to act in a positive
way.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3555 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2NDT     06-04 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BELGRADE, Yugoslavia: positive way.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Yugoslav United Left party, which is led by Ms. Markovic,
has spoken of the post-war period as a time of renewal, but it will
most likely be a period of lower living standards, increased
poverty and a slow rebuilding of damaged infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most analysts here _ including the former editor of the
Belgrade magazine Vreme, Zoran Jelicic _ say that while the
domestic political situation will become more tense, the
difficulties of everyday life will make popular political unrest
less likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very hard time ahead,'' said Jelicic, who lost his
top editing job when he opposed Milosevic. ``We will have
inflation, shortages and severe unemployment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those factors, said Jelicic, who is also an economist, will
force the government either to open up the economy to the world
market, despite international sanctions, or to turn to a
socialist-style economy to get through the most difficult periods.
``But hard times will just strengthen the authorities,'' he said.
``In our experiences, there are no protests during the worst
times.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the West's effort to ``bribe the population into
overthrowing Milosevic,'' he said, ``it even makes me resentful,
and I've tried to bring him down from day one.''
</P>
<P>
   If the senior officials have concerns about the post-war
economy, they add that Milosevic faces little internal political
threat. Seselj has a history of being the government's in-house
nationalist.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday morning, when he met with party leaders to tell
them he would accept the Russian-NATO proposal and urged them to
vote for it in parliament that day, Milosevic asked Seselj to at
least abstain in the voting.
</P>
<P>
   But Seselj, meeting with his party just before the vote, ended
up opposing the pact. Afterward, he said he would quit the Serbian
government once Western troops arrive in Kosovo. ``Certainly we
won't stay in the Serbian government to see a possible entrance of
troops from aggressor countries into Kosovo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Seselj also promised Milosevic that he would support the
government in parliament or not vote against it, and that he would
not organize any demonstrations against the Kosovo deal in the
streets, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   They noted that Seselj has few firm supporters of his own, but
tends to draw defectors from Milosevic or from Vuk Draskovic, a
former leader of the democratic opposition and now the head of the
Serbian Renewal Movement. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
