<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, June 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dry weather will dominate the Northeast this weekend as an
expansive area of high pressure near the New England coast protects
the region from clouds. Sunshine will be ample, nearly 15 hours, in
the Northeast and afternoon readings will rise as much as 40
degrees from morning minimums. A light flow from the southeast will
encourage active afternoon sea breezes from Cape Cod to Cape Henry,
especially as the interior becomes quite warm around midday.
</P>
<P>
   Less humid air will filter into North and South Carolina, but
along the periphery of a sultry air mass over the South, a few
thunderstorms will develop. Scattered afternoon thunder is likely
in sections of Florida as well as Alabama and Tennessee. High
pressure in northern Louisiana will limit clouds over the lower
Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of thunderstorms will erupt in the Plains from Texas to
the western Great Lakes as a corridor of steamy air streams toward
Canada. The largest and perhaps most potent storms will be over
Minnesota, northern Wisconsin and western Michigan. A cold front
drifting east from the Rockies will be the mechanism to trigger the
thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Very cool, moist air over Wyoming and parts of Utah will be
accompanied by thick clouds and showers. After record chill in
parts of the Southwest, sunny skies will boost temperatures back to
seasonal levels. Low clouds will cling to the West Coast and the
Pacific Northwest will become windy and cooler with showers near
the coast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Thunderstorm Complex
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday evening, a few strong thunderstorms erupted in
the northern Plains. Within a few hours, the thunderstorms, drawing
energy from moisture-laden winds from the Gulf of Mexico, had
organized themselves into a large cluster of storms called a
mesoscale convective complex. By early Friday, the cloud shield
from the expanding system engulfed much of the Missouri Valley.
These thunderstorm complexes, which are common from May through
July, cover hundreds of square miles and provide more than half the
rainfall during the growing season for the nation's central farm
lands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
