<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Daily Cost of Saving On Other People's Taxes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does that special tax break that Archer Daniels Midland gets for
making alcohol fuel for cars burn you up? Well, it's not worth the
postage stamp it takes to complain to your senator.
</P>
<P>
   The break costs each of the 94 million couples or individuals
who file federal income tax returns about 16 cents, says Martin A.
Sullivan, who writes for the magazine Tax Notes.
</P>
<P>
   But the research and development credit that is dear to the high
technology industries, and that President Clinton wants to extend
for another year, is pricier. It will cost $2.3 billion, or $24 per
taxpayer, Sullivan wrote in the June 1 issue of Tax Notes. And the
rule that lets timber companies write off expenses immediately
rather than over the lives of their trees costs $5.30 per taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   Total up all the 140 special breaks in the official list of what
the government calls ``tax expenditures,'' and they add about $200
to the average federal income tax bill this year. That's just
$23.45 more than the cost of stamps for complaint letters to all
535 members of the House and Senate. David Cay Johnston &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Interest Rebate Card Dies &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Mellon Bank's Cornerstone Mastercard program comes to an end,
customers are being freed from a dubious, though superficially
attractive, bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, begun by the Pittsburgh bank in 1993, was that
consumers would get all their interest payments back in a rebate &UR;  &LR; _
after 20 years. In return, they had to pay a high interest rate on
unpaid balances _ the prime rate plus 11.9 percentage points, or,
currently, 19.65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Citicorp, which bought Mellon's credit-card business this year,
is ending the program. Cornerstone customers will get money back
much sooner, though not all they have paid.
</P>
<P>
   In October, card holders will get one-twentieth of the interest
paid for each year they were in the program, bringing them out
roughly even, since the bank will no longer hold their money for
the remainder of the planned 20-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Citicorp would not discuss customer reaction to the plan or say
how many cards are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Robert D. Hershey Jr. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Talk Your Way Out of This! &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some People who claim that they do not have to pay income taxes
are being hit with tough penalties by United States Tax Court
judges.
</P>
<P>
   A $10,000 penalty was imposed recently on Kermit W. Kinkade, a
jewelry maker in Jeffersonville, Ind., who claimed he had no duty
to file tax returns for 1992 through 1994, when he earned an
average of about $37,300 a year. Mr. Kinkade argued that he would
owe tax only if he were causing harm or had a government license.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months Tax Court judges have imposed big fines and
expressed weariness at ridiculous claims, such as that the income
tax is unconstitutional or that it does not apply to wages. A small
industry peddles seminars, books and videos purporting to show that
the tax is a hoax and that payment is voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voluntary compliance means that taxpayers willingly fulfill
their responsibilities under the tax law,'' said Steve Pyrek, an
Internal Revenue Service spokesman. ``It doesn't mean that paying
taxes is optional any more than stopping at a red light is
optional.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinkade, who could not be located, now owes more than $46,500 in
tax, penalties and fines, court records show, plus interest.
</P>
<P>
   David Cay Johnston &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
