<HEADER>
A3562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-VODKA-ART-NYT &LR;      06-04 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-VODKA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHING RUSSIANS TO SAVOR _ NOT GUZZLE _ VODKA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo and graphic are being sent. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UGLICH, Russia _ In a large second-floor room of the Rossiya
movie theater in this shabbily genteel town, Vladimir Shabalin
teaches people how to drink vodka.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smell it first,'' he tells visitors clasping murky antique
shot glasses. They do. ``Take a sip, and hold it in your mouth for
just a bit. Swallow, and then have a mild snack.''
</P>
<P>
   The chilled vodka, Shuiskaya Classic, is sold only in a region
near Moscow and is considered among the best in Russia. It goes
down as smoothly as Shabalin promised. His visitors then dutifully
begin munching pickles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you equate vodka with drunkenness,'' Shabalin says, ``it's
like saying love is the same as venereal disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Such distinctions may be lost on most Russians, who are living
through a time of catastrophically widespread alcoholism. But as
director of a new vodka library in Uglich, 200 miles north of
Moscow, Shabalin and his partners are part of a scattered effort to
create a new, upscale culture of drinking the ancient spirit.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, for instance, the Russian distiller Smirnov is
fighting to protect its image as a brand to be savored rather than
guzzled. The Kristall distillery, one of Russia's largest vodka
companies and maker of its most renowned exported brand,
Stolichnaya, has begun producing upscale vodkas for domestic
consumption. Not far from the Kremlin, Mikhail Kozhukov, a
journalist, has opened a vodka restaurant with 40 different brands
of the drink to ``show regard for elite vodka and to push out the
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   These businesses are banking on the growing worldliness of the
Russian middle class, which has begun to appreciate the nuances of
liquors. At the same time, they worry that many successful Russians
are moving away from vodka to what are viewed as more refined
drinks, including gin, whisky and expensive wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If before, people drank to get drunk, now they drink as social
drinking,'' says Natalya Karchazhkina, senior analyst with Qualitel
Data Services, a Moscow market research firm. ``These people are
afraid of alcoholism, and vodka is strongly associated in their
minds with alcoholism.''
</P>
<P>
   The vanguard of the new drinking culture hopes to refurbish
vodka's reputation by teaching people to drink it for its taste
rather than its punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ban vodka, so you have to teach people how to drink
it properly,'' says Viktor Minayev, a folklorist and partner in the
Uglich vodka library. ``What's a culture of drinking? It's placing
limits on yourself and determining the norms in any situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Vodka is the lubricant for most serious discussion in Russia and
often, its controversial subject. There is little agreement about
when it was introduced, where or by whom, though most broadly agree
that mass production of the grain-based spirit began in the 15th
century in northern Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the resplendent and crumbling churches of 1062-year-old
Uglich is the Aleksandrovsky monastery where the friars began
making vodka in the late 16th century. Mainly, the bread wine was
used to pay people, and until the end of the Soviet era, vodka was
arguably the only hard currency in Russia, viable in most
transactions and necessary in others. Gravediggers, for instance,
are still paid in bottles so they can toast the deceased.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been part of our history, though it may be
something we should be ashamed of,'' Kozhukov said over lunch at
his restaurant, Petrov Vodkin, as he fingers a list of medieval
battles Russia lost because of mass drunkenness. ``In the late 18th
century, if your guests were able to leave on their own two feet,
then the evening wasn't a success.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistics on Russian alcohol consumption are unreliable, though
one fact is clear: Russians drink vast quantities of hard liquor,
mainly in the form of vodka. Per capita consumption of hard liquor
amounted to 2.2 gallons a year in 1997, compared with 1.2 gallons
in the United States, based on tax receipts.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers understate Russian consumption because they fail
to capture the enormous black market. The Russian Health Ministry
estimates that domestic hard-liquor consumption is much higher _
3.7 gallons per capita. The World Health Organization considers 2.1
gallons per capita as highly dangerous, which is reflected in the
declining average life expectancy of Russian men, which is now
about 58 years.
</P>
<P>
   Minayev contends that Russia was not always like this. He sits
in a corner of the library decorated to look vaguely like a
19th-century Russian tavern, where visitors can sample any four of
the collection of 400 Russian vodkas. The bottles themselves are on
brightly lit shelves like something out of a trade fair.
</P>
<P>
   Russian men did not always drain every 100 gram toast of vodka
down to the very bottom, Minayev says. There was a time when
drinking vodka meant reconciliation rather than murderous fights in
urban kitchens late at night. Russian cadets used to drink their
third toast to women, always gallantly standing up. Women were
advised to drink 25 grams a day for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Minayev points out the taste of vodka varies mainly because of
the water used to make the alcohol. In the fall, the library will
hold a vodka festival featuring old, arcane regional recipes for
everything ranging from garlic to gooseberry vodka. People will be
taught to drink vodka in contemplative sips.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to earn money, too. Minayev and his partner, Artur
Sazonov, a teetotaler Moscow businessman, opened the vodka library
in March to reap revenue for the town, which is visited by about
80,000 tourists annually. The businessmen plan to expand the
collection to at least 800 different brands by the end of the year.
Entrance to the library costs $1, and the vodkas, many of them
local specialties, can be bought for $7 to $14. ``We'll even have a
machine that will take your picture and make it into a label for a
bottle of vodka,'' Minayev said, proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Most czars placed vodka production under state control to bring
the huge revenue directly into their coffers. The Russian
government has not been so adept at regulating the now-private
liquor industry. Sales revenues of individual producers are not
available, but the overall market amounts to hundreds of millions
of gallons a year.
</P>
<P>
   Counterfeiting is rampant. At least half of the Russian vodka
market is made up of counterfeits, and dozens of people die
annually from drinking lethal fakes. Smirnov has had its factory
outside Moscow turn rotgut into windshield cleaner just to stress
how undrinkable counterfeits are. (Smirnov differs from the
Smirnoff brand of vodka sold by Heublein, and both have been
litigating over Smirnov's desire to sell its brand outside Russia.)
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, the company tries through advertising to position its
vodka as an elite brand to appeal to the middle class. ``Drinking
has become very fussy and discriminating,'' Aleksandr Drozdov, a
Smirnov vice president, said about middle-class tastes. ``The
political and economic changes have brought new values. Now people
are too busy to drink as much as before.''
</P>
<P>
   But the purveyors of the vodka culture believe that most
Russians, after drinking vodka to celebrate births and mourn
deaths, will return to the tastes of their forefathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may be drinking French wines now,'' Kozhukov says, ``but
in their heart, there is still a place for vodka. The smell of it
is still in some small corner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1905EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3563 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-GUCCI-ART-$ADV06-     06-04 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-GUCCI-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 A SPURNED SUITOR WHO WON'T JUST GO AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of revenue and net income of Gucci is being sent
to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6)  
 (af)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ What the Gucci Group really wanted was to get clean away
from the dreaded embrace of Bernard Arnault. What it got was the
uncomfortable prospect of a future with his company, its biggest
rival, as its biggest minority shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   A takeover battle over Gucci was decided a bit ambiguously on
May 27, when a Dutch court approved the sale of a $3 billion
controlling stake in Gucci to the Pinault group of France. Gucci,
which is based in the Netherlands for tax reasons but has most of
its operations in Italy, had agreed to the deal with Francois
Pinault, the billionaire owner of French department stores and the
Christie's auction house, to thwart the hostile bid by Arnault,
chairman of the luxury goods maker LVMH Moet Hennessy-Louis
Vuitton. But the decision did not affect the 20 percent stake in
Gucci that LVMH has amassed.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci is a hot property, and buying it would have given a needed
jolt to Arnault's empire, which was hard hit by the economic crises
in Asia. But Gucci's management thought being sucked into the
corporate culture of LVMH would be deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Domenico De Sole, Gucci's chief executive, has ambitions far
above being a satrap of Arnault: He wants to create a powerful
multibrand luxury group big enough to challenge LVMH, whose
portfolio includes Louis Vuitton luggage, Christian Dior fashions
and Guerlain perfumes.
</P>
<P>
   To advance De Sole's plans, Pinault intends to sell to Gucci the
Yves Saint Laurent couture and perfume business, which he had just
acquired for $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Pinault, controlled bhy Francois Pinault, is also the owner of
French department stores and Christie's auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Arnault, who has not conceded defeat, is threatening to appeal
the court's ruling and ask that the Pinault deal be declared
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while Gucci may be red-hot, its stock price has been
cold lately, falling 6 percent the day of the court decision and
then drifting downward. (It closed on Friday at $62.45.) That is
partly because speculators who had bet that Arnault would raise his
bid for Gucci after the decision have sold in disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   But it also reflects investor hesitance about Gucci's ability to
digest a mouthful the size of Yves Saint Laurent.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst, Nathalie Saleur of Dresdner Kleinwort Benson,
estimated that the Yves Saint Laurent takeover could dilute Gucci's
profits by 10 percent to 15 percent. Gucci lacks a track record in
integrating big acquisitions, she said, and ``the market prefers to
wait for evidence.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   De Sole is in a hurry to supply it. He flew to Paris last week
to discuss with Pinault getting the legal groundwork underway for
the Gucci-Yves Saint Laurent combination. Barring surprises, that
agreement could be signed by the end of July. De Sole, meanwhile,
is arranging a trip to the United States to explain his plans to
institutional investors who are among Gucci's most fervent backers.
</P>
<P>
   Such quick acceleration is in line with De Sole's record. Since
he took Gucci public in 1995, sales have exploded _ to $1 billion
in 1998, from $264 million. Crises in Asian economies caused luxury
goods sales to crumble last year, but Gucci used a timely expansion
in the United States and a shift from accessories to ready-to-wear
garments to maintain growth.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its recent weakness, Gucci's stock price has grown more
than fourfold since it went public in 1995. De Sole, together with
Tom Ford, the designer of the hour, have built Gucci into a
fast-growing fashion darling.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, profits at LVMH, the luxury market leader, sank 29
percent last year, dragged down mostly by weakness in Asia, though
its recovery in the first months of this year has been remarkably
strong.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say the gap between Gucci and LVMH is largely a
question of fashion leadership, with Italian houses like Gucci,
Prada and Armani rivaling the French.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italy has a tremendous degree of creativity and resources,''
said Henry Welt, an expert on luxury goods at the New York law firm
of Kronish, Lieb, Weiner &AMP; Hellman.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, LVMH shares leapt on a report, denied by the compony,
that it was in talks to acquire a stake in Armani. The stock closed
at 276 euros, just off its 52-week high.
</P>
<P>
   To revive LVFMH's ateliers, Arnault turned to Britain, he said,
hiring young designers like John Galliano at Christian Dior and
Alexander McQueen at Givenchy. But Italy, he said, ``brings to the
table a number of things the French don't have,'' like related
technologies in fabric and leather finishing. That, in part, was
why Arnault wanted Gucci in the first place, he said.
</P>
<P>
   De Sole says that, though integrating Yves Saint Laurent will be
a challenge, his plans for Gucci are far from exhausted. Last year,
Gucci paid $150 million to acquire the Swiss company that supplies
its watches.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci has already introduced a line of jewelry in its own
stores, and next year will begin selling it in 300 top-of-the-line
jewelry stores worldwide. And it continues to open new stores in
Japan, Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ALL that expansion should please shareholders, making it
relatively unlikely that Arnault would be able to make much trouble
from his 20-percent shareholding stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   De Sole categorically rules out a board seat for LVMH, and while
Gucci bylaws permit shareholders with more than 10 percent of the
company to convene an extraordinary shareholder meeting, it is
unclear what such a gathering could accomplish for Arnault as long
as Gucci is thriving.
</P>
<P>
   According to Welt of Kronish, Lieb, LVMH could make a nuisance
of itself by requesting privileged financial data, but De Sole said
no single shareholder would be favored. ``We're an incredibly
transparent company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, Welt said, the effect of Arnault's restive presence
will be to keep Gucci management from becoming complacent.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say the biggest challenge for Gucci, awash with so
much acquisition cash, may be finding suitable brands to swallow.
``Italian families seem quite content,'' said John Wakely of Lehman
Brothers. ``What is Gucci going to do with the cash?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, De Sole says he will begin massaging prospective takeover
targets right away, given the slowness with which Italian
family-run companies with prestigious names tend to make decisions.
John Grace, executive director of Interbrand, a New York brand
consulting company, said that, at any rate, Gucci was on the right
track, adding that ``as Cecil B. DeMille said, everything's
negotiable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gucci's doing the absolutely right thing,'' Grace said.
``They're building a portfolio.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
