<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 DAYS BEFORE INDONESIAN VOTE, POLICE CLASH WITH VIOLENT
PROTESTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ In a reminder of the dangers that surround
Indonesia's parliamentary election, a whiff of violence came to the
capital Friday as police fired warning shots to halt an attack on
supporters of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   The attack came on the final day of a largely peaceful and
festive three-week campaign before a parliamentary election Monday
that will be Indonesia's first free ballot since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are to choose 462 representatives who will make up the
bulk of a 700-member electoral assembly that is to pick Indonesia's
next president before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling party, Golkar, is one of the leading contenders, with
the advantages of incumbency, wealth and a nationwide organization.
But it is also the common opponent of a welter of opposition
parties that demand its ouster as the capstone to President
Suharto's forced resignation a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   After a campaign that mostly saw mutual tolerance among jostling
crowds whose allegiance ranged among 48 parties, mobs turned on
Golkar campaigners Friday in at least three places here in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   They threw rocks, set a motorcycle on fire, stripped some Golkar
campaigners of their yellow T-shirts and burned some Golkar
banners, and the police fired what officers said were blanks as a
warning.
</P>
<P>
   Though the election campaign has been far less violent than was
widely predicted, there has been bloodshed in several remote areas
that are the scenes of separatist rebellions or other local
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   These include the northern Sumatran province of Aceh, the far
eastern province of Irian Jaya, the Maluku islands and South
Sulawesi. Continuing violence in the disputed territory of East
Timor has been due less to the national election campaign than to a
referendum on independence that is scheduled for August.
</P>
<P>
   Violence lies just beneath the surface of society throughout
this nation of 200 million _ the fourth most populous in the world.
Some political analysts warn that the country has been enjoying
only a brief holiday from bloodshed as people pour their emotions
into sometimes overwrought campaign rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the animosity against the party associated with
Suharto _ whose presidential candidate is his interim successor,
B.J. Habibie _ there are fears that a victory by Golkar could lead
to more widespread violence on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who attacked Golkar supporters Friday shouted
their support of Megawati Sukarnoputri, the daughter of Indonesia's
founding president, Sukarno. She is the most popular of the
opposition candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long live Mega!'' one man shouted, using her nickname. ``We
hate Golkar!''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as two years ago, when Indonesia held its last
election, that would have been a brave thing to shout. Golkar,
backed by the full weight of Suharto's government and his
politically powerful military, won every election in his 32 years
in power.
</P>
<P>
   The thugs and enforcers of the past have not disappeared and
could still be used to help Golkar muscle its way to a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them, indeed, were evident on the streets Friday as
Golkar campaigned in several locations. They included well-drilled
squads of unsmiling young men known as Pancasila Youth, who wore
orange and black camouflage outfits and looked at strangers with
fixed stares.
</P>
<P>
   Golkar's chairman, Akbar Tandjung, on the other hand, offered a
friendlier face to reporters at a forum Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall be grateful if Golkar is given the trust to be the
winner in the upcoming elections,'' he said. ``However, should we
lose, we are ready to be outside the circle of government and
become a power to balance the government as an opposition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
