<HEADER>
A3565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEXSMITH-MUSIC-REVIEW     06-04 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXSMITH-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RON SEXSMITH: NOT REALLY A WALLFLOWER, BUT QUIET AND TENDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Ron Sexsmith sings, he rarely places a note
squarely on the beat. He eases into it a little ahead of time, or
hesitates and lets it drift in late. Then he holds it with a
slow-quivering vibrato that wobbles around the pitch as if he's not
quite ready to commit himself. The tone is hesitant, uncertain,
like a wallflower trying to slip into a party unnoticed. That
self-effacement carried into Sexsmith's deadpan patter when he
performed on Wednesday night at the Bowery Ballroom. Mentioning his
new album, ``Whereabouts'' (Interscope), he asked: ``Do you like
it? Is it all right? It's all right if you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   But the show of modesty was subterfuge. Behind it, Sexsmith is a
completely assured and stubborn songwriter, doing only what he
wants. He never rushes his music or raises his voice, and his songs
take their time as they calmly unveil their finely wrought
melodies. Their quiet tenderness is a matter of determined choice.
</P>
<P>
   Sexsmith's band _ with his producer, Mitchell Froom, sitting in
on keyboards _ kept the music lean and understated, a discreet
backdrop for guitar hooks and Sexsmith's diffident voice. He harks
back to 1960s rock songwriting: the harmonic twists of the Beatles,
the gleaming guitar lines of the Byrds, the introspection of Brian
Wilson, the stolidity of the Band and the vocal turns of Tim
Hardin. He also hints at a fondness for old-time country music,
both for its irregular line lengths and its willingness to be
unabashedly sincere. While he puts clever twists into his melodies,
he works to make his lyrics direct and concise.
</P>
<P>
   Sexsmith writes, as an observant wallflower might, about
loneliness and inevitable despair. He started his Bowery Ballroom
set with ``Doomed,'' which muses, ``Sometimes it seems as though we
were doomed from the start,'' one of his many songs that seeks
serenity after love has faded. He lends hymnlike melodies to songs
like ``Doomed'' and ``Seem to Recall,'' or he brings a music-hall
oompah to songs like ``One Gray Morning,'' which begins, ``You can
count on many things/to let you down.'' Sometimes he becomes an
observer, as in ``Nothing Good,'' which watches a man start an
affair he'll regret while the folk-rock melody rises
optimistically.
</P>
<P>
   Now and then, he tries to will himself toward positive thinking:
``Still Time'' urged, ``Where there's still hope, there's still
time.'' Yet even his downhearted songs are more contemplative than
gloomy; the melodies let the singer stand outside his troubles and
promise consolation even when everything's gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall Payne, the 19-year-old songwriter who opened the show,
could be a one-woman Lilith Fair. She uses Sarah McLachlan's
tremulous vibrato, Natalie Merchant's touches of smoke and Jewel's
coffeehouse guitar-strumming. She also has Jewel's earnestness and
adolescent self-regard, unabashedly singing lines like ``I need to
know who and what I am.'' Yet she already knows how to build a
song, from confession of vulnerability to life lesson. One song,
``Honest,'' urges, ``If you can be honest, I can be too,'' with an
inspirational melody that could make it a sensitive teen-ager's
anthem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
