<HEADER>
A3568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-KIRNA-BOUTIQUE-ADV     06-04 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KIRNA-BOUTIQUE-ADV06-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YA-YA SISTERS IN FASHION RETAILING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)   (For release Sunday, June 6)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They are 27 years old, grew up in Virginia and are
both Libras.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, they take turns reciting aloud their horoscope in The
New York Post. Between them, they have read ``Divine Secrets of the
Ya-Ya Sisterhood'' six times.
</P>
<P>
   Epitomizing downtown chic in their Tracey Feith slip dresses,
jean jackets and pashmina shawls, Sarah Hailes and Beth Shepherd
are so alike they not only complete each other's sentences, but
also could be sisters. In fact, they were sorority sisters at the
University of Virginia, where the two women met as roommates a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ms. Hailes and Ms. Shepherd are still best friends, as
well as business partners. Next month, they plan to open Kirna
Zabete, a two-level clothing store at 96 Greene St. that will marry
NoLiTa and Neiman Marcus. It will sell cutting-edge European
designers like Josephus Thimister alongside funkier, lower-priced
designs by unknown labels like Double Happiness. It is a formula
the partners are betting is fresh and appealing enough to succeed
in a highly competitive retail climate.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hailes is a former manager of Christian Lacroix boutiques at
three Saks Fifth Avenue stores, and Ms. Shepherd is a former
fashion editor at New York magazine. Over a series of lunches at
Burger Heaven on 54th Street last summer, they hatched their idea
for a dream shop. ``It would be everything we wanted to buy for
ourselves but couldn't find in one store in New York,'' Ms.
Shepherd said at her Greenwich Village apartment, which doubles as
an office while the 5,000-square-foot SoHo store is being finished.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hailes piped in. ``Kirna Zabete reflects our different
personalities _ Goth, glamorous and girlie,'' she said. ``We made a
no-gray policy right from the start because gray is tired. Color is
fresh and modern. And absolutely no designers who advertise on the
side of a bus. We're all about mixing. We believe in rubber
flip-flops with a silk dress and a red velvet handbag in summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The store will carry some 60 labels, from high-fashion Europeans
like Olivier Theyskens and Balenciaga to American hipsters like
Daryl K and Susan Cianciolo, to new names like Andrew Gn and Jenny
Udale, designers that Ms. Hailes and Ms. Shephard discovered while
scavenging the cobblestone alleys of London and Paris. The name
Kirna Zabete (pronounced KEAR-nah ZAH-bet) refers to nicknames Ms.
Hailes (Kirna) and Ms. Shepherd (Zabete) acquired in college.
</P>
<P>
   The store is inspired by Colette, the Paris shop with a
following among fashionistas that presents a hyper-edited selection
of clothes and accessories, from Nike sneakers to Gucci bikinis,
all displayed like reliquaries.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hailes and Ms. Shepherd call Kirna Zabete a ``lifestyle
store'' and contend it is a new concept for SoHo, now dominated by
single-designer boutiques or chains like J. Crew. Besides clothes,
their store will have fresh flowers for sale by the door (``just in
case a customer is going to a dinner party after she's bought an
evening dress,'' Ms. Hailes explained), art shows and computer
terminals, to give idle boyfriends something to do. There will also
be candy sold in bulk. ``But no candy with wrappers,'' Ms. Shepherd
said. ``They're not pretty. We're only selling pretty candy like
Good &AMP; Plenty, Swedish Fish and Mike &AMP; Ikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Inacio Ribeiro, one half of the Clements Ribeiro label, which is
supplying cashmere baby clothes and dog accessories to Kirna
Zabete, thinks the store represents a breath of fresh air. ``SoHo
needs an injection of life in terms of multi-label shops,'' he
said. ``It's gotten very dated. SoHo was an '80s phenomenon _
label- or designer-driven. The '90s are much more subtle. It's more
lifestyle-oriented. The idea that fashion is one amongst many other
elements is brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marc Bagutta, the owner of Bagutta, a 12-year-old designer
clothing store in SoHo, is skeptical. ``They're a straight copy of
Colette,'' he said of Kirna Zabete. ``But there is only one
Colette, and it is in Paris. Those girls said they'll show a $1,000
Theyskens jacket with a T-shirt. Well, what's so different about
that? I question selling high fashion with bubble gum. When someone
drops $5,000 in a store, they want service. Barneys was pretty good
at what they did, and even they couldn't sustain the pressure of
fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Barneys from Seventh Avenue created a void
downtown, which Kirna Zabete is not alone in trying to fill. In
August, Jeffrey Kalinsky, a former Barneys shoe buyer, plans to
open Jeffrey New York on West 14th Street in the meatpacking
district _ an enormous 18,000-square-foot store with more
established designers, including Helmut Lang and Dries van Noten,
just like Barneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the downtown Barneys closed, it made a huge hole in
shopping,'' said Alix Brown, an editor at Visionaire, the
avant-garde fashion magazine, who bumped into Ms. Shepherd and Ms.
Hailes at European showrooms this spring. She predicted that Kirna
Zabete will be ``a mecca for the fashion-hungry who could care less
about big labels like Gucci and Prada.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're finding all the new great people who journalistically
I've been trying to find,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Occupying the space once rented by Architektura, Kirna Zabete is
being designed by Nick Dine, a son of the artist Jim Dine.
Featuring a lavender vinyl floor, red fixtures and a central glass
tower from which the owners will be able to oversee the fashion
show below, it will look ``clean and happy,'' Nick Dine said,
adding, ``It's in keeping with Beth and Sarah's bubbly
personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Being entrepreneurs hasn't interfered with the traditions of
sorority solidarity between the two women. Since moving to New York
in 1993, they have been the hosts for Monday Assembly Night, as
they call it, when eight girlfriends get together to gab about
guys, breakups, careers and clothes. The group is so close-knit
that when one member confessed she was seeing a psychiatrist, the
others felt betrayed. ``But what about us?'' Ms. Shepherd remembers
thinking. ``In the South, you talk about your problems with your
girlfriends.''
</P>
<P>
   Living in New York where neuroses, therapy and crass
commercialism prevail is another matter. ``We come from a place
where women are nice and well behaved,'' Ms. Shepherd said. ``But
here if you don't stick up for yourself, no one else will. That's
been the greatest challenge. Especially when it comes to
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Thanksgiving, both women quit their jobs to put together a
business plan. Without any income, they got by eating Campbell's
soup, Lean Cuisine and cereal. They were late paying their rent and
used their credit cards to their limits.
</P>
<P>
   But six weeks and 60 pages later, they had drawn up maps of
SoHo, spread sheets, sales projections and every detail of their
store's operation. The plan was so thorough that their accountant
asked who did it.
</P>
<P>
   The two women came up with a list of 10 potential investors, and
at the Mercer Kitchen in January, they presented their plan to one
of them. To their surprise, he immediately agreed to finance the
entire project. (Although the women confirmed that their backer is
involved in the entertainment and Internet industries, they signed
a confidentiality agreement and would not name him.)
</P>
<P>
   Reminded of the high-profile retail failures in New York of the
last decade, including the downtown Barneys, the Charivari chain
and Galleries Lafayette, Ms. Hailes and Ms. Shepherd, who seem
congenitally optimistic, smiled politely, then recounted a
conversation they had last summer. While lunching on cheeseburgers
and imagining themselves as shop owners, they turned to their
horoscope in Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   `` `At this time, the expression, `Rome was not built in a day,'
affords you wonderful insight,''' Ms. Hailes repeated from memory.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Think of potential, not limits,''' Ms. Shepherd added, right
on cue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
