<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-INSURER-NYT &LR;      06-04 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-INSURER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG JAPANESE INSURANCE FIRM FOLDS, HIGHLIGHTING INDUSTRY'S WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Financial authorities on Friday suspended operations at
Toho Mutual Life Insurance Co., only the second major insurer in
Japan to go out of business since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Toho's trouble underscores problems facing the entire industry.
And because Toho has a tie-up with GE Capital Corp. of the United
States, the suspension will be watched closely by the foreign
financial community as a test of whether foreign concerns can
withstand possible spillover effects from weak or ailing Japanese
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Japan's insurers have been staggering under the weight
of billions of dollars in property losses and bad debts. Like the
nation's big banks, Japan's life insurance companies went on buying
sprees during the economic go-go years at the end of the last
decade, and they are now stinging from losses as property prices
have in some cases plunged 90 percent from their peak values.
</P>
<P>
   ``The life insurance industry in Japan has problems which could
be equally as serious as those in the banking industry,'' said
Andrew Smithers, president of Smithers &AMP; Co., a financial
consultancy based in London.
</P>
<P>
   Smithers said Toho was probably the most vulnerable of the
insurers, but that there were a couple of other insurers that were
also bleeding. Partly because Toho's demise had been anticipated,
financial experts say that there is unlikely to be any backlash
effect on other financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The government has established a new protection fund for
insurance policyholders, but analysts say the fund has very little
money and that it is possible that the Bank of Japan may have to
extend loans to the fund to cover payments to policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1997, Nissan Mutual Life Insurance Co. collapsed,
leaving many policyholders nearly empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, GE Capital, a unit of General Electric,
negotiated its way into Japan's closed and clubby insurance
industry by striking a deal with Toho and setting up a joint
venture, GE Edison Life Insurance Co. Analysts said the deal looked
good because the new venture would start afresh with only Toho's
new business, while the old, more risky policies remained with Toho
Mutual. GE thus seemed to isolate itself from the fallout from a
collapse of Toho.
</P>
<P>
   But the suspension order by the Financial Supervisory Agency
appears to affect at least a small part of GE Edison's operations.
It is not clear whether negative publicity over the collapse of
Toho may also have any impact in the minds of policyholders on the
reputation of GE Edison. GE Edison issued a statement Friday saying
that its operations would be ``secure and unaffected'' by Toho's
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Toho officials told a news conference Friday evening that its
accountants refused to attach their blessing to the financial
statements for the year ending March 31. Accountants in Japan have
a reputation for being generally lenient in their audits, and their
refusal suggests that Toho was in severe financial distress.
</P>
<P>
   Toho officials said that its auditors figured that the company
had to dispose of 230 billion yen, or about $2 billion, in bad
assets arising from potential losses on securities, foreign
exchange deals and bad loans. If the company had done so, then it
would have had a capital deficit of about 200 billion yen, or about
$1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese life insurers, like Toho, have been squeezed by
plummeting interest rates in Japan. For years, government rules had
forced them to pay out high, fixed returns on insurance policies.
But with interest rates falling to nearly zero, the money that life
insurance companies received from policyholders was invested in
stocks and bonds offering increasingly lower returns so that they
often ended up paying more out to policyholders than they received
from their investments, which are their major source of income.
</P>
<P>
   One measure of financial health at life insurers is called the
solvency ratio, and the government has said that a ratio below 200
percent is a severe warning sign. A year ago, Toho reported a
solvency ratio of 154 percent, and that ratio probably tumbled in
the year ending March 31, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
