<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard's Windsor Is Shaking the Blues &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No less an authority than John C. Bogle, founder of the Vanguard
Group, has inveighed against market-timing _ switching in and out
of the market in hopes of catching rallies and avoiding drops. A
``fruitless pursuit,'' he has called it.
</P>
<P>
   The recent rebound in Vanguard's $17 billion Windsor fund
suggests that timing a change in fund managers isn't a particularly
easy hobby to master, either.
</P>
<P>
   After an 18-month spell when the fund _ under the guidance of
Charles T. Freeman _ lagged behind its peers, Vanguard announced in
late March that it had signed Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co. to take
over management of part of the fund; the move took effect last
week.
</P>
<P>
   But as it turns out, since March 25, the day Vanguard announced
the change, Windsor has trounced most of the nation's other big
funds as well as Vanguard's most popular offerings. For example, as
Windsor soared 13.2 percent through Friday, the Vanguard 500 Index
fund rose just 3.2 percent while Janus 20, the hottest big fund
during the first quarter, fell 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman, who took the reins of the Windsor in 1996 from John
Neff, was helped by the strengthening economy and weakening
concerns about global economic problems, which prompted investors
to pour money into the deep-value companies Windsor owns.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman says energy stocks like Burlington Resources, Anadarko
Petroleum and Union Pacific Resources and cyclical issues like
Alcoa and Caterpillar contributed most to Windsor's turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``We paid a price in 1998 by staying true to our style,''
Freeman said. But, he added, ``we were confident we had a lot of
unrecognized value in our portfolio. It's been validating to see
that recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   The move by Vanguard came after a long period of
underperformance: Windsor had a total return of about 20 percent
during the previous two years, compared with about 70 percent for
the 500 Index fund. Investors withdrew $1.2 billion from Windsor in
just the first three months of this year. The fund, which was
closed to new investors 10 years ago, reopened last week.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard officials noted that when they announced the change,
they emphasized their full confidence in Freeman and his firm,
Wellington Management, and that he would remain the lead manager,
responsible for overseeing the majority of the fund's assets.
</P>
<P>
   They also said they had discussed assigning some portion of the
portfolio to other managers long before Windsor's problems, to
increase its diversification _ an action taken previously at other
Vanguard funds despite their good performance.
</P>
<P>
   Richard A. Oppel Jr. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Calpers Will Start to Invest in Money Managers It Hires &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The California Public Employees' Retirement System, the giant
pension fund, will invest in some small money management companies
it hires to manage its assets.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe the move by Sacramento, California-based
Calpers is the first time a pension fund has sought to take equity
interests in the managers it hires to invest its money.
</P>
<P>
   Calpers, which has more than $150 billion in assets, said it
will commit $4 billion to the program, spreading the money among 10
to 30 managers over the next three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a good situation,'' said Edd Fong, a Calpers
spokesman, adding that the fund will benefit from the managers'
ideas and by ``generating earnings from growth of the equity
position.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bloomberg News) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Debut for Internet Futures &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is upset by the recent volatility in Internet
stocks. Consider the Kansas City Board of Trade, which began
trading futures on ISDEX index of 50 Internet stocks last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we want,'' said Michael Braude, president of the
board, best known for its wheat futures trading. As for volume on
the Internet futures, the first such contracts available, Braude
said he was pleased. ``It's about exactly where I predicted,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 ISDEX contracts were traded daily last week, about the
same volume as for the exchange's Value Line stock index and
natural-gas futures.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Teitelbaum
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
