<HEADER>
A3574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANASTASIA-BALLET-REVI     06-04 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANASTASIA-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANASTASIA': MEMORIES OF A (PERHAPS) PRINCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If only Kenneth MacMillan's ``Anastasia'' were a
novel. Then one could skim over its loquacious bits and finally be
gripped by a thrilling conclusion. But ``Anastasia'' is not a
novel. It's a three-act ballet that entered American Ballet
Theater's repertory Thursday night at the Metropolitan Opera House.
And it cannot be skimmed.
</P>
<P>
   The production is marvelously danced, but the choreography is
uneven. Telling the story of Anastasia, a daughter of Czar Nicholas
II and Czarina Alexandra Feodorovna, the Russian emperor and
empress, the ballet begins with its heroine as a girl enjoying a
picnic aboard a yacht in 1914. This idyll is interrupted by news of
war. In the second act, set in 1917, Anastasia is now a young woman
at a palace ball. Her happiness is again shattered, this time by
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The third act takes place in a hospital many years later. A
woman who purports to be Anastasia relives memories of the Russian
Revolution, and past and present mingle in hallucinatory episodes,
some of them blending action onstage with old newsreels. This act
displays MacMillan's ability to devise powerful and almost
Expressionistically dramatic choreography. But one has to wait a
long time for it.
</P>
<P>
   MacMillan based the act on the actual case of a woman known as
Anna Anderson who did indeed insist she was Anastasia, although her
claims have been seriously questioned. But in the ballet, Anna and
Anastasia are presumably the same person. In any case, they are
portrayed by the same dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Viviana Durante was the heroine Thursday. A ballerina from
Britain's Royal Ballet who is a principal dancer with Ballet
Theater this season, Ms. Durante understands MacMillan's style, and
her lurchings, staggerings and moments of stony immobility in the
last act convincingly suggested that this hospital patient was
trapped in a nightmare from which she could not wake. Before that,
in the first act, Ms. Durante was appealingly girlish as she made
an entrance on roller skates, and she was a charming princess in
the second act.
</P>
<P>
   It is the third act that one remembers. Dramatically
self-contained, it can serve as an independent ballet in its own
right. In fact, MacMillan originally choreographed it in 1967 as a
one-act work for the Ballet of the Deutsche Oper in West Berlin.
Then he created his three-act production for the Royal Ballet 1971.
Yet the one-act version has also been performed by companies,
including Ballet Theater in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   What do the other acts add? Dramatically, not much.
Nevertheless, the first act had technically spectacular dancing by
Maxim Belotserkovsky, Marcelo Gomes, Keith Roberts and Ethan
Stiefel, as officers. Victor Barbee and Christine Dunham were
dignified as the czar and czarina and Ethan Brown was a sullen
Rasputin. In the second act, Ashley Tuttle and Gomes were imposing
in a pas de deux supposedly performed by stars of the Imperial
Ballet. Yet MacMillan stretches his story very thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anastasia'' is musically unusual. Whereas the first act is set
to Tchaikovsky's Symphony No. 1, Opus 13 (``Winter Dreams'') and
the second is to Tchaikovsky's Symphony No. 3, Opus 29 (``The
Polish''), the third combines electronic sounds with Bohuslav
Martinu's ``Fantasies Symphoniques.''
</P>
<P>
   New York balletgoers will find some of this music familiar.
George Balanchine chose the Third Symphony, shorn of its first
movement, for the ``Diamonds'' episode of ``Jewels,'' which the New
York City Ballet produced in 1967. And Antony Tudor used the
Martinu for ``Echoing of Trumpets,'' the harrowing anti-war ballet
that he staged for the Royal Swedish Ballet in 1962 and that has
gone in and out of Ballet Theater's repertory since 1967. Musically
as well as choreographically, the third act stands on its own.
</P>
<P>
   MacMillan died in 1992, and this complete ``Anastasia'' has been
staged from Benesh Notation by Monica Parker, a notation
specialist. Each act in the production designed by Bob Crowley
begins by showing a curtain with a portrait of the Russian imperial
family on it. The simple settings suggest a deck, a palace with
fantastically tilted chandeliers and a bleak hospital room. In
contrast, the costumes, in period style, are elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Ermanno Florio conducted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
