<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-04 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION: FOR THE BUDDHIST CALENDAR, A BUSY FEW WEEKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the number of Americans practicing or at least
interested in Buddhism grows, so, not surprisingly, do the number
of public events associated with Buddhism, and the attention paid
it by the news media and book publishers.
</P>
<P>
   This may well become evident in events the next couple of
months.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably the 14th Dalai Lama, exiled spiritual leader of
Tibet, is scheduled to give a public lecture in New York's Central
Park on the morning of Sunday, Aug. 15. He will speak about the
essentials of having a life of compassion and happiness, say the
event's organizers, one of which is the Tibet Center, a Tibetan
Buddhist organization in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama has been in the city before. But this time one
might say the ground for the visit will be prepared spiritually by
another event in Central Park, Change Your Mind Day, a free program
being offered Saturday to introduce people to Buddhist meditation,
sponsored every year by Tricycle: The Buddhist Review, a magazine
published in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   And in something of a coincidence, the public television program
``Religion and Ethics Newsweekly'' will broadcast a two-part report
on the Dalai Lama and the Tibetan exile community, the first
installment being shown in New York Saturday at 10:30 a.m. (and
again Sunday at 6 p.m.) on WNET, Channel 13. (It will be televised
at other times over the weekend in other cities.)
</P>
<P>
   According to a transcript of the report, the Dalai Lama
discusses his staunch commitment to nonviolence, a topic both
timeless and, in a season scarred by school shootings and the
Balkan war, timely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need human values,'' he tells his interviewer. ``The
troubled family can be a peaceful family, not through money, not
through other means, but through transformation within ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Tibetan Buddhists view the Dalai Lama as a reincarnation of his
predecessor. He was born Tenzin Gyatso in 1935, two years after the
13th Dalai Lama died, and has lived outside Tibet, in Dharamsala,
India, since he and many thousands of Tibetans fled a Chinese
military invasion of their homeland 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The destruction of Tibet's monasteries that followed has been
well documented. The report broadcast by ``Religion and Ethics
Newsweekly'' says the assault on Tibet's religious life continues,
albeit more subtly. One Tibetan scholar says China is creating a
thoroughly materialistic culture in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama elaborates on his broad vision in a forthcoming
book, ``Ethics for a New Millennium,'' to be published by Riverhead
Books in August. According to a galley copy, he describes his hope
for a spiritual transformation in the world, a movement he says
need not be linked to dogmatic religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a call to turn toward the wider community of beings with
whom we are connected,'' he writes, ``and for conduct that
recognizes others' interests alongside our own.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama has written other books as well, an
autobiography, ``Freedom in Exile'' (HarperCollins, 1990), and
``The Art of Happiness'' (Riverhead, 1999), with Howard Cutler.
</P>
<P>
   The attention given him and his teachings points to the growth
in public interest in Buddhism, said Rande Brown, a member of
Tricycle's board. The magazine's event, Change Your Mind Day, will
take place on Central Park's Great Hill, near West 98th Street,
beginning at 12:30 p.m. Nine teachers, from varying Buddhist
traditions, will offer instruction in silent meditation and
chanting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an introduction to meditation itself, and it's also an
introduction to the variety of Buddhist practice,'' Ms. Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The first year it was held, in 1994, about 300 people attended.
Ms. Brown estimated that 10 times that number came last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough people wander by and are serendipitously drawn into the
silence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of interest by Buddhist groups elsewhere, similar events
under the same name will be held today in San Francisco's Golden
Gate Park and in Williamsport, Pa. And on July 10, in another
example of Buddhism's reach, Buddhists in Alaska will hold an event
of their own at a park in Anchorage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
