<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PHILHARMONIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE NEW YORK PHILHARMONIC, A DRUMMER GETS LUCKY WITH WATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The violinists have it easy. When other members of an
orchestra step forward to play solos, as several did Thursday at
the New York Philharmonic, they face harder choices.
</P>
<P>
   Some may get lucky, with the occasional ready-made masterpiece,
as Joseph Robinson did in Richard Strauss' Oboe Concerto. Others
may dig up oddities that are generally neglected, often justly, as
Joseph Alessi did in William Grant Still's Romance for Trombone and
Orchestra. And the truly adventurous may offer pieces newly written
for them, as Christopher Lamb did in Tan Dun's ``Concerto for Water
Percussion and Orchestra in Memory of Toru Takemitsu.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``adventurous'' hardly begins to cover the ground in
this case. In a grand and entertaining circus of a piece, Lamb,
aided by fellow percussionists, was asked to fill some 25 minutes
by audibly manipulating water (patting, pounding, dribbling,
swirling, pouring and splashing) as well as instruments in water,
holding water or evoking water (including a Slinky).
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the orchestra spared adventures of its own, in imitation
or contrast, with ripping or percussive strings and whining or
blaring winds. (The blaring was often done by bare reeds or
mouthpieces: what would so much water be without duck calls?) Here
was a notion worthy of P.D.Q. Bach, though to judge from the
dedication to the Japanese composer Takemitsu, Tan intended it in
all seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   There may indeed have been trenchant comment here on the notion
of virtuoso performance as the very circus act the pianist Glenn
Gould suggested it was when he gave up public performance decades
before he died. But was it music?
</P>
<P>
   Not as we have come to think of music, able to make a coherent
effect through sheer sound. It is hard, for example, to imagine an
audio recording of the work; the effect would be lost on New
Yorkers who already hear gurgles and whooshes coming from the pipes
between the walls of their apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all its episodic nature, the work, experienced live,
held at least one semi-jaded audience spellbound and received a
semi-standing ovation. The Chinese-born Tan, coming from a culture
in which the indigenous form of opera is an all-encompassing art
including even acrobatics and slapstick, knows spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, he made a listener ponder the nature of music and
its materials, a line of thought that continued as Robinson busily
set about a comparable manipulation of air, transforming flowing,
endless streams of breath into limpid, seamless melody with
masterly ease.
</P>
<P>
   Alessi made much of little in the Still, which backed his fluent
melodism with insipid strains, and Kurt Masur conducted this, like
the rest, with beaming pride in his troops. But the third good
reason to catch this program (which is repeated tonight and on
Tuesday) was something else: a performance of Strauss' ``Till
Eulenspiegel,'' big, boisterous and sly, in which Masur proved
utterly in his element.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
