<HEADLINE>
ADVANCE FOR EDITIONS OF JUNE 7 AND THEREAFTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
 OOH LA LA, THAT ARCH OF TRIUMPH 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paris Las Vegas will open in September, and the Wall Street
Journal provides a list of Parisianities  &LR; being provided by the
thoughtful planners:
</P>
<P>
   _ A former French waiter who has agreed to grow a mustache
``into a handlebar style'' (apparently deemed French by somebody)
will ride a large tricycle periodically through the lobby. His
vehicle will carry a basket containing fresh bread baked by French
bakers (whose mustaches should be contained in nets).
</P>
<P>
   _ The carpets in the casinos will be patterned on a floral
painting by  &UR; Claude Monet &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Housekeepers are being taught to say ``bonjour'' to guests;
valets are instructed to say ``allez, allez'' to each other; and
bartenders are studying history, in particular why the Arc de
Triomphe was built. (It's difficult to know whether this is
forecast as the question customers are most likely to ask the
bartenders, or that the bartenders are expected to make small talk
by bringing this up.)
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Two thousand items from the archives of  &UR; Elvis Presley &LR;  at
Graceland will be auctioned in Las Vegas in September by Guernsey's
auction house. Among the artifacts is a letter from Buckingham
Palace inviting Presley to perform for  &UR; Queen &LR; 
 &UR; Elizabeth &LR; . He said no.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Time magazine completes its list of the 100 Persons of the
Century with this week's ``Heroes and Inspirations'' installment,
which includes  &UR; Harvey Milk &LR; , who is described as a ``gay rights
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Personals found only two other Bay Area figures on the complete
list of 100: BofA founder  &UR; A.P. Giannini &LR; , ``architect of
nationwide banking,'' is included in ``Builders &AMP; Titans''; and
``solid-state physicist''  &UR; William Shockley  &LR; (whose views on race
made him infamous well after the man in the street had forgotten
his Nobel Prize), &LR;  was included in ``Scientists &AMP; Thinkers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ John Munch, the ``Homicide'' character played by  &UR; Richard &LR; 
 &UR; Belzer &LR; , is in negotiations to move from Baltimore to New York and
join ``Special Victims Unit,'' a spin-off of ``Law &AMP; Order'' to
debut this fall. Munch will  &LR; also  &LR; appear from time to time on
``Law &AMP; Order,'' reports the New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homicide'' executive producer  &UR; Tom Fontana &LR;  told the Daily
News that he wished the series had ended less abruptly. `` `St.
Elsewhere' ended,'' he said, `` `Gunsmoke' ended. I wish we could
have written a final episode of `Homicide.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ The San Francisco Zoo wished to tell  &UR; Sophia Loren &LR;  last week
about its own Sophia Loren, a beautiful year-old Magellanic penguin
named after the actress.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ken Maley &LR;  points out that among the four auto license plates
pictured on Subaru ads currently emblazoned on the sides of buses
is one from Colorado, decorated with a rainbow. It was Colorado
that passed anti-gay-rights legislation in 1992 (struck down by the
Supreme Court the following year); the rainbow is a gay and lesbian
icon. The words on the license plate: ``CAMP OUT.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Congratulations from  &UR; Fran Johns &LR;  to the Nob Hill Gazette for
winning the Journalistic Achievement Award bestowed by the American
Society for Aesthetic Plastic Surgery.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking at commencement exercises at Duke University's Fuqua
School of Business,  &UR; Ted Turner &LR;  made mention of another celebrity
in the audience. ``I know this is childish,'' he said, in remarks
quoted in People magazine, ``but I just have to say, I think it's
so cool that  &UR; Oprah &LR;  has to listen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mirror of London has expressed its displeasure _ reported
by MSNBC _ over  &UR; Sophie Rhys-Jones &LR; ' wearing the same hat twice in
public in a week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE HAPPY TRAILS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Examining the State Department's on- &LR; line travel advisories in
preparation for a trip she's making this summer,  &UR; Dede Tisone &LR;  came
across a set of warnings for motoring in Turkey, where drivers are
warned to ``make no assumptions about what another driver may do or
how they will react in a situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of ``Key Motoring Terms'' at the end of the advisory
includes the Turkish words for fate (kismet); may God protect me
(Allah korusun); careless (dikkatsiz), &LR;  and disorderly (duzensiz).
</P>
<P>
   _ A friend  &UR; Ward Schumaker &LR;  took to church in Omaha recently was
shocked that the recessional hymn was _ you guessed it _  &UR; Dale &LR; 
 &UR; Evans &LR; ' greatest hit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we make technology sexy? ... There have been all sorts
of movies with extended laptop sequences, and we've seen everyone
from Meg Ryan to Sandra Bullock to Tom Cruise tapping away at
keyboards, hoping to create international suspense, erotic danger
or at least some swoony date chat. There's something frustrating
about paying nine bucks to watch stars type.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Libby Gelman-Waxner on the problems of moviemaking in the
'90s, in Premiere magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
