<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS URGE BUSH TO SIGN LEGAL DEFENSE BILL TO HELP POOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A delegation of lawmakers and legal and civil
rights advocates Friday urged Gov. George W. Bush to sign into law
a bill they say will strengthen the way attorneys are appointed to
represent poor people charged with crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (legislation) did not come out of thin air,'' said Sen.
Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, and chief sponsor of Senate Bill 247. ``It
did not come from nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill was passed without objection in both houses and is on
the governor's desk awaiting his decision on whether to sign it, to
let it become law without his signature or to veto it. He has until
June 20 to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's office, however, has been swamped in recent days with
protests from Harris and other counties asking the governor to veto
the measure. Harris County, which includes most of Houston, has 3.1
million people and is the largest county in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal district judges in Harris County voted unanimously
earlier this week to authorize administrative Judge George Godwin
to urge Bush to veto the measure. They contend it would shift the
power to appoint defense attorneys from trial judges to county
commissioners court. If Bush does not veto it by June 20, it will
become law Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis and other supporters of the measure said the legislation
would not require commissioners court to make any changes other
than to hold a public hearing to set a formal policy on appointment
of lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Most counties in Texas will likely continue to use the system
they have now, said Jim Allison, general counsel for the &UR;  &LR; County
Judges and Commissioners Association, a group that is supporting
the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who ask Gov. Bush to veto it are asking him to defy the
unanimous will of the Legislature,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the current system of allowing the more than 500
district judges in the state to appoint defense attorneys for the
poor has resulted in a ``hodgepodge'' of policies. The legislation
grew out of a State Bar of Texas study of the issue; similar bills
were proposed in 1995 but did not pass.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sharlot, dean of the University of Texas School of Law,
said some counties might be concerned that the new system would be
more costly. ``That may be true,'' he said, but the additional
costs might be offset by speedier resolution of legal matters.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Senate Bill 247 would require:
</P>
<P>
   _ Commissioners courts to set a formal policy on the appointment
of defense attorneys for those too poor to hire their own,
including fees to be paid. Counties could elect to have
commissioners make the appointments, allow judges to continue doing
so or hire an outside agency to handle the legal representation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defendants to be provided an attorney within 20 days of
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   _ Counties to report annually information on the court
appointments; a new office of court administration would review
counties' compliance with state law and the constitutional
requirements that indigent defendants be provided a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said he sponsored the legislation because abuses in the
current system, which allows judges to appoint defense attorneys
and decide how much to pay them, is flawed. There is ample
evidence, he said, for why the system of defense attorney
appointments should be overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, a court-appointed attorney in a capital
murder trial several years ago slept through portions of the trial,
which resulted in a death sentence. He also cited an instance in
which two disabled defendants were jailed four years awaiting trial
on minor charges because court-appointed counsel did not know the
procedures for getting the men transferred to a mental hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said he expects the governor will withhold a decision on
whether to sign the bill until close to the June 20 deadline so the
he can study the measure.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Ellis said, he will be on a business trip in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to be over there in South Africa celebrating
democracy in South Africa and find out that things got pretty
undemocratic over here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, he added, ``It could get ugly. If it is vetoed
there is another side to my personality.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
