A3602 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-HASTERT-NYT &LR;      06-04 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-HASTERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASTERT WILL REWRITE SPENDING BILLS TO SHIFT EASE CUTS IN SOCIAL
PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Exclusive)  
(rm) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, his bills stymied and
his control of the House insecure, has decided to rewrite
Republican spending plans and shift some money from increased
military spending to ease cuts in social programs like health and
education, key aides said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert will tell the House Republican caucus on Monday that
``we're going to trim off some of the allocations for defense,
treasury, the legislative branch, and feed some of that back'' into
bills financing programs for labor, health and human services,
education, housing and veterans' affairs, a senior Republican aide
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a work in progress,'' said John Feehery,
spokesman for Hastert. ``We are going to have to fight each bill.''
So far, the House has failed to pass a single one of the 13
separate appropriations measures that finance the government for
fiscal 2000, which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, five months into his tenure, is having a hard time
carrying out the Republican strategy: to be the party of national
defense and fiscal discipline, pour billions into new Pentagon
spending, freeze or cut everything else, and pass the spending
bills on time and in good order. Now, only the Pentagon's windfall
seems assured.
</P>
<P>
   Under the original plan for the coming year, the Defense
Department received $19 billion more than this year; domestic
programs received $26 billion less. Under the evolving plan,
several billion dollars would be transferred from the military
ledger into domestic programs. Military spending would still rise
and domestic spending would still fall, but by less than first
planned. No final figures are set.
</P>
<P>
   The new goal is to restore cuts in domestic spending that
moderate Republicans find intolerable, keep at least some
conservatives happy, and win over enough moderate Democrats to pass
the bills.
</P>
<P>
   The shift would bring the House spending plan closer to the
Senate's. But with a perilously slim 223-212 majority in the House,
Hastert needs Republican unity to pass anything. He lacks it. And
House Democrats will do little to help him.
</P>
<P>
   When he became speaker, Hastert vowed to pass the spending bills
on time.
</P>
<P>
   The year's first major spending measure, a $60.8 billion
agriculture bill, was derailed last week by fiscal conservatives
who wanted to block all such bills until there was a plan for
protecting the Social Security surplus. Then Hastert could not
summon the votes to bring a $289 billion defense authorization bill
to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Republicans' conservatives are in revolt, their
moderates frustrated and their leadership red-faced. They recall
the 1998 budget breakdown and the 1995 government shutdown and
worry that their slim majority may be threatened if they appear
inept.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   If Republican leaders ``can't communicate a strategy to their
members, they can't communicate a strategy to the American people,
and if they can't do that, they are going to be in a world of hurt
when they go up against the Democrats in 2000'' said Peter Sperry,
a budget analyst at the Heritage Foundation, a conservative
think-tank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the House, where spending bills traditionally originate,
Republicans have allocated $270 million for the Pentagon and $268
billion for every other arm of the government in fiscal 2000. That
latter sum, expressed as a percentage of the American economy, is
the lowest allocation for domestic spending since 1962.
</P>
<P>
   And the way that sum was divided among the 13 House
appropriations subcommittees set moderate Republican chairmen
howling that the wealth was spread too thin. To Hastert's left,
liberals warned that the Republican plan starved needy people and
worthy programs. To his right, conservatives promised to hew to the
cuts, stop dipping into surplus Social Security revenues, and keep
the spending caps enacted by Congress and the White House in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The caps held the budget down and helped create the surplus, but
both Republicans and Democrats are asking if they still make sense
in an era of economic prosperity. Hastert says the caps were a
solemn promise to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Hastert, prodded by his two Texas colleagues, the
majority leader, Dick Armey, and the Majority Whip, Tom DeLay, came
up with two new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   One aims to shift responsibility, or blame, for increased
spending to individual members. A key Republican aide said the idea
would ``keep the caps but insert a trigger'' to blow them away.
``If members want to, they could vote on cap-busting amendments,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The other idea ``was changing the allocations, working with
chairmen to take a whole new approach,'' another senior Republican
aide said.
</P>
<P>
   That would redistribute billions from the bills financing the
Department of Defense, Congress, the Treasury Department and the
Postal Service. The money would be shifted to two other bills. One
finances the Departments of Labor, Health and Human Services and
Education, which took a $10.7 billion cut in this year's plan, from
$88.8 billion to $78.1 billion. The other, for housing, urban
development, veterans and several independent agencies, took a $5.7
billion cut, from $71.9 billion to $66.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce, Justice and State Departments, which face a $3
billion cut, and the Interior Department, cut by $2.6 billion, also
might also see some money restored.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Republicans have promised to stop the spending
bills in their tracks unless each one is cut or frozen at last
year's level. That forces Hastert find 13 magic numbers: sums that
will allow the 13 bills to win 218 votes in in the House.
</P>
<P>
   If he cannot, he will face a reprise of last year's last-minute
free-for-all spending bill, loaded with $21 billion of extras
financed from the Social Security surplus, or a repeat of the 1995
government shutdown. In each event, House Republicans lost face,
President Clinton gained political capital, and programs the
Republicans wanted to cut or kill won new life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
