u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV06-B     06-04 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING 10 YEARS OF A MODEL PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 6, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most things don't work out as planned, some things go roughly as
planned, and a few things work out much better than planned.
</P>
<P>
   In that third category we place City Year, the Boston-based
national volunteer youth service corps that became the model for
AmeriCorps, the Clinton administration's domestic version of the
Peace Corps. City Year is 10 years old, and the
volunteer-for-a-year service corps is flourishing.
</P>
<P>
   It's biggest boosters? Clinton &AMP; Clinton. The First Mom &AMP; Pop
latched onto the City Year idea initially when they were running
around the country in campaign mode in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw City Year I knew that I had found the concrete,
living, breathing embodiment of what I thought politics ought to be
about,'' Clinton told 1,000 City Year volunteers two weeks ago in
Washington. On Friday it was Hillary's turn, showing up at Faneuil
Hall for the 10th anniversary of the enterprise that is a model,
wedding entrepreneurial and non-profit traits with corporate and
government backing.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you call it ``the New Covenant,'' as he did in his first
campaign, or ``the so-called Third Way,'' as liberal political
parties that move to the center are labelled, said Clinton, ``It
simply means that government can't solve all our problems, but it
can't leave people to sink or swim on their own, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said: ``It means that we have an obligation, all of us,
to give every single person the tools to make the most of his or
her life. It means that we have an obligation, together, to create
opportunity for those who have been forgotten, to take
responsibility for the welfare of not only ourselves and our
families, but of our whole community.''
</P>
<P>
   For both Clintons, celebrating City Year in two different cities
two weeks apart was a welcome change from the visit the couple made
recently to Littleton, Colo., and the Columbine high school
students whose high school year collapsed in gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that community service can have a profound impact on
diminishing, even erasing, the sense of alienation and isolation so
many of our young people feel,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In Littleton, ``We talked to the young people still in their
wheelchairs from their grievous wounds.'' The president said ``one
of the things that struck me so strongly, in following all the
accounts of what happened, and what could have motivated those two
young men to descend into darkness, and take the actions they did,
was the repeated description of the sense of alienation they felt
-- that they and their group were somehow looked down on by others
in their school, and that in reaction, they not only felt
bitterness against those who were looking down on them, they turned
around and looked for someone else to look down on.''
</P>
<P>
   Using language very similar to the words he used in urging
Kosova refugees to forgive their Serb oppressors, Clinton said:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an endless cycle, Everybody has a beef in life,
Everybody! Everybody has resentments because of slights or
mistreatment, whether imagined or real. A big part of living is
finding ways to overcome your own smallness, to get out of your own
skin -- to let go of all the things not only tghat you have
imagined have happened to you, but things that have really happened
to you, that should not have.''
</P>
<P>
   The two shooters at Columbine became ''trapped in their own
fears and resentments and hatreds,'' and ``they must have drifted
to get to the point where they could literally dehumanize the other
children. ...''
</P>
<P>
   With that, he hailed the assembled thousand volunteers, as ``the
America we have, the America we're going to be; we're growing more
and more diverse.'' You're the future, Clinton said. ``I'm telling
you, you can reach the poor in spirit amoung our youngf. You can
tell them that no matter what has happened, no matter what's
bugging them, no matter who is dissing them, no matter what they
have a beef about, real or imagined, what you're doing is a better
way to live, and they ought to join you and live that way too.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill's a believer.
</P>
<P>
   City Year started with a Boston pilot project ten years ago,
enlisting 50 young people, public school kids and prepsters, black
and white, Hispanic and Asian, from city and suburb.
</P>
<P>
   That summer-long commitment began with a three-day outing on
Thompson's Island in Boston Harbor, utilizing techniques from
retreats and encounter groups that welded the disparate individuals
into a team that assembled weekday mornings on Boston Common to do
calesthenics in their trademark chinos-and-T-shirt work duds.
</P>
<P>
   The early money came from BankBoston and four other corporate
sponsors, and the enterprise has expanded every year since.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by Mike Brown and Alan Khazei in Boston as a framework
to harness the energy and idealism of young people who wanted to
improve society, City Year caught a break when candidate Clinton in
1991 was casting about for ways to plug young people into grass
roots community work. ''And when I went to City Year in Boston, the
lights came on and I said 'this is what I want to do'.''
</P>
<P>
   With the founding AmeriCorps in 1994, the City Year model became
the blueprint for a national service corps that has given America
the fruits of a year of organized effort by 100,000 young
Americans. City Year has prospered as well. From Boston it expanded
to Chicago, Cleveland, Detroit, Philadelphia, San Antoni, San Jose,
Seattle, Columbia, SC., Columbus, OH, and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers between 17 and 24 give up a year for a weekly stipend
and a college scholarship grant upon completion. There are nearly
1,000 current City Year volunteers, and 3,981 alumni. The computer
geeks calculate these kids contributed over 5.8 million hours of
community service in a variety of ways.
</P>
<P>
   So there was lots to celebrate Friday at Faneuil Hall with
Hillary Clinton leading the cheers. The First Lady was in town for
a Boston Medical Center speech and her 30th Wellesley College
reunion, and generating buzz about her announcement of an
exploratory committee to plan for a potential race for a US Senate
seat in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bain Capital, BankBoston and Timberland Co. each kicked in $1
million Friday to endow corporate-sponsored City Year teams for the
next 50 years. On top of that, Holly Davidson, Sidney and Judy
Swartz, and Paul and Phyllis Fireman each committed another $1
million each towards endowment projects. Compaq Computer also
donated a $1 million gift.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Brown and Alan Khazei had the idea, and the knack for
persuading businessmen and politicians that the idea was solid, and
the proof was on display Friday afternoon at Faneuil Hall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
