<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3610 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-JACKSON05-COX     06-04 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-JACKSON05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Freedom is sought for CARE employees
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Saying that a new wave of international humanitarian
aid workers will be needed to rebuild Yugoslavia now that peace is
near, the Rev. Jesse Jackson came to Atlanta on Friday to urge
Yugoslav authorities authorities to release three CARE workers he
said were convicted and imprisoned on false charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot rest until all the captives have been set free, and
leaders on all sides have made a decision to study war no more,''
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights activist and former presidential candidate
succeeded in May in securing the release from Yugoslavia of three
American soldiers. He said he is prepared to return to Belgrade, if
necessary, to try to negotiate the release of the CARE workers.
</P>
<P>
   The three men _ two Australians and a Yugoslav _ work for CARE
Australia. The two Australians, Steve Pratt and Peter Wallace,
stayed in Belgrade after other workers were evacuated. They were
detained March 31, a week after NATO forces began bombing
Yugoslavia, as they tried to cross into Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Branko Jelen, a Yugoslav staff member, was arrested about a week
later in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt was shown April 11 on Serbian TV, confessing to having
used his position with CARE to perform covert intelligence
activities. Peter Bell, the president of CARE USA, which is based
in Atlanta, said he believes the confession was coerced and false.
</P>
<P>
   Charges of spying against the three were dropped. Instead, they
were convicted May 29 at a closed military trial of passing secret
information to a foreign organization _ namely CARE.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three CARE captives are innocent,'' Bell said. ``They have
committed no crime. They are being held prisoner essentially for
having done their humanitarian jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   In Yugoslavia, CARE rendered assistance not only to ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, but also to Serbian refugees from Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Bell were joined at a news conference by Malcolm
Fraser, a former prime minister of Australia who is chairman of
CARE Australia's Board of Directors, and former Atlanta Mayor
Andrew Young, a member of CARE USA's Board of Overseers. The
meeting was held at National Park Service Visitor's Center across
Auburn Avenue from the Martin Luther King Center, and afterward the
four men laid a wreath on King's tomb, held hands and prayed.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said he had been assured by senior officials of the U.S.
State Department that the fate of the three will not be forgotten
in negotiations with Yugoslav authorities over implementation of
the peace agreement. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and outgoing
South African President Nelson Mandela have also intervened on the
workers' behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Young said that, with refugees returning and winter not far off,
humanitarian workers will be needed to provide food and shelter _
and the safety of humanitarian workers must be assured.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser agreed. ``If, as seems likely, this wretched war is
coming to an end, the humanitarian need in Yugoslavia is going to
be massive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
