<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3615 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV06-B     06-04 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS THE FIFTH DISCIPLINE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 6, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two things made a huge difference in Peter Senge's life. His
father, an Eastman Kodak executive, was transferred to California
when he was a boy. So he grew up as a witness to profound and
unanticipated change _ social, cultural, economic, environmental.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when Senge came from Stanford to the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology as a graduate student, he met Jay
Forrester. Forrester, a computer pioneer who left engineering to
develop what he called ``systems dynamics,'' was a commanding
presence at MIT _ but a fringe figure in its intellectual life, an
autodidact who had set out to reinvent economics.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost ten years now since Senge distilled Forrester's
views on the counterintuitive behavior of social systems in ``The
Fifth Discipline.' A couple of workbooks have followed, including
recently ``The Dance of Change: The Challenges to Sustaining
Momentum in a Learning Organization.''' Senge's book has acvhieved
the status of a management classic.
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly is the Fifth Discipline?
</P>
<P>
   The first four disciplines in Senge's schema _ make that
``component technologies'' of corporate cultures, if you like _ are
familiar enough to those of us who think about our lives in
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Personal mastery has to do with individual vision and
dedication. Whatever it is that makes a master craftsman, this is
it: a private, passionate commitment to lifelong acquisition of new
skills and improvement of old ones through learning.
</P>
<P>
   Mental models are the assumptions, myths, stereotypes, pictures,
and images that inform personal understanding. These mostly
unconscious ``scenarios,'' in the parlance made familiar by the
planners at Royal Dutch Shell, have great power to guide workers to
opportunities _ or blind them.
</P>
<P>
   Shared visions are like mental models, except that they are
blunt and widely held. They are the stories that bind individuals
to a common purpose in an organization. They may be extrinsic (``I
was taught to hate the Russians, Yale and the Brigham and Women's
Hospital,'' says the Massachusetts General Hospital surgeon) or
intrinsic (ordinary people empowered by computers was the shared
vision of the founders of Apple Computer; people want styling was
for many years the shared vision of General Motors.)
</P>
<P>
   Team learning, the fourth discipline, builds on personal mastery
and shared vision but goes beyond it into the realm of
improvisation, says Senge. ``The great jazz ensemble has talent and
a shared vision (even if they don't discuss it), but what really
matters is that the musicians know how to play together.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fifth Discipline, says Senge, is systems thinking, the habit
of seeing interdependent wholes and fathoming their logic. Among
the ``laws'' of the Fifth Discipline identified by thinkers as
various as Garrett Hardin, Indries Shah, Jay Forrester, Donella
Meadows, and Kahlil Gibran:
</P>
<P>
   Today's problems come from yesterday's solutions.
</P>
<P>
   The harder you push, the harder the system pushes back.
</P>
<P>
   Behavior grows better before it grows worse.
</P>
<P>
   The easy way out usually leads back in.
</P>
<P>
   The cure can be worse than the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Faster is slower.
</P>
<P>
   Cause and effect are not closely related in time and space.
</P>
<P>
   The areas of the highest leverage are often least obvious.
</P>
<P>
   You can have your cake and eat it to _ but not at once.
</P>
<P>
   Dividing an elephant in half does nor produce two small
elephants.
</P>
<P>
   There is no blame for failure _ the ``cure'' lies in your
relationship with your ``enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fifth Dimension'' has sold more than 600,000 copies, and
catapulted Senge into the front ranks of management gurus, along
with Tom Peters, Michael Porter, Henry Mintzberg, John Kotter,
Rosabeth Moss Kanter and a handful of others. For a time in the
1990s, enthusiasm for the ``learning organization'' was rivaled
only by the ``re-engineering'' craze. That in turn brought about
Senge's separation from MIT (he remains a senior lecturer at the
school's Sloan School of Management.)
</P>
<P>
   From the very beginning, Senge worried about what would happen
when the fad began to fade. After all, Total Quality Management
(TQM), among the most widespread movements of the 1980s, petered
out in two thirds of the organizations in which it was tried for
lack of hoped-for results. Re-engineering didn't do much better.
</P>
<P>
   So Senge now pins his hopes now on a pair of unusual
institutions. His Society for Organizational Learning, spun out of
MIT into an East Cambridge office park, welds together employees at
all levels in a couple of dozen organizations and corporations _
the American Medical Association, the World Bank, AT&AMP;T, Chrysler
Corp., Federal Express and Pratt and Whitney _ in an ongoing
experiment in ``capacity building'' that is overseen by a small
staff, 56 academic research fellows and 106 consultant members.
</P>
<P>
   Senge also has assembled and maintained a small team of writers
who have produced two attractive workbooks designed to help
managers implement his ideas, ``The Fifth Discipline Fieldbook''
and now ``The Dance of Change.'' These include Charlotte Roberts
and Richard Ross, a pair of consultants; Bryan Smith, an
international vice president of Arthur D. Little; George Roth,
director of the Ford-MIT Research and Development Project; and Art
Kleiner, author of ``The Age of Heretics,'' a lively study of
management practices.
</P>
<P>
   So what is the Fifth Disciple really? It is a ``community of
inquiry and experimentation'' of some tens of thoudand of disciples
distributed about equally among big US corporations and the
education establishment. The editorial dogma resembles in style and
content the Whole Earth Catalog of a few years back. It is not for
everybody. But it is good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Warsh writes about economics for the Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
