<HEADER>
A3620 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$A     06-04 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDICAPPING WALL STREET AS OLD LINE GOES ON LINE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In hindsight, rather than extolling the Internet, maybe
securities firms should have advised customers to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   Now the retail brokerage business, which generated about $12.8
billion in commissions in 1997, is getting a comeuppance because of
low-cost, on-line trading.
</P>
<P>
   The latest _ and biggest _ blow to the primacy of
flesh-and-blood brokers came last week, when Merrill Lynch said
that by December it would offer on-line trading for as little as
$29.95 a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that could generate huge savings for its five million
customers. Less obvious, however, is how Merrill will recoup the
big chunk of change it will lose.
</P>
<P>
   The market has apparently decided that there is no positive
answer to that question, and most brokerage stocks have moved
sharply lower since Merrill made its move.
</P>
<P>
   Sallie Krawcheck, an analyst who follows Wall Street firms for
Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co., talked last week about Merrill's
announcement. Here are some excerpts. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Just how big a deal is Merrill's move?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It is hard to overstate the significance of this. It is a sea
change in the retail brokerage business. Managements at all of
these firms are going to have to craft responses to what Merrill
has just announced in very short order.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional businesses of firms like Merrill, Dean Witter
and Smith Barney have never experienced pricing pressure, and now
they are. And we are not talking about taking prices down by 20
percent, but by 90 percent. For some time, we had been forecasting
that the retail business would contract by 5 percent a year going
forward, as the traditional business became outdated. This is like
death by fire. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Aside from the cost issue, why have so many people
apparently turned away from full-service brokers?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Retail brokers have done a poor job of attracting the next
generation of investors. If full-service retail brokers don't get
clients early, they generally don't get them at all, because those
who need brokers have not gone to full-service brokers, but a whole
set of different financial intermediaries.
</P>
<P>
   The typical client of a retail broker is in his or her mid-60s.
So the image of a traditional broker in the industry has evolved to
something like a Cadillac, or the last car you drive before you
die. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)A number of on-line trading firms have run
advertisements belittling the advice retail brokers offer. Is it
realistic to think that investors can do everything on their
own?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Over the last few years, there has been a lot of bickering
between brokers and the Internet. But all of these things can
co-exist. There is no reason advice can't be delivered
electronically. And the value of advice, given the massive amount
of information available to everyone now, is, if anything, even
greater than previously. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Based on the recent movement in the stocks,
investors seem to agree with you that the Merrill announcement is a
seismic event. But is it fair to assume that retail is equally
important to all these firms?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The market does an extremely poor job in discriminating among
the companies. Momentum is the biggest driver for the group.
</P>
<P>
   We estimate that for Merrill, retail brokerage accounts for
about 25 percent of its quarterly earnings. The stock has fallen
about 14 percent in a week.
</P>
<P>
   At Paine Webber, the same number is about 50 percent. Its stock
is down by about 11 percent.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)The threat of on-line trading isn't the only reason
these stocks are down, is it?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In addition to the Internet fears, we have fears of Fed
tightening and concerns about Y2K. Of the three, the Fed will
probably impact the group the least. When the Fed fine-tuned
monetary policy in 1997, it was a tremendous opportunity to buy the
group.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these worries, right now the businesses for these firms
are in good shape. All of the stocks are telling us earnings are
not going to be good, but equity underwriting is on a path to be up
25 percent over the first quarter. Trading volumes remain robust,
both in fixed income and, to a lesser extent, in equity. And Asia
and Europe are real bright spots for these firms. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)So which stocks do you like?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter is down 22 percent from its highs
and has taken a greater hit relative to its retail earnings than
Merrill has. It appears the market has again forgotten the real
underlying earnings power this company has displayed. For clients
who want exposure to financial service stocks, we think this is a
real core holding.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns is also off 27 percent, but should it be taking a
hit? They are primarily a clearinghouse, and the stock is
perennially cheap. At the moment, it is trading at less than nine
times next year's earnings. It just doesn't get any respect.
</P>
<P>
   For long-term investors with a bullish long-term view on the
international aspects of the business, we like Goldman Sachs,
though the stock appears fairly valued.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
