<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 MINOR TIANANMEN PROTESTS IN BEIJING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also HONGKONG-TIANANMEN) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Two one-man protests near Tiananmen Square,
immediately snuffed out by police, were the only brief
interruptions in a normal workday here Friday as the 10th
anniversary of the violent crackdown on pro-democracy
demonstrations passed without official notice.
</P>
<P>
   The square itself is fenced off for resurfacing. Directly across
the street Friday morning, under a large portrait of Mao Tse-tung,
a middle-aged man opened an umbrella marked with political slogans
including ``Remember the student movement!'' He was quickly led
away by police.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday afternoon at the same spot, a young man suddenly
threw flyers into the air bearing a fervent message against
corruption and the growing divisions in society. He ran into the
street, where eight policemen tackled him and bundled him off by
car.
</P>
<P>
   Police scrambled to pick up the flyers, which mentioned the need
for democracy but not the student movement of 10 years ago, and
ended with the slogans ``Long Live Chairman Mao'' and ``Down with
American Imperialism.''
</P>
<P>
   After the incidents, a few foreign camera operators and
photographers were briefly accosted by police and forced to hand
over their exposed film.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3625 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-TIANANMEN-NY     06-04 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-TIANANMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HONG KONG, 70,000 COMMEMORATE TIANANMEN SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also CHINA-TIANANMEN) 
(mk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ More than 70,000 people turned out here Friday night
on a balmy evening to hold candles, sing songs and pay respects to
those who lost their lives a decade ago in the bloodshed at
Tiananmen Square in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only major public commemoration of the crackdown held
on Chinese soil. And for the people who gathered here to demand
that the Chinese government make amends, it was a powerful reminder
that Hong Kong remains an island of free expression amid the
government-imposed silence in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are calling out to all the heroes who died 10 years ago,''
said Szeto Wah, a pro-democracy leader, in a speech that mixed
poetry and politics. ``I hope you will come to our little island of
China. Your anger is our anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Szeto called on the Chinese government to reassess its actions
on the night of June 3-4, 1989, when it sent tanks and troops into
Tiananmen Square, crushing the student-led democracy movement and
killing hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has stopped remembering this part of history,'' he
said. ``We are ready, generation after generation, to fight until
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Silently, the crowd stood and held candles aloft, turning
Victoria Park into a sea of softly flickering lights. Around the
crowd, a wall of twinkling skyscrapers rose up into the cloudless
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited,'' said Betty Li, 60, a retired engineer from
Beijing who marched in the pro-democracy demonstrations in 1989 and
traveled from the mainland city of Zhuhai to mark the anniversary.
``In China, they're still not giving people these kinds of
freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the vigil's organizers expressed fears this week that 10
years after the crackdown and nearly two years after Hong Kong
reverted to Chinese rule, people's emotions would have cooled.
Judging from the crowd Friday, though, feelings here remain
fervent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a massacre,'' said a 40-year-old dentist who
identified himself as Alan. ``It is a terrible memory. Time can't
wash out the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizers, who had expected that the 10th anniversary would
draw a larger crowd than past anniversaries did, were delighted
with the turnout, which was the largest in several years. The
weather played a role. Last year, fewer than 20,000 gathered in a
torrential downpour.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the turnout was nothing like the 1 million people
who jammed a racecourse here in 1989 to protest the crackdown. But
then, Hong Kong's relationship to Beijing was entirely different _
it was a British colony still eight years away from reverting to
Chinese sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The events in Beijing traumatized people in Hong Kong because
they seemed to foretell a grim future for this capitalist enclave.
People here were terrified by the prospect of being taken over by a
government willing to cut down its own citizens.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1989 rally, hundreds of thousands of protestors chanted,
``We now stand side by side with the Chinese people and we declare
war on the government of Li Peng,'' referring to the former Chinese
prime minister who orchestrated the crackdown on the students in
Beijing and is now the No. 2 official in the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, even critics of Beijing acknowledge that Hong Kong is
outwardly the same. Officials in Beijing have not suppressed civil
liberties, including the right of pro-democracy groups to hold
protests. But some people here say that what they see as pernicious
trends in Hong Kong _ like the weakening of the rule of law _ have
their roots in the crackdown and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   ``By expressing such support for pro-democracy forces in
Beijing, Hong Kong spooked the Chinese leadership into hardening
its attitude toward the handover,'' said Yeung Wai Hong, the
publisher of Next magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hong Kong was granted a degree of autonomy after the
handover, Chinese officials were determined that it not become a
staging area for subversive activities. Among other things, Beijing
retained the right to countermand rulings by Hong Kong's courts.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, this annual vigil has become a way for Hong Kong
to reaffirm its differences from mainland China. In contrast to
Beijing, where nervous officials have sealed off Tiananmen Square
for renovation, the police presence here was light and officials
treated the vigil as a routine event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a showcase for the international community that people
can still demonstrate in Hong Kong,'' said Albert Cheng, a radio
talk-show host. ``On the other hand, the government certainly
wouldn't want it to attract 100,000 or 200,000 people. Then Beijing
would think that it was spinning out of control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
