<HEADER>
A3626 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLEMAN-MUSIC-REVIEW-     06-04 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLEMAN-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVE COLEMAN: A BEAT THAT LINGERS IN THE MIND AFTER A TRIPLE
BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Most of Steve Coleman's music sounds as if it begins
life as drum patterns. He is an alto saxophonist whose connection
to Charlie Parker is always clear in darting movements and clear
articulation, and his greatest departure from the main line of jazz
esthetics currently is in the hard, slapping Afro-Cuban drumming
that lies behind his work. It's partly an interpretation of Yoruban
religious music, the kind that accompanies Candomble and Santeria
ceremonies, and it replaces the airy netting of swing and bop
rhythm with a kind of beautifully detailed concrete wall.
</P>
<P>
   As played by Sean Rickman on a normal drum kit (no congas, no
unusual percussion), those layered drumbeats _ at times machinelike
and done at brutally fast tempos _ were the sounds that lingered in
the mind after leaving the Knitting Factory on Thursday, the first
night of the Bell Atlantic Jazz Festival.
</P>
<P>
   First on the triple bill came Ravi Coltrane, whose music is more
flexible. The tenor saxophonist played tunes built on small
syncopated rhythmic motifs that informally wound their way into the
music; each written nugget triggered a few arrangement ideas for
his quartet, including pianist Andy Milne, bassist Daryl Hall and
drummer Steve Hass, so the structure of the piece sprang into being
by sudden decision. When Coltrane's band is at its best, you never
quite know where the music is going. His saxophone style is a bit
mumbling and consciously leached of stylization. But this, of
course, its a style in itself. (The pianist Paul Bley has a
similarly mysterious touch.) Little by little, Coltrane is
constructing one of the more compelling musical personalities in
jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, on the other hand, has a drive that doesn't let up, nor
does it change much over the course of an evening. His group, Five
Elements, around for nearly 20 years now, has moved into a hard,
brash and exact realm; there's little emotional comfort in it or
range of mood. Instead the music approximates a dangerous sport
like bronco-busting or fire-juggling; the trick was for the
musicians to hang on to the polyrhythms without hurting themselves.
The enterprise was fascinating in its single-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   The musicians ( Coleman, the trumpeter Ralph Alessi, the bassist
Anthony Tidd, and Rickman) each performed their small rhythmic
cycles, forming a great wheel of rhythm that eventually spun so
fast that it sounded like the new skittering styles of English
dance-club music. A recent piece, ``Pi,'' contained a long written
melody that was picked up in part and then set aside for rounds of
soloing; at the end, the band converged on the melody, playing it
fast in lock step. Even Rickman rattled out the tune on his drums.
</P>
<P>
   The third group of the night, Renegade Way, isn't Coleman's his
band per se, but it used his rhythm section and his methods. If
Five Elements plays insistent music, this group hammered away with
four times the force. There was a curtain of saxophonists in the
front line: Coleman, Coltrane, the alto saxophonist Greg Osby and
the tenor saxophonist Gary Thomas. Without creating particularly
compelling harmonies, they teased counterpoint out of several long
pieces by Coleman; they took turns at being the central soloist,
then came together in unison on long, knotty melodies.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Coltrane, these players have a lot in common; they
used short, pinpointed notes in their improvisations. Coltrane, on
the other hand, generally expresses himself with longer, smoky,
smeared sounds. So there was a moment of tension on the fastest
tune of the night, when Coltrane soloed last after three
improvisations that sounded like Charlie Parker played at triple
speed. What would he do? He played fast phrases but left gaps in
his discourse; even traveling at superspeed, he deliberated. Taken
as a whole, the performance felt like a study in different kinds of
coolness, of grace under pressure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
