<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-LAWSUIT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke says talk OK if silent on lawsuit
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. told an Atlanta federal court judge
Friday that the company should be allowed to freely communicate
with its U.S. employees about workplace diversity if it does not
express its views about a recently filed racial discrimination
suit.
</P>
<P>
   If the plaintiffs succeed in restricting such communication,
``every business decision Coca-Cola makes concerning diversity
among its employees will be misinterpreted as primarily about this
lawsuit merely because it is made while the lawsuit is pending,''
the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola was responding to a plaintiffs' motion asking the
judge to order the company to send out a special notice advising
black salaried employees that they can participate in the suit
without fear of retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' request came after Coca-Cola Chairman and Chief
Executive M. Douglas Ivester sent a May 26 e-mail to U.S. employees
telling them he was forming a Diversity Action Council and that
there was ``no room'' and ``no tolerance'' for discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   A month earlier, four current and former employees filed suit
against the beverage giant, alleging that it has a companywide
practice of discriminating against African-Americans in pay,
promotions, performance evaluations and terminations. The
plaintiffs are seeking class-action status so they can include
another 1,500 black salaried employees in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Richard Story already has ordered the
company to put two disclaimer sentences on the e-mail messages it
sends to employees about the lawsuit, telling those workers it is
illegal for Coca-Cola to retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   But Coca-Cola did not include the disclaimer sentences in
Ivester's May 26 memo, which the plaintiffs contend was an ``end
run'' around the order.
</P>
<P>
   The company, however, said the plaintiffs' attorneys have a
``tortured and expansive reading'' of that order.
</P>
<P>
   Story must decide the issue, as well as whether Ivester can hold
small group meetings about diversity with employees who could
become plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' attorneys said such meetings could be coercive
and intimidating for black employees. But the company said these
are business-related meetings that will not address the substance
of the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
