<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cousins Properties adds Dallas unit to the family
 &HT;    By Sallye Salter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cousins Properties Inc., which has been expanding into
key development markets by buying local real estate firms, has
acquired a foothold in Dallas through a 50 percent stake in a real
estate service company there.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based real estate investment trust did not disclose
the terms.
</P>
<P>
   Cousins' acquisition of a half interest in Faison-Stone, which
manages 7 million square feet of office space, does not include any
properties.
</P>
<P>
   However, the deal is expected to yield development opportunities
for Cousins, a major developer of office buildings and retail
centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is significant to us is the potential for the long-term
development of office space in Texas,'' said Cousins President
Daniel M. DuPree.
</P>
<P>
   Dary Stone, founder and president of 8-year-old Faison-Stone,
will be Cousins' 50 percent partner.
</P>
<P>
   He will oversee the Texas operations and seek development
opportunities for Cousins. Clients of Faison-Stone, which is a fee
developer, include Motorola, Lincoln National Life and Taylor
Simpson Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past couple of years, we have expanded into the San
Francisco, Los Angeles, Charlotte, Birmingham and Alexandria, Va.,
office markets through successful partnerships with strong local
companies,'' DuPree said.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Tully, securities analyst at Wachovia Securities, called
the acquisition ``a logical way to enter a good market. Real estate
is still very much a local business.''
</P>
<P>
   Cousins has developed major Atlanta complexes in both downtown
and suburban locations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
