<SLUG> BC-AIR-FORCE-RECRUITING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE FALLS SHORT OF RECRUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Air Force has pummeled Yugoslavia without
losing a single pilot, but hasn't yet turned the tide in its war to
win recruits.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of May, the service was 2,578 recruits short of where
it should have been in its drive for 33,800 personnel by the end of
the federal fiscal year on Sept. 30, the San Antonio-based Air
Force Recruiting Service reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Army, too, was struggling, but the Navy and Marine Corps
exceeded their goals, the Defense Department said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, anytime there is a shortfall in recruiting there is
cause for concern,'' said Lt. Col. Tom Begines, a Defense
Department spokesman. ``More importantly, all of the services have
renewed and re-energized their recruiting efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing the possibility of not achieving its recruiting goal for
the first time since 1979, the Air Force plans to spend $54 million
on advertising through the end of September 2000, said Tim Talbert,
the Air Force's chief of advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Master Sgt. Tom Clements blamed the lackluster recruiting
numbers on a slow period that is now ending. He expressed optimism
that the Air Force would get back on track as the new TV spots air.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force's top civilian leader shared that view, but
cautioned that ads aren't a cure-all.
</P>
<P>
   ``All advertising can do for you, really, is to get somebody to
call you,'' Acting Air Force Secretary F. Whitten Peters said.
``Whether you can actually get the recruit in depends on a lot of
other factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Grappling with a shortage of pilots and enlistees in a variety
of critical career fields, Peters and other top Air Force leaders
last week issued a ``stop-loss'' order that will keep 6,000
personnel from leaving the service as previously planned.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force, meanwhile, has seen its recruiting shortfall rise
from 696 in February to 2,039 in April. The Army fell short by
6,791 recruits in April, while the Navy and Marines exceeded their
quota by 288 and 299, respectively, the Defense Department
reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember the last time that happened,'' Sara Lister,
former assistant secretary of the Army for manpower and reserve
affairs, said of the Air Force's shortfall. ``They have very little
trouble, usually, getting recruits because airplanes are still
viewed as the most interesting, and they also teach good, useful
skills.''
</P>
<P>
   The nation's robust economy often is seen as a chief culprit
behind recruiting shortfalls that last year rocked the Army and
Navy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
