<SLUG> BC-SWIM-FASHION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMFORT PLAYING A BIGGER ROLE IN SWIMWEAR FASHION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Swimwear shopping is getting easier.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean stores have installed dim lighting and tinted
mirrors in dressing rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Dream on!
</P>
<P>
   It means swimwear manufacturers are making more suits with
built-in support for an aging population who needs them. And
they're marketing a wider range of styles so customers have a
greater chance of finding a suit that fits and flatters.
</P>
<P>
   Big retailers are even grouping all swimwear together so a
shopper can select without having to move to another department or
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Some suits hang with little tags attached to show shoppers the
body shapes they're meant to enhance.
</P>
<P>
   Even catalogs are making swimwear shopping easier, grouping
suits on their pages by styles _ suits for full hips on one page,
for example, skimpy bikinis on another.
</P>
<P>
   Lands' End puts a small symbol _ a triangle, rectangle, circle,
hourglass or inverted triangle _ with each suit description so
readers can see immediately if the suit they admire is suitable to
their body shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business this year is being driven by newness and the tankini
is the No. 1 new silhouette,'' says Candace Bergstrom, divisional
manager for swimwear at The Bon Marche.
</P>
<P>
   A tankini, the most sought-after style of the season, is a
design that flatters many and gets high marks for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   It's a two-piece with a tanklike top made of conventional
swimwear fabric, with either a brief or bikini bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The tank top can be pushed or rolled up for more exposure. It
also provides coverage for those with long or out-of-shape torsos.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Chan, brand manager for women's swimwear at Jantzen, a
Portland manufacturer, says baby boomers are affecting the swimwear
market. ``They have a youthful attitude. They want more color.
Brighter, younger styling. But their figures are changing,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Boomers may opt for built-in support, but the look is more
natural. Prints that draw the eyes upward, ``floating underwires''
attached to suit straps, and narrow straps are just a few of the
details appealing to boomers who don't want swimwear that resembles
something their mothers or grandmothers wore.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Phillips, a trend manager for Mervyn's, says boomers want
style, fit and coverage. Today, about 25 percent of all swimwear
carried in Mervyn's stores has some kind of hidden support. That's
up about 10 percent in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Chan says every swimwear company is offering a variety of styles
in today's collections. ``That's one thing that's changed in the
last 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Suit pieces sold separately were once rare. The Bon now carries
separate suit pieces from three different companies. Some tops have
a bralike construction, perfect for large-busted women. But those
who need small tops and larger bottoms can also be fitted. Mervyn's
has a ``Suit Yourself'' line with tops sold by cup size.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swimwear is often more difficult than lingerie to buy,'' Chan
says. But the bottom line is comfort. ``Skimpy isn't really in.
Comfort is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
