A3636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CNN05-COX     06-04 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CNN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yugoslavia agrees to more coverage
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Yugoslav government's war with CNN may be over,
after five days of secret negotiations in Belgrade between Yugoslav
officials and CNN International President Eason Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said Friday that Yugoslavia, which had accused CNN of war
crimes because of its reporting, will allow more CNN reporters and
equipment into the country starting today. CNN has been pretty much
limited to reporting from Belgrade; the new agreement allows them
to report live from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demonization of CNN had to stop. We achieved everything we
hoped to achieve and more,'' Jordan said in a cell phone call from
the Yugoslav-Hungarian border.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and two CNN International employees, Steve Cassidy and
translator Mena Ivanovich, met with several top Yugoslav officials.
Although they did not meet with President Slobodan Milosevic, he
was aware of the negotiations, Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting today, CNN will double its staff in Yugoslavia from
five to 10 and will bring in an extra satellite uplink unit to
Pristina, the capital of Kosovo. ``These are major breakthroughs
for us,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said the meetings were sometimes frightening and included
discussions with officials who have been indicted by the United
Nations for alleged war crimes. He said he was told by independent
Serbian journalists that some people in the Yugoslav government
considered CNN a greater enemy than NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The rapprochement between Yugoslavia and CNN comes just as peace
between Yugoslavia and NATO seems to be on track, but Jordan
wouldn't speculate on why Yugoslavia suddenly changed its position
on CNN. ``They were impressed that leaders from CNN would make the
trip in the midst of war to explain CNN's efforts and to defend
CNN's reporting,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Even before NATO bombing of Yugoslavia began, the government was
strongly anti-CNN. Early in the bombing, the government briefly
arrested many Western journalists, and Serbian paramilitary units
attacked and confiscated CNN trucks and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's most honored international correspondent, Christiane
Amanpour, has not been in the country since she left early in the
bombing campaign because CNN executives in Atlanta were fearful for
her life. Her plans are still unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said CNN International's signal may be made available to
all Yugoslav homes starting this summer as part of the new deal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
