<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-660&AMP;ADD     06-04 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN OFFICIALS EXPRESS ANGER AT KOSOVO PEACE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Kosovo peace agreement that was struck on Thursday
with the consent of President Boris Yeltsin and his special envoy
got a scalding reception in its first review here Friday, not
merely from politicians, but from some of Yeltsin's own officials.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators who attended a closed meeting in the lower house of
parliament said officials of the defense and foreign ministries who
had been sent there to explain the agreement actually attacked it
more than they supported it.
</P>
<P>
   The city's premier news radio station reported that Yeltsin's
deputy foreign minister had said his ministry had disassociated
itself from the settlement, a report his subsequent public remarks
did nothing to dispel.
</P>
<P>
   Leftist and nationalist members of parliament condemned it as a
Kremlin sellout of Yugoslavia and a betrayal of Russia's strategic
interests. One of Moscow's more substantial newspapers,
Nezavisimaya Gazeta, wrote that Russia had succumbed to NATO
pressure and that its role in the peace talks had been ``whittled
down to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a less than auspicious welcome for Yeltsin's envoy to the
talks, Viktor Chernomyrdin, who announced Friday that he is a
candidate for the same legislative body that was so
enthusiastically flaying him.
</P>
<P>
   But the outbursts almost certainly will have no impact on the
Kosovo accord, and it is not even clear that the broad political
center from which Chernomyrdin sprang, and which was mostly silent
Friday, shares the rage.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few Russian legislators who openly supports NATO's
role in Yugoslavia, Konstantin Borovoi, suggested in an interview
that many of Friday's critics were as much outraged at losing a
political issue as they were by any details of the accord itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lost the adventure that they had created,'' he said.
``The feeling of loss _ that there was not going to be a third
world war started _ was quite strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it clear that ordinary Russians will share the critics'
sentiments, despite the wide streak of anti-Americanism that many
have lately shown. Although many Russians see the Kosovo conflict
as a bald act of American expansionism, they also want the war to
end without deeper Russian involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Springing to his own defense, Chernomyrdin said Friday that he
had achieved both. ``There were two options: either to stop the war
by political methods or to fight, to put on our greatcoats and
march ahead,'' he said. ``I don't think that this way suits the
Russian people today.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin said through a spokesman that he thought Chernomyrdin
had performed his job well.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview Thursday night, Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin offered this: ``At least one serious result has been
achieved. We've moved from the dead point.''
</P>
<P>
   The day's hottest rhetoric came from the left. Gennady Zyuganov,
the Communist Party leader and almost certainly a candidate in the
2000 presidential election, said Russia's parliament ``must sort
out the situation and answer the question of why the person who was
named special envoy pushes through the main ideas which NATO
dictates in the form of an ultimatum.''
</P>
<P>
   Zyuganov called the agreement ``a Balkan Khasavyurt,'' a clear
jab at Yeltsin. Khasavyurt was the scene of the 1996 cease-fire
accord in which Yeltsin gave Russia's Chechen republic considerable
autonomy in order to end a disastrous war.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Kharitonov, the Agrarian leader, outdid Zyuganov. ``It's
1938; Munich plot,'' he said hours after the agreement was
announced on Thursday.'' Even the generals who are also present
around Chernomyrdin at the talks are puzzled, because all his
initiatives are in NATO's interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Borovoi, the legislator who is supportive of NATO, said the same
themes were echoed when officials of the defense and foreign
ministries briefed legislators in Friday's closed session. Asked
whether anyone rose to defend Chernomyrdin or Yeltsin, he replied,
``I wasn't given the microphone.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Legislators said later that the presentation by Yeltsin's
ostensible representatives in the session was more critical than
supportive. Sergei Ivanenko, a top official in the centrist Yabloko
faction, said the representatives' remarks suggested that ``the
special envoy conducted the negotiations not very successfully and
made a number of concessions'' which were unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Radio Echo Moskvy quoted unnamed sources as saying that Deputy
Foreign Minister Aleksandr Avdeyev disassociated his ministry from
the accord during the session.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, Avdeyev complained to reporters that the agreement
contained ``a vague formulation'' that has allowed NATO forces to
continue bombing Yugoslavia over Russian objections. He left
hanging the question of whether their was a split in Yeltsin's
delegation to the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a delegation,'' he said. ``We have a special
envoy who has done his job and who will report to the country's
leadership.'' For its part, he added , the Foreign Ministry is
trying to represent Russia's interests in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Borovoi said the reaction of military leaders who also attended
the session was especially striking. ``Their feelings were,
basically, full despair,'' he said. ``The disappointment was pretty
strong and they didn't conceal it. I'm afraid that they will try to
spoil this process of the settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   The hawkish head of the defense ministry's department for
international military assistance, Col. Gen. Leonid Ivashov, made
little effort to conceal his contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Ivashov, who has dispatched some of the military's more ominous
warnings about the consequences of continued war over Kosovo, said
the peace plan could leave Kosovo's 250,000 Serbs helpless at the
hands of Albanian rebels in the Kosovo Liberation Army. Meanwhile,
he said, Russia's role in peacekeeping and Yugoslavia's territorial
integrity depend entirely on NATO's whims.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether all that amounts to a betrayal of Russia by
Yeltsin and Chernomyrdin, Ivashov replied simply, ``Everyone should
decide that with his own heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
