<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS RALLY AS INVESTORS SEEM PREPARED FOR RATE INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices rallied Friday and bond prices moved
slightly lower as investors signaled that many expected a rate
increase when Federal Reserve policy-makers meet at the end of this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The selloffs in stocks since May 18, when the Fed first
indicated it was leaning toward a rate increase, have been enough
to compensate for higher interest rates, in the view of many
investors. Sectors that had been hit particularly hard, including
drugs, banks and technology stocks, helped lead the rally Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 136.15 points, or 1.28
percent, to 10,799.84 behind rallies in American Express, up 3 5/8,
to 125 1/4; DuPont, up 3 5/16, to 70 1/4, and Procter &AMP; Gamble, up
3 1/8, to 96 5/8. The Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks rose
28.21 points, or 2.17 percent, to 1,327.75.
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ composite index, which had dropped 10 percent from
its recent high, jumped 75.02 points, or 3.12 percent, to 2,478.34,
lead by Microsoft, up 3 3/16, to 79 9/16; Cisco Systems, up 6 1/16,
to 114 7/8, and Intel, up 2 11/16, to 53 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   There was little change in the bond market, where yields had
shot sharply higher in the last two months as the economy refused
to slow down. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond inched up to
5.96 percent from 5.95 on Thursday. The price, which moves in the
opposite direction, slipped 3/32, to 90 5/32. The yield on the
two-year Treasury note, which is very sensitive to fears of Fed
rate increases, rose to 5.53 percent from 5.52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This performance came after the Labor Department said that only
11,000 new jobs were created in May, an increase that was sharply
lower than Wall Street forecasts of a gain of nearly 220,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, such an unexpectedly weak report would have sent bond
prices higher as investors figured that a slowing economy would
lessen the risk of a Fed rate increase. Stock prices, in such a
situation, could go either way, with some investors buying because
of the reduced risk of a rate increase while others sold on worries
that slower growth would curb corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, investors decided that despite the weakness of
the jobs data, the outlook for the economy had not really changed.
This means that growth has not slowed enough for the Fed to ignore
the jump in consumer prices that was reported for April and is
likely to be seen again in the May data due out in a week and a
half. Next week's retail sales data could also show that consumers,
who have been the driving force behind the economy's rapid growth,
have not cut back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you thought about the labor market before this
number, you still think about the labor market,'' Donald Fine,
chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management, said. Other data
released earlier this week, including automobile and light truck
sales and a key manufacturing index, all showed that the economy
was still surprisingly strong last month.
</P>
<P>
   But the run-up in interest rates already, which has seen the
yield on the two-year note jump two-thirds of a percentage point in
two months, has given the Fed a green light to raise interest
rates, he said. The yield on the two-year note is nearly a half of
a percentage point higher than it would be if no rate increase were
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Battipaglia, chief investment strategist for Gruntal &AMP;
Co., agreed. ``Nothing much will happen,'' he said, after a quarter
of a percentage move up in the Fed interest rate target, which is
now 4.75 percent. But he said that if there were indications that
the Fed would move interest rates still higher, there might be more
reverberations.
</P>
<P>
   Battipaglia also said stocks were likely to get support from
what he expects to be very positive earnings news for the second
quarter, which would begin to be reported in July, just after the
next meeting of Fed policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
   First Call Corp., which tabulates corporate earnings estimates,
says Wall Street analysts currently expect second-quarter earnings
for the companies in the S&AMP;P 500 index to rise by 12.8 percent,
compared with a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Battipaglia said, the global financial crisis that
shook the financial markets last summer is gone. ``The landscape
for this summer looks dramatically different than last summer,'' he
said, ``and that has to be good for stocks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
