<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASPOLE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Monster Mile's now a fast, smooth ride
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ The white patches on the surface of Dover Downs
International Speedway make the one-mile concrete track look like
it's drying after a rain, or as though someone has whitewashed the
place.
</P>
<P>
   It may as well be a smiley face: A grinder has smoothed out the
one-time Monster Mile. Monster? The top 32 cars in Friday's
qualifying for the MBNA Winston Cup Platinum 400 on Sunday broke
the track record, led by pole-winner Bobby Labonte's 159.320 mph
lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty hair-raising,'' Labonte said.
</P>
<P>
   But his was the only testimony to a track that usually devours
stock cars and is hard on drivers. Earlier Friday, all 36 cars that
qualified for today's Busch series race also bettered the track
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obvious it was going to be fast,'' said Mark Martin,
who qualified third at 158.325 mph, right behind Dale Jarrett
(158.576). ``Everywhere it's white, there's a lot less bumps,''
Martin said. ``That's everywhere they've ground the bumps off.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin held the old track qualifying record, 155.966 mph, set
last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lap times will be faster (Sunday) than they were the last
time we raced here,'' Martin said. ``Maybe we can be less cautious.
It's smoother, it may be easier to race on. We'll find out a lot
more (in practice today).''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte's effort continued a strong qualifying run in 1999. It's
his fourth pole of the season, tops in Winston Cup, and second in
two weeks. But he is still winless in 12 races.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed that the smoothed out Dover surface is less than a
Monster this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been here before and we'll wreck six or seven cars in
practice,'' Labonte said. ``Today there wasn't an incident that I
know of in Winston Cup practice. It's tamed down but the speed is
... one slip and it's over. But I think the air dam, the spoilers
and the tires help the cars stick better.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon's problems continued. He qualified 14th, his worst
qualifying effort of the season. His bad luck Friday was drawing
the second qualifying spot and was on the track too early.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being the second car out, I'm pretty disappointed because I
went quite a bit faster in practice,'' Gordon said. ``The car
tightened up a bunch on me. I didn't really expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton, the winner last week at Charlotte, didn't bring any
momentum into qualifying. He was only 40th fastest in the No. 99
Pontiac. He was so bad in practice, he had teammate Mark Martin hop
in to drive the car before qualifying. ``He couldn't pinpoint it
either,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Other surprisingly poor qualifying efforts included Tony Stewart
(24th), Dale Earnhardt (31st) and Terry Labonte (37th).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
