<HEADER>
A3640 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-$ADV06     06-04 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME IN ISRAELI PROXY MILITIA FACE DIFFICULT DECISION AFTER
PULLOUT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, June 6) 
 
By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEZZINE, Lebanon _ As his Lebanese comrades in Israel's proxy
militia retreated south last week, Manuel Nistirof, a baby-faced
18-year-old, was faced with an unsavory choice:
</P>
<P>
   Stay with his beleaguered Israeli-paid militia, known as the
South Lebanon Army, or SLA, and continue to be demoralized by
relentless attacks from guerrillas of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Or, surrender now and hope the Lebanese authorities would offer
amnesty and the Hezbollah would spare his life.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, 83 of his SLA comrades chose to turn in their
weapons. They told their commanders they wanted to stay in this
mountain town in southern Lebanon rather than withdraw with the
militia to a 9-mile-wide border ``security zone'' set up by Israel
years ago to protect its northern communities from attack. They
brought the number of militia members who want to quit to 203.
</P>
<P>
   Nistirof, standing guard in a wrinkled Israeli army uniform at
the entrance to Jezzine, said he would wait to see how those men
were treated before deciding what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I see them get amnesty,'' he said, ``I'll surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of more SLA desertions adds urgency to Israeli
Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak's promise to withdraw Israeli
troops from Lebanon within a year, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   For 14 years, SLA militiamen have been on the front lines of
Hezbollah's war of attrition to oust Israel from the occupied zone.
Culled from the impoverished villages of Lebanon's south and from
the ranks of Christian militias defeated in Lebanon's civil war,
the SLA has been the key to Israel's continuing presence in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   If the SLA unravels, Israel will lose an ally that until now has
helped provide a foothold in strategic places like Jezzine, a
Marionite Christian town just north of the Israeli-occupied zone.
The SLA abandoned the town in the wee hours Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Israel also will lose a force that has helped provide its 1,500
soldiers, whose positions are farther south, with a buffer against
increasingly deadly Hezbollah attacks.
</P>
<P>
   That scenario is what Hezbollah hopes to provoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (SLA) are serving as sandbags to the Israelis, as a
barrier, a shield`` said Ibrahim Moussawy, Hezbollah's spokesman in
Beirut. ``We want to drop this shield in order to target the
Israelis so they will feel the necessity to leave south Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   Many SLA members say there is a feeling that the militia is
crumbling. Fighters are quitting. Their commander, Gen. Antoine
Lahd, it is whispered, is planning to quit, and those still in the
force know that their patron, Israel, wants to pull out soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in this area, Hezbollah won,'' said the 18-year-old
Nistirof, who is a Christian. ``Hezbollah is winning everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But with parents living in the Christian town of Marj Ayyoun,
further inside the Israeli-occupied zone, and a father wanted by
the Lebanese government for crimes committed during the civil war,
Nistirof said he had no choice but to stick with the SLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joining them was a mistake, but I was young and I didn't know
what I was getting into,'' he said. ``I could be a normal citizen
going to Beirut, but instead I'm going further into the occupied
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who've cast their lot with the retreating militia say
sticking with the side most admit is losing is preferable to
chancing their fate with the Lebanese government or the Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this talk of amnesty is just a mirage,'' said a
28-year-old major, who refused to give his name, as he also guarded
the entrance to Jezzine. ``I don't trust my government. I'm waiting
for a real solution for the region.''
</P>
<P>
   He says those members who surrendered made a big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Hezbollah will come inside Jezzine one by one and
kill them,'' said the militiaman.
</P>
<P>
   Moussawy, the Hezbollah press attache, blamed Israel for
increasing anxiety among militiamen and their families by
exaggerating the Hezbollah threat to discourage the men from
deserting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hezbollah has sacrificed a lot of lives and shed the blood
of its young men just to help liberate Jezzine and the people
there,'' Moussawy said. ``So it's no way in favor of harming any
one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   A politically savvy Hezbollah seems to realize what Lebanese
observers in Beirut have been saying all along: that the quickest
way to bring about the demise of the SLA would be for Hezbollah and
the Lebanese government to treat those who defected with kid
gloves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would encourage more surrenders,'' said Farid el-Khazen, a
political scientist at the American University of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, the SLA checkpoint that had been on the terraced
slopes leading to Jezzine had disappeared. Nistirof was gone,
presumably somewhere in the hills to the south with his automatic
rifle slung over his back.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Jezzine, young men and women gathered in a grassy park,
waving Lebanese flags not far from a giant statue of the Virgin
Mary. Some of the 203 SLA defectors walked freely through the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid of the government or the Hezbollah,'' said a
33-year-old defector with a thick beard and pock-marked face. He
also refused to give his name, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government has something against me, I'm ready for
trial,'' said the man, who also said that he had tried to leave the
militia several times but was always caught and coerced to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows we were forced to join,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside a grocery store, another, younger defector, said he had
no qualms about quitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no guarantees if I followed them south,'' said the
former militiaman, who gave his name only as Sharbel. He said
Israel earlier had told men who wanted to quit that they would get
guarantees from the Lebanese government that they wouldn't be
jailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones who stayed with (the militia) went south because they
were officers,`` Sharbel added. ``Most of them are from the
(Christian militias who fought in the civil war) and the government
is looking for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Khawand, a Maronite monk from the nearby community of
Siddoun, met with Hezbollah general-secretary Hassan Nasrallah last
week to discuss the fate of the defectors. Khawand said the
defectors had trickled north to surrender at a checkpoint
controlled by the regular Lebanese Army.
</P>
<P>
   Khawand is part of a committee of lawyers and prominent leaders
who are putting together a compensation package for the departing
militiamen. Lahd has reportedly agreed to pay the defectors $1
million in what Khawand described as ``severance pay.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Khawand said, he had offered his monastery, Our
Lady of Mashmoushe, as a sanctuary to militiamen or their families
who feared reprisals from the Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, no one had come.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Khawand said, he has pleaded with SLA fighters to
quit the militia. Many were once his students at the monastery,
which also has a school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `Why should you die?''' recalled Khawand, who
stood under a pine tree a few miles from Jezzine. ``There is no
cause. It's better to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, they understand after so many years that they are
alone,'' he added. ``They are making this war all alone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
