r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HURRICANES-1STL     06-04 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HURRICANES-1STL-WRITETHRU-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM ODDS STACK UP AGAINST TEXAS GULF COAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 6)   (EDs: Adds 1graf after 6thgraf, ``We have, to add last hurricane to
hit coast. Pickup: Being prepared)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RALPH WININGHAM  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT LAVACA, Texas _ Since the early 1800s, there has never been
a 10-year period when the Gulf Coast of Texas has gone without a
hurricane coming ashore. Until now.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to hurricanes, being a perfect 10 is not
considered a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1900, Texas has suffered through 10 of the 30 worst
hurricanes to make landfall in the United States. Near the top rank
as the deadliest storm was the Sept. 8, 1900, hurricane that killed
as many as 8,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   During the past 10 years, the rapid growth along the Gulf Coast
has resulted in only about 10 percent of the population having had
any close experience with a major storm. And forecasters fear many
current residents of coastal areas may not fully appreciate the
potential threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no longer a matter of if, but when,'' Terry Huber, a
National Weather Service meteorologist in Corpus Christi, said of a
hurricane hitting the coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work together to get out the message to the
community,'' he told about 400 officials at the 7th annual Calhoun
County Emergency Management Conference here last week. They
represented coastal counties.
</P>
<P>
   The last hurricane to strike the Texas Gulf Coast was in 1989,
when Jerry, a Category 1 storm, hit Galveston Island.
</P>
<P>
   Being prepared and stressing the potential life-threatening
impact of hurricanes were the themes of the conference, held at the
start of the 1999 hurricane season. The Atlantic and Gulf season
runs through November.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should know what you're going to do before we issue a
hurricane watch. High winds, heavy rain and tornadoes can hit long
before the eye makes landfall,'' said Huber, who added that the
watch is issued about 36 hours in advance of projected strike.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that planning sessions are a must for officials if
they are to use all their resources in reducing the potential death
toll.
</P>
<P>
   The word hurricane is derived from Spanish and Caribbean Indian
terms for evil spirits and big winds.
</P>
<P>
   William Gray and his research team at Colorado State University,
who provides hurricane predictions to weather watchers throughout
the world, have said they believe there will be 14 named storms,
nine hurricanes and four intense hurricanes this year.
</P>
<P>
   That estimate is about 160 percent of the normal rate of
occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, no one can predict where any of the storms may come
ashore.
</P>
<P>
   Gray is also suffering through a storm of his own, with much of
his research funding being cut by the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, the National Science Foundation and the
insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   He has said he believes funding reductions are the reaction to
his public questioning of sophisticated computer programs _ called
numeric models _ that are becoming the dominant method of hurricane
forecasting.
</P>
<P>
   The programs use mathematics to forecast the weather, while Gray
and his team combine computer programs and a study of past storm
activity in their predictions.
</P>
<P>
   Gray's predictions were still the major focus at the Port Lavaca
conference, where representatives of numerous agencies discussed
storm preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems we seem to fall into is we don't want to
evacuate people until the last minute, but you have to make the
decision to have enough time to evacuate,'' Ken Baxter, hurricane
program manager for the Federal Emergency Management Agency, told
the county officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate we evacuate (storm-prone areas) seven times for
every one time you truly have to,'' Baxter said.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Schumann, senior research associate at Texas A&AMP;M
University, said evacuation models for the coastal area have
examined a number of issues to give officials a better
understanding of when to make their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the items that have to be considered are traffic load
capacity; routes; congestion in getting ready to evacuate;
evacuation times; the lowest elevation of roadways; and other
information,'' Schumann said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is no way we're ever going to replace your
experience. You know your areas better than anyone,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 2014EDT &QL; 
