<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3642 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI &LR;      06-04 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Saturday, June
5, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   MS-PATIENT (Seattle) _ James ``Jay'' Ellison goes home Sunday
possibly cured of the disease, MS, that had been short-circuiting
his nervous system and rapidly robbing him of a future. Ellison had
to fight for the stem cell transplant after his insurance company
denied payment. He went public, aided by consumer advocates and
state Insurance Commissioner Deborah Senn.It's such an amazing
success, so far anyway, that the docs at Fred Hutch can hardly
maintain their neutrality. With sidebar slugged TRANSPLANT.
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Paulson. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TRANSPLANT (Seattle) _ Scientists at the University of
Washington and the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center are
leading a rapidly growing movement to treat autoimmune diseases by
transplantation. The UW is leading a nationwide consortium of
clinical studies aimed at evaluating stem cell replacement for
treatment of a variety of immune disorders such as MS, lupus and
others.
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Paulson. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CIGARETTES-EXPORT (OLYMPIA, Wash.) _ The calls started coming
just a few months ago, wholesalers offering name brand cigarettes
at deep discounts. What's the catch, asked Matt Yorkston, who, with
his family, owns six convenience stores in Whatcom County. The
catch was this: The cigarettes were manufactured for sale only in
foreign countries, but somehow found their way back into the U.S.
market. Yorkston was getting a glimpse of the ``gray market,'' a
netherworld of trade and commerce that skirts illegality, but
manages to stay within the law.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Gavin. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SHIP-MERCY (Seattle) _ Remember the famous old hospital ship,
Hope? The Caribbean Mercy, a floating hospital currently in Seattle
to load up on rice and medical supplies before sailing with doctors
and nurses urgently needed in North Korea, is part of its legacy.
The ship, fully equipped with things like a high-tech eye surgery
clinic, has been here since May 29, leaves June 6, and its stay
coincides with a diplomatic mission to N. Korea being led by former
U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry.
</P>
<P>
   By Mike Barber. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TEMPS (Seattle) _ A row develops over the latest
attempt by 18 so-called ``perma-temps'' at Mirosoft to form a
Union.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Richman. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SWIM-FASHION (Undated) _ Swimwear shopping is getting easier.
That doesn't mean stores have installed dim lighting and tinted
mirrors in dressing rooms. Dream on! It means swimwear
manufacturers are making more suits with built-in support for an
aging population who needs them. And they're marketing a wider
range of styles so customers have a greater chance of finding a
suit that fits and flatters.
</P>
<P>
   By Susan Phinney. (Story will move in the ``l'' category.)
