<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3643 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMY-ART-NYT &LR;      06-04 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR MARKET STAYS ROBUST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By SYLVIA NASAR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's unemployment rate dropped to 4.2 percent in May, the
Labor Department reported Friday. That matches the 29-year low
first reached in March and is just the latest sign that the
nation's labor market remains remarkably robust.
</P>
<P>
   But there was also a strong hint in Friday's report that the
jobs boom may be moderating. While employers actually added 841,000
workers to their payrolls in May, the increase was rather paltry
given it is usually the peak time of year for seasonal hiring.
After the Labor Department took account of the usual spring hiring
surge, the seasonally adjusted gain in payroll employment turned
out to be virtually nil _ a net gain of a mere 11,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the increase for April was a whopping 343,000 when
adjusted for seasonal factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some signs of slowing,'' said Richard Rippe, chief
economist at Prudential Securities, ``but at the same time the
labor market is very tight and there's some upward pressure on
wages.''
</P>
<P>
   As seen through the corrective lens of seasonal adjustment, the
weakness in May hiring was widespread. Manufacturers, who have been
buffeted by the economic slowdown in the rest of the world, trimmed
45,000 workers from their payrolls, bringing the total reduction
since March 1998 to nearly half a million. Construction payrolls,
which had been climbing, on average, by 28,000 workers a month,
fell by 40,000. And services _ the main engine of job growth _
added far fewer workers than usual, just offsetting the losses
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping back a bit, it turns out that the economy has added an
average of 196,000 jobs a month on a seasonally adjusted basis in
the first five months of 1999, significantly fewer than the average
of 243,000 a month in the second half of 1998. What is more, total
hours worked are growing more slowly, at an annual rate of less
than 1 percent in the second quarter versus 2 percent in the first.
</P>
<P>
   May's mixture of strength and weakness gave investors no clear
idea of whether the Federal Reserve, whose monetary policy
committee meets at the end of the month, is likely to raise
interest rates or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very much a `wait and see what happens next' report,''
said Katherine Abraham, the commissioner of the Bureau of Labor
Statistics. ``It's too soon to draw any conclusions about this
being a turning point.''
</P>
<P>
   David Wyss, chief economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, agreed.
``It leaves the Fed where they were,'' he said, ``looking for a
sign that inflation is dangerous enough to be worth stomping on or
just a phantom menace.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last several weeks, one strong report after another on
everything from car sales to house purchases to factory output has
fanned fears that the Federal Reserve is about to raise rates. Last
month, the Fed's monetary policy-making committee, citing an
``already tight labor market'' and strong domestic spending, voted
to adopt a ``bias'' toward raising rates _ though it did not
actually raise them.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank has been on the alert for signs that the good
times are pushing wages up faster. Hourly pay did jump a bit,
rising 5 cents to $13.19 in May.
</P>
<P>
   But pay increases have been exhibiting a seesaw pattern over the
last few months, up one month, fairly flat the next, rather than a
clear acceleration. The increase from a year ago is 3.6 percent,
the same as last month. Last year, wages rose 4.4 percent. ``You
still see a deceleration,'' Rippe said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, who typically pay more attention to payrolls than to
the unemployment rate, reacted to the report with a collective sigh
of relief. Bond prices inched lower, while several stock indexes
rallied.
</P>
<P>
   American workers, of course, have been celebrating the current
state of the job market at shopping malls, car dealers' lots and
new housing subdivisions. It is easy to see why. Last month, the
unemployment rate for college graduates dipped to 1.9 percent. Over
the last year, while the number of college graduates in the work
force rose by 1.7 million, the number of managerial, professional
and technical jobs rose by an even larger number.
</P>
<P>
   Even the youngest, least educated, least experienced workers are
doing nicely. Unemployment among teenagers dropped to 12.6 percent
in May from nearly 15 percent at the beginning of the year. And the
unemployment rates among African-American and Hispanic workers
remain at historic lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still a very strong economy,'' said Wyss of Standard &AMP;
Poor's. ``The problem is much more that people can't find workers
than that people can't find jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The pattern of job growth may be shifting a bit along with the
pace. Hiring by service firms, whose appetite for more workers has
seemed to have no bounds, turned sluggish in May for the first time
since 1996. Hotels and landscaping services hired fewer workers
than earlier in the year, but even industries less prone to
seasonal ups and downs _ financial services and management
consulting, for example _ pulled back. Employment in health care
services leveled off after months of rapid growth. Retailers, which
added sales clerks like mad during the past year, hardly hired any
in May. Exceptions included car dealers and furniture stores, a
reflection of the hot market for cars and houses. Business services
_ mainly computer services and data processing _ continued to pull
in workers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the boom in all kinds of construction, which has been
adding an average of 28,000 jobs a month since last fall, payrolls
actually shrank in May. The decline mostly reflects what the Labor
Department referred to as ``erratic'' weather, which has caused
this year's seasonal hiring to begin earlier than usual. But higher
interest rates, falling housing starts and a shrinking backlog of
new commercial construction contracts suggests that hiring may stay
weak in months to come.
</P>
<P>
   Industries that have been shedding jobs continued to do so.
Despite the recent rebound in oil prices, mining outfits cut 7,000
jobs, mostly in oil and gas extraction. Declines in factory
employment were widespread, encompassing heavy machinery, aircraft,
clothing and textiles.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that this may change, said Robert Barbera, chief
economist at Hoenig &AMP; Co. Workers who are on the assembly lines are
busier than ever. The average factory workweek, nearly 42 hours,
and the average overtime, 4.6 hours, are high by historical
standards. Together with fatter order books, higher production and
shrinking inventories, this suggests that manufacturers may soon be
running help wanted ads.
</P>
<P>
   The May jobs report reflects an annual benchmark revision in the
Labor Department's payroll survey. As usual, the department found
that more jobs had been created than originally estimated.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Abraham said this year's upward revision of 44,000 jobs
was smaller than usual.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
