<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON SURVEYS, RESEARCH AND NEW PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   $50 Million Farewell For Employees &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CMP Media, whose trade publications include Computer Reseller
News, Information Week and Windows magazine, has long had a
reputation for generosity toward its employees. It was one of the
first companies on Long Island to set up day care and fitness
programs; Working Woman magazine has called it one of the best
companies to work for.
</P>
<P>
   Employees who feared that the coddling had ended in April, when
CMP agreed to be acquired for $920 million by Miller Freeman, a
unit of United News and Media of Britain, need not have worried.
</P>
<P>
   The Leeds family, which founded the company and still controlled
a 70 percent stake at the time of the sale, is giving CMP's 18,000
employees $50 million from the proceeds. Michael Leeds, president
of CMP, said the family ``felt very strongly that these people had
committed themselves to building the company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted them to share in its success,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Employees will get $4,000 for each year at CMP, plus one-fifth
of their 1998 compensation. The Leeds family, for its part, will
reap $663 million from the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Leeds said the employee windfall was in keeping with the outlook
of his parents, Gerard and Lilo Leeds, who founded the company in
1971. German immigrants, they ``wanted to prove that you could run
a company that was profitable and good for the employees,'' Leeds
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine Fabrikant &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   56K Fingers? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are two safe predictions: The pace of business and of life
will keep accelerating, and a keyboard will figure in an ever
larger share of the communicating we do, commercial and personal
alike.
</P>
<P>
   At the intersection of those two trends is a species of
virtuosity that is master of both. And for a change, the virtuosos
in question are not 20-something geek-savants, but rather more
mature figures imbued with something of a nostalgic air: speed
typists.
</P>
<P>
   The OPAC unit of Biddle &AMP; Associates, a company that sells
skills-testing software, sponsors an annual competition for the
fastest professional typist in America (measured by its software,
of course), with accuracy taken into account.
</P>
<P>
   The three 1999 winners all run secretarial services businesses,
and none is under 40: Karen Schouest of New Orleans, Kathy Jerome
of Phoenix and Barbie Dallmann of Charleston, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   How fast is fast? At the rate she was clocked in the contest,
Ms. Schouest could reproduce this item flawlessly in 88 seconds.
(The winner of a parallel contest for students, Keith Wilson of
Virginia Beach, Va., would need 89.)
</P>
</TEXT>
