<HEADLINE>
STARR PROBE OF CLINTON MAY PLAY ROLE IN CISNEROS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The independent counsel investigation of President
Clinton's affair with a White House intern is expected to become an
issue when jurors are chosen for the conspiracy trial of former
Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the Cisneros case have told U.S. District Judge
Stanley Sporkin they want to quiz prospective jurors on whether
they agree with the widespread feeling that Congress should let the
law that authorizes the appointment of independent prosecutors
expire later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackowski, a prosecutor for Independent Counsel David
Barrett, and Barry Simon, a lawyer for Cisneros, will submit those
questions to Sporkin on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's investigation led to the indictment of Cisneros on
charges that he lied to the FBI about payments made to a former
mistress. The issue arose during a background check into Cisneros'
appointment to head the Department of Housing and Urban Development
in Clinton's first term.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection will begin later this month in preparation for
the July 6 trial.
</P>
<P>
   Jackowski told Sporkin he wants to poll prospective jurors about
``the debate in Congress on the independent counsel law.'' The law
dates to the years after the Watergate affair when Congress sought
to allow attorneys general to name a special investigator who was
sheltered from political influence.
</P>
<P>
   There is growing sentiment in Congress not to renew the statute,
saying it is too narrow in its application and that the duty of
investigating executive branch officials could be better performed
by career lawyers in the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Even Kenneth Starr, whose investigation of Clinton's affair with
Monica Lewinsky led to the impeachment of the president, has called
for a repeal of the statute.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the Cisneros case are eager to determine the
impact of the Starr investigation on the 200 people who have been
summoned for possible jury duty in the Cisneros trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Starr investigation was widely criticized by Democrats as a
Republican-led effort to embarrass the president and force him from
office. Although Clinton was impeached by the House for lying about
his affair in sworn testimony, the Senate could not muster the
votes to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   The pool from which jurors in the Cisneros case will be selected
is heavily Democratic. Of the 316,000 voters eligible for jury duty
in the District of Columbia as of May 31, 248,040 were registered
Democrats, 41,204 were independents and 22,606 were Republican,
according to the city's Board of Elections and Ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Questions posed by prosecutors and defense lawyers will be
submitted to Sporkin for approval, with a final questionnaire going
to possible jurors when selection begins June 28.
</P>
<P>
   Larger issues still unresolved will be taken up at a June 21
motions hearing where Cisneros' lawyers are expected to fight the
government's efforts to submit taped telephone conversations that
Cisneros' former lover, Linda Jones, had with him as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers argue that Jones' wiretapping was illegal, and
therefore the tapes are inadmissible as evidence. They also plan to
call the government's tape recording expert to testify that the
tapes were altered.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes are considered a crucial part of the government's
case.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI claims Cisneros told investigators that he paid Jones
about $60,000. The indictment charges that Cisneros paid her
$250,000, including $73,000 he paid Jones after he became a member
of Clinton's Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, Cisneros and two aides, John Rosales and Sylvia Arce, are
charged with conspiracy to conceal the financial arrangement from
the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, once considered a rising political star in the
Democratic Party, was HUD secretary from 1993 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a former San Antonio political fund-raiser known by her
married name, Linda Medlar, is currently serving time in a federal
prison for pleading guilty to bank fraud, obstruction of justice
and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were part of a 28-count indictment returned by a
federal grand jury in Texas as part of Barrett's $7 million
investigation into Cisneros' affair with Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros never denied the extramarital affair, which he publicly
disclosed in 1988 while mayor of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation into the payments to Jones began shortly after
he took office as HUD secretary, when an unemployed Jones went on
national television and claimed Cisneros had reneged on a pledge to
provide for her.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' paid television interview included tape-recorded
conversations of her and a man she said was Cisneros scheming to
mislead the FBI about the financial arrangement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
