u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-(2TAKES     06-04 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIES WARY OF EMBOLDENED KOSOVO REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS and IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once Yugoslavia withdraws its forces from Kosovo,
NATO envisions disbanding the Kosovo Liberation Army and
transforming its fighters into civilians, many as police officers.
Western officials are already scouring refugees camps in Albania
and Macedonia in search of recruits.
</P>
<P>
   But emboldened by NATO's wearing down of Yugoslavia's army and
police forces, the rebels may not share NATO's vision of a return
to civilian life. And with their fractious, opaque command
structure, the rebels may complicate NATO's plans for establishing
peace in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here and in Europe said Friday that they expected that
the ethnic Albanian rebels would abide by the broad terms of the
agreement reached with President Slobodan Milosevic. Although many
details of their interaction with NATO's peacekeeping force must
still be worked out, the officials appealed for the rebels'
cooperation and demilitarization.
</P>
<P>
   But in Albania's capital, Tirana, a senior official of the
Kosovo Liberation Army refused Friday to explicitly endorse the
agreement with Milosevic, saying the rebels had strong misgivings
about it, especially the requirement that they lay down their arms
and the extent of the role Russians will play in the peacekeeping
force.
</P>
<P>
   Jakup Krasniqi, one of the rebels' leaders, said he welcomed any
agreement that would call for withdrawal of Serb forces from
Kosovo, clearing the way for the return of hundreds of thousands of
refugees, but he expressed distrust of Milosevic and his
willingness to honor the deal, the details of which were still
being decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will carry on with our resistance because we do not believe
in the maneuvers of Milosevic, who has been massacring civilians
for years,'' Krasniqi said in a news conference at the Hotel
Europapark in Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels' reticence underscored the fact that when it comes to
the mechanics of peace, the Serbs are not the only complicating
factor facing the NATO allies as they move into Kosovo. Having
forced Milosevic to accept a complete withdrawal of Serb forces,
NATO does not now want to see a new armed force taking their place.
</P>
<P>
   But as has been clear from statements by the rebels, who only a
year ago were even a more loosely organized and poorly trained
force, the group's ambitions have grown along with its size. And
their aims in Kosovo _ namely independence _ go beyond well beyond
NATO's.
</P>
<P>
   Krasniqi said that he envisioned the rebels _ also known as the
UCK, its acronym in Albanian _ being transformed into what his
interpreter called an ``army,'' though the word could also mean a
force, more generically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The UCK is the only force that really defended, with all the
means they had for the last year or so, the Albanians living in
Kosovo,'' he said. ``They would like to have their own army, which
would give them security in Kosovo in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, announced on Thursday, calls for the disbanding
of the rebels, but myriad details must still be worked out between
the NATO peacekeepers and the rebels. The Pentagon's spokesman,
Kenneth H. Bacon, said Friday that it was premature to concentrate
on the rebels' future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first task is to get the Serbs out, and that hasn't
happened yet,'' he said. ``After that, we will concentrate on how
to manage the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the air war, NATO dealt warily with the Kosovo
Liberation Army, the only fighters on the ground attacking
Yugoslavia's Army and police units. Militarily, officials insisted
they did not coordinate strikes with the rebels, though one senior
officer described ``a flow of information'' from the rebels that
NATO warplanes used, and diplomats from the State Department kept
in regular contact with the rebels' leaders.
</P>
<P>
   With a settlement apparently at hand, allied officials are even
more wary of the emboldened rebels, who now see themselves as the
emerging political and military power in a liberated Kosovo. Within
the Pentagon, especially, the rebels and their intentions remain a
deep concern and, with the group's uncertain commitment to
democracy and unsavory ties to drug dealers and arms merchants, a
potential threat to the peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Only a year ago, the rebels numbered no more than 2,000, but
they are now estimated to have as many as 17,000 fighters, many of
them revenge-minded young men recruited from the hordes of refugees
driven from Kosovo by Serb forces after NATO's bombing began on
March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks ago, Milosevic declared he had eradicated the
U.C.K.,'' a senior defense official said. ``That was like us with
the Vietcong in Vietnam. They're still there in strong numbers.
They're still capable of creating a lot of headaches and trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The agreement negotiated at Rambouillet, France, earlier this
year, which representatives of the rebels signed but the Serbs did
not, laid out in detail the ``demilitarization'' of their army.
They would have been required to give up most of their weapons, but
not hunting rifles and other smaller arms. Within a month, they
would have had to stop wearing uniforms and military insignia; by
four months, there would be no force at all.
</P>
<P>
   The Rambouillet agreement also envisioned giving the insurgents
new roles as police officers _ as individuals, though, not
collectively. The senior defense official said that the allies had
been aggressively recruiting the rebels in the hopes of using them
in the political and civil administration that emerges in the
province.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working very hard to try to co-opt them into legitimate
institutions, like the police,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO's spokesman, Jamie P. Shea, said that the
allies still hoped that the rebels would disband along the
timetables laid out in the Rambouillet talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as were concerned that aspect of the Rambouillet
agreement is valid and were hoping the U.C.K. sees it the same
way,'' he said. He added that the NATO forces takes away ``the
rationale for that kind of armed struggle which, in the eyes of
U.C.K. leaders, may have had its meaning when they were being
repressed by Yugoslav forces but which will not have its raison
d'etre once the international security presence is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, however, rebel leaders said that events inside
Kosovo had clearly overtaken the agreement at Rambouillet. They
have also made it clear they have not yet accepted the latest
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In Albania, which the ethnic Albanian rebels have used as a base
of operations, Krasniqi refused even to describe the agreement to
end the conflict as an agreement, calling it only a ``document.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to President Clinton's remarks on the agreement on
Thursday, he added, ``He never mentioned they were going to make us
accept this agreement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
