<HEADER>
A3653 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-EMERGE-MARKETS     06-04 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EMERGE-MARKETS-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CASE FOR A RATE INCREASE IS STILL STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of the yield on the federal funds futures
contract for August is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
(af) 
By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors, it seemed, were ready to concede that the Federal
Reserve would have to raise interest rates to slow growth and curb
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But when the May employment report was released on Friday
morning, there was a surprise. Job growth was unexpectedly weak.
Instead of an increase approaching 220,000 new nonfarm jobs, as
Wall Street had forecast, there were only 11,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't give you closure,'' lamented Robert J. Barbera,
chief economist at Hoenig &AMP; Co. ``We can't say we're done.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet this surprising report should not change the outlook for the
economy. (It is still strong.) Or interest rates. (They should move
higher.) Or the intent of the Fed. (It should raise rates soon.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one could conclude otherwise by focusing on the
nonfarm jobs data, which were weak in May and have not been
disturbingly strong for the year, increasing at a monthly average
of 197,800. But that focus would be deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the rest of the economic data released last week,
although with much less fanfare than the jobs report.
</P>
<P>
   _ The factory index of the National Association of Purchasing
Management jumped to 55.2 in May, its highest level since October
1997. Prices paid to producers also rose.
</P>
<P>
   _ Car and truck sales are soaring, with the annual rate in May
hitting 17.1 million, a May record and the fifth highest ever.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sales of new homes in April jumped 9.2 percent, to an annual
rate of 978,000, the second-strongest month on record.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sales in stores open at least a year rose 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All this indicates that consumers are still spending while the
nation's weakest sector, manufacturing, appears to be rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   On top of this, the underlying data in the May jobs report were
stronger than indicated by the meager nonfarm jobs increase.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for that surprisingly small overall gain was a
decline of 40,000 in construction jobs and a plunge of 45,000 in
manufacturing. In addition, the service sector created just 71,000
jobs, well below its average of 125,000 over the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Construction jobs have been rising and falling with the weather,
jumping 44,000 in April before last month's decline, on a
seasonally adjusted basis. Since March of last year, 453,000
manufacturing jobs have been lost as recessions in Asia and Latin
America slashed demand for American goods.
</P>
<P>
   But while jobs have been declining, the growth rate of average
hourly earnings in manufacturing is rising again. For all of last
year, average hourly earnings for manufacturing were up just 1.6
percent. So far this year, they are up 4.3 percent at an annual
rate.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown of wage increases in manufacturing had helped
restrain overall wage increases, allowing the growth rate to
decline while the economy was booming. That mitigating factor now
appears to be gone.
</P>
<P>
   The closure sought by Barbera must wait for the release of other
key data ahead of the Fed's policy-making meeting on June 29 and
30. Those include the government's formal tabulation of retail
sales for May, to be released on Friday, and the Labor Department's
measure of consumer prices for last month, due on June 16.
</P>
<P>
   If they are strong, retail sales will serve to prove that the
consumer has bounced back after a weak March and April. The
Consumer Price Index for May will show whether the April gain of
0.7 percent, the largest monthly jump in eight and a half years,
was a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   And if it is possible to scrutinize Alan Greenspan, the chairman
of the Federal Reserve, any more closely, investors will do so on
June 17, when he is scheduled to testify before Congress's Joint
Economic Committee on monetary and economic policy. Many expect him
to use the occasion to signal that a rate increase is coming.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the data, there is another reason the Fed should move
rates higher. Based on the movement of the many market barometers
of investor sentiment, a quarter-percentage-point increase in the
Fed's short-term interest rate target, to 5 percent, is already
expected.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Fed could raise the rate on overnight loans
between banks _ the Federal Funds rate _ without too much
disruption, argued Robert V. DiClemente, chief United States
economist at Salomon Smith Barney. In fact, he added, ``the Fed
might cause more questions if they do not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
