<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL TOTALS IN SOUTH AFRICA ELECTION STILL IN DOUBT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRETORIA, South Africa _ Votes came on to the huge digital board
here, and then they came off. One million of them, at one point.
</P>
<P>
   The final outcome of this week's election was still in limbo
late Friday evening as the ballot-counting continued slowly, with
about half the votes either unverified or plagued with errors.
</P>
<P>
   Though figures bounced up and down, the African National
Congress clearly beat the opposition. But its chances of winning
the two-thirds majority it hoped for looked less certain than on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The million-vote mistake _ a typing error from one district _
pushed the ANC's national vote tally above the two-thirds mark, but
when the number was corrected, the party fell back below it.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the Zulu-nationalist Inkatha Freedom Party also
surged ahead, to be the leading opposition party. But that lead
also turned out to be a mistake, and by 8 p.m. it had fallen back
to third place behind the liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, the seven leading opposition parties
banded together to challenge the way in which the votes were being
verified. The parties requested copies of the result sheets filed
from all 14,650 polling stations in order to have the count
independently checked.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Independent Electoral Commission, the seven
parties said that some results sheets were hard to read and that
some stations reported more votes than the number of eligible
voters on their rolls. ``Our beautiful ideal of a free and fair
election may be harmed by unnecessary suspicion and uncertainty
about the correctness of the results,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the system developed by the Independent Electoral
Commission, votes counts are to be checked in several ways. The
commission had to receive the vote in two different ways, like
telephone and fax, and the tallies had to match. In addition, the
vote counts had to be in line with the number of ballots issued to
the polling station.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the votes are coming in far slower than expected, in
part because some stations stayed open for 24 hours to accommodate
long lines of voters, and presiding officers were too exhausted to
count immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's director of operations, Norman du Plessis,
dismissed mounting concerns over the fluctuating numbers, saying
they in fact proved the commission was doing its job.
</P>
<P>
   Final official results are not expected until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of South Africa's newspapers have assumed that the ANC will
get a two-thirds majority and editorials Friday, including those in
the influential daily The Sowetan, urged the party not take
advantage of such power. Such a majority would give the party the
votes to change some aspects of the constitution, like curtailing
the powers of watchdog agencies.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The country's next president, Thabo Mbeki, has said that he had
no intention of making such changes.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
