A3657 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX-(2TA     06-04 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL DEBATE RAGES ON AS END OF WAR IN KOSOVO APPEARS
IMMINENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton declared Friday that he was
``anxious to end the bombing'' in Yugoslavia, and the Pentagon said
the 10-week-old air war could end as early as Sunday if Serbia
begins a troop withdrawal from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As Washington became more optimistic that peace in the Balkans
was in fact at hand, Clinton also sought to assure the American
public that the nation had pursued a ``goal that has been worth
fighting for'' _ stability in Europe and the return of more than
800,000 ethnic Albanians to their homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an enormous opportunity to be seized here,'' the
president said in the ornate East Room of the White House, ``a
chance to shift our focus from defeating something evil to building
something good, a chance to work with our allies to bring a stable
and prosperous and democratic southeastern Europe in which people
are never again singled out for destruction simply because of their
religious faith or their ethnic origin.''
</P>
<P>
   Though a NATO commander is to meet his counterparts from
Yugoslavia and Russia on Saturday to establish a timetable for
withdrawal and verification procedures, NATO kept up its bombing
campaign for a 73rd day _ hitting 51 targets in 24 hours, according
to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes avoided Belgrade, hitting ammunition depots in Novi
Pazar, Boljevac and Kursumlija and oil or gas installations in
Sombor and Leskovac.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials emphasized that most of the latest bombing was
focused on forces in the field in Kosovo, and they said they had
yet to see any evidence of Serbian withdrawals. Serbian army units
clashed Friday with rebels trying to hold a strategic mountain
called Pastrik. The Pentagon reported Serbian counterinsurgency
operations against Kosovo separatist guerrillas but said the
fighting seemed to have eased. But there were also reports that the
Serbs were still forcing people from villages, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important that we continue the military action
against the military targets until we have some evidence that there
are more than words here,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But there were clear signs that NATO was wrapping up its war
effort and preparing to send a peacekeeping force into Kosovo. For
instance, the Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth H. Bacon, said Friday
that the United States had suspended the deployment of 36 F-15
fighters to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   If the end of the air war looked imminent, the political debate
raged on over just what NATO and Clinton had accomplished with a
military campaign that was limited to an air war that would carry
little risk of allied casualties. More than 800,000 ethnic
Albanians were expelled from Kosovo by Serbian forces and now need
to be returned to a devastated land requiring a vast reconstruction
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said this week's diplomatic breakthrough was a
vindication of the president's policy and persistence with the air
strikes. ``It's clear the air campaign has been effective,'' said
Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the minority leader. ``It has
forced Milosevic to acknowledge that his options are running out.''
</P>
<P>
   One beneficiary of the accord was Vice President Al Gore. If all
goes as planned, he will be able to seek the Democratic
presidential nomination free of the shadow of the air war, or of
the possibility that American ground forces would invade Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, were critical of the accord, emphasizing
that President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, indicted on
charges of war crimes, had not been toppled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is right and proper that all parties work to find
peace and justice in the troubled Kosovo region,'' said the Speaker
of the House, J. Dennis Hastert. ``However, we should not let
exuberance get in the way of the hard reality that Slobodan
Milosevic is still in control of Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, a Republican presidential
contender, pointed to President Saddam Hussein of Iraq as the model
for the problems caused by leaving a dictator in power after a war.
``The fact that it was an air campaign virtually guaranteed that he
would remain in power,'' he said of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Senator Mitch McConnell, a Kentucky Republican, said:
``It seems to me that the practical effect of this being a U.N.
mission is that it would seem to guarantee Milosevic's continuation
in power. Is that a good outcome, given the fact that we have
labeled him a modern day Hitler and he has been indicted in The
Hague?''
</P>
<P>
   The Belgrade agreement says an international force in Kosovo
would have ``fundamental'' NATO participation but be authorized by
the United Nations. Senator McConnell and Senator Chuck Hagel, a
Nebraska Republican, both warned that could mean that Russia and
China could have too much control over the force.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials insisted that the force would have NATO
troops at its core, with a NATO general in charge and a unified
command structure.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, Republican of North Carolina and the chairman
of the Foreign Relations Committee, demanded that the president
seek formal approval from Congress before sending any troops into
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He also served notice that he would use confirmation hearings,
now planned for this month, on the nomination of Richard C.
Holbrooke as chief American diplomat at the United Nations to
scrutinize American policy in the Balkans. He said the committee
would explore Holbrooke's ``role and responsibility for this
administration's misguided policy of appeasing Slobodan
Milosevic.'' Holbrooke negotiated the Dayton peace accord that
halted the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said Clinton did not need
Congressional approval for troops and estimated that the Kosovo
force could be deployed in a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department the spokesman, Jamie P. Rubin, argued
that the 10 weeks of NATO air strikes had dealt a great deal of
damage to Milosevic. ``Clearly he is weaker,'' he said. ``He is
indicted. His country has been set back decades economically. His
military has been largely broken through the air campaign. The
reputation of Serbia has suffered mightily around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said there would be no Western
assistance to rebuild Serbia until it became more democratic, and
strongly suggested that Milosevic would have to be turned over in
The Hague for prosecution before Serbia would be allowed access to
international financial institutions like the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say we cannot imagine a situation in which
President Milosevic remains in Serbia and all of the different
pieces of the puzzle get put together,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said the vanguard of American troops for the Kosovo
operation was aboard a three-ship Marine amphibious group en route
to Salonika, Greece. About 2,000 marines would be the first
American troops to move into Kosovo, as part of an international
force that is to grow to 50,000. The United States has pledged to
send a total of 7,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   Once they reach Greece, the marines will travel by road to
Skopje, Macedonia, and wait for NATO to order them into Kosovo
after the alliance can verify that a significant Serbian withdrawal
is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said Serbian forces would pull out of Kosovo from west to
east. A 15-mile buffer zone will separate Kosovo from the rest of
Serbia, and will help insure that remnants of the Serbian forces
cannot re-enter Kosovo or fire at NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said the marines would patrol a section of eastern
Kosovo assigned to the United States. They would then yield to Army
troops and heavy armor from bases in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Russia was instrumental in brokering the peace deal, but
American officials are still uncertain what role Russia will play
in the international force. Joe Lockhart, the White House press
secretary, said Russia's role remained an ``open question.'' But he
said, ``We are confident that we can work with them constructively
and they can participate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
