<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3659 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-04 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO, YUGOSLAV OFFICERS PLAN TALKS ON KOSOVO WITHDRAWAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ The commander of NATO forces in Macedonia is expected
to meet Saturday with Yugoslav Army officers to arrange for the
withdrawal of some 40,000 Serb troops from Kosovo, a move that
would end NATO airstrikes and begin the war-torn Serbian province's
status as an international protectorate.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. General Mike Jackson, a British officer, was to lead the
NATO delegation that will meet his Serb counterparts near the
border checkpoint where more than a quarter of the 800,000 ethnic
Albanians who have been forced out of Kosovo have crossed into
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   They will map out agreed timetables and routes so that the Serb
forces will not be bombed as they withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting comes as NATO scaled back its bombing of Yugoslavia
in response to the Yugoslav government's acceptance of an
international peace plan aimed at ending hostilities over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive day, there were no bombing raids here
in the Yugoslav capital, and French President Jacques Chirac
confirmed Friday that NATO had decided to confine its bombing to
``strictly military objectives.'' That means so-called ``dual use''
targets that are used both by the military and civilians, such as
power plants and bridges, would not be hit.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officers and their Yugoslav counterparts have been in
telephone contact since Thursday afternoon, when Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and the Serbian parliament accepted the terms of
a cease-fire devised by the so-called Group of Eight industrialized
nations and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday's meeting on the Serbia-Macedonia border would mark
the first face-to-face meeting of the opposing military camps since
NATO began bombing Yugoslavia March 24. Russian military officials
and an aide to Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, who with the
Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin persuaded Milosevic to take the
deal, were also expected to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Russia, who together will make up the bulk of the
50,000 peacekeeping troops expected to replace Serb forces in
Kosovo, have still not agreed on the breakdown of personnel, where
they will be stationed, and under whose command they will be
placed. After meeting in Helsinki Friday with Ahtisaari, US Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott said he believed those
differences could be worked out soon.
</P>
<P>
   NATO insists it must see evidence of a Serb withdrawal before it
calls a suspension and eventual halt to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not there yet,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said in
Brussels. ``The promise of peace is not yet the reality of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   But in recognition of the Yugoslav gesture, NATO appeared to be
confining its raids to Kosovo. Shea said that in the 24-hour period
that had passed since Yugoslav officials said they accepted the
peace plan, NATO pilots had struck 21 artillery pieces, 30 mortar
positions, four tanks, 10 armored personnel carriers and eight
anti-aircraft pieces, all in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said NATO intended to monitor the Serb withdrawal closely
to guard against atrocities by the retreating forces. But he said
NATO would not escort the Serbs out, saying, ``They know the way
home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is not to have any clashes of forces,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has still not made a public comment or gone on state
television to explain why he sued for peace, accepting virtually
the same terms that were on offer before his country was bombed for
72 days.
</P>
<P>
   In several areas, the plan Milosevic accepted is worse than what
he could have had without his country's infrastructure being laid
to waste. Under the Rambouillet agreement which he rejected because
it called for the presence in Kosovo of foreign troops that he now
accepts, Yugoslav soldiers had 180 days and Serb police up to a
year before pulling out of Kosovo. Some 2,500 border guards would
have been allowed to stay to police the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   But now the army and police have only seven days to pull out
before they are replaced by the same foreign troops that Milosevic
was willing to go to war over. In addition, the peace plan allows
for only a token presence of ``hundreds, not thousands'' of Serb
forces to clear mines, man border checkpoints and guard Serb
monasteries and heritage sites in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Official statements from the Yugoslav government have sought to
portray the deal as a victory for the country because the post-war
administration of Kosovo will be overseen by the United Nations,
not NATO. But the end result _ Serb forces out, international
forces in, and autonomy for the ethnic Albanians who make up 90
percent of population _ is the same.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, meanwhile, declared there
was no way Milosevic's acceptance of the peace plan would deter his
indictment by the war crimes tribunal in The Hague. Cook said there
would be no immunity or amnesty for Milosevic, who was charged with
war crimes for orchestrating the forced expulsion of some 800,000
refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 16,000 NATO troops already in Macedonia, and the
government there Friday said it has authorized NATO to deploy
another 14,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   At a summit of European Union leaders in Cologne, Germany,
British Prime Minister Tony Blair stressed that the western allies
would not help rebuild Serbia unless Milosevic was removed from
power.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac echoed that sentiment, saying that while the western
allies should refrain from humiliating Serbia, reconstruction help
from the west would be authorized only when the country was ruled
by ``a regime which respects democracy and human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Yugoslav pledges to end the fighting, Hashim Thaci, the
political leader of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army, said that
Serb forces had launched a new offensive against the separatist
group. The peace plan calls for the disarming of the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   It was the attempts by Serb forces to crush the rebel group that
led to the conflict with NATO. After the KLA attacked Serb police
in Kosovo, the Serbs launched a scorched earth policy, shelling and
torching villages where the KLA drew support, killing scores of
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The US and European Union demanded that Milosevic end his
offensive, and threatened to bomb when he didn't. Attempts to hash
out a compromise in France ended in March when Milosevic refused to
allow foreign troops in as peacekeepers. NATO began bombing, and
Serb forces drove hundreds of thousands of refugees out of Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
