<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3661 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GUN-CONTROL-N     06-04 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUN-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRKED CLINTON DEFENDS EFFORT ON GUN BILLS DURING TELEVISION
INTERVIEW
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With his commitment to gun control challenged
Friday on national television, President Clinton delivered a
stinging lecture on achieving the politically possible in a
Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The president erupted after Charles Gibson of ABC's ``Good
Morning America'' suggested in an interview broadcast live from the
White House that Clinton ``had a chance to roar'' on gun control in
the aftermath of the shootings in Littleton, Colo., but instead
``meowed'' by gaining Senate passage of a modest set of gun-control
measures.
</P>
<P>
   In a monologue of 2 1/2 minutes, Clinton turned aside repeated
efforts by Gibson to get a word in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, let's join the real world here,'' Clinton said, stabbing
the air with an index finger. ``You want to have an honest
conversation? Let's have an honest conversation. I am the first
president who ever took on the NRA, he said referring to the
national Rifle Association. ``I got my party in Congress to stand
with me on the Brady Bill, which has made a difference, on the
assault weapons ban.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, used the program
to highlight their campaign against youth violence, and were joined
in the Roosevelt Room of the White House by a group of teen-agers
who asked them questions about restrictions on gun ownership.
</P>
<P>
   But the segment was dominated by the heated exchange between the
president and Gibson, who quoted someone he described as ``a
friend'' of Clinton's as saying the President had missed an
opportunity to be tough with the gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   In a sharp rejoinder, Clinton spoke of the political price the
Democrats had paid in his first term for passing gun-control
measures, including a ban on some assault weapons and the so-called
Brady law, which included a mandatory waiting period for handgun
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1994, we lost between 12 and 20 members of the House of
Representatives because they were targeted by the NRA for standing
up for the lives of children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the shootings that left 15 people dead at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Clinton did propose a package of far-reaching
gun-control measures, including raising the minimum age for all
handgun purchases to 21 from 18 and limiting gun buyers to the
purchase of one a month.
</P>
<P>
   But to gain Senate passage of the bill, the White House agreed
to drop such contentious items and pressed for the enactment of
more modest changes, like requiring background checks of
individuals who buy firearms at gun shows and including child
safety devices with new guns.
</P>
<P>
   Even with those scaled-back goals, the White House needed the
vote of Vice President Al Gore to break a deadlock on the measure _
a fact that the president obviously believed Gibson failed to
appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now wait a minute,'' a visibly angry Clinton said at one point
when Gibson sought to interject. ``You talk about roaring and
meowing _ then I came forward with this legislation. Did it roar
through the Senate? No. We passed a bill closing the gun show
loophole by 51-50 because of the vice president of the United
States. Did the House of Representatives make a priority out of
what was passed in the Senate and pass it right through? No. They
went home before taking action. Why? To give the NRA time to lobby
them to water down what was passed.''
</P>
<P>
   The testy back-and-forth pleased the producers of ``Good Morning
America,'' if not Clinton. They saw it as great television, full of
passion and fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie Gibson is a phenomenal interviewer,'' said Shelley
Ross, the program's executive producer. ``He didn't want to go over
the same old gun-control debate. The intention was to be
provocative, insightful and in-depth. He opened things up and we
could see how deeply the president feels on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But at times, Clinton appeared to be treating the interviewer as
naive about the hardball world of Washington politics. He declared
that it would be ``wrong'' for the White House to pass up the
opportunity to achieve some success on gun control to press for
measures that stood little chance of enactment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say there are stronger measures that could be taken,''
Clinton said. ``You are absolutely right. You have no evidence that
they could pass the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson retorted that polls indicated the American public would
accept registration of firearms. Yet, Gibson said, ``we don't do
that, and we're not fighting about the regulation of guns.''
</P>
<P>
   This served only to prompt another lecture from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason is, this Congress came to power after the 1994
elections because in critical races the people who voted for more
modest things, like the Brady Bill, which the polls showed the
voters support, got beat. They got beat, Charlie.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
