<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNIV-OF-CHICAGO-PRESI     06-04 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIV-OF-CHICAGO-PRESIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF CHICAGO'S CONTROVERSIAL PRESIDENT WILL STEP DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   University of Chicago president Hugo Sonnenschein, whose moves
to expand and modernize one of the nation's most revered
universities became controversial, announced Friday that he would
step down next year and return to teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Sonnenschein, a 58-year-old economist, came to Chicago in 1993
from Princeton University, where he had been provost. He soon began
updating the University of Chicago, which has long nurtured a
reputation for intellectual rigor.
</P>
<P>
   He won acclaim for improving finances and modernizing the campus
and the university's management, but some of his efforts to
increase the size of the student body, trim the core curriculum and
make the institution's image less severe met with the indignation
of some students, professors and alumni.
</P>
<P>
   The plans even led to the formation of an ad hoc group of
nationally known conservative intellectuals called Scholars for the
University of Chicago that sought to block the changes. Among those
involved were author Saul Bellow, sociologist David Riesman and
educator Mortimer Adler.
</P>
<P>
   Sonnenschein's opponents expressed satisfaction Friday and said
the board of trustees had urged him to step down because it had
grown weary of the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   But board chairman Howard Krane praised Sonnenschein and said it
was going ahead with his plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board was fully informed about all of the issues involved
in these initiatives, and our goal in approving them was to
preserve and enhance our university well into the future,'' Krane
said in a statement that was also signed by his designated
successor as chairman, Edgar Jannotta. ``Our resolve remains
unchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonnenschein issued a separate statement saying he had
accomplished what he had set out to do, and adding, ``I have come
to feel that it is time for another president, one who is less a
symbol of change and who has less reason to initiate change, to
carry the momentum forward.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Sonnenschein acknowledged the
existence of what he called ``noisy minorities,'' but he said they
had nothing to do with his decision to step down as president in
June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have begun a collection of initiatives that couldn't be
going better,'' he said. ``The selectivity of the college is up, we
have strong building programs and in 13 months I'll be nearing my
60th birthday and will go back to the best economics department in
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Aleem Hossain, 21, of Bolton, Conn., who is finishing his third
year at the university and has helped lead a student movement
opposed to the changes, said he found it hard to believe that
Sonnenschein's decision to leave had nothing to do with the
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see his stepping down as a concession that our points were
serious,'' he said. ``I think that the expansion he started will go
ahead but more slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   The university said the trustees would establish a search
committee to find a new president.
</P>
<P>
   Since early winter, when Sonnenschein's plans gained attention,
small groups of students and faculty members have agitated against
the changes.
</P>
<P>
   On April 20, Hossain and others organized a day of protest,
called a ``fun-in'' to satirize the administration's emphasis on
lightening the college's image. It drew 1,700 people. The
university has 10,000 undergraduate and graduate students.
</P>
<P>
   Undergraduates at Chicago take what is one of the most demanding
core curriculums in the United States. Some say that is what drew
them to the university, so that the plan to reduce the number of
courses, even by a small margin, was unwelcome.
</P>
<P>
   The courses are taught by professors in a small seminar style,
and Sonnenschein's plan to increase the number of undergraduate
students from 3,500 to 4,500 over 10 years without clear plans to
increase the size of the faculty caused some to worry that in
future such courses would be in danger of growing unwieldy.
</P>
<P>
   But Sonnenschein's administration said the increase was
manageable and necessary to insure the long-term economic health of
the university. While the university's faculty is regarded as being
among the nation's best, Chicago's endowment and applicant pool are
much lower than those of the top Ivy League institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Sonnenschein also believed that the university needed to attract
a broader range of applicants, and thus had to make clear to high
school students that life at Chicago was neither dreary nor a
grind. To that end, colorful marketing brochures were drawn up;
applications rose 25 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, many faculty members said, Sonnenschein did much
that was good but had failed to maintain their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had been tremendous attacks on Hugo from faculty and
students,'' said Bertram Cohler, a professor of psychology and
education. ``He just didn't have the confidence of the faculty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
