<HEADER>
A3664 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-OPPOSITION-BOS &LR;      06-04 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-OPPOSITION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV OPPOSITION PARTIES SEE CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ With Slobodan Milosevic all but admitting defeat at
the hands of NATO, the opposition parties here see the vast damage
inflicted on Serbia as an opportunity to get rid of the Yugoslav
president once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   But even as opposition leaders have been handed a strong case to
argue for the Serb leader's ouster, there is growing concern that
the propensity of pro-democracy forces here to engage in petty
squabbling could squander what may be the best opportunity yet to
end Milosevic's malevolent use of power in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Huge chunks of Yugoslavia's infrastructure _ roads, bridges, oil
refineries, and factories _ have been destroyed by NATO bombs. And
while the Western allies have said they will rebuild Yugoslavia,
they say they will do so only if Milosevic, who has been indicted
on war crimes charges, is removed from power and Yugoslavia becomes
a Western-style democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders say they will try to convince most Serbs that
Milosevic foolishly provoked a war with NATO and needlessly wrecked
the country by subjecting it to more than 70 days of bombing before
accepting a deal he could have got without going to war. More than
just blame Milosevic for provoking a fight he could not win, the
opposition says it will stress that the country will remain an
international pariah, and an economic wasteland, unless and until
Milosevic goes.
</P>
<P>
   Dragan Veselinov, a member of the Serbian Parliament who voted
for the peace plan approved Thursday, accused Milosevic of making
``the entire nation paupers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't get a cent of international aid as long as this
government keeps running the country, because it would be nothing
short of madness to invest a single dollar in this country with the
present government in charge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zoran Zivkovic, vice president of the Democratic Party, one of
the main opposition groups, predicted elections within a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who have destroyed the country for the last 10 years
must leave office. The democratization of Serbia is impossible with
this regime,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the opposition has its best opportunity in years to
oust Milosevic, there is already a growing rift within Serbia's
notoriously fractured opposition. Opposition leaders and dissidents
who left the country during the bombing are being dismissed as
cowards by those who stayed.
</P>
<P>
   There are two competing schools of thought. One holds that it is
imperative to stay in Serbia while NATO bombs, so that when the
bombing stops the opposition will be insulated from criticism that
it ``ran away.'' The other holds that, given the extent of
censorship here, and the personal risks faced by anyone considered
a dissident, riding out the war in exile gives the opposition a
platform it would never have in Serbia and offers protection from
harassment, arrest, or worse.
</P>
<P>
   When Sonja Biserko, president of the Belgrade chapter of the
Helsinki Committee for Human Rights, left Serbia and began issuing
statements from Budapest, some of the most bitter attacks on her
came not from the government but from her colleagues in the
pro-democracy movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonja accused those of us who stayed here of being
collaborators,'' said Vojin Dimitrijevic, director of the Belgrade
Center for Human Rights. ``It did not go over very well here.''
</P>
<P>
   Such animosity is more than just a falling out between friends
and like-minded dissidents. Milosevic has remained in power, in
large part, due to a fractured opposition. The infighting over
where dissidents should ride out the war does not augur well,
according to Western diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the Democratic Party, and as mayor of Belgrade,
Zoran Djindjic was well positioned to lead the campaign to
challenge Milosevic when the war ended. And though conventional
wisdom here was that it would be political suicide to attack
Milosevic while NATO was bombing, especially from outside Serbia,
that is just what Djindjic did after fleeing to Montenegro last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Djindjic ran away, he does not matter anymore,'' said Vuk
Draskovic, who was fired as a deputy prime minister in April after
suggesting that Milosevic cut a deal with NATO. He is now
considered a serious rival to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than rejoice at their leader's high international
profile, which was guaranteed by his pointed criticism of
Milosevic, Djindjic's colleagues worry that his decision to go into
exile obscured their message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand why he left for personal reasons, for his family,
but politically it is a disaster,'' said one high-ranking
Democratic Party member. ``People aren't thinking about politics
now. They don't think about Milosevic. They think about their kids,
electricity, bread, money, water. They think about surviving this
war. We need an end to the war first, then we go after Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanimir Miljkovic, 26, one of the leaders of the student
movement that staged massive street demonstrations against the
Milosevic regime two years ago, said those who want a new
government have to be pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the war stops, it will be easier. Right now, you can
dismiss the opposition as traitors, and most people will listen to
that because NATO is bombing and killing our people,'' he said.
``It is a mistake to leave the country. I'm not judging people
individually, but anyone who leaves is politically dead.
Politically, I think Djindjic is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   But the idea that the country will be rebuilt only if Milosevic
quits, or is voted out, is not dead. Even if most Serbs blame NATO,
not Milosevic, for wrecking their country, they also know that it
is the United States and the European Union, not Milosevic's
cronies and their impoverished allies in Moscow, who have the money
needed for reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Zarko Korac, leader of the small opposition Social Democratic
Union, said Milosevic will survive only if the state-controlled
media are able to persuade most Serbs ``that they won'' by standing
up to the world's most powerful military alliance for more than 70
days of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic's propaganda machine has a tough job, convincing
Serbs that they have won a great victory. That will be hard to do
when the Americans come in,'' said Korac.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
