<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-LYNCH-BIAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH MOVES TO SETTLE SOME GENDER BIAS SUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ind.)   (bl)  
 By ANN WOZENCRAFT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. said Friday that it would begin
settlement discussions or seek additional information on about
one-third of the 904 sexual discrimination claims filed against it
by current or former employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some instances, where it is clear that co-workers or
managers did not treat women properly, Merrill Lynch will take
appropriate actions against those responsible,'' said John
Steffens, vice chairman of Merrill and head of its retail brokerage
division, in a memo to the firm's 14,800 retail brokers, about 16
percent of whom are women.
</P>
<P>
   About 31 percent of the 2,900 women eligible to file claims did
so by March 2, the deadline set by a federal judge in Chicago when
he gave final approval to the settlement on Sept. 2, 1998. The
class-action suit was filed in February 1997 by one current and
seven former Merrill brokers who accused the firm, the nation's
largest retail brokerage house, of discriminating against women in
wages, promotions, account distributions, maternity leaves and
other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill made its announcement after delivering letters to the
plaintiffs' lawyers, Stowell &AMP; Friedman, in Chicago. All eight
women who originally filed claims are included in the 300 claims
being discussed. Merrill did not identify the others and did not
say how many of the 300 would receive a settlement offer.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Friedman, a partner with Stowell &AMP; Friedman, said: ``When
300 women in offices all over the country complain of sexual
discrimination, these are clearly not isolated instances. It's a
pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   Steffens contended that information available in the remaining
600 cases ``does not support the allegations made in the claims.''
But he said those cases would be reviewed ``if new information is
provided.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' lawyers said they planned to seek mediation of
all claims for which settlements are not offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cautiously positive that we're moving forward,'' said
Linda Conti, one of the original plaintiffs and a former broker in
Merrill's Indianapolis office.
</P>
<P>
   Marybeth Cremin, who first sued Merrill in June 1996 before
joining the class-action suit the following year, said, ``They're
the biggest firm on the street, so anything they can do to effect
change will have big impact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
