</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-CATHAY-PHILIPPINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 ASIAN AIRLINES SEE SOME IMPROVEMENT IN LABOR AND FINANCIAL
PROBLEMS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ The skies may soon become smoother for two Asian
airlines buffeted by labor disputes and financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine Airlines said Friday that it had raised $200 million
in fresh capital to resuscitate its debt-ridden operations. Cathay
Pacific Airways is preparing for talks with its pilots to resolve a
dispute that has grounded between a third and half of its daily
flights since May 28.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, analysts cautioned that the good news should be
tempered by caution.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cathay Pacific made a significant concession when it
agreed on Thursday to reopen negotiations with its pilots, it is
not clear that more talking can close the wide gap between the
carrier and its pilots over salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Cathay's senior pilots called in sick in record numbers Friday
to protest a deadline that the airline had given them to accept a
new pay package. That forced the carrier, which is based in Hong
Kong, to cancel 59 of its 117 scheduled flights. Cathay made up
some of the flights with 26 chartered planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very positive step that they're talking,'' said Peter
Negline, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in Hong Kong. ``But
both parties have gone over this ground at length. I don't have
reason to believe that either side has moved its stance enough to
reach an immediate resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathay has threatened that if the senior pilots do not accept
its salary offer by June 11, it will lay them off. The airline had
earlier said that it would not reopen talks unless the pilots made
concessions, but now it has agreed to meet with their union, the
Hong Kong Aircrew Officers Association, here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Philippine Airlines, the carrier met a Friday
deadline to raise $200 million or face liquidation. The trouble is,
most of the money is being contributed by the company's largest
shareholder, Lucio C. Tan, and investors close to him. Tan himself
has put up $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear that the creditors of Philippine Airlines, who
have been increasingly hostile toward Tan, will support his bid to
stay in control of the carrier. Tan, a big player in tobacco and
beer, is one of the richest men in the Philippines. He has relied
on his close ties to President Joseph P. Estrada of the Philippines
to keep the airline operating, despite its $2.2 billion in debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tan clearly has an understanding with Estrada,'' said Jim
Eckes, a consultant at Indoswiss Aviation Ltd. in Hong Kong. ``But
does he have an understanding with the creditors? I don't see the
creditors, who haven't been paid for a year, being in a position to
accept him in top management.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the largest creditors of Philippine Airlines is the
Export-Import Bank of the United States, which announced plans in
May to seize four planes. The bank had earlier endorsed a plan to
rehabilitate the airline _ after Tan ceded day-to-day management to
a team of executives from Cathay Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   But Tan took back the chief executive title in late April,
consigning the team from Cathay to a marginal role.
</P>
<P>
   Cathay Pacific and Philippine Airlines have more differences
than similarities. Cathay's investors include Swire Pacific, a
leading Hong Kong business empire, as well as the China
International Trust and Investment Corp., China's big state-run
investment banking concern, and is regarded as one of Asia's
best-run airlines. Philippine Airlines, which was once owned by the
Philippine government, is a virtual catalog of airline maladies _
with unprofitable routes, a costly and oversized fleet and a
bloated work force.
</P>
<P>
   Yet both carriers have suffered during the Asian crisis, which
has sapped tourism and business travel throughout the region.
Cathay recorded its first loss in 35 years in 1998, $542 million
(Hong Kong), or $69.9 million (United States). Philippine Airlines
has lost more than $330 million the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   Negline estimated that Cathay could lose $38 million because of
the canceled flights. But given its underlying strengths, he and
other analysts are sanguine about its prospects. Salaries of
Cathay's top pilots are among the highest in the industry. Hong
Kong's laws favor employers over employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cathay will start firing people at some point,'' Eckes said.
``I just don't think the pilots can afford to go on strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Hong Kong are praying for a quick end to the
dispute. The territory's tourism industry was just starting to perk
up after a long drought. By disrupting the travel plans of 40,000
passengers and counting, Cathay's dispute could hampering Hong
Kong's recovery from the recession.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
