<HEADER>
A3670 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-US-BOS &LR;      06-04 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SAY IT'S TOO EARLY FOR CLINTON CELEBRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They said it wouldn't work.
</P>
<P>
   NATO was too diverse. President Clinton was too poll-driven. And
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright had no foreign policy
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it would seem, those critics of the NATO bombing of
Yugoslavia could be eating their words _ just as Clinton
administration officials are beginning to quietly celebrate their
vindication. And yet among many policy analysts as well as many
officials on Capitol Hill, including some Democrats, there are
still questions about whether the end of the war would really mean
the beginning of the Clinton foreign policy victory party.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, many argue, there is virtually no guarantee
Slobodan Milosevic will keep his word _ or that NATO has a plan to
combat him if he does not. And even if the Yugoslav president is
sincere, there are many who believe the costs of the bombing
campaign outweighed the benefits, and that the NATO action
effectively caused the crisis it now purports to have fixed. Still
others, like Senator John F. Kerry, say the administration did not
make the right moves ``every step of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe they did the right thing,'' Kerry said. ``I do not
think their choice of force buildup or deployment were an
appropriate way to go about it, and I think it may have complicated
their capacity to get this done as rapidly as they might have . . .
And there are still some serious dangers in the equation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry added, ``It's much too early to be anything but cautiously
optimistic. ... It's way too early to be crowing.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would oppose a swift end to the war. And the current
peace plan, if implemented exactly as NATO desires, has almost
universal support. Advocates of the administration policy argue
this is just how things were supposed to go: airstrikes until
Milosevic capitulated, without a single US combat casualty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We conducted approximately 30,000 sorties and lost not a
soldier in the whole conflict. It worked,'' said Senator Joseph I.
Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat and member of the Senate Armed
Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly appears the administration has been successful,''
said Representative Sam Gejdenson of Connecticut, the ranking
Democrat on the House International Relations Committee. ``I think
they deserve great credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the criticism of the operation could be dismissed as
politically motivated, particularly since so many detractors are
Republicans who voted in April against the NATO airstrikes.
Representative Bill Goodling, a Pennsylvania Republican who helped
lead the opposition to US involvement and had warned there was a
``real possibility the conflict will escalate,'' expressed hope
this week that ``the president saves face and gets us out of this
mess. Though I shouldn't hope that, because we know he'll find
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many Republicans in Congress, Goodling's chief complaint is
cost _ ``billions of dollars on a civil war,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others question what those billions paid for. Although NATO may
have prevailed and Milosevic may have been stopped, some wonder
whether the Kosovar refugees are truly better off than they were
before the NATO air campaign, which is widely believed to have
provoked Serb troops into at least expanding the expulsion of
ethnic Albanians from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could very well be that this is a victory for those who
advocated the use of force, but you still have to set up some
metrics by which to measure this,'' said Representative Tom
Campbell, Republican of California. ``How many people died during
the operation? What is the condition of the homes they're returning
to? Are the Kosovars better off?''
</P>
<P>
   If a successful peace process, assuming there is one, is not
enough to change the minds of Clinton's political opponents, it
also may not be enough to persuade outside policy analysts,
military experts, and even some Democrats that this administration
is a diplomatic force.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, some Democratic aides say they are relieved by the
agreement with Milosevic, if only because they were so convinced in
recent months that the United States was headed into a quagmire. As
a staff member for one senior Democrat said: ``We never really
thought we ought to be doing this in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Some military officials are still reluctant to applaud the
airstrikes-only strategy they had criticized, especially since the
NATO bombing has not stopped. And observers of the State Department
insist Albright is still lacking a comprehensive foreign policy.
The real test, some say, will be in future dealings with places
vital to US interests _ China, North Korea, the Middle East, and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Eland, the director of defense policy studies at the Cato
Institute, a conservative think tank, said he was ``not sure we can
take this as a vindication of air power or the Clinton
administration's foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they got lucky, frankly,'' he said. ``The air war
didn't stop the atrocities. In fact, the Clinton policy caused
instability throughout the region, and the airstrikes accelerated
the ethnic cleansing. We destroyed Kosovo to save it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
