A3672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTWORK-HOLOCAUST-NYT     06-04 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTWORK-HOLOCAUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN FOUNDATION AGREES TO RETURN A VAN GOGH TO FAMILY OF
HOLOCAUST VICTIM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain )   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In a decision that should open the way for returning
other artworks seized by the Nazis, the German foundation that runs
many of Berlin's most prominent museums agreed Friday to return a
van Gogh drawing to the heir of a German-Jewish collector who was
forced to auction off the work shortly before the outbreak of World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Prussian Cultural Heritage Foundation said
it was convinced that the collector, Max Silberberg, had sold the
drawing, called ``L'Olivette,'' or ``The Olive-Grove,'' under
duress. He said it would be returned shortly to Silberberg's
daughter-in-law, Gerta, 83, who lives in Britain. Silberberg died
in a Nazi death camp.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting in Berlin Friday, the foundation's 20-member board
of trustees also authorized the foundation's president,
Klaus-Dieter Lehmann, to decide any future claims to artworks
belonging to German Jews that may have been illegally seized or
forcibly sold by the Nazis and are now in the collections of the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation operates 17 museums, including the National
Gallery and the Pergamon Museum in Berlin and the Gemaeldegalerie
in Dresden.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said no other claims were outstanding but that the
foundation was in contact with the German bureau of the Jewish
Claims Conference. He said that it was the bureau that drew the
foundation's attention to the van Gogh drawing in the National
Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't realize this drawing came from a former Jewish
collector because in our catalog it was always mentioned as a gift
from the Club of Friends of the National Gallery,'' he said. ``When
we received the documentation, it was clear that the drawing had
been sold under Nazi pressure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
