<P>
   INTERNET-INDULGENCE (New York) _ A Park Avenue couple has
created LuxuryFinder.Com, an E-commercie web site that will sell
high-end merchandise like Ghurka luggage, Brioni men's accessories
and hair-care products from John Barrett of Bergdorf Goodman. It
will offer online services like an ``electronic secretary'' to
alert subscribers when the latest merchandise has arrived at
upscale stores. By Monique P. Yazigi. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NY-KIRNA-BOUTIQUE (New York) _ They are 27 years old, grew up in
Virginia and are both Libras. Each day, they take turns reciting
aloud their horoscope in The New York Post. Epitomizing downtown
chic in their Tracey Feith slip dresses, jean jackets and pashmina
shawls, Sarah Hailes and Beth Shepherd are so alike they not only
complete each other's sentences, but also could be sisters. In
fact, they were sorority sisters at the University of Virginia,
where the two women met as roommates a decade ago. Today, Ms.
Hailes and Ms. Shepherd are still best friends, as well as business
partners. Next month, they plan to open Kirna Zabete, a two-level
clothing store in Manhattan that will marry NoLiTa and Neiman
Marcus. By Elizabeth Hayt. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-AWARDS (New York) _ The first and by no means only
foul-up at the Council of Fashion Designers of America's annual
awards gala last Wednesday was that hardly any of the guests at the
Lexington Avenue armory could see one another. Somebody had draped
the room in black and dimmed the lights. You had to be practically
on top of a person to see who it was. The awards evening has a
reputation for being longer, duller and ultimately less fun than
almost any such event, and it surpassed expectations this year as
technical delays _ presumably caused by the ceremony's being
televised for the first time _ turned it into a six-and-a-half-hour
ordeal of dinner, speeches and wilting hairdos. By Cathy Horyn.
Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAPEZE-THERAPY (McLEAN, Va.) _ I'm not sure what I was thinking
when I decided to fly the trapeze. In retrospect, it seems, I
wasn't thinking at all. I arrived at Circus Arts Workshop, an
outdoor trapeze rig here, to meet Sam Keen, the author of
``Learning to Fly: Trapeze _ Reflections on Fear, Trust and the Joy
of Letting Go,'' (Broadway Books, 1999; $23). Keen is based in
Sonoma, Calif., where he runs a program called Upward Bound,
teaching people to use the trapeze experience as a mechanism to
examine their own fears about life. It has been particularly
successful with abused women and recovering drug addicts, but
garden variety neurotics like me have also been able to benefit. By
Alex Witchel. &QL; 
 &QL;
