<HEADER>
A3680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-RECOVERY-ASSESS-     06-04 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-RECOVERY-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: U.S. LEFT TO DEAL WITH MILOSEVIC STILL IN POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like the war in the Persian Gulf, the war in Kosovo
appears to be ending with major issues unresolved, not least the
future of President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia and what the
United States ought to do about him.
</P>
<P>
   Although air power apparently achieved one of its greatest
successes in the 10-week campaign in the Balkans, it did not bring
about a change in government in Belgrade _ something that only an
invasion by ground forces and a prolonged occupation could be
expected to accomplish. So for the time being, the United States is
stuck with a Serbian leader it neither likes nor trusts.
</P>
<P>
   The parallels with Iraq are intriguing: Once again, a rogue
leader, demonized by Washington, is emerging from a conflict with
an apparently firm grip on power, with a significant part of his
military forces fighting fit and with sovereignty over his
country's territory technically intact.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton acknowledged Friday that NATO's terms for
peace did not in any way address the question of Milosevic staying
in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``That question is left open,'' the president said. ``He is
subject to the terms of the international war-crimes tribunal,
which means that if he comes within the jurisdiction of any country
that is cooperating with the United Nations, they would have an
obligation to turn him over.''
</P>
<P>
   But a senior administration official, speaking on condition that
he not be identified, acknowledged that ``that is not going to
happen.'' On the one hand, Milosevic has been indicted in The Hague
as a war criminal; on the other, he is for the moment NATO's
indispensable partner in the effort to stabilize Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an awkward, embarrassing situation,'' said Michael
Mandelbaum, a professor at Johns Hopkins University who advised
Clinton on foreign-policy issues during the 1992 election campaign.
``Nobody's about to arrest him, but it's hard just to say, `Never
mind.' How can you let it pass when you went to war because you had
to stop this evil man from committing genocide?''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is complicated by the international tribunal's
plan to send investigators into Kosovo when NATO and other
peacekeepers enter that shattered province. Presumably, they will
amass forensic evidence pointing to war crimes committed by
soldiers and paramilitary groups operating under the direct orders
of Milosevic and his associates in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Wedgwood, a senior fellow at the Council on Foreign
Relations who specializes in international law, said it was
``incongruous but not illegal'' for a person indicted as a war
criminal to hold high office and conduct a nation's business. ``The
facts of life,'' she said, ruled out an arrest of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration's best hope is slowly to marginalize him
politically,'' she said. ``They would like to put him away like
Greta Garbo.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the two Bosnian Serb leaders who were indicted as war
criminals, Radovan Karadzic and Ratko Mladic, have been turned over
to the authorities, even though NATO has tracked their movements
and they have traveled through parts of Bosnia patrolled by allied
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has made clear that he expects the Europeans to pay the
bulk of the cost of restoring Yugoslavia to economic health _ a
rebuilding program that could cost as much as $6 billion. How much
Congress would authorize in aid while Milosevic retains power could
be a complicated question.
</P>
<P>
   Richard N. Haass, the director of Foreign Policy Studies at the
Brookings Institution, who worked at the National Security Council
during the Bush administration, said economic help other than food
and medicine should be linked directly to the ouster of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give the Yugoslavian people every incentive to get
rid of him,'' Haass said. ``Every morning, they should get up, go
out into the streets and see the results of this man's actions
around them.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Milosevic appeared to be preparing the way for an
escape to Greece or even South Africa, but that now appears to be
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   An uprising against Milosevic, perhaps abetted by covert NATO
operatives, remains a possibility, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Liubco Georgievski of neighboring Macedonia
suggested on Thursday that Milosevic would be ousted in a matter of
weeks. But he gave no evidence to support that opinion, and
Milosevic's grip on the army and secret police remains firm,
American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that might make an uprising in Serbia more likely than
one in Iraq, which has often been predicted by American officials
but has never taken place, is that Yugoslavia is a much more
developed society. The lives of ordinary people in cities there are
more disrupted by bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   If the pact as now constituted takes effect, Milosevic will have
an ``agreed number'' of troops in Kosovo and more on the border.
That troubles some Republicans, including Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., a candidate for his party's presidential nomination. In a
statement Friday, he asked several questions: How many Serbs?
Permitted to do what? Based where? Armed, and if so, how heavily
armed?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are loopholes big enough to drive an armed battalion
through,'' McCain declared. ``I don't know how you can convince
Kosovars'' _ ethnic Albanians expelled from their homeland _ ``to
return, much less give up their weapons, while there are armed
Serbs in the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Signaling Republican hostility to the tentative agreement, Sen.
Jesse Helms of North Carolina, chairman of the Foreign Relations
Committee, said he would use hearings this month to discuss ``this
administration's misguided policy of appeasing Slobodan Milosevic''
in Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
