r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-04 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST CALL HIM BOB BAFFLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Bob Baffert comes to you _ late, but what else is
new? _ as the reigning expert on Triple Crown dreams and
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   He trained Silver Charm, who lost the Triple Crown by less than
a length in the 1997 Belmont Stakes, and Real Quiet, who went down
by a nose in '98. High highs, low lows.
</P>
<P>
   So, what does he know that D. Wayne Lukas and the nine other
trainers in today's Belmont do not?
</P>
<P>
   He knows how much a good haircut costs in Manhattan, for one
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy-eight dollars,'' he said grandly, feathering that
distinctive white mop with his fingers a day after a visit to a
Gotham stylist.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he knows there's more than one use for a bidet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry I'm late,'' he said about 9:30 a.m. Friday as he stepped
from a Triple Crown sponsor's sedan outside a Belmont Park barn.
``I couldn't get the bootwasher next to the toilet in that hotel to
work. I couldn't get the mud off.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, he knows the star of NBC News.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday was unbelievable!'' Baffert said. ``I'm walking down
_ I don't know if it was Park Avenue _ one of those avenues _ and
this guy comes up to me and says, `Bob, I'm a big fan. Good luck
this weekend.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saying, `Help me out here, I recognize you.' It's Tom
Brokaw! Mike Pegram is right in front of me. I said, `Mike, come
here, I need a witness!'''
</P>
<P>
   And what does he know about the Belmont? Put it this way, if
Baffert has been up nights, it's not because he's worrying about
his chances in the race.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a different kind of Belmont week for Baffert and
Pegram, trainer and owner of Silverbulletday, the filly who will
try to stop Charismatic from clinching a Triple Crown today.
</P>
<P>
   They're staying in Manhattan, such a rough commute to the Long
Island racetrack that Baffert has been getting to the barn about
9:30 each morning, which is about 5{ hours after Lukas has been
going to work on Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert hasn't gotten to Belmont Park early enough to watch
Silverbulletday in either of her morning gallops since she arrived
Wednesday from Louisville, Ky., leaving supervision of her first
visit to the main track on Friday to exercise rider Peter Hutton
and a local trainer's assistant.
</P>
<P>
   He has been invisible to reporters who don't want to make the
15-minute hike to barn 50, on the roughest edge of the tree-lined
Belmont backside, where he moved after being assigned the close-in
barn 1.
</P>
<P>
   He appears to have entered the Belmont mainly so he can enjoy
the downtown nightlife, hence a fancy hotel in Manhattan instead of
a fancy hotel near the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supertourists,'' Baffert calls himself and Pegram. ``We're
very low-key this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this any way to win a $1 million horse race? Or show you care
about winning a $1 million horse race?
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not, and maybe that's a good enough reason to throw
Silverbulletday, the 4-1 third choice on the Belmont morning line,
out of your trifecta wagers this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Baffert isn't exactly an early riser even in the peace and
quiet of Southern California or the dull and quiet of Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   But 9:30 arrivals at the barn? This is getting ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   He hopped out of the car Friday morning with a smile on his face
and asked reporters to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lemme act like a trainer, and go look at her
(Silverbulletday),'' Baffert joked.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's a practical reason for this odd approach.
</P>
<P>
   After the past two years, when he was the center of Belmont
attention, Baffert wants to get away from it all. After hearing too
many questions about his rivalry with Lukas, he wants to get away
from the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier when you don't win the first two (races),
because the media leaves you alone,'' Baffert said. ``I know Wayne,
(Charismatic owners) Bob and Beverly Lewis and (jockey) Chris
Antley have to be mentally exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   Belmont-day advice to the Team Charismatic from a man who's been
there?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just enjoy it,'' Baffert said. ``If it's meant to be, it's
meant to be. If I was Lukas and the Lewises, about 5 o'clock
(Friday) afternoon, I'd start drinking heavily.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Baffert goes into the Belmont with low pressure,
because although Silverbulletday's fans will expect big things,
their girl being the winner of eight straight races against
fillies, she is facing males for the first time under
less-than-ideal circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   A mile-and-a-half race, five weeks after Baffert declared
Silverbulletday couldn't handle the Kentucky Derby's 1\ miles?
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know until they turn for home whether the fuel light
will come on. All I can tell you is, she's training great,''
Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   Or so he's been told.
</P>
<P>
   Who'll win the Belmont? No knock on Charismatic, the best horse
in the Derby and Preakness, but I'm jumping off his bandwagon
without ever jumping on. There's no value in his 2-1 morning line
or in Menifee's 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   I'll take a shot with 20-1 Patience Game, a California-based
colt who is nicely bred for the Belmont and lightly raced, leaving
room to improve on the his victory in the Derby Trial and troubled
fifth in the Preakness. Kent Desormeaux rides to forget about Real
Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   As for Silverbulletday, I don't know what Tom Brokaw would say,
but I call her a long shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
