<SLUG> BC-NEWJOBS-DECLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYMENT GROWTH SLOWED IN MAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growth in the nation's payrolls slowed sharply in May to just
11,000 new jobs, surprising experts who attributed it to a shortage
of workers to fill jobs that remain plentiful in a robust economy.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said evidence of a tightening labor market, which
could eventually push up wages and inflation, may add pressure on
the Federal Reserve Board to raise interest rates at its next
meeting scheduled for June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The jobs report ``seems to be quite a shock,'' said William
Cheney, economist for John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Company.
``The problem is supply. People can't find the bodies to hire.''
</P>
<P>
   The US unemployment rate dipped 0.1 percentage point to 4.2
percent last month, the Department of Labor said Friday in its
monthly jobs report. Economists said that the remarkably low
jobless rate has remained below 5 percent since June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As the labor market tightened, it caused a decline in the
unemployment rate for blacks, a segment of the population that has
suffered chronically high joblessness, for a third consecutive
month. Unemployment among blacks was 7.5 percent _ the lowest level
ever recorded, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses also rapidly absorbed teenagers seeking summer jobs,
driving teen unemployment to 12.6 percent in May, from 14.1 percent
in April, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's jobs report and an upcoming report on the consumer
price index for April could prove key to whether Federal Reserve
members decide to raise interest rates later this month. Fed
watchers said that if the CPI surges again in May _ as it did in
April _ there would be extreme pressures to raise rates in an
attempt to control inflation. The CPI spiked up 0.7 percent in
April.
</P>
<P>
   John Youngdahl, an economist for Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. in New
York, predicted the Fed would raise rates by 0.25 percent at the
next meeting. Given evidence of a tight labor market the Fed, led
by chairman Alan Greenspan, is likely to believe the economy is
``tending toward higher costs for labor,'' Youngdahl said.
</P>
<P>
   Workers' wages rose 5 cents last month to an average $13.19 an
hour. That compared with a 3 cent per hour rise in April and a 4
cent per hour rise in March.
</P>
<P>
   But John Hancock's Cheney said there is little consensus among
economists about the Fed's next move.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market reacted to the ambiguous report by bouncing
around early in the day. By the close, the Dow Jones industrial
stock index rose 136.15 to 10,799.84.
</P>
<P>
   The 11,000 new jobs added last month pales when compared to
343,000 job growth in April, and 83,000 growth in March. May marked
the worst monthly performance since January 1996, when the economy
lost 7,000 jobs. Economists said that the numbers may reflect, in
part, problems with seasonal adjustments in the government's data.
</P>
<P>
   The government report showed that job losses in the
manufacturing and construction sectors in May were barely offset
last month by modest gains in services and other sectors. ``It
certainly is well below expectations _ a surprisingly weak
report,'' said Denis McSweeney, regional commissioner of the Labor
Department's Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers, after suffering huge job losses in 1998, due to
weakness among Asian trading partners, continue to be hammered by
competition from low-cost imports. Factory jobs shrunk by 45,000 in
May _ there are 453,000 fewer factory jobs than in March 1998. A
loss of 40,000 construction jobs last month, following a 44,000
decline in April, was blamed on rising home-mortgage interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The most robust sector _ services _ added 71,000 new jobs last
month, but that was well below the average monthly gains of 125,000
experienced over the past year, the government said. Hiring by
business services firms, including computer services, continued to
show strength but the call for engineering, health services and
lodging employees waned.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Latta, a US economist for Standard &AMP; Poor's/DRI in
Lexington said a 4.2 percent unemployment rate is ``testimony to
the fact the job market remains very, very good.'' Even given
Friday's weak report, job growth has averaged 210,000 a month in
1999, compared with 236,000 last year, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
