<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO MAY SOON HALT YUGOSLAV BOMBINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO could stop bombing Yugoslavia as early as
Sunday if the Serbs cooperate, but Pentagon officials Friday warned
that they have seen no signs of movement in the day after Slobodan
Milosevic yielded to allied demands.
</P>
<P>
   A top NATO commander, Britain's Michael Jackson, will meet
Saturday along the Macedonia and Kosovo border with his Yugoslav
counterpart to present the details for withdrawal of Serb troops
from Kosovo and the deployment of a NATO-led international security
force to protect ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton continued to voice caution about the possible
end of the 11-week-old conflict and said bombing runs aimed at
Yugoslav military targets will continue until ``we have some
evidence that there are more than words here.''
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,'' Clinton
said, ``I'm anxious to end the bombing, but I want to know that our
objectives have been achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's Yugoslav government accepted an international peace
plan Thursday, but NATO leaders, including Clinton, fear that the
Serb leader will renege as he has several times before.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Serbia cooperates, I think the bombing could be halted by
the end of the weekend or very early next week,'' said Pentagon
spokesman Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said Jackson will present his military counterpart with a
schedule for withdrawal and explain the benchmarks that NATO must
see as proof of a withdrawal before the bombing will stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we could have that movement within a day or two. But
it could take much longer than that,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Yugoslavian Parliament's action to accept the peace
plan, its armed forces continued firing at insurgent Kosovo
Liberation Army rebels and harassing the few ethnic Albanians
remaining in Kosovo, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not see signs that they have pulled punches, and we do
not see signs that they've begun to pull out,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 40,000 Yugoslav troops, plus Serb irregulars, poured into
the Serb province of Kosovo as the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization began bombing March 24. The troops and masked security
forces have ousted nearly all the 1.7 million Kosovar Albanians
from their homes in ``ethnic cleansing'' raids.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 850,000 ethic Albanians who fled Kosovo,
and hundreds of thousands of others are hiding in the Kosovo
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The peace plan, similar to one Milosevic rejected earlier this
year, requires Yugoslavia to remove its troops and security forces
from Kosovo, to allow a NATO-dominated international security force
into Kosovo, to allow the return of all Kosovar refugees and to
allow autonomy for the Kosovar Albanians although Kosovo will
remain a province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also required the Yugoslavian military to remove its
anti-aircraft equipment within 48 hours and to remove all troops
and irregular forces within seven days. Bacon said the Yugoslav
forces must withdraw beyond a 25 kilometer security zone along the
Serbia-Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said a Marine Expeditionary Unit aboard the USS Kearsarge
was moving from the Adriatic Sea to the Aegean Sea. The unit will
land in Greece, where it will position itself to become the lead
element of American forces into Kosovo. NATO intends to deploy
50,000 troops into the province, 7,000 from the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, at a White House ceremony, called the conflict a ``just
and necessary'' military campaign aimed at ending the persecution
of a people based on race and ethnicity. ``Our experience in the
Balkans teaches us that true peace can only come when progress in
discussions is followed by progress on the ground,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, he noted the agreement that ended the conflict in
Bosnia between Serbs, Muslims and Croats was successful only
because international security forces stayed in Bosnia after the
peace accord was signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, there is an enormous opportunity to be
seized here _ a chance to shift our focus from defeating something
evil to building something good; a chance to work with our allies
to bring a stable and prosperous and democratic southeastern Europe
in which people are never again singled out for destruction simply
because of their religious faith or their ethnic origin,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a goal that has been worth fighting for over the last
weeks ... And I believe that the overwhelming majority of Americans
share this goal. We do not want our children to grow up in a world
which is dominated by people who believe they can kill innocent
civilians because of the way they worship God or the way they were
born,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But the peace agreement also leaves Milosevic in power, although
his policies also have fueled conflict in Bosnia. Milosevic also
was indicted last week on charges of crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, on ABC, said Milosevic's future was not addressed by
NATO. ``That's an open question,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, several leaders said they would be unwilling to
provide any reconstruction aid to Yugoslavia while Milosevic
remains in power. Joe Lockhart, the president's spokesman, echoed
those sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that beyond some humanitarian assistance that
the United States will be interested in working with an
authoritarian regime like Milosevic to help them rebuild,''
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will be traveling to
Europe next week to meet with foreign ministers to discuss the next
steps. She also will meet with ethnic Albanian leaders, the State
Department said.
</P>
<P>
   On day 73 of the air campaign, NATO jets made 610 sorties and
234 strikes, according to Jamie Shea, the NATO spokesman in
Brussels, Belgium. He called the air raids ``a typical day and a
typical night by the standards of this air operation.''
</P>
<P>
   But NATO also was showing some restraint, keeping as its targets
military equipment and forces in Kosovo rather than any broad
attacks against Belgrade and the civilian infrastructure in Serbia,
the largest Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
