u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-0605-COX     06-04 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DRUG ALLEGATIONS DOG ANNUAL MEETING OF U.S. AND MEXICAN
OFFICIALS
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A fresh round of explosive allegations linking
high-ranking Mexican politicians to drug-trafficking put U.S.
Attorney General Janet Reno and Mexican officials on the defensive
during an official two-day visit here that ended Friday.
</P>
<P>
   During the 16th annual U.S.-Mexico Binational Commission meeting
here, U.S. and Mexican officials hammered out agreements to help
mutually fight forest fires and border pollution, and to reduce the
risks to illegal immigrants making dangerous border crossings.
</P>
<P>
   But when officials from both countries first gathered Thursday,
some participants said relations were noticeably strained because
of press reports this week alleging that U.S. intelligence agencies
were deeply suspicious of two major Mexican political figures.
</P>
<P>
   The two are wealthy Mexican businessman Carlos Hank Gonzalez(CQ
both), who served twice as a cabinet member under previous Mexican
presidents, and Jose Liebano Saenz Ortiz, private secretary to
current Mexican president Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   Both men have publicly declared that they are innocent and that
suspicions are unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a press conference Friday, Reno did not deny the
existence of U.S. intelligence gathering on the men but she
downplayed its significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should not jump to judgment based on fragmentary
reports,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno added, after persistent questioning, ``I know of no
evidence that would permit me to correctly conclude . . . that
(Saenz Ortiz) is guilty of any wrongdoing. It is unfair and just
plain wrong to make judgments based on fragmentary reports.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Mexican officials have been particularly
critical of U.S. authorities not sharing information about drug
traffickers gathered by U.S. intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Secretary of State Rosario Green reflected this view
Friday, when she told reporters that the Mexican government had
asked U.S. officials this week to clarify what information it had
about both men or ``publicly denounce'' the reports.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. anti-drug czar Gen. Barry McCaffrey, who also was in Mexico
for the meeting, also reacted angrily to the press reports based on
leaks of confidential information.
</P>
<P>
   He downplayed the intelligence reports and said that dossiers
are often compiled on U.S. citizens as well, but do not prove
guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we've got credible evidence, we should not be trashing
people's reputations,'' McCaffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Reno, McCaffrey said he didn't have any information about
Saenz Ortiz that would lead him to confront Mexican officials and
say ``we've got a problem with this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said he hadn't read the intelligence report on Hank
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   According to published accounts in Mexico and the United States,
a report by the U.S. National Drug Intelligence Center called the
Hank Gonzalez family a ``significant criminal threat to the United
States'' because of alleged drug-smuggling activites.
</P>
<P>
   The National Drug Intelligence Center compiles information from
the Drug Enforcement Administration, the FBI, the CIA, the U.S.
Customs Service and other agencies.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday Reno called the binational meeting, which takes place
every year, ``bread-and-butter diplomacy,'' where issues that
affect the daily lives of citizens of both countries are discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The binational commission is where good things happen,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
