<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CLEAR CHOICES FOR REFUGEES CAUGHT BETWEEN TWO WORLDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By DAVID ROHDE with ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANKOVEC I REFUGEE CAMP, Macedonia _ Both families face the
same decision. After being forced from their homes, herded onto
trains or pursued over mined mountain passes, they spent weeks
crowded into this sweltering refugee camp. Now they must choose
whether to return to a ravaged Kosovo or to seek a new life in
another country.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-member Shala family has three children under the age of
10 who can no longer stand temperatures of more than 100 degrees.
Their house in Pristina, Kosovo's capital, has been burnt to the
ground. The Serbs stole the family's prime income source _ the taxi
belonging to 29-year-old Zegir.
</P>
<P>
   The Shalas decided this afternoon that they could not trust the
latest talk of peace and boarded a plane evacuating refugees to
Denmark, only 24 hours after the Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic agreed to a full withdrawal of his forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the politicians don't know how long this is going to
take,'' Zegir said as he guided the family onto a bus to the
airport. ``I don't trust Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, the Llalloshi family is choosing to stay and
see if they can go home to Kosovo. There are nine members of the
family who managed to flee, including a 4-year-old boy and
68-year-old and 61-year-old grandparents withering in the heat.
Their home in Pristina is occupied by Serb soldiers. Skender, 31,
was a teacher who supported the rest of the family. But he has no
idea if the elementary school he taught in is even standing. The
Llalloshis are hoping that a Serb capitulation, and their
dreamed-of return to Kosovo, may, in fact, be at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't trust Milosevic but we have more hope now,'' Skender
said. The decisions these two families are wrestling with echo
those of hundreds of thousands of refugees here and in Albania. For
those who can choose to leave for other countries, the question is
whether to go far away when peace suddenly appears tantalizingly
close.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement came so suddenly that both NATO and relief
agencies were caught without a plan. Refugees were still straggling
over the border Friday. Even though the safe return of the refugees
to Kosovo became the central goal of the NATO air campaign, such
basic issues as who will escort the refugees back to Kosovo, who
will dismantle the booby traps to make it safe for them once they
arrive, and who will ensure that the refugees follow the plan have
yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   NATO fears that once the Albanian refugees realize that the
settlement is real, they will bolt from the sweltering camps here
and try to return on their own, before Kosovo has been pacified by
NATO troops. The result, according to Major Trey Cate, a NATO
officer here, ``could be a lot of families with missing limbs once
they hit the mines on the border.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations refugee agency, which until Wednesday was
drawing up plans to winterize those camps, is now worried that many
refugees will refuse to believe that Kosovo is safe. They fear the
refugees will decide to remain behind in a Macedonia that does not
want them because their presence would upset Macedonia's precarious
ethnic balance.
</P>
<P>
   For all of these reasons, the paramount goal of the NATO
peacekeeping force headquartered here is to get into Kosovo first
and hold off any refugee return until the Serbian province is safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``How will NATO go into Kosovo with 100,000 or more refugees
clogging the road?'' asked Major Cate. ``Imagine what would happen
if they all wanted to go home the day the peace agreement is
signed.''
</P>
<P>
   But holding back the refugees is against international law and
the mandate of the refugee agency.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) The basic division of labor is clear. NATO
troops are charged with providing a ``safe and secure environment''
in Kosovo for the refugees. That involves securing the province
under the eventual control of 30,000 NATO troops, ensuring that
neither the Serbs nor the Kosovo Liberation Army renew the
conflict, and clearing the major roads of mines.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees ensures the
right of the refugees to return _ or to chose not to return _ and
to coordinate the relief aid for them once they are in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The refugees, as usual, are caught in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Zegir, the main wage-earner in the Shala family, had little time
to choose. His name, as well as the names of all of the roughly
100,000 refugees in camps in Macedonia, was entered into a database
when he and his family arrived here in April after being expelled
from their home in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   The database is scoured by diplomats from the dozens of
countries now accepting Kosovar refugees for potential evacuees.
The ill, women with children and the elderly are given priority,
but families like the Shalas are also sometimes chosen at random.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, the name of Zegir and his relatives was posted on
a list of people accepted for evacuation to a country he knew next
to nothing about _ Denmark. Zegir, who had never traveled outside
the former Yugoslavia, had no idea what to expect. He and his
family say they only hope that it will be nice there.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of a peace deal on the eve of their departure
only complicated their decision. While some refugees are eager to
permanently move abroad, Zegir and other Shala family members said
they want to return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will go back as fast as we can,'' said Shemsije, Zegir's
20-year-old sister.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
