<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3688 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-2NDTA     06-04 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
STANKOVEC I REFUGEE CAMP, Macedonia: 20-year-old sister.   But the
Shalas are afraid of what they might face in Kosovo. Three of their
brothers are in the Kosovo Liberation Army, and they believe that
is why they were targeted early by the Serb paramilitaries. After
the Serbs burned their home, the Shalas took a train to the border
and have been waiting in the camp for two months.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the end, Zegir, a man who insists on dressing in slacks and a
button-down shirt in a refugee camp, decided it would be
irresponsible for him to believe Milosevic's peace offer and
subject his family to weeks more in the heat and squalor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to live in a foreign country,'' he said. ``But we
are used to Milosevic's agreements. I can't trust them.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, eight friends wept as the Shalas entered a small
fenced- off area in this dusty camp to be cleared before boarding
the bus. So did the Shalas. As they boarded the bus, they clung to
small pamphlets they were handed describing their rights as
refugees in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   The Llalloshi family, while not guaranteed a trip abroad, could
likely get one. They have a close relative, a brother, in Sweden
and reunifying families is an evacuation program priority.
</P>
<P>
   Skender, the elementary school teacher who is the chief decision
maker, said he is considering sending his parents to Sweden because
they are suffering in the heat. But he, his wife, his 4-year-old
son, and three siblings will wait in the camp for peace.
</P>
<P>
   The Llaloshis spent six weeks fleeing from village to village,
hiding in friends' homes. They finally decided they could take no
more two weeks ago, and walked over the mountains to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Skender said he believed that NATO would eventually help them to
go home, and he feared that if they left, they might never return
to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get spoiled by the conditions and don't return,'' he
said. ``Milosevic wants that.''
</P>
<P>
   Skender, whose family lives in an 80-person tent here, battles
regret and frustration as he watches his family suffer. He does not
know what the right choice is for his family.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, a column of British NATO military vehicles could
give him a partial answer. The NATO vehicles are expected to drive
past this camp on their way to a Yugoslav border post just up the
road. There, British Gen. Michael Jackson is expected to meet with
senior Serb military officials to negotiate a promised Serbian
withdrawal from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll believe it,'' Skender said, referring to the peace deal,
``when I see NATO troops go into Kosovo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
