<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some Room at the Inn &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the saddest to see Robert E. Rubin step down as Treasury
Secretary are the employees at the Jefferson Hotel in Washington,
where Rubin has made Room 214 his home for the last six years.
Rubin, a former co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs, kept his permanent
residence in New York, where his wife, Judy, remained.
</P>
<P>
   His Jefferson suite includes office, living room, exercise room
and bedroom. Next door is an office for his Secret Service agents,
who are the ones lingering, but never drinking, at the hotel bar
while Rubin dines.
</P>
<P>
   Suites at the Jefferson, a five-minute walk from the White
House, usually go for $400 to $1,200 a night, with discounts for
extended stays. Rubin often entertained in the hotel's private
dining rooms, on both government and personal business.
</P>
<P>
   During the Clinton presidential campaigns, he also used the
hotel for fund-raising dinners. The staff regards him as a
courteous guest.
</P>
<P>
   Other Jefferson regulars include Sam Donaldson and his ABC staff
on Thursday nights at the bar, and Vernon E. Jordan Jr. and Erskine
B. Bowles, Clinton confidantes who confer there.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Morris, the campaign strategist, romped with a prostitute
in Room 205 _directly across a courtyard from Rubin's suite. In the
Reagan years, the Jefferson was home to William French Smith, the
attorney general, and Sen. John G. Tower.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Rubin's likely departure, the Jefferson is apt to
maintain its status as the Treasury Department annex. Spotted at
dinner last Tuesday night was Lawrence H. Summers, Rubin's
successor.
</P>
<P>
   LESLIE WAYNE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Making Scents Visible &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eugene P. Grisanti, the chief executive of International Flavors
and Fragrances, thinks he knows simpatico when he sees it _ for
instance, in Marilyn Monroe's global sex appeal and the sensuality
of the fragrances his company makes, behind the scenes, for the
likes of Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, Emporio Armani and Clinique.
</P>
<P>
   So when Christie's went looking for a sponsor to help defray the
marketing costs for its auction in October of Monroe's personal
effects, Grisanti signed on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an image-building thing,'' he said, and well worth the
six-figure cost. (Neither he nor Christie's would be more
specific.) For many brand names, ``we have always been
ghostwriters, but it's becoming more and more known that IFF makes
the fragrances,'' he added. ``The perfume industry was always very
French, and that an American company is now the leader in the
perfume business _it's like California wines taking over the wine
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie's plans to put Monroe's items _ evening gowns, jewelry,
books, letters _ on exhibition in New York, Los Angeles, Buenos
Aires, London and Paris. The International Flavors name will go
along for the ride, and so will Grisanti, giving parties to
entertain customers and potential customers at each stop.
</P>
<P>
   For Christie's, the partnership with Grisanti is its second
corporate sponsorship, after Vogue magazine backed its
``Unforgettable: Fashions of the Oscars'' sale in March.
</P>
<P>
   For Grisanti, it's an attempt to raise his company's flag
overseas, where 70 percent of its sales originate but where the
French still get credit for the great perfumes. Besides, Grisanti
added, ``There may be a great `Marilyn' fragrance in this; that
would be a natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith H. Dobrzynski &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bookshelves to Grocery Shelves &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soft-spoken and even timid in public, Louis Borders, the founder
of Borders Books and Music, has entrepreneurial visions that
contrast with his demeanor. At a ribbon-cutting ceremony on
Wednesday in Oakland, Calif., flanked by Jerry Brown, the city's
animated mayor, Borders traded literature for food and drink, and
bricks and mortar for a virtual storefront, in starting Webvan, a
new competitor in the on-line-only grocery store business.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, it is the most ambitious entrant to date. Borders, 51,
promises that orders will be delivered by one of his tan-painted
vans within five hours. The service is rolling out in the San
Francisco Bay area and there are plans to be in 10 markets _ most
locations still to be announced _ by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Borders, who is no longer involved with Borders Books, said he
was returning to the family business; his father was a meat
distributor in Louisville, Ky. More generally, he said that in
starting Webvan, he wanted to meet his own hearty appetite for big
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   He debated trying other on-line ventures, but decided he had to
try using the Net for a shot at the grocery business and its
roughly $500 billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Richtel &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
