<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC'S CHANCE TO JOIN THE GREATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELMONT, N.Y. _ Moments after D. Wayne Lukas, Chris Antley, and
Bob Lewis arrived in New York last Wednesday, they were gathered
together for a press conference. The three were seated in front of
a huge banner for the New York Racing Association, and on the
banner were the proud names of the Triple Crown winners.
</P>
<P>
   One of the three would talk. But the eyes of at least one
observer would wander to the name ``Omaha.'' Another would talk.
This time, the eyes fixed on ``Count Fleet'' and ``Whirlaway.'' And
still a third member of Charismatic's team would speak, and the
names ``Secretariat,'' ``Seattle Slew,'' and ``Affirmed'' would
overwhelm all words.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it seemed more than a leap of faith to imagine the
name ``Charismatic'' on the same list with America's great
3-year-old horses of the past _ Gallant Fox, War Admiral, Assault,
and the others. Late Saturday afternoon at Belmont Park, though, it
just may happen.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 80,000 could be on hand to see if Charismatic can
jump from the ranks of racing's blue-collar workers _ claiming
horses _ and into immortality. It would be a huge jump.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere would be charged enough with Charismatic's
attempt to win the Triple Crown, which has not been accomplished
since Affirmed edged out Alydar in 1978 in one of the great races
in American history. But the atmosphere will be doubly-charged
because one of Charismatic's main threats will be Silverbulletday,
a superior filly who has won 11 of 12 races.
</P>
<P>
   Guys and a Doll is how Broadway might title this show _ the girl
taking on the boys _ but it certainly won't be a musical. Rather,
it will be a thriller, with each going for the others' throats. And
adding even more anticipation is the hot rivalry between Lukas,
Charismatic's trainer, and Bob Baffert, the trainer of the filly.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic likely will be 2-1 on the tote board when the gates
open, a favorite, finally, after being overlooked at 12-1 in the
Lexington Stakes, 31-1 in the Kentucky Derby, and 8-1 in the
Preakness, his last three races _ all of which he won. Even so,
many horse fanciers have not warmed up to Charismatic, and he
probably will be the highest-odds ever in the Belmont of the 25
horses who came to New York after winning the Derby and Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet and Sunday Silence, for instance, went for the Triple
Crown last year and in 1997, respectively, and each went off as
overwhelming favorites at 4-5 (each also lost). Alysheba was 4-5 in
1987 when he failed in the Belmont, Spectacular Bid was 1-5 in
1979, and others such as Tim Tam (3-20 in 1958), Carry Back (2-5 in
1961), and Northern Dancer (4-5) in 1964), were bet heavily and
still lost.
</P>
<P>
   Of those 25 who came to New York with a chance to win the Triple
Crown, of course, only eight have won. Charismatic, though, is
coming into the Belmont off a vastly-improved effort in the
Preakness and seems on the upswing. Many who have tried the
Belmont, especially those coming out of the Derby and Preakness,
have been on the downslope of their form cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Even more promising for Charismatic is that he was able to win
the Derby and the Preakness off two vastly different scenarios. In
the Derby, the pace was dawdling, and the colt was able to lay
close and take the lead early in his stretch run. In the Preakness,
by contrast, the pace was blistering, and Charismatic was forced
back to 10th place, but he was able to close from there and win
easily. No matter the pace, Charismatic can adjust.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday may need a softer pace if the filly is to shock
the colts. Even though Nick Zito, trainer of Adonis and Stephen Got
Even, seems to have trained speed into Adonis so he can be close to
the pace, or on the pace, it seems Silverbulletday's jockey, Jerry
Bailey, may get to the lead and try to coax the filly along on a
relatively slow pace. If Bailey can do that, the filly will be
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Only four horses can make the board in the Belmont _
Charismatic, Silverbulletday, Stephen Got Even, and the plodding
Menifee. Of the 12 horses in the Belmont, though, Silverbulletday's
situation is totally different from the rest. Baffert has said he
will instruct Bailey that if the filly is beaten coming for home,
the jockey is not to abuse her. So it seems more likely that
Silverbulletday would finish first if she had the lead down the
stretch, but second if she is trailing at that point.
</P>
<P>
   Lingering in the back of one's mind, though, were the words in
Boston last Saturday from Gary Stevens, who rode Silverbulletday
before departing to ride in Europe. Stevens surprisingly said that
he felt Charismatic would win the Triple Crown, and he had doubts
whether the filly could go 1 1/2 miles.
</P>
<P>
   So there are two plays in the Belmont. In the first, take
Silverbulletday to win, Charismatic second, and Stephen Got Even
third. The filly is extraordinary, and it still seems that the
colts in this race _ aside from Charismatic _ are more common than
excellent.
</P>
<P>
   The other approach to the Belmont is this: Charismatic wins the
Triple Crown, edging out Stephen Got Even, with Menifee plodding
along for third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
