<SLUG> BC-U.S.-EMBASSY-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO SEEK $264 MILLION FOR BUILDING OF EMBASSIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration, responding to criticism
that it had failed to protect U.S. diplomats from terrorist
attacks, said Friday that it would ask Congress for an additional
$264 million next year to build new, more secure embassies.
</P>
<P>
   An independent panel that investigated the bombings of two U.S.
embassies in East Africa last August concluded in January that the
State Department needed to substantially increase its spending on
security, especially for construction of new posts that meet the
department's own internal-security guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The embassies that were attacked, in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es
Salaam, Tanzania, did not meet those guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after the panel issued its report, the State Department's
budget for the next fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1, proposed a
spending increase less than half the amount the panel had
recommended for embassy security. Adm. William Crowe, the retired
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, who led the panel's
investigation, publicly complained that the budget request was
inadequate, and congressional leaders contended that the
administration was shortchanging security needs.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, State Department officials said the Office of
Management and Budget had blocked their efforts to propose a larger
budget increase. But with pressure building from Crowe and
Congress, the White House agreed to review the fund levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Admiral Crowe did a service by bringing so much attention to
this,'' an administration official acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   In its budget request for the next fiscal year, sent to Congress
in February, the State Department asked for an additional $36
million for new embassy construction. Now, that is being raised to
$300 million, an administration official said. A further $268
million is being sought for the hiring of new security guards and
other continuing security measures, apart from the construction of
embassies.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the administration plans to ask Congress to
allocate an extra $150 million a year for the following four years.
In 2001, funds for embassy construction would be increased to $450
million, and by 2004, this would reach $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official declined to say how many new
embassies the State Department planned to build with this money.
The official also said that the additional funds, which will be
proposed to Congress next week, would not be offset by reductions
in other State Department spending programs, although they would
have to be offset from expenses elsewhere in the federal budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
