<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3700 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-04 1498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD NEWS FOR CELTICS, WIDOW OF REGGIE LEWIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dr. Job Fuchs told the Northeastern University school
paper this week that he will testify in court that Reggie Lewis
tested positive for cocaine while he played basketball at the
school.
</P>
<P>
   This is bad news for both the Celtics and Reggie's widow, Donna
Harris-Lewis, who filed a malpractice suit against three doctors
who had treated Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Fuchs, who has flip-flopped in the past about whether Lewis
tested positive in 1987, told reporter Mike Trocchi: ``I think it
was pretty clear that he tested positive on the first test. A few
days later he tested negative.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 and '91, while playing for the Celtics, Lewis signed
three insurance applications, totaling $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   On the applications, Lewis was asked if he ``ever'' had used
marijuana, cocaine, etc. Lewis said no.
</P>
<P>
   If Fuchs is correct _ and his testimony will be supported by
others from Northeastern _ this becomes a $17 million fraud.
</P>
<P>
   It also contradicts the testimony of Harris-Lewis that her late
husband never used drugs, that it was against Reggie's
``philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics could find themselves at risk for $5 million. This
comes on the heels of their last financial report, which stated
that the Boston Celtics Limited Partnership, which owns 48.3
percent of the team, lost $8.5 million in the last six months of
'98.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis is being paid close to $12 million from those
insurance policies, which are covered under the statute of
limitations. However, the last policy for $5 million is not, and
the insurance company will have an open door to try to recoup that
money.
</P>
<P>
   Former NU athletic director Irwin Cohen has said all along that
Fuchs told him in 1987 that both Lewis and teammate Andre LaFleur
tested positive for cocaine. And Karl Fogel, who was the NU coach
at the time, told the school newspaper that LaFleur came to him a
few days after the test and told him that he and Lewis had tested
positive. Fogel told the paper he talked to Lewis about the tests.
</P>
<P>
   Fuchs said he expects to be called by the defense lawyers in the
next couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Payne Stewart knows who the winner will be in the upcoming
made-for-TV, head-to-head match between David Duval and Tiger
Woods. ``IMG will be a big winner,'' laughs Stewart, who will visit
The Country Club in Brookline in a few weeks before heading to
Europe. Stewart hopes to be back in September as part of the US
team for the Ryder Cup. ``I really hope it works out that way,''
says Stewart, who acknowledges that there is no pressure in golf
like Ryder Cup play. ``(Team captain) Ben Crenshaw has talked to
some of the guys about what we would like to see (in the course in
Brookline), and I told him that I would like to see a setup that
gives us a chance to make shots. The pressure will make all of us
either look silly or brilliant.'' As for the Woods-Duval encounter,
Stewart seemed more curious than anything. ``IMG has both golfers,
so they will start out by getting 20 percent of what they make on
the deal,'' he says. ``And then I'm sure IMG will get a piece of
the television money for putting the package together. So they are
going to do well. I hope it goes well, because I think it could
help all of golf. But I don't know how it is going to happen. It
will be live, and there is a lot of time to fill between shots when
you have those guys walking the course. When we play Skins games
they have us miked and want a lot of banter back and forth with the
players. Both of these two guys are very quiet, intense. They don't
say a lot on the golf course. I just hope it works and brings more
of the viewing public to watching golf.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   M.L. Carr doesn't find it easy watching Tim Duncan become the
best player in the NBA in less than two years. ``I think of what
might have been and it hurts,'' says Carr, thinking back to the day
a couple of years ago when he and Celtics publicist Jeff Twiss went
to New Jersey, confident they were going to bring back Duncan and
start a new dynasty in Boston. ``Jeff and myself went down for the
draft lottery,'' remembers Carr. ``We had a higher percentage of
chances than anyone else to get the top pick, and Duncan. He is the
guy we coveted. I didn't think we would miss him. And when we did,
a little piece of me died. I took a lot of bullets (coaching the
year before) hoping we could get this kid, and it just didn't work
out.'' San Antonio ended up with the first pick and took Duncan,
who is now the cornerstone of that team. ``When we got to New York,
I was very confident we were going to get the top pick,'' says
Twiss. ``We had two lottery picks, and two expansion teams,
Vancouver and Toronto, couldn't pick if they were in the top three.
But I started to worry in the warmup. They had a mock draft to show
us how the real one was going to go, and San Antonio wound up with
the first pick in the mock draft. My palms started to sweat. Then,
when they won it again, I couldn't believe it. We could have come
out of that draft with Duncan and Keith Van Horn, and instead we
ended up with the third and sixth picks, when we had a chance for
one and two.'' Carr says Duncan is everything he thought he would
be: ``He is a dominant player. He can run the floor. Passes out of
the post. Has a nice jump hook. Can step outside and hit the jump
shot. Can go either way. If I brought him home that time there'd be
a second statue in Faneuil Hall right beside Red (Auerbach), and
that guy would be waving a towel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics may bring a WNBA team to Boston, but it won't be for
another three years. Rick Pond, the Celtics' chief operating
officer, says the team has been doing all of its financial homework
and doesn't have the right formula yet. ``The big drawback is that
most of the (teams) that have WNBA teams own their own buildings.
We don't. We are tenants in the FleetCenter. The present teams in
the WNBA have their own buildings, and the new teams being added
this year all have new buildings. I don't see us being able to do
anything until 2002 at the earliest, but we do have a strong
interest, and if we can make it feasible financially, then we will
want to do it.'' What Pond is saying is that it is much easier for
a team like the Knicks, who are owned by the company that owns
Madison Square Garden, to bring in a women's team, because the
concessions, souvenirs, etc., are all owned by the same entity. In
the FleetCenter, which is owned by Delaware North (which owns the
Bruins), all of the concessions, etc., go to the FleetCenter, not
the Celtics. Therefore, it doesn't make as much sense for the
Celtics to jump into the WNBA right away. In fact, the Celtics were
thinking about putting a WNBA team in Hartford because it would be
cheaper, but the league wants the WNBA squads to play in the same
city as their brother teams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although it has yet to be finalized, Boston College and Notre
Dame have made a deal for seven more football games, which will
stretch the present arrangement to 2013. In the first contract,
Notre Dame got eight games at South Bend with four in Boston. This
time ND gets four in South Bend with three in Boston. Somewhere in
the middle, the teams will not play each other for two years, due
to prior commitments . . . The day after his Bruins were whacked
out of the playoffs by Buffalo, Harry Sinden said Boston will be
willing to spend bigger bucks to land players in free agency. But
assistant general manager Mike O'Connell doesn't see that happening
at this point. ``There is no one that we can see as a free agent
now that would have a lot of interest for us,'' says O'Connell.
``But we are hoping that will change. With so many teams losing
money, we think that some of them might have to let players go
after July 1 to save money that they would not let go otherwise. If
someone pops up after July 1 that we would have an interest in,
then we would be willing to spend big money to get him.'' O'Connell
says the team's first wish would be a scoring forward. He thinks it
is solid in net and on defense. Signing goalie Byron Dafoe,
defenseman Hal Gill, and forward P.J. Axelsson are top priorities .
. . Glenn Foley is a big Keyshawn Johnson fan. Johnson, the Jets'
All-Pro wide receiver, gave Foley and the other New York
quarterbacks each a $15,000 watch for helping him get to the Pro
Bowl last season. In Foley's case, it is a special gesture because
Glenn has been traded to Seattle, and Vinny Testaverde played most
of the time last year . . . Congrats to John Scarpellini of the
Josten's Co. in North Attleborough. Scarpellini pulled a rare
``double'' for the NFL, getting to make the Super Bowl rings for
both the champion Denver Broncos and the runner-up Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
