<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3702 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAEHR05-COX     06-04 1838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAEHR05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A former Atlantan wages a crusade for wholesome films on the
industry's home turf _ and has made some friends there.
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMARILLO, Calif. _ Ted Baehr, actor, lawyer, minister and movie
producer in former lives, uses all those skills and more nowadays
in his attempt to reform the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Baehr, formerly of Atlanta, moved west 2 1/2 years ago to be
near the home court of the Hollywood elite. But he's not standing
on his northern suburban hillside throwing stones. He's come not to
conquer but to convert.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really is a positive light in everyone he touches,'' says
Dick Cook, chairman of the Walt Disney Motion Pictures Group, whose
recent films include ``Tarzan'' and ``A Bug's Life.'' ``He is not
afraid to let you know when he thinks you've done something
inappropriate, but at the same time, he takes the position that if
you honor the good, more good will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook is one of dozens of studio executives and celebrities who
attended Baehr's seventh annual Movieguide Awards Gala at the
Hilton Universal Hotel in Los Angeles this spring. Along with
watching the presentation of statuettes including _ yes _ crystal
teddy bears, attendees got to hear Baehr's annual Report to the
Entertainment Industry. Among its findings:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More films with what Baehr calls a ``strong Christian
worldview'' were released in 1998 than in any of the previous 14
years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Films with little or no sex gross more than twice as much
money as sex-laden films. &QR;  G-rated movies gross, on average, three
times as much as R-rated ones.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremonies will be featured on PAX TV (WPXA in Atlanta) at
10 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Baehr, obviously, has yet to win over the entire industry. Some
insiders criticize him for being too hard-line, while some
Christian colleagues say he's too soft.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeffrey Katzenberg, co-founder of DreamWorks films, asked
Baehr to pull together religious leaders to review ``The Prince of
Egypt.'' Tom Sherak, one of the top executives at 20th Century Fox,
has been known to call. And Cook of Disney considers him a friend.
</P>
<P>
   On any day of the week, Baehr, who maintains offices in both
Atlanta and Camarillo, is likely to be taping his nationally
syndicated radio or television segments, writing material for
Movieguide magazine (also on the Internet at www.movieguide.org),
reviewing screenplays, advising would-be Christian filmmakers,
lecturing at academic or religious events, attending early
screenings of new movies, or chatting with producers or designers
about religious details in their television shows.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls helping the directors of JAG stage a baptism,
suggesting some Scripture for ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman,'' and
giving the makers of ``The Magnificent Seven'' television series
some synonyms for the devil.
</P>
<P>
   He comes to show biz naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Son of an actor
</P>
<P>
   He was born in 1946 to Theodore Baehr, better known as Robert
``Tex'' Allen, the original ``Texas Ranger,'' and his wife, Evelyn
Peirce, an ingenue at MGM. As a child, he performed in commercials,
movies and television, and on stage.
</P>
<P>
   The home where Ted Baehr and his sister were raised was not
religious, although the entire family eventually became Christian.
Baehr had studied at Munich, Cambridge, Bordeaux and Toulouse
universities in Europe, graduated from Dartmouth with a degree in
literature and from New York University School of Law before he
turned his life over to God.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the date and the time: Feb. 12, 1975, at 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   His mother had died when he was 14, and a woman who was dating
his father encouraged him to read the Bible. Feeling nagged by his
father to comply, he agreed to read the New Testament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got as far as Matthew,'' he said _ and then was converted.
</P>
<P>
   Baehr was financing independent films at the time _ mostly
sleazy, he says. He refuses to reveal the titles, but mumbles
something about ``motorcycle gangs.''
</P>
<P>
   He soon decided to go to seminary and enrolled at the Institute
of Theology at the Cathedral of St. John the Divine, an Episcopal
institution. To foot the bills, he took a job as director of the
television center at the City University of New York. There he
first began examining the impact of TV.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, he was elected president of the Atlanta-based Episcopal
Radio-Television Foundation (now the Episcopal Media Center),
which, while he headed it, won an Emmy for ``The Chronicles of
Narnia: The Lion, The Witch and the Wardrobe,'' an animated
special.
</P>
<P>
   By then he had already begun thinking that there should be an
organization to promote Christian values in entertainment. Then, in
1983, while serving on both the communications board of the
mainline National Council of Churches and the evangelical National
Religious Broadcasters, he met George Heimrich.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s and 1960s, as head of the old Protestant Film
Office funded by the National Council of Churches, Heimrich had
served as a kind of Christian lobbyist and consultant with
producers and directors. He warned them of scenes or dialogue that
would be offensive and helped them to be accurate in their
portrayals.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Ken Wales, who made the ``Pink Panther'' movies and
most recently the television series ``Christy,'' introduced the
two.
</P>
<P>
   Studio executives viewed Heimrich just as they would a
historical consultant or an expert on any other subject, said
Wales. ``They saw him as a bright, intelligent friend.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Baehr met Heimrich, the NCC had long since
stopped funding the position.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Wales says, Baehr has filled in the vacuum. ``We're all
very pleased to have his presence out here,'' said Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Baehr has published Movieguide since 1985 to advise parents of
film content. The magazine rates films in two separate categories:
quality and content. ``The Matrix,'' for instance, received four
stars for excellent production quality, but a -2 for acceptability,
with ``discretion advised for adults'' (a +4 is the best rating, a
-4 the worst). ``Body parts all over the place,'' says Baehr.
``It's a symphonic opera of death, a fantasy Columbine world, but
it's very exciting stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Many kids, he says, love it. ``But just because they enjoy it,
it doesn't mean it's appropriate for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sex, violence a concern
</P>
<P>
   On a recent sunny California morning, Baehr sat in his back yard
with his wife and partner, Lili. Around them birds sang, flowers
bloomed and the world seemed serene. Baehr sipped coffee from a mug
featuring a bear wearing moose antlers with the slogan ``Please
Don't Feed the Bears,'' and talked about movies, television,
violence and sex.
</P>
<P>
   In a guesthouse nearby, two employees of Movieguide worked in an
office where even the bathroom was stacked with videotapes and
papers. Prominent in Baehr's own quarters is a poster of his
father, called Papa Baehr by the family, who died last year at 92 _
the same year, coincidentally, that the film world lost two other
famous cowboys, Roy Rogers and Gene Autrey.
</P>
<P>
   When Baehr started his enterprise, it seems most conservatives
were concerned about sex in entertainment and most liberals worried
about violence. Today almost everyone gives lip service to both, he
said, and people on both sides seem to accept that there is some
connection between what people watch and what they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the good news _ everybody's worried about everything,''
he said, ``but nobody's doing anything about it. We want to be
entertained. We're like the Romans going into the Colosseum.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Baehr is out to get every bit of sex and violence
removed from cinema. ``Victorianism is not the answer,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   If only G-rated movies were produced, he points out, there would
be no ``Schindler's List.'' No ``Amistad.'' Baehr advocates getting
the industry ``to adopt standards and stick to them.'' He also
hopes more Christians will acquire the skills to produce their own
films with quality that matches the best on the market.
</P>
<P>
   He sees some indication that many studios are paying more
attention to what they produce, and he sees more avowed Christians
attaining influential positions in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   But those things alone won't be enough, he says. To really
change the culture, people have to become ``media literate'' and
pass it on to their children.
</P>
<P>
   In his own home, he says, he and Lili talk to their four
children, ages 10 to 18, and make sure they know what the family
believes so they can apply discernment to everything they see.
Every parent should do as much, he advises in his book ``The
Media-Wise Family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just engaging their minds and giving them the right questions
to ask can change their attitude about what they're watching,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   But Baehr, mellower than when he began 15 years ago, does not
see a revolution coming. Now, with a $1.2 million annual budget and
a name that gets his telephone calls returned, he still finds
progress slow and hard-won. With every school shooting people ask
the questions again, but they seldom seriously try to find answers,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his yard looking over the flowers, he becomes
pensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably go on to glory and still not have this issue
resolved,'' he concedes.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIEGUIDE'S TAKE ON THREE CURRENT FILMS
</P>
<P>
   The following are excerpts from reviews in Ted Baehr's
Movieguide magazine, billed as ``A Family Guide to Movies and
Entertainment'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrapment''
</P>
<P>
   Production quality:
</P>
<P>
   Moral acceptability: Extreme caution.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the movie premise that it takes a thief to catch a
thief, ``Entrapment'' is a retread of many Hollywood crime dramas
with some fancy special effects scenes, credible acting and
serviceable direction. Containing action violence, many obscenities
and sexual innuendo, this movie portrays the thieves as the good
guys and the FBI as the bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``William Shakespeare's
</P>
<P>
   A Midsummer Night's Dream''
</P>
<P>
   Production quality:
</P>
<P>
   Moral acceptability: Extreme caution.
</P>
<P>
   Featuring a stellar cast, sumptuous photography and art
direction, and a little naughtiness, this is perhaps one of the
most pagan of all Shakespeare's stories as it champions romantic
love in a world of fairies, sexuality and magic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: Episode 1_ The Phantom Menace''
</P>
<P>
   Production
</P>
<P>
   quality:
</P>
<P>
   Moral acceptability: Caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' is an epic symphony based on mythic concepts.
There are constant references to be mindful of the living Force,
which is personalized in this episode. In terms of action and plot,
``The Phantom Menace'' is comfortably PG. What is threatening is
the New Age philosophy that creeps into this movie all too
frequently. Concerned parents whose children demand to see it
should see ``Star Wars'' with their children to help them think
through the movie's theology.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
