<HEADER>
A3703 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUMMY-DNA06-COX     06-04 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUMMY-DNA06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: Embagoed for Sunday June 6.
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Michael C. Carlos Museum may have acquired more
than it bargained for with its recent purchase of a $2 million
Egyptian mummy collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a possibility _ and at this point it is only a
possibility _ that one of our new mummies might be Rameses I,''
says Museum Director Anthony Hirschel. ``If that is the case, this
would be the only royal mummy outside of Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   The curatorial coup that brought the world-class collection to
the Emory University campus last month has rekindled interest in
one of archaeology's great unsolved mysteries _ the disappearance,
probably sometime in the 1800s, of the remains of Rameses I,
founder of one of ancient Egypt's most powerful dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   Where did his mummy go? Who spirited him away from his tomb in
central Egypt? No one knows for sure. But Carlos museum officials
are wondering if one of the 10 mummies they recently acquired from
the Niagara Falls Museum in Canada might be the missing patriarch
of Egypt's 19th dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   On the off chance that the mummy now lying in stiff repose in
the museum's climate-controlled storeroom is Rameses I, museum
officials this week began drafting an ambitious research plan _ and
moved to pre-empt any possible political fallout before it occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Although dozens of museums around the world own mummies, Egypt
looks upon the remains of its royalty much as the United States
does its dead presidents: They belong at home.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt has an uneven record of enforcing its antiquities laws,
but it has always been adamant about its pharaohs. The museum room
in Cairo that contains their remains is sealed by presidential
decree.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this turns out to be Rameses I, the right thing to do would
be to reunite him with the other royal mummies in Egypt,'' Hirschel
said. ``A royal mummy could be a terrific draw for our museum, but
if this really is Rameses I, there is absolutely no question that
we will do the right thing. We will send him home where he
belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials are in the process of notifying Egyptian
authorities and the Cairo Museum _ which holds the mummies of
Rameses I's son and grandson, Seti I, and Rameses II, one of
Egypt's most reknowned pharaohs _ of their suspicions about the
possible identity of the mummy.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschel hopes the Carlos museum's voluntary expression of good
intentions will help enlist Egypt's assistance in identifying the
mummy _ and, if it should prove to be Rameses I, might merit some
reciprocal gesture, like the loan of other Egyptian antiquities for
exhibit in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Any successful investigation would have to be built on evidence
_ scientific, archival and anecdotal _ that bridges the gap between
the late 20th century and the age of the pharaohs.
</P>
<P>
   Like all good detective stories, though, the search for answers
promises to be as intriguing as the answers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the notion that the mummy of Rameses I somehow
found its way out of Egypt's Valley of the Kings to Atlanta, with a
stopover in Niagara Falls, Canada, is based on incomplete,
unsubstantiated and circumstantial evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But officials hope that a battery of tests _ including emerging
molecular genetics techniques that may make it possible to compare
the DNA of the mummy with that of Rameses I's descendants in the
Cairo Museum _ will tell them who the mummy is. Or, at least, who
he is not.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of all the attention, a 5-foot-5 mummified male _
museum accession number 1999.1.4 _ now lies swathed in mounds of
archival quality plastic wrap in a simple cardboard box in the
storeroom of the Carlos museum. His skin is taut and blackened by
the plant resins used to embalm him. He is naked, head tilted back,
mouth open and arms crossed over his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crossed arms are usually reserved for royalty,'' said
Peter Lacovara, curator of ancient art for the museum. ``And the
scar that was left when he was eviscerated for embalming is
consistent with what we see in other mummies from around 1500 B.C.
to 1200 B.C., a period that includes the reign of Rameses I.''
</P>
<P>
   A radioactive carbon test performed in Canada several years ago
also suggests that the mummy is about 3,200 years old, give or take
a few hundred years.
</P>
<P>
   Lacovara says the mummy's facial features bear uncanny
resemblance to those of Seti I, his son and successor to the
throne.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crossed arms do suggest that he was a member of a royal
family,'' agreed Gayle Gibson, staff member of the Royal Ontario
Museum and president of the Society for the Study of Egyptian
Antiquities, who studied the collection when it was in Canada. ``If
that's the case, given what is known about the time and place that
these mummies were collected in Egypt, he could very well be
Rameses I.''
</P>
<P>
   The mummy collection, owned by the Niagara Falls Museum for
nearly 140 years, was assembled in the 1860s by Col. Sydney
Barnett, son of the founder of the museum. He acquired the mummies
during a visit to Thebes, in Egypt's Valley to the Kings, in 1861,
at a time when the thirst for Egyptian antiquities abroad was
fueling an epidemic of tomb robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Just how he acquired the mummies and managed to circumvent
Egypt's 1835 ban on the export of antiquities is unclear. Until
this year they remained the property of the Canadian museum.
</P>
<P>
   Rameses I's tomb was found in the same area, near Luxor, about
35 years earlier, but the whereabouts of the pharaoh's remains were
never determined. Egyptologists believe it may have been looted in
ancient times, or moved to a safer location, a secret cache for
royal mummies at Deir-el-Bahri in western Thebes.
</P>
<P>
   Tomb robbers were raiding that cache repeatedly within a decade
or so of Barnett's visit to the area. Looting and the sale of
artifacts in the area was so rampant that in 1881, Egyptian
authorities moved the rest of the royal remains to Cairo for
safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barnett was in the right area of Egypt at about the right
time,'' says Hirschel. ``We are trying to obtain more detailed
records of his collecting. We hope they'll tell us more.''
</P>
<P>
   More telling evidence, however, may come from just across
campus, where the laboratory headed by Douglas Wallace, of Emory's
Center for Molecular Medicine, has pioneered the use of new
technology for the study of human genetic roots.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's discoveries about the origins of prehistoric people in
America, which can be read in the genetic traits of modern Native
American populations, are helping overturn popular theories about
the peopling of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   After conferring with Carlos museum officials this week, Wallace
says he is excited about the opportunity to see if emerging DNA
analytical techniques can provide a positive ID for a
3,000-year-old mummy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, I would have said it was impossible. But now,
with some of the new techniques that have just become available, I
think the probability of success is great enough that it will make
the investment of time and money required worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the DNA in humans' Y-chromosome is passed from father to
son virtually unchanged, Wallace says, at least in theory genetic
material from the mummies in Cairo _ the son and grandson of
Rameses I _ could be used to determine whether they are related to
the mummy in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But there are major hurdles to be overcome. Mitochondrial DNA,
which is passed on maternally from generation to generation, is
hardier and more plentiful in ancient tissue than that of the
Y-chromosome. But all of the mummies in question are males.
</P>
<P>
   Using a process called polymerase chain reaction, scientists can
amplify even minute quantities of genetic material. But because the
magnification process also magnifies the DNA from any modern
contaminants, the need for purity is paramount. The best source for
uncontaminated DNA may be the tissue inside one of the mummy's
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace says the research will require a willingness by Egyptian
authorities to make their mummies available for testing _ and
background testing of living Egyptians to determine what kind of
normal genetic variation exists in the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to raise false hope,'' he said. ``There may be no
good DNA in this mummy. It's not like taking a blood sample. This
will be a long, and very careful process that will require many
steps, with no certainty that it will give us an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Toner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
