<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDVEDEV BESTS NERVES, CRAMPS, AND A NO-HOPE REPUTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Suddenly Andrei!
</P>
<P>
   For the many followers of the little bald-headed, pigeon-toed
guy from Las Vegas with the same-sounding name _ the former
roommate of ``Suddenly Susan'' TV diva Brooke Shields _ it was the
wrong one. It was bulky Ukrainian Andrei Medvedev holding a
reservation in the French Open final, and not _ not yet, anyway
_Andre Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it was Medvedev who became the symbol of love
conquering all, and not Agassi, whose highly hyped romance with
Shields has bageled out. Love's labor was not lost, after all, for
Medvedev. Nor was Friday's totally unexpected semifinal with a
delightfully loosey-goosey Brazilian, Fernando Meligeni, a 7-5,
3-6, 6-4, 7-6 (8-6) Medvedev victory in which the Ukrainian had to
squirm out of five set points in the 10th game of the opening set
and another in the tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   While his reclaimed lady love, Anke Huber, smiled on him from a
courtside box (as the sun refused to do), Medvedev overcame nerves,
cramps, and a no-hope reputation to get past the barrier where he'd
crashed six years before. He also beat the rain that was bound to
leak from mean, smoky clouds, and, ranking No. 100, is in position
to become the longest-shot champ in French annals. Nice.
</P>
<P>
   His adversary in Sunday's final is a mystery because the
downpour chased Agassi and Dominik Hrbaty, plus 16,000 onlookers,
from Stade Roland Garros.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Agassi was threatened. Yes, he did end the day in the
lead, 6-4, 7-6 (8-6), 3-6, 1-2, and he will be serving when they
return Saturday at noon for the conclusion of their semifinal, an
appetizer for the women's title clash between a phoenix named
Steffi Graf and a phenom named Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Las Vegas Andre is that the slugging Slovak,
21-year-old Hrbaty, acts intimidated not a bit. He pounced when it
seemed he was finished, with Agassi gripping a break point for a
3-1 edge in the third. With those coal yard clouds practically on
his shoulder, Agassi was trying too hard to get it suddenly over,
and he made mistakes that resulted in him and Hrbaty stewing all
night with their fates dangling in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   No such bad luck for the Andrei from Kiev, suddenly restored
because ``my game and Anke came back to me. I don't know why God
did this for me, in the city where I had my first big success, but
I have never been so happy in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   A chirpy 18-year-old in 1993, Medvedev beat Stefan Edberg to
make the semis, then stalled against the champ-to-be, Sergi
Bruguera. For a time, he inhaled the heady atmosphere at No. 4. He
fell for Huber, a German top-10 habitue, and made a lot of money _
``more than anybody I know in Kiev ever see.'' Life was good for
the big kid, a 6-foot-4-inch, 200-pounder. But Huber dumped him,
injuries cut in, and his tennis and ranking went south.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky to get in this year, No. 100,'' he said. ``But I
have put in the work, the game has come together, and Anke and I
are together again. I'm not saying if we'll be married soon, or
when, but you will have plenty of notice to buy presents.''
</P>
<P>
   What were Hrbaty (No. 30), Meligeni (No. 54), and the centurion
Medvedev doing in the French semis anyway, along with
twice-flunking finalist (1990, '91) Aggasi, who ranks No. 14? It's
been a wonderfully wacky fortnight, that's all, an indication that
nobody is safe in the male precinct these days.
</P>
<P>
   Hrbaty had already rid the place of No. 1 Yevgeny Kafelnikov,
the 1996 champ, and another favorite, Marcelo Rios. Meligeni bumped
off US Open champ Patrick Rafter and 1998 runner-up Alex Corretja.
Medvedev took care of Pete Sampras, 1997 champ Guga Kuerten, and
then Guga's countryman, Meligeni. ``I don't think I can get a visa
for Brazil,'' Medvedev said.
</P>
<P>
   Scratch Meligeni and you may find Al Pacino in ``Dog Day
Afternoon.'' There's an uncanny facial resemblance. A wispy court
clown, he's 140 pounds of pantomimist, grimacer, and pure
enjoyment, a lefthander (naturally) and ``very happy to be playing
in France,'' he said. ``The crowd know a lot about tennis, not just
coming to watch and say, `Who's this guy?' Everyone knows everyone
who's playing, 128 players. Is very good feeling in center court,
and you feel everybody's cheering for you, like you are a good
player, a nice guy. This is important for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It is suddenly important for Agassi to spring off the mark
Saturday to avoid a repeat of a dog day afternoon in 1991, when a
rain interruption (though not overnight) soaked his title bid
against Jim Courier. Andre led, 6-3, 3-1, then lost in five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' said Agassi's coach, Brad Gilbert, ``it's not gonna
happen that way. The passion's back in his game.''
</P>
<P>
   You could say the same for the other Andrei and his Anke.
Successful again, suddenly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
