<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY MOVES ONE BIG STEP CLOSER TO SENATE BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After months of conjecture and nearly a dozen visits to New York
state, Hillary Rodham Clinton said Friday that in July she would
take the first formal step toward running for the Senate from New
York, registering an exploratory committee with the Federal
Election Commission. Her aides said that would almost certainly
lead to her becoming the first first lady to run for federal
office.
</P>
<P>
   For all the tumult that has surrounded Mrs. Clinton's political
future these past six months, the first lady confirmed her
intentions _ which were by now something short of a surprise _ in a
quiet, almost matter-of-fact voice in the midst of the ``Good
Morning America'' TV program broadcast from the White House. Mrs.
Clinton answered a question posed by Diane Sawyer during a
commercial break; ABC played a tape of the exchange as soon as the
program went back on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to open an exploratory committee in July,'' Mrs.
Clinton said. ``And than I'll spend some time _ a lot of time _ in
New York listening to people, and I'm looking forward to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's announcement would appear to end a political and
semantic furor that had engaged politicians and reporters from the
first time her name was mentioned as a possible candidate in
February. It was the first time that the first lady herself had
expressed such intentions publicly, and it was the first time that
anyone in her camp had described her plans without any qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, who has enjoyed the largely uncritical attention
that comes from being an unannounced candidate, seemed to reveal
her intentions earlier than she might have liked, and with less
pageantry than normally accompanies such announcements. Her
comments came a day after Rep. Nita Lowey, the Westchester County
Democrat who had said she would run for the Senate if Mrs. Clinton
did not, announced that she would run for reelection because she
was convinced that the first lady was running.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, some Democrats said Mrs. Clinton ran a risk of
appearing coy if she continued to assert that she had not decided
whether to form an exploratory committee, even as she continued to
make trips to New York and her aides were saying the decision about
the committee was all but certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had to put it to bed after yesterday,'' said Lisa Caputo,
her former press secretary and longtime adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's announcement does not signal an actual change
in her timetable. Mrs. Clinton is to return to New York next
Wednesday, but then is traveling to Europe and the Mideast for the
remainder of the month. She will formally establish the exploratory
committee upon her return, and then begin traveling across the
state in July and August, meeting with voters in what will probably
be formats similar to the town hall meetings that have been used so
frequently by her husband.
</P>
<P>
   The visits are part of a concerted effort to deflect what has
been the main attack against her by Republicans: That the first
lady, who has never lived in New York, has little knowledge of the
state that she wants to represent.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Ickes, Mrs. Clinton's main political strategist, said
that it was very possible that the exploratory committee would, as
allowed by law, consist of one person _ the treasurer, who would be
charged with keeping the committee's books. Notwithstanding the
name, the committee's real purpose would be to allow her to collect
campaign contributions that would go to financing her travels in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, those trips have been paid for by either taxpayers or
local political committees; Mrs. Clinton has come under some
criticism for that.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding its lack of formality, Mrs. Clinton's
announcement Friday offered her most prominent possible Republican
opponent, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a stark illustration of
the artillery that the first lady will be able to command in a run
for office.
</P>
<P>
   Most candidates who make such announcements have to rent a
ballroom, hang banners and hope that reporters will arrive to
chronicle the events. Mrs. Clinton spoke on national television
from the White House, with the president at her side, during the
broadcast of a segment of Good Morning America devoted to guns,
children and violence.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani announced his own exploratory committee six weeks
ago, it was briefly noted in most of the state's newspapers and
television stations. By contrast, Mrs. Clinton's statement was
moved as an urgent dispatch on the Associated Press wire shortly
after ABC televised the snippet.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's announcement also immediately rallied her
opponents, who for now at least seem to be focusing on the
carpetbagger issue. State Assemblyman Dov Hikind, a Brooklyn
Democrat who has often sided with Republicans, said that he would
devote his weekly radio show to rallying his supporters to urge
Mrs. Clinton to stay out of the race. ``New York's issues are not
Arkansas' issues or Illinois issues,'' Hikind said.
</P>
<P>
   The Star-Gazette of Elmira, N.Y., took sarcastic note of the
fact that Mrs. Clinton had boasted during a visit to Manhattan this
week that she had ``been to Elmira,'' offering an article based on
interviews with longtime Democratic leaders who could not recall
seeing the first lady in their part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's press secretary, Marsha Berry, offered an
explanation after checking with the first lady. ``She was in Elmira
probably 40 years ago,'' Ms. Berry said. ``On a family excursion
between Chicago and Scranton.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
