<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-MENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDVEDEV, A FRENCH OPEN FINALIST, CAN FEEL THE LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ First the course of true love finally did run smooth for
Andrei Medvedev, the decidedly romantic giant from Ukraine who
reunited with his longtime paramour, Anke Huber, just before the
French Open began. And once his heart felt lighter, Medvedev's
moribund career took a turn for the brighter.
</P>
<P>
   After barely squeaking into the main draw, a break he described
as ``a minor miracle'' for a former top 10 player ranked 100th,
Medvedev has bulldozed through his half of the draw, taking down
some big names along the way. In Friday's semifinal against
Fernando Meligeni, a clay-covered 140-pound gnat of a man, Medvedev
soldiered through his 2-hour-59-minute assignment with due
diligence but little brilliance and emerged the winner, 7-5, 3-6,
6-4, 7-6 (8-6).
</P>
<P>
   It is the first Grand Slam final for the 24-year-old Medvedev,
who had not distinguished himself at a major tournament since
reaching the 1993 semifinals here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a second birth to me,'' said Medvedev, whose
six-match rampage has featured upsets of second-seeded Pete Sampras
and eighth-seeded Gustavo Kuerten, the Brazilian who won here in
1997 and had been predicted to do so again this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been out of the competitive tennis for a long time,''
Medvedev said. ``Now to be back, but not by accident, it feels
great.''
</P>
<P>
   But Medvedev slept poorly on the eve of this semifinal despite
the calming advice of Huber, a Grand Slam finalist herself at the
1996 Australian Open, and he figured to experience another restless
night tonight because he did not know the identity of his next
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   While Medvedev and Meligeni were able to complete their match
despite intermittent rain, 13th-seeded Andre Agassi and 30th-ranked
Dominik Hrbaty had just entered the fourth set when a stubborn
system of showers settled in for the evening. Play was suspended
with Agassi out in front but no longer exerting complete control,
leading the 21-year-old Slovak by 6-4, &QC; 7-6 (8-6), 3-6, 1-2.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi's poor third set, which he opened by dropping his serve
and concluded by being broken on a backhand return on Hrbaty's
third set point, transformed what had looked to be a triumph of
experience over inexperience into an overnight cliffhanger.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, the French Open runner-up in 1990 and 1991, is battling
to reach his first Grand Slam final since he won the 1995
Australian Open. With a title here, Agassi would become the first
man to win all four Grand Slam crowns in his career since Rod Laver
did it in a single season, in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Medvedev, who has hedged his bets and called his chances 50-50
against anybody in this field, said he was so happy to be in the
final, he did not really care which opponent came his way. ``I
think I can beat both of them, but that will take everything I've
got,'' he said. ``It's not going to be easy. Like I've said, I've
surpassed my expectations by a mile. I cannot lose, basically. Even
if lose, I would still be the happiest man on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it achieved the desired result, Medvedev's semifinal form
was far from perfect. He survived 85 unforced errors and a 0-4
beginning, not to mention the fact that his irrepressible Brazilian
opponent, who played with a liberal amount of histrionics and
comedy worthy of a Marx Brothers routine, actually won two more
points than he did.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4-inch Medvedev, to whom scrambling around the court
does not come as naturally as it does to Meligeni, also suffered
from cramping in the third and fourth sets and eventually required
a double dose of medication, plus some smelling salts, from a
trainer.
</P>
<P>
   When the trainer, Doug Spreen, balked at handing out a second
dose, Medvedev talked him into cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me one; it didn't work,'' Medvedev said. ``I said,
`I'm a double guy, give me one more,' and he did, and then the
cramps were gone. And he also brought me the towel with the smell
where you get awake even if you're dead. I think he did a great job
on me. Thank God I'm not doing doping control today.''
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's women's final, sixth-seeded Steffi Graf, a
five-time champion here, takes on top-seeded Martina Hingis, the
18-year-old with a now-or-never attitude toward capturing the only
Grand Slam to evade her. Graf, 29, has not won a Grand Slam title
since the 1996 U.S. Open and came into this one with misgivings
about her durability. Graf boasts the best record against Hingis of
any player, leading her by 6-2, but the German lost their only
meeting on clay and lost to Hingis, 3-6, 6-2, 6-4, in their most
recent match, at the Pan Pacific quarterfinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can beat anybody,'' Graf said. ``I obviously feel I
don't have to prove anything; I think that's going to work for
me.'' Even though Hingis has hinted that Graf is over the hill, she
has yet to beat her at a Grand Slam event, where she is 0 for 3. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
