<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-HEARINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELMS SAYS COMMITTEE READY TO HOLD HEARINGS ON HOLBROOKE'S
NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee announced Friday that the panel was ready to hold
hearings on the long-stalled nomination of Richard Holbrooke as the
chief American diplomat at the United Nations. But the senator made
it clear that the nomination was anything but a sure bet.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who is a leading critic
of the United Nations, said in a statement that the panel would
hold four hearings beginning on June 17 and that Holbrooke would be
carefully questioned about his career, particularly his role as
mediator with President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia in
negotiating the Bosnia accords.
</P>
<P>
   Helms said that the committee would explore in detail
Holbrooke's ``role and responsibility for this administration's
misguided policy of appeasing Slobodan Milosevic,'' a comment that
also seemed to suggest that the hearings could be a vehicle for
closer scrutiny of administration policies in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's statement also alluded to the ethics inquiries
that were the subject of an investigation by the Justice Department
that delayed the nomination for eight months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must confess that I cannot recall another Cabinet-level
nomination sent to this committee with so much ethical baggage
attached to it,'' Helms said. The federal inquiry ended in
February, when Holbrooke agreed to pay $5,000 to the government to
settle civil accusations that he had violated federal lobbying laws
in his role at an investment banking firm that he joined after
leaving the State Department. Holbrooke has denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they welcomed the announcement of
the hearings, despite the tone of Helms' statement. They had feared
that Helms might kill the nomination by refusing to hold
confirmation hearings, just as he killed the nomination of William
F. Weld, a former governor of Massachusetts, as ambassador to
Mexico in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have long said they are willing to
endure harsh criticism of Balkans policies and other issues because
they believed that the nomination enjoyed broad bipartisan support
and that Holbrooke would be easily confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic congressional officials said they were pleased that
Helms had decided to devote just one of the four hearing days to
the Balkans, because that would limit the chance that the hearings
might become a vehicle for a full-scale Republican assault on the
administration policies which led to 10 weeks of airstrikes on
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, architect of the 1995 peace settlement that halted
the war in Bosnia and Herzegovina, has been the administration's
principal envoy to Milosevic, serving in that role part time while
continuing to work at the Credit Suisse First Boston investment
banking firm.
</P>
<P>
   The ranking Democratic on the Foreign Relations Committee, Sen.
Joseph Biden of Delaware, said he hoped the nomination would be
approved by the end of the month and sent to the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Helms has made the right call in moving this
nomination forward,'' he said. ``We need Dick Holbrooke in New
York. The United Nations will play an important role in helping to
end the conflict in Kosovo, and I can't think of anyone better than
Dick Holbrooke to safeguard our interests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
