<SLUG> BC-MIT-CLICKCLACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM `CAR TALK' TO COMMENCEMENT CHATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ When MIT's president announced the names of
this year's commencement day speakers April 1, he had to assure the
public that it wasn't an April Fools' Day hoax. Tom and Ray
Magliozzi? Huh?
</P>
<P>
   But the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, which last year
had President Clinton deliver its commencement address, wasn't
kidding. Click and Clack, the irrepressible hosts of National
Public Radio's call-in show, ``Car Talk,'' were on.
</P>
<P>
   And so, Friday, there they were, America's most beloved auto
mechanics, side-by-side on the dais incongruously clad in black
faille robes with velvet trim and eight-sided black tams. For 45
rambling minutes, the Magliozzis dished out their folksy brand of
slapstick. The speech was twice as long as it was supposed to be
and was punctuated by their guffaws, which echoed across Killian
Court like an old Chevy backfiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have spent the last four, five or six years working in the
wrong direction,'' Tom Magliozzi told the 2,087 undergraduate and
graduate students, who included budding particle physicists,
nuclear engineers, aeronautics experts, and economists. ``You are
sliding down the razor blade of life. You must stop this from
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Using graphs, the Magliozzis sought to demonstrate that there
was an inverse relationship between intelligence and happiness. One
of the graphs purported to show that humans were the least happy of
all living things, followed in order of rising happiness by golden
retrievers, cows, worms. At the top of the list was grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always thought we were the highest form of life on the
planet,'' said Tom. ``It turns out we're the lowest.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the big questions surrounding the event concerned the
Magliozzi brothers' choice of transport (Clinton arrived last year
by helicopter). The Magliozzis envisioned a more modest entrance in
Tom's red 1952 MG-TD.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom wanted to take the MG but it wasn't starting this month,''
said ``Car Talk'' producer Doug Berman, who added that MIT was
unwilling to delay graduation until the vehicle was resuscitated.
</P>
<P>
   So how'd they get there?
</P>
<P>
   ``Their wives drove them,'' said Berman. ``They said they
couldn't bear the embarrassment if they broke down on the way.''
</P>
<P>
   That the speech even happened is testament to the terrier-like
persistence of the Magliozzis and the good humor of MIT President
Charles M. Vest.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Magliozzis, who are both MIT graduates, have been
goodnaturedly teasing MIT on their radio show about the ``relative
unknowns'' who have been delivering MIT commencement addresses _
``nobodies'' like UN Secretary General Kofi Annan, Vice President
Al Gore, and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Vest politely rebuffed their overtures, saying they'd only be
considered as speakers if they brought their own flag. The UN, he
noted jokingly, had ``a really spiffy flag.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If `Car Talk' . . . had possessed a similarly attractive
flag,'' Vest wrote in a letter to the Magliozzis, ``we might have
been able to use you, but, as it was, we felt that we really had to
go with the secretary general for aesthetic reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Magliozzis prevailed after they designed their own flag.
</P>
<P>
   As they spoke Friday, the 4-by-6-foot banner fluttered behind
them. It was adorned with a seal that commemorated the rear of
Tom's recently departed 1963 Dodge Dart, complete with a raccoon
tail on the trunk. The flag was emblazoned with the slogan ``Non
Impediti Ratione Cogitantonis.''
</P>
<P>
   In closing their talk, the pair tried to get the audience to
repeat the English translation of the slogan: ``Unencumbered by the
thought process.''
</P>
<P>
   They signed off with their usual flourish. ``Don't drive like my
brother,'' they chimed.
</P>
</TEXT>
