<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC IS PREPARED IN BID FOR TRIPLE CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ It was 5:30 on a clear, cool and quiet morning at
Belmont Park. D. Wayne Lukas led Charismatic out of his barn as the
first horse entering the track on the day before battle _ just as
he expected Charismatic to be first in the 131st Belmont Stakes on
Saturday before a crowd of more than 80,000 at Belmont Park, and
complete his dramatic surge from claimer to the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The chestnut colt galloped one mile and three-quarters, which is
a quarter of a mile more than he will race in the historic main
event Saturday. Then the trainer said all was right in
Charismatic's world, and pronounced him fully prepared to take the
final step on the road to riches: $600,000 as the winner's share of
the purse plus $5 million as a bonus for sweeping the three
classics for 3-year-old horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like his old self,'' Lukas said. ``I don't see
anything different than going into the Preakness or the Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing and winning every couple of weeks, Charismatic has spun a
romantic tale that is hard to match in modern racing: ignored as a
claimer in California as late as February, fourth in the Santa
Anita Derby on April 3, first in the Lexington Stakes on April 18,
first in the Kentucky Derby at 31-1 on May 1, first in the
Preakness at 8-1 on May 15 and favored at 2-1 to win the Belmont
and make history June 5.
</P>
<P>
   To do it, he will have to outrun one fine filly,
Silverbulletday, and 10 colts, including Menifee, who ran closest
to him in the Derby (by a neck) and in the Preakness (by a length
and a half). So, for the third consecutive year, the Belmont will
feature a horse shooting for the Triple Crown. In 1997, Silver
Charm lost a thriller to Touch Gold, and in 1998, Real Quiet lost
by a whisker to Victory Gallop. Only 11 horses in racing history
have completed the sweep; 14 have failed when they lost the
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   A fair and pleasant day was forecast with temperatures in the
70s, something like Friday, when Charismatic led the way onto the
track for his morning exercise. He handled the Belmont surface
gracefully and drew cheers from his trainer, who is still searching
for his first Triple Crown sweep with one horse although he has won
12 classics and at one point had won six Triple Crown races in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charismatic goes off with the first set of horses whether it's
here, California, Kentucky or wherever,'' Lukas said, explaining
their early hours. ``We always try to get them on the track when
it's freshly harrowed. We think that's the best time. It's a
routine we've followed with all of our good horses over the
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Menifee was an early riser, too, jogging three-quarters of a
mile and then galloping a mile and a quarter. His trainer, Elliott
Walden, who also trained Victory Gallop in his memorable Triple
Crown sequence, said that his main concern Saturday would be the
lack of early speed to set things up for late closers like Menifee,
who was the second choice in the race at 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a front-runner in there,'' Walden said.
``If there's not a true front-runner, sometimes you wind up with a
slower pace than you really like. Menifee might sit closer to the
pace than usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he confessed to being ``talked out,'' and said: ``It's time
to be quiet and let the horse run.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday, third choice at 4-1, has won eight straight
races and 11 of 12 in her career, but she will be racing colts for
the first time. She will attempt to become only the third filly to
win the Belmont in 131 years, and the first since Tanya in 1905.
She got to the track early, too, and galloped a mile and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's sharp; she's doing great,'' said her trainer, Bob
Baffert. ``Whether the fuel light comes on turning for home, we
won't know until the race. Distance is the only question. She can
handle it with a certain kind of pace. She's healthy, she's happy,
she's on her toes.''
</P>
<P>
   Best of Luck, who won the Peter Pan Stakes two weeks ago, walked
the grounds Friday and will gallop over the main track Saturday
morning as he gets ready for the Belmont Stakes. His trainer, Allen
Jerkens, one of the foremost horsemen in New York, has started only
two horses in the Belmont but has never won it. Virginia Rapids ran
fifth in 1993 and Limit Out ran ninth last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows there are people coming around looking at him all the
time,'' Jerkens said. ``He's got a shot. The key to most races is
pace, especially for a closer like Best of Luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Belmont will open its gates at 8:30 on Saturday morning for its
day of days. The first race goes off at 12:30, the Belmont Stakes
at 5:27. The rest is up to Charismatic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
