<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN GUNDY'S GRIPES MAKE PACERS GROAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As expected, Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy's portrayal of the
Pacers as whimpering whiners did not go over big in Indiana. Mark
Jackson and Reggie Miller were among several Pacers who fired
verbal shots at the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's practice in Indianapolis, Jackson was asked if he
wanted to say anything about Van Gundy's comments.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson replied: ``Nothing, just them being what they said we
were: a bunch of babies, a nursery and whining. There's no time for
crying and complaining. Just play basketball. That's something I
expected from Phil Jackson, not Jeff Van Gundy.''
</P>
<P>
   With Game 3 Saturday night at New York's Madison Square Garden,
the gamesmanship _ well, paranoia _ grows. The Knicks and the
Pacers have a contentious subplot to support their on-court battle.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy's comments came after the Knicks were whistled for 40
fouls on Tuesday in Game 2, including controversial calls against
Marcus Camby and Chris Childs in the final minutes. The comments
also came after the Pacers took umbrage with some of the Knicks'
physical tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the team that's physical,'' said Van Gundy, who
spoke to Rod Thorn, the league's senior vice president of
basketball operations, regarding the calls. ``They've got the
physical players.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Bird was asked if he had any gripes about Van
Gundy's assessment. ``Everything but the bully part,'' he said, his
voice thick with sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said: ``There's no whining on our part. I think
everything is coming from their camp. If they're going to call Rod
Thorn and beg for calls, they need to look at themselves in the
mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton Wowed by Turnaround
</P>
<P>
   Bill Walton has been amazed at the Knicks' transformation. He is
so impressed with their speed in the open court that he gives them
an advantage over the Pacers even without Patrick Ewing. But Walton
is putting the responsibility on the Knick players, especially the
nonstarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these guys have been whining about shots and
complaining about not getting enough time for most of the season,''
he said. ``Now it's their time to prove whether they can play well
without Patrick.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton admires the Knicks' resilience, but he is not a huge fan
of Larry Johnson's self-congratulatory ``L'' sign for 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a former college player of the year, a
two-time All-Star, a guy who needs no introduction,'' Walton said.
``It makes no sense. Can you imagine Michael Jordan wasting his
time with that, or Dr. J? Bring some class and dignity to the
proceedings. I'm sorry, I just don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Are Players at Fault, Too?
</P>
<P>
   When Larry Johnson entered the locker room after Game 2, he had
been the victim of a beer-dousing from the Market Square Arena
stands. In another incident, Chris Childs and Kurt Thomas traded
obscenities with courtside patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants to talk to the fans while we're trying to play
ball, let him talk to the fans,'' the Pacers' Derrick McKey said,
referring to Childs' altercation with a young fan during the game.
``If you're talking to the fans and feeding into that, sometimes
you've got to expect other things happening from the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackson added: ``If they did that, then they're just as
much to blame as the fans. Now it's different if there are two
jerks behind our bench being disrespectful, tasteless, and we
counter what they did. But if we add to it and go back and forth
with them, then we're just as much to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers are preparing for a similar deluge Saturday night at
the Garden. Reggie Miller's gum-flapping aside, the Pacers do not
want to behave like the Knicks, who some Pacers think brought the
crowd-control problems upon themselves. Antonio Davis and Jackson
have made public pleas for fans to restrain their venomous behavior
for Game 5 in Indianapolis on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not right,'' Jackson said. ``That can't be accepted. I
make a plea to our fans to not let that happen again, because it's
a reflection on all of us. That's not fair and that's tasteless.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Garden fans, he added: ``Hopefully, they won't react and
try something like that. If they do, so be it. But we certainly
don't condone behavior like that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
