u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-STRATEGY-BOS &LR;      06-04 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-STRATEGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIZING UP THE CLASH: CLINTON VS. GIULIANI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's the out-of-towner vs. the schoolyard bully, the
PLO partisan vs. the narrow-minded cop-coddler, the limousine
liberal vs. the scab.
</P>
<P>
   It's the upcoming New York Senate race _ first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton vs. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani _ and you can already
hear the lips smacking over the brickbats and catcalls to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three things are certain,'' said pollster Maurice Carroll,
reflecting the consensus. ``The race will be close, it will be
nasty, and, oh boy, will it be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Friday confirmed what her political adviser, Harold
Ickes, let slip the day before _ that sometime next month she will
start an exploratory committee for a Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani jabbed, ``She should spend some time exploring New
York,'' a not-so-veiled reference to the fact that the first lady
has never lived here.
</P>
<P>
   And so, as the announcer says at Belmont, ``They're off!''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show a neck-and-neck race, with Clinton ahead in New York
City, Giuliani ahead in the suburbs, and the contest suspensefully
close in the vast land mass called ``upstate.''
</P>
<P>
   The curious thing is that the two agree on most of the
hot-button issues dividing Republicans and Democrats elsewhere.
Both favor gun control, capital punishment, abortion rights, gay
rights, and immigration.
</P>
<P>
   One peculiarity of New York politics is that whatever issues end
up inflaming this election, they do so for their appeal or
repellency to various ethnic groups, which tend to vote in blocs.
</P>
<P>
   Education is the biggest issue raised to date. Clinton recently
spoke out against school vouchers. She never mentioned Giuliani,
but her audience knew the mayor advocates vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Sheinkopf, a Democratic consultant who supports but does
not work for Clinton, said, ``Opposing vouchers will hurt her with
Catholics, who know what parochial schools are about and wouldn't
mind being given the choice to send their kids there instead of to
the local public school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teachers' union will open their phone banks for her,'' he
went on, ``but Rudy will get the Catholic vote, and the Catholic
vote in this state is crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton opposes the shutdown of municipal
hospitals, which Giuliani wants to privatize. This helps her not
only with still more pools of union activists, but with many black
and Hispanic voters, who cannot afford private care.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, like her husband, enjoys overwhelming support among
these minority groups. Giuliani has never been very popular there,
and he lost further ground after the police shooting of an unarmed
West African immigrant, Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Clinton leading among blacks by an astonishing 96-4,
with virtually nobody undecided _ suggesting she could stimulate an
unusually high turnout from these groups.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton advisers note she must strengthen her base of support,
which is New York City _ and boosting turnout among blacks and
Hispanics, who together comprise over half its population, is
critical.
</P>
<P>
   However, they also note she needs to cut into Giuliani's edge
upstate and in the suburbs, where she is largely untested.
</P>
<P>
   One electoral model might be Democrat Charles Schumer's
impressive 54-45 victory over three-term Republican incumbent
Alfonse D'Amato in last year's Senate contest.
</P>
<P>
   However, Schumer won three-quarters of New York City, probably
more than Clinton can swing against Giuliani. And he split the
suburbs, another big challenge.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato also ran a miserable campaign, as evidenced by his
winning just one-quarter of the downstate Jewish vote _ as opposed
to the 40 percent he had always won before. Last time out, he
alienated many Jews by trying to politicize his support of the
Holocaust Museum, calling Schumer by an awkwardly constructed
Yiddish vulgarity, and caricaturing Jerrold Nadler, an overweight
Jewish congressman, as ``Jerry Wadler.'' Nor did it help that
Schumer is Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, on the other hand, has solid support among Jews, and
has pointedly noted that the first lady once advocated a
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   He is unlikely to make mistakes on D'Amato's scale, though the
possibility must rank high on Clinton's wish list. ``How does Rudy
lose?'' asked Sheinkopf. ``By being harsh, by engaging in
over-the-top attacks, by trying to belittle her _ in short, by
doing the Rudy thing.''
</P>
<P>
   New York politics contain the seed of another hope for Clinton _
a third party. Governor George Pataki and other upstate Republicans
so dislike Giuliani that they are encouraging Representative Rick
Lazio to run as the Conservative Party's nominee, to thwart the
mayor's ambitions by splitting the Republican vote.
</P>
<P>
   That's another strangeness in this Senate race: united Democrats
and divided Republicans, where it's usually the other way around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
