<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ The British general who is to direct NATO forces in Kosovo is
to meet Saturday with his Yugoslav counterpart on the
Serbia-Macedonia border to plan the Yugoslavs' withdrawal and
verification of the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Foreign ministers of the Group of Seven industrial nations and
Russia are drafting a U.N. resolution supporting an allied force in
Kosovo, though some allies say this step is not needed.
</P>
<P>
   _ The vanguard of the American contingent, 2,000 Marines, is en
route to a Greek port, then will move inland and remain on stand-by
to patrol eastern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ The European Union named Javier Solana, secretary-general of
NATO, to direct its foreign policy and security concerns. But
Solana will stay at NATO until the Kosovo crisis is under control.
</P>
<P>
   COMBAT
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO bombers swept over Yugoslavia again on Friday and early
Saturday but apparently avoided Belgrade, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pentagon and the allies reported continuing Yugoslav
attacks against Kosovars, but said the tempo of the attacks seemed
to have lessened.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yugoslav artillery shells hit Albania along a 12-mile stretch
of border and four people were injured, local police and
international monitors said.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict and the diplomatic progress
to end it is available from The New York Times on the Web:
http://www.nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
