<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES WANT OUT OF CAMPS BUT DISTRUST MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Alush Bytyqi dreams of returning to his home
in Gjakovica, the Kosovar town where he spent much of his 83 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the home Bytyqi knew does not exist anymore, literally or
otherwise. In the days following the NATO bombing, Bytyqi's son
watched in terror as, Bytyqi recounts, 12 of the two men's
relatives were shot by uniformed Serbs, then burned with the looted
family home.
</P>
<P>
   Bytyqi escaped, and has spent the past two months in a crowded
refugee camp in central Tirana. Struggling to stand, even with his
cane, Bytyqi waits for the day when he can go back to the place
where his home had been.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my land,'' he said, near tears. ``Even if my house has
burned down, I want to be there. I will sleep in a tent, if I have
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Bytyqi is like so many Kosovar refugees who are still digesting
the news that the leader they despise, Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, has agreed to a peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   Haunted by terrifying memories of the forced deportations and
reported murders in their towns, and lulled by the sweeter
recollections of a more peaceful time in their homeland, the ethnic
Albanians are torn. They want to leave the dismal existence of the
refugee camps, but they are afraid to trust Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Milosevic is willing to withdraw his military troops,
the Albanians say, they cannot live with the presence of anyone
they see as allies of the hated Yugoslav president _ be they
ordinary Serbs, or Russian peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not safe when the Serbs are there,'' said Sali Gashi, 34,
a refugee from the city of Pec who has reported atrocities to
International War Crimes Tribunal investigators. ``If we go back to
Kosovo, the Serbs must know they must leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Serbian neighbors watched'' the soldiers ``kill my father,
my brother, my uncle,'' Gashi added. ``And they didn't do anything
to stop it. How can I live with them?''
</P>
<P>
   While international military and political leaders map out a
plan to stop the fighting in Kosovo, the victims of the alleged
ethnic cleansing say there is no emotional peace at hand.
</P>
<P>
   The wounds are so deep, the fear so consuming, and the distrust
so entrenched that the possibility of a return to an earlier life _
Serbs and Albanians sharing a territory inside Yugoslav borders _
is unthinkable now, refugees here say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't sleep at night,'' said Sabrije Thaqi, 68. ``They can't
live there. All this war wasn't so that the Serbs could live there.
I don't even want to look at them. Do you know how many massacres
they did?''
</P>
<P>
   The psychological damage is obvious. Children make crayon
drawings of their villages under siege, pictures that show tiny
Kosovars, disproportionately large soldiers, planes overhead, and
houses engulfed in flames. Many of the children have nightmares, or
still fear the soldiers at the refugee camps who serve them food,
since the youngsters are nervous about men in uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   An ill 96-year-old man shook in fear recently as he was
approached by non-uniformed strangers, apparently confusing them
with enemy soldiers. ``Please, don't beat me!'' the man pleaded,
taking off his Muslim cap and cowering.
</P>
<P>
   Universally, the refugees do not want to stay at the camps,
where water and medicines are both scarce. Under the moist heat of
Tirana's early summer, the lack of adequate sewage facilities in
one of the camps here is nauseatingly apparent.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no celebrations going on among the worn-down
refugees. None is collecting his belongings, or making plans to
travel back to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Many have prayed for the end of the war, for a chance to return
to a more normal life. But the end of the battle in Kosovo as
negotiated by Russian and European Union envoys also means the end
of a much greater war for separatist ethnic Albanians _ a war they
fear they will have lost for good.
</P>
<P>
   Without independence, some Albanians say, they will never be
free from the threat of Serb repression. Despite NATO's
long-standing insistence that it did not support a partitioning of
Kosovo _ its punishing bombing of the Serbs notwithstanding _ many
Albanians nursed a dream that the war would end with an
independent, Serb-free Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won? We don't know what we won,'' said Burim Hadri, a
29-year-old refugee from Gjakovica.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't fight, have all the killing, all the victims, so the
Serbs could stay in Kosovo,'' he said. ``Only with independence''
can Albanians live peacefully, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Serbs stay, ``there will be war again,'' he predicted
sadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will kill them!'' a teenage Albanian blurted out,
overhearing Hadri's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Many Albanians are also suspicious of Russian involvement in the
peacekeeping force _ a provision believed to be key to Milosevic's
ultimate approval of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Russians are there, I don't want to go back,'' Bytyqi
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians are the same as the Serbs,'' said Rustem Gashi,
59, who fled from Suva Reka.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only if it is 100 percent without Serbs, then we will go back
to Kosovo,'' Gashi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
