<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3736 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-(2TAK     06-04 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO CAMPAIGN RELIED ON PRECISION BOMBING AND LOW ALLIED LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT and MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 73 long days of bombing, NATO finally broke the will of
President Slobodan Milosevic by finding new ways to destroy the
Serbian military, inflicting real damage on power, water, factories
and other non-military targets and demonstrating the ability to
bomb with virtual impunity, allied commanders said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a slow start, hampered by political constraints and bad
weather, NATO was able to take advantage of a rebel Albanian
offensive in recent days to draw Serb forces out of hiding near the
Kosovo-Albania border. That enabled NATO bombers to hit them hard
and inflict the first major damage to Serbian forces in the field.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance also escalated the pressure on the Milosevic regime
by stepping up attacks on command centers, television stations and
electrical power stations in the heart of Serbia. In doing so, it
demonstrated that it would not be deterred by the public outcry
over civilian casualties caused by a relative handful of mistaken
attacks and errant bombs.
</P>
<P>
   And by holding down its own losses to the surprisingly low toll
of two combat planes over more than 33,000 missions it also proved
that it could carry out its strikes at a negligible cost to itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did the trick was the accuracy of the precision weapons,
the avoidance of losses and the increasing destruction of the Serb
forces,'' the top NATO commander, Gen. Wesley K. Clark, said Friday
in a interview.
</P>
<P>
   Still, just days ago, American and NATO generals were warning
that air power alone was not enough to win. And even General Clark
concedes that NATO was not certain that air strikes alone would be
sufficient to compel Milosevic to accept NATO's terms when the
allies began their military campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And while NATO savors its victory, many current and former
allied officers say the alliance must not take away the wrong
lessons from the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Senior NATO officers said that political constraints imposed by
allied diplomats prevented them from conducting it the way they
would have liked, thereby prolonging the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of taking the war to downtown Belgrade during the
opening hours of the war, NATO waited weeks before attacking
targets in the Yugoslav capital, blunting the allies' ability to
shock the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also began with the promise never to mount a ground attack.
Only recently did it begin to assemble a peacekeeping force which
might have become an element of a larger invasion force. When
Milosevic agreed to NATO's terms on Thursday _ the very day that
President Clinton was to talk about ground troops with his top
generals _ the Yugoslav leader could not be sure that a ground
invasion would never happen.
</P>
<P>
   But what enabled the alliance to overcome the deficiences in its
strategy, allied commanders say, was the willingness of NATO
diplomats to allow them to broaden and intensify the bombing over
time. The alliance also used the professionalism of its pilots, its
high-tech weaponry and novel tactics.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Vice Admiral Daniel J. Murphy Jr., the commander of NATO naval
forces in the Adriatic, said in a telephone interview that the war
could have been shorter and caused fewer casualities had NATO's
military been given a freer hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you followed the military template, we wouldn't have had as
many restrictions as we had, but that was a political reality,''
Admiral Murphy said. ``It's certainly true that from a military
point of view, we'd have liked to have taken the gloves off
earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   NATO diplomats never expected that their decision to put an end
to Milosevic's campaign against the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo
would lead to 10 weeks of day and night bombing. Their hope was
that a few days of air strikes would suffice.
</P>
<P>
   NATO started out with a three-phase plan of gradually escalating
air strikes, a far cry from the 1991 Persian Gulf conflict when
warplanes pounded central Belgrade from the opening minutes of the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Air Force officers said the Yugoslavia conflict was a
case in which the military strategy succeeded despite serious
flaws. ``It's a strange situation,'' said General Ronald Fogleman,
a former Air Force Chief of Staff. ``Just because it comes out
reasonably well, at least in the eye of the Administration, doesn't
mean it was conducted properly. The application of air power was
flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clever tactics and some luck enabled NATO commanders to
compensate for some of the weaknesses in their plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Liberation Army, for example, emerged as an important
element of NATO's strategy. The Serbs initially frustrated NATO by
hiding, hunkering down and trying to ride out the air war.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian partisans changed that by trying to infiltrate into
Kosovo from their bases in Albania about two weeks ago. The
light-armed KLA were a poor match for the heavily equipped Serbian
military, which was armed with tanks, armored personnel carriers
and artillery, and the offensive fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   But Serbs had to mass in the open to take on the guerrillas,
making them vulnerable to allied attacks from the air. In recent
weeks, Serbian forces near the Albanian-Kosov border have taken a
heavy pounding.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced American military technology also helped. The Clinton
administration never allowed General Clark to send the battalion of
24 Apache helicopters in Albania into the fray and use the battery
of MLRS surface-to-surface rockets that were deployed with them.
</P>
<P>
   But the Army used the U.S. Army's Q-37 radar, the target
acquisition radar for the rockets. They calculated the source of
the Serbian artillery fire on the Kosovo rebels in a matter of
seconds. All this information was provided to NATO warplanes,
helping them carry out punishing attacks.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also used the U.S. Army's Predator and Hunter drones to
locate Yugoslav troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Serbs first used artillery, they could locate where
they were coming from,'' General Gordon Sullivan, the retired Army
chief of staff said in an interview. ``That took away their
capability to hide. It gave the Air Force a direct shot at the
artillery. That gave targeting a real-time impact.''
</P>
<P>
   The attacks on the troops, however, were just one source of
pressure. As the war dragged on, NATO diplomats decided to give
General Clark more latitude in prosecuting the war in Belgrade and
throughout Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The mistaken attack against the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade and
a handful of errant bombs received enormous attention by the media.
</P>
<P>
   The larger story was that the precision guided bombs, such as
laser-guided and satellite-guided weapons, enabled NATO to strike
throughout Serbia with relatively few civilian casualities.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to step up the pressure on the Milosevic regime, NATO
warplanes bombed factories owned by close associates of the
Yugoslav president, using the justification that the the goods they
made could be used by the military.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's ability to avoid losses was also an important factor,
Clark noted.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its weeks of bombardment, NATO never succeeded in
demolishing the Serbian air defenses. Unlike the Iragis during the
Gulf war, the Serbs cleverly turned their targeting radars on and
off, making it hard for NATO warplanes to locate and attack Serbian
surface to air missiles. When SAM batteries were damaged, parts
were quickly replaced.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   NATO military spokesman said recently that the alliance had
confirmed the destruction of only three of Yugoslavia's
approximately 25 mobile SA-6 surface to air missile batteries. Even
though that assessment may be overly conservative, intelligence
specialists believe that the majority of the SA-6 batteries are
still operational.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs also sought to take advantage of NATO's reluctance to
attack Montenegro _ a Yugoslav republic that has sought to maintain
a degree of independence from Belgrade _ by hiding radars there.
</P>
<P>
   Another Serb tactic was to try to attack the last plane in a
NATO strike formation as it headed back to its air bases. The Serb
calculated that the aircraft would be low on fuel by that point and
relatively unprotected by other planes. Also, the last plane in a
strike formation is often flown by one of the less experienced
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said the tactic almost worked last week when an
allied warplane was force to drop its fuel tank to gain the
maneuverability to dodge surface to air missiles near Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Still, only two allied planes, anF-117 and an F-16, were shot
down by the Serbs. And in both cases, special operations forces
were able to rescue the pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The limited losses made it easier for the alliance to maintain
public support for the fight. While no NATO pilots were killed in
combat two American pilots were killed when their Apache helicopter
crashed in Albania during training.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tabulating the results of its attack, NATO said it took a heavy
toll on the Serb military, claiming to have destroyed more than 100
Yugoslav aircraft, 314 artillery piees, 203 armored personnel
carriers, 120 tanks, 268 other military vehicles, 14 command posts,
29 highway bridges and 11 railroad bridges.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean, however, that current and previous NATO
commanders think the air war against Yugoslav should be a model for
future conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   General George Joulwan, General Clark's predecessor as NATO
commander, said in an interview that the Clinton administration
reluctance to prepare for a ground offensive had undercut the
allies leverage on Belgrade and prolonged the conflict. President
Clinton's assertion that all options were on the table was helpful
but came too late, General Joulwan added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to be careful about what victory means, given
that the initial goal was to avoid a humanitarian catastrophe,'' he
said. ``What if we go in and find a lot of mass graves? The devil
is in the details.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
