<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trickle's track-record lap holds off youngsters
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ How does it feel to win the pole for a Busch
series race at the ripe old age of 57? Like being king for a day,
Dick Trickle said.
</P>
<P>
   Trickle, whose average start in 12 Busch races this year has
been 19.5, won the pole for today's MBNA 200 with a track record
lap of 155.213 mph Friday at Dover Downs International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice thing about starting on the pole is No. 1, you're
king for a day,'' Trickle said. ``No. 2, if there's a wreck that
starts in the third row or something, you ain't a victim of it.
I've been victimized in wrecks this year terribly. You know how
this racing is: One guy messes up and collects up another five-10
cars with him.''
</P>
<P>
   All 36 drivers who qualified on speed Friday bettered the old
track Busch qualifying record of 153.498 mph held by Kevin Grubb.
Grubb qualified second at 154.952.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as good a lap as I could make it and as good a lap as the
car could make it,'' Trickle said. ``You know, the car is my
dancing partner. And if someone was going to beat my lap, they had
a lot of credit coming.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Trickle's seventh career Busch pole and third at Dover,
where he hasn't finished in the top 10 since 1991. Trickle's best
finish this year is 11th, three times, the last at Richmond in
mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be fighting the kids for the checkered flag today.
Combined, Grubb, 21, and Stanton Barrett, 26, who qualified third,
don't total Trickle's age.
</P>
<P>
   All 10 Winston Cup drivers who were doing double duty in
qualifying for both the Busch and Cup races made the field, led by
Kenny Irwin in fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Atwood, who had qualified 19th, was penalized by NASCAR
and sent to the rear of the 43-car field when a routine fuel
inspection revealed his car did not meet specifications.
</P>
<P>
   Santerre returns
</P>
<P>
   Busch series driver Andy Santerre's return to racing was brief.
He was back behind the wheel Friday nearly four months after
breaking his right leg in six places in a season-opening wreck
during the NAPA 300 at Daytona. But he failed to qualify, running
40th fastest and getting bumped from the field by provisionals.
</P>
<P>
   Santerre had three plates and 18 screws inserted into his leg.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers game
</P>
<P>
   David Green had to tape a No. 6 on the door panels of his
Chevrolet Friday to turn his No. 41 into No. 46. Joey McCarthy has
the number registered to him by NASCAR and was also attempting to
qualify his Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: McCarthy's car, among the slowest in practice,
failed to qualify. Green qualified fifth best among the No. 41s and
the three Green brothers (Mark starts 22nd; Jeff 30th) and may go
back to his preferred 41 for the race.
</P>
<P>
   Charity checks
</P>
<P>
   On behalf of the 49 drivers who endorse MBNA's NASCAR credit
card program, Bill Elliott and Jeff Burton presented checks of
$53,000 each Friday to the Brain Injury Association and the
Make-A-Wish Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
