<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUXENBOURG-AMBASSADOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON APPOINTS GAY MAN AS AMBASSADOR AS CONGRESS IS AWAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (rk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Over Republican objections, President Clinton
Friday appointed James Hormel as ambassador to Luxembourg,
employing a rarely used executive privilege to make him the
nation's first openly gay envoy.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, a San Francisco philanthropist and heir to a
meat-packing fortune, was first nominated to the post by Clinton in
October 1997. The Senate Foreign Relations Committee approved the
nomination, but Senate conservatives, led by the majority leader,
Trent Lott of Mississippi, blocked it from a vote on the Senate
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who pledged months ago to gay advocacy groups that he
was determined to make the appointment, did so Friday through a
constitutional device available to the White House when Congress is
in recess. Congress returns from its 10-day Memorial Day vacation
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the provisions of a so-called recess appointment, Hormel,
65, could remain in the job until the end of the next session of
Congress, probably in October of next year, effectively installing
him through the duration of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton had decided to use the recess
appointment when it was clear that all public and private
strategies for a vote had failed.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, who has said homosexuals are sinners, like alcoholics or
kleptomaniacs, said through a spokesman Friday that he opposed the
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Lott opposes the nomination of someone who has
supported an extremist, anti-Catholic group to represent the United
States,'' said the spokesman, John S. Czwartacki. ``Hormel's
refusal to condemn this brand of religious intolerance makes his
appointment by the Clinton-Gore administration a slap in the face
to Catholics everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Hormel's refusal to condemn the activities
of the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence, a San Francisco acting
troupe featuring men who wear nuns' habits. Luxembourg is 99
percent Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Thiessen, a spokesman for Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who is
chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee, said Clinton's move
was intended for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the president's contempt for the constitutional
process, No. 1,'' Thiessen said. ``This is an effort to get
political gain out of certain presidential constituencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative and religious groups also expressed outrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton does unpopular things in sneaky ways,'' said Robert
Knight, a spokesman for the Family Research Council. ``This
appointment was not going to fly, so he imposed it on the country.
And it means that he's using this nation to make the case to the
world for sodomy and adultery.''
</P>
<P>
   David M. Smith, a strategist for the Human Rights Campaign, a
gay advocacy group, rejected the suggestion that Clinton had acted
purely for political gain or to benefit his political heirs, Vice
President Al Gore, who is running for president, and Hillary Rodham
Clinton, who is likely to run for the Senate from New York. ``He
wanted to make a very strong statement that this type of
discrimination was not going to be tolerated,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Socarides, who oversees gay and lesbian issues for the
White House, said Gore and Mrs. Clinton would probably do well with
gay and lesbian voters anyway. Mrs. Clinton is participating in a
private fund-raising dinner on Wednesday night in New York for gay
men and lesbians sponsored by the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
