<HEADLINE>
REPLAY COULD BE RIGHT CALL FOR BASEBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball awoke one day this past week to find that the genie
called technology had somehow escaped from its bottle. Offered a
single wish _ that the most questionable of an umpire's calls be
verified or corrected through instant replay _ baseball passed. In
the name of tradition, baseball executives stuffed the genie back
in its bottle and buried it under the tarpaulin to remain
forevermore, or until the Cubs win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, National League president Leonard Coleman's decision to
ban the use of television replays to review umpire decisions upheld
a grand tradition of the game: the blown call.
</P>
<P>
   Said Coleman, after rebuking umpire Frank Pulli's unsanctioned
use of replay: ``Use of the video replay is not an acceptable
practice. Part of the beauty of baseball is that it is imperfect.
Players make errors. Managers are constantly second-guessed. But
the game is played and determined by two teams between the white
lines.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of what is traditional about our national pastime is good,
including the frailties of ballplayers and the foibles of managers,
charming elements Coleman cited in justifying his decision. It is
hard to see, though, how the outcome of a game can truly be
``determined by two teams between the white lines'' when an umpire
has made the wrong call.
</P>
<P>
   Just consider the incident Monday that set off this storm.
Florida Marlins player Cliff Floyd smashed a drive that umpire Greg
Gibson said hit off the scoreboard and ruled it a double. The
Marlins argued that the ball hit a facade behind the scoreboard, a
home run in Miami. After a conference, crew chief Pulli ruled it a
home run. That prompted a protest from the opposing St. Louis
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Pulli decided to take a look at the videotape, which
showed Gibson was right all along. Floyd went to second base and
the game resumed. That Gibson was correct is further proof that
umpires, for all the criticism they receive, get a lot more right
than they do wrong. That without replay the crew would have
reversed his call and gotten it wrong shows that they are fallible,
that they can be corrected. And what's wrong with that?
</P>
<P>
   If the home run had stood, it would have affected the score of
the game, maybe even the outcome. It certainly would have affected
Floyd's statistics, perhaps his salary negotiations in the
off-season. While the game in question probably won't have much
bearing on the pennant race, there have been calls over the years
that have had an impact on critical games. With replay, they could
have been corrected, or at least confirmed as accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Replay reviews can be a valuable tool precisely because they can
give the game back to the players. If all calls were correct,
wouldn't that be the fairest way to determine the best team on a
given night? Letting a bad call stand isn't dishonest per se, but
it unfairly affects a game and may even change its outcome. There's
no justice in that.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of practical and historical reasons to oppose
the use of replay, of course. The NFL's original experiment with
replay from 1986-91 proved, that even with the best intentions,
technology can actually make a bigger mess of things. The league's
modified review system might be an improvement, but there are still
bound to be problems.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's use of replay, limited to goal reviews, has not gone
without criticism, either. Reviews can take too long and they can
prove inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when properly implemented, replays don't make a correct
call wrong, and they can make a bad call right. And that is the
real point of officiating. If baseball can accept the designated
hitter and interleague play, it surely can accept that.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
