<SLUG> BC-BOX-KING-PROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI SEARCHES KING'S OFFICES FOR EVIDENCE OF GRAFT IN IBF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.J., Calif.)   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FBI agents swept through the promoter Don King's offices in
Deerfield Beach, Fla., Friday morning, searching for information as
part of an investigation by the U.S. attorney's office in Newark,
N.J., into alleged illegal payments and kickbacks for rankings in
the International Boxing Federation.
</P>
<P>
   At the time agents were seizing boxes of files from his offices,
King was in Manhattan meeting with executives at Time Warner, the
parent company of HBO and TVKO, trying to get them to drop a clause
in a contract for a possible rematch between Evander Holyfield and
Lennox Lewis. That clause would remove King from being the lead
promoter if he is indicted for anything stemming from the boxers'
first bout, which ended in a controversial draw. King has refused
to sign a contract with that clause in it. The cable network showed
the first Holyfield-Lewis bout on TVKO, its pay-per-view arm, and
has the rights to the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   King did not return a telephone message seeking comment on the
meeting or the FBI raid. Two weeks ago, King said that he believed
he was the main target of the federal investigation in Newark and
said he believed he would be indicted. He also said he had done
nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In Deerfield Beach, which is near Fort Lauderdale, two of the
three flags that usually fly above King's offices were
conspicuously missing Friday. Gone were the ``Only in America''
flag and the stars and stripes that can usually be seen from nearby
Interstate 95. The flag with ``Liberty'' emblazoned on it still
flew.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI agents blocked off the two-story office building in the
morning and began loading boxes of seized material onto a Ryder
rental truck. At 5:10 p.m., another truck arrived and more boxes
were loaded from the building, which King owns. Both parking lot
entrances were blocked by FBI cars, and a Broward County sheriff's
deputy stood guard.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fabregas, an FBI special agent in Miami, said that his
office executed search warrants of King's office as part of a
continuing federal investigation. But he would not comment on
whether they were related to the federal investigation in Newark.
He would also not say whether there was a search warrant for King's
Deerfield Beach home.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Krovatin, the lawyer for IBF president Robert Lee, said
the FBI did not search his organization's offices in East Orange,
N.J., Friday. The IBF is holding its annual convention in San Diego
this week, and its offices are closed. No one answered the
telephones there Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no search warrants, no subpoenas or any other paper
outstanding on Bob Lee or anyone else connected with the IBF,''
Krovatin said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal investigation into boxing has been going on for
several months. The federal grand jury in Newark has subpoenaed the
records of promoters, managers and boxers who have conducted
business with the IBF. Among those who have testified before the
grand jury are the promoter Bob Arum and the heavyweights George
Foreman and Francois Botha.
</P>
<P>
   Botha said he was asked how he received his rankings in the IBF.
While he was a cruiserweight, Botha became the IBF's No. 9-ranked
heavyweight before he fought his first heavyweight bout. Later, he
jumped from No. 4 to No. 1 with King as his promoter. That move
prompted Michael Moorer, who was No. 2 at the time, to sue the IBF
in 1995, a lawsuit that prompted the FBI investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how the rankings work,'' Botha said. ``I told
them what I know. From the things they asked me, I believe they are
looking into racketeering throughout boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   King has come under Federal indictment three times in the last
14 years and has never been convicted. In 1985 he was acquitted of
tax evasion charges. In 1995 there was a hung jury in an insurance
fraud trial stemming from an allegation that he altered a contract
with Julio Cesar Chavez to steal $350,000 from Lloyd's of London.
Last July he was acquitted of those charges in the retrial. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
