<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE RING CAPTURES THE ACORN AT BELMONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three Ring bounced back from her last-place finish in
the Kentucky Derby on Friday, survived a disputed decision by the
stewards not to disqualify her for apparently bumping in the
homestretch and won the Acorn Stakes, the first race in Belmont
Park's Triple Tiara series.
</P>
<P>
   The objection was raised by Richard Migliore, the jockey on
Better Than Honour, who finished second after a meandering
homestretch ride that saw her forced wide and brushed twice by
Three Ring, the favorite. But the three stewards, after viewing the
films of the race, ruled that both fillies had moved to the right
of their lanes and declined to reverse the order of finish.
</P>
<P>
   Three Ring, who is owned by Barry Schwartz, a trustee of the New
York Racing Association, was ridden for the first time by Jerry
Bailey, who stalked Sapphire n' Silk for half a mile. Then Three
Ring edged into the lead, only to be challenged by Better Than
Honour, and they dueled the rest of the way home. Three Ring veered
from inside her rival toward the outside under left-handed
whipping, and twice seemed to brush Better Than Honour, who lost by
a head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both fillies moved toward the outside,'' said David Hicks, the
steward representing the New York Racing Association. ``Yes, Three
Ring moved from left to right. But so did Better Than Honour. They
both changed paths. But it did not seem decisive.''
</P>
<P>
   Migliore said that Three Ring ``came out a long way,'' and
added, ``She came way, way out, about five paths, and brushed us
later.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bailey said: ``I didn't feel there was contact. I knew we
were floating out, everyone was, but I didn't feel contact. I just
followed. I knew the horse next to me was going out, but I didn't
cause it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Plesa, the trainer of Three Ring, was cheered by his
filly's return from a violent experience in the Derby, and said,
``Physically, she came out of the Derby fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Ring ran the Acorn mile in 1:36, paid $3.80 for a $2 bet
to win and earned $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   99-1, but in the Race
</P>
<P>
   The king of the long shots is back in the Belmont Stakes: Robert
Perez has run five horses in New York's premier race in the last
six years, and has finished no better than fifth in 1995 with Pana
Brass, at 79-1.
</P>
<P>
   But that was a victory of sorts. His 1992 entry of Agincourt and
Robert's Hero finished seventh and ninth at 24-1; Ulises ran last
in 1994 at 28-1, and Energizer ran last in 1997 at 45-1.
</P>
<P>
   His candidate in the Belmont on Saturday is Teletable, who is
99-1 in the morning line. He is a son of Colonial Affair, who won
the Belmont in 1993, but he has raced only four times and won once,
in his last start, at Gulfstream Park on Feb. 15. Still, his
trainer, Alfredo Callejas, said Friday that the colt has always
been considered a distance runner and not a jack rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he runs on the lead,'' Callejas said, with a smile, ``he'll
finish at Kennedy Airport.''
</P>
<P>
   A Wall Street Portent  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rider Chris Antley's top picks? Charismatic, America Online
and Intel. Friday, however, he could do something about only the
last two _ he rang the opening bell at the New York Stock Exchange.
Antley, a high school dropout, made more than $1 million last year
as a day trader via the Internet. His interest in stocks and bonds
began 10 years ago when he started paying attention to how Merrill
Lynch and Prudential-Bache invested his 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   Now he has his own tip sheet, of the stock variety, ``The Ant
Man Report,'' and is about to launch a web site. Barely five months
ago, he passed out his newsletter to about 30 trainers around the
California tracks. Now he has 1,000 subscribers. He characterized
himself as a momentum trader _ in and out of stocks as they rise
and fall.
</P>
<P>
   It pretty much describes an often brilliant riding career that
has been interrupted by substance abuse problems and battles with
weight. So, how did he move the market Friday? Well, the Dow closed
at 10,799.84, up 136 points. Sounds like a good omen for a Triple
Crown. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
