<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-KUEHNE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOGEY-FREE KUEHNE SHOOTS 71, FALLS BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ Kelli Kuehne no longer sits atop the leader
board at the U.S. Women's Open. But the Dallas resident has
achieved something unmatched by any of her 149 competitors at Old
Waverly Golf Club:
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne has completed two rounds without a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not supposed to happen,'' said Kuehne, who logged 17
pars and a birdie during a second-round 71 yesterday to move to 9
under par for the tournament, a stroke behind co-leaders Juli
Inkster and Lorie Kane.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd told me at the start of the week I'd be doing this,
I'd have said, `No way,' '' Kuehne said. ``This is the U.S. Open.
Par is a prized possession. Birdie is like a bonus, and bogey is
expected. I've played very well. But to not have made any bogeys,
I've been very fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Kuehne has been very consistent. For a second
consecutive day, she reached 15 greens in regulation. This time,
she needed 32 putts to complete her round _ seven more than in her
opening 64.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's your seven-stroke difference right there,'' said
Kuehne, adding that she did not fully comprehend the significance
of her 64, which matched the best round in relation to par (8
under) in tournament history, until walking up to the 17th hole
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Kuehne, 22, turned to caddie Tracy Phillips and
said: ``I can't believe I shot 64 \RThursday\S. I'm doing
everything just as well but I'm 1 under, instead of 8 under. That
just shows you're living in a fantasy world if you think you're
going to shoot 64 every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally unlikely, in Kuehne's opinion, would be to finish 72
holes at the Open without a bogey. Although she is halfway home,
Kuehne said she does not expect to keep up this pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of time before I make one,'' Kuehne said.
``Hopefully, I'll make a whole lot more pars and birdies than I
will bogeys.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question for Kuehne will be how she handles the pressure
of playing in the final groups during weekend rounds at a major
championship for the first time in her LPGA Tour career. Kuehne
said she is relaxed and ready after finishing seventh and first in
her past two events.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, a three-time major champion, said Kuehne will have one
advantage over her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's in a no-lose situation because she'd never been there,''
said Inkster, 38. ``She can go out there and play aggressive, and
if she doesn't do good, she's never been there. If she does, it's a
bonus. I think she's in a great position, and she looks pretty
confident to me. I don't see her backing down at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 2138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
