u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-REFUGEES-     06-04 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-REFUGEES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS AIRLIFT ENDS, REFUGEES WEIGH LURE OF U.S. AGAINST PULL OF HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT DIX, N.J. _ With the Yugoslav government having agreed to
withdraw military and police forces from Kosovo, the United States
will stop its emergency airlift of refugees to this army base,
administration officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Shalala, the secretary of Health and Human Services, said
that about 3,500 refugees already in Fort Dix would continue to be
screened for resettlement in communities around the country. The
pace of the resettlement, about 100 people a day, would not slow,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional visit here, during which she heard groups of
women describe how they fled Kosovo, Shalala told them to treat the
Yugoslav pledge ``with caution,'' much as the Clinton
Administration viewed it. ``My message to the refugees today was to
get on with your lives,'' she said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala, whose parents came to the United States as refugees
from Lebanon, promised to let the Kosovars know when it is safe to
return home, and said the U.S. government would pay their air fare.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Kosovars are under no legal obligation to return,
many, especially the young, said they feel divided: duty tells them
to rebuild and repopulate their destroyed homeland, they say, but
the chance to live in the United States, away from the threat of
annihilation and ethnic hatreds, is hard to turn down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to return home as soon as possible, but I'd also like
to take back some experience from America,'' said Rudi Rubik, a
23-year-old student.
</P>
<P>
   Ardita Spahiu, a 20-year-old lab technician, said that she was
divided, too. ``Since I was a little girl my dream was to come to
the United States,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among older refugees, the urge was strong to reclaim the shreds
of all they had built and lost. Demiri Riza, a 70-year-old farmer
who is hard of hearing, somehow had missed the news that Yugoslavia
bowed to NATO demands and would allow the Kosovars back. He wept as
Rubik, acting as translator, told him about it today. ``Really?''
he asked in disbelief. ``Really?''
</P>
<P>
   Riza said he wanted to go home as soon as possible, to his house
in ``I don't know if it's still there,'' he said. There is also
fear that the Serbs may leave mines behind, and Riza said he would
wait for Washington to give the all-clear before going home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love America, but Kosovo is sweet,'' he said, and turned to
the younger Rubik, to ask, ``Don't you miss your country?''
</P>
<P>
   Mirvete Halimi said her husband was skeptical about Serbian
intentions, even in peace, but vowed that her family would return
regardless of what their sons _ who are 11 and 13 _ want. In
Kosovar families, she said, ``There is only one boss, the mother or
the father.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Halimi said, ``I'll tell my children, `It's time to go home.
Don't make any problems, because our country is calling us.'''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has so far taken in 6,000 of the 20,000
refugees it pledged to resettle. About 4,000 have come through Fort
Dix, and 2,000 others went straight to relatives in the United
States who offered to sponsor them.
</P>
<P>
   About 650 refugees have by now left Fort Dix for communities
around the United States, leaving 3,400 still awaiting resettlement
or a return to Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
