<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3757 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-STOCKS-ART-3     06-04 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-STOCKS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEEDING A FRENZY: WHY INTERNET INVESTORS ARE STILL RAVENOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.J., N.Y., Mich., Md.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of performance, number of IPO of internet stocks
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6)  
 (Eds: The (star) word should be replaced with the symbol)  
 (af)  
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ The ink on the first draft of the history of
the Internet stock boom isn't yet dry, and the revisionists are
already having their say.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Internet shares were tumbling from their highs, three of
the companies backed by Accel Partners, a venture capital firm,
went public last month. Though their net losses total $56 million,
the three now have a combined market capitalization of $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Astounding,'' James W. Breyer, the firm's managing partner,
calls that performance, echoing the giddiness common in Silicon
Valley when people talk about the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But in the same breath, Breyer decries the shortcomings of the
crop of new offerings following in his companies' footsteps.
``We've had far too many low-quality companies go public,'' he
scoffed. The recent market turmoil that has sliced the value of
many Internet stocks in half is making investors more
discriminating, he added approvingly: ``Investors can more easily
distinguish between companies building a long-term business and
those which have been merely opportunistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, to be a master of the Internet universe and not only make
business history, but spin it, too. As some of the air leaks out of
the Internet stock bubble, the same people who manufactured the
feeding frenzy _ the venture capitalists, entrepreneurs and
investment bankers who have been the biggest promoters of the
phenomenon _ are beginning to say it may have spun out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks not ready for prime time were foisted on a welcoming
public lusting for the big score, they now say. In Silicon Valley's
effervescence the past few months, discretion lost out to greed.
</P>
<P>
   And yet even as they apply the rhetorical brakes to careening
Internet mania, those same financiers are stepping on the gas,
racing to bring companies to market before the Internet euphoria
disappears. Some investment bankers say clients are asking them to
pull together ``road shows'' _ in which executives pitch their
companies to prospective buyers _ in little more than two weeks,
half the usual time. And many of the bankers, supposed arbiters of
a company's market-worthiness, are only too happy to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it's hang onto the rocket ship and giggle all the
way to the moon,'' said Mark G. Shafir, an investment banker at
Merrill Lynch in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Already, 59 Internet companies have gone public this year _
compared with 30 in all of 1998, according to Thomson Financial
Securities Data, which tracks such numbers. Fifty-six percent of
the 212 Internet and Internet-related companies filing plans to go
public with the Securities and Exchange Commission since January
1994 did so in the last six months. May was the busiest month on
record, as 35 companies registered with regulators.
</P>
<P>
   That pace concerns David Menlow, who, as the longtime president
of IPO Financial Network, a firm in Milburn, N.J., that tracks new
offerings, has seen his share of hysteria on Wall Street. Even he
is stunned at the crush of companies rushing to go public since
Internet stocks hit a record high in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   Menlow's most recent newsletter is chock-full of comments on the
new crop, and few are charitable. ``Right church, wrong pew,'' he
writes about one Internet-related medical concern. ``Talk about
swimming upstream,'' he says of a company that creates computer
operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   The market for Internet stocks is still fertile, Menlow said,
but companies like these will be judged more harshly in coming
months, since the euphoria over the sector has ebbed. ``Before, the
window was wide open,'' he said. ``Now the window has a fine mesh
screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet with Silicon Valley still working overtime to generate
excitement _ and the transformative power of Internet innovation a
genuine, powerful lure _ investors can be said to share a new
caution only if their behavior is judged against the hysteria of
the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   In January, according to Securities Data, initial public
offerings of Internet companies averaged a first-day gain of 248
percent. By the end of May, with so many deals to choose from and
appetites waning a bit, that gain had dwindled to 73 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fearlessly, though, Silicon Valley financiers are developing
ways to institutionalize the Web frenzy. Venture capitalists are
demanding that shares of some new companies be sold on line, where
Internet-hungry investors are abundant. And some neophyte
investment firms see that as an opportunity to supplant the more
established banks.
</P>
<P>
   Looked at innocently, they are aiming to democratize investment.
Looked at cynically, they are looking to give every investor equal
standing in the hype.
</P>
<P>
   Some Silicon Valley veterans believe it is time for some
cooling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually despair what is going on in the Valley,'' said Judy
Estrin, chief technology officer at Cisco Systems, herself an
entrepreneur who was a co-founder of three companies. ``It used to
be if you had good products and you took care of your clients and
customers, you'd win. That's not enough anymore. Today it's more
about marketing hype and rising above the noise level.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be overly pessimistic. Most here are ecstatic at the
speed and breadth of innovation that the Internet has unleashed.
But for the financiers, one thing is certain, even with Web shares
down: It doesn't get much better than this.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Silicon Valley's venture capitalists and investment
bankers ply their trade in Menlo Park, not far from grassy pastures
dotted with cows and an occasional deer. There, in the 2700 block
of Sand Hill Road (more aptly named ``Stand Still Road'' when
rush-hour traffic clogs the four-lane route), two of the fiercest
competitors in investment banking have set up shop. A small,
flower-filled courtyard separates the offices of rivals Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter and the Goldman Sachs Group, their buildings
connected by a covered walkway 100 yards long.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It's an intimacy rare even in a place where deals are cut at
Saturday-morning soccer games. ``We have a pact not to go through
the trash,'' joked Eff W. Martin, a Goldman partner, pointing at
Morgan's offices through a slit in the window blinds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the arrangements seem a bit cozy, as if what the bankers
have in common _ their insider status in a very rich game _ trumps
any antagonisms. Bradford C. Koenig, Goldman's co-head of high
technology, employed the same nanny later hired by Rex Golding, a
Harvard Business School classmate and his counterpart at Morgan
Stanley. And it is not uncommon to see bankers from both camps
schmoozing at the same Valley soirees.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, investment bankers sit at the top of the
financial pyramid; here they mainly play the role of courtiers. The
true princes of finance are the venture capitalists, who invest in
start-ups with the hope of a big payoff when a company goes public
or is sold.
</P>
<P>
   More Internet venture dollars are chasing deals than ever
before. Funds raised by venture capitalists have blossomed in the
past four years, from $774 million in 1995 to $4.9 billion last
year, according to the VentureOne Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Lee, an entrepreneur in Redwood City, Calif., who last
September started a company called Corio that distributes business
software over the Internet, said he was approached by no fewer than
20 venture capital firms, including the godfather of Silicon Valley
venture capital, Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, ``there wasn't a countervailing presence to the
lunacy of the bankers,'' said Gary Rieschel, managing general
partner at Softbank Technology Ventures, an early investor in
Yahoo, the Internet directory service. ``Now you have the lunacy of
the venture capitalists to counter the lunacy of the bankers.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this decade's venture capitalists have much in common
with bankers of a decade ago who hired publicists to promote
themselves and their successes. In keeping with the spirit of the
companies they finance, most have their own Web sites and are
skilled at creating a buzz loud enough to rise above the Valley
static.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more accomplished is Robert Kagle, a venture
capitalist at Benchmark Capital in Menlo Park. Benchmark was an
early investor in Ebay, the on-line auction company that has seen
its share price climb more than 1,000 percent since going public
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Kagle, 43, a Michigan native who, like many Valley veterans,
moved to Palo Alto to attend Stanford Business School and never
left, is self-deprecating. ``Some venture capitalists see
themselves as the center of the universe,'' he said. ``We see it as
a service business.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as he shares credit with colleagues for his successes,
Mr. Kagle is an adept salesman for the companies he backs. In a
recent interview, for instance, he readily volunteered that he
collects antique fishing decoys _ bought through Ebay, of course.
And he strained to use the term ``Ebaysian'' (``pronounced
e-BAY-ze-an,'' he said) no fewer than five times in a 35-minute
telephone conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Why? It is his attempt to introduce Ebay culture _ which
advocates the equal standing of every bidder _ into the new
language of the Internet, a bit of manipulation that he doesn't
deny and even laughs about.
</P>
<P>
   No other Internet company has been so hotly fought over as Ebay,
and the story of its public offering suggests how eager bankers are
to hook up with a company they think will be a winner.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, when Kagle and Ebay's chief executive, Meg Whitman,
invited investment banks to pitch for the job of taking the company
public, Goldman and Morgan jumped at the chance. Ms. Whitman had
one peculiar demand: When they came calling, each bank had to bring
an item bought on Ebay.
</P>
<P>
   A team of eight Goldman executives entered Ebay's headquarters,
bags crammed with charts, market data _ and Tank the Armadillo, a
Beanie Baby that Koenig had bought for his 7-year-old son, Austin,
for $32.75 in an Ebay auction.
</P>
<P>
   Michael K. Parekh, an analyst, had a 25-year-old Parcheesi game
that he had bought for $110. He also presented the Ebay executives
with a sample research report before the Goldman team swept them
off to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear they would be a leader in this market,'' Koenig
said, explaining the avid campaign. ``The more time we spent on the
site, we realized it was a whole new dimension in personal
trading.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's inventiveness struck a chord with Ebay, though Morgan
Stanley was dogged, too. Its executives also logged hours on Ebay's
Web site, buying fine French wine and a couple of piggy banks in
which Ebay could stuff its newfound money. But ``they didn't
display as deep an understanding,'' Kagle said. And it cost Morgan
the job.
</P>
<P>
   The bankers were devastated. ``We walked out of the meeting
right then and knew that it didn't click,'' said Mary Meeker,
Morgan's celebrated Internet analyst _ ``Queen Mary'' to her fans,
``Bloody Mary'' to her detractors and a stock-moving powerhouse in
the eyes of both.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meeker was convinced that Ebay would be a market leader, and
after Morgan lost, she quickly went to work repairing the
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   She spent hours getting to know Ms. Whitman, including a dinner
at Logan Airport in Boston last July, one of several meetings over
a period of months. In August, Ruth Porat, Morgan's co-head of
global technology and Ms. Meeker spent an evening on the phone with
Ms. Whitman, critiquing Goldman's road-show presentation.
</P>
<P>
   They suggested that the company demonstrate its users'
enthusiasm better; as a result, Ebay created slides listing some of
the thousands of items for sale related just to the baseball
superstar Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meeker also took the unprecedented step of publishing a
favorable research report the day after Ebay began trading last
September. (Analysts usually like to wait until the company has a
track record before giving an endorsement.)
</P>
<P>
   Goldman was legally barred from talking up the stock for 30 days
after the offering, Ms. Whitman noted, ``so Mary became the one the
press called. She became associated with Ebay.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley's hard work paid off. In March, Goldman lined up
investors for Ebay's $1 billion secondary stock offering but was
forced to share the business with Morgan. Goldman chafed at the
concession but was powerless to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morgan earned it,'' Ms. Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any question that technology is transforming
business, investors need look only at the most staid rite of
passage on Wall Street: going public.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that for a standard 7 percent underwriting fee,
bankers would herd management onto a chartered jet for a two-week
road show, cram in 10 to 12 meetings a day with mutual fund
managers and other investors and hope to end up with a list of
interested buyers _ with a tiny portion of the stock reserved for
mom-and-pop investors.
</P>
<P>
   Now, investors' mania for the stocks minted by Silicon Valley
financiers _ along with the growing trend toward do-it-yourself
investing on line _ has banks scrambling to find new ways to get
stock in IPOs into the hands of individuals. And the new on-line
banks, without armies of bankers and salesmen, expect to charge
companies fees of 5 percent or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``First you had the discount brokers,'' said Michael Moritz, a
venture capitalist at Sequoia Capital in Menlo Park. ``Now you have
the emergence of the discount investment banker.''
</P>
<P>
   Established firms like the Charles Schwab Corp. and DLJ Direct,
the on-line affiliate of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, already
distribute shares on line and help underwrite stock offerings. But
the emergence of on-line investment banks _ like the Wit Capital
Group of New York (which itself went public on Friday) and
E(star)Offering, which is backed by Sanford Robertson, a co-founder
of Robertson, Stephens &AMP; Co. of San Francisco _ could open the
process further, with new stocks available on a first-come,
first-served basis.
</P>
<P>
   The most revolutionary concept is being championed by William
Hambrecht, co-founder of another San Francisco investment bank,
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. Housed in a former warehouse in the city's
design district, his firm, W.R. Hambrecht &AMP; Co., sells new stocks
over the Internet in a so-called Dutch auction, with investors
setting the price.
</P>
<P>
   Investors place bids for the number of shares they want at a
price they are willing to pay. After a few weeks of bidding, a
clearing price is set at the lowest offer at which all shares can
be sold. Those bidding above the clearing price get all the shares
they asked for. Investors bidding at that price may get only a
percentage of the shares they want. Those who bid too low are shut
out.
</P>
<P>
   The concept, while by no means proven, appeals to venture
capitalists like Bruce Dunlevie, a partner at Benchmark Capital.
``I think the trends favor it,'' he said. ``It is the rise of the
consumer in the IPO market.''
</P>
<P>
   But the mechanics may serve only to feed the frenzy further,
encouraging overbidding. ``If you guess the actual price, you run
the risk of not getting stock,'' acknowledged Ian H. Zwicker,
president of W.R. Hambrecht.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, it is unclear whether many analysts will follow the
companies and offer investors needed guidance. Ravenswood Winery,
the first company whose stock was auctioned this way, got a tepid
reaction from investors. But most experts believe the logical users
of Hambrecht's services are Internet entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   If the market for Internet stocks remains weak, Silicon Valley
may have no choice but to pause and catch its breath. That would
please Lee, the founder of Corio.
</P>
<P>
   Corio's fiercest competitor, a Maryland company called
USinternetworking, was grabbing headlines after its stock price
shot up from $21 to a high of $60 on April 9, the day it went
public. Though USinternetworking had $33 million in net losses and
a still-developing business model, the first day's trading gave it
an eye-popping market capitalization of $2.4 billion and, Lee
worried, instant credibility.
</P>
<P>
   He was faced with a decision: Should Corio go public, too? It
had promising sales but couldn't guarantee the same success in the
coming months. And while Wall Street analysts may not require
profits, they do demand predictability.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't come without processes, people and tools in
place,'' Lee said. After an agonizing two-hour board meeting in
April, the company chose to hold off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely felt the pressure,'' Lee said. ``You get caught
up in the hype. Given that we could do it, of course we thought
about it. A lot of people do. We are fighting a clock.''
</P>
<P>
   A month later, he doesn't regret the decision.
USinternetworking's market capitalization has fallen to $1 billion,
and investors who bought in the first day's euphoria are facing
losses of more than 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy is that an IPO is a measure of doing something
well,'' Lee said. He hesitated for a moment, reconsidering the
thought. ``But it's also about being at the right place at the
right time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
