<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3762 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AIRPOWER-NYT &LR;      06-04 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AIRPOWER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO OUTCOME SHOWS HOW AIR POWER CAN WIN WITHOUT GROUND TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic once boasted that a
high-technology bombing war would never force Serbian soldiers out
of Kosovo. ``You are not willing to sacrifice lives to achieve our
surrender,'' he proclaimed five weeks into the 10-week conflict.
``We are willing to die to defend our rights as an independent
sovereign nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet without one combat casualty, the U.S.-led NATO alliance has
proved the dictator wrong. If the peace deal that Milosevic agreed
to on Thursday holds up, his government has unwillingly become the
first case study in how precision weaponry, overwhelming resources
and a steely willingness to keep bombing can compel victory _ all
without risking NATO soldiers on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's dismissive view of a ``say uncle'' strategy that
from Day 1 ruled out U.S. ground forces was echoed by many of the
West's most prominent military experts. They and Milosevic
certainly had history on their side. From World War II to Vietnam
to the Persian Gulf war, air power has always promised far more
than it delivered. Victory, if it came at all, demanded that young
men get down in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   But after two and a half months in which the only ground combat
was conducted by Albanian separatist guerrillas, Milosevic
apparently calculated that the cost of controlling Kosovo, which
Serbs regard as the sacred root of their national identity, was
more than his government could bear.
</P>
<P>
   The cost included the death of 5,000 members of the Yugoslav
armed forces and the wounding of more than 10,000 other fighters,
according to NATO. As important, the air campaign, which Milosevic
was apparently powerless to stop or substantially hinder, ravaged
the basic installations of Yugoslavia and, for the first time in a
decade of fighting in the Balkans, brought home the misery of war
to the middle classes in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO victory represented by the peace deal also exacted a
savage human price from the people in whose name the war in Kosovo
was fought. Nearly a million ethnic Albanians were forced out of
their homeland by a Serbian campaign of intimidation and murder
that accelerated with the NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said at the beginning of the bombing that it
would protect the Kosovo Albanians, who made up 90 percent of the
population in the province. But White House strategists have since
conceded that that was never really a practical goal. Bombing could
neither protect the Kosovars, the officials said, nor could it
force out the Yugoslav armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   What the White House had hoped air power would do and what it
has apparently done, after an air campaign that continued far
longer than planned, is diminish Milosevic's chances of survival to
the point where it made sense for him to sue for peace.
</P>
<P>
   A supposedly crippling flaw that military analysts diagnosed in
the bombing strategy was that it allowed Milosevic to be the sole
judge of when he had lost the war. Gen. Colin Powell, the Gulf war
strategist who championed the idea that America should go to war
only when victory was guaranteed by overwhelming force, said that
an air-only campaign gave Milosevic the option of deciding ``when
he's had enough.''
</P>
<P>
   What Powell appears not to have noticed is that throughout this
decade Milosevic has been quite willing to ``say uncle'' and lose
wars, provided that it is in his interest to do so. The Kosovo
accord makes this the fourth time since 1991 that Milosevic has
done exactly that, initiate damage control and give up on wars that
he started.
</P>
<P>
   As far as saving his own skin, the deal that Milosevic, an
indicted war criminal, agreed to is a considerable improvement on
the Rambouillet plan that the West tried and failed to impose on
him this year.
</P>
<P>
   The new pact calls for a NATO and Russian force under United
Nations auspices to deploy only in and near Kosovo. The Rambouillet
plan would have given purely NATO forces guaranteed access to all
of Yugoslavia, including Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The White House calculated, at the start of the bombing in March
that Milosevic's resolve in Kosovo would crumble in a few days,
just as it did in Bosnia in 1995. The Administration was shocked, a
former White House official recounted, that Milosevic was using the
bombing as an occasion for stepped-up ``ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacking Plan B and nervous about the political effects of combat
deaths in an obscure corner of Europe, the White House and NATO
stuck to its air strategy, while increasing the number of bombing
runs to a level never contemplated before the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In late April, after the bombing strategy set off a
rally-round-the-flag reaction in Yugoslavia, Milosevic publicly
sneered at the West's plan. ``Your leaders are not strategic
thinkers,'' he said in an interview with United Press
International. ``Short-term quick fixes, yes. They said, `Let's
bomb Yugoslavia and then figure out what to do next.'''
</P>
<P>
   What the United States and NATO did next was simply bomb some
more. Spokesmen in Washington and Brussels publicly but
perfunctorily regretted raids that killed civilians, but the
bombing steadily increased in frequency and ferocity.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts of American public opinion have found, after examining
polls dating from the Korean War, that the single most important
factor that can turn the American public against a foreign war is a
spike in U.S. combat casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public applies a fairly reasonable cost-benefit analysis
when evaluating foreign affairs, but it vastly overvalues the lives
of Americans and undervalues the lives of foreigners,'' said John
Mueller, an expert on polling and foreign wars who is a professor
of political science at the University of Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   Polling since April by the Pew Research Center has found 60
percent of Americans ``very worried'' about American combat
casualties, although there have been none. The polling also found
that even after bombing mistakes killed scores upon scores of
civilians, just 40 percent of Americans were ``very worried'' about
that.
</P>
<P>
   By that measure, the Kosovo effort was perfectly attuned to
American opinion. The sole American deaths occurred when two
helicopter pilots died in a training accident.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, two planes went down, and the pilots were whisked
away by a supersecret high-technology rescue force. The leap in
high-tech warfare, even compared to the gulf war in 1991, when 75
coalition aircraft were shot down, was nothing less than
extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   In an entirely different way, the campaign was also attuned to
Serbian opinion. There is an enduring myth among the Serbs of brave
and hopeless struggle against overwhelming odds. It dates from 1389
and the Serbian loss in Kosovo to Ottoman invaders. The myth has
been relentlessly reinforced by Milosevic's control of state
television.
</P>
<P>
   If the war does end with the new accord, lost-cause myths are
highly unlikely to sustain Milosevic, especially as the Serbian
people add up the costs of their fight. In that accounting, the
Bosnia precedent could be telling. Eighteen months after
Milosevic's surrender there in 1995, tens of thousands of unhappy
and increasingly impoverished Serbs took to the streets to demand
his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The gestation period for protests in Belgrade seems quite likely
to be much shorter after Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
