<HEADER>
A3764 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-LPGA-NYT &LR;      06-04 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIRDIE BARRAGE AT THE LPGA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Miss., Ore., Korea, Sweden)   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ One day after Kelli Kuehne shot a 64 at the
U.S. Women's Open, Lorie Kane and Becky Iverson did the same.
</P>
<P>
   Don't players usually struggle to make par at the Open? Aren't
birdies supposed to be precious, and bogeys commonplace? Not this
year, and not at Old Waverly Golf Club, which may surrender the
lowest 72-hole score in Open history.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting an eight-under-par 64, and soaring from seven strokes
behind into a tie for first place, Kane was 10 under par (134) for
the tournament and shared the second-round lead with Juli Inkster
after another day of high temperatures and low scores.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne was one stroke behind in third place, still very much in
the picture after shooting a 71 Friday. Iverson, who equaled Kane
with the day's best round (64), was in fourth place at 136 and in
contention to capture her first major.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-hole cut was par-144, the lowest in U.S. Women's Open
history. The previous low cut was three over par, in 1993 at
Crooked Stick Golf Club in Carmel, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Notable players missing the cut included Annika Sorenstam and
Laura Davies, at 146, and Nancy Lopez, who was at 149 in her 23d
attempt to win the Open.
</P>
<P>
   Four talented players were tied for fifth place at seven under
par _ Grace Park, the reigning U.S. Amateur champion who is turning
professional after the tournament; Dottie Pepper, who won the
year's first major, the Nabisco Dinah Shore; Sherri Steinhauer, who
made the winning putt for last year's U.S. Solheim Cup team, and
Catriona Matthew of Sweden, a member of last year's European
Solheim Cup team. The defending champion, Se Ri Pak, was six under
par.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten under is not going to win this tournament,'' said Inkster,
who shot a 69 and finished with a birdie on No. 18 to tie Kane.
``You've got to play aggressive. You've got to make birdies. I
don't think there's anything wrong with that. I would rather see
what I'm seeing this week than see what I saw last year. I mean, it
was a joke. Bogey, bogey, bogey.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no comparison between this Open and last year's, held
at Blackwolf Run Golf Course in Kohler, Wis., one of the most
demanding venues ever.
</P>
<P>
   Pak and Jenny Chuasiriporn finished tied for the lead at six
over par after 72 holes before Pak won in a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   This year, six over par sent you home for the weekend. The
72-hole Open record of 10 under par, set by Alison Nicholas in 1997
at Pumpkin Ridge Golf Club in North Plains, Ore., is in serious
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   With wide-open fairways, manageable rough and perfectly
manicured greens that were softened by heavy rain Wednesday, Old
Waverly has been defenseless to stop the birdie barrage.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the most demanding obstacle has been the weather, as the
afternoon temperature reached 93 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   But the heat did not break the concentration of Kane, 34, who
breezed through Old Waverly just as Kuehne did Thursday. Kane set
the tone by starting with three consecutive birdies, making a
20-footer on the opening hole. She made three putts from 15 feet or
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some putts that kind of hung on the edge and fell in,''
Kane said. ``I keep learning from those experiences and try to
build on them. If it stays this hot and we don't get rain, then
it's going to be a different ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kuehne's 71 was a far cry from her opening-round 64, she
has yet to make a bogey and remained confident about her chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't shoot 64 every day at the U.S. Open,'' said Kuehne,
a 22-year-old former two-time U.S. Amateur champion. ``I wish you
could. I hit 15 greens yesterday and 15 today. I hit a lot of great
putts today that I did not make. That's golf.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
