<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SMOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SPENDING TO STOP SMOKING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, June 5:
</P>
<P>
   New York lags woefully behind states like California and
Massachusetts in combating smoking, the leading preventable cause
of death and disease. More than 30,000 New York residents die
annually from tobacco-related illness. Yet the state spends a
pittance _ $6.5 million annually, or 37 cents per person _ on
anti-smoking efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The windfall from the multistate tobacco settlement should make
it possible for New York, which expects to receive roughly $1
billion a year, to turn that around. This week Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver outlined a plan that would provide about $80 million
a year for new smoking-prevention programs, financed mostly by the
settlement money and part of a five-cent increase on the minimum
price of cigarettes. Gov. George Pataki says he is not opposed to
spending more, but his own proposal to use 75 percent of the state
government's share of the settlement on debt reduction and the rest
on other health care programs might leave too little for new
anti-smoking measures.
</P>
<P>
   There is strong evidence that aggressive anti-tobacco programs
can reduce the allure of smoking to teen-agers. Florida, for
example, spent $70 million last year on a comprehensive
youth-oriented smoking prevention plan. In just one year, smoking
rates declined by 19 percent among Florida's middle-school
students, and by 8 percent among high schoolers. California, which
spends $120 million a year on anti-smoking programs, and
Massachusetts, which spends $60 million a year, have slowed the
growth rate in teen-age smoking. In Oregon, per capita cigarette
consumption dropped by 11 percent after a ballot measure raised
cigarette taxes to finance anti-smoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Centers for Disease Control suggested last year that
a comprehensive tobacco control strategy for New York would require
between $93 million and $259 million a year. A coalition of health
groups has urged a very reasonable $90 million a year for
anti-tobacco education, counter-advertising campaigns and smoking
cessation programs. Silver's plan would come close to that goal.
New York taxpayers spend $1.8 billion a year in Medicaid costs
alone to treat smoking-related illnesses. Spending a tiny fraction
of that amount on smoking prevention would help curb medical costs
and reduce a lot of human misery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
