</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STRUGGLING TO MOVE BEYOND OK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Depending on your rooting interests, the Mets-Yankees subway
series comes at a curious time. If you're pulling for the Yankees,
it couldn't come at a better time. After two terrible losses to
Cleveland, the Bombers are looking to shift into a higher gear. If
you're pulling for the Mets, the series couldn't come at a better
time. The team entered the series on a six-game losing streak, five
games out of first place and reeling.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're pulling for Bobby Valentine, the series couldn't
have come at a worse time. The timing has matched the wobbling Mets
against the World Series champion Yankees in a venue regarded as
the most hallowed in sports. Most of all, the three-game series
juxtaposes Joe Torre, the epitome of managing, with Valentine, a
manager who specializes in rebuilding teams but one who has never
been able to get past ``OK''
</P>
<P>
   In 14 seasons, Valentine has never led a team to a division
title, and this season the wheels are wobbling on the Mets, a team
with the fifth-highest payroll in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The latest embarrassing moment came Friday when it was reported
that two Mets, Bobby Bonilla and Brian McRae, were placed on
irrevocable waivers. Both players were in the starting lineup, and
McRae even homered. What bothered both McRae and Bonilla was that
they found out about the move as they arrived at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a bad way to find out about something like that,''
McRae said. ``Especially just before the series starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine once again found himself in a difficult position and
before the game asked reporters, in typical sarcastic fashion, what
he might say to McRae and Bonilla to smooth ruffled feathers.
``What do you say: `It wasn't me, it was him?' It's not going to be
an easy situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Add McRae and Bonilla to a growing list of players Valentine has
had nasty snits with: Todd Hundley, Pete Harnisch, Lance Johnson.
But if the Knicks have proved anything this season, it is that
winning makes blemishes seem acceptable, if not beautiful. A sea of
sins will be forgiven when you win or are perceived as a winner.
This is where Valentine runs into problems. There is a sense he may
have hit his ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine spent a career trying to get past being ``OK'' as a
player _ he was never the same after he broke his leg _ and as a
manager. As a manager his record is barely .500. What might may
define Valentine's career is the end of last season, when the Mets,
needing one or two victories to capture a wild-card berth, lost all
five games. Valentine could not find a way to win.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has a high-priced team. Last winter Steve Phillips, the
Mets' general manager, said, ``We put together a wish list and were
able to get everyone on it.'' Is this an echo of 1992? The Mets
slumped in 1991, and in the winter they acquired big-name veteran
players through trades and free agency. That summer, the Mets were
miserable. They had the highest payroll in the game but finished 18
games under .500 and 24 games out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla had a nightmare of a first run in New York in 1992; this
week the Mets all but tried to give him away. Will the recent moves
backfire as they did seven seasons ago?
</P>
<P>
   Back then the Mets put big names together without thinking
chemistry. They became the worst team money could buy: David Cone
was sent away; Bonilla wound up hitting .249 and constantly feuded
with the news media. And 1993 was worse.
</P>
<P>
   But give Valentine some credit: He took over in 1997 and turned
the Mets around. Now the payroll is between $65 million and $70
million _ the Yankees' is $84 million. Valentine's Achilles' heel
has been a contentious personality: starting messes when there were
none, inciting feuds rather than quelling them, circumventing
rather than facing up and expressing contrition when he gets
caught.
</P>
<P>
   When Torre came back from cancer surgery and the Yankees were
unsettled, he soothed nervous spirits and righted the listing ship.
What would Valentine do with this Yankees roster? You shudder to
think.
</P>
<P>
   Last night someone asked Valentine if he felt he had ``fences to
mend.''
</P>
<P>
   With McRae and Bonilla, Valentine didn't waver. ``When you're a
professional guy and you're making a salary and you're getting paid
to play and something happens that doesn't affect your job today, I
think you still got to do your job,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Bonilla's physical condition, Valentine said
the outfielder was looking better, but added, ``I'm just trying to
determine if better is good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely what the Mets must eventually decide about
Valentine. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
