A3773 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDSOX05-C     06-04 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDSOX05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    16-K job by Martinez
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Against the best pitcher in the majors right now, and
one of the best teams in the American League, the Braves needed Tom
Glavine at his best Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   It's a place he hasn't been all season, and wasn't going to find
even in the comfort of his home state with 80 family and friends
watching at Fenway Park. Not against Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez struck out 16 and won his ninth consecutive decision as
the Boston Red Sox took the first game of this interleague series
5-1, and it didn't seem that close.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez (11-1) pitched a three-hitter and lowered his
major-league best ERA to 1.91 while dominating Braves hitters like
they haven't been since losing to Randy Johnson in April.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez struck out nine of the first 19 batters he faced. Both
Andruw Jones and Randall Simon were caught swinging at pitches up
around eye level. Martinez humored the Braves by allowing a runner
to take third base in the second and fifth innings, but they
advanced no further. Andruw Jones was on third base with nobody out
in the fifth inning, but was left there as Simon and Gerald
Williams struck out and Walt Weiss popped up to short to cheers of
``Pedro, Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   The chants started up again at the end of the next inning after
Martinez collected his 10th strikeout, the third by Braves cleanup
hitter Brian Jordan. Martinez has hit double-digits in strikeouts
in eight of his 12 starts this season. Three of the four times he
missed, he had nine.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves got a little redemption with a solo home run from
Ryan Klesko in the seventh inning, but it only had to travel an
estimated 310 feet before clearing the right field wall just inside
the foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   While Martinez rolled to his 11th win, Glavine was on his way to
his seventh loss, one more than he had all last season. He survived
the first inning by allowing two runs. Four times he faced batters
with the bases loaded and had to feel good about giving up only two
runs, which he did on consecutive two-strike hits to left field by
Troy O'Leary and Damon Buford.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
