<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3774 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLIAMS-WILLIAMS_SFC     06-04 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMS-WILLIAMS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Slow but Steady, Williams-Sonoma Finally Goes Online  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The preparation of Williams-Sonoma Inc.'s Web site has been more
like that of a slow-cooking roast than a three-minute egg.
<P>
   Depending on who you ask, the kitchenware retailer's late entry
to e-commerce _ its first major site was launched just this week _
could be a benefit or a disadvantage. But if the gambit proves
successful, it could debunk the conventional wisdom that the
earliest e-commerce entrants will shut out the arrivistes.
</P>
<P>
   The early reviews are positive. By waiting, Williams-Sonoma got
its site right the first time rather than starting with a primitive
storefront and improving it through successive overhauls, said Kate
Delhagen, an analyst with Forrester Research of Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``No.1, I'd say better late than never and No.2, I'd say maybe
it's better because they're late,'' said Delhagen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Back in 1994 and 1995, when pioneering retailers like Land's
End were launching first-generation sites, San Francisco-based
Williams-Sonoma was battling bugs in the computer systems that
support its brick-and-mortar stores and catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Because of glitches at a new distribution center in Tennessee,
stock outages were common and holiday catalog shoppers were finding
the wrong gifts on their doorsteps.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious problems were corrected by mid-1996, but the
company's stock and profits had taken a beating. On top of that, a
Williams-Sonoma home page on Time-Warner's ill-fated Pathfinder
mall was a disappointment and was dropped quickly in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Williams-Sonoma's management is inherently conservative,
particularly in contrast with wild and woolly Web-only companies.
Couple that tendency with the mid-1990s computer headaches, and the
result was predictable: Executives moved cautiously in setting up
their first full-scale e-commerce site.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Williams-Sonoma launched a bridal registry with some
43,000 registrants at  &LR; www.wswedding.com.  &LR; This fall it will add an
online Williams-Sonoma store that eventually will include features
like a database of 8,000 recipes and printable grocery lists.
</P>
<P>
   Early next year, the company will open either a bridal registry
or general e-commerce site for Pottery Barn, its home furnishings
chain, and the second Pottery Barn site will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Connolly, executive vice president of Williams-Sonoma,
acknowledges his company is late to the game, but insists that's
all to the good because of improvements in Web technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt from the beginning we had to operate at a higher
standard,'' Connolly said. ``We spent a lot of time on this because
it's important that customers have the same kind of experience on
the Net that they have in our stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams-Sonoma has spent recent years ironing out wrinkles in
its existing computer and telecom systems, strengthening its
financial position in the wake of the mid-1990s problems and
plotting its Web strategy, Connolly said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; While it may have lost some sales over the years,
Williams-Sonoma avoided the cost of launching and then remodeling
its site. And it didn't alienate customers with a clumsy effort
that didn't work well, Connolly said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  As to whether a site launched in mid-1999 can still attract
eyeballs, the answer seems to be yes. In its first week, sales on
wswedding.com were running at triple the rate of toll-free
telephone orders. And there were no significant glitches, Connolly
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams-Sonoma contacted people who had signed up for the
registry in stores, only 3 percent asked that their gift lists not
be posted.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the registry, there seems to be plenty of demand on
the Web for a Williams-Sonoma store. A small site slapped up in
December with 25 holiday gift items generated twice as many sales
as expected.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday site was created to convince the company's last
foot-draggers that e-commerce should be a priority. ``That sort of
testing is already a couple of years out of date,'' noted a local
Web developer who is familiar with Williams-Sonoma's cyber efforts.
He described the company as having ``a special kind of
conservativism you'll see in the old-guard type of businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   By launching its site now, Williams-Sonoma is just squeaking
under the e-commerce wire, said Delhagen. ``If you miss the fourth
quarter of 1999, you're pretty much toast because this is going to
be another big learning season,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Next week Williams-Sonoma will begin promoting the site with
in-store signs and ads in its catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Williams-Sonoma moved quickly to set up wswedding.com after
making the final decision to proceed with it late last year. Soon
90 people were involved, half Williams-Sonoma employees and half
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara's USWeb/CKS was assigned the complicated task of
linking the Web site to the rest of Williams-Sonoma's computer
systems, from the accounting department to the Tennessee warehouse;
San Francisco's Adjacency helped design the graphics; and Prophet
Brand Strategy, also of San Francisco, coordinated the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Because Williams-Sonoma went to the trouble and expense of
integrating the site into its existing systems, it can update
registries everywhere _ in stores, in the call centers that handle
catalog orders and on the Web _ within minutes after a gift is
purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Web site is tied into Williams-Sonoma's inventory
database, shoppers are told whether a requested item is in stock
when they place an order. Many sites, including that of rival Crate
&AMP; Barrel, accept orders and then send an e-mail message hours or
days later if the item is not in stock. (Crate &AMP; Barrel currently
operates an online store and is launching its Web registry this
summer.)
</P>
<P>
   Such services are ``absolutely critical,'' Delhagen said. ``This
will put more pressure on Macy's and Crate &AMP; Barrel to get their
registries up to snuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Krishnan Menon, a partner with USWeb/CKS, estimates that only 10
to 15 percent of brick-and-mortar retailers' Web sites have fully
integrated systems. Instead, most rely on staffers to bridge the
connection by updating Web registries and checking inventories.
</P>
<P>
   John Nicolai, an e-commerce consultant with Ernst &AMP; Young in San
Francisco, said he found the site unusually attractive, easy to
use, ``and it has a lot of good information.''
</P>
<P>
   Connolly refused to divulge how much Williams-Sonoma spent to
set up the site, but the developer, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, estimated it at $3 million to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
