<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FINLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO AND RUSSIA WORK TO FILL IN PACT'S DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland _ American leaders and NATO officials said
Friday that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had yet to take
concrete steps to back up the peace accord for Kosovo and warned
that the deal could still slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story is not over,'' Strobe Talbott, the U.S. deputy
secretary of state, said Friday, before meeting with President
Martti Ahtisaari of Finland, who acted as an envoy for NATO.
``Trust does not belong in the vocabulary,'' Talbott remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all their caveats, American and Finnish diplomats
declared themselves genuinely optimistic and indeed surprised by
Milosevic's abrupt turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Chernomyrdin, representing Russia in the negotiations,
canceled plans for a meeting Friday with Talbott and Ahtisaari in
Helsinki and flew back to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats from all three countries said Chernomyrdin changed his
plans in order to shore up political support for the deal in
Moscow. Russian and American officials remain at odds over at least
one important aspect of the plan _ the extent to which Russian
peacekeeping troops in Yugoslavia would be under NATO authority.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott said Milosevic must now come up with concrete measures
to make good on his pledge, in particular how he plans to
accommodate international troops in Kosovo with NATO in a ``core''
role.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Yugoslav leaders plan to meet on Saturday on the
Macedonian border with Yugoslavia, the first effort to establish
what Talbott called ``military-to-military'' contacts. Talbott said
such military talks appeared Friday to be the best approach.
``That's where the action is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   American officials must still work out at least one major issue
with the Russians. Russia adamantly objects to the idea of putting
its troops under NATO control, since NATO was founded as an
anti-Soviet military alliance and Russia's post-communist leaders
are deeply unhappy about NATO's expansion into central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   American leaders badly want to retain Russian support in dealing
with Milosevic, and diplomats on all sides say that Chernomyrdin's
agreement with NATO was crucial to Milosevic's consent to the deal
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   American officials plainly hope to smooth their way around the
issue by creating a force that would be dominated by NATO yet not
be an official NATO enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a precedent for Russian government participation in
an international peacekeeping operation that does not have NATO in
the name,'' Talbott said. ``We did in Bosnia and I think we can do
it again in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari pursued a diplomatic effort for much of the past
month, though he studiously kept himself out of the spotlight until
just a few days ago. Even after leaving Belgrade, the Yugoslav
capital, with the new promises from Milosevic, Ahtisaari has let
others do most of the talking.
</P>
<P>
   American officials went out of their way Friday to praise
Ahtisaari's efforts. Talbott called him one of the ``heroes'' of
the last few days and said he had struck ``exactly the right note''
in conveying the proposal to Belgrade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 2205EDT &QL; 
