</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) KUKES, Albania -- June 4, 1999 -- KOSOVO-KUKES-COX, 6-4
-- With the camps full, refugees arriving in Kukes have made camps
in city parks and other open areas. Here, refugees live outside the
town's central mosque. International relief agencies are attempting
to persuade the refugees in Kukes, about 100,000 of them, to move
to other places in Albania. (Charles W. Holmes/Cox News Service
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) SEMA, Albania -- June 4, 1999 -- KOSOVO-KLA-COX, 6-4 --
Sabri Jmahone listens to news about a peace deal for Kosovo as his
family prepares to have breakfast in Camp Hope, a U.S.- built
refugee camp for 20,000 refugees from Kosovo in southern Albania.
Jmahone greeted the news with considerable skeptism, saying he will
have to see NATO troops in Kosovo before he and his family will
return. (Bert Rought Jr./Cox Newspapers Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) FORT DIX, N.J. -- June 4, 1999 -- KOSOVO-U.S.-REFUGEES,
6-4 -- Riza Demiri, right, becomes emotional after hearing of the
latest developments in his native Kosovo from Rudi Rubik, a fellow
ethnic Albanian refugee from Kosovo, on Friday. Rudi, one of
hundreds of refugees living at this Army base while waiting for a
home, had mixed feelings Friday about a possible peace agreement in
his troubled homeland. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- June 4, 1999 -- KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX, 6-4 --
President Clinton gives a thumb-up as he leaves the East Room of
the White House following an awards ceremony honoring companies
with exceptional track records on hiring people with disabilities
on Friday. Earlier, President Clinton told reporters that he was
``anxious to end the bombing'' in Kosovo but not until NATO had
proof that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was complying with
the alliance's terms. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- June 4, 1999 -- ANASTASIA-BALLET-REVIEW ,
6-4 -- Viviana Durante dancing in the role of Grand Duchess
Anastasia in the American Ballet Theatre's production of
``Anastasia'' at the Metropolitan Opera House. The production is
marvelously danced, but the choreography is uneven. (Michelle V.
Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- June 4, 1999 -- HARVARD-REFUGEE-BOS,
6-4 -- Selamawi Asgedom, a half-Ethiopian, half-Eritrean refugee,
will give the senior English oration on Harvard's Commencement Day.
While it has been a long journey from the snake-infested refugee
camps of the Sudan to Harvard's Tercentenary Theatre, America has
not been the safe haven Asgedom's family thought it would be.
Asgedom's father and brother were killed in separate accidents by
drunk drivers in the United States. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BOSTON -- June 4, 1999 -- HORSE-MONTY-BOS, 6-4 -- Monty
Roberts, 64, travels from town to town spreading the latest gospel
on nonviolent horsemanship, is now on a mission to teach
non-violence toward people as well. ``What we've done to the horse
is criminal,'' he says. ``We must make it up to a species that has
been wonderful to us while we've abused and mistreated them. For no
reason except ignorance.'' (Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) HOUSTON -- June 4, 1999 -- PLASTIC-RADIOS-HNS, 06-04 --
Annette Wilzig and her husband Thom Andriola in front of their
extensive collection of 250 plastic radios, from table-top models
to transistors. ``They're just beautiful to look at,'' says
Andriola, whose radios provide a visual history of the plastic
radio from the 1930s to the early 1970s. (Andrew Innerarity/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
