<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3779 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPEN-OPEN_SFCHRON &LR;      06-04 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEN-OPEN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 AT&AMP;T Ordered to Open Cable Line Access  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In a groundbreaking decision that could give consumers more choices
and lower prices for high-speed Internet access, a federal judge in
Portland has ruled that AT&AMP;T must open its cable lines in that city
to competitors such as America Online and other Internet service
providers.
<P>
   The ruling is significant for San Francisco and other cities,
which have been closely watching the Portland case and may model
their own policies based on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   If the ruling survives appeals, it could set a nationwide
precedent, allowing customers to get high-speed Internet access via
cable TV from several providers, not just the company that owns the
cable.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is a blow to AT&AMP;T, which has been trying to keep
control of the cable TV lines it inherited when it bought TCI
Cable &UR;  &LR; earlier this year. The decision is the first to chip away at
AT&AMP;T's growing cable empire, which will be the nation's No.1 cable
company if its planned purchase of MediaOne Group goes through.
</P>
<P>
   It is also damaging to Redwood City's Excite AtHome, the
high-flying Internet company. AT&AMP;T owns 40 percent of Excite AtHome
and controls 70 percent of its board votes.
</P>
<P>
   Excite AtHome, which offers consumers a super-fast way to surf
the Internet via cable TV lines, would have to share its
proprietary lines with other ISPs like AOL and Prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   The decision sent Excite AtHome's stock tumbling by $10.75 to
$94.50 yesterday. AT&AMP;T shares slipped 88 cents to $53.38, while AOL
rose $12 to $117.75.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T officials called the decision ``inexplicable'' and said it
would appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to believe strongly in the merits of our legal
arguments,'' said Mark Rosenblum, AT&AMP;T vice president. ``AT&AMP;T
raised numerous substantial challenges. ... This decision can only
have the potential to delay and reduce the new services that
companies like AT&AMP;T will be able to offer them.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who pressed for AT&AMP;T to open its cable lines said the
decision is a win for consumers and one that may be hard to
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is potentially very far-reaching because many
cities ... have been waiting to see what the Portland court does,''
said John Raposa, assistant general counsel for GTE Corp. ``What
this means is that consumers can have a choice of ISPs and won't be
locked into AT&AMP;T's affiliate, Excite AtHome.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling stems from a lawsuit filed by AT&AMP;T and TCI Cable
against the city of Portland. &UR;  &LR; When AT&AMP;T bought TCI, it had to
apply for a ``transfer of control'' of TCI's cable TV franchises in
each city where TCI operates.
</P>
<P>
   As a condition of approving the franchise transfer in Portland,
officials there wanted to force AT&AMP;T to lease its cable lines to
competitors so they could offer phone, video and high-speed
Internet access. Portland officials argued that without ``open
access,'' TCI customers would have only one choice for high-speed
Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and TCI sued Portland, saying cities had no right to
require open access as a condition of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, U.S. District Judge Owen Panner disagreed, saying
cable regulators in Portland can require open access as a condition
of AT&AMP;T's $55 billion purchase of TCI Cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The open access requirement is within the authority of the
city and county to protect competition,'' Panner wrote in his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said the decision will be hard to challenge
given AT&AMP;T's dominance in the cable market. If it buys Denver-based
MediaOne, it will be the nation's No.1 cable company with more than
16 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that AT&AMP;T has a dominant position in the cable industry,
if they don't open their networks to competitors, everyone loses,''
said Jeffrey Kagan, a telecommunications analyst in Atlanta. ``With
size comes responsibility. Had they remained a 20 percent market
share player, it would have been an issue in only those markets,
but if they're a 60 percent market share player and they're keeping
AOL and other ISPs out of the competitive marketplace for those
high-speed services, it will harm competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, if Bay Area customers want to connect to the Internet
via cable TV lines, they have to go through Excite AtHome. The
service is available in about 40 Bay Area communities for $40 a
month, on top of the fee for cable TV service.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to acting as a fast ISP, Excite AtHome also offers
content, e-mail and other services _ putting it in direct
competition with AOL.
</P>
<P>
   To fight back, AOL wants to let its customers access its content
via cable modems, which are about 100 times faster than traditional
dial-up modems. Earlier this year, AOL tried to buy MediaOne so it
could get access to cable lines, but eventually dropped out of the
bidding after AT&AMP;T increased its offer. The only other way to
access cable lines is to lease them from the provider, and AT&AMP;T has
been reluctant to lease its lines to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's ruling would change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``What open access would mean is just as you can now use your
phone line to dial any ISP, you'd be able to use your cable modem
to connect to any ISP,'' said Katie Roper, acting executive
director of the Bay Area Open Access Coalition. ``You wouldn't be
restricted to the ISP that is affiliated with the cable provider,
in this case Excite AtHome.''
</P>
<P>
   Most ISPs also are signing agreements with phone companies to
offer a fast Internet service called digital subscriber line, but
DSL is still &LR; not as fast as a cable modem.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry watchers warned that yesterday's decision could
have a ``chilling effect'' on AT&AMP;T's plans to upgrade TCI's cable
systems to handle high-speed access. If AT&AMP;T has to share its cable
lines _ and thus give up market share _ the company might be
reluctant to upgrade quickly, said Vince Tobkin, who follows
telecommunications for consulting firm Bain &AMP; Co. in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may chill AT&AMP;T's interest in investing capital to upgrade
its network and it could have the perverse effect of slowing down
high-speed access,'' Tobkin said. ``For any community that does
this, they can be sure they'll be moved to the back of the list for
spending.''
</P>
<P>
   But others disagreed, saying AT&AMP;T bought TCI so it could offer
phone and Internet access to customers and is not likely to upset
shareholders by backing away from that strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T spent a fortune to buy TCI and in order to make it work,
they have to upgrade their cable. If they don't, shareholders could
revolt,'' said Kagan, the telecommunications analyst.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
