<HEADER>
A3784 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUC-PUC_SFCHRON &LR;      06-04 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-PUC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Governor Davis to Replace PUC Reps 
 &HT;     By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Two interim commissioners appointed just before Thursday's Public
Utilities Commission meeting apparently won't be back for next
Thursday's meeting, according to a spokesman for Governor Gray
Davis.
<P>
   ``They have not been unappointed quite yet, but they will be
shortly,'' said Davis press secretary Michael Bustamante.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamic duo that practically parachuted into Thursday's PUC
meeting were Loretta Lynch, director of the governor's Office of
Planning and Research, and Tal Finney, the governor's director of
policy. Both had been sworn in that morning to the $100,000-a-year
positions that normally carry six-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   PUC President Richard Bilas said he was alerted new
commissioners were coming only an hour before the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Bilas said he knew they were temporary, but assumed they'd be
around longer than a day or two. After all, Steve Jobs has been
Apple Computer's interim CEO for almost two years now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``We've got computers, offices, secretaries, cars and advisers
for them. Everything,'' Bilas said.
</P>
<P>
   The quick decommissioning of the commissioners seems to support
speculation that the two Davis aides had been appointed merely to
delay three crucial votes scheduled for Thursday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The current rumor is that Davis will have permanent replacements
ready for the PUC's next meeting on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The name that pops up most often is Southern Californian Carl
Wood, a national representative for the Utility Workers Union of
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible this commissioner-du-jour drama was a stop-gap
measure and he has permanent members in the wings,'' said Nettie
Hoge, director of the consumer group, The Utility Reform Network.
``It's the only explanation that makes any sense. Otherwise, what
was accomplished?''
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time that Davis has plugged holes with
temporary appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Finney has been a gubernatorial ``temp'' on four previous
occasions, dispatched to short stints at the Department of Social
Services, the Agricultural Labor Relations Board, the Managed Risk
Medical Board and the California Earthquake Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Until Davis took office, such temporary appointments were almost
unprecedented in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   One of the last times it happened was two decades ago, when
then-Governror Jerry Brown appointed an aide named Gray Davis to a
temporary stint on the California Horse Racing Board to settle a
beef with the Service Employees International Union.
</P>
<P>
   It's less clear what the purpose of this week's PUC appointments
may have been. The pair's first, and perhaps only, act was to ask
that the full commission delay votes on three issues:
</P>
<P>
   One decision could have raised the cost of Internet access for
consumers by changing the way phone companies pay each other for
completing each other's calls.
</P>
<P>
   Another would have let electric utilities earn as much as an
11.6 percent profit on regulated activities. Consumer advocates
have favored a lower profit cap, something closer to 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The final measure would establish the PUC's position on a bill
that would change it governance structure. One thing the bill would
do is allow the PUC's president to be picked by the governor _ not
by peer selection.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Finney nor Lynch returned phone calls yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   They clearly understood their assignments were interim, but
neither seemed to know how brief the tenure was to be.
</P>
<P>
   Following Thursday's meeting, each gathered up armloads of
materials which they said they were going to read over the weekend
in preparation for next week's PUC meeting.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
