r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-VICTIMS-TEX     06-04 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-VICTIMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO CRASH VICTIMS SHARED DESIRE TO SEE FRIENDS IN ARKANSAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By YVETTE CRAIG 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ One couldn't wait to return to childhood
friends in her tranquil hometown. Another planned to meet an
Internet friend for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Elizabeth Couch and Debra Ann Sattari didn't know each
other, but they shared a goal of getting to Little Rock on American
Airlines Flight 1420.
</P>
<P>
   Neither made it.
</P>
<P>
   They were among the nine people killed when the jetliner crashed
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Couch, 68, stunned her hometown of Havana, Ark., a
farming community with a population of 350. She was on the flight
with a group of widows and older couples returning from London.
</P>
<P>
   Five tour group members from the nearby town of Russellville
also perished in the fiery crash.
</P>
<P>
   Their deaths came just a month after three other Russellville
residents _ Jim and Floye Patterson and their daughter, Jennifer _
died when an amphibious tourist craft sank on Lake Hamilton near
Hot Springs, the ``Arkansas Democrat-Gazette'' reported.
</P>
<P>
   Couch loved animals and had nine cats and a dog. A mother of
three adult children, she had a daily routine that began with a
stop at the local post office.
</P>
<P>
   Then she would head to the Guinn McBride country store and later
take a 2-mile walk with friends before an evening visit with
members of the Active Extensions Homemakers Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to believe what happened,'' said Norman Jones,
Havana's postmaster. ``There's an empty place in my stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Couch often exchanged friendly ribbing with him and
the postal carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, her mother was the postmaster,'' he said. ``I think
that's why she was so comfortable coming here every day. ... Later,
her mother and father ran the town's bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Gillespie, who had known Couch since the seventh grade,
said the two were like sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``She used to love the (University of Arkansas) Razorbacks,''
Gillespie said, laughing. ``She couldn't watch it if the game was
too close. She'd call me to find out who won.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie said she won't question why the tragedy occurred.
</P>
<P>
   In California on Friday, Victoria Cutchens answered the
telephone in a voice heavy with grief. But as she reminisced about
her best friend, Sattari, she broke into laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to describe Debra is that she was all heart,''
said Cutchens, whose home is across the street from Sattari's.
``Whenever times were tough, she used to tell me, `When God gives
you lemons, you make lemonade.' I'll never forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sattari, 38, the mother of a 19-year-old son, was on medical
leave from her job as food-and-beverage manager for the
Hiddenbrooke Country Club in Vallejo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   When she wasn't relaxing by listening to soft jazz, she occupied
her time chatting on the Internet. She established a friendship
with someone she had planned to meet for the first time in Little
Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Sattari was scheduled to return Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debra hated to fly,'' Cutchens said. ``She was afraid to fly.
She decided to take this trip because she thought it would be good
for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Sattari's sister, a flight attendant for American Airlines,
arranged for a complimentary first-class ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Cutchens said that word of her friend's death left her
distressed and fighting for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was her destiny,'' Cutchens said. ``This was her date
with God.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
