<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3788 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-SURVIVORS-TEX     06-04 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SURVIVORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE CRASH SURVIVORS FACE LONG RECOVERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GABRIELLE CRIST 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ When 8-year-old Samantha Salmans closes her
eyes, the crash of Flight 1420 is in her mind. But she spends most
of her time dreading the next dressing change for the burns that
cover 20 percent of her body.
</P>
<P>
   The youngster from Cabot, Ark., is one of three crash survivors
recovering in the Arkansas Children's Hospital 10-bed burn unit.
All three have long, very painful recoveries ahead of them,
hospital officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha seems to be lucky as far as burn injuries go: She might
be able to go home within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Maddox, 22, of Ponca City, Okla., is on a ventilator and
has burns on her arms and face. Maddox's hospital roommate and
acquaintance, 14-year-old Rachel Fuller of Arkadelphia, also is on
a ventilator and has burns on 55 percent of her body. Both will
need skin grafts.
</P>
<P>
   It's the dressing changes that are the most painful.
</P>
<P>
   During the changes, doctors and nurses at the state's only burn
unit unwrap the dressings from the burns, which sometimes have
exposed nerve endings. The burns then must be cleaned and redressed
to prevent infection, said Esther Pipkin, a specialist with the
hospital's Child Life &AMP; Education Department who works with
children in the burn and rehabilitative units and provides support
to their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every move that they make hurts. Every anticipation of every
move hurts,'' Pipkin said.
</P>
<P>
   It takes up to four hours to change the dressings that cover
Rachel's burns, hospital officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Pipkin has spent time with the three survivors, trying to help
them cope with the crash, their burns and the scars that will
forever be with them.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Pipkin uses dolls to show the younger children how
different medical procedures will work. Sometimes she plays music
for them or provides a distraction during a dressing change.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the time, Pipkin just listens and holds their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox is smiling and using hand signals, and she requested some
classical music, which she plays in her room.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel can't talk because she is on a ventilator. She's still
disoriented, Pipkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha is still in a lot of pain and has had to spend most her
energy dealing with the medical procedures that consume her day.
But the trauma of the plane crash hasn't escaped her, Pipkin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she closes her eyes, she still sees it,'' Pipkin said.
``She's a very intelligent little girl.''
</P>
<P>
   For burn patients, the first 72 hours are the most critical,
said Sandra Meredith, a nurse and burn unit manager.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the risk of infection, burns cause patients to lose
fluids, and they increase patients' body temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nutrition is a huge part of'' the healing process, Meredith
said. ``If you were burned today, your required caloric intake
would double tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the pain medication, the trauma of the fire and the
pain, however, most patients cannot eat, so they are fed through
tubes, Meredith said.
</P>
<P>
   Once patients learn to cope with the agony of a dressing change
and the pain of movement, they have to work through the emotional
trauma of being scarred forever.
</P>
<P>
   At first they don't seem to understand that their scars are
permanent, Meredith said. Once they do, depression sets in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't force them to look in the mirror if they've been
burned in the face,'' Meredith said.
</P>
<P>
   Because patients feel they've lost control of their lives,
hospital staff members allow them to hang posters in their rooms
and listen to whatever music they like, Meredith said.
</P>
<P>
   Some patients attend Camp Sunshine, a three-day camp for burn
victims. There, those who were recently injured can meet other burn
victims, Meredith said, and ``see that life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   If patients are still in school, a team from the Child Life &AMP;
Education Department will visit the patient's class, explaining to
classmates what a burn feels like and showing them pictures of the
patient's wounds.
</P>
<P>
   That prevents the ``recoil'' that often happens when someone
first sees a burn victim, Meredith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the child knows what to expect, it's not such a shock,''
Meredith said.
</P>
<P>
   And although Samantha, Rachel and Maddox are not yet showing any
signs of depression, they, too, will experience a range of emotions
as they heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether that lasts an hour, a day or a month, that depends,''
Meredith said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
