A3792 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-LAWSUIT-TEX     06-04 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-LAWSUIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH VICTIM SUES AMERICAN AIRLINES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEANNA BOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. An Arkansas man who survived the American
Airlines crash sued Friday, saying that the pilots were negligent
in landing the plane in tumultuous weather.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit names the airline as the only defendant and does not
specify the amount of damages sought.
</P>
<P>
   Little Rock attorney Peter Miller sued on behalf of Darrell
Arnold of Cabot, a 38-year-old truck driver who suffered cuts,
bruises, and back and neck injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he has asked Arlington, Texas, attorney Bob Bodoin
to assist in the case. Bodoin represented Walter Ward Richardson, a
North Texas man awarded $4.75 million for injuries suffered in the
1989 crash of an American Airlines plane at Chicago's O'Hare
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that although filing the suit three days after the
crash may seem premature, he and his client believe that the
airline was negligent in endangering the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a passenger in a plane that was apparently negligently
operated,'' Miller said. ``The plane crashed, and he was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear in my mind that American Airlines is at fault.''
</P>
<P>
   American spokesman Al Becker said company attorneys had not seen
the suit and had no comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus right now is on taking care of the needs of
passengers and the families of the victims,'' Becker said. ``Beyond
that we will have no other comment.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilot of the McDonnell Douglas Super 80 jetliner and eight
passengers were killed in the crash. At least 82 of the 136
survivors were injured, some critically.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold's suit alleges that the cockpit crew did not follow
``established or reasonable and prudent procedures'' for landing an
aircraft in bad weather. The suit also accuses the crew of
negligence for not advising and preparing passengers for the
emergency situation and not evacuating them using ``established or
reasonable and prudent emergency procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodoin said the plane that crashed is not designed to land in
crosswinds exceeding 35 knots (40.25 mph). The plane crashed at
11:51 p.m Tuesday, when winds at Little Rock National Airport were
clocked at 35 mph. Within five minutes, federal investigators have
said, a gust of more than 80 mph was recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold was sitting in seat 15F when the jet skidded on the
runway and barreled through steel poles supporting lighting
structures, splitting the plane into three pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold escaped by slipping through a rip in the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Since the crash, Miller said, Arnold has suffered ``intense''
mental pain and anguish.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been having flashbacks, dizzy spells. He's been having
panic attacks,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines sent all passengers on the jet $25,000 checks
for unanticipated expenses. Although the checks came with ``no
strings attached,'' Miller described them as ``hush money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want the victims to call lawyers. They don't want
the victims to assert their rights. They want the victims to think,
`Well, American is giving us this money, and that's nice.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that since Tuesday night's crash, he has received
about five or six phone calls from people involved in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas law prevents lawyers from calling or visiting accident
victims for 30 days. Lawyers can, however, send direct mail to the
injured if it is in an envelope marked ``advertisement'' in red
letters.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he routinely advertises on television but does not
send out letters.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
