<HEADER>
A3796 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-SCENE-TEX     06-04 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SCENE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVORS SHOCKED AT SIGHT OF DAMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ When American Airlines Flight 1420 broke
apart, Stephanie Manus could think only of saving her two young
daughters. With the help of two other passengers, Manus carried
Lauren, 4, and Emily, 2, to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Benton resident was on one of the seven buses that
returned survivors to the crumpled McDonnell Douglas Super 80,
allowing passengers to comprehend how they survived as the jet
separated and caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to see it,'' Manus said. ``I had no idea the plane
was damaged that badly. You could see where it had burned above our
seats. It just makes me even more thankful that I got my daughters
out alive.''
</P>
<P>
   In what was similar to a presidential motorcade, the passengers
were escorted slowly along a taxiway adjacent to Runway 4R. The
buses were flanked by five police motorcycles, three police cars
and an ambulance. The buses stopped at a distance from the
wreckage, and passengers and relatives got out to look at the site
in daylight. Some of the injured looked at the debris from
wheelchairs. Some took photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Manus talked to reporters outside the Excelsior Hotel in
downtown Little Rock shortly after returning from Little Rock
National Airport. Most of the passengers were too upset to talk
after the hourlong visit as they entered the hotel escorted by
American Airlines support teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible,'' said one woman, who had her left hand in a
cast, before declining to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Manus, who was comforted by her husband, Jimmy Manus, credited
two men sitting near her on the plane with leading her children to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thank God those men were there,'' Stephanie Manus said
as she began crying. ``They were looking after our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Manus, who was inside the terminal and saw the plane land,
is worried about the psychological toll on Lauren. Both girls
escaped serious injury in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry if this is going to hit her later,'' Jimmy Manus said.
``I don't want her to be scarred by this event but, right now, we
just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Manus was critical of American for landing the plane
in the middle of a thunderstorm. The couple also complained about
the way the airline and the airport responded to the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the plane go by and then waited and waited,'' Jimmy
Manus said. ``Then Stephanie called me on a cell phone, and said
she was OK and she was off the plane, and I was like, `What?
Where?' That's when she said they had crashed. We weren't told
anything for several hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many survivors were overcome by emotion after seeing
the site where nine lost their lives, Caroline Golden, 20, was
remarkably composed. The Ouachita Baptist University sophomore was
part of a school choir returning from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it will affect me later, but I haven't been
crying,'' Golden said. ``I was really surprised by the damage. I
didn't think it was that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   One member of the choir, James Harrison, 21, died in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel lucky I got out, that I wasn't hurt,'' Golden said. ``I
just remember the plane coming down and looking back and seeing
flames. For a second, I thought that was the only way out and then
someone pointed to an opening in the plane and I climbed out.''
</P>
<P>
   At the crash site Friday, Golden took photographs and swapped
addresses with other passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a time to see other people and see that they were
all right,'' Golden said. ``We plan on talking to each other again
and remembering that we survived. I'm just relieved that most of us
got out of there. When you look at the damage, it's kind of
shocking that so many of us made it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
