<HEADER>
A3801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      06-04 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EXPECT A FED RATE INCREASE
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices rallied and bond prices moved slightly lower as
investors signaled that many expected a rate increase when Federal
Reserve policy-makers meet at the end of this month. The selloffs
in stocks since May 18, when the Fed first indicated it was leaning
toward a rate increase, have been enough to compensate for higher
interest rates, in the view of many investors. Sectors that had
been hit particularly hard, including drugs, banks and technology
stocks, helped lead the rally Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 136.15 points, or 1.28
percent, to 10,799.84, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500
stocks rose 28.21 points, or 2.17 percent, to 1,327.75. The NASDAQ
composite index, which had dropped 10 percent from its recent high,
jumped 75.02 points, or 3.12 percent, to 2,478.34.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond inched up to 5.96
percent, from 5.95 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   BANKERS TRUST ACQUIRED; JOBS CUT
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank, sealing its position as the world's largest bank,
completed its $9 billion acquisition of Bankers Trust and said it
planned to phase out use of the Bankers Trust brand name. A round
of layoffs also began at Bankers Trust with large job cuts in the
fixed-income business. Deutsche has announced a plan to lay off
5,500 people from both companies over a three-year period.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL LYNCH STARTS DEAL TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch said that it would begin settlement discussions or
seek additional information on about one-third of the 904 sexual
discrimination claims filed against it by current or former
employees.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN CLOSES AN INSURANCE COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   Japanese authorities suspended operations of Toho Mutual Life
Insurance Co., which has a link to GE Capital of the United States.
Although Toho is only the second major insurer in Japan to go out
of business since World War II, its trouble underscores
industrywide problems.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINE AIRLINES RAISES CAPITAL
</P>
<P>
   Debt-ridden Philippine Airlines met the deadline to raise $200
million or face liquidation. But half the money comes from its
largest shareholder, Lucio Tan. Creditors have been increasingly
hostile toward him and may not support his bid to keep control of
the carrier. And Cathay Pacific Airways is preparing for talks with
its pilots to resolve a dispute that has grounded many of its
flights since May 28, but analysts were cautious about the outlook
for the talks.
</P>
<P>
   RESOLUTION SOUGHT ON GOLD SALES
</P>
<P>
   The head of the International Monetary Fund, Michel Camdessus,
said that he hoped the thorny issue of sales of gold from IMF
reserves could be resolved before the fund's annual meeting in
September. The sale proceeds would be used to create a trust fund
to aid poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. TRIES TO UNDERCUT MICROSOFT
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft introduced a host of evidence this week to show that
the Netscape browser was still healthy and thriving. But in a
single stroke, a government lawyer undercut Microsoft's strategy by
producing a Microsoft e-mail written in January suggesting that the
company had cynically and selectively produced data to support this
point of view.
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON.COM SEEKS COURT RULING
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com sought a ruling in federal court to allow it to
continue posting The New York Times best-seller lists online after
the newspaper had demanded that the Seattle company stop publishing
the lists in the absence of a licensing agreement.
</P>
<P>
   PATENT FRAUD COMPLAINT DISMISSED
</P>
<P>
   A judge dismissed a government complaint accusing Visx, the
maker of vision-correction lasers, of patent fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
