<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3802 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-LEDE-TEX     06-04 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INKSTER, KANE SHARE LEAD, RECORD PACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ Juli Inkster buried a 30-foot birdie putt on
her final stroke of yesterday's second round, joining Lorie Kane on
a pace to par their remaining 36 holes and still tie the tournament
scoring record at the U.S. Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Inkster uttered the words that cut to the quick of every
U.S. Golf Association official at Old Waverly Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this golf course, 10 under is not going to win this
tournament,'' said Inkster, who joined Kane at 10 under par through
36 holes after a second-round 69. ``You've got to go out and make
some birdies. I know that you can't play to the middle of the
greens. You have to be aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different mind-set for the Open. But I don't think
there's anything wrong with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, a birdie-fest was not what USGA officials had in
mind when Old Waverly was selected as site of this event. But the
rough topped out at two inches, about half its target height,
because of Mississippi's sizzling spring temperatures. In addition,
heavy rains Wednesday night and a light shower after the opening
round Thursday left greens soft and receptive for a second
consecutive day. And the wind has not been a factor in determining
scoring conditions in either round.
</P>
<P>
   Kane took full advantage, firing a second-round 64 that matched
the lowest score of the tournament and tied the Open record for
lowest in relation to par (8 under) in any round. By the end of the
day, Becky Iverson leaped onto the leader board with a 64 of her
own, moving to 8 under for the tournament and a stroke behind
Dallas resident Kelli Kuehne (9 under), the first-round leader who
opened with 64 but slid to 71 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother Nature is dictating a lot more of this than the golf
course,'' said Dottie Pepper, who moved to 7 under after a
second-round 69. ``Some people have termed this an easy course, but
that's not something I agree with.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet that figures to be Old Waverly's legacy in Women's Open
lore, unless a radical reversal of fortune takes place during the
weekend rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the scoring records in the books for the 1999 Women's
Open:
</P>
<P>
   Lowest cut total (even par) in tournament history, eclipsing the
mark of 3 over set at the 1993 Open at Crooked Stick Golf Club in
Carmel, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Most sub-par rounds in tournament history (105), with two days
remaining. The mark was 89, set over four days in 1993 at Crooked
Stick.
</P>
<P>
   Most sub-par rounds in a single day (62), set yesterday. The
previous high was 43, set in the opening round at Old Waverly.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, 44 of the 63 cut survivors will carry under-par totals
into the weekend rounds, the most in Open history.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely an element of playing aggressively,'' said
Kane, who balanced nine birdies with a bogey. ``I birdied the first
three holes \Ryesterday\S and that set the tone. That's the type of
player I am. If I can get rolling early, I'm comfortable for the
whole day.''
</P>
<P>
   Meg Mallon (4 under), who won the 1991 Women's Open at Colonial
Country Club, predicted some ``payback'' from USGA officials in the
form of well-tucked pins for the weekend rounds. Inkster suggested
that might not matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as it doesn't set a standard, I think one year of
really low scores is OK at the Open.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
