<SLUG> BC-ALLERGY-BLUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH POLLEN COUNTS MEAN SWAMPED ALLERGY CLINICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On top of a building in downtown Brooklyn _ with nice
views of the harbor on one side and Manhattan on the other _ sits a
little monitor of human misery called a Rotorod Sampler, Model 140.
</P>
<P>
   It's about the size of a hatbox, with a whirligig that twirls in
the breeze. And every weekday afternoon, Dr. Ishtiaq Chaudhry makes
his way upstairs to hear it tell its sad tale. ``Today,'' he
announces, after extracting a pair of tiny glass rods and checking
them under a microscope, ``we have 61. Another bad day.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not measuring bad vibes, but he might as well be. He is
counting grass pollen, which along with tree pollens waged its
nastiest assault in years last spring and summer on more than one
million seasonal allergy sufferers across the New York metropolitan
region. This year, according to the detector, it is much worse.
</P>
<P>
   But Chaudhry does not need a machine to know this. Downstairs in
the allergy clinic at Long Island College Hospital, there are a
dozen wheezing, watery-eyed, walking pollen detectors like
Christina Clum, who describes what feels like ``a bunch of pollen
lodged in the back of my throat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If my nose isn't running all over the place,'' complains Ms.
Clum, 30, a freelance camera assistant, ``it's totally clogged
up.'' Right now, it is clogged up, and she sounds like she cannot
decide whether to talk or breathe.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a month now, allergy clinics and doctors' offices
across the city, the suburbs and beyond have been swamped with the
same complaints. People say they are itching in places they cannot
scratch. They are astounded at the amount of stuff coming out of
their noses all day. It hurts to eat because the roofs of their
mouths have become raw. People tell horror stories of going to
their cars and finding them coated with a menacing green fuzz, like
targets of chemical warfare.
</P>
<P>
   And the heavy pollen counts contribute to more than just
miserable-but-ultimately-manageable suffering. In the Bronx, for
example, the Childhood Asthma Initiative at Montefiore Medical
Center is treating nearly 300 children who live in city shelters _
many with little continuous health care. Half of the asthmatic
children have seasonal allergies, which can trigger dangerous
asthma attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to add antihistamines to a lot of the asthma
treatments,'' said Dr. Shawn Bowen at Montefiore. ``Their coughing
was getting worse, and their asthma was getting worse. We're seeing
a lot of children much younger than usual with runny noses and
itchy eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say several factors have contributed to the feeling
sweeping through the region in recent weeks that some kind of
allergy apocalypse is under way. For one thing, two mild winters
have promoted the growth of pollen-producing grass and weeds. Then,
this spring, the tree pollen season, which usually tapers off in
late April and gives sufferers a respite, got pushed far into May
because of a dozen rainy days in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to put yourself in the place of the poor tree,''
explains Dr. Ira Finegold, chief of allergy at St. Luke's-Roosevelt
Hospital Center, which is receiving hundreds of allergy sufferers
who complain of being assaulted by Central Park. ``Trees don't have
any pretty flowers to attract insects; they have to put their
pollen airborne. So they wait for good conditions, and balmy, dry
days are great.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially in his profession, Finegold should be careful about
betraying any feelings for trees. One day last week in Brooklyn,
just after Alicia Sirico, 7, was examined by her allergy doctor,
she sat near the waiting room and colored in a picture she had
drawn: It showed a tree with a villainous, scowling face. She
leaned over to her mother, Maria, and whispered: ``Mommy, please
tell the doctor I do this all the time.'' Then she started to
twitch her nose like something had landed on it.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arlene T. Schneider, acting chairwoman of the Department of
Allergy and Immunology at Long Island College Hospital, says that
the hospital's pollen counter, the only one in the city that
supplies data to the National Allergy Bureau in Milwaukee, recorded
nine days in May with a grass pollen count of more than 100, which
is considered high. Last year in May, only three days showed those
levels. Also this May, there were 18 days with counts above 30 _
which is when allergic people start showing symptoms _ compared
with 12 such days last May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year for the past three years we've had higher and higher
counts,'' Dr. Schneider said, adding that grasses _ all with such
idyllic-sounding names as timothy and orchard, sweet vernal and
meadow fescue _ can waft their pollen airborne as far as 300 or 400
miles, meaning that a window washer on a tower in midtown could get
pollen from Wheeling, W. Va., stuck in his eyeballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't think,'' she said, ``that if you're in the middle of a
city you'll be protected.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way to achieve some measure of protection is to follow
allergists' rules, which sound a lot like guidelines for becoming a
recluse: don't go out when it's windy or in the morning, because
that is when pollen is usually emitted; keep your windows closed at
home and in your car; don't hang anything outside to dry; don't
work in your yard; don't have too many indoor plants; keep your air
conditioner and your air filter humming; make sure to take the
cocktail of pills and nose sprays that you will probably need to
control your symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   And here's some other great news: seasonal allergies generally
work on a principle called ``priming,'' which Finegold explains is
a technical way to say that things will get worse before they get
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that when allergy season starts, your whole system
gets completely primed to respond, and when the next allergen comes
along, it hits you even harder,'' he said. By July 4 the height of
the grass pollen season will have passed. But by mid-August,
ragweed season, which causes hay fever, will take its place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
