<SLUG> BC-GLF-NFL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWDED AT TOP: TREVINO SHARES LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON, N.J. _ After nine holes Friday, Lee Trevino's
appearance in the Cadillac NFL Golf Classic had the look of another
forgettable round, one that would make him a postscript to a
tournament he once dominated. Heading to the back nine at the Upper
Montclair Country Club, Trevino was sent off with no more than
polite applause from the gallery, something that came as little
surprise to Trevino, a winner only once on the Senior Tour in the
last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Five birdies and two hours later, Trevino approached the 18th
green greeted by a cheering crowd that whistled and hooted. His
ball awaited where he had hit it from 60 yards away _ 10 inches
from the cup _ and after his tap-in birdie, the 59-year-old Trevino
was tied for the first-round lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I tell you; I'm big in New Jersey,'' Trevino said
moments after his five-under-par 67 left him tied with five other
golfers. ``Man, they like me here.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two years after he burst on the national scene with a
fifth-place finish at the United States Open at the nearby
Baltusrol Country Club and six years after he won the inaugural
Cadillac NFL Golf Classic, Trevino was back in New Jersey and
proclaiming his admiration for everything about the state, even the
way the locals drive their cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said this before: I like the people and their approach to
life,'' Trevino said. ``Aggressive drivers, aggressive people, I
love watching them. I got here and saw people weaving in and out,
cars turning over on the freeway. I'm telling you, these people
could go right to Nascar.''
</P>
<P>
   He also likes the Upper Montclair course, designed in 1901 by
A.W. Tillinghast with tree-lined fairways and large, accessible
greens that afford the golfer a variety of approach shot choices.
Imagination and flexibility has always been a Trevino strength, and
though he came to this week's tournament with a dismal record
recently, he found himself overcoming a discouraging 37 on the
front nine with a dazzling array of bump-and-run shots and other
creative recoveries as his round concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Trevino, who has never finished out of the top 10 in six
appearances at this event, entered Saturday's second round tied
with Tom McGinnis, DeWitt Weaver, Bob Charles, Joe Inman and Allen
Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an older course like this one,'' Trevino said, ``if your
A game isn't working, you can go to your B game or your C game. You
can't do that on the newer courses where you have to hit everything
high and land it soft.''
</P>
<P>
   Trevino has won 28 Senior PGA Tour events, one more than he won
in a Hall of Fame career on the PGA Tour. But since 1994 there have
been only four victories, and this year has been particularly
vexing. In his last three tournaments, there have been three rounds
of 76 and a 78.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been playing very well,'' Trevino said. ``But maybe
I'm too comfortable in life and the golf doesn't matter as much.''
</P>
<P>
   With a 10-year-old daughter and a 6-year-old son at home,
Trevino said he practiced no more than three times a week, and only
45 minutes at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be 1,000 balls a day, every day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Trevino's competitive zeal is not completely lost.
Asked if he could win this week's tournament, Trevino said: ``Well,
New Jersey is where I got my start, at Baltusrol. Anything's
possible. If I hit it like I did today I should be OK come
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL portion of the tournament ends Saturday with a final
round pitting those players who posted the 12 best scores Friday.
Glenn Foley, the former Jets quarterback now with the Seattle
Seahawks, qualified with a 76 Friday. It was a score bettered only
by the Tennessee Titans punter Craig Hentrich, who shot a 75. But
Foley withdrew from Saturday's round because he had agreed to be
the best man in a wedding outside Boston. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
