<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      06-04 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEWS MIXED ON THE IMPACT OF EWING'S ABSENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Dudley is a well-traveled center, master of the hard foul,
a wise and crafty veteran who can be valuable in a limited role.
</P>
<P>
   With Patrick Ewing sidelined for the season with a partly torn
left Achilles' tendon, the unassuming Dudley will be called on to
be a major contributor for the Knicks for the rest of the Eastern
Conference finals. Coach Jeff Van Gundy announced Friday that
Dudley, who often fouls more than he scores, will start Saturday
night in Game 3 against the Indiana Pacers at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley, a 13-year backup who has played in 42 playoff games but
never with so much at stake, admitted to being excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great situation, although I don't like how it
happened,'' Dudley said Friday after taking extra time to hone his
offensive skills at SUNY-Purchase. ``Pat's a friend of mine, and
I'm real disappointed for him that he got hurt. I was happy enough
just contributing. Contributing quality minutes off the bench with
Pat playing would've been a better scenario for me, because I hate
to get Pat hurt at this time. But it's not just me replacing
Patrick. Everybody's got to step up in different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The views are mixed about what the loss of Ewing will do to the
Knicks, who were 9-7 in Dudley's 16 starts this season. While some
observers contend that the Knicks' free spirits will be fully
unencumbered and more effective, a more pensive group wonders if
the Knicks can overcome the lack of Ewing's presence. No matter how
sluggish Ewing was, the Pacers had to respect his offensive
ability, double-team him at times and pay a little less attention
to Allan Houston, Latrell Sprewell and Larry Johnson. Ewing gave
Rik Smits fits, keeping the Pacers center in constant foul trouble.
Now another Knick, preferably Dudley, will have to at least make
Smits and the rest of the Pacers defenders mindful of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably have to find some unexpected offense somewhere,''
Van Gundy said. ``Who that comes from, I don't know. We know that
we need Larry and Allan and Latrell to be very efficient and then
get some unexpected production from some other people, like a
couple of guys having double-figure games. Like Dudley did in the
Atlanta Game 3.''
</P>
<P>
   In that Knicks-Hawks second-round playoff game, Dudley shocked
the Garden crowd, the television and radio audiences, his
opponents, his teammates and perhaps even himself. Matched against
Dikembe Mutombo, a three-time defensive player of the year, Dudley
had career playoff highs of 12 rebounds and 14 points, 2 of which
came on an emphatic tip dunk. Even in his finest post-season
moment, Dudley was still bound by his inability to stay out of foul
trouble. He fouled out of Game 3 against Atlanta in 23 minutes, and
he has 10 fouls in 25 minutes in this series.
</P>
<P>
   If he cannot give Van Gundy a respectable allotment of foul-free
play Saturday night, the Knicks could find themselves calling on
the 41-year-old Herb Williams. Even with such precarious
possibilities, Van Gundy and his players are confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more than enough to win with,'' Van Gundy said boldly.
``Is our margin of error smaller? Absolutely. But we have more than
enough to win with, and I think our guys believe that. We also know
what a great team we're facing too.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of proclaiming the Knicks' superiority, Van Gundy
lobbed a few well-intentioned praises in Indiana's direction. After
tagging the Pacers as whiners on Thursday, he overstated their
ability to play on the road, saying they were better at Milwaukee
and at Philadelphia than they were in Indianapolis. Never mind that
Indiana won all of its playoff games, home and away, before facing
the Knicks, or that the Pacers were a shabby 2-6 on the road in
last year's post-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they've been a much better road team in the playoffs
than they've been at home,'' Van Gundy said. ``Reggie Miller plays
better on the road. He's played extremely well in the Garden, as
has Mark Jackson and Chris Mullin and Smits. So we know we're going
to play a team that's going to play better than they have in their
two previous games, and we've got to be ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy said he did not know whether he would use a big
backcourt of Sprewell and Houston, which proved effective against
Indiana in Game 2. While he admitted to having secretly planned
that strategy before the series, he said whether he went to it
Saturday night would depend on the circumstances, one being the
foul situation of the team's post men.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he does not want Dudley to quash his
aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go into the game trying to avoid foul trouble, you
can't be effective,'' Van Gundy said. ``We can't go into the game
with our primary thinking being to avoid foul trouble, because then
we're not going to be effective. We've got to be aggressive. We've
got to be tenacious. We've got to be passionate. But we've also got
to be smart.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
