<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-CRASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS INTERVIEW CO-PILOT ABOUT CRASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ The pilots of American Airlines Flight 1420
never discussed diverting to another airport while they approached
Little Rock National Airport in a thunderstorm Tuesday night, First
Officer Michael Origel told federal investigators Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Origel told investigators during a two-hour interrogation that
the jet's approach looked good and he was able to keep the runway
in sight all the way to touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But after the plane landed in heavy rain, its wheels seemed to
be hydroplaning on the wet runway and there was no ``feeling of
deceleration,'' the investigators quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots could not see the end of the runway after touching
down, Origel said. Visibility was 1,600 feet _ only a few seconds
at the touchdown speed of 143 knots, or about 164 mph. The limited
visibility could have been partly responsible for their inability
to keep the jet on the runway until it stopped, federal
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane drifted to the right after touchdown, indicating a
crosswind blowing from the left, or west, side of the field. But
the plane went off the left side of the runway into the grass about
1,000 feet before the end of the 7,200-foot runway, which led
investigators to believe that the winds might have shifted to the
opposite direction right after touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Wind data are still being studied, said George W. Black Jr., the
National Transportation Safety Board member in charge of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 1420 from Dallas/Fort Worth Airport slid off the runway
at 11:51 p.m. at a speed between 92 and 103 mph, went down an
embankment, struck steel supports for runway approach lights, broke
apart and caught fire. Nine people died, including Capt. Richard
Buschmann, and 82 people were injured, several seriously. Little
Rock Mayor Jim Dailey called the survival of 136 people ``a real
miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Origel, who broke his leg in the crash, had been flying the
McDonnell-Douglas MD-82 since February. But Buschmann was a 20-year
American Airlines veteran pilot and one of the airline's chief
pilots in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Buschmann was flying the plane and Origel was talking with the
air traffic controller by radio and going over the landing
checklist as the jet approached Little Rock, Origel told
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said they had to dodge some clouds, but that the approach
to the airport was pretty clear, like coming down a bowling lane,''
Black said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots were aware of the approaching storm but did not know
how strong it was or that it was moving onto the airport, Origel
told safety board interviewers, who included airline pilots
employed by the safety board and American.
</P>
<P>
   Origel could not shed any light on why the ground spoilers did
not pop up from the top of the wings after touchdown to help slow
the plane, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Those spoilers must be armed before landing so that sensors in
the nose wheel will trigger them to deploy once the plane is on the
runway, and Origel told investigators that he thought the captain
had pulled a lever on his side of the center control stack in the
cockpit that arms the spoilers, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   But an American Airlines spokesman said the airline's policy is
for the nonflying pilot _ in this case, Origel _ to arm the
spoilers before landing. Investigators don't know whether the lever
was put into the armed position, chief investigator Greg Feith
said.
</P>
<P>
   The lever was in an ``abnormal position'' as the plane lay on
the ground after the crash, but that could have been caused by the
crash or by rescue workers accidentally hitting it while trying to
remove the pilot and co-pilot from the cockpit, Feith said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the spoilers would have helped slow the plane, they
would not necessarily have had to be deployed for it to stop
safely, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   The captain tried twice to use the thrust reversers to slow down
the jet, but the procedure did not seem to help, Origel told
interviewers.
</P>
<P>
   The captain might have cycled the thrust reversers to the off
position after the first use to give him better control of the
aircraft as it was veering off the runway, Black said. Use of the
thrust reversers can decrease the effectiveness of an MD-82's
rudder, which is used to help steer it in the air and at high
speeds on the ground, Feith said.
</P>
<P>
   Origel could not explain why one of the two thrust reversers was
deployed a third time just before the crash, but the other one was
left in the off position. Investigators suggested Thursday that the
captain might have tried to use the thrust reverser on the left
side of the plane to help steer it back to the right and onto the
runway after it went into the grass.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators used a runway friction-testing truck lent to the
safety board by Dallas/Fort Worth Airport on Friday to determine
how well an aircraft might have been able to stop if the runway
surface were wet, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skid resistance checks showed that this was the best
runway surface the D/FW Airport people had ever tested,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The concrete runway was built in 1991 and is in excellent
condition, but the rain may have been heavy enough to overtax the
drainage system and leave the runway dangerously wet when the plane
landed, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots had been told about the rapidly deteriorating weather
at the airport, had been given two wind-shear alerts, and had been
given 20- to 30-second updates on increasing wind speeds as they
neared the field, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That information should have been enough to persuade the crew
not to attempt a landing, David Stempler, executive director of the
Air Travelers Association and an aviation attorney, said Friday
from his office in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frightening thing for airline passengers to know is that
pilots do this all the time,'' Stempler said. ``The big question
that needs to be answered to prevent an accident such as this in
the future is why a well-trained, highly experienced pilot like
this captain would make this kind of decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Airlines is a very safe airline with a good training
program, and if a pilot like that can make bad decisions that cost
people their lives, what can we expect of airlines that aren't
quite that good?''
</P>
<P>
   Stempler suggested that maybe the captain succumbed to what
pilots sometimes refer to as ``get-home-itis,'' a burning desire to
complete a flight against all odds.
</P>
<P>
   To get more details about the flight and the crash, safety board
investigators interviewed passengers Friday at Little Rock
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, Black discounted reports that a power failure at
the Little Rock airport just before the crash might have kept
rescue vehicles locked in their station because an electric garage
door wouldn't open.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicles were delayed in reaching the scene because rescuers
went to the wrong end of the runway, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That cost them three or four minutes getting there, but we
don't believe that was a factor in helping save lives,'' Black
said.
</P>
<P>
   Black also said investigators don't know whether crew fatigue
played a role in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that even though the pilots had been on duty 13
hours and 20 minutes at the time of the accident _ 40 minutes shy
of their maximum allowed 14-hour duty period _ they had logged only
five hours of flying during that time. They were waiting on the
ground the rest of the time, including a two-hour weather and
equipment delay Tuesday night before leaving D/FW for to Little
Rock.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
