</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-JOCKEYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCKEYS USUALLY WIN OR LOSE BELMONT THROUGH PACING ON BACKSTRETCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE DRAPE   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Chris Antley moved Charismatic down the
backstretch in the Preakness, hopeful but not confident that he
could capture the second leg of the Triple Crown. As he reached the
half-mile mark, the jockey felt trapped by what he believed was a
struggling Stephen Got Even on his outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``G-Man, give me a shot,'' Antley hollered at Stephen Got Even's
rider, Gary Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go ahead, little buddy,'' Stevens said, according to Antley,
who took Charismatic outside and to the doorstep of Triple Crown
history.
</P>
<P>
   The conversations amid tons of horse flesh traveling at 35 miles
an hour are far briefer than the dozens of communications that
owners, trainers and jockeys will be engaged in during the hours
leading to Saturday's Belmont Stakes. This is a talking game,
especially before a $1 million race at the unusual and grueling
distance of 1{ miles, as Pat Day, the rider of Menifee, observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have 12 different sets of connections trying to figure out
what's the best way to run their horse: on the pace or off the
pace, inside or outside,'' Day said. ``You're trying to guess what
everybody else is going to do, and that's difficult to do. And
finally, there are the horses. They have to cooperate, and that
doesn't always happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what happens about 50 percent of the time, especially in
big races, is that the gates open and the riders adjust and figure
it out as we go.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the trainer D. Wayne Lukas, who says he was ``dead on''
about how Charismatic's victories in the Kentucky Derby and
Preakness would set up, concedes that the Belmont is a rider's
race. But he still intends to bend Antley's ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't run this distance but once in a horse's lifetime,''
Lukas said. ``There's no telling what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Quoting Charlie Whittingham, the late Hall of Fame trainer,
Lukas said: ``A bad rider can't do what you tell him and a good one
won't listen to you anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Belmont is known for its staggering stretch run, the
race is usually won or lost on the backstretch. The trick is
staying close, but without stretching the horse's comfort level.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want the horses to stride quickly, but not ask for much,''
said Day, who is aboard a notorious late runner. He acknowledged
that Menifee must be kept closer earlier than he was as the
runner-up in the Derby and Preakness. ``You want to lope along.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear which horse will dictate the early pace because
there are no definitive speed horses in the field of 12, though the
99-1 Teletable is likely to rocket ahead from the rail. The filly,
Silverbulletday, is quick but does not need the lead. Her trainer,
Bob Baffert, says he will spend the first part of the race watching
the timer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a leisurely pace,'' Baffert said, hoping for times for
the quarter-mile of ``24 and change'' and for the half-mile of 49
seconds. ``If they're going any faster than that, I'll be
worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with a slow pace, Menifee, along with other late runners
like Best of Luck and Pineaff, must do much work. ``I'll be on him
on the back side, keeping his attention,'' said Jean-Luc Samyn, who
will ride Best of Luck, trained by Allen Jerkens. ``I have to give
him a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   When the horses enter Belmont Park's wide sweeping far turn,
they will have traveled a mile, and recent history says the
eventual winner will be on the lead or at least within five lengths
of it.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 Belmonts, only Easy Goer and Touch Gold came on
to win from far behind heading into the turn. In 1989, Easy Goer
was in third place, five lengths back. In 1997, Touch Gold was in
fourth place, four lengths back. The race begins in the last
half-mile, according to Lukas, who expects Charismatic to be ready
to launch his bid for history then.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stays in the race and can make a prolonged drive,'' Lukas
said. ``Most horses can run full out for an eighth of a mile, good
ones for a quarter of the mile, and great ones a half-mile.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Kent Desormeaux sent Real Quiet around the far turn
and had a four-length lead at the stretch. In retrospect, Baffert
says he moved the Triple Crown hopeful too early. When Victory
Gallop caught him by a nose at the wire, Real Quiet flunked Lukas'
criteria for greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Though a crowd of more than 80,000 is certain to drown them out,
the riders will get noisier in the stretch. There is chatter as
they go around. When Day feels someone is dangerously crowding him,
he says he will ask, ``How're you doing, jock?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear guys making kissing sounds and clucking to their
horses,'' Day said. He then proceeded to demonstrate his sound
effects. ``The hollering starts in the stretch. I get in rhythm
with my whip: `Hah! Hah!' It is sort of an unconscious thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas insists there is no manual on how to win the Belmont. He
ran seven horses here, beginning in 1980, before he got his first
victory in 1994 with Tabasco Cat. He won the next two years with
Thunder Gulch and Editor's Note.
</P>
<P>
   On one of his unsuccessful visits, Lukas stayed up late and
watched tapes of every Belmont ever recorded, including
Secretariat's gate-to-wire victory in 1973. Secretariat won the
Belmont, and with it the Triple Crown, by 31 lengths in 2 minutes
24 seconds, which remains an American record. And all that tape
review?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hell of an idea to have Secretariat as your horse is
all I got out of them,'' Lukas said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
