u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-POLICE-TRIA     06-04 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-POLICE-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY IN POLICE BRUTALITY CASE BEGINS DELIBERATIONS  
 (DW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ The jury in the Abner Louima brutality case began
deliberations Friday, quickly turning to the most serious charge
remaining and asking to have testimony read concerning a police
officer's alleged role in the torture of Louima in a Brooklyn
station house.
</P>
<P>
   About two hours after the jurors began considering a month's
worth of testimony in the trial in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn,
they sent out a note asking to rehear the testimony of Louima, two
officers and a police investigator concerning a charge that one
officer, Charles Schwarz, held Louima down while another officer,
Justin Volpe, rammed a stick into Louima's rectum.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe is one of four police officers who went to trial on
charges of brutalizing Louima. All four officers were accused of
beating Louima in a police car, and two of them _ Volpe and Schwarz
_ were also accused of attacking him with the stick in a restroom
at the 70th Precinct station house in Brooklyn. Prosecutors said
these assaults occurred after Louima, a 32-year-old Haitian
immigrant, was arrested in a brawl outside a nightclub in August
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe interrupted the trial last week to plead guilty in the
hope that in doing so, he would receive less than the life prison
sentence he could get for violating Louima's civil rights. Volpe's
departure from the courtroom _ he was immediately dismissed from
the police force _ left Schwarz facing the same charge and possible
sentence if he is convicted of aiding Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also charged that Schwarz had taken Louima, in
handcuffs and with his pants down, from the main desk of the
station house directly to the restroom after he had been booked on
a charge of assaulting Volpe during the street brawl. The charge
against Louima was later dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's first note called for all of Louima's testimony
``from the time in front of the main desk until the conclusion of
the alleged bathroom assault and subsequent leading of Louima out
of the bathroom into the cell.''
</P>
<P>
   Louima testified that an officer whom the prosecution said was
Schwarz had taken him directly from the main desk of the police
station to the restroom and had restrained him there.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also asked for the testimony of two police officers who
had said they had seen Schwarz walk Louima from the desk toward the
restroom area, and for the testimony of a Police Department
investigator who was the first to interview Louima, at Coney Island
Hospital the day after he was attacked. The investigator testified
that Louima had told him that he had been put in a cell for 10
minutes before two officers had taken him to the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz's lawyer, Stephen Worth, said the investigator's
testimony called into question the testimony incriminating his
client.
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor, Loretta Lynch, said it did not because Louima was
under heavy medication during that interview, and the rest of his
account was ``consistent with the major point of everything he has
said since.''
</P>
<P>
   The jurors were still hearing the testimony they had called for
Friday when they were dismissed for the weekend by Judge Eugene
Nickerson. The jurors are to remain ``partially sequestered,'' as
the court defines it. This means they go home after each day's
court session, but are transported to and from the courthouse by
federal marshals, and, when not in the courtroom, are kept together
in the jury room.
</P>
<P>
   Partial sequestration is an approach often used in sensitive
cases in federal court, where it is rare that juries are fully
sequestered. Lawyers said that if the Louima case were being tried
in state court, the jury would probably be fully sequestered during
deliberations. The Louima jurors are also anonymous, their
identities withheld from defense and prosecution lawyers as well as
from the public. Nickerson ruled that this was necessary to insure
that the jurors' judgment would not be tainted by outside
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   The other officers accused of assaulting Louima in the police
car are Thomas Wiese and Thomas Bruder. A fifth officer, Sgt.
Michael Bellomo, is also on trial. He is accused of trying to cover
up that beating and Volpe's assault of a second man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
