<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TEMPS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWS MAKE IT TOUGH FOR TEMP WORKERS TO ORGANIZE, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Laws preventing temporary workers from organizing into
collective bargaining units, as 18 Microsoft temps have been
struggling to do for the past month, are outdated and should be
reworked, two officials connected with the National Labor Relations
Board said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the laws are changed, such a small group faces a daunting
task of getting companies to negotiate, say the labor experts.
</P>
<P>
   William Gould, who chaired the labor organization from 1994 to
1998, said the law is ``creating a second class of subordinate
workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gould, now a professor of law at Stanford University, said, ``I
think one of the great challenges of American labor law is to bring
these contingent workers into the mainstream so they can enjoy
fringe benefits including health benefits, which are vital, and
collective bargaining rights if they choose to exercise them.''
</P>
<P>
   The 18 workers, many of whom are certified public accountants,
lawyers and MBAs, on May 19 wrote to the four temporary agencies
that represent them, asking to negotiate job classification, wages,
benefits and working conditions. A majority of the 18 had voted to
form a collective-bargaining unit through the Washington Alliance
of Technology Workers (WashTech), a Seattle local of the
Communications Workers of America.
</P>
<P>
   The group is participating in a confidential Microsoft project
code-named Dingo.
</P>
<P>
   Two agencies, Volt Services Group and Excell Data Corp., have
refused to bargain with the group, said Barbara Judd, representing
the 18 workers. The other two, Kelly Technical Services and General
Employment, have not yet given their final responses.
</P>
<P>
   Under the National Labor Relations Act, the primary law
governing U.S. labor relations, employers are under no obligation
to negotiate with a group unless it has been certified by the
National Labor Relations Board. The Dingo group has not sought such
certification, and Judd said it doesn't intend to. It's too long
and involved a process, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The group's only alternative is to expand, then try to use its
clout to force the agencies to bargain, said Dan Sanders, an
attorney with the NLRB's Seattle office.
</P>
<P>
   Gould said that for several reasons it may be almost impossible
for workers like the Dingo group to win the right to bargain
collectively.
</P>
<P>
   _ In order to be certified as a bargaining unit, a group must
show that it has a ``community of interests,'' in the words of the
National Labor Relations Act. Among temporary workers, those
communities can be small. Creating bargaining units with so few
people is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   _ Collective bargaining must be performed between employees and
employers. But in the case of temporary workers, there is still
controversy over who the employer is, the temp agency or the
company whose work is being done. Two cases currently in the
Seattle U.S. District Court, Vizcaino vs. Microsoft and Hughes vs.
Microsoft, indicate that acting like an employer makes a company an
employer, no matter who actually issues the paycheck. This issue
must be resolved before workers know whom to negotiate with.
</P>
<P>
   _ Often temporary workers labor side by side with permanent
employees on a project. A 1973 NLRB case known as Greenhoot ruled
that under those circumstances, both the temporary agency and the
employer must give their consent to collective bargaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
