A3815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMB-SERGEANT-NYT &LR;      06-04 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-SERGEANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDICTED EX-SERGEANT SAYS HE KNOWS WHO BOMBED U.S. EMBASSIES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A former U.S. Army sergeant accused of being a part
of a terrorist conspiracy has told the FBI that he knew the people
who carried out the embassy bombings in Africa last year but has
refused to identify them, according to court documents released
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The former sergeant, Ali A. Mohamed, was indicted last month
after talks with the government broke down. The discussions were
held to determine whether he would cooperate with the federal
investigation into Osama bin Laden, the Saudi exile charged in the
bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The documents offer much more detail about Mohamed's dealings
with the FBI, showing that the bureau began talking with him about
Laden as early as 1993, according to one document.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1993 interview, for example, Mohamed told FBI agents ``that
Osama bin Laden ran an organization called al Qaeda and was
building an army which may be used to overthrow the Saudi
government,'' a document shows.
</P>
<P>
   In another interview with the FBI, in October 1997, Mohamed said
he had lived in Laden's house in Khartoum, Sudan, in 1994, and had
trained Laden's bodyguards after an attempt was made to assassinate
Laden.
</P>
<P>
   No details were provided in the documents about that attempt,
except that an FBI agent said he was aware of such an attempt in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   The documents were unsealed by U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand
in Manhattan, after The New York Times filed a request with the
court seeking their release and the government agreed, making
certain changes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the material is a 10-page government complaint detailing
the charges made against Mohamed, also known as Abu Omar, when he
was secretly arrested last September.
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed's lawyer, James Roth, had no comment Friday night on the
new disclosures. Mohamed recently refused to enter a plea at his
arraignment, and a federal magistrate entered a not guilty plea for
him. After that hearing, Roth said his client was protesting the
prosecution. ``Mohamed has difficulty recognizing the jurisdiction
of this court,'' Roth said. ``He thinks basically that it's a
political indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.S. attorney, Mary Jo White, declined to
comment Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The newly released documents also show for the first time the
existence of three confidential sources who are working with
prosecutors in the investigation. Previously, the government has
confirmed only that one source, identified as CS-1, a convicted
terrorist and former associate of Laden, was cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   The new documents cited confidential sources 2, 3, and 4 as
having provided information about Mohamed and his activities with
al Qaeda in the United States and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   What is not made clear in the newly disclosed papers is the
precise nature of Mohamed's relationship with the FBI. It has been
previously reported that Mohamed, who had also sought
unsuccessfully to work for the CIA in the mid-1980s, had acted as
an informant for the bureau on the West Coast in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The documents made public Friday shed new light on this
ambiguous relationship between a covert source and a man the
government now says is one of the perpetrators of terrorism against
U.S. citizens. It offers new suggestions that he tried to insinuate
himself with the sensitive U.S. government agencies while he was
associated with Laden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
