<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 23:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3850 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HISPANICS-     06-04 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON ASTROS OWNER FACES HISPANIC COMMUNITY'S OUTRAGE OVER
ALLEGED REMARKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A night Drayton McLane Jr. was honored for his
marketing skills turned into a public relations nightmare as
Houston's Hispanic community became outraged by comments the Astros
owner allegedly made about it.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish-speaking television station KTMD-Channel 48 Telemundo
reported Thursday night that McLane had made offensive remarks to
the station's general manager earlier that evening.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, McLane said he does not market to the
Hispanic community because baseball is too complicated for its
citizens and they don't keep up with the sport because it requires
reading newspapers daily.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said McLane complained that Hispanics buy the
cheaper seats at games and don't buy food at the Astrodome because
they don't like what is served there.
</P>
<P>
   The comments came during a casual conversation McLane had with
Telemundo Vice President and General Manager Marco Camacho, two
other Telemundo executives and several others during a reception at
the Aerial Theater in Houston. Later that evening, the Houston
Advertising Federation presented McLane its Trailblazer Award for
improving Houston's image with his strong marketing acumen.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, Camacho was telling story to radio talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he said this shows he has a misperception of
Hispanics,'' Camacho said. ``He doesn't understand the market in
the community. He tells me he doesn't think this is a market that
is important for him to market.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday afternoon, amid growing pressure from Hispanic
groups, McLane issued a prepared statement denying the comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am angry and outraged by the accusation that KTMD-Channel 48
Telemundo made last night,'' McLane said. ``The report was
absolutely not true. I did not do an interview with the television
station nor did I make any such remarks to anyone in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will seek an apology from Telemundo.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros players, mired in a minislump, refused comment.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Hispanic community was not as silent, said Bob Perry,
general manager of KQQK radio.
</P>
<P>
   After Camacho called the Spanish-speaking station to tell it of
the Telemundo report the night before, the station's morning talk
show was deluged with calls, Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really made a lot of callers very, very mad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As pressure mounted Friday and Astros officials grew more
concerned the incident could harm the team, McLane cut short a
vacation with his wife and flew from Harlingen in South Texas to
what turned into a bizarre press conference at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   While McLane further explained his statements, which he said
were taken out of context, Camacho and two of his employees _ Rod
Rodriguez and Abel Salas _ sat on the front row of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 minutes into the 45-minute press conference _ parts of
which were broadcast live by three TV stations _ Camacho took the
microphone to deny McLane's account.
</P>
<P>
   The two politely traded their versions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of talking specifically about Hispanics, McLane said he
was referring to problems marketing the team to all potential fans.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has had a hard time attracting fans, he said, because
it is hard to understand because of its large amount of strategy.
He said his comments about reading the newspaper was a point that
baseball requires daily attention because the season has 162
regular-season games, not 16 like professional football.
</P>
<P>
   His comments about the food, he said, were that all sections of
the community periodically complain about it. He said he did not
indicate that Hispanics buy only the least expensive seats, but
that those are available to anyone who can't afford more costly
ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking about everybody,'' McLane said. ``I've had lots
in my family that I had to teach baseball to. It was never meant to
be about Hispanics. It was meant for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Camacho stuck by his story, which whipped up a maelstrom of
criticism from Houston's Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his mind, there is nothing we can do to help the Hispanic
market _ we don't understand the game, we don't read the
newspaper,'' Camacho said.
</P>
<P>
   Camacho, who did not tape the original discussion or tell McLane
he would broadcast the remarks, said he went public to let people
know how business is done in Houston. ``I want people to know what
is said during these cocktail parties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez and Salas backed up the story.
</P>
<P>
   McLane would not speculate on Camacho's motives. But Astros
officials speculated that Camacho was trying to boost Telemundo's
viewership, which is far behind Houston's other Spanish-language TV
station, KXLN-Channel 45 Univision.
</P>
<P>
   Camacho discounted such talk, saying that ratings weeks have
passed.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Telemundo was the talk of Houston's Hispanic
community. Not only were Spanish-speaking radio stations flooded
with angry callers, the Houston League of United Latin American
Citizens is considering a boycott of Astros games.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, LULAC wants Major League Baseball to consider
sanctioning McLane, comparing his alleged comments to those by
Cincinnati Reds owner Marge Schott.
</P>
<P>
   MLB fined Schott $25,000 and banished her for a year after an
investigation indicated she made disparaging remarks about blacks
and Jews to employees of her ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the harm and damage this man (McLane) has done,''
Johnny Mata, Houston LULAC spokesman said, ``it's hard to see how
someone who made so many millions of dollars can be so stupid. It
makes your blood boil.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball Commissioner Bud Selig issued a release supporting
McLane after talking with the Astros owner, who has been one of
Selig's biggest supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drayton McLane is one of the most honorable, sensitive and
dedicated individuals in the game today and one of the finest men I
have ever had the privilege to call a friend,'' Selig said. ``It is
an outrage that he would be targeted for this kind of slander by
any media outlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drayton has accomplished wonders for Houston and for the
community of Houston. He has my full support and the support of
everyone in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The racial brouhaha placed Houston's Hispanic leaders in a bind.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, McLane promised Hispanic and African-American
leaders 30 percent of the concession business at Enron Field in
return for support of a referendum on building the downtown
baseball park now under construction.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum's narrow victory was attributed to McLane's
last-second pledge, as Hispanics and African-Americans approved the
referendum by a substantially higher margin than whites.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Torres, president of the Hispanic Chamber of Commerce,
which endorsed the referendum, said Friday he wanted to talk to
McLane before passing judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, in fact, he said this ... it's not only insulting to the
baseball fans, but the players,'' Torres said. ``We hope that in
fact it is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Mario Gallegos, D-Houston, and City Councilman
Orlando Sanchez took essentially the same approach, saying it was
difficult to determine which version of the story to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos, adding he had no reason to doubt Telemundo, said he
will suggest that McLane and members of Houston's Hispanic
community meet to try and resolve the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider Drayton my friend and if he did make these
comments, Drayton needs a lot of help in understanding our
community, the fastest-growing population not only in Houston, but
the country,'' Gallegos said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
