<SLUG> BC-BIKE-BY-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN HELD AFTER VIDEOTAPE SHOWS HIM RIDE BICYCLE FROM FATAL
SHOOTING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., France)   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An 18-year-old high school student was charged Friday
with fatally shooting a Morningside Heights woman two months ago
when she tried to keep him from stealing her purse, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The student, Shawn Harris, had been arrested Thursday night at
his home in Morningside Heights on charges of murder, robbery and
using a firearm in the commission of a felony, police officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said Harris had confessed to
detectives, who had arrested him after receiving tips from
witnesses and reviewing videotape from surveillance cameras at an
apartment building near the scene of the killing. The videotape did
not include the killing, but did show a man riding away on his
bicycle, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, Jacqueline Frezza, 34, was shot after leaving her
co-op apartment at 9 a.m. on April 15.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Frezza was carrying her purse and a canvas bag of clothes to
be cleaned when she was approached by the gunman, who rode up to
her on a bicycle , the police said. The man grabbed her purse and
she jerked it back. The gunman then shot Ms. Frezza once in the
chest and rode away, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   After the slaying, detectives canvassed nearby neighborhoods,
posting fliers and showing the surveillance videotape to anyone who
might be able to identify the man.
</P>
<P>
   The crime shook merchants, students and retirees around
Morningside Gardens, a seven-building, 1,000-apartment complex
built as city-supervised, middle-income housing. It was the third
slaying this year in the 26th Precinct; there were only three
homicides there in all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives arrested Harris on Thursday night after keeping him
under surveillance for six days, Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said one or two people might be able to claim the $45,000
reward offered for information leading to the arrest if Harris is
convicted. The money was raised by the police department, local
residents and the co-op.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Harris had been suspended for unknown reasons from
Louis D. Brandeis High School before the arrest. Safir said Harris
did not have a criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Frezza grew up in Cocoa Beach, Fla., and moved to New York
about 10 years ago to attend Hunter College. She had lived in the
city since then, except for one year in which she lived in France.
She had been working for herself as a marketing consultant after
leaving a job with Merrill Lynch a few years ago, and relatives
said she had been helping set up a nonprofit organization to teach
the elderly and the poor how to use computers.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Arthur Frezza, a retired engineer from NASA in Cape
Canaveral, Fla., called his daughter ``a wonderful human being''
and said he hoped Harris ``may have enough goodness to do good the
rest of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asked, `Aren't you angry at the person?' but that will
not change what has been done,'' Frezza said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
