u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BENITEZ-MARTINEZ-     06-04 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BENITEZ-MARTINEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THE BIG DEAL? FOR BENITEZ AND MARTINEZ, PLENTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sometime during this highly anticipated and
scrutinized three-game series between the Yankees and Mets, Armando
Benitez could be summoned to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez will be booed incessantly by the Yankee Stadium fans,
who will recall how he pinned a fastball between the 2 and the 4 on
Tino Martinez's back while he was with the Baltimore Orioles 13
months ago. He expects to be bathed in boos and should.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's routine,'' Benitez said. ``That's normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Plunking Martinez was a terrible act by Benitez, an act that
would have put Martinez's career in peril had he been drilled in
the head. Martinez barely managed to avoid being bashed in the
helmet, but the questionable pitch caused a nasty brawl. The
Yankees felt that Benitez aimed at Martinez in retaliation for
Bernie Williams' mammoth two-run homer in the previous at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez was suspended for eight games, and some Orioles were so
embarrassed by the incident that they publicly criticized him and
in effect apologized to Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Ray Miller was so spooked by Benitez's pitch and the
possibility of repercussions that he did not use him the next nine
times the Orioles and the Yankees played. The Orioles traded
Benitez last December. They had to.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it is obvious that Benitez regrets the pitch, he
still tried to convince a reporter that he was just throwing inside
because Martinez steps toward the plate when he swings.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez giggled about being booed, but he conceded that it
disturbed him a little to be considered such a villain. He sounded
sheepish as he apparently revealed for the first time how he tried
to apologize to Martinez and how he had seemingly been ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote him a letter,'' Benitez said. ``I told him I was
sorry. I was trying to pitch inside. We're all real people. I know
he has a family. I didn't want this to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Benitez said that it was his idea to write the letter and that
he had his agent, Mike Powers, read it and send it to Martinez
through the Yankees. Benitez said Powers mailed it May 22, 1998,
three days after he plunked Martinez. Does Benitez know if the
letter reached Martinez?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Benitez said. ``I know he's still ticked off.
Nobody wants to go through that. They don't want to be hit by a
pitch, especially from somebody like me. I throw hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Before batting practice, Martinez diplomatically answered three
questions about Benitez. He said that he tries not to think about
what happened last season and said that Benitez is not the only
pitcher to have hit him on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Benitez has hit Martinez twice: the hard-throwing
right-hander also buzzed him in the upper back after Edgar
Martinez's grand slam while Martinez was with Seattle in 1995,
inciting another fight.
</P>
<P>
   After Benitez made his revelation about the apology letter, a
reporter approached Martinez a second time and asked him if he had
ever received it. The normally polite first baseman grew agitated
and said: ``I'm not going to answer that. Why is that important?''
</P>
<P>
   It is still a tender issue for Martinez. Joe Torre has
repeatedly said that Martinez, who went 18 for 100 after being hit,
struggled for more than a month, though he still hit .281 with 23
homers and 118 runs batted in. Martinez refuses to admit that being
hit by a 97-mile-an-hour fastball, which left an ugly bruise on his
back and influenced his flexibility and swing, contributed to his
slump.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter persisted whether Martinez received the letter,
he waved his hands and said: ``It's not me against him. It's us
against the Mets. I haven't been asked about any other pitcher. I
haven't been asked about Rick Reed, Yoshii or Al Leiter. I don't
want this to be the focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez then retreated into the players' lounge, which is off
limits to reporters. It was his indication that he did not want to
talk about Benitez's letter.
</P>
<P>
   Why would Martinez consider the topic taboo? Perhaps Martinez
does not want to acknowledge the receipt of Benitez's letter
because, in some way, that would signal that he forgives Benitez or
would at least let Benitez off the hook. Benitez does not deserve
sympathy, and Martinez, who has two hits and has been hit twice in
four at-bats against him, does not have to grant forgiveness. They
could meet again this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, sure, if the situation arises, I'd like to face him
again,'' Martinez said. ``I'm not saying I want to face him more.
But if he's out there and I'm hitting, I'm not going to want to get
pinch-hit for.''
</P>
<P>
   Benitez will be ready, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I have to do is pitch like it's normal if I face Tino,''
Benitez said. ``If I have to throw inside against him, I'll throw
inside.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
