<HEADER>
A3929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FISCAL-NYT &LR;      06-04 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FISCAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK LEADERS AGREE ON A $35.3 BILLION BUDGET  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After two weeks of relatively painless negotiations,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and City Council leaders agreed Friday on a
$35.3 billion budget that takes advantage of record-high tax
revenues and contains only a smattering of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and City Council Speaker Peter Vallone gleefully
announced the agreement in the City Hall rotunda, boasting that
they had easily reached a consensus while politicians in Albany
were still struggling to adopt a state budget that is now 66 days
late.
</P>
<P>
   In another swipe at state lawmakers, the two leaders said their
only hurdle had been the Legislature's repeal of the city's
commuter tax last month, which punched a $360 million hole in the
budget.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden loss of revenue forced the mayor and the speaker to
jettison many of their own tax cut proposals, they said, including
cuts that would have helped businesses, working parents, home
buyers and car owners. But their budget plan still includes modest
tax cuts, and spending increases for the Board of Education, the
Police Department and many other agencies for the city's fiscal
year, which begins July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sweet because we were able to do an awful lot to enhance
the quality of life in our city,'' Vallone said of the budget.
``It's bitter, also, because in spite of all we've been able to do,
for the first time ever we have had a hostile act from our brethren
in Albany.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement follows the framework of the budget that the
Republican mayor proposed in May, although Council leaders won some
concessions. Giuliani allowed them to restore $165 million in cuts
he had planned for cultural institutions, libraries and community
programs. The Council extracted an additional $80 million for those
programs, including $9.5 million for a summer reading program in
libraries and $17 million for services for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also modified his plan to accelerate a class of 1,500
police recruits, agreeing to delay their hiring by three months. He
agreed, as he had been expected to do, to at least temporarily
abandon his plan to use city funds for an experimental school
voucher program, instead agreeing to spend $6 million to study
several education ideas, including vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Council accepted the mayor's controversial
plan to set aside millions of dollars for stadium construction in
the future. But Vallone insisted that the amount come down to $90
million, from $96 million. He demanded that the money come from the
general budget, instead of from commercial rent tax revenue, as
Giuliani had proposed. The mayor also agreed to let the Council
have a say in how the money is eventually spent.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone also compromised in the area of tax reductions, agreeing
to $348 million in cuts instead of the nearly $700 million he
proposed in March. The most significant cut _ eliminating the sales
tax on clothing and shoes that cost less than $110 _ was Giuliani's
idea. That cut, which will take effect in December, will cost the
city $134 million next year, growing to $237 million in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The budget agreement also extends a tax relief program for
owners of co-ops and condominiums, worth $166 million a year, and
provides an earned income tax credit for the working poor, worth
$48 million a year. New York would be the first city in the nation
to offer its own earned income tax credit, which would save the
average family $100 a year. Both cuts would need approval from Gov.
George Pataki and the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The city has sued to overturn the commuter tax repeal, and
Giuliani said Friday that if the suit succeeded, he might use that
money to cut more taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The budget agreement still requires the approval of the full
51-member Council, but that is a formality because Vallone, a
Democrat, wields tight control.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who has all but declared himself a candidate for the
U.S. Senate, heaped praise on his own spending practices Friday,
saying he had dramatically improved the city's fiscal health by
keeping spending under the rate of inflation and reducing budget
gaps in the future.
</P>
<P>
   But independent budget monitors said Friday that future budget
deficits remained a serious problem, especially since Giuliani's
estimates do not account for potentially costly settlements with
municipal workers. They questioned whether the $629 million that
the mayor is setting aside for unanticipated needs is enough, given
that the local economy, driven mostly by Wall Street, could weaken.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Vallone's chumminess _ the mayor not only pumped
the speaker's hand, but kissed several Council members on the cheek
_ contrasted sharply with last year's stormy budget negotiations,
which broke off when Vallone refused to abandon a plan to hold a
referendum on the future of Yankee Stadium. This time around they
emphasized that they had agreed on a new budget before the legal
deadline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
