<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PSYCHOLOGIST-VERDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY AWARDS FORMER PSYCHOLOGIST $16.6 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal jury in Manhattan has awarded a former
state psychologist $16.6 million in damages after concluding that
he was the victim of false allegations, orchestrated by another
employee, that he had sexually abused mentally retarded patients in
a treatment center in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The employee, Melanie Fudenberg, who was ordered to pay the
damages, was a mental health therapy aide at the Williamsburg
Residential Training Center in the mid-1980s, at the same time that
the psychologist, Mark Komlosi, practiced there.
</P>
<P>
   Komlosi said Friday that he believed that Ms. Fudenberg was
carrying out a personal vendetta against him. A lawyer for Ms.
Fudenberg denied that she had been behind the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict returned Thursday in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan ended a torturous, almost Kafkaesque legal battle for
Komlosi, who had fought for about 15 years to win back his
reputation and compensation, he said, for the damage caused by the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the accusations, made originally in 1984 and 1985
by several retarded patients at the training center, Komlosi was
arrested and jailed for 15 days. The headline of one newspaper
article in The New York Post said: ``Shrink held in sex attacks on
patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately in 1986, Komlosi was put on trial in the state
Supreme Court in Brooklyn, charged with sexual abuse of one of the
patients. But more than a week into the trial, the patient who had
testified that he was abused by Komlosi broke down after court and
admitted, as the judge said at the time, that ``the entire thing
was a lie; that it never happened and was completely made up,'' a
transcript shows.
</P>
<P>
   The case was dropped, and the justice presiding at the time told
Komlosi that the legal ``process works in strange ways.''
</P>
<P>
   That proved to be an understatement, as far as Komlosi was
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, he sued state and city officials, as well as Ms.
Fudenberg. But in subsequent court rulings, the officials were
found to be immune from suit in federal court, leaving only Ms.
Fudenberg to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   The entire jury award, including $10 million in punitive
damages, was returned against her, according to the verdict sheet.
It was unclear Friday how much of the award Ms. Fudenberg would be
able to pay, but one of Komlosi's lawyers, Jeremiah Sheehan, said
the verdict would enable Komlosi to seek payment of damages from
the state and the city in other court actions. Komlosi, 59, who has
a master's degree in psychology and was working toward a doctorate
when he was first accused, said the allegations destroyed his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from being a professional,'' he said, ``to being
professionally lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not able to recover,'' he added, saying that he now
works as a doorman in a building on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   He said of the jury's verdict, ``It's like when you unload a
truck of huge stones from my soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Goidell, a lawyer for Ms. Fudenberg, said she would appeal
the ruling. Goidell said that his client denied having patients
falsely accuse Komlosi, and that she was passing on patient
complaints she believed to be true.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a messenger,'' Goidell said. ``She was an extremely
caring and concerned therapy aide.'' He said that Ms. Fudenberg
``denied concocting anything against Komlosi.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Peter Collins, another lawyer representing Komlosi, said the
allegations against his client first surfaced in 1984, when a
female patient accused him of sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   In a court affidavit, Komlosi has said that he learned later
that Ms. Fudenberg had told the patient ``to play a game on me''
and ``had manipulated and coerced'' the patient ``to make these
statements in return for a bribe of cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, several other patients made false accusations of abuse
against Komlosi, at Ms. Fudenberg's direction, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said that repeated investigations by state agencies
cleared Komlosi, but that in March 1985, he was accused again, by
the patient who later recanted his statement at trial.
</P>
<P>
   In the federal trial that ended last week before Magistrate
Judge Henry Pitman, the jury found that Komlosi ``had a right to be
free of malicious prosecution,'' the verdict sheet shows, and that
``Ms. Fudenberg knew with absolute certainty that the allegations
of sexual misconduct'' by Komlosi were false.
</P>
</TEXT>
