<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA PLANS TO ENFORCE RULE REQUIRING PILOT REST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration said Friday that it would
soon begin strictly enforcing a 1985 regulation requiring airline
pilots to have at least eight hours of uninterrupted rest in the 24
hours before finishing their flight duty.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots and safety advocates have been calling on the agency to
enforce the rule for years. In May, the Allied Pilots Association,
which represents 9,500 pilots at American Airlines, asked the
inspector general of the Department of Transportation to
investigate why the agency had refused.
</P>
<P>
   Union president Richard LaVoy said that FAA Administrator Jane
Garvey, the administrator of the agency, told him at a meeting
Friday that the FAA would publish a notice in the Federal Register
next week giving airlines 120 days to comply with the rule, which
most major carriers now routinely ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Alison Duquette, a spokeswoman, confirmed that the agency
intended to enforce the rule but would not say when the notice
would be published or how long a grace period the airlines would be
given.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to getting it out soon,'' Ms. Duquette said.
``We hope in the next few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilot fatigue is one factor being investigated in the crash this
week of an American Airlines jet in Little Rock, Ark. Nine people
were killed, including the jet's captain. At the time of the crash,
the captain and first officer had been on duty for more than 13
hours.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Duquette said that Friday's action by the agency was a
decision that was made weeks ago, long before the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the crash may now tip the balance in the battle that has
raged for more than a decade between safety experts and pilot
groups on one side and the airline industry on the other. Pilot
unions and the National Transportation Safety Board say crew
fatigue is a significant factor in many accidents and have urged
the aviation agency to revise its regulations to reflect new
scientific evidence on the subject. The transportation board has
also strongly criticized the aviation agency for not enforcing the
current rule mandating pilot rest.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Transport Association, the industry's lobbying group,
has countered that fatigue is not a major safety threat and that
making carriers fully comply with the current regulation would
force them to hire more pilots, adding billions of dollars to the
industry's costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure that because of this crash in Little Rock
there is no rush to judgment on this issue,'' said David A. Fuscus,
a spokesman for the association. ``These are very complicated
issues with a wide diversity of opinion about them and they need to
be addressed in the right manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulation requiring eight hours' rest does not pose a
problem for most senior pilots who fly regular schedules. But
thousands of reserve pilots get up each morning, not knowing if
they will be asked to fly at 10 a.m. or 10 p.m. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  A few airlines comply with the rule by dividing their reserve
pilots into three groups that are scheduled to rest in staggered
eight-hour shifts throughout the day. But most major carriers
ignore the rule.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the aviation agency announced its intention to modify
the regulation and asked for suggestions. But after receiving 2,000
comments on all sides, it declined to act. Last year, Ms. Garvey
asked a committee of pilots and airline executives to draft a new
proposal, promising to enforce the current rule strictly if the
panel could not reach a consensus.
</P>
<P>
   The group disbanded in February after failing to reach an
agreement, but Ms. Garvey still did not act. Last month, the Air
Line Pilots Association, which represents 53,000 pilots at 50
airlines, publicly called on Ms. Garvey to make good on her
promise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
