u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMAZON.COM-BESTSELLER     06-04 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON.COM-BESTSELLERS-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM SEEKS RULING ON USE OF N.Y. TIMES BEST-SELLER LISTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)   By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The leading online bookseller, Amazon.com, sought a legal ruling
in federal court Friday to allow it to continue posting The New
York Times best-seller lists after the newspaper had demanded in a
letter that the Seattle company stop publishing the lists in the
absence of a licensing agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The legal action came as a price war over best sellers on The
New York Times lists has engulfed the top online bookstores,
including Borders.com and Barnesandnoble.com. All three booksellers
are offering 50 percent discounts on more than 60 titles on the
various best-seller lists of The Times, which the companies post on
their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Times also sent a similar letter Thursday to executives at
Borders.com, a unit of Borders Group Inc., seeking to stop it from
using the best-seller lists. But Friday, a spokesman for Borders,
Rich Fahle, said it had not ``made a decision on how to proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnesandnoble.com did not get a warning because executives of
The New York Times Co. said it had a business relationship with the
book chain that included a licensing agreement, stipulating when
Barnesandnoble.com could post the best-seller lists. The Times
maintains ties to Barnesandnoble.com through links from its Web
site to the electronic bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's best-seller list has been used widely for more
than 20 years by bookstores as a standard to promote popular
titles. Amazon spokesman Bill Curry said the company had filed a
motion in U.S. District Court in Seattle, where the company is
based, seeking a ruling on whether it could cite the best-seller
lists to promote its discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Curry said the company believed that its citations were a ``fair
use of the information on the list, and it's like saying, `Here's
an Academy Award winner.' It's a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Richieri, an assistant general counsel for The New York
Times, said that the company became aware of the extensive use of
the lists after the price wars started in May. He said that the
company was particularly concerned that Amazon was posting the
lists on the Wednesdays before they were formally published each
Sunday in The New York Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   Richieri said The Times Co. was not concerned that Amazon
labeled books as best-sellers on The Times lists. The issue, he
said, ``is taking the list in its entirety and publishing it and
using that list in essentially a commercial way.''
</P>
<P>
   Since The Times Co. complained, the bookseller has altered the
list so that titles are alphabetical rather than in order of
popularity. Amazon is also posting its new listing on the Mondays
after the rankings appear in The Times, and it has added a
disclaimer, saying the newspaper ``does not sponsor or endorse the
services of Amazon.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Richieri said those changes ``are basically an acknowledgment
that they were over the line before.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the company was open to establishing licensing
agreements with Amazon but wanted Amazon to remove the list first.
``Amazon just put it up,'' Richieri said. ``They just dissed us.
Their view is that they don't need the license.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
