<HEADER>
A3945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-COURT-RESIGNATION-     06-04 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COURT-RESIGNATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDLER ANNOUNCES HE WILL RETIRE FROM NEW JERSEY SUPREME COURT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By JERRY GRAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ New Jersey Supreme Court Justice Alan Handler
announced Friday that he would retire in September. His departure
will open the way for Gov. Christie Whitman to make her fourth
nomination to the state's highest court and will assure that her
imprint is stamped on one of the nation's most respected benches
for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Handler made the announcement barely a month after Attorney
General Peter Verniero was confirmed for a seat on the bench at the
end of a grueling political fight over his nomination. Handler will
leave the bench Sept. 1, the same day that Verniero is scheduled to
join the court.
</P>
<P>
   At 68, Handler, one of the most liberal voices on the court, is
still two years away from the mandatory retirement age. He gave no
specific reason for stepping down, other than that it was time to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know exactly why I decided to retire now,'' he said in
a telephone interview Friday. ``It's one of these indefinable inner
clocks that ticks away. It's long enough. I look forward to taking
life a little less seriously; that's as close to elation as I
get.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman has made three appointments to the seven-member court:
Verniero, Chief Justice Deborah Poritz and Justice James Coleman.
She will have the chance to place at least one more person on the
Supreme Court early next year because Justice Daniel O'Hern will
reach the mandatory retirement age of 70 on May 30.
</P>
<P>
   Jayne O'Connor, a spokeswoman for Whitman, said that the
governor had not decided on a replacement for Handler. But Ms.
O'Connor said, ``The governor will not be submitting her nominee to
the State Bar Association.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, angry over the bar association's rejection of Verniero
as unqualified to be a justice, said last month that she would not
send any future Supreme Court nominees to the bar for review.
Governors, including Whitman on all her nominations to date, have
submitted nominations for the bar association's review for 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   Handler's retirement gives Whitman the opportunity to make some
of the most significant changes to the court in its history, and
her choices could determine the court's views on issues from the
fate of death row inmates to how the state deals with inequities
between rich and poor school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Handler is the most outspoken opponent of capital punishment
remaining on the court. Although that position has placed him in a
decided minority, his arguments over 22 years have persuaded many
of his colleagues who support the death penalty to grant enhanced
protections for capital defendants. New Jersey has not carried out
an execution since it restored the death penalty in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   After the retirement of Chief Justice Robert Wilentz in 1996,
Handler became the leading voice on the court in the state's long
fight over school financing. That legal battle, embodied in a 1990
case known as Abbot vs. Burke, has led to years of court rulings in
which the state is constitutionally required to provide parity in
financing for all school districts. Handler wrote the court's
majority decision in the two most recent rulings on the issue, in
1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For a generation, Handler, Wilentz, and Justice Stewart Pollock,
whom Verniero will replace in September, were the strong liberal
voices on the New Jersey Supreme Court, leading the way on
decisions about race, criminal justice, abortion and equal rights
for women.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this wonderful court is quickly being transformed,''
said Frank Askin, a professor at Rutgers University Law School and
general counsel for the American Civil Liberties Union of New
Jersey. ``Handler was clearly the conscience of this court. His
retirement is going to put a lot of pressure on Chief Justice
Poritz because it is definitely turning into the Poritz court.''
</P>
<P>
   Handler said that even with the probability of at least five
nominees to the bench by Whitman, he was not worried that the court
would swing drastically in any particular direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's really possible to control these things too
closely,'' he said, ``and I don't think people should be unduly
concerned or perturbed that coincidentally one governor has the
opportunity to make fewer or more appointments than another.''
</P>
<P>
   Handler attended Princeton University and is a graduate of the
Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs. He
received his law degree from Harvard Law School in 1956 and was
admitted to the New Jersey bar the same year. He was a deputy
attorney general and a first assistant attorney general before he
was appointed to the state Superior Court in 1967. He quit the
bench in 1976 to work as special counsel to Gov. Brendan Byrne. A
year later, Byrne nominated him to the state Supreme Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-99 2340EDT &QL; 
