<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-DOGBITES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC COLUMN: THROUGH RAIN, SLEET AND BITES FROM DOGS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., N.Y., Texas)   (rk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Ryder post office on East 45th Street near
Flatbush Avenue is the busiest in Brooklyn, and on Thursday morning
the talk among the men and women in gray and blue was of dogs.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 350,000 dogs in Brooklyn and only 2,200 mail
carriers, a ratio that helps explain why the U.S. Postal Service
this week ranked Brooklyn fifth on its annual list of Top 10 Dog
Bite Cities.
</P>
<P>
   The news had Joseph Lubrano grabbing the back of his right
thigh. Lubrano is now the postmaster of Brooklyn, but years ago as
a rookie carrier in Queens, he met the business end of a Doberman
pinscher.
</P>
<P>
   He had followed protocol, stepping inside the fence only after
he rattled the gate. But the Doberman rounded the corner and
clamped onto his leg, and the memory hasn't ever quite gone away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 injury that a letter carrier sustains nationally is
a dog bite,'' said Lubrano, ``so we take it very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if much of the mail-receiving public does not. The struggle
between mailman and mutt is eternal and pretty lopsided if you're
rooting for the mailman. People in all 50 states love dogs much
more than they do the Postal Service, a fact not lost on Lubrano
and other mail officials. They went to the Ryder office bearing
grim dog war stories and glossy literature to drum up attention as
part of a national dog bite prevention campaign.
</P>
<P>
   First, they played on sympathy. Angelo Mangano carried mail for
37 years and escaped flesh wounds thanks to his quick feet and a
supply of dog biscuits in his bag. But as president of the Brooklyn
letter carrier's local, he relayed tales from others of mangled
forearms and punctured legs and rabies scares.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for those moved more by money than suffering, Lubrano
noted that the 2,541 dog bites in fiscal year 1998, including 22 in
Brooklyn, cost the Postal Service $25 million. (Houston ranked
first, with 49, followed by Chicago, Miami and Los Angeles.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a visitor was allowed to venture outside the Ryder
office and follow Bruno Papalia, 28, on his route through Brooklyn.
Energetic and friendly, Papalia said the dog count on his route is
seven pit bulls, two Dalmatians, two cocker spaniels, a black
Labrador, three poodles, two Rottweilers and dozens of mutts and
strays. He does not think Brooklyn dogs are any more malicious than
suburban or small-town dogs, only that there are more of them.
</P>
<P>
   He is armed with a 1.5-ounce canister of ``Halt!'' pepper spray,
but didn't have time to use it when he was attacked on April 30,
his third bite in less than three years. He still has five pink
puncture wounds on his shin, but his pride suffered the greater
injury _ his assailant was a poodle.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got me all the way down to the bone,'' Papalia said. A
co-worker gave him the card of a lawyer specializing in dog
litigation, but he decided not to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Papalia knows that conflict is inevitable between a beast
trained to protect home and hearth and a carrier sworn to deliver
mail through adversity. He also thinks dogs hate his uniform. Dogs
have pushed through screen doors to attack him.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a pit bull chased him around a car after its owner
accidentally dropped its leash. On Thursday morning, a black dog
contentedly riding in the back seat of a blue sedan stuck its wet
nose out the window and barked at the sight of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``7329 Avenue M,'' Papalia said respectfully, recognizing the
Labrador.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he came to Bergen Court, known among carriers at the Ryder
office as ``Satan's block.'' There is even a ``Dog Warning Card''
filed at the office alerting carriers to Satan's address.
``Everybody knows Satan,'' Papalia said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a fence and a ``Beware of Dog'' sign, but no Satan.
The owner, Steve Goldman, described his dog as ``a pussycat. She
just doesn't like uniforms.'' He pointed to Papalia and said, ``If
you hide him, I'll let the dog out and he'll lick you in the
palm.''
</P>
<P>
   Papalia smiled and hurried down the block to deliver more mail.
Satan emerged and bounded down the steps, equal parts pit bull,
English bulldog and fire hydrant. She growled through the fence.
But when Goldman opened the gate and let the visitor in, she seemed
almost, well, sweet. He said Satan growls and nips only at people
outside the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``And her name is Sadie,'' Goldman said.
</P>
<P>
   So there you have the root of problem. One man's Satan is
another man's Sadie. It all depends on which side of the fence
you're standing on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
