<HEADER>
A3953 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MS-PATIENT-SPI &LR;      06-04 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MS-PATIENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAY ELLISON, A STREET FIGHTER AND A SURVIVOR, GETS A SECOND
CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ James ``Jay'' Ellison will return home a new man on
Sunday, free of the violent tremors that had caused his body to
painfully jerk and shudder, the visible symptoms of a disease that
was rapidly eroding his nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison firmly believes he has been cured of multiple sclerosis
by the high-dose chemotherapy, radiation and stem cell transplant
he fought so hard to get.
</P>
<P>
   He calls the day he got the transplant, March 22, his ``new
birthday.'' He fought hard for that day. He battled the disease,
and he battled his insurance company after it refused to pay for
the experimental transplant.
</P>
<P>
   He took his fight for coverage public until an anonymous donor
stepped in, making the transplant possible. Today, he says the
transformation that led him on this path to rebirth began many
years ago when he was a troubled youth with a criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose I learned from my mistakes, and I learned you can
change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As one of his doctors noted, Ellison also apparently learned
some ``street fighter'' skills that served him well in his battle
with the insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, he will return home to Covington, Wash., (near Kent)
after two months of ``house arrest'' at the Marriott Residence Inn,
next door to the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison was discharged from the hospital in early April, but
like all transplant patients has had to stay near Fred Hutchinson
so his post-transplant progress could be monitored.
</P>
<P>
   His doctors say there is no way to know yet if the treatment, a
refinement of the bone marrow transplant, has worked. But
privately, in conversations with their patient, it's clear they are
as elated with his progress as the patient himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever something like this happens, when there are dramatic
changes, as researchers we have to be careful not to overstate
things,'' said Dr. Richard Nash, one of Ellison's transplant
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all very impressed with the response so far.''
</P>
<P>
   But it would be premature, Nash said, to say the transplant has
rid Ellison of disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep telling me to stop saying I'm cured, but I know I
am,'' the 37-year-old former painting contractor said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, who has four children, plans to work hard to get out of
his wheelchair and take full advantage of this hard-won contract on
a new life.
</P>
<P>
   He was diagnosed last fall with primary progressive MS. Doctors
said the disease was moving so rapidly without remission that none
of the standard drug therapies offered him any benefit. His only
hope was the transplant, which would cost $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Nash and other experts at the University of Washington pleaded
with Ellison's insurance company, Premera Blue Cross, to pay for
coverage, saying Ellison's unusually aggressive form of MS did not
respond to standard therapies and the transplant offered him his
only hope.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison refused to take no for an answer. With help from the
advocacy group Washington Citizen Action and state Insurance
Commissioner Deborah Senn, he went to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   A public fund-raising effort was launched and then abruptly cut
short when an anonymous donor contacted Fred Hutchinson and agreed
to pay the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Bowen, a UW neurologist who advocated for Ellison's
transplant, said part of what made Ellison different from other
patients who face such denials was his savvy and direct
confrontation of the insurer.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor also noted his patient's gift for public speaking, an
ability for rhetorical counterpunch that even Bill Clinton might
admire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd describe it as non-physical street fighting,'' Bowen said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Jay Ellison the public knows: a dedicated and
hard-working family man, a devout Christian, who smiles easily and
speaks with a kind of common-man sincerity that almost seems quaint
these days.
</P>
<P>
   And this is the real Ellison today. But the savvy, street-smart
side probably owes a lot to the old Jay Ellison _ the boy who never
graduated from high school and who spent 18 months behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say just about every kid in my old neighborhood ended up
in prison at some point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a professional gambler he never met, Ellison grew up
in Auburn, Kent and Federal Way. He and his family spent part of
their lives in the housing projects. Ellison said he lived in a
culture where petty crime was routine and often done simply for
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 15, he was arrested for burglarizing the home of a
Washington State Patrol officer. He and his teenage friends took
the loot _ guns, alcohol and video equipment _ to their fort in the
woods. When they returned the next day, the police were waiting.
``Looking back on it now, that was the best thing that could have
happened to me,'' Ellison said. ``I was a follower then, in with
some pretty bad kids. I needed discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   After release from youth detention, Ellison said he resolved to
clean up his act. He got a job and, at 17, got married. But his
troubles weren't over. Ellison said he and his wife still dabbled
in drugs, using them even as they were starting a family. Compared
with his earlier mistakes, he said it seemed a small vice at the
time. It wasn't. Early on in the marriage, the couple had a
daughter, Cerena. Four years later, the marriage had disintegrated
but the couple had another child on the way. Ellison said his
second son, Brian, was born with severe health problems that the
doctors attributed to maternal drug use. Ellison has custody of
both children.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, Ellison's own mother was diagnosed with
MS. He was so busy dealing with his son's health problems he said
he wasn't able to give his mother's diagnosis much attention. Just
as it would hit him about 15 years later, the disease hit his
mother with lightning suddenness and immediately put her in a
wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty overwhelming,'' said Cathy Ellison, Jay's second
wife.
</P>
<P>
   The experts wanted to keep the infant boy medicated with
phenobarbital to prevent seizures. But the Ellisons did their own
research and decided the long-term medication was doing more harm
than good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd already decided that we'd rather have him live one day
with a clear mind than live a lifetime on the medications they had
him on,'' Jay Ellison said.
</P>
<P>
   They found other doctors who were willing to wean the boy off
his medications, and today Brian is doing fine, excelling at karate
and acting in all other ways like a normal teenager. He is quiet
about his father's battle with MS, and Jay Ellison said he's not
sure how to handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I know how to be a father to a teenager, maybe
because I didn't have a father when I was a teenager,'' Ellison
said.
</P>
<P>
   He seems most uncertain when he talks about his family. His
confidence when testifying in Olympia in favor of patient-rights
legislation or when holding a news conference to challenge the
health insurance industry seems to ebb then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made a lot of mistakes and, by golly, I'll probably keep
on making mistakes,'' Ellison said.
</P>
<P>
   But most agree he has made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison has drawn attention to a promising new treatment for
people with the severest forms of MS and other autoimmune diseases.
Since he went to the media, calls to Fred Hutchinson and the UW
about stem cell transplantation for MS have come in from around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison also drew attention to a huge gap in the health care
system _ the lack of consistent financing for experimental
therapies. At the request of Washington Citizen Action and the
insurance commissioner, he became the poster boy for a drive to
pass a patients bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   That effort failed to produce a new law, and Ellison has since
grown a little wiser about life as a media symbol. He is grateful
to those who helped him, but at the same time he said he is
uncomfortable that his name was used like a political commodity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I was kind of naive,'' Ellison said. ``I just figured
they were trying to help me. And they did help me. ... But after a
while it was pretty clear it wasn't about me so much as it was
about politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, it is going to be about his family. Ellison
believes this treatment has given him a new beginning. He is one of
only about 60 people in the world to have received a stem cell
transplant for MS and hopes to be one of the very few to show it
can do more than simply stop the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been pretty fortunate,'' Ellison said. ``I'm thinking
there's a reason for all this. Maybe this guinea pig was meant to
fly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
