<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN BUSINESS BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   COMPLAINT ON MEAT BAN
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission called a U.S. ban on poultry and pork
imports from all European Union countries ``disproportionate.'' The
U.S. Agriculture Department issued the ban on Thursday after meat
from Belgium was found to contain the toxic chemical dioxin. Amid
concern the chemical may also be present in Belgian beef, the
Netherlands, Austria, Switzerland, Canada and Hong Kong have joined
the United States in restricting Belgian food imports. The European
Commission has said it will ban the sale of chicken, pork, beef and
dairy products from around 1,000 Belgian farms.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Alan Cowell
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA JOBLESSNESS
</P>
<P>
   Canada's economy lost 14,000 jobs in May, the fourth consecutive
month with no growth in employment, Statistics Canada reported.
Nevertheless, the national unemployment rate dipped to 8.1 percent,
from 8.3 percent in April, because 49,000 people withdrew from the
labor force. Ruth Getter, chief economist at Toronto Dominion Bank,
said all the jobs lost were for full-time work in the private
sector, while public sector employment continued to grow.
Statistics Canada also reported that the consumer price index was
1.7 percent higher in April than a year ago, the largest annual
increase since October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Timothy Pritchard
</P>
<P>
   BRAZILIAN NATURAL GAS PROJECT
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Brazilian government's effort to increase the use
of natural gas as an energy source instead of petroleum, a group of
state-controlled energy companies and regional administrations
announced plans for two gas pipelines to fuel the electric energy
grids of three far-flung Amazonian states. Led by the state oil and
gas company Petrobras, the group, which also includes Eletrobras, a
state holding company for energy investments, plans to invest about
$860 million in the project. The pipelines are part of a larger
push by federal authorities to improve infrastructure in some of
Brazil's most remote regions.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Simon Romero
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN PHONE USE
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Telecommunications Commission of Mexico reported
increased use of mobile phones in May after a system that charges
callers was put into effect. The agency disputed a report by
Salomon Smith Barney that cellular phone use fell 50 percent in
May. One beeper company in Mexico also attributed a recent 30
percent increase in clients to frustration with costlier cellular
phones. When the ``caller pays'' system went into effect for mobile
phone users on May 1, the government also authorized higher rates,
as high as 75 cents for a three-minute call, and added complicated
dialing procedures.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Rick Wills
</P>
</TEXT>
