 PM-NYT-BUDGET-2TAKES  
 bl 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the top stories from The New York Times News Service
report for PMs of Saturday, June 5.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, (212) 556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. ET. To get
story repeats before this hour, call (212) 621-1595 for reruns on
AP DataFeatures or (214) 980-8305 or 8306 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   ART ADV: Graphics and photos are being sent, as indicated below,
to NYT Graphics and Photos subscribers. Clients needing
retransmissions or information, or non-subscribers seeking to
arrange individual purchases, should call (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category; other foreign stories listed below)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX (Washington) _ President Clinton declared
Friday that he was ``anxious to end the bombing'' in Yugoslavia,
and the Pentagon said that the 10 week air war could end as early
as Sunday if Serb military authorities begin their troop withdrawal
from Kosovo. By Alison Mitchell. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ Gen. Michael Jackson, the
British officer who will command peacekeeping force, is going to
Belgrade on Saturday to meet Yugoslav army brass; bombing may end
Sunday. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AIRPOWER (Undated) _ Without one combat casualty, NATO
has turned Milosevic's Yugoslavia into the first case study in how
precision weaponry, overwhelming resources and a steely willingness
to keep bombing can compel victory _ all without risking NATO
soldiers on the ground. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-RECOVERY-ASSESS (Washington) _ On how Yugoslavia's recovery
might be constrained by fact that its president has been indicted
on war-crimes charges. Like the Persian Gulf war, the Kosovo war
appears to be ending with major issues unresolved, not least the
future of President Slobodan Milosevic and what the U.S. ought to
do about him. By R.W. Apple.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade) _ As soon as Russia came to
agreement with NATO on the principles for a peace settlement for
Kosovo, Milosevic understood that he had no choice but to accept
the terms put in front of him, senior Yugoslav officials said
Friday. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ The Kosovo pact that was struck
Thursday with the consent of President Boris Yeltsin and his
special envoy got a scalding reception in its first review here
Friday, not merely from politicians, but from some of Yeltsin's own
officials. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FINLAND (Helsinki) _ U.S. leaders and NATO officials said
that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had yet to take concrete
steps to back up the peace accord for Kosovo and warned that the
deal could still slip away. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ How/why the military campaign is
ending. After 73 days of bombing, NATO finally broke Milosevic's
will by finding new ways to destroy the Serb military, inflicting
real damage on power, water, factories and other non-military
targets and demonstrating the ability to bomb with virtual
impunity, allied commanders said. By Eric Schmitt and Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ A day after Yugoslavia accepted a peace
plan for Kosovo, China restated its demand that NATO halt its
bombing before discussions begin in the U.N. about a peacekeeping
force. But Chinese support for the peace plan seems likely. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Washington) _ Through the war, NATO has only
warily dealt with the Kosovo Liberation Army, the only fighters on
the ground in Yugoslavia. Now with a settlement at hand, NATO is
even more wary of the emboldened rebels, who see themselves as the
emerging political and military power in a liberated Kosovo. By
Steven Lee Myers and Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Macedonia) _ Refugees try to make up their
