   EUROPE-SOLANA (Brussels) _ Javier Solana, who as
secretary-general of NATO pressed strongly for the Yugoslavia
bombing campaign, was named by the European Union as its first
foreign policy and security czar. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   NEPAL-GODDESS (Manakamana, Nepal) _ Since the 17th century,
Hindus in search of their heart's desire have ascended a steep and
rocky mountain to the temple of Manakamana, the wish-fulfilling
goddess. Now, modern technology is making that pilgrimage alot
easier. By Barry Bearak. WITH MAP.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIANANMEN (Beijing) _ Two one-man protests near Tiananmen
Square, immediately snuffed out by police, were the only brief
interruptions in a normal workday here Friday as the 10th
anniversary of the violent crackdown on pro-democracy
demonstrations passed without official notice. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-TIANANMEN (Hong Kong) _ About 70,000 people turn out
for the only major June 4 commemoration on Chinese soil. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ELECTION (Jakarta) _ In a reminder of the dangers that
surround Indonesia's parliamentary election, a whiff of violence
came to the capital Friday as police fired warning shots to halt an
attack on supporters of the ruling party. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-EMBASSY-SECURITY (Washington) _ The Clinton administration,
responding to criticism that it had failed to protect U.S.
diplomats from terrorist attacks, said Friday that it would ask
Congress for an additional $264 million next year to build new,
more secure embassies. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   BOMB-SERGEANT (New York) _ A former U.S. Army sergeant accused
of being a part of a terrorist conspiracy has told the FBI that he
knew the people who carried out the embassy bombings in Africa last
year but has refused to identify them, according to court documents
released here Friday. By Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
