<P>
   RUSSIA-VODKA (Moscow) _ Vodka is the lubricant for most serious
discussion in Russia and often its subject, as the country goes
through a period of inordinately destructive alcoholism. But a
number of Russian distillers are trying to create a more upscale
culture of drinking. These businesses hope they can make money by
teaching people to drink vodka for its subtly varied taste rather
than its roundhouse-punch effect. By Neela Banerjee. WITH PHOTO and
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-INTERNET-RULING (Undated) _ In a decision that could have
far-reaching implications for consumers and the telecommunications
industry, a federal court in Oregon ruled Friday that a local
government could force AT&AMP;T to share its cable lines with competing
Internet service providers. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TRIAL (Washington) _ Trying to defang the government's
antitrust charges against it, Microsoft Corp. introduced a host of
evidence in court this week in an effort to show that the Netscape
browser is still healthy and thriving, despite Microsoft's all-out
assault on the browser market. But in a single stroke Friday, a
government lawyer undercut Microsoft's strategy. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-CATHAY-PHILIPPINES (Hong Kong) _ Philippine Airlines said
that it had raised $200 million in fresh capital to resuscitate its
debt-ridden operations. And Cathay Pacific Airways is preparing for
talks with its pilots to resolve a dispute that has grounded
between a third and half of its daily flights since May 28. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
