<DOCNO> NYT19990604.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-04 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3963 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRANSPLANT-SPI &LR;      06-04 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSPLANT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE AT FOREFRONT OF STEM CELL TRANSPLANT RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Like so many discoveries in science, the idea that
bone marrow transplantation might be useful in the treatment of
autoimmune disorders such as multiple sclerosis, rheumatoid
arthritis or lupus came about by accident.
</P>
<P>
   It is an accident upon which medical researchers intend to
capitalize. Seattle is at the center of a rapidly expanding
nationwide effort, led by the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research
Center, to study the effectiveness of bone marrow or stem cell
transplantation as a treatment for autoimmune diseases.
</P>
<P>
   About 300,000 Americans have multiple sclerosis, with the rate
much higher in the Pacific Northwest and other northern regions.
About 150 people per 100,000 population have the disease in the
Northwest, compared with about half that in California. Scientists
don't know why the rate is higher in the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The stem cell transplant, a refinement of the bone marrow
transplant, involves injecting basic blood-forming cells back into
a patient to create a new immune system and costs about $100,000.
For people with leukemia or lymphoma, the transplant is standard
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   For some people with autoimmune disorders, it's the choice
between this experimental therapy or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a big deal for a patient group like MS, because
there is so little standard therapy can do for people with severe
forms of the disease,'' said Dr. Peter McSweeney, a transplant
physician who helped develop the autoimmune project at Fred
Hutchinson.
</P>
<P>
   McSweeney, who is leaving Seattle to direct a bone marrow and
stem cell transplant program at the University of Colorado hospital
in Denver, said the primary impetus for this approach came from
patients who had autoimmune rheumatoid arthritis in addition to
leukemia or lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   These patients were treated for their cancer by high-dose
chemotherapy and radiation followed by bone marrow transplantation
to restore immunity, McSweeney said. But in addition to being rid
of cancer, he said, these patients also appeared to rid themselves
of their arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most of these transplants involved the use of donor
marrow, which is more risky than autologous transplants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Development of autologous transplantation _ using the patients'
own marrow or immmune system cells _ involved enough of a reduction
in risk to get people thinking about pursuing transplantation as a
treatment for non-terminal autoimmune disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. George Kraft, director of University of Washington's
Multiple Sclerosis Research and Training Center, said most people
with MS will respond well to one of the available medications. But
those with severe forms of the disorder _ about 10 percent _ often
fail to respond to drug therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still experimental, but for some people it's the right
option,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Bowen, a UW neurologist who has referred people with
MS to Fred Hutchinson for transplantation, said it's really not
much of conceptual stretch to move from current drug therapies for
MS to transplantation. Both, Bowen noted, are attempts to combat a
dysfunctional immune system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've long had suspicions that something gone wrong in the
immune system might be the cause of multiple sclerosis,'' he said.
In MS, he said, the body's own immune system cells attack the
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   The current drug therapies are all immunosuppressive agents,
Bowen said, whereas high-dose chemotherapy and radiation wipes out
the immune system so the bone marrow or stem cell transplant can
rebuild a healthy new system.
</P>
<P>
   It's still not fully accepted, he said, that MS is an autoimmune
disorder. And it's certainly not been accepted yet, Bowen said,
that transplantation should be the treatment of choice for severe
cases of MS.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the research consortium launched by Fred Hutchinson,
in partnership with the UW and also with arthritis researchers at
Virginia Mason Medical Center, hopes to answer. The City of Hope
biomedical research institution in Los Angeles is also part of the
project.
</P>
<P>
   A similar but separate clinical study looking at marrow or stem
cell transplantation for autoimmune disorders is also under way at
Northwestern University in Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
